<L N="644">But who-so wolde in o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing him grope</L>
<L>Thanne hadde he spent al his philosophie</L>
<L>Ay questio quid Iuris wolde he crye</L>
<L>He was a gentil harlot and a kynde<MILESTONE N="9b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="648">A bettre felaw schulde men nowher fynde</L>
<L>He wolde suffre for a quart of wyn</L>
<L>A good felawe han his concubyn</L>
<L>A .xij. moneth. and excuse him atte fulle</L>
<L N="652">And pryuely a Fynch eek cowde he pulle</L>
<L>And if he fond owher a good felawe</L>
<L>he wolde teche him for to haue non awe</L>
<L>In such a caas of &thorn;e archedeknes curs</L>
<L N="656">But if a mannes soule were in his purs</L>
<L>For in his purs he scholde punyssched be</L>
<L>Purs is the Ercedeknes helle quod he</L>
<L>But wel I woot he lyeth right in dede</L>
<L N="660">Of cursyng oweth ech gulty man to drede</L>
<L>For curs wol slee. right as assoillyng saueth</L>
<L>And also ware him of a Significauit</L>
<L>In daunger he hadde at his owne assise</L>
<L N="664">The &yogh;onge gurles of the Diocise</L>
<L>And knew here counseil and was al here red</L>
<L>A garland had he set vpon his heed</L>
<L>As gret as it were for an ale stake</L>
<L N="668">A bokeler had he maad him of a cake</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>With him &thorn;er rood a gentil Pardoner</L>
<L>Of Rounciual his frend and his comper</L>
<L>That streyt was comen from &thorn;e court of Rome</L>
<L N="672">Ful lowde he sang com hider loue tome</L>
<L>The sompnour bar to him a stif burdoun
<PB REF="00000032.tif" N="20"></L>
<L>was neuere trompe of half so gret a soun</L>
<L>This pardoner hadde heer as &yogh;elwe as wex</L>
<L N="676">But smothe it heng. as doth a strike of Flex</L>
<L>By vnces hynge his lokkes &thorn;at he hadde</L>
<L>And &thorn;erwith he his schuldres ouerspradde</L>
<L>Ful thenne it lay by culpons on and oon</L>
<L N="680">And hood for Iolitee ne wered he noon</L>
<L>For it was trussud vp in his walet</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ought he rood al of &thorn;e newe get</L>
<L>Discheuele sauf his cappe he rood al bare</L>
<L N="684">Suche glaryng ey&yogh;en hadde he as an hare</L>
<L>A vernicle hadde he sowed on his cappe<MILESTONE N="10a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>His walet lay byforn him in his lappe</L>
<L>Bret ful of pardoun come from Rome al hoot</L>
<L N="688">A voys he hadde as smal as eny goot</L>
<L>No berd ne hadde he ne neuer scholde haue</L>
<L>As smothe it was as it ware late I-schaue /</L>
<L>I trowe he were a geldyng or a mare</L>
<L N="692">But of his craft fro Berwyk vnto ware</L>
<L>Ne was &thorn;er such another pardoner</L>
<L>For in his male he hadde a pilwebeer</L>
<L>which &thorn;at he saide was oure lady veyl</L>
<L N="696">he seide he hadde a gobet of &thorn;e seyl</L>
<L>That seynt Petur hadde whan he wente</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e see til ih&umacr; crist him hente</L>
<L>he hadde a cros of latoun ful of stones</L>
<L N="700">And in a glas he hadde pigges bones</L>
<L>But with &thorn;ise reliqes whanne &thorn;at he fand</L>
<L>A pore parsoun dwellyng vppon land</L>
<L>vpon a day he gat him more moneye</L>
<L N="704">Than &thorn;at &thorn;e parsoun gat in monthes tweye</L>
<L>And &thorn;us with feyned flaterie and Iapes</L>
<L>he made &thorn;e parsoun and &thorn;e poeple his apes</L>
<L>But trewely to tellen atte laste</L>
<L N="708">He was in churche a noble ecclesiaste</L>
<L>wel cowde he rede a lessoun or a storye
<PB REF="00000033.tif" N="21"></L>
<L>But altherbest he sang an offertorie</L>
<L>For wel<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>later</I> wyst <I>at side</I>]</NOTE> he whan &thorn;at song was songe</L>
<L N="712">he moste preche and wel affyle his tunge</L>
<L>To wynne siluer as he right wel cowde</L>
<L>Therefore he sang ful meriely and lowde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOw haue I told &yogh;ou schortly in a clause</L>
<L N="716">Thestat &thorn;array &thorn;e nombre and eek &thorn;e cause</L>
<L>why &thorn;at assembled was &thorn;is companye</L>
<L>In Southwerk at &thorn;is gentil Ostelrie</L>
<L>That highte &thorn;e Tabbard faste by &thorn;e belle</L>
<L N="720">But now is tyme to &yogh;ow for to telle</L>
<L>how &thorn;at we bare vs in &thorn;at ilke night</L>
<L>whan we were in that Ostelrie alight</L>
<L>And aftur wol I telle of oure viage<MILESTONE N="10b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="724">And al &thorn;e remenaunt of oure pilgrimage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But ferst I pray &yogh;ou of &yogh;our curtesie</L>
<L>That &yogh;e ne rette it nat my vilanye</L>
<L>Though &thorn;at I speke al pleyn in &thorn;is matere</L>
<L N="728">And telle &yogh;ou here wordes and here cheere</L>
<L>Ne though I speke here wordes propurly</L>
<L>For &thorn;is &yogh;e knowen also wel as I</L>
<L>who-so schal telle a tale aftur a man</L>
<L N="732">He moste reherce as neigh as euer he can</L>
<L>Euery word if it be in his charge</L>
<L>Al speke he neuer so Rudely ne large</L>
<L>Or elles he moot telle his tale vntrewe</L>
<L N="736">Or feyne &thorn;ing or fynde his wordes newe</L>
<L>He may not spare &thorn;ough he were his bro&thorn;ur</L>
<L>He moste as wel sey oo word as ano&thorn;ur</L>
<L>Crist spak himself ful broode in holy writ</L>
<L N="740">And wel &yogh;e woot no vilanye is it</L>
<L>Eke Plato seith who-so &thorn;at can him rede</L>
<L>The wordes mot be cosyn to &thorn;e dede</L>
<L>Also I pray &yogh;ou to for&yogh;eue it me</L>
<L N="744">Al haue I folk nat set in here degre</L>
<L>Here in &thorn;is tale as &thorn;at &thorn;ei schulde stonde
<PB REF="00000034.tif" N="22"></L>
<L>My witt is thynne. &yogh;e may wel vndurstonde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>GReet cheere made oure ost vs euerichon</L>
<L N="748">And to &thorn;e souper sette he vs anon</L>
<L>He serued vs with vitaille atte beste</L>
<L>Strong was &thorn;e wyn and wel to drynke vs leste</L>
<L>A semely man oure Ooste was wi&thorn; alle</L>
<L N="752">For to han been a Marchal in an halle</L>
<L>A large man was he with ey&yogh;en stepe</L>
<L>A fairere burgeys is &thorn;er noon in chepe</L>
<L>Bold of his speche and wys and wel I-taught</L>
<L N="756">And of manhede lakkede he right naught</L>
<L>Eke &thorn;erto he was right a mery man</L>
<L>And after soper playen he bygan</L>
<L>And spak of myrthe. among o&thorn;ur &thorn;inges</L>
<L N="760">whan &thorn;at we hadde maad our rekenynges</L>
<L>And sayde &thorn;us. Lo lordynges trewely<MILESTONE N="11a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;e ben to me right welcome hertily</L>
<L>For by my trouthe if &thorn;at I schal not lye</L>
<L N="764">I ne saugh &thorn;is &yogh;eer so mery a companye</L>
<L>At oones in this herbergh as is now</L>
<L>Fayn wold I do &yogh;ow merthe wiste I how</L>
<L>And of a merthe I am right now bythought</L>
<L N="768">To doon &yogh;ou eese and it schal coste nought</L>
<L>&YOGH;e goon to Caunturbury god &yogh;ou speede</L>
<L>The blisful martir quyte &yogh;ou &yogh;oure meede</L>
<L>And wel I woot/ as &yogh;e gon by &thorn;e weye</L>
<L N="772">&YOGH;e schapen &yogh;ow to talken and to pleye</L>
<L>For trewely comfort ne merthe is noon</L>
<L>To Ryde by &thorn;e weye domb as a stoon</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore wol I make &yogh;ou disport /</L>
<L N="776">As I seyde erst and do &yogh;ou som confort</L>
<L>And if &yogh;ow liketh alle by oon assent</L>
<L>Now for to standen at my Iuggement</L>
<L>And for to werken as I schal &yogh;ou seye</L>
<L N="780">To morwe whan &yogh;e riden by &thorn;e weye</L>
<L>Now by my fadres soule &thorn;at is deed
<PB REF="00000035.tif" N="23"></L>
<L>But &yogh;e be merye smyte&thorn; of myn heed</L>
<L>hold vp &yogh;oure hond with-oute more speche</L>
<L N="784">Oure counseil was not longe for to seche</L>
<L>vs &thorn;oughte it nas nat wor&thorn; to make it wys</L>
<L>And graunted him wi&thorn;oute more avys</L>
<L>And bad him seie his verdite as him leste</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="788">LOrdynges quo&thorn; he now herkene&thorn; for &thorn;e beste</L>
<L>But taketh not I pray &yogh;ou in disdayn</L>
<L>This is &thorn;e poynt to speken schort and playn</L>
<L>That ech of &yogh;ow to schorte with &yogh;oure weie /</L>
<L N="792">In &thorn;is viage schal telle tales tweye</L>
<L>To Caunturburiward I mene it so</L>
<L>And homward he schal tellen o&thorn;ur tuo</L>
<L>Of auentures &thorn;at &thorn;er han bifalle</L>
<L N="796">And which of &yogh;ow &thorn;at bere&thorn; him best of alle</L>
<L>That is to seye &thorn;at telle&thorn; in &thorn;is caas</L>
<L>Tales of best sentence and of solas</L>
<L>Schal han a soper at &yogh;our al&thorn;er cost<MILESTONE N="11b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="800">Here in &thorn;is place sittynge by &thorn;is post</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at we comen ageyn from Canturbery</L>
<L>And for to make &yogh;ou &thorn;e more mery</L>
<L>I wol my seluen gladly with &yogh;ou ryde</L>
<L N="804">Right at myn owen cost and be &yogh;oure gyde</L>
<L>And who-so wole my Iuggement withseie</L>
<L>Schal paye for al we spenden by &thorn;e weye</L>
<L>And if &yogh;e vouche sauf &thorn;at it be so</L>
<L N="808">Telle me anoon wi&thorn;outen wordes moo</L>
<L>And I wole erely schappe me &thorn;erfore</L>
<L>This &thorn;ing was graunted and oure othus swore</L>
<L>with ful glad herte and prayden him also</L>
<L N="812">That he would vouche sauf for to doon so</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he wolde ben oure gouernour</L>
<L>And of our tales Iugge and reportour</L>
<L>And sette a souper at a certeyn prys</L>
<L N="816">And we wolde rewled be at his deuys</L>
<L>In heygh and lowe. and &thorn;us by oon assent
<PB REF="00000036.tif" N="24"></L>
<L>We been acorded to his Iuggement</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-vpon &thorn;e wyn was fet anoon</L>
<L N="820">we dronken and to reste wente echoon.</L>
<L>wi&thorn;outen eny lengere taryinge</L>
<L>A morwe whan &thorn;at &thorn;e day bigan to sprynge</L>
<L>vp roos oure Ost and was oure althur cok</L>
<L N="824">And gaderud vs to-gidur alle in a flok</L>
<L>And forth we riden a litel more &thorn;an paas</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e waterynge of seint Thomas</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere oure Ost bigan his hors areste</L>
<L N="828">And seyde lordus herkene&thorn; if &yogh;ow leste</L>
<L>&YOGH;e woot &yogh;oure forward and I it &yogh;ou recorde</L>
<L>If euesong and morwesong acorde</L>
<L>Lat se now who schal telle ferst a tale</L>
<L N="832">As euere I moote drinke wyn or ale</L>
<L>who-so be rebel to my Iuggement</L>
<L>Schal paye for al &thorn;at by the weye is spent</L>
<L>Now draweth Cut/ er &thorn;at we forther twynne</L>
<L N="836">which &thorn;at hath &thorn;e schortest schal bygynne</L>
<L>Sire knight quo&thorn; he maister and my lord<MILESTONE N="12a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Now draweth Cut. for &thorn;at is myn acord</L>
<L>Cometh ner quod he my lady prioresse</L>
<L N="840">And &yogh;e sir Clerk lat be &yogh;our schamfastnesse</L>
<L>Ne studieth nat ley hand to euery man</L>
<L>Anon to drawen euery wight bigan</L>
<L>And schortly for to tellen as it was</L>
<L N="844">were it by auenture or sort or cas</L>
<L>The soth is &thorn;is the Cut fil to the knight</L>
<L>Of which ful glad and bli&thorn;e was euery wight</L>
<L>And telle he moste his tale as was resoun</L>
<L N="848">By forward and by composicioun</L>
<L>As &yogh;e han herd what neede&thorn; wordes moo</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is goode man seigh &thorn;at it was so</L>
<L>As he that wys was and obedient</L>
<L N="852">To kepe his forward by his fre assent</L>
<L>He seyde syn I schal bygynne the game
<PB REF="00000037.tif" N="25"></L>
<L>what welcome be &thorn;ou cut. a goddus name</L>
<L>Now lat vs ryde and herkne&thorn; what I seye</L>
<L N="856">And with &thorn;at word we riden for&thorn; oure weye</L>
<L>And he bigan with right a merie chere;</L>
<L>His tale. and seide right in &thorn;is manere.<NOTE PLACE="end">[break of one line in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000038.tif" N="26">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHilom as olde stories tellen vs<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I>12</NOTE></L>
<L N="860">Ther was a Duk &thorn;at highte Theseus</L>
<L>Of Athenes he was. lord and gouernour</L>
<L>And in his tyme swich a conquerour</L>
<L>That gretter was ther non vnder &thorn;e sonne</L>
<L N="864">Ful many a Riche Contre hadde he wonne</L>
<L>That with his wisdam and his chiualrie</L>
<L>He conquered al the regne of Femynye</L>
<L>That whilom was I-cleped Cithea</L>
<L N="868">And weddede the queen Ipolita</L>
<L>And brought hire hoom with him in his Contre</L>
<L>with moche glorie and gret solempnite</L>
<L>And eek hire &yogh;onge suster Emelye</L>
<L N="872">And &thorn;us with victorie and with melodye</L>
<L>Lete I &thorn;is noble duk to Athenes ryde /</L>
<L>And al his Ost in armes him biside<MILESTONE N="12b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>At certes if it nere to long to heere</L>
<L N="876">I wolde han told &yogh;ow fully &thorn;e manere</L>
<L>How wonnen was the regne of Femenye</L>
<L>By Theseus and by his Chiualrye</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e grete bataille for &thorn;e nones</L>
<L N="880">By-twix athenes. and amazones</L>
<L>And how asegid was ypolita</L>
<L>The faire hardy Quyen of Cithea</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e feste that was at hire weddynge</L>
<L N="884">And of &thorn;e tempest at hire hoom comynge</L>
<L>But al &thorn;at &thorn;ing I most as now forbere</L>
<L>I haue god wot a large feeld to Ere</L>
<L>And wayke ben &thorn;e Oxen in my plough</L>
<L N="888">The remenaunt of the tale is long I-nough</L>
<L>I wol not lette eek. non of al &thorn;is rowte
<PB REF="00000039.tif" N="27"></L>
<L>lat euery felawe telle his tale aboute</L>
<L N="891">And lat see now who schal &thorn;e soper wynne</L>
<L>And ther I lafte I wolde agayn begynne<NOTE PLACE="marg">[break of one line in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This Duk of whom I make mencioun</L>
<L>whan he was comen almost vnto &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>In al his wele and in his moste pryde</L>
<L N="896">he was war as he cast his ey&yogh;e aside</L>
<L>wher &thorn;at ther kneled in &thorn;e hye weye</L>
<L>A companye of ladies tweye and tweye</L>
<L>Ech after other clad in clo&thorn;es blake</L>
<L N="900">But such a cry and such a woo &thorn;ey make</L>
<L>That in &thorn;is world nys creature lyuynge</L>
<L>Ther herde such ano&thorn;er weymentynge</L>
<L>And of &thorn;at cry ne wolde &thorn;ey neuer stenten</L>
<L N="904">Til &thorn;ey &thorn;e Reynes of his bridel henten</L>
<L>what folk be &yogh;e &thorn;at at myn hom comynge</L>
<L>Partourben so my feste with cryenge</L>
<L>Quod Theseus. haue &yogh;e so gret enuye</L>
<L N="908">Of myn honour &thorn;at &thorn;us compleyne and crie</L>
<L>Or who hath &yogh;ow mysboden or offendid</L>
<L>And telle&thorn; me if it may ben amendid.</L>
<L>And why &thorn;at &yogh;e ben clad &thorn;us al in blak<MILESTONE N="13a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="912">The oldest lady of hem alle spak</L>
<L>whan sche had swowned with a dedly chere</L>
<L>That it was routhe for to seen or heere</L>
<L>And seyde lord to whom fortune ha&thorn; &yogh;euen</L>
<L N="916">victorie and as a conquerour to luyen</L>
<L>Nought greueth vs &yogh;oure glorie and honour</L>
<L>But we beseken mercy and socour</L>
<L>Haue mercy on oure woo and oure distresse</L>
<L N="920">Som drope of pitee thurgh &yogh;oure gentilnesse</L>
<L>Vppon vs wrecchede wommen lat &thorn;ou falle</L>
<L>For certus lord. ther nys noon of vs alle</L>
<L>That sche nath ben a duchesse or a queene</L>
<L N="924">Now be we Caytifs as it is wel seene</L>
<L>Thanked be fortune. and hire false wheel
<PB REF="00000040.tif" N="28"></L>
<L>That noon estat assureth to ben weel</L>
<L>And certus lord to abiden &yogh;oure presence</L>
<L N="928"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>a later</I> 'here' <I>in margin</I>]</NOTE>Ther in &thorn;e temple of &thorn;e goddesse Clemence</L>
<L>we han ben waytynge al &thorn;is fourtenight</L>
<L>Now helpe vs lord syn it is in &thorn;y might</L>
<L>I wrecche which &thorn;at wepe and waylle &thorn;us</L>
<L N="932">was whilom wyf to kyng Capaneus</L>
<L>That starf at Thebes. cursed be &thorn;at day</L>
<L>And alle we &thorn;at ben in &thorn;is array</L>
<L>And maken alle &thorn;is lamentacioun</L>
<L N="936">we leften alle oure housbondes at &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>whil &thorn;at &thorn;e sege. &thorn;er aboute lay</L>
<L>And &yogh;et &thorn;e olde Creon welaway</L>
<L>That lord is now of thebes &thorn;e citee</L>
<L N="940">Fulfilde of Ire and of Iniquite</L>
<L>He for despyt and for his Tyrannye</L>
<L>To do &thorn;e deede bodyes vilonye</L>
<L>Of alle oure lordes which &thorn;at ben I-slawe</L>
<L N="944">Ha&thorn; alle &thorn;e bodies on an heep y-drawe</L>
<L>And wol not suffren hem by noon assent</L>
<L>Nother to ben y-buried nor I-brent</L>
<L>But make&thorn; houndes ete hem in despite</L>
<L N="948">And with &thorn;at word withoute more respite</L>
<L>They fillen gruf and criden pitously<MILESTONE N="13b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>haue on vs wrecched wommen som mercy</L>
<L>And lat oure sorwe synken in thyn herte</L>
<L N="952">This gentil duke doun from his courser sterte/</L>
<L>with herte pitous whan he herde hem speke</L>
<L>him &thorn;oughte &thorn;at his herte wolde breke</L>
<L>whan he seyh hem so pitous and so maat</L>
<L N="956">That whilom weren of so gret estat</L>
<L>And in his armes he hem alle vp hente</L>
<L>And hem conforte&thorn; in ful good entente</L>
<L>And swor his oth as he was trewe knight</L>
<L N="960">he wolde do so ferfor&thorn;ly his might</L>
<L>vpon &thorn;e tyraunt Creon hem to wreke
<PB REF="00000041.tif" N="29"></L>
<L>That al &thorn;e poeple of grece scholde speke</L>
<L>how Creon was of Theseus y-serued</L>
<L N="964">As he &thorn;at ha&thorn; his deth right wel deserued</L>
<L>And right anoon wi&thorn;oute eny abood</L>
<L>his baner he desplaye&thorn; and for&thorn; rood</L>
<L>To Thebes-ward. and al his oost bysyde</L>
<L N="968">No ner athenes wolde he go ne ryde</L>
<L>Ne take his eese fully half a day</L>
