<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000101.tif" N="89">
<HEAD>&para; And &thorn;us bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e myllere<NOTE PLACE="head">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHan &thorn;at &thorn;e knight had &thorn;us his tale I-told</L>
<L>In al &thorn;e route nas &thorn;er &yogh;ong ne old</L>
<L>That he ne seyde it was a noble story</L>
<L N="3112">And wor&thorn;i to be drawen in memory</L>
<L>And namely &thorn;e gentils euerich oon</L>
<L>Oure host &thorn;o lowh and swoor so moot I goon</L>
<L>This go&thorn; right wel vnbokeled is &thorn;e male /</L>
<L N="3116">Let se now who schal telle ano&thorn;er tale</L>
<L>For trewely &thorn;is game is wel bygonne /</L>
<L>Now telle&thorn; now sir monk if &thorn;at &yogh;e konne</L>
<L>Som what to quyte wi&thorn; &thorn;e knightes tale /</L>
<L N="3120">The Myller &thorn;at for drunken was al pale</L>
<L>So &thorn;at vnnethe vpon his hors he sat<MILESTONE N="42a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he wold auale now&thorn;er hood ne hat</L>
<L>Ne abyde no man for his curtesye</L>
<L N="3124">But in Pilates voys he gan to crye</L>
<L>And swor by armes and by blood and bones</L>
<L>I can a noble tale for &thorn;e noones</L>
<L>with which I wol now quyte &thorn;e knightes tale</L>
<L N="3128">Oure hoost saugh wel how dronke he was of ale</L>
<L>And seyde Robyn abyde my leue bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>Som bettre man schal telle vs first ano&thorn;er</L>
<L>Abyd and let vs worken &thorn;riftyly</L>
<L N="3132">By goddes soule quod he &thorn;at wol nat I</L>
<L>For I wol speke or elles go my way</L>
<L>Oure host answed / tel on a deuel way</L>
<L>Thou art a fool &thorn;y witt is ouercome /</L>
<L N="3136">&para; Now herkne&thorn; quod &thorn;is myller al and some</L>
<L>But first I make a protestacioun</L>
<L>That I am dronke I knowe wel by my soun</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore if &thorn;at I mys speke or seye</L>
<L N="3140">wyte it &thorn;e ale of Southwerk I &yogh;ou preye
<PB REF="00000102.tif" N="90"></L>
<L>For I wol telle a legende and a lyf</L>
<L>Bothe of a Carpenter and of his wyf</L>
<L>how &thorn;at &thorn;e clerk ha&thorn; set &thorn;e wri&yogh;tes cappe /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3144">The reue answered and seyde stynt &thorn;i clappe /</L>
<L>let be &thorn;y lewed drunken harlottrye</L>
<L>It is a synne and eek a greet folye</L>
<L>To apeyren eny man or him defame</L>
<L N="3148">And eek to brynge wyues in ylle name</L>
<L>Thou mayst ynow&yogh; of o&thorn;er &thorn;inges seyn</L>
<L>This dronken Miller spak ful sone a-geyn</L>
<L>And seyde leeue brother Osewold</L>
<L N="3152">who hath no wyf he is no Cokewold</L>
<L>But I seye not &thorn;erfore &thorn;at &thorn;ou art oon</L>
<L>Ther been ful goode wyues many oon</L>
<L>And euer a &thorn;ousand goode agayns oon badde</L>
<L N="3156">That knowest &thorn;ou wel &thorn;y self but if &thorn;ou madde</L>
<L>why art &thorn;ou angry with my tale now /</L>
<L>I haue a wyf par de as wel as thow</L>
<L>&YOGH;it nolde I for the oxen in my plough<MILESTONE N="42b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3160">Take vpon me more &thorn;an ynough</L>
<L>Though &thorn;at &thorn;ou deme &thorn;iself &thorn;at &thorn;ou be oon</L>
<L>I wol bileeue wel &thorn;at I am <NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>a later</I> n <I>prefixt</I>]</NOTE>oon</L>
<L>An housbond schal not be inquisityf</L>
<L N="3164">Of goddes pryuete ne of his wyf</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he fynde goddes foysoun &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e remenaunt neede&thorn; nought enquere /</L>
<L>what schuld I seye but &thorn;at &thorn;is proud Millere</L>
<L N="3168">he nolde his wordes for no man forbere</L>
<L>But tolde his cherlisch tale in his manere</L>
<L>Me a&thorn;inke&thorn; &thorn;at I schal reherce it heere</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfor euery gentil wight I preye.</L>
<L N="3172">For goddes loue as deme nat &thorn;at I seye</L>
<L>Of yuel entent but for I moot reherse</L>
<L>here wordes alle &para; al be &thorn;ey better or werse</L>
<L>Or elles falsen som of my mateere</L>
<L N="3176">And &thorn;erfor who-so list it nat to heere
<PB REF="00000103.tif" N="91"></L>
<L>Turne ouer &thorn;e leef and cheese ano&thorn;er tale</L>
<L>For he schal fynde ynowe bothe gret and smale</L>
<L>Of storial &thorn;ing &thorn;at touche&thorn; gentilesse</L>
<L N="3180">And eek more ryalte and holynesse</L>
<L>Blame&thorn; nat me If &thorn;at &yogh;e cheese amys</L>
<L>The Miller is a cherl &yogh;e know wel &thorn;is</L>
<L>So was &thorn;e reeue and o&thorn;ir many mo</L>
<L N="3184">And harlotry &thorn;ey tolden bo&thorn;e two</L>
<L>Auyse&thorn; &yogh;ou and put me out / of blame</L>
<L>And men schulde nat make ernest of game</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>HEre ende&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e Miller<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000104.tif" N="92">
<HEAD>&para; And bygynneth his tale</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whilom &thorn;er was dwellyng at Oxenford</L>
<L>A riche gnof that gestes heeld to boorde</L>
<L N="3189">And of his craft he was a Carpenter</L>
<L>wi&thorn; him &thorn;er was dwellyng a pore scoler</L>
<L>had lerned art but al his fantasye</L>
<L N="3192">was torned for to lerne astrologye</L>
<L>An cowde a certeyn of conclusiouns</L>
<L>To deme by interrogaciouns</L>
<L>If &thorn;at men axed him in certeyn houres</L>
<L N="3196"><MILESTONE N="43a" UNIT="folio">whan &thorn;at men schuld han drought or ellys schoures</L>
<L>Or if men axed him what schulde bifalle</L>
<L>Of euery &thorn;ing I may nou&yogh;t reken hem alle</L>
<L>This clerk was cleped heende Nicholas</L>
<L N="3200">Of derne loue he cowde and of solas</L>
<L>And &thorn;er wi&thorn; he was sleigh and ful priue</L>
<L>And lik amayden meke for to se</L>
<L>A chambir had he in his hostillerye</L>
<L N="3204">Alone wi&thorn;outen eny compaignye</L>
<L>Ful fetisly I-dight with herbes soote /</L>
<L>And he himself as swete as is &thorn;e roote</L>
<L>Of lokorys or eny Cetewale</L>
<L N="3208">his almagest and bookes gret and smale</L>
<L>his astrylabe longyng for his art</L>
<L>his augrym stoones leyen faire a part</L>
<L>On schelues couched at his beddes heed</L>
<L N="3212">his presse I-couered wi&thorn; a faldyng reed</L>
<L>And al aboue &thorn;er lay a gay Sawtrye</L>
<L>On which he made a nightes melodye</L>
<L>So swetely &thorn;at al &thorn;e chambur rang</L>
<L N="3216">And angelus ad virginem he sang</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at he sang &thorn;e kynges note</L>
<L>Ful often blissed was his mery &thorn;rote
<PB REF="00000105.tif" N="93"></L>
<L>And &thorn;us &thorn;is sweete clerk his tyme spente</L>
<L N="3220">After his frendes fyndyng and his rente</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This carpenter had weddid newe a wyf</L>
<L>which &thorn;at he loved more &thorn;an his lyf</L>
<L>Of ey&yogh;teteene &yogh;eer sche was of age</L>
<L N="3224">Gelous he was and heeld hir narwe in cage</L>
<L>For sche was wilde &amp; &yogh;ong and he was old</L>
<L>And demed himself be lik a Cokewold</L>
<L>he knew nat Catoun for his wit was rude</L>
<L N="3228">That bad man schulde wedde his similitude</L>
<L>Men schulde wedde aftir here astaat</L>
<L>For eelde and &yogh;ou&thorn;e ben often at debaat</L>
<L>But syn &thorn;at he was brou&yogh;t in to &thorn;e snare</L>
<L N="3232">He moste endure as o&thorn;ere doon his care</L>
<L>Fair was &thorn;e &yogh;onge wyf and &thorn;er wi&thorn; al</L>
<L>As eny wesil hir body gent and smal<MILESTONE N="43b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A seynt sche wered barred al of silk</L>
<L N="3236">A barmclo&thorn; eek as whit as morne mylk</L>
<L>vpon hir lendes ful of many a gore</L>
<L>whit was hir smok and browdid albyfore</L>
<L>And eek byhynde on hir coler aboute</L>
<L N="3240">Of coleblak silk wi&thorn;inne and eek wi&thorn;oute</L>
<L>The tapes of hir white voluper</L>
<L>weren of &thorn;e same sute of hire coler</L>
<L>hir filet brood of silk y-set ful heye</L>
<L N="3244">And certeynly sche hadd a licorous ey&yogh;e</L>
<L>Ful smal y-pulled weren hir browes two /</L>
<L>And &thorn;o were bent as blak as a slo</L>
<L>Sche was wel more blisful on to see</L>
<L N="3248">Than is &thorn;e newe perionette tree</L>
<L>And softer &thorn;an &thorn;e wol is of a we&thorn;ir</L>
<L>And by hir gurdil hyng a purs of le&thorn;ir</L>
<L>Tassid wi&thorn; silk and perled wi&thorn; latoun</L>
<L N="3252">In al &thorn;is world to seken vp and doun</L>
<L>Ther nys no man so wys &thorn;at cou&thorn;e &thorn;enche /</L>
<L>So gay a popillot or such a wenche /
<PB REF="00000106.tif" N="94"></L>
<L>For brighter was &thorn;e smylyng of hir hewe</L>
<L N="3256">Than in &thorn;e tour &thorn;e noble I-forged newe</L>
<L>But of hir song it was as lowde and &yogh;erne</L>
<L>As eny swalwe chiteryng on a berne</L>
<L>Ther to sche cowde skippe and make game</L>
<L N="3260">As eny kyde or calf folowyng his dame</L>
<L>hir mouth was sweete as bragat is or meth</L>
<L>Or hoord of apples layd in hay or heth</L>
<L>wynsyng sche was as is a Ioly colt</L>
<L N="3264">long as a mast / and vpright as a bolt /</L>
<L>A broch sche bar vpon hir loue coleer</L>
<L>As brod as is &thorn;e bos of a bocleer</L>
<L>hir schos were laced / on hir legges hey&yogh;e</L>
<L N="3268">Sche was a primerole<NOTE PLACE="marg">[a later &amp; is put in here]</NOTE> a pigges ney&yogh;e</L>
<L>For eny lord haue liggyng in his bedde</L>
<L>Or &yogh;et for eny good &yogh;eman to wedde</L>
<L>Now sir and eft sir / so bifel &thorn;e cas</L>
<L N="3272">That on a day &thorn;is heende Nicholas<MILESTONE N="44a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Fil wi&thorn; &thorn;is &yogh;onge wyf to rage and pleye</L>
<L>whil &thorn;at hir housbond was at Oseneye</L>
<L>As clerkes ben ful sotil and ful queynte</L>
<L N="3276">And pryuely he caught hir by &thorn;e queynte</L>
<L>And seyde I-wis but if I haue my wille</L>
<L>For derne loue of &thorn;e lemman I spille /</L>
<L>And heeld hir harde by &thorn;e haunche boones</L>
<L N="3280">And seyde lemman loue me al at ones</L>
<L>Or I wol dye as wisly god me saue</L>
<L>And sche sprang out / as do&thorn; a colt/ in traue</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; hir heed sche wried fast awey</L>
<L N="3284">I seyde I wol nat kisse &thorn;e by my fey</L>
<L>why let be quod sche / lat be &thorn;ou nicholas /</L>
<L>Or I wol crye out harrow and allas</L>
<L>Do wey &yogh;our handes for &yogh;our curtesye</L>
<L N="3288">This nicholas gan mercy for to crye</L>
<L>And spak so faire and profred him so faste/</L>
<L>That sche hir loue him graunted atte laste /
<PB REF="00000107.tif" N="95"></L>
<L>And swor hir oth / by seynt thomas of kent</L>
<L N="3292">That sche wol be at his comaundement</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at sche may hir leysir wel aspye</L>
<L>Myn housbond is so ful of Ielousie /</L>
<L>That but &yogh;e wayten wel and be pryue</L>
<L N="3296">I woot right wel I am but deed quod sche</L>
<L>&YOGH;e mosten be ful derne as in &thorn;is caas</L>
<L>Ther of ne care &thorn;e nought quod Nicholas</L>
<L>A clerk ha&thorn; litherly byset his while</L>
<L N="3300">But if he cowde a carpenter bygyle</L>
<L>And &thorn;us &thorn;ey ben acorded and I-sworn</L>
<L>To wayte a tyme as I haue told biforn</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan Nicholas had doon &thorn;us euery del</L>
<L N="3304">And thakked hire aboute &thorn;e lendys wel</L>
<L>he kist hir sweet / and take&thorn; his sawtrye</L>
<L>And pleye&thorn; fast and make&thorn; melodye</L>
<L>Than fyl it &thorn;us / &thorn;at to &thorn;e parisch chirche /</L>
<L N="3308">Cristes owen werkes for to wirche</L>
<L>This goode wyf / went on an haly day</L>
<L>Hir forheed schon as bright as eny day<MILESTONE N="44b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So was it waisschen whan sche leet hir werk</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3312">NOw &thorn;er was of &thorn;at chirche a parisch clerk</L>
<L>The which &thorn;at was I-cleped Absolon</L>
<L>Crulle was his heer and as &thorn;e gold it schon</L>
<L>And strowted as a fan right large and brood</L>
<L N="3316">Ful streyt and euene lay his ioly schood</L>
<L>his rode was reed his ey&yogh;en gray as goos</L>
<L>with Powles wyndowes coruen in his schoos</L>
<L>In his hoses reed he went fetusly</L>
<L N="3320">I-clad he was ful smal and propurly</L>
<L>Al in a kirtel of a fyn wachet</L>
<L>Schapen with goores in &thorn;e newe get</L>
<L>And &thorn;er vpon he had a gay surplys</L>
<L N="3324">As whyt as is &thorn;e blosme vpon &thorn;e rys</L>
<L>A mery child he was so god me saue</L>
<L>wel cou&thorn;e he lete blood and clippe and schaue
<PB REF="00000108.tif" N="96"></L>
<L>And make a chartre of lond and acquitaunce</L>
<L N="3328">In twenty maners he coude skip and daunce</L>
<L>After &thorn;e scole of Oxenforde &thorn;o</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his legges casten to and fro</L>
<L>And pleyen songes on a smal rubible</L>
<L N="3332">Therto he sang som tyme a lowde quynyble</L>
<L>And as wel coude he pleye on a giterne /</L>
<L>In al &thorn;e toun nas brewhous ne tauerne</L>
<L>That he ne visited with his solas</L>
<L N="3336">Ther as any gaylard tapster was</L>
<L>Bot so&thorn; to say he was som del squaymous</L>
<L>Of fartyng / and of speche daungerous</L>
<L>This absolon &thorn;at ioly was and gay</L>
<L N="3340">Go&thorn; wi&thorn; a senser on &thorn;e haly day</L>
<L>Sensyng &thorn;e wyues of &thorn;e parisch fast</L>
<L>And many a louely look on hem he cast</L>
<L>And namely on &thorn;is Carpenteres wyf</L>
<L N="3344">To loke on hire him &thorn;ought a mery lyf</L>
<L>Sche was so propre sweete and licorous</L>
<L>I dar wel sayn if sche had ben a mous</L>
<L>And he a cat he wold hir hent anoon</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3348">This parisch clerk this Ioly Absolon<MILESTONE N="45a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ha&thorn; in his herte such a loue longyng</L>
<L>That of no wyf ne took he noon offryng /</L>
<L>For curtesy he seyde he wolde noon</L>
<L N="3352">The moone at night ful cleer and brighte schoon</L>
<L>And absolon his giterne ha&thorn; I-take</L>
<L>For paramours he seyde he wold awake /</L>
<L>And for he go&thorn; iolyf and amerous /</L>
<L N="3356">Til he cam to &thorn;e Carpenteres hous</L>
<L>A litel after &thorn;e cok had y-crowe /</L>
<L>And dressed him vp by a schot wyndowe /</L>
<L>That was vnder &thorn;e Carpenteres wal</L>
<L N="3360">he synge&thorn; in his voys gentil and smal</L>
<L>Now deere lady if &thorn;i wille be</L>
<L>I praye &yogh;ow &thorn;at &yogh;e wol rewe on me
<PB REF="00000109.tif" N="97"></L>
<L>Ful wel acordyng to his gyternyng</L>
<L N="3364">This carpenter awook and herde him syng</L>
<L>And spak vnto his wyf and sayde anoon</L>
<L>what alisoun herestow not absolon</L>
<L>That chaunte&thorn; &thorn;us vnder oure boure smal</L>
<L N="3368">And sche answerd hir housbond &thorn;er wi&thorn; al</L>
<L>&YOGH;is God woot Iohn I heere it euery del</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This passe&thorn; forth what wil &yogh;e bet &thorn;an wel</L>
<L>Fro day to day &thorn;is Ioly Absolon</L>
<L N="3372">So wowe&thorn; hire &thorn;at him is wo bigon</L>
<L>he wake&thorn; al &thorn;e night and al &thorn;e day</L>
<L>To kembe his lokkes brode and made him gay</L>
<L>he wowith hire by mene and by brocage</L>
<L N="3376">And swor he wolde ben hir owne page /</L>
<L>he synge&thorn; crowyng as a nightyngale</L>
<L>And sent hire pyment meth and spiced ale /</L>
<L>And wafres pypyng hoot out of &thorn;e gleede</L>
<L N="3380">For &thorn;at sche was of toune he profred meede</L>
<L>For som folk wol be wonne for richesse</L>
<L>And som for strokes som for gentillesse</L>
<L>Som tyme to schewe his lightnes and maistrye</L>
<L N="3384">he pleyeth herod&yogh; on a scaffold hye</L>
<L>But what avayle&thorn; him as in &thorn;is caas /</L>
<L>Sche loue&thorn; so &thorn;is heende Nicholas<MILESTONE N="45b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That absolon may blowe &thorn;e bukkes horn</L>
<L N="3388">he ne had for al his labour but a skorn</L>
<L>And &thorn;us sche make&thorn; absolon hir ape</L>
<L>And al his ernest torne&thorn; to a Iape</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ful so&thorn; is &thorn;is prouerbe it is no lye</L>
<L N="3392">Men seyn right &thorn;us alway &thorn;e ney slye</L>
<L>Make&thorn; &thorn;e ferre leef to be lo&thorn;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ough &thorn;at absolon be wood or wroth</L>
<L>By cause &thorn;at he fer was from here sight</L>
<L N="3396">This Nicholas ha&thorn; stonden in his light</L>
<L>Now bere &thorn;e wel &thorn;ou heende Nicholas</L>
<L>For absolon may wayle and synge allas
<PB REF="00000110.tif" N="98"></L>
<L>&para; And so bifell it on a Satyrday</L>
<L N="3400">This Carpenter was gon to Osenay</L>
<L>And heende Nicholas and alisoun</L>
<L>Acordid ben to &thorn;is conclusioun</L>
<L>That Nicholas schal schapen hem a wyle</L>
<L N="3404">This sely Ielous housbond to begyle /</L>
<L>And if so were &thorn;is game wente aright</L>
<L>Sche schulde slepe in his arm al night</L>
<L>For &thorn;is was hire desir and his also</L>
<L N="3408">And right anoon wi&thorn;outen wordes mo</L>
<L>This Nicholas no lenger wold he tarye</L>
<L>But do&thorn; ful softe in to his Chambur carye</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e mete and drynke for a day or tweye</L>
<L N="3412">And to hir housbond bad hir for to seye</L>
<L>If &thorn;at he axed after Nicholas</L>
<L>Sche schulde seye sche wiste nat wher he was</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;at day sche saw him nat with eye</L>
<L N="3416">Sche trowed he were falle in som maladye</L>
<L>For no cry &thorn;at hir mayden cowde him calle</L>
<L>he nolde answere for nought &thorn;at may bifalle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This passe&thorn; for&thorn; al &thorn;at ilke satyrday</L>
<L N="3420">Tha Nicholas in his chambre lay</L>
<L>And eet and drank and dede what/ him leste</L>
<L>Til soneday &thorn;e sonne was gon to reste</L>
<L>This sely carpenter ha&thorn; gret meruaile<MILESTONE N="46a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3424">Of Nicholas or what &thorn;ing may him ayle</L>
<L>And seyde I am a-drad by seynt Thomas</L>
<L>It stonde&thorn; nat aright wi&thorn; Nicholas</L>
<L>God schilde &thorn;at he deyde sodeinly</L>
<L N="3428">This world is now ful tykel sikerly</L>
<L>I saugh to-day a corps y-born to chirche</L>
<L>That now on monday last I saugh him wirche</L>
<L>Go vp quod he vnto his knaue anoon</L>
<L N="3432">Clepe at his dore and knokke wi&thorn; a stoon</L>
<L>Loke how it is and telle me boldely</L>
<L>This knaue go&thorn; him vp ful sturdily
<PB REF="00000111.tif" N="99"></L>
<L>And at &thorn;e chambir dore whil he stood</L>
<L N="3436">he cryed and knokked as &thorn;at he were wood</L>
<L>what how what do &yogh;e mayster nicholay</L>
<L>how may &yogh;e slepen al &thorn;is longe day</L>
<L>But al for nought he herde nat o word</L>
<L N="3440">An hole he fond right lowe vpon a boord</L>
<L>Ther as &thorn;e cat was wont in for to creepe /</L>
<L>And at &thorn;at hole he loked in ful deepe /</L>
<L>And atte laste he hadde of him a sight</L>
<L N="3444">This nicholas sat euer gapyng vpright</L>
<L>As he had loked on &thorn;e newe moone</L>
<L>Adoun he go&thorn; and tolde his mayster soone</L>
<L>In what aray he sawh &thorn;is ilke man</L>
<L N="3448">This carpenter to blessen him bygan</L>
<L>And seyde now help vs seynte Frideswyde</L>
<L>A man woot litel what him schal betyde</L>
<L>This man is falle with his astronomye</L>
<L N="3452">In som woodnesse or in som agonye</L>
<L>I thought ay wel how &thorn;at it schulde be</L>
<L>Men schulde nought knowe of goddes pryuyte</L>
<L>&para; &YOGH;e blessed be alwey a lewed man</L>
<L N="3456">That nat but oonly his bileeue can</L>
<L>So ferde ano&thorn;er clerk with astronomye /</L>
<L>he walked in the feeldes for to prye</L>
<L>vpon &thorn;e sterres what &thorn;er schulde bifalle</L>
<L N="3460">Til he was in a marle pit I-falle /</L>
<L>he saugh nat &thorn;at but &yogh;et by seint Thomas /</L>
<L>Me reweth sore for heende nicholas<MILESTONE N="46b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he schal be ratyd of his studyyng</L>
<L N="3464">If &thorn;at I may by ih&umacr; heuen kyng</L>
<L>Gete me a staf &thorn;at I may vnder spore</L>
<L>whil &thorn;at &thorn;ou Robyn heuest vp &thorn;e dore</L>
<L>he schal out of his studyyng as I gesse</L>
<L N="3468">And to &thorn;e chambir dore he gan him dresse /</L>
<L>his knaue was a strong karl for &thorn;e noones</L>
<L>And by &thorn;e hasp he haf it vp at oones
<PB REF="00000112.tif" N="100"></L>
<L>And in &thorn;e floor &thorn;e dore fil doun anoon</L>
<L N="3472">This nicholas sat stille as eny stoon</L>
<L>And euer he capyd vpward to &thorn;e eyr</L>
<L>This Carpenter wende he were in despeir</L>
<L>And hent him by &thorn;e schuldres mightily</L>
<L N="3476">And schook him harde and cryed spitously</L>
<L>what Nicholas what how man loke a doun</L>
<L>A-wake and &thorn;ynk on cristes passioun</L>
<L>I crowche &thorn;e from Elues and from wightes</L>
<L N="3480">Ther-with &thorn;e night-spel seyde he anon rightes</L>
<L>On &thorn;e foure halues of &thorn;e hous aboute /</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e &thorn;reisshfold of &thorn;e dore wi&thorn;oute</L>
<L>lord Ih&umacr; crist and seynte bendight</L>
<L N="3484">Blesse &thorn;is hous from euery wikkede wight</L>
<L>for nyghtes verray &thorn;e white pater-noster</L>
<L>wher wonestow now, seynte petres soster</L>
<L>And atte laste heende Nicholas</L>
<L N="3488">Gan for to syke sore and seyde allas</L>
<L>Schal al &thorn;e world be lost eft sones now</L>
<L>This Carpenter answerde what seystow /</L>
<L>what &thorn;enk on god as we doon men &thorn;at swynke</L>
<L N="3492">This Nicholas answerde fette me drynke</L>
<L>And after wol I speke in pryuyte</L>
<L>Of certeyn &thorn;ing &thorn;at touche&thorn; &thorn;e and me</L>
<L>I wol telle it non o&thorn;er man certayn</L>
<L N="3496">This Carpenter go&thorn; forth and com&thorn; agayn</L>
<L>And brought of mighty ale a large quart/</L>
<L>whan ech of hem y-dronken had his part</L>
<L>This Nicholas his dore gan to schitte</L>
<L N="3500">And dede &thorn;is carpenter doun by him sitte<MILESTONE N="47a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And seide Iohan myn host ful leue and deere</L>
<L>Thou schalt vpon &thorn;y trou&thorn;e swere me heere /</L>
<L>That to no wight &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;is counsel wreye</L>
<L N="3504">For it is cristes counsel &thorn;at I seye</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou telle it man &thorn;ou art forlore</L>
