<L N="3816">This Carpenter out of his slumber sterte</L>
<L>And herd on crye watir as he were wood</L>
<L>He &thorn;ought allas for now come&thorn; Noes flood</L>
<L>he sit him vp wi&thorn;oute wordes mo</L>
<L N="3820">And wi&thorn; his ax he smot &thorn;e corde a-two</L>
<L>And doun he go&thorn; he fond nowthir to selle /</L>
<L>No bred ne ale til he com to &thorn;e selle/</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e floor and &thorn;er aswoun he lay</L>
<L N="3824">vp styrt hir alisoun and Nicholay</L>
<L>And cryden out and harrow in &thorn;e strete /</L>
<L>The neyghebours bo&thorn;e smal and grete /</L>
<L>In ronnen for to gauren on &thorn;is man</L>
<L N="3828">That a swowne lay bo&thorn;e pale and wan</L>
<L>For with &thorn;e fal he brosten had his arm</L>
<L>But stond he muste to his owne harm</L>
<L>For whan he spak he was anon born doun</L>
<L N="3832">with heende Nicholas and alisoun
<PB REF="00000122.tif" N="110"></L>
<L>They tolden euery man &thorn;at he was wood</L>
<L>he was a gast and feerd of Noes flood</L>
<L>Thurgh fantasie &thorn;at of his vanite /</L>
<L N="3836">he hadde I-bought him knedyng tubbes &thorn;re /</L>
<L>And hadde hem hanged in &thorn;e roof aboue /</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he preyed hem for goddes loue /</L>
<L>To sitten in &thorn;e roof par compaignye</L>
<L N="3840">The folk gan lawhen at his fantasye /</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e roof &thorn;ey kyken and &thorn;ey gape</L>
<L>And torne al his harm in to a Iape</L>
<L>For what so euer &thorn;e carpenter answerde</L>
<L N="3844">Hit was for nought no man his resoun herde<MILESTONE N="51b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>wi&thorn; o&thorn;is greet he was so sworn a doun</L>
<L>That he was holden wood in al &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>For euery clerk anon right heeld wi&thorn; o&thorn;ir</L>
<L N="3848">They seyde &thorn;e man was wood my leeue bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>And euery man gan lawhen at his stryf</L>
<L>Thus swyued was &thorn;e Carpenteres wyf</L>
<L>For al his kepyng and his gelousye</L>
<L N="3852">And absolon ha&thorn; kist hir ne&thorn;ir ye</L>
<L>And Nicholas is skaldid in his towte</L>
<L>This tale is doon and god saue al &thorn;e route</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>HEre endeth &thorn;e Millers tale<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000123.tif" N="111">
<HEAD>&para; And bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e Reeue</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan folk hadde lawhen of &thorn;is nyce caas</L>
<L N="3856">Of Absolon and heende Nicholas</L>
<L>Dyuerse folk dyuersely &thorn;ey seyde</L>
<L>But for &thorn;e moste part &thorn;ey lowh and pleyde /</L>
<L>Ne at &thorn;is tale I sawh no man him greue</L>
<L N="3860">But it were oonly Osewald &thorn;e Reeue</L>
<L>By cause he was of Carpentrye craft</L>
<L>A litel Ire is in his herte is laft</L>
<L>He gan to grucche and blamed it a lite</L>
<L N="3864">So theek quod he ful wel coude I &thorn;e quyte</L>
<L>with bleryng of a prowd mylleres ye</L>
<L>If &thorn;at me luste speke of Ribaudye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But yk am old me list not pley for age</L>
<L N="3868">Gras tyme is doon my foddir is now forage</L>
<L>My whyte top write&thorn; myn olde &yogh;eeres /</L>
<L>Myn hert is al so moulyd as myn heeres /</L>
<L>And &yogh;it I fare as do&thorn; an open-ers</L>
<L N="3872">That ilke fruyt is euer lenger &thorn;e wers</L>
<L>Til it be rote in mullok or in stree</L>
<L>we olde men I drede so fare we /</L>
<L>Til we be roten can we nat be rype</L>
<L N="3876">we hoppen alway whil &thorn;e world wol pype</L>
<L>For in oure wil &thorn;er stike&thorn; euer a nayl</L>
<L>To haue an hoor heed and a greene tayl</L>
<L>As hath a leek for &thorn;ough oure might be doon</L>
<L N="3880">Oure wil desire&thorn; folye euer in oon</L>
<L>For whan we may nat do &thorn;an wol we speke /<MILESTONE N="52a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;et in oure aisshen old is fyr I-reke /</L>
<L>Foure gledys haue we which I schal deuyse</L>
<L N="3884">Auantyng / lyyng / angur coueytise</L>
<L>This foure sparkys longen vnto eelde /</L>
<L>Oure olde lymes mowen be vnweelde /
<PB REF="00000124.tif" N="112"></L>
<L>But wil ne schal nat fayle vs &thorn;at is so&thorn;</L>
<L N="3888">And &yogh;et I haue alwey a coltes to&thorn;</L>
<L>As many a &yogh;eer as it is passed henne</L>
<L>Syn &thorn;at my tappe of lyf bygan to renne /</L>
<L>For sikirlik whan I was born anon</L>
<L N="3892">Deth drough &thorn;e tappe of lyf and leet it goon</L>
<L>And now so longe / ha&thorn; &thorn;e tappe I-ronne</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at almost al empty is &thorn;e tonne</L>
<L>The streem of lyf now droppeth on &thorn;e chymbe</L>
<L N="3896">The sely tonge may wel rynge and chimbe<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? <I>first</I> clymbe]</NOTE></L>
<L>Of wrecchednes &thorn;at passed is ful &yogh;oore</L>
<L>with olde folk / sauf dotage is no more</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan &thorn;at oure host had herd oure sermonyng</L>
<L N="3900">he gan to speke as lordly as a kyng</L>
<L>And seyde what amounte&thorn; al &thorn;is wit</L>
<L>what schul we speke alday of holy wryt</L>
<L>The deuyl made a Reue for to preche</L>
<L N="3904">Or of a sowter schipman or a leche /</L>
<L>Sey for&thorn; &thorn;i tale and tarye nat &thorn;e tyme</L>
<L>Lo heer is Depford / and it is passed prime</L>
<L>Lo Grenewich &thorn;er many a schrewe is Inne</L>
<L N="3908">It were al tyme &thorn;i tale to bygynne</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOw sires quod &thorn;is Osewold &thorn;e Reue</L>
<L>I pray &yogh;ow alle // &thorn;at noon of &yogh;ou him greeue</L>
<L>Though I answere and somwhat sette his howue</L>
<L N="3912">For leeful is wi&thorn; force force to showue</L>
<L>This dronken myllere ha&thorn; I-told vs heer</L>
<L>how &thorn;at bygiled was a Carpenter</L>
<L>Parauenture in scorn for I am oon</L>
<L N="3916">And by &yogh;our leue I schal him quyte anoon</L>
<L>Right in his cherles termes wol I speke /</L>
<L>I pray to God his nekke mot tobreke</L>
<L>he can wel in myn eye see a stalke<MILESTONE N="52b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3920">But in his owne he can nought seen a balke</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>HEre ende&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e Reue<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000125.tif" N="113">
<HEAD>And here bygynne&thorn; his tale</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT Trompyngtoun nat fer fro Cantebrigge</L>
<L>Ther goth a brook and ouer &thorn;at a brigge</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e whiche brook &thorn;er stant a melle</L>
<L N="3924">And &thorn;is is verray so&thorn; &thorn;at I &yogh;ou telle /</L>
<L>A meller was &thorn;er dwellyng many a day</L>
<L>As eny Pecok he was prowd and gay</L>
<L>Pipen he coude and fissh and nettys beete</L>
<L N="3928">And turne cuppes wrastle wel and scheete</L>
<L>Ay by his belt he bar a long panade</L>
<L>And of a swerd ful trenchaunt was &thorn;e blade</L>
<L>A Ioly popper bar he in his pouche</L>
<L N="3932">Ther was no man for perel durst him touche /</L>
<L>A Scheffeld thwitel bar he in his hose</L>
<L>Round was his face and camois was his nose</L>
<L>As pyled as an ape was his skulle/</L>
<L N="3936">he was a market beter at &thorn;e fulle</L>
<L>Ther durste no wight hand vpon him legge</L>
<L>That he ne swor anon he schuld abegge /</L>
<L>A &thorn;eef he was for-so&thorn; of corn and mele</L>
<L N="3940">And &thorn;at a sleigh and vsyng for to stele /</L>
<L>his name was hoote deynous Symekyn</L>
<L>A wyf he hadde / come of noble kyn</L>
<L>The parsoun of the toun hir fader was</L>
<L N="3944">with hire he &yogh;af ful many a panne of bras</L>
<L>For &thorn;at Symkyn schuld in his blood allye</L>
<L>Sche was I-fostryd in a Nonnerye</L>
<L>For Symkyn wolde no wyf as he sayde</L>
<L N="3948">But sche were wel I-norissched and a mayde /</L>
<L>To sauen his estaat and &yogh;omanrye</L>
<L>And sche was proud and pert/ as is a pye</L>
<L>A ful fair sighte was &thorn;er on hem two /</L>
<L N="3952">On haly dayes bifore hir wolde he go
<PB REF="00000126.tif" N="114"></L>
<L>with his typet ybounde aboute his heed</L>
<L>And sche cam aftir in a gyte of reed</L>
<L>And Symkyn hadde hosen of &thorn;e same /<MILESTONE N="53a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3956">Ther durste no wight clepe hir but ma dame /</L>
<L>was noon so hardy walkyng by &thorn;e weye</L>
<L>That with hir dorste rage or elles pleye</L>
<L>But if he wold be slayn of Symekyn&middot;</L>
<L N="3960">wi&thorn; panade or with knyf or boydekyn&middot;</L>
<L>For gelous folk ben perilous eueremo</L>
<L>Algate &thorn;ey wolde here wyues wende so</L>
<L>And eek for sche was somdel smoterlich</L>
<L N="3964">Sche was as deyne as water in a dich</L>
<L>As ful of hokir and of bissemare</L>
<L>hir thoughte ladyes oughten hir to spare /</L>
<L>what for hir kynreed and hir nortelrye</L>
<L N="3968">That sche had lerned in &thorn;e Nonnerye</L>
<L>A dou&yogh;ter hadden &thorn;ey betwix hem two</L>
<L>Of .xx.<SUP>ti</SUP> &yogh;eer wi&thorn;outen eny mo</L>
<L>Sauyng a child that was of half &yogh;er age</L>
<L N="3972">In cradil lay and was a proper page /</L>
<L>This wenche &thorn;ikke and wel I-growen was</L>
<L>wi&thorn; Camoys nose and ey&yogh;en gray as glas /</L>
<L>And buttokkes brode and brestes round and hye</L>
<L N="3976">But right fair was hir heer I wol nat lye /</L>
<L>The parsoun of &thorn;e toun for sche was feir</L>
<L>In purpos was to maken hir his heir /</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e of his catel / and his mesuage /</L>
<L N="3980">And straunge made it of hir mariage</L>
<L>his purpos was to bystow hir hye</L>
<L>In to som wor&thorn;y blood of ancetrye</L>
<L>For holy chirche good moot be despendid</L>
<L N="3984">On holy chirche blood &thorn;at is descendid</L>
<L>Therfore he wolde his Ioly blood honoure /</L>
<L>Though &thorn;at he schulde holy chirche deuoure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>GRet soken had &thorn;is meller oute of doute</L>
<L N="3988">with whete and malt of al &thorn;e lond aboute
<PB REF="00000127.tif" N="115"></L>
<L>And namely &thorn;er was a gret Collegge</L>
<L>Men clepe it &thorn;e Soler hall of Cantebregge</L>
<L>Ther was here whete and eek here malt I-grounde /</L>
<L N="3992">And on a day it happed on a stounde /</L>
<L>Syk lay &thorn;e mauncyple on a maledye<MILESTONE N="53b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Men wenden wisly &thorn;at he schulde dye</L>
<L>For which &thorn;is meller stal both mele &amp; corn</L>
<L N="3996">A &thorn;ousend part more &thorn;an byforn</L>
<L>For &thorn;er biforn he stal but curteysly</L>
<L>But now he is a &thorn;eef outrageously</L>
<L>For which &thorn;e wardeyn chidde and made fare</L>
<L N="4000">But ther of sette &thorn;e meller not a tare</L>
<L>he crakked boost and swor it was nat so</L>
<L>Thanne weren &thorn;ere poore scoleres tuo</L>
<L>That dwelten in &thorn;e halle of which I seye</L>
<L N="4004">Testyf &thorn;ey were and lusty for to pleye</L>
<L>And oonly for here mir&thorn;e and reuelrye<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>the</I> l <I>is later</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e wardeyn bysily &thorn;ey crye</L>
<L>To &yogh;eue hem leue but a litel stounde /</L>
<L N="4008">To go to melle and see here corn I-grounde</L>
<L>And hardily &thorn;ey dursten ley here nekke /</L>
<L>The meller schuld nat stel hem half a pekke</L>
<L>Of corn by sleighte ne by force hem reue</L>
<L N="4012">And atte last &thorn;e wardeyn &yogh;af hem leue</L>
<L>Iohn hight &thorn;at oon and Alayn hight &thorn;at o&thorn;er</L>
<L>Of o toun were &thorn;ey born &thorn;at highte Strothir /</L>
<L>Fer in &thorn;e north I can nat telle where /</L>
<L N="4016">This aleyn make&thorn; redy al his gere</L>
<L>And on an hors &thorn;e sak he cast anoon</L>
<L>For&thorn; go&thorn; aleyn &thorn;e clerk and also Ion</L>
<L>wi&thorn; good swerd and wi&thorn; bocler by her side</L>
<L N="4020">Iohn knew &thorn;e way &thorn;at hem needith no gyde /</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e mylle &thorn;e sak a-doun he layth</L>
<L>Alayn spak first al heil Symond in faith</L>
<L>how fares &thorn;y faire doughter and &thorn;y wyf</L>
<L N="4024">aleyn welcome quod Symond by my lyf
<PB REF="00000128.tif" N="116"></L>
<L>And Iohn also how now what do &yogh;e heere</L>
<L>By god quod Iohn, Symond, neede has na peere</L>
<L>him falles serue himself &thorn;at has na swayn</L>
<L N="4028">Or elles he is a fon as clerkes sayn</L>
<L>Our mancyple as I hope wil be deed</L>
<L>Swa werkes ay &thorn;e wanges in his heed</L>
<L>And therfore I is come and eek aleyn<MILESTONE N="54a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4032">To grynde oure corn and carie it / ham ageyn</L>
<L>I prey &yogh;ou speed vs in al &thorn;at &yogh;e may</L>
<L>It schal be doon quod Symkyn by my fay</L>
<L>what wol &yogh;e do whil &thorn;at it is in hande</L>
<L N="4036">By god right by &thorn;e hoper wol I stande</L>
<L>Quod Iohn and se how &thorn;at &thorn;e corn gas Inne</L>
<L>&YOGH;et sawh I neuer by my fader kynne /</L>
<L>how &thorn;at &thorn;e hoper waggis to and fra</L>
<L N="4040">Aleyn answerde / Iohn and wiltow swa</L>
<L>Than wol I be by-ne&thorn;e by my croun</L>
<L>And se how &thorn;at &thorn;e mele fallys doun</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e trough &thorn;at schal be my desport /</L>
<L N="4044">For Ion in faith I may be of &yogh;our sort</L>
<L>I is as ille a meller as ere &yogh;e</L>
<L>This mellere smyleth for here nycete</L>
<L>And &thorn;ought al &thorn;is is doon but for a wyle</L>
<L N="4048">They wenen &thorn;at no man may hem bigile</L>
<L>But by my &thorn;rift &yogh;et schal I blere here ye</L>
<L>For al here sleight and al here philosophie /</L>
<L>The more queynte knakkes &thorn;at &thorn;ey make /</L>
<L N="4052">The more wol I stele whan I take /</L>
<L>In stede of mele &yogh;et wol I &yogh;eue hem bren</L>
<L>The grettest clerkes be&thorn; not wisest men</L>
<L>As whilom to &thorn;e wolf &thorn;us spak &thorn;e mare</L>
<L N="4056">Of al hert art ne counte I nat a tare</L>
<L>Out at &thorn;e dore he goth ful pryuyly</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at he saugh his tyme sotyly</L>
<L>he loke&thorn; vp and doun til he hath founde</L>
<L N="4060">The Clerkes hors &thorn;er as it stood I-bounde /
<PB REF="00000129.tif" N="117"></L>
<L>Behynde &thorn;e mylle vnder a leuesel</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e hors he go&thorn; him faire and wel</L>
<L>He strepeth of &thorn;e bridel right anoon</L>
<L N="4064">And whan &thorn;e hors was loos he gan to goon</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e fen &thorn;ere wilde mares renne</L>
<L>For wi&thorn; wihe / &thorn;urgh &thorn;ikke and eek &thorn;urgh &thorn;enne</L>
<L>This meller goth agayn and no word seyde</L>
<L N="4068">But doth his note and wi&thorn; &thorn;e clerkes pleyde /</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at her corn was fair and wel I-grounde<MILESTONE N="54b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And whan &thorn;e mele was sakked and I-bounde /</L>
<L>This Iohn go&thorn; out and fynt his hors a-way</L>
<L N="4072">And gan to crye harrow and weylaway</L>
<L>Oure hors is lost aleyn for goddes banes</L>
<L>Step on &thorn;y feet cum on man al at anes</L>
<L>Aleyn &yogh;our wardeyn ha&thorn; his parfray lorn</L>
<L N="4076">This aleyn al forgete&thorn; mele and corn</L>
<L>Al was out of his mynd his housbondrye</L>
<L>what wikked way is he gan gan he crye</L>
<L>The wyf cam lepyng inward wi&thorn; a ren</L>
<L N="4080">Sche seyde allas &yogh;our hors go&thorn; to &thorn;e fen</L>
<L>wi&thorn; wylde mares as fast as he may go /</L>
<L>vn&thorn;ank come on his heed &thorn;at band him so /</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at bettir schuld han knyt &thorn;e Reyne</L>
<L N="4084">Allas quod Iohan aleyn / for cristes peyne</L>
<L>Leg doun &thorn;i swerd and I sal myn alswa /</L>
<L>I is ful wight god wat as is a Ra</L>
<L>By goddes hart/ he sal nat scape vs bathe</L>
<L N="4088">why nad &thorn;ou put &thorn;e capil in &thorn;e lathe</L>
<L>Ilhail aleyn by god &thorn;ou is a fon</L>
<L>This sely clerkes speeden hem anoon</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e fen bo&thorn;e aleyn and eek Ion</L>
<L N="4092">And whan &thorn;e myller sawh &thorn;at &thorn;ey were gon</L>
<L>he half a busshel of &thorn;e flour ha&thorn; take</L>
<L>And bad his wyf go knede it in a cake</L>
<L>he seyde I trowe &thorn;e clerkes ben a ferd</L>
<L N="4096">&YOGH;et can a Miller make a clerkes berd
<PB REF="00000130.tif" N="118"></L>
<L>For al his art/ &yogh;e lat hem go here way</L>
<L>lo wher &thorn;ey goon // &yogh;e lat &thorn;e children play</L>
<L>They get hym nat so lightly by my croun</L>
<L N="4100">This seely clerkes ronnen vp and doun</L>
<L>wi&thorn; keep / keep. stand stand Iossa ware derere</L>
<L>Ga wightly &thorn;ou and I sal keep him heere /</L>
<L>But schortly til &thorn;at it was verray night /</L>
<L N="4104">They cowde nat &thorn;ough &thorn;ey did al here might</L>
<L>here capil cacche it ran away so fast /</L>
<L>Til in a diche &thorn;ey caught / him atte last/</L>
<L>wery and wete as bestys in &thorn;e Reyn<MILESTONE N="55a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4108">Comth sely Iohn and wi&thorn; him com&thorn; aleyn</L>
<L>Allas quod Iohn &thorn;at day &thorn;at I was born</L>
<L>Now are we dryue til he&thorn;ing and to scorn</L>
<L>Oure corn is stole men woln vs foles calle /</L>
<L N="4112">Bathe &thorn;e wardeyn and eek our felaws alle /</L>
<L>And namely &thorn;e myller weyloway</L>
<L>Thus pleyneth Iohn as he go&thorn; by &thorn;e way</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e mylle and bayard in his hand</L>
<L N="4116">The myller sittyng by &thorn;e fyr he fand</L>
<L>For it was night and for&thorn;er might &thorn;ey nought</L>
<L>But for &thorn;e loue of god &thorn;ey him bisought</L>
<L>As herberwh and of ese as for her peny</L>
<L N="4120">&THORN;e myller sayd agayn if &thorn;er be eny</L>
<L>Swich as it is &yogh;it schul &yogh;e haue &yogh;our part</L>
<L>Myn hous is streyt. / but &yogh;e han lerned art/</L>
<L>&YOGH;e conne by argumentes make a place</L>
<L N="4124">A myle brood of twenty foote of space /</L>
<L>let se now if &thorn;is place may suffyse</L>
<L>Or make it rom wi&thorn; speche as is &yogh;our gyse</L>
<L>Now Symond seyde &thorn;is Iohn by seynt Cuthberd</L>
<L N="4128">Ay is &thorn;ou mery and &thorn;at is fair answerd</L>
<L>I haue herd say men suld take of twa &thorn;inges</L>
<L>Slik as he fynt / or tak slik as he bringes</L>
<L>But specially I pray &thorn;e host ful deere</L>
<L N="4132">Get vs som mete and drynk and mak vs cheere
<PB REF="00000131.tif" N="119"></L>
<L>And we wol paye trewly at &thorn;e fulle</L>
<L>wi&thorn; empty hand men may na hawkes tulle</L>
<L>Lo heer our siluer redy for to spende</L>
<L N="4136">This meller in to toun his doughter sende</L>
<L>For ale and breed and rosted hem a goos</L>
<L>And band her hors he schold no more go loos</L>
<L>And in his owne chambir hem made a bed</L>
<L N="4140">with schetys and with chalouns fair I-spred</L>
<L>Nat from his owen bed ten foot or twelue /</L>
<L>his doughter had a bed al by hir selue</L>
<L>Right in &thorn;e same chambre by and by</L>
<L N="4144">Hit mighte be no bet and cause why /</L>
<L>Ther was no rommer herberw in &thorn;e place<MILESTONE N="55b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>They sowpen and &thorn;ey speke hem to solace</L>
<L>And dronken euer strong ale atte beste</L>
<L N="4148">Aboute mydnyght wente &thorn;ey to reste</L>
<L>wel ha&thorn; &thorn;e myller vernysshed his heed</L>
<L>Ful pale he was for dronken and nat reed</L>
<L>he &yogh;oxeth and he speke&thorn; &thorn;urgh &thorn;e nose /</L>
<L N="4152">As he were on &thorn;e quakke or on &thorn;e pose /</L>
<L>To bed he go&thorn; and wi&thorn; him go&thorn; his wyf</L>
<L>As eny Iay sche light was and iolyf</L>
<L>So was his ioly whistel wel y-wet</L>
<L N="4156">The cradil at hire beddes feet is set</L>
<L>To rokken and to &yogh;iue &thorn;e child to souke /</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at dronken was al in &thorn;e crouke</L>
<L>To bedde went the dou&yogh;ter right anon</L>
<L N="4160">To bedde go&thorn; aleyn and also Ion</L>
<L>Ther nas no more him needed no dwale</L>
<L>This meller ha&thorn; so wysly bibbed ale /</L>
<L>That as an hors he snortith in his sleep</L>
<L N="4164">Ne of his tayl bihynd took / he no keep</L>
<L>his wyf burdoun a ful strong</L>
<L>Men might her rowtyng heeren a forlong</L>
<L>The wenche route&thorn; eek par companye</L>
<L N="4168">Aleyn &thorn;e clerk &thorn;at herd &thorn;is melodye
<PB REF="00000132.tif" N="120"></L>
<L>He pokyd Iohn / and seyde slepistow</L>
<L>Herdistow euer slik a sang er now</L>
<L>Lo slik a couplyng is betwix hem alle</L>
<L N="4172">A wilde fyr vpon &thorn;air bodyes falle</L>
<L>wha herkned euer swilk a ferly &thorn;ing /</L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;ei sul haue &thorn;e flour of ille endyng</L>
<L>This lange night &thorn;er tydes me na rest</L>
<L N="4176">But &yogh;et na fors al sal be for &thorn;e best</L>
<L>For Iohn sayd he as euer mot I &thorn;ryue</L>
<L>If &thorn;at I may &yogh;one wenche sal I swyue</L>
<L>Som esement ha&thorn; lawe schapen vs</L>
<L N="4180">For Iohn &thorn;er is a lawe &thorn;at says &thorn;us</L>
<L>That if a man in a poynt be agreued<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Qui in vno grauatur in alio debet releuari</NOTE></L>
<L>That in ano&thorn;er he sal be releeued</L>
<L>Oure corn is stoln so&thorn;ly it is na nay<MILESTONE N="56a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4184">And we haue had an ylle fitt to day</L>
<L>And syn I sal haue nan amendement</L>
<L>Agayn my los I wol haue esement /</L>
<L>By godde sale it sal nan o&thorn;er be /</L>
<L N="4188">This Iohn answerd / aleyn auyse &thorn;e</L>
<L>The Miller is a parlous man he sayde</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at he out of his sleep abrayde</L>
<L>he mighte do vs bo&thorn;e a vilonye</L>
<L N="4192">Aleyn answerd I count it nat a flye</L>
<L>And vp he roos and by &thorn;e wenche crepte</L>
<L>This wenche lay vpright and faste slepte</L>
<L>Til he so neih was or sche might aspye</L>
<L N="4196">That it had ben to late for to crye</L>
<L>And schortly for to seye &thorn;ey weren at oon</L>
<L>Now pley aleyn for I wol speke of Ion</L>
<L>&para; This Iohn lith stille a forlong whyle or two</L>
<L N="4200">And to him self compleyned of his woo</L>
<L>Allas quod he &thorn;is is a wikked Iape /</L>
<L>Now may I say &thorn;at I am but an ape</L>
<L>&YOGH;et ha&thorn; my felaw somwat for his harm</L>
<L N="4204">he ha&thorn; &thorn;e myllers doughter in his arm
<PB REF="00000133.tif" N="121"></L>
<L>he auntred him and has his needes sped</L>
<L>And I lye as a draf sak in my bed</L>
<L>And when &thorn;is Iape is tald ano&thorn;er day</L>
<L N="4208">I sal be held a daf a cokenay</L>
<L>vnhardy is vnsely as men saith</L>
<L>I wol arise and auntre it in good fai&thorn;</L>
<L>And vp he ros and softely he wente /</L>
<L N="4212">vnto &thorn;e cradil and in his hand it hente</L>
<L>And bar it softe vnto his beddis feet</L>
<L>Soone after &thorn;is &thorn;e wyf hir routyng leet /</L>
<L>And gan awake and went hir for to pisse</L>
<L N="4216">And cam agayn and gan hir cradel mysse</L>
<L>And groped heer and &thorn;er but sche fond noon</L>
<L>Allas quod sche / I had almost mys goon</L>
<L>I had almost goon to &thorn;e clerkes bed</L>
<L N="4220">Ey bendicite &thorn;an had I foule I-sped</L>
<L>And for&thorn; sche go&thorn; til sche &thorn;e cradil fand<MILESTONE N="56b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sche gropith alway forther with hir hand</L>
<L>And fand &thorn;e bed and &thorn;oughte nat but good</L>
<L N="4224">By cause &thorn;at &thorn;e cradil by hit stood</L>
<L>Nat knowyng wher sche was for it was derk</L>
<L>But fair and wel sche creep in to &thorn;e clerk</L>
<L>And lith ful stille and wolde han caught a sleep</L>
<L N="4228">wi&thorn;inne a while Iohn &thorn;e clerk vp leep</L>
<L>And on this goode wyf ley&thorn; on ful sore</L>
<L>So mery a fytt/ ne hadd sche nat ful &yogh;ore</L>
<L>he prike&thorn; harde and deepe as he were mad</L>
<L N="4232">This Ioly lyf han &thorn;is twey clerkes had</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;ridde cok bygan to synge</L>
<L>Aleyn wax wery in &thorn;e dawenynge</L>
<L>For he had swonken al &thorn;e longe night/</L>
<L N="4236">And seyd far wel malyn my sweete wight</L>
<L>The day is come I may no lenger byde /</L>
<L>But euermo wher so I go or ryde</L>
<L>I am &thorn;in owen clerk so haue I seel</L>
<L N="4240">Now deere lemman quod sche go far wel
<PB REF="00000134.tif" N="122"></L>
<L>But or &thorn;ou go o thing I wol &thorn;e telle</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at &thorn;ou wendist homward by &thorn;e melle</L>
<L>Right at &thorn;e entre of &thorn;e dore byhynde</L>
<L N="4244">Thou schalt a cake of half a busshel fynde</L>
<L>That was I-maked of &thorn;yn owen mele</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at I hilp myn owen self to stele</L>
<L>And goode lemman god &thorn;e saue and kepe</L>
<L N="4248">And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word almost sche gan to weepe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Aleyn vprist and &thorn;ought er &thorn;at it dawe</L>
<L>I wol go crepen in by my felawe</L>
<L>And fand &thorn;e cradil wi&thorn; his hand anon</L>
<L N="4252">By god &thorn;ought he al wrong I haue I-goon</L>
<L>My heed is toty of my swynk to nyght</L>
<L>That / makes me &thorn;at I ga nou&yogh;t aright</L>
<L>I wot wel by &thorn;e cradel I haue mys go</L>
<L N="4256">heer lith &thorn;e myller and his wyf also</L>
<L>For&thorn; he go&thorn; in twenty deuelway</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e bed &thorn;er as &thorn;e Miller lay</L>
<L>he wende haue crope by his felaw Ion<MILESTONE N="57a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4260">And by &thorn;e myller in he creep anon</L>
<L>And caught him by &thorn;e nekke and soft he spak</L>
<L>And seyde Ion &thorn;ou swyneshed awak</L>
<L>For cristes sowle and here a noble game</L>
<L N="4264">For by &thorn;at lord &thorn;at cleped is seynt Iame</L>
<L>As I haue &thorn;ries in &thorn;is schorte night</L>
<L>Swyued &thorn;e myllers dou&yogh;ter bolt vpright</L>
<L>whiles &thorn;ou hast as a coward ben agast</L>
<L N="4268">&YOGH;e false harlot quod &thorn;is mellere hast/</L>
<L>A false traitour false clerk quod he</L>
<L>Thou schalt be deed by goddes dignite</L>
<L>who durste be so bold to disparage</L>
<L N="4272">My doughter &thorn;at is com of hih lynage /</L>
<L>And by &thorn;e &thorn;rote-bolle he caught aleyn</L>
<L>And he hent him dispitously ageyn</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e nose he smot him with his fest</L>
<L N="4276">Doun ran &thorn;e blody streem vpon his brest
<PB REF="00000135.tif" N="123"></L>
<L>And in &thorn;e floor wi&thorn; nose and mou&thorn; to-broke</L>
<L>They walweden as pigges in a poke</L>
<L>And vpon &thorn;ay goon and doun &thorn;ey goon anon</L>
<L N="4280">Til &thorn;at &thorn;e Millner stumbled at a ston</L>
<L>And doun he felle / bakward on his wyf</L>
<L>That wyste no&thorn;ing of &thorn;is nyce stryf</L>
<L>For sche was falle a sleepe a litel wight</L>
<L N="4284">wi&thorn; Ion &thorn;e Clerk &thorn;at waked al &thorn;e night</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;e falle right out of slepe sche brayde</L>
<L>help holy croys of Bromholme sche sayde</L>
<L>In manus tuas lord to &thorn;e I calle /</L>
<L N="4288">Awake Symond &thorn;e feend is in &thorn;in halle</L>
<L>My hert is broken help I am but deed</L>
<L>Ther lythe vpon my wombe and on myn heed</L>
<L>Help Symkyn for &thorn;is false clerkes fight</L>
<L N="4292">This Iohn stert vp as fast as euer he might</L>
<L>And grasped by &thorn;e walles to and fro</L>
<L>To fynde a staf &amp; sche sturt vp also</L>
<L>And knewe &thorn;e estres bet &thorn;an dede Ion</L>
<L N="4296">And by &thorn;e wal sche took a staf anon</L>
<L>And sawh a litel glymeryng of light<MILESTONE N="57b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For at an hool in schon &thorn;e moone light</L>
<L>And by &thorn;at light she saugh hem bo&thorn;e two</L>
<L N="4300">But sikirly sche wiste nat who was who</L>
<L>But sche saugh a whit &thorn;ing in hir ye</L>
<L>And whan sche gan &thorn;is white &thorn;ing aspye</L>
<L>Sche wend &thorn;e clerk had wered a volupeer</L>
<L N="4304">And wi&thorn; a staf sche drough hir neer and neer</L>
<L>And wend haue hit &thorn;is Aleyn atte fulle</L>
<L>And smot &thorn;is meller on &thorn;e piled sculle</L>
<L>And doun he go&thorn; and crye&thorn; harrow I dye</L>
<L N="4308">This clerkes beeten him wel and leet him lye</L>
<L>And greyth hem wel and take her hors anon</L>
<L>And eek/ here mele and hoom anon &thorn;ey goon</L>
<L>And at the Millen dore &thorn;ey tok here cake</L>
<L N="4312">Of half a buisshel flour ful wel I-bake
<PB REF="00000136.tif" N="124"></L>
<L>Thus is &thorn;e prowde Miller wel I-bete</L>
<L>And ha&thorn; I-lost &thorn;e gryndyng of &thorn;e whete /</L>
<L>And payed for &thorn;e soper euerydel</L>
<L N="4316">Of aleyn and of Iohn &thorn;at beten him wel</L>
<L>His wyf is swyued and his doughter als</L>
<L>Lo such it is a Miller to be fals</L>
<L>And &thorn;erto &thorn;is prouerbe is seyd ful so&thorn;</L>
<L N="4320">he &thorn;ar nat weene wel &thorn;at euyl do&thorn;</L>
<L>A gylour schal him self bygiled be</L>
<L>And god &thorn;at sittest in &thorn;y mageste</L>
<L N="4323">Saue al &thorn;is compaignie gret and smale /</L>
<L>Thus haue I quit &thorn;e Miller in his tale /</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; her ende&thorn; &thorn;e Reeues tale<NOTE PLACE="end">[Break of one line in the MS.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000137.tif" N="125">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The Cook of londoun whil &thorn;e Reeue spak</L>
<L>For Ioye he &thorn;ought / he clawed him on &thorn;e bak</L>
<L>ha ha quod he / for cristes passioun</L>
<L N="4328">This meller ha&thorn; a scharp conclusioun /</L>
<L>vpon his argument of herburgage</L>
<L>wel seyde Salomon in his langage /</L>
<L>Ne bryng nat euery man in to &thorn;yn hous</L>
<L N="4332">For herburgage by night is perilous</L>
<L>wel aught a man avised for to be</L>
<L>whom &thorn;at he brought in to his pryuyte<MILESTONE N="58a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I pray to god so gyf my body care /</L>
<L N="4336">&YOGH;if euer si&thorn;&thorn;e I highte hogge of ware</L>
<L>herd I better myller set a werke /</L>
<L>he hadde a Iape of malice in &thorn;e derke /</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore if &yogh;e fouche sauf to heere</L>
<L N="4340">But god forbede &thorn;at we stynten heere /</L>
<L>A tale of me &thorn;at am a pouer man</L>
<L>I wol &yogh;ow telle as wel as I kan</L>
<L>A litel Iape &thorn;at fel in oure cite</L>
<L N="4344">Oure host seyde I graunt it the</L>
<L>Now telle on Roger &amp; loke it be good</L>
<L>For many a pastey hastow lete blood</L>
<L>And many a Iakk of douer hastow sold</L>
<L N="4348">That ha&thorn; be twyes hoot and twyes cold</L>
<L>Of many a pilgrym hastow cristes curs</L>
<L>For &thorn;y persly &thorn;ey faren &yogh;et &thorn;e wors</L>
<L>That they haue eten wi&thorn; &thorn;e stubbil goos</L>
<L N="4352">For in &thorn;y schoppe is many a flye loos</L>
<L>Now goode / gentil Roger by &thorn;y name /</L>
<L>But &yogh;it I pray &thorn;e be nought wro&thorn; for game</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">No gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4356">Thow saist ful so&thorn; quod Roger by my faith
<PB REF="00000138.tif" N="126"></L>
<L>But soth play quad play as &thorn;e flemyng saith</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">No gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Be thou nat wro&thorn; or we departe her</L>
<L N="4360">Though &thorn;at my tale be of an hostyler</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles I wol not telle it &yogh;it/</L>
<L>But or we departe it schal be quyt/</L>
<L>And &thorn;er wi&thorn; al he lowh / and made chere</L>
<L N="4364">And seyde his tale as &yogh;e schal after heere<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000139.tif" N="127">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A Prentys dwelled whilom in oure Citee,</L>
<L>Of a craft of vitaillers was he</L>
<L>Gaylard he was as goldfynch in &thorn;e schawe /</L>
<L N="4368">Broun as a bery and a propre felawe</L>
<L>wi&thorn; lokkes blak and kempt ful fetously</L>
<L>Dauncen he cowde wel and prately</L>
<L>That he was cleped Perkyn reuellour</L>
<L N="4372">he was ful of loue and paramour</L>
<L>As is &thorn;e hony combe of hony swete</L>
<L>wel were &thorn;e wenche &thorn;at mighte him meete<MILESTONE N="58b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="4376">. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">No gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>FOr whan &thorn;er eny rydyng was in cheepe /</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e schoppe &thorn;ider wolde he lepe /</L>
<L>Tyl he hadde al &thorn;at sight I-seyn</L>
<L N="4380">And daunced wel he nold nat come ageyn</L>
<L>And gadred him a meyne of his sort</L>
<L>To hoppe and synge and make such disport</L>
<L>And &thorn;er &thorn;ey setten steuene for to meete</L>
<L N="4384">To pleyen atte dys in such a strete</L>
<L>For in &thorn;e toun ne was &thorn;er no prentys</L>
<L>That fairer cowde caste a peyre dys</L>
<L>Than Perkyn cou&thorn;e and &thorn;erto he was free /</L>
<L N="4388">Of his dispence in place of pryuyte</L>
<L>That fand his mayster wel in his chaffare</L>
<L>For often tyme he fond his box ful bare</L>
<L>For such a ioly prentys reuelour</L>
<L N="4392">That haunte&thorn; dys Reuel or paramour</L>
<L>his maister schal it in his schoppe abye</L>
<L>Al haue he no part of &thorn;e mynstralcye</L>
<L>For &thorn;efte and ryot be conuertyble</L>
<L N="4396">Al can &thorn;ey pley on giterne and rubible
<PB REF="00000140.tif" N="128"></L>
<L>Reuel and trou&thorn;e as in a lowe degre</L>
<L>They ben ful wro&thorn; al day as &yogh;e may see</L>
<L>This Ioly Prentys with his mayster bood</L>
<L N="4400">Til he was oute ney&yogh; of his prentys hood</L>
<L>Al were he snybbyd bo&thorn;e erly and late</L>
<L>And som tyme lad with reuel in to Newgate</L>
<L>But atte laste his mayster him bythought</L>
<L N="4404">vpon a day whan he his papyr sought</L>
<L>Of a prouerbe &thorn;at si&thorn; &thorn;is same word</L>
<L>wel bette is roten appul out of hord</L>
<L>Than it rote al &thorn;e remenaunt/</L>
<L N="4408">So fareth it by a ryotous seruaunt</L>
<L>hit is ful lasse harm to late him pa</L>
<L>Than he schend al &thorn;e seruauntes in &thorn;e place</L>
<L>Therfore his mayster &yogh;af him acqueyntaunce</L>
<L N="4412">And bad him go wi&thorn; sorwe and wi&thorn; meschaunce</L>
<L>And &thorn;us &thorn;e ioly prentys had his leue //</L>
<L>Now let hym ryot al &thorn;e night or leue.<NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>Lines</I> 4413, 4414 <I>form the last line of the page in the MS.</I>]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000141.tif" N="129">
<HEAD>APPENDIX TO GROUP A.</HEAD>
<HEAD>[THE SPURIOUS TALE OF GAMELYN.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1">LItheth and lestne&thorn; and herkne&thorn; aright<MILESTONE N="59a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &yogh;e schul heere a talkyng of a doughty knight</L>
<L>Sire Iohn of Boundys was his right name</L>
<L N="4">he cowde of/ norture ynough &amp; mochil of game</L>
<L>Thre sones &thorn;e knight &middot; &thorn;at with his body he wan</L>
<L>The eldest was a moche schrewe / and sone he bygan</L>
<L>his bre&thorn;eren loued wel here fader / and of him were agast /</L>
<L N="8">The eldest deserued his fadres curs / and had it at &thorn;e last /</L>
<L>The goode kni&yogh;t his fader lyuede so &yogh;ore</L>
<L>That deth was comen him to and handled him ful sore</L>
<L>The goode knight cared sore . sik &thorn;er he lay</L>
<L N="12">how his children scholde lyuen after his day</L>
<L>he hadde ben wyde wher . but non housbond he was</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e lond &thorn;at he had / it was verrey purchas</L>
