<L>Now is &thorn;y power y-don &thorn;ou most nedes arise</L>
<L>Thow hast &yogh;euen domes &thorn;at ben yuel dight</L>
<L N="848">I wil sitten in &thorn;y sete an dressen hem aright
<PB REF="00000165.tif" N="153"></L>
<L>The Iustice sat stille and roos nought anoon</L>
<L>And Gamelyn cleuede his cheeke boon</L>
<L>Gamelyn took him in his arm and no more spak</L>
<L N="852">But &thorn;rew him ouer &thorn;e barre and his arm tobrak</L>
<L>Durste non to Gamelyn seye but good</L>
<L>For fered of &thorn;e company &thorn;at wi&thorn;oute stood</L>
<L>Gamelyn sette him doun in &thorn;e Iustices sete /</L>
<L N="856">And sire Ote his bro&thorn;er by him / and adam at his feet</L>
<L>whan Gamelyn was I-set in &thorn;e Iustices sete</L>
<L>herkne&thorn; of a bourde &thorn;at Gamelyn dede /</L>
<L>he leet fetre &thorn;e Iustice and his fals bro&thorn;er</L>
<L N="860">And dede hem come to &thorn;e barre &thorn;at oon wi&thorn; &thorn;at o&thorn;er</L>
<L>Tho Gamelyn hadde &thorn;us y-doon had he no rest</L>
<L>Til he had enquered who was on &thorn;e quest</L>
<L>For to deme his bro&thorn;er sir Ote for to honge /</L>
<L N="864">Er he wiste which &thorn;ey were he &thorn;oughte ful longe</L>
<L>But as sone as Gamelyn wiste wher &thorn;ey were</L>
<L>he dede hem euerichone fetere in feere /</L>
<L>And bringen hem to &thorn;e barre and sette hem in rewe /</L>
<L N="868">By my fai&thorn; seyde &thorn;e Iustice &thorn;e Scherreue is a schrewe</L>
<L>Than seyde Gamelyn to &thorn;e Iustise</L>
<L>Thou hast y-&yogh;eue domes of &thorn;e wors assise</L>
<L>And &thorn;e .xij. sisours &thorn;at weren of &thorn;e queste /</L>
<L N="872">They schul ben hanged &thorn;is day so haue I reste</L>
<L>Thanne seide &thorn;e scherreue to &yogh;onge Gamelyn &middot;</L>
<L>Lord I crie &thorn;e mercy bro&thorn;er art &thorn;ou myn</L>
<L>Therfore seyde Gamely haue &thorn;ou cristes curs</L>
<L N="876">For and &thorn;ou were maister &yogh;it I schulde haue wors<MILESTONE N="70b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For to make schort tale and nou&yogh;t to tarie longe</L>
<L>he ordeyned him a queste of his men so stronge</L>
<L>The Iustice and &thorn;e scherreue bo&thorn;e honged hye</L>
<L N="880">To weyuen wi&thorn; ropes and wi&thorn; &thorn;e wynd drye</L>
<L>And &thorn;e .xij. sisours sorwe haue &thorn;at rekke</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ey were hanged faste by &thorn;e nekke /</L>
<L>Thus ended &thorn;e fals knight wi&thorn; his treccherie</L>
<L N="884">That euer had I-lad his lyf in falsnes and folye
<PB REF="00000166.tif" N="154"></L>
<L>He was hanged by &thorn;e nek and nou&yogh;t by &thorn;e purs</L>
<L>That was &thorn;e meede &thorn;at he had for his fadres curs</L>
<L>Sir Ote was eldest and Gamelyn was &yogh;ing</L>
<L N="888">&thorn;ey wenten wi&thorn; here freendes euen to &thorn;e kyng</L>
<L>They made pees wi&thorn; &thorn;e kyng of &thorn;e best assise</L>
<L>The kyng loued wel sir Ote and made him Iustise</L>
<L>And after &thorn;e kyng made Gamelyn bo&thorn;e in Est and west</L>
<L N="892">Chef Iustice of al his fre forest</L>
<L>Alle his wighte &yogh;onge men &thorn;e kyng for&yogh;af here gilt</L>
<L>And sitthen in good office &thorn;e kyng hem hath I-pilt</L>
<L N="895">Thus wan Gamelyn his lond and his leede</L>
<L>And wrak him of his enemys and quyt hem here meede</L>
<L>And sire Ote his bro&thorn;er made him his heir</L>
<L>And si&thorn;&thorn;en wedded Gamelyn a wyf bo&thorn;e good and feyr</L>
<L>They lyueden to-gidere / whil &thorn;at crist wolde</L>
<L N="900">And si&thorn;en was Gamelyn grauen vnder molde</L>
<L>And so schal we alle may &thorn;er no man fle</L>
<L>God bryng vs to &thorn;e Ioye &thorn;at euer schal be / AMEN<NOTE PLACE="end">[The rest of the page, eleven lines, is blank in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="B" TYPE="group">

<PB REF="00000167.tif" N="155">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="129">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>B.</B> (FRAGMENT II.)</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; <B>1.</B> MAN OF LAW'S HEAD-LINK.</HEAD>
<HEAD><B>HARLEIAN MS. 7334</B> (British Museum).</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Owre Hoste sawh &thorn;at &thorn;e brighte sonne<MILESTONE N="71a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>The arke of his artificial day ha&thorn; I-ronne</L>
<L>The four&thorn;e part of half an hour and more /</L>
<L N="4">And &thorn;ough he were nat depe in lore</L>
<L>he wist it was &thorn;e &thorn;retten&thorn;e day</L>
<L>Of april &thorn;at is messanger to may</L>
<L>And sawe wel &thorn;at &thorn;e schade of euery tree</L>
<L N="8">was in &thorn;e lengthe &thorn;e same quantite</L>
<L>That was &thorn;e body erecte &thorn;at caused it</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore by &thorn;e schadwe he took his wit</L>
<L>That Phebus which &thorn;at schoon so fair and bright</L>
<L N="12">Degrees was .xlv. clombe on hight</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at day as in &thorn;at latitude</L>
<L>Hit was ten of &thorn;e clokke he gan conclude /</L>
<L>And sodeynly he plight his hors aboute</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="16">LOrdynges quod he I warne &yogh;ou al &thorn;e route</L>
<L>The four&thorn;e party of &thorn;is day is goon</L>
<L>Now for &thorn;e loue of god and of seint Ion</L>
<L>lese&thorn; no tyme as for&thorn;e as &yogh;e may</L>
<L N="20">lordynges &thorn;e tyme passe&thorn; night and day</L>
<L>And steli&thorn; fro vs what pryuely slepyng</L>
<L>And what &thorn;urgh necligence in oure wakyng</L>
<L>As do&thorn; &thorn;e streem &thorn;at torne&thorn; neuer agayn</L>
<L N="24">Descendyng fro &thorn;e mounteyn in to playn</L>
<L>wel can senek and many philosopher</L>
<L>Bywaylen tyme more &thorn;an gold in cofre</L>
<L>For losse of catel may recouered be /</L>
<L N="28">But losse of tyme schendeth vs quod he
<PB REF="00000168.tif" N="156"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="130"></L>
<L>It wil nat come agayn wi&thorn;oute drede</L>
<L>Nomore &thorn;an wol malkyns maydenhede</L>
<L>whan sche had lost it in hir wantownesse /</L>
<L N="32">let vs nat mowlen &thorn;us in ydelnesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SIr man of lawe quod he so haue &yogh;e blisse</L>
<L>Telle vs a tale anon as forward ys</L>
<L>&YOGH;e be submitted &thorn;urgh our fre assent/</L>
<L N="36">To stonden in &thorn;is cas at my Iuggement</L>
<L>Acquyte&thorn; &yogh;ow and holde&thorn; &yogh;oure byheste /</L>
<L>Than haue &yogh;e doon &yogh;our deuour atte leste</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HOst quod he depardeux I assent<MILESTONE N="71b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="40">To breke forward is nat myn entent/</L>
<L>Byheste is dette and I wol holde fayn</L>
<L>Al my byhest I can no better sayn</L>
<L>For such lawe as a man &yogh;eueth ano&thorn;er wight</L>
<L N="44">he schuld him selue vsen hit by right</L>
<L>Thus wol oure text but na&thorn;eles certeyn</L>
<L>I can right now non o&thorn;er tale seyn</L>
<L>That Chaucer &thorn;ey he can but lewedly</L>
<L N="48">On metres and on Rymyng certeynly</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; seyd hem in such englisch as he can</L>
<L>Of olde tyme as knowe&thorn; many man</L>
<L>And &yogh;if he haue nou&yogh;t sayd hem leeue brother</L>
<L N="52">In O bok he ha&thorn; seyd hem in ano&thorn;er</L>
<L>For he ha&thorn; told of louers vp and doun</L>
<L>Moo &thorn;an Ovide made of mencioun</L>
<L>In his Epistelles &thorn;at ben so olde</L>
<L N="56">what schuld I tellen hem syn &thorn;ey be tolde /</L>
<L>In &yogh;ou&thorn;e he made of Coys and alcioun</L>
<L>And si&thorn;&thorn;e ha&thorn; he spoke of euerychon</L>
<L>These noble wyfes and &thorn;ese louers eeke</L>
<L N="60">who-so wole his large volume seeke</L>
<L>Cleped &thorn;e seintes legendes of Cupide</L>
<L>Ther may he see &thorn;e large woundes wyde</L>
<L>Of lucresse and of Babiloun Tysbee</L>
<L N="64">The sorwe of Dido for &thorn;e fals Enee
<PB REF="00000169.tif" N="157"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="131"></L>
<L>The tree of philles for hir demephon</L>
<L>The pleynt of Dyane and of Ermyon</L>
<L>Of Adrian and of ysyphilee</L>
<L N="68">The barren yle stondyng in &thorn;e see /</L>
<L>The dreynt leander for hir Erro</L>
<L>The teeres of Eleyn and eek &thorn;e woo</L>
<L>Of bryxseyde and of ledomia</L>
<L N="72">The cruelte of &thorn;e queen Medea</L>
<L>The litel children hangyng by &thorn;e hals</L>
<L>For &thorn;ilke Iason &thorn;at was of loue so fals</L>
<L>O ypermystre penollope and alceste /</L>
<L N="76">&YOGH;oure wyfhood he comendeth wi&thorn; &thorn;e beste</L>
<L>But certeynly no worde write&thorn; he<MILESTONE N="72a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;ilke wikked ensample of Canace</L>
<L>That loued hir owen bro&thorn;er synfully</L>
<L N="80">On whiche corsed stories I seye fy</L>
<L>Or elles of Tyro appoloneus</L>
<L>how &thorn;at &thorn;e cursed kyng Anteochus</L>
<L>Byreft his doughter of hir maydenhede</L>
<L N="84">That is so horrible a tale as man may reede</L>
<L>whan he hir &thorn;rew vpon &thorn;e pament</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore he of ful auysement</L>
<L>wolde neuer wryte in non of his sermouns</L>
<L N="88">Of such vnkynde abhominaciouns</L>
<L>Ne I wol non reherse if &thorn;at I may</L>
<L>But of my tale how schal I do &thorn;is day</L>
<L>Me were loth to be lykned douteles /</L>
<L N="92">To muses &thorn;at men clepen Pyerides</L>
<L>Methamorphoseos wot what I mene</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles I recche nat a bene</L>
<L>They I come after him with hawe-bake /</L>
<L N="96">I speke in prose<NOTE PLACE="foot">Was <I>Melibe</I> first meant for the Man of Law?</NOTE> and let him rymes make</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word he wi&thorn; a sobre cheere</L>
<L>Bygan his tale as &yogh;e schal after heere</L>
<TRAILER>&para; Explicit prologus<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">


<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000170.tif" N="158">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="132">
<HEAD>[The Proem]</HEAD>
<HEAD>incipit fabula /</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="99">O Hateful harm condicion of pouert<NOTE PLACE="marg">on</NOTE><MILESTONE N="72a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>wi&thorn; &thorn;urst wi&thorn; cold wi&thorn; honger so confoundyd</L>
<L>To asken help it schame&thorn; in &thorn;in hert</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou non aske wi&thorn; neede so art &thorn;ou woundyd</L>
<L>That verray neede vnwrappe&thorn; al &thorn;y woundes hyd</L>
<L>Maugre &thorn;yn heed &thorn;ou most for Indigence</L>
<L N="105">Or stele or begge or borwe &thorn;y dispence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="106">Thow blamest crist and seyst ful bitterly</L>
<L>he mys departe&thorn; riches temporal</L>
<L>And &thorn;yn neyhebour &thorn;ou wytes synfully</L>
<L N="109">And seyst &thorn;ou hast to litel and he ha&thorn; al</L>
<L>Parfay seystow som tyme he rekne schal</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at his tayl schal brennen in &thorn;e gleede</L>
<L N="112">For he nought helpe&thorn; &thorn;e needful in his neede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="113">HErkne&thorn; what is &thorn;e sentens of &thorn;e wyse</L>
<L>Bet is to dye &thorn;an haue indigence</L>
<L>Thy selue neyghebour wol &thorn;e despyse<MILESTONE N="72b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="116">If &thorn;ou be pore far wel &thorn;y reuerence</L>
<L>&YOGH;et of &thorn;e wyse man tak &thorn;is sentence</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e dayes of pore men be wikke /</L>
<L N="119">Be war &thorn;erfore or &thorn;ou come to &thorn;at prikke /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="120">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou be pore &thorn;y bro&thorn;er hate&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;y frendes flee&thorn; fro &thorn;e allas</L>
<L>O Riche marchaund&yogh; ful of wele be &yogh;e</L>
<L N="123">O noble prudent folk as in &thorn;is cas</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure bagges be&thorn; nat fuld wi&thorn; ambes aas</L>
<L>But wi&thorn; sys synk &thorn;at renne&thorn; on &yogh;our chaunce</L>
<L N="126">At crystemasse wel mery may &yogh;e daunce
<PB REF="00000171.tif" N="159"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="133"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="127">&YOGH;e seeke land and see for &yogh;our wynnynges</L>
<L>As wyse folk as &yogh;e knowe alle &thorn;astates</L>
<L>Of regnes / &yogh;e be fadres of tydynges</L>
<L N="130">Of tales bo&thorn;e of pees and of debates /</L>
<L>I were right now of tales desolat</L>
<L>Nere &thorn;at a marchaunt gon si&thorn;&thorn;en many a &yogh;ere /</L>
<L N="133">Me taught a tale which &yogh;e schal after heere
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000172.tif" N="160"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="134">
<HEAD>[The Tale]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="134">IN Surrie dwelled whilom a companye<NOTE PLACE="marg">on</NOTE><MILESTONE N="72b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of Chapmen riche and &thorn;erto sad and trewe</L>
<L>That wyde where sent her spycere</L>
<L N="137">Clo&thorn;es of gold and satyn rich of hewe /</L>
<L>her chaffar was so &thorn;rifty and so newe</L>
<L>That euery wight had deynte to chaffare</L>
<L N="140">wi&thorn; hem and eek to selle hem of here ware /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="141">Now fel it &thorn;at &thorn;e maystres of &thorn;at sort</L>
<L>han schapen hem to Rome for to wende</L>
<L>were it for chapmanhode or for disport</L>
<L N="144">Non o&thorn;er message nolde &thorn;ey &thorn;ider sende /</L>
<L>But came hemself to Rome &thorn;is is &thorn;e ende</L>
<L>And in such place / as &thorn;ought hem auanntage</L>
<L N="147">For here entent &thorn;ey tooke her herburgage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="148">Soiourned naue &thorn;ese marchaunt&yogh; in &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>A certeyn tyme as fel to here plesaunce</L>
<L>But so bifell &thorn;at &thorn;excellent renoun</L>
<L N="151">Of &thorn;emperoures doughter dame Custaunce</L>
<L>Reported was with euery circumstaunce</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;ese surrien&yogh; marchaunt&yogh; in such wyse<MILESTONE N="73a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="154">Fro day to day as I schal &yogh;ou deuyse /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="155">This was &thorn;e comyn voys of euery man</L>
<L>Oure emperour of Rome god him see</L>
<L>A doughter ha&thorn; &thorn;at si&thorn; &thorn;e world bygan</L>
<L N="158">To Rekne as wel hir goodnes as hir bewte /</L>
<L>Nas neuer such ano&thorn;er as was sche</L>
<L>I prey to god hir saue and susteene</L>
<L N="161">And wolde sche were of al Europe &thorn;e queene
<PB REF="00000173.tif" N="161"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="135"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="162">In hire is hye bewte wi&thorn;oute pryde</L>
<L>&YOGH;ow&thorn;e wi&thorn;oute grefhed or folye</L>
<L>To alle here werkes vertu is hire gyde /</L>
<L N="165">humblesse ha&thorn; slayne in hir tyrrannye /</L>
<L>Sche is myrour of alle curtesye /</L>
<L>hir herte is verrey chambre of holynesse</L>
<L N="168">hir hond mynistre of fredom and almesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="169">And al &thorn;is voys is so&thorn; as god is trewe</L>
<L>But now to purpos let vs turne a&yogh;ein</L>
<L>These marchant&yogh; haue don fraught here schippes newe /</L>
<L N="172">And whan &thorn;ey haue &thorn;is blisful mayde seyn &middot;</L>
<L>Home to Surrey be &thorn;ey went a&yogh;ein /</L>
<L>And doon here needes as &thorn;ey haue don &yogh;ore</L>
<L N="175">And lyuen in wele I can &yogh;ou say no more /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="176">Now fel it &thorn;at &thorn;ese marchaunt&yogh; stooden in grace /</L>
<L>Of him &thorn;at was &thorn;e Sowdan of Surrye</L>
<L>For whan &thorn;ey come fro eny straunge place /</L>
<L N="179">he wolde of his benigne curtesye</L>
<L>Make hem good chere and busily aspye</L>
<L>Tydynges of sondry regnes for to lere/</L>
<L N="182">The wordes &thorn;at &thorn;ey mighte seen and heere /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="183">Among o&thorn;er &thorn;inges specially</L>
<L>These marchaunt&yogh; him told of dame Constaunce</L>
<L>So gret noblesse in ernest so ryally</L>
<L N="186">That &thorn;is Sowdan ha&thorn; caught so gret plesaunce</L>
<L>To haue hir figure in his remembraunce</L>
<L>And al his lust and al his besy cure</L>
<L N="189">was for to loue hir whiles his lyf may dure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="190">Par auenture in &thorn;ilke large booke /</L>
<L>which &thorn;at is cleped &thorn;e heuen I-write was<MILESTONE N="73b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>wi&thorn; sterres whan &thorn;at he his bur&thorn;e took</L>
<L N="193">That he for loue schulde haue his de&thorn; allas /
<PB REF="00000174.tif" N="162"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="136"></L>
<L>For in &thorn;e sterres clerere &thorn;en is glas /</L>
<L>Is wryten god woot who-so cow&thorn;e it rede</L>
<L N="196">The de&thorn; of euery man wi&thorn;outen drede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="197">IN sterres many a wynter &thorn;er byfore</L>
<L>was write &thorn;e de&thorn; of Ector and Achilles /</L>
<L>Of Pompe Iulius er &thorn;ey were I-bore /</L>
<L N="200">The stryf of Thebes and of Ercules /</L>
<L>Of Sampson Turnus and of Socrates</L>
<L>The de&thorn; but mennes wittes ben so dulle /</L>
<L N="203">That no wight can wel rede it at &thorn;e fulle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="204">This sowdan for his pryue counseil sent</L>
<L>And schortly of &thorn;is mater for to pace /</L>
<L>he ha&thorn; to hem declared his entent</L>
<L N="207">And seyd hem certeyn but he might haue grace /</L>
<L>To haue Constance wi&thorn;inne a litel space</L>
<L>he nas but deed and charged hem in hy&yogh;e</L>
<L N="210">To schapen for his lyf som remedye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="211">Dyuerse men dyuers &thorn;inges seyde</L>
<L>The argumentes casten vp and doun</L>
<L>Many a subtyl resoun for&thorn; &thorn;ey leyden</L>
<L N="214">They spekyn of magike and of ambusioun</L>
<L>But finally as in conclusioun</L>
<L>They can nought seen in &thorn;at non auauntage</L>
<L N="217">Ne in non o&thorn;er wey saue in mariage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="218">Than sawgh &thorn;ey &thorn;er in such difficulte</L>
<L>By wey of resoun to speke it al playn &middot;</L>
<L>By cause &thorn;at &thorn;er was such dyuersite /</L>
<L N="221">Bitwen here bo&thorn;e lawes as &thorn;ey sayn</L>
<L>They trowe &thorn;at no cristen prince wold fayn</L>
<L>wedden his child vnder our lawe swete /</L>
<L N="224">That vs was taught by mahoun oure prophete /
<PB REF="00000175.tif" N="163"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="137"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="225">And he answerde ra&thorn;er &thorn;an I lese</L>
<L>Constance I wol be cristen douteles /</L>
<L>I moot be heres I may non o&thorn;er cheese /</L>
<L N="228">I pray &yogh;ou haldeth &yogh;our arguments in pees /</L>
<L>Saue&thorn; my lyf and be&thorn; nat recheles /<MILESTONE N="74a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Go&thorn; gete&thorn; hire &thorn;at ha&thorn; my lyf in cure /</L>
<L N="231">For in &thorn;is wo I may no lenger dure /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="232">What neede&thorn; gretter dilatacioun</L>
<L>I say by tretys and ambassatrye</L>
<L>And by &thorn;e popes mediacioun</L>
<L N="235">And al &thorn;e chirche and al &thorn;e chyualrye /</L>
<L>That in destruccioun of mawmetrye</L>
<L>And in encresse of cristes lawe deere /</L>
<L N="238">They ben acordid as &yogh;e schal after heere/</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="239">How &thorn;at &thorn;e Soudan and his baronage</L>
<L>And alle his lieges schuld I-crystned be /</L>
<L>And he schal haue Constance in mariage/</L>
<L N="242">And certeyn gold I not what quantite</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore founden &thorn;ey suffisant seurte</L>
<L>This same acord was sworn on euery syde/</L>
<L N="245">Now fair Constance almighty god &thorn;e guyde /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="246">Now wolde som men wayten as I gesse</L>
<L>That I schulde tellen al &thorn;e puruyaunce /</L>
<L>That &thorn;emperour of his gret noblesse /</L>
<L N="249">Ha&thorn; schapen for his doughter dame Constaunce /</L>
<L>wel may men knowe &thorn;at so gret ordynaunce</L>
<L>May no man telle in so litel a clause /</L>
<L N="252">As was arrayed for so high a cause /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="253">Bisschops ben schapen with hir for to wende</L>
<L>lordes ladyes and knightes of renoun</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er folk ynowe &thorn;is &thorn;is is &thorn;e ende</L>
<L N="256">And notefied is &thorn;urgh out &thorn;e toun
<PB REF="00000176.tif" N="164"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="138"></L>
<L>That euery wight wi&thorn; gret deuocioun</L>
<L>Schulde preye crist &thorn;at he &thorn;is mariage</L>
<L N="259">Receyue in gree and spede &thorn;is viage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="260">The day is come of hire departyng</L>
<L>I say &thorn;e woful day &thorn;at &thorn;an is come</L>
<L>That &thorn;er may be no lenger tarryyng</L>
<L N="263">But for&thorn;eward &thorn;ey dresse hem alle &amp; some /</L>
<L>Constance &thorn;at with sorwe is ouercome</L>
<L>Ful pale arist and dresse&thorn; hir to wende /</L>
<L N="266">For wel sche saugh &thorn;er nas non o&thorn;er ende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="267">Allas what wonder is it/ &thorn;ough sche wepte<MILESTONE N="74b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That schal be sent to straunge nacioun</L>
<L>Fro freendes &thorn;at so tenderly hir kepte /</L>
<L N="270">And to be bounde vndur subieccioun</L>
<L>Of oon sche knew nat his condicioun</L>
<L>Housbondes ben al goode and han be &yogh;ore</L>
<L N="273">That knowen wyfes I dar say no more /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="274">Fader sche seid &thorn;y wrecched child Costaunce</L>
<L>Thy &yogh;onge doughter fostred vp so softe /</L>
<L>And &yogh;e my mooder my souerayn plesaunce</L>
<L N="277">Ouer al &thorn;ing outaken crist on lofte /</L>
<L>Constaunce &yogh;our child hir recomaundeth ofte</L>
<L>Vnto &yogh;our grace / for I schal in to Surrye</L>
<L N="280">Ne schal I neuer see &yogh;ou more wi&thorn; ye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="281">Allas vnto &thorn;e barbre nacioun</L>
<L>I most anoon / se&thorn;ens it is &yogh;our wille</L>
<L>But crist &thorn;at starf for our redempcioun</L>
<L N="284">So &yogh;eue me grace his hestes to fulfille /</L>
<L>I wrecched womman no fors &thorn;ey I spille /</L>
<L>wommen ben born to &thorn;raldam and penaunce</L>
<L N="287">And to ben vnder mannes gouernaunce
<PB REF="00000177.tif" N="165"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="139"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="288">I trowe at Troye whan Pirrus brak &thorn;e wal</L>
<L>Or yleon &thorn;at brend Thebes &thorn;e Citee</L>
<L>Ne at Rome for &thorn;e harme &thorn;urgh hanibal</L>
<L N="291">That Romayns han venquysshed tymes &thorn;re</L>
<L>Nas herd such tender wepyng for pite</L>
<L>As in &thorn;e Chambur was for hir partyng</L>
<L N="294">But for&thorn; sche moot whe&thorn;er sche weep or syng</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="295">O firste meuyng cruel firmament</L>
<L>with &thorn;i diurnal swough &thorn;at crowdest ay</L>
<L>And hurlest al fro Est to Occident</L>
<L N="298">That naturelly wold hold ano&thorn;er way</L>
<L>Thyn crowdyng sette &thorn;e heuen in such array</L>
<L>At &thorn;e bygynnyng of &thorn;is fiers viage</L>
<L N="301">That cruel marc&yogh; ha&thorn; slayn &thorn;is marriage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="302">Infortunat ascendent tortuous</L>
<L>Of which &thorn;e lordes helples falle allas</L>
<L>Out of his angle in to &thorn;e derkest hous</L>
<L N="305">O . Mari&yogh; atte&yogh;ere as in &thorn;is caas<MILESTONE N="75a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>O feble moone vnhappy been &thorn;i paas /</L>
<L>Thou knettest &thorn;e &thorn;er &thorn;ou art nat receyued</L>
<L N="308">Ther &thorn;ou were wel fro &thorn;ennes artow weyued</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="309">Inprudent Emperour of Rome allas</L>
<L>was &thorn;er no philosopher in al &thorn;y toun</L>
<L>Is no tyme bet &thorn;an o&thorn;er in such caas</L>
<L N="312">Of viage is &thorn;er noon eleccioun</L>
<L>Namly to folk of heigh condicioun</L>
<L>Nought whan a roote is of a birthe I-knowe</L>
<L N="315">Allas we ben to lewed and eek to slowe /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>[<NOTE PLACE="marg">[In a later hand.]</NOTE>To Shipe] is brought &thorn;is woful faire mayde /</L>
<L>Solempnely with euery circumstaunce /</L>
<L>Now Ih&umacr; crist so be wi&thorn; &yogh;ou sche sayde /</L>
<L N="319">Ther nys nomor but far wel fair Custaunce
<PB REF="00000178.tif" N="166"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="140"></L>
<L>She peyneth hire to make good contienaunce</L>
<L>And for&thorn; I lete hire sayle in &thorn;is manere /</L>
<L N="322">And torne I wol a&yogh;ein to my matiere /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="323">The moder of &thorn;e Sawdan ful of vices</L>
<L>Aspyed ha&thorn; hir sones playn entent/</L>
<L>how he wol lete his olde sacrifices</L>
<L N="326">And right anoon sche for hir counseil sent</L>
<L>And &thorn;ey ben come to knowe what sche ment</L>
<L>And whan assembled was &thorn;is folk in fere</L>
<L N="329">Sche sette hir doun and sayd as &yogh;e schal heere /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="330">Lordes quod sche &yogh;e knowen euerichon</L>
<L>how &thorn;at my sone in poynt is for to lete</L>
<L>The holy lawes of our alkaron</L>
<L N="333">&YOGH;e ben goddes messangere makamete /</L>
<L>But oon avow to grete god I hete</L>
<L>The lyf schuld ra&thorn;er out of my body stert</L>
<L N="336">Or makametes law go out of myn hert</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="337">What schal vs tyden of &thorn;is newe lawe</L>
<L>But &thorn;raldam to oure body and penaunce</L>
<L>And afterward in helle to be drawe /</L>
<L N="340">For we reneyed mahound oure creaunce</L>
<L>But lordes wol &yogh;e maken assuraunce</L>
<L>As I schal say assentyng to my lore</L>
<L N="343">And I schal make vs sauf for euermore<MILESTONE N="75b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="344">They sworen and assenten euery man</L>
<L>To lyf wi&thorn; hir and dye and by hir stonde</L>
<L>And euerich in &thorn;e beste wise he can</L>
<L N="347">To streng&thorn;en hir schal al his frendes fonde</L>
<L>And sche ha&thorn; Emperise take on honde</L>
<L>which &yogh;e schul heere &thorn;at I schal deuyse /</L>
<L N="350">And to hem alle sche spak in &thorn;is wyse /
<PB REF="00000179.tif" N="167"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="141"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="351">We schul first feyne ous cristendom to take</L>
<L>Cold watir schal nat greue vs but a lite /</L>
<L>And I schal such a fest and Reuel make /</L>
<L N="354">That as I trow I schal &thorn;e Sowdan quyte</L>
<L>For &thorn;ough his wyf be cristned neuer so white</L>
<L>Sche schal haue need to waissche away &thorn;e rede</L>
<L N="357">They sche a font of watir wi&thorn; hir lede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="358">O Sowdones root of iniquite</L>
<L>Virago &thorn;ou Semyram &thorn;e secounde</L>
<L>O serpent vnder feminite</L>
<L N="361">Lyk to &thorn;e serpent deep in helle I-bounde</L>
<L>O feyned womman alle &thorn;at may confounde</L>
<L>Vertu and Innocence &thorn;urgh &thorn;y malice /</L>
<L N="364">Is bred in &thorn;e as nest of euery vice</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="365">O Satan enuyous syn &thorn;ilke day</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou were chased fro oure heritage</L>
<L>wel knewest &thorn;ou to wommen &thorn;e olde way</L>
<L N="368">Thou madest Eue to bryng vs in seruage</L>
<L>Thou wolt fordoon &thorn;is cristen mariage</L>
<L>Thyn instrument so weylaway &thorn;e while</L>
<L N="371">Makestow of wommen whan &thorn;ou wolt bygile</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="372">This Sawdones whom I &thorn;us blame and wary</L>
<L>let pryuely hir counseil gon his way</L>
<L>what schuld I in &thorn;is tale lenger tary</L>
<L N="375">Sche ride&thorn; to &thorn;e Soudan on a day</L>
<L>And seyd him &thorn;at sche wold reney hir lay</L>
<L>And cristendam of prestes handes fonge</L>
<L N="378">Repentyng hir sche hethen was so longe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="379">Bysechyng him to doon hir &thorn;at honour</L>
<L>That sche most haue &thorn;e cristen men to feste /</L>
<L>To plesen hem I wil do my labour<MILESTONE N="76a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="382">The sawdan seith I wol do at &yogh;our heste
<PB REF="00000180.tif" N="168"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="142"></L>
<L>And knelyng &thorn;anke&thorn; hir of &thorn;at requeste</L>
<L>So glad he was he nyst nat what to seye</L>
<L N="385">Sche kyst hir sone and hom sche go&thorn; hir weye</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[PART II.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="386">Arryued ben &thorn;e cristen folk to londe /</L>
<L>In Surry with a gret solempne route</L>
<L>And hastily &thorn;is soudan sent his sonde</L>
<L N="389">First to his moder and al &thorn;e regne aboute</L>
<L>And seyd his wyf was comen out of doute</L>
<L>And preye&thorn; hir for to ride a&yogh;ein &thorn;e queene</L>
<L N="392">The honour of his regne to susteene /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="393">Gret was &thorn;e prees and riche was tharray</L>
<L>Of Surriens and Romayns mette in feere</L>
<L>The moodur of &thorn;e Sowdan riche and gay</L>
<L N="396">Receyued hir with al so glad a cheere</L>
<L>As eny modir might hir doughter deere</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e nexte Citee &thorn;er bysyde</L>
<L N="399">A softe paas solempnely &thorn;ay ryde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="400">Nought trow I &thorn;e triumphe of Iulius</L>
<L>Of which &thorn;at lukan make&thorn; moche bost</L>
<L>was ryaller ne more curious</L>
<L N="403">Than was thassemble of &thorn;is blisful oost</L>
<L>But &thorn;is Scorpioun &thorn;is wikked goost</L>
<L>This Sowdones for al hir flateryng</L>
<L N="406">Cast vnder &thorn;is ful mortally to styng</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="407">The Sawdan com&thorn; himself sone after &thorn;is</L>
<L>So really &thorn;at wonder is to telle</L>
<L>And welcome&thorn; hir wi&thorn; ioy and blys</L>
<L N="410">And &thorn;us with myrth and ioy I let hem dwelle
<PB REF="00000181.tif" N="169"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="143"></L>
<L>The fruyt of &thorn;is matier is &thorn;at I telle</L>
<L>whan tyme com men &thorn;ought it for &thorn;e best</L>
<L N="413">That reuel stynt and men goon to her rest</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="414">The tyme com &thorn;e olde Sowdonesse</L>
<L>Ordeyned ha&thorn; &thorn;is fest of which I told</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e feste cristen folk hem dresse</L>
<L N="417">. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ther men may fest and realte byholde</L>
<L>And deyntes mo / &thorn;an I can of deuyse</L>
<L N="420">But al to deere &thorn;ey bought it ar &thorn;ey ryse<MILESTONE N="76b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="421">O sodeyn wo &thorn;at euer art successour</L>
<L>&para; To worldly blis spreynd is wi&thorn; bitternesse /</L>
<L>The ende of oure ioye of oure worldly labour</L>
<L N="424">wo occupieth &thorn;e fyn of oure gladnesse</L>
<L>herken &thorn;is counseil for thyn sikernesse</L>
<L>vpon &thorn;yn glade dayes haue in &thorn;i mynde</L>
<L N="427">The vnwar woo &thorn;at cometh ay bihynde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="428">For schortly for to tellen at o word</L>
<L>The Sawdan and &thorn;e cristen euerichone</L>
<L>Ben al to-hewe and stiked atte bord</L>
<L N="431">But it were Dame Constaunce allone</L>
<L>This olde Sowdones &thorn;is cursed crone</L>
<L>ha&thorn; wi&thorn; hir frendes doon &thorn;is cursed dede</L>
<L N="434">For sche hir self wold al &thorn;e contre lede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="435">Ne &thorn;er was surrien noon / &thorn;at was conuerted</L>
<L>That of &thorn;e counseil of &thorn;e Sawdon woot</L>
<L>That he nas alto-hewe or he asterted</L>
<L N="438">And Constaunce haue &thorn;ey take anon foot-hoot</L>
<L>And in a schippe / steleres god it woot</L>
<L>They haue hir set. and bad hir lerne to sayle</L>
<L N="441">Out of Surry a&yogh;einward to ytaile
<PB REF="00000182.tif" N="170"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="144"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="442">A certein tresour &thorn;at sche &thorn;ider ladde</L>
<L>And so&thorn; to sayn vitaile gret plente</L>
<L>They haue hir &yogh;euen and clo&thorn;es eek sche hadde</L>
<L N="445">And for&thorn; sche sayle&thorn; to &thorn;e salte see</L>
<L>O my Constaunce ful of benignite</L>
<L>O Emperoures &yogh;onge doughter deere</L>
<L N="448">he &thorn;at is Lord of fortun be &thorn;i steere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="449">Sche blesse&thorn; hir and with ful pitous voys</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e croys of crist &thorn;an seyde sche</L>
<L>O cler o welful auter holy croys</L>
<L N="452">Rood of &thorn;e lambes blood ful of pite</L>
<L>That wissh &thorn;e world fro old iniquite</L>
<L>Me fro &thorn;e feend and fro his clowes keepe</L>
<L N="455">That day &thorn;at I schal drenchen in &thorn;e deepe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="456">Victorious tre proteccioun of trewe</L>
<L>That oonly were worthy for to bere</L>
<L>That kyng of heuen with his woundes newe<MILESTONE N="77a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="459">The white lamb &thorn;at hurt was with a spere</L>
<L>Flemer of feendes out of him and here /</L>
<L>On which &thorn;y lymes feithfully extenden</L>
<L N="462">Me kepe and &yogh;if me might my lyf to menden</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="463">&YOGH;eres and dayes flette &thorn;is creature</L>
<L>Thurghout &thorn;e see of Grece in to &thorn;e strayte</L>
<L>Of Marrok as it was hir aduenture /</L>
<L N="466">O many a sory mele may sche bayte</L>
<L>After hir deth ful / ofte may sche wayte</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at &thorn;e wilde wawe wol hir dryue</L>
<L N="469">Vnto &thorn;e place &thorn;er as sche schal arryue</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="470">Men mighten aske why sche was nou&yogh;t slayn</L>
<L>Ek at &thorn;e fest. who might hir body saue</L>
<L>And I answered that demaunde agayn</L>
<L N="473">who saued Daniel / in thorrible Caue
<PB REF="00000183.tif" N="171"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="145"></L>
<L>That euery wight sauf he mayster or knaue</L>
<L>was wi&thorn; &thorn;e lioun frete or he asterte</L>
<L N="476">No wight but god &thorn;at he bar in his herte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="477">God lust to schewe his wondurful miracle</L>
<L>In hir for sche schuld seen his mighty werkes</L>
<L>Crist which &thorn;at is to euery harm triacle</L>
<L N="480">By certeyn menes ofte as knowen clerkes</L>
<L>Doth &thorn;ing for certeyn ende &thorn;at ful derk is //</L>
<L>To mannes witt / &thorn;at for our ignoraunce</L>
<L N="483">Ne can nought knowe his prudent puruyaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="484">Now sith sche was nat at &thorn;e fest I-slawe /</L>
<L>who kepte hir fro drenching in &thorn;e see /</L>
<L>who kepte Ionas in &thorn;e fisches mawe</L>
<L N="487">Til he was spouted vp at Niniue</L>
<L>wel may men knowe it was no wight but he</L>
<L>That kept &thorn;e pepul Ebrayk fro her drenchyng</L>
<L N="490">wi&thorn; drye feet / &thorn;urghout &thorn;e see passyng</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="491">Who hadde foure spirit&yogh; of tempest</L>
<L>That power han to noyen land and see</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e nor&thorn; and sou&thorn; and also west and Est</L>
<L N="494">Anoye&thorn; ney&thorn;er londe / see ne tree /</L>
<L>So&thorn;ly &thorn;e comaunder of &thorn;at was he</L>
<L>That fro &thorn;e tempest ay &thorn;is womman kepte<MILESTONE N="77b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="497">As wel when sche awok as when sche slepte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="498">Wher might &thorn;is womman mete and drinke haue /</L>
<L>Thre &yogh;er and more / how laste&thorn; hir vitaille</L>
<L>who fedde &thorn;e Egipcien marie in &thorn;e Caue</L>
<L N="501">Or in desert no wight but crist saun&yogh; faile</L>
<L>Fyf &thorn;ousand folk / it was a gret meruaile/</L>
<L>wi&thorn; loues fyf and fissches tuo to feede</L>
<L N="504">God sent his foysoun at her grete neede
<PB REF="00000184.tif" N="172"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="146"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="505">Sche dryue&thorn; for&thorn; in to oure Occean</L>
<L>Thurghout oure wilde see til atte last</L>
<L>vnder an holte &thorn;at men nempne can</L>
<L N="508">Fer in Northumberland &thorn;e wawe hir cast</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e sand &thorn;e schip styked so fast</L>
<L>That &thorn;ennes wold it nou&yogh;t in al a tyde</L>
<L N="511">The wille of crist was &thorn;at sche schold abyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="512">The Constabil of / &thorn;e castel doun is fare /</L>
<L>To se &thorn;is wrak / and al &thorn;e schip he sought</L>
<L>And fond &thorn;is wery womman ful of care</L>
<L N="515">And fand also &thorn;e tresour &thorn;at sche brought</L>
<L>In hir langage mercy sche bisought</L>
<L>The lif out of her body for to wynne</L>
<L N="518">hir to delyuer of woo &thorn;at sche was Inne /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="519">A maner latyn corupt was hir speche</L>
<L>But algates / &thorn;er by sche was vnderstonde</L>
<L>The constabil whan him lust no lenger seche</L>
<L N="522">This woful womman broughte he to londe /</L>
<L>Sche knele&thorn; doun and thanketh goddes sonde</L>
<L>But what sche was sche wolde no man seye</L>
<L N="525">For foul ne faire / &thorn;ough sche scholde deye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="526">Sche was sche seyd so mased in &thorn;e see</L>
<L>That sche forgat hir mynde by hire trow&thorn;e /</L>
<L>The constable had of hir so gret pitee</L>
<L N="529">And eek his wyf &thorn;ey wepeden for routhe</L>
<L>Sche was so diligent wi&thorn;outen slou&thorn;e /</L>
<L>To serue and plese euer in &thorn;at place</L>
<L N="532">That alle hir louen &thorn;at loken on hir face</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="533">The Constable and dame hermegyld his wyf</L>
<L>To telle &yogh;ou playne in peynes bo&thorn;e were<MILESTONE N="78a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But hermegyld loued constance as hir lyf</L>
<L N="536">And Constance ha&thorn; so long herberwed &thorn;ere
<PB REF="00000185.tif" N="173"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="147"></L>
<L>In orisoun wi&thorn; many a bitter teere /</L>
<L>Til ih&umacr; ha&thorn; conuerted &thorn;urgh his grace</L>
<L N="539">Dame hermegyld &thorn;e Constables wif of &thorn;e place</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="540">In al &thorn;e lond no cristen men durst route</L>
<L>Al cristen men ben fled from &thorn;at contre</L>
<L>Thurgh payens &thorn;at conquered al a-boute /</L>
<L N="543">The places of &thorn;e north by land and see</L>
<L>To wales fled &thorn;e cristianite</L>
<L>Of olde britouns dwellyng in &thorn;is yle /</L>
<L N="546">Ther was hir refut for &thorn;e mene while</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="547">But/ &yogh;it nere cristen britouns so exiled</L>
<L>That &thorn;er / nere some in here pryuite /</L>
<L>honoured crist and he&thorn;en men bygiled</L>
<L N="550">And neigh &thorn;e Castel such &thorn;er dwellid &thorn;re</L>
<L>That oon of hem was blynd and might nat se /</L>
<L>But if it were wi&thorn; eyen of his mynde</L>
<L N="553">wi&thorn; which men seen after &thorn;at &thorn;ey ben blynde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="554">Bright was &thorn;e sonne as in someres day</L>
<L>For which &thorn;e constable and his wif also</L>
<L>And Constaunce had take &thorn;e righte way</L>
<L N="557">Toward &thorn;e see a forlong wey or two</L>
<L>To pleyen and to Romen to and fro</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at/ walk the blynde men &thorn;ey mette</L>
<L N="560">Croked and olde with eyen fast y-schette</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="561">In name of crist / cryed &thorn;is old britoun</L>
<L>Dame hermegyld &yogh;if me my sight a&yogh;eyn</L>
<L>This lady wax affrayed of &thorn;e soun</L>
<L N="564">lest &thorn;at hir houseband schortly to sayn</L>
<L>wold hir for ih&umacr; cristes loue haue slayn</L>
<L>Til Constaunce made hir bold and bad hir werche</L>
<L N="567">The wil of crist as dou&yogh;ter of holy chirche
<PB REF="00000186.tif" N="174"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="148"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="568">The Constable wax abaisshed of &thorn;at sight</L>
<L>And sayde what amounte&thorn; al &thorn;is fare</L>
<L>Constaunce answered / sir it is cristes might</L>
<L N="571">That helpeth folk out of &thorn;e feendes snare /</L>
<L>And so ferfor&thorn; sche gan hir lay declare/<MILESTONE N="78b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That sche &thorn;e Constable er &thorn;at it was Eue</L>
<L N="574">Conuerted and on crist made him bileue</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="575">This Constable was no &thorn;ing lord of &thorn;e place</L>
<L>Of which I speke &thorn;er he Constance fond</L>
<L>But kept it strongly many a wynter space</L>
<L N="578">vnder alla kyng of Northumberlond</L>
<L>That was ful wys and wor&thorn;y of his hond</L>
<L>A&yogh;ein &thorn;e scottes as men may wel heere</L>
<L N="581">But tourne a&yogh;ein I wil to my mateere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="582">Satan &thorn;at euer vs wayte&thorn; to begile /</L>
<L>Sawe of Constaunce &thorn;e persecucioun</L>
<L>And cast anoon how he might quyt hir while /</L>
<L N="585">And made a &yogh;ong knight &thorn;at dwelt in &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>Loue hir so hoot of foul affeccioun</L>
<L>That verrayly him &thorn;ou&yogh;t he schulde spille</L>
<L N="588">But he of hire / oones had his wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="589">He wowith hir but it avayle&thorn; nought</L>
<L>Sche wolde do no synne by no weye</L>
<L>And for despyt / he compassed in his &thorn;ought</L>
<L N="592">To maken hir a schamful de&thorn; to deye</L>
<L>he wayteth whan &thorn;e Constable was aweye</L>
<L>And pryuyly vpon a nyght he crepte</L>
<L N="595">In hermyngyldes chambre whil sche slepte /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="596">Wery forwaked in here Orisoun</L>
<L>Slepe&thorn; Constaunce and hermyngyld also</L>
<L>This knight &thorn;urgh Satanas temptacioun</L>
<L N="599">Al softely is to &thorn;e bed y-go
<PB REF="00000187.tif" N="175"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="149"></L>
<L>And kutte &thorn;e &thorn;rote of hermegild a two /</L>
<L>And leyd &thorn;e bloody knyf/ by dame Constaunce</L>
<L N="602">And went his way &thorn;at god &yogh;eue him meschaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="603">Sone after com&thorn; &thorn;is Constable hom agayn</L>
<L>And eek alla &thorn;at was kyng of &thorn;at lond</L>
<L>And say his wyf dispitously I-slayn</L>
<L N="606">For which ful oft / he wept and wrong his hond</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e bed &thorn;e blody knyf he fond</L>
<L>By Dame Custaunce allas what might he say</L>
<L N="609">For verray woo / hir witt was al a-way</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="610">To king Alla was told al &thorn;is meschaunce<MILESTONE N="79a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And eek/&thorn;e tyme and wher and eek &thorn;e wyse</L>
<L>That in a schip was founden &thorn;is Constaunce</L>
<L N="613">As here bifore &yogh;e haue herd me deuyse /</L>
<L>The kinges hert of pite gan agrise</L>
<L>whan he saugh so benigne a creature</L>
<L N="616">Falle in disese and in mysauenture</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="617">For as &thorn;e lomb toward his de&thorn; is brought /</L>
<L>So stant &thorn;is Innocent bifore &thorn;e kyng</L>
<L>This false knight &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;is tresoun wrought</L>
<L N="620">Bere&thorn; hir an hand &thorn;at sche hath don &thorn;is &thorn;ing</L>
<L>But neuer &thorn;e les &thorn;er was gret mornyng</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e people and seyn &thorn;ey can not gesse</L>
<L N="623">That sche had doon so gret a wikkednesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="624">For &thorn;ey han seyen hir so vertuous</L>
<L>And louyng hermegyld right as hir lyf</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is bar witnesse euerich in &thorn;at hous</L>
<L N="627">Saue he &thorn;at slow&yogh; hermegyld with his knyf</L>
<L>This gentil kyng ha&thorn; caught a gret motyf</L>
<L>Of his witnesse and &thorn;ought/ he wold enquere</L>
<L N="630">Deppere in &thorn;is cas a trou&thorn;e to lere
<PB REF="00000188.tif" N="176"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="150"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="631">Allas Constaunce &thorn;ou ne has no champioun</L>
<L>Ne fighte canstow nat so welaway</L>
<L>But he &thorn;at for oure redempcioun</L>
<L N="634">Bonde Sathan and &yogh;it li&thorn; &thorn;er he lay</L>
<L>So be &thorn;y stronge champioun &thorn;is day</L>
<L>For but crist vpon &thorn;e miracle kythe</L>
<L N="637">withouten gilt &thorn;ou schalt be slayn as swithe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="638">Sche set hir doun on knees and &thorn;an sche sayde</L>
<L>Immortal god &thorn;at sauedest Susanne</L>
<L>For false blame and &thorn;ou mercyful mayde</L>
<L N="641">Mary I mene doughter of seint Anne</L>
<L>Bifore whos child aungeles syng Osanne</L>
<L>If I be gultles of &thorn;is felonye</L>
<L N="644">My socour be for elles schal I dye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="645">Haue &yogh;e not seye somtyme a pale face</L>
<L>Among a prees of him &thorn;at ha&thorn; be lad</L>
<L>Toward his de&thorn; wher him geyne&thorn; no grace /</L>
<L N="648">And such a colour in his face ha&thorn; had<MILESTONE N="79b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Men mighte knowe his face was so bystad</L>
<L>Among alle &thorn;e faces in &thorn;at route</L>
<L N="651">So stant Constance and loke&thorn; hire aboute /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="652">O queenes lyuyng in prosperite</L>
<L>Duchesses and &yogh;e ladies euerychon</L>
<L>haue&thorn; som reu&thorn;e on hir aduersite</L>
<L N="655">An emperoures doughter stond allon</L>
<L>Sche nath no wight to whom to make hir moon</L>
<L>O blod ryal &thorn;at stondest in &thorn;is drede /</L>
<L N="658">Ferre be &thorn;y frendes at &thorn;y grete neede /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="659">This Alla kyng ha&thorn; such compassioun</L>
<L>As gentil hert/ is fulfild of pite</L>
<L>That from his eyen ran &thorn;e water doun</L>
<L N="662">Now hastily do fech a book quod he /
<PB REF="00000189.tif" N="177"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="151"></L>
<L>And if &thorn;is knight wil swere how &thorn;at sche /</L>
<L>This womman slow&yogh; &yogh;et wol we us avyse</L>
<L N="665">whom &thorn;at we wille schal be oure iustise</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="666">A britoun book I-write wi&thorn; euaungiles</L>
<L>was fette and on &thorn;is book/ he swor anoon</L>
<L>Sche gultif was and in &thorn;e mene whiles</L>
<L N="669">An hond him smot vpon &thorn;e nekke boon</L>
<L>That doun he fel anon right at a stoon</L>
<L>And bo&thorn;e his yen brast out of his face</L>
<L N="672">In sight of euery body in &thorn;at place</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="673">A vois was herd in general audience</L>
<L>And seist &thorn;ou hast disclaundred gulteles</L>
<L>The doughter of holy chirche in hire presence</L>
<L N="676">Thus hastow doon &amp; &yogh;it I holde my pees</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is meruaile agast was al &thorn;e prees</L>
<L>As mased folk &thorn;ey stooden euerychon</L>
<L N="679">For drede of wreche saue Custaunce allon</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="680">Gret was &thorn;e drede and eek &thorn;e repentaunce</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at hadden gret suspeccioun</L>
<L>vpon &thorn;e sely Innocent Custaunce</L>
<L N="683">And for &thorn;is miracle in conclusioun</L>
<L>And by Custaunces mediacioun</L>
<L>The kyng and many o&thorn;er in &thorn;e place</L>
<L N="686">Conuerted was / thanked be cristes grace<MILESTONE N="80a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="687">This false knight was slayn for his vntrou&thorn;e /</L>
<L>By Iuggement of Alla hastyly</L>
<L>And &yogh;it Custaunce ha&thorn; of his de&thorn; gret rou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="690">And after &thorn;is ihus of his mercy</L>
<L>Made alla wedde ful solempnely</L>
<L>This holy mayde &thorn;at is bright and schene /</L>
<L N="693">And &thorn;us ha&thorn; crist I-maad Constance a queene
<PB REF="00000190.tif" N="178"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="152"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="694">But who was woful if I schal not lye /</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is weddyng but Domegild and &thorn;o</L>
<L>The kynges mooder ful of tyrannye</L>
<L N="697">hir &thorn;ought hir cursed herte brast a-two</L>
<L>Sche wolde nat hir sone had I-do so</L>
<L>hir &thorn;ought despyte / &thorn;at he schulde take</L>
<L N="700">So straunge a creature vnto his make</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="701">Me lust not of &thorn;e caf ne of &thorn;e stree</L>
<L>Make so long a tale as of &thorn;e corn</L>
<L>what schuld I telle of &thorn;e realte</L>
<L N="704">Of mariage / or which cours go&thorn; biforn</L>
<L>who bloweth in a trompe or in an horn</L>
<L>The fruyt of euery tale is for to seye</L>
<L N="707">They ete &amp; drynk / and daunce / and synge &amp; pleye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="708">They gon to bed as it was skile &amp; right</L>
<L>For &thorn;ough &thorn;at wyfes ben ful holy &thorn;inges</L>
<L>They moste take in pacience a night</L>
<L N="711">Such maner necessaries as ben plesynges</L>
<L>To folk that han I-wedded hem wi&thorn; rynges</L>
<L>And haluendel her holynesse ley a side</L>
<L N="714">And for &thorn;e tyme it may non o&thorn;er betyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="715">On hire he gat a knaue child anoon</L>
<L>And to a bisschope &amp; a Constable eeke</L>
<L>he took his wyf to kepe whan he is goon</L>
<L N="718">To scotlondward his foomen for to seeke</L>
<L>Now faire Custaunce &thorn;at is so humble &amp; meeke</L>
<L>So long is goon wi&thorn; childe til &thorn;at stille</L>
<L N="721">Sche held hir chambre abidyng goddes wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="722">The tyme is come a knaue child sche bere</L>
<L>Maurius atte funstone men him calle</L>
<L>This Constabil do&thorn; come for&thorn; a messager<MILESTONE N="80b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="725">And wrot to his kyng &thorn;at cleped was Alle
<PB REF="00000191.tif" N="179"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="153"></L>
<L>how &thorn;at &thorn;is blisful tydyng is bifalle</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er &thorn;inges spedful for to seye</L>
<L N="728">he take&thorn; &thorn;e lettre and for&thorn; he go&thorn; his weye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="729">This messanger to doon his auauntage</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e kynges moder he go&thorn; ful swi&thorn;e</L>
<L>And salueth hire / fair in his langage</L>
<L N="732">Ma dame quod he &yogh;e may be glad and bli&thorn;e</L>
<L>And &thorn;anke god an hundred &thorn;ousand si&thorn;e</L>
<L>My lady queen ha&thorn; child wi&thorn;outen doute</L>
<L N="735">To ioye and blis of al &thorn;e reame aboute</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="736">Lo heer &thorn;e lettres sealed of &thorn;is &thorn;ing</L>
<L>That I mot bere with al &thorn;e hast I may</L>
<L>If &yogh;e wole ought vnto &yogh;oure sone &thorn;e kyng</L>
<L N="739">I am &yogh;oure seruaunt bo&thorn;e night and day</L>
<L>Doungyld answerde as now &thorn;is tyme nay</L>
<L>But here al nyght I wol &thorn;ou take &thorn;y rest</L>
<L N="742">To morwen I wil say &thorn;e what me lest</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="743">This messanger drank sadly ale and wyn</L>
<L>And stolen were his lettres pryuely</L>
<L>Out of his box whil he sleep as a swyn</L>
<L N="746">And countrefeet &thorn;ey were subtily</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er sche him wroot ful synfully</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e kyng direct/ of &thorn;is matiere</L>
<L N="749">Fro his Constable as &yogh;e schul after heere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="750">The lettre spak &thorn;e queen delyuered was</L>
<L>Of so orryble and feendly creature</L>
<L>That in &thorn;e castel noon so hardy was</L>
<L N="753">That eny while dorste &thorn;erin endure /</L>
<L>The mooder was an Elf by auenture</L>
<L>Bycome by charmes or by sorcerie</L>
<L N="756">And euery man hati&thorn; hir companyne
<PB REF="00000192.tif" N="180"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="154"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="757">Wo was &thorn;is kyng whan he &thorn;is letter had sein</L>
<L>But to no wight he told his sorwes sore</L>
<L>But of his owen hand he wrot agayn.</L>
<L N="760">welcome &thorn;e sond of crist for eueremore</L>
<L>To me &thorn;at am now lerned in his lore</L>
<L>lord welcome be &thorn;y lust and &thorn;y pleasaunce<MILESTONE N="81a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="763">My lust I putte al in &thorn;yn ordinaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="764">Kepeth &thorn;is child al be it foul or fair</L>
<L>And eek my wyf vnto myn hom comyng</L>
<L>Crist whan him lust may sende me an hair</L>
<L N="767">More agreable &thorn;an &thorn;is to my likyng</L>
<L>The lettre he seleth pryuyly wepyng</L>
<L>which to &thorn;e messager he took ful sone</L>
<L N="770">And for&thorn; he goth &thorn;er nys no more to done</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="771">O messager fulfild of dronkenesse</L>
<L>Strong is &thorn;y bre&thorn; &thorn;y lymes faltren ay</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou bywreyest alle sykernesse</L>
<L N="774">Thy mynde is lorn &thorn;ou ianglest as a Iay</L>
<L>Thy face is torned al in a newe array</L>
<L>Ther drunkenesse regne&thorn; in eny route</L>
<L N="777">Ther is no counseil hid wi&thorn;outen doute</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="778">O Domegyld I haue non englisch digne</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;y malice and &thorn;y tyrannye</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfor to &thorn;e feend I &thorn;e resigne</L>
<L N="781">let him endyten of &thorn;i treccherie</L>
<L>Fy mannyssch fy .o. nay by god I lye</L>
<L>Fy feendly spirit for I dar wel telle</L>
<L N="784">Though &thorn;ou here walke &thorn;y spirit is in helle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="785">This messanger com&thorn; fro &thorn;e kyng agayn</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e kinges modres court he light</L>
<L>And sche was of &thorn;is messenger ful fayn</L>
<L N="788">And plese&thorn; him in al &thorn;at euer sche might
<PB REF="00000193.tif" N="181"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="155"></L>
<L>he drank and wel his gurdel vnderpight</L>
<L>he slepe&thorn; and he fare&thorn; in his gyse</L>
<L N="791">Al nyght vnto &thorn;e sonne gan arise</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="792">Eft were his lettres stolen euerichon</L>
<L>And countrefeted lettres in &thorn;is wise</L>
<L>The kyng comaunde&thorn; his constable anon</L>
<L N="795">vp peyne of hangyng of an hei&yogh; Iustise</L>
<L>That he schulde suffre in no maner wyse</L>
<L>Constaunce in his regne for to abyde</L>
<L N="798">Thre dayes and a quarter of a tyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="799">But in &thorn;e same schip as he hir fond</L>
<L>hire and hir &yogh;onge sone and al hire gere<MILESTONE N="81b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he schulde putte and crowde fro &thorn;e londe</L>
<L N="802">And charge hire &thorn;at sche neuer eft come &thorn;ere</L>
<L>&middot;O. my Constaunce wel may &thorn;y goost haue fere</L>
<L>And slepyng in &thorn;y drem ben in penaunce</L>
<L N="805">whan Domegyl cast al &thorn;is ordynaunce /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="806">This messanger a-morwe whan he awook</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e castel held &thorn;e nexte way</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e constable he &thorn;e lettre took</L>
<L N="809">And whan &thorn;at he &thorn;e pitous lettre say</L>
<L>Ful ofte he seyd allas and welaway</L>
<L>Lord crist quod he how may &thorn;is world endure</L>
<L N="812">So ful of synne is many a creature</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="813">O mighty god if &thorn;at it be &thorn;y wille</L>
<L>Se&thorn; &thorn;ou art rightful iugge how may &thorn;is be /</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou wolt suffre Innocent&yogh; to spille /</L>
<L N="816">And wikked folk regne in prosperite</L>
<L>&middot;O good Constance allas so wo is me</L>
<L>That I moot be &thorn;y tormentour or deye</L>
<L N="819">On schamful de&thorn; &thorn;er is non o&thorn;er weye
<PB REF="00000194.tif" N="182"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="156"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="820">Wepyng bo&thorn;e &yogh;ong &amp; olde in al &thorn;at place</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng &thorn;is corsed lettre sent</L>
<L>And Constance with a dedly pale face</L>
<L N="823">The fayre day toward hir schip sche went</L>
<L>But neuer&thorn;eles sche take&thorn; in good entent</L>
<L>The wil of crist / and knelyng on &thorn;e grounde</L>
<L N="826">Sche sayde lord ay welcome be &thorn;y sonde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="827">He &thorn;at me kepte fro &thorn;e false blame</L>
<L>whil I was on &thorn;e lond amonges &yogh;ou</L>
<L>He can me kepe from harm &amp; eek fro schame</L>
<L N="830">In &thorn;e see al &thorn;ough I se nat how</L>
<L>As strong as euer he was he is right now</L>
<L>In him trust I. &amp; in his mooder deere</L>
<L N="833">That is to me my sayl and eek my steere /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="834">Hir litel child lay wepyng in hir arm</L>
<L>And knelyng pitously to him sche sayde /</L>
<L>Pees litle sone I wol do &thorn;e noon harm</L>
<L N="837">wi&thorn; &thorn;at hir kerchef of hir hed sche brayde</L>
<L>And ouer his litel y&yogh;en sche it layde<MILESTONE N="82a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And in hir arm sche lullith it wel faste</L>
<L N="840">And vnto heuen hir ey&yogh;en vp sche caste</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="841">Moder quod sche and mayde bright marie</L>
<L>So&thorn; is &thorn;at &thorn;urgh wommannes eggement</L>
<L>Mankynde was lorn and dampned ay to dye</L>
<L N="844">For which &thorn;y child was on a cros torent</L>
<L>Thyn blisful ey&yogh;en sawh al &thorn;is torment</L>
<L>Then nys &thorn;er noon comparisoun bitwene</L>
<L N="847">Thy wo and any woo may nat sustene</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="848">Thow saugh &thorn;y child I-slaw byfor &thorn;yn yen</L>
<L>And &yogh;it now lyue&thorn; my litel child par fay</L>
<L>Now lady bright to whom alle woful cryen</L>
<L N="851">Thou glory of wommanhod &thorn;ou faire may
<PB REF="00000195.tif" N="183"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="157"></L>
<L>Thou heuen of refute brighte sterre of day</L>
<L>Rewe on my child &thorn;at of &thorn;yn gentilnesse /</L>
<L N="854">Rewest on euery synful in destresse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="855">O litel child allas what is &thorn;i gilt</L>
<L>That neuer wroughtest synne as &yogh;et par de</L>
<L>why wil &thorn;yn harde fader han &thorn;e spilt</L>
<L N="858">O. mercy deere and Constable seyde sche</L>
<L>And let my litel child here dwelle with &thorn;e</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou darst not sauen him for blame /</L>
<L N="861">So kys him oones in his fadres name</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="862">Ther wi&thorn; sche loked bakward to &thorn;e lond</L>
<L>And seyde far wel housbond rew&thorn;eles</L>
<L>And vp sche rist and walke&thorn; doun &thorn;e stronde</L>
<L N="865">Toward &thorn;e schip hir folwe&thorn; al &thorn;e prees</L>
<L>And euer sche preye&thorn; hir child to hold his pees</L>
<L>And took hir leue and wi&thorn; an holy entent</L>
<L N="868">Sche blesse&thorn; hire and to &thorn;e schip sche went</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="869">Vytailled was &thorn;e schip it is no drede</L>
<L>Abundauntly for hire ful longe space</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er necessaries &thorn;at schulde nede</L>
<L N="872">Sche had ynow&yogh; heryed be criste&yogh; grace</L>
<L>For wynd and water almighty god purchace</L>
<L>And bryng hir hom I can no bettre say</L>
<L N="875">But in &thorn;e see sche dryue&thorn; for&thorn; hir way</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[PART III.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="876">Alla &thorn;e kyng com&thorn; hom soon after &thorn;is<MILESTONE N="82b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e Castel of &thorn;e which I tolde</L>
<L>And aske&thorn; wher his wyf and his child ys</L>
<L N="879">The Constable gan aboute his herte colde
<PB REF="00000196.tif" N="184"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="158"></L>
<L>And playnly al &thorn;e maner he him tolde</L>
<L>As &yogh;e han herd / I can telle it no better</L>
<L N="882">And schewed &thorn;e kynges seal and his letter</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="883">And seyde lord as &yogh;e comaunded me</L>
<L>vp peyne of de&thorn; so haue I do certayn</L>
<L>This messager tormented was til he</L>
<L N="886">Moste biknowe and telle it plat and playn &middot;</L>
<L>Fro nyght to night in what place he had layn &middot;</L>
<L>And &thorn;us by witt/ and subtil enqueryng</L>
<L N="889">ymagined was by wham &thorn;is gan to spryng</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="890">The hand was knowen &thorn;at &thorn;e lettre wroot</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e venym of &thorn;is cursed dede</L>
<L>But in what wyse certeynly I noot</L>
<L N="893">Theffect is &thorn;is &thorn;at alla out of drede</L>
<L>his moder slough as men may pleynly reede /</L>
<L>For &thorn;at sche traytour was to hir ligeaunce</L>
<L N="896">Thus ende&thorn; olde Domegild wi&thorn; meschaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="897">The sorwe &thorn;at/ &thorn;is alla night and day</L>
<L>Mak&thorn; for his wyf and for his child also</L>
<L>Ther is no tonge &thorn;at it telle may</L>
<L N="900">But now I wol vnto Custaunce go</L>
<L>That fleetet&thorn; in &thorn;e see in peyne and wo</L>
<L>.V. &yogh;eer and more as like&thorn; cristes sonde</L>
<L N="903">Er &thorn;at hir schip approched vnto londe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="904">Vnder an hethen castel atte last</L>
<L>Of which &thorn;e name in my text nou&yogh;t I fynde</L>
<L>Constaunce and eek hir child &thorn;e see vpcast</L>
<L N="907">Almighty god &thorn;at saueth al mankynde /</L>
<L>Haue on Constaunce and on hir child som mynde</L>
<L>That fallen is in hethen hond eft sone</L>
<L N="910">In poynt to spille as I schal telle &yogh;ou soone
<PB REF="00000197.tif" N="185"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="159"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="911">Doun fro &thorn;e Castel com&thorn; &thorn;er many a wight</L>
<L>To gawren on &thorn;is schip and on Constaunce</L>
<L>But schortly fro &thorn;e castel on a night</L>
<L N="914">The lordes styward God &yogh;iue him meschaunce<MILESTONE N="83a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A &thorn;eef &thorn;at had reneyed oure creaunce</L>
<L>Com in to schip alone and seyd he scholde</L>
<L N="917">hir lemman be whe&thorn;ir sche wold or nolde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="918">Wo was &thorn;is wrecched womman &thorn;o bigoon</L>
<L>hire childe crie&thorn; and sche pytously</L>
<L>But blisful mary hilp hir right anoon</L>
<L N="921">For wi&thorn; hir streng&thorn;e wel and mightily</L>
<L>The theef fel ouer boord al sodeinly</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e see he drenched for vengaunce</L>
<L N="924">And &thorn;us ha&thorn; crist vnwemmed kept Constance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="925">O foule lust/ O luxurie lo &thorn;in ende /</L>
<L>Nought oonly &thorn;at &thorn;ou feyntest mannes mynde</L>
<L>But verrayly &thorn;ou wolt his body schende</L>
<L N="928">The ende of &thorn;yn werk or of &thorn;y lustes blynde</L>
<L>his compleynyng how many may men fynde</L>
<L>That nought for werk som tyme but/ for &thorn;entent</L>
<L N="931">To doon his synne ben ey&thorn;er slayn or schent /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="932">How may &thorn;is weyke womman han &thorn;e streng&thorn;e</L>
<L>hir to defende a&yogh;ein &thorn;e renegat</L>
<L>O Golias vnmesurable of leng&thorn;e</L>
<L N="935">how mighte dauid make &thorn;e so mate</L>
<L>So &yogh;ong and of armure so desolate</L>
<L>how dorst he loke vpon &thorn;yn dredful face</L>
<L N="938">wel may men seyn it nas but goddes grace</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="939">Who &yogh;af Iudith corage or hardynesse /</L>
<L>To slen him Olefernes in his tent</L>
<L>And to delyueren out &thorn;e wrecchednes</L>
<L N="942">The peple of god I say in &thorn;is entent
<PB REF="00000198.tif" N="186"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="160"></L>
<L>That right as good spiryte vigor sent</L>
<L>To hem and saued hem out of meschaunce /</L>
<L N="945">So sent he might and vigor to Constaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="946">Forth go&thorn; hir schip &thorn;urghout &thorn;e narwe mouth</L>
<L>Of Iubalter and Septe dryuyng ay</L>
<L>Somtyme west som tyme north and south</L>
<L N="949">And somtyme Est ful many a wery way</L>
<L>Til cristes mooder blessed be sche ay</L>
<L>ha&thorn; schapen &thorn;urgh hir endeles goodnesse</L>
<L N="952">To make an ende of hir heuynesse<MILESTONE N="83b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="953">Now let vs stynt of Constance but a &thorn;rowe</L>
<L>And speke we of / &thorn;e Romayn Emperour</L>
<L>That out of Surrye ha&thorn; by lettres knowe</L>
<L N="956">The slaughter of cristen folk and deshonour</L>
<L>Doon to his dou&yogh;ter by a fals traytour</L>
<L>I mene &thorn;e cursed and wikked sowdenesse</L>
<L N="959">That at &thorn;e fest leet slee bo&thorn;e more and lesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="960">For which &thorn;is Emperour ha&thorn; sent anoon</L>
<L>his senatours with real ordynaunce</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er lordes got wot many oon</L>
<L N="963">On surriens to take high vengaunce</L>
<L>They brenne / sleen / and bringen hem to meschaunce</L>
<L>Ful many a day but schortly &thorn;is is &thorn;ende</L>
<L N="966">homward to Rome &thorn;ey schapen hem to wende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="967">This Senatour repayre&thorn; wi&thorn; victorie</L>
<L>To Romeward saylyng ful really</L>
<L>And mette &thorn;e schip dryuyng as sei&thorn; &thorn;e story</L>
<L N="970">In which Constance sitte&thorn; ful pitously</L>
<L>No &thorn;ing ne knew he what sche was ne why</L>
<L>Sche was in such aray / sche nolde seye</L>
<L N="973">Of hire astaat al &thorn;ough sche scholde deye
<PB REF="00000199.tif" N="187"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="161"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="974">He brynge&thorn; hir to Rome and to his wyf</L>
<L>he &yogh;af hir and hir &yogh;onge sone also</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;e Senatour lad sche hir lyf</L>
<L N="977">Thus can our lady. bryngen out of woo</L>
<L>woful Constance and many ano&thorn;er moo</L>
<L>And longe tyme dwelled sche in &thorn;at place</L>
<L N="980">In holy werkes. as euer was hir grace /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="981">The Senatoures wif hir aunte was</L>
<L>But for al &thorn;at sche knew hir neuer more</L>
<L>I wol no lenger taryen in &thorn;is cas</L>
<L N="984">But to kyng Alla which I spak of &yogh;ore /</L>
<L>That for his wyf wepe&thorn; and sike&thorn; sore /</L>
<L>I wol retorne / and lete I wol Constaunce</L>
<L N="987">vnder &thorn;e Senatoures gouernaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="988">Kyng alla which &thorn;at had his mooder slayn</L>
<L>vpon a day fel in such repentaunce /</L>
<L>That if I schortly telle schal and playn<MILESTONE N="84a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="991">To Rome he come&thorn; to receyue his penaunce</L>
<L>And putte him in &thorn;e popes ordynaunce</L>
<L>In heigh and lowe and ih&umacr; crist bysought</L>
<L N="994">For&yogh;ef his wikked werkes &thorn;at he wrought</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="995">The fame anon &thorn;urgh Rome toun is born</L>
<L>how alla kyng schal come in pilgrymage</L>
<L>By herberiour&yogh; &thorn;at wenten him biforn</L>
<L N="998">For which &thorn;e Senatour as was vsage</L>
<L>Rood him a&yogh;ein and many of his lynage</L>
<L>As wel to schewen his magnificence</L>
<L N="1001">As to doon eny kyng a reuerence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1002">Gret cheere do&thorn; &thorn;is noble Senatour</L>
<L>To kyng Alla and he to him also</L>
<L>Euerich of hem do&thorn; o&thorn;er gret honour</L>
<L N="1005">And so bifel &thorn;at on a day or two
<PB REF="00000200.tif" N="188"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="162"></L>
<L>This Senatour is to kyng Alla go</L>
<L>To fest and schortly if I schal not lye</L>
<L N="1008">Constances sone / went in his companye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1009">Som men wold seyn at request of Custaunce</L>
<L>This Senatour ha&thorn; lad &thorn;is child to feste</L>
<L>I may not telle euery circumstaunce</L>
<L N="1012">Be as be may &thorn;er was he atte leste</L>
<L>But soth it is right at his modres heste</L>
<L>Byforn hem alle duryng &thorn;e metes space</L>
<L N="1015">The child stood lokyng in &thorn;e kynges face</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1016">This alla kyng ha&thorn; of &thorn;e child gret wonder</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e Senatour he seyd anoon</L>
<L>whos is &thorn;at faire child &thorn;at stonde&thorn; &yogh;onder</L>
<L N="1019">I not quod he by god and by seynt Ion</L>
<L>A moder he ha&thorn; but fader ha&thorn; he non</L>
<L>That I of woot and schortly in a stounde</L>
<L N="1022">he told Alla how &thorn;at &thorn;is child was founde /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1023">But god woot quod &thorn;is senatour also</L>
<L>So vertuous a lyuer in my lyf</L>
<L>Ne saugh I neuer such as sche nomo</L>
<L N="1026">Of worldly womman mayden or of wyf</L>
<L>I dar wel say sche hadde leuer a knyf</L>
<L>Thurghout hir brest &thorn;an ben a womman wikke<MILESTONE N="84b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1029">Ther is no man can bryng hir to &thorn;at prikke</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1030">Now was &thorn;is child as lik vnto Custaunce</L>
<L>As possible is a creature to be</L>
<L>This alla ha&thorn; &thorn;e face in remembraunce</L>
<L N="1033">Of Dame Custaunce and &thorn;er on mused he</L>
<L>If &thorn;at &thorn;e childes mooder were ought sche</L>
<L>That is his wyf and pryuely he hight</L>
<L N="1036">And sped him fro &thorn;e table &thorn;at he might
<PB REF="00000201.tif" N="189"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="163"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1037">Par fay &thorn;ought he fantom is in myn heed</L>
<L>I ought to deme of righful Iuggement</L>
<L>That in &thorn;e salte see my wyf is deed</L>
<L N="1040">And afterward he made &thorn;is argument</L>
<L>what woot I wher crist ha&thorn; hider sent</L>
<L>My wyf by see as wel as he hir sent</L>
<L N="1043">To my contre fro &thorn;ennes &thorn;at sche went</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1044">And after noom home wi&thorn; &thorn;e senatour</L>
<L>Goth alla for to see &thorn;is wonder chaunce</L>
<L>This Senatour do&thorn; alla gret honour</L>
<L N="1047">And hastely he sent after Custaunce</L>
<L>But truste&thorn; wel hir luste nat to daunce /</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at sche wiste wherfore was &thorn;at sonde</L>
<L N="1050">vnnethes on hir feet/ sche mighte stonde /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1051">Whan alla saugh his wyf fayre he hir grette</L>
<L>And wepte &thorn;at it was rew&thorn;e to se</L>
<L>For at &thorn;e firste look he on hir sette</L>
<L N="1054">he knew wel verrely &thorn;at it was sche</L>
<L>And for sorwe as domb sche stant as tre</L>
<L>So was hire herte schett in his distresse</L>
<L N="1057">whan sche remembred his vnkyndenesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1058">Twies sche swowned in his owen sight</L>
<L>he wept and him excuse&thorn; pitously</L>
<L>Now god quod he and alle his halwes bright</L>
<L N="1061">So wisly on my soule haue mercy</L>
<L>That of &yogh;oure harm as gulteles am I</L>
<L>As is maurice my sone so lyk &yogh;oure face</L>
<L N="1064">Elles &thorn;e feend me fecche out of &thorn;is place /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1065">Long was &thorn;e sobbyng and &thorn;e bitter peyne</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at here woful herte mighte cesse<MILESTONE N="85a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Gret was &thorn;e pite for to here hem pleyne</L>
<L N="1068">Thurgh whiche playnt&yogh; gan here wo encresse
<PB REF="00000202.tif" N="190"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="164"></L>
<L>I pray &yogh;ou alle my labour to relesse</L>
<L>I may not telle al here sorwe vnto morwe</L>
<L N="1071">I am so wery for to speke of &thorn;e sorwe /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1072">But fynally whan &thorn;at the so&thorn; is wist</L>
<L>That alla gilteles was of hir woo</L>
<L>I trowe an hundred tymes &thorn;ey ben kist</L>
<L N="1075">And such a blys is &thorn;er bitwix hem tuo</L>
<L>That saue &thorn;e ioye &thorn;at laste&thorn; eueremo</L>
<L>Ther is noon lyk &thorn;at eny creature</L>
<L N="1078">ha&thorn; seyn or schal. whil &thorn;at &thorn;e world may dure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1079">Tho prayde sche hir housbond meekely</L>
<L>In &thorn;e relees of hir pytous pyne</L>
<L>The he wold preye hir fader specially</L>
<L N="1082">That of his maieste he wold enclyne</L>
<L>To vouche sauf som tyme with him to dyne</L>
<L>Sche preye&thorn; him eek he schulde by no weye</L>
<L N="1085">Vnto hir fader no word of hir seye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1086">Som men wold seye &thorn;at hir child Maurice</L>
<L>Do&thorn; his message vnto &thorn;e Emperour</L>
<L>But as I gesse alla was nat so nyce</L>
<L N="1089">To him &thorn;at is so souerayn of honour</L>
<L>As he &thorn;at is of cristes folk &thorn;e flour</L>
<L>Sent eny child but it is best to deeme</L>
<L N="1092">he went himsilf and so it may wel seme /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1093">This Emperour ha&thorn; graunted gentilly</L>
<L>To come to dyner as he him bysought</L>
<L>As wel rede I he loked besily</L>
<L N="1096">vpon &thorn;e child and on his dou&yogh;ter &thorn;ought</L>
<L>Alla go&thorn; to his In and as him ought</L>
<L>Arrayed for &thorn;is fest in euery wyse</L>
<L N="1099">As ferforth as his connyng may suffise
<PB REF="00000203.tif" N="191"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="165"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1100">The morwe cam and alla gan him dresse</L>
<L>And eek his wyf &thorn;e Emperour for to meete</L>
<L>And for &thorn;ey ryde in ioye and in gladnesse /</L>
<L N="1103">And whan sche saugh hir fader in &thorn;e streete</L>
<L>Sche light a doun and falle&thorn; him to feete<MILESTONE N="85b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Fader quod sche &yogh;our &yogh;onge child Constance</L>
<L N="1106">Is now ful clene ou of &yogh;our remembraunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1107">I am &yogh;our doughter Custaunce quod sche</L>
<L>That whilom &yogh;e haue sent vnto Surrye</L>
<L>It am I fader &thorn;at in &thorn;e salte see</L>
<L N="1110">was put alloon and dampned for to dye</L>
<L>Now goode fader mercy I &yogh;ou crye</L>
<L>Send me no more vnto noon hethenesse</L>
<L N="1113">But &thorn;anke my lord her of his kyndenesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1114">Who can &thorn;e pytous Ioye telle al</L>
<L>Bitwix hem &thorn;re si&thorn; &thorn;ey be &thorn;us I-mette</L>
<L>But of my tale make an ende I schal</L>
<L N="1117">The day go&thorn; fast I wol no lenger lette</L>
<L>This glade folk to dyner &thorn;ey ben sette</L>
<L>In ioye and blys at mete I let hem dwelle</L>
<L N="1120">A &thorn;ousand fold wel more &thorn;an I can telle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1121">This child Maurice was si&thorn;&thorn;en Emperour</L>
<L>I-maad by &thorn;e pope and lyued cristenly</L>
<L>To cristes chirche dede he gret honour</L>
<L N="1124">But I let al his story passen by</L>
<L>Of Custaunce is my tale specially</L>
<L>In olde Romayn gestes men may fynde</L>
<L N="1127">Maurices lyf I bere it nought in mynde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1128">This kyng alla whan he his tyme say</L>
<L>with his Constaunce his holy wyf so swete</L>
<L>To Engelond &thorn;ey com &thorn;e righte way</L>
<L N="1131">wher as &thorn;ey lyue in ioye and in quyete
<PB REF="00000204.tif" N="192"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="166"></L>
<L>But litel whil it last I &yogh;ou biheete;</L>
<L>Ioy of &thorn;is world // for tyme wol not abyde</L>
<L N="1134">Fro day to night it chaungeth as &thorn;e tyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1135">Who lyued euer in such delyt a day</L>
<L>That him ne meued ey&thorn;er his conscience</L>
<L>Of Ire or talent / or som maner affray</L>
<L N="1138">Enuy or pride or passioun or offence</L>
<L>I ne say but for &thorn;is ende &thorn;is sentence</L>
<L>But litel whil in ioye or in plesaunce</L>
<L N="1141">laste&thorn; &thorn;e blis / of alla with Custaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1142">For deth &thorn;at tak&thorn; of heigh &amp; low his rent<MILESTONE N="86a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>whan passed was a &yogh;eere as I gesse /</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is worlde / kyng alla he hent</L>
<L N="1145">For whom Custauns. ha&thorn; ful gret heuynesse /</L>
<L>Now let vs pray. &thorn;at god his soule blesse /</L>
<L>And dame Custaunce fynally to say</L>
<L N="1148">Toward &thorn;e toun of Rome go&thorn; hir way</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1149">To Rome is come &thorn;is nobil creature</L>
<L>And fynt hir freendes &thorn;er bo&thorn;e hool &amp; sound</L>
<L>Now is sche skaped al hir auenture</L>
<L N="1152">And whanne sche hir fader had I-founde</L>
<L>Doun on hir knees falle&thorn; sche to grounde</L>
<L>wepyng for tendirnes in herte blithe</L>
<L N="1155">Sche heried god an hundred &thorn;ousand sithe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1156">In vertu and in holy almesdede</L>
<L>They lyuen alle. and neuer a sondre wende</L>
<L>Til de&thorn; departe hem &thorn;is lyf &thorn;ey lede</L>
<L N="1159">And far now wel my tale is at an ende</L>
<L>Now ih&umacr; crist &thorn;at of his might may sende /</L>
<L>Ioy after wo gouerne vs in his grace /</L>
<L N="1162">And keep ous alle. &thorn;at ben in &thorn;is place /
<PB REF="00000205.tif" N="193"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="167"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Our Ost vppon his styrops stood anoon&middot;</L>
<L>And seyde good men herkneth euerychoon&middot;</L>
<L>This was a &thorn;rifty tale for &thorn;e noones</L>
<L N="1166">Sir parissh prest quod he for goodes boones</L>
<L>Tel out a tale / as was &thorn;y forward &yogh;ore</L>
<L>I see wel &thorn;at &yogh;e lered men in lore</L>
<L>Can moche good by goddes dignete</L>
<L N="1170">The parsoun him answerde ben dicite</L>
<L>what eyle&thorn; &thorn;e man so synfully to swere</L>
<L>Our Ost answerd. O Iankyn be &yogh;e &thorn;ere</L>
<L>I smel a loller in &thorn;e wynd quod he</L>
<L N="1174">Now good men quod our Oste / herkne&thorn; me</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="inline">[A break of one line in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
<L>For we schul haue a predicacioun</L>
<L>This loller wolde prechen vs heer som what /</L>
<L N="1178">Nay by my fader soule &thorn;at schal he nat/</L>
<L>Sayde the sompnour he schal heer nau&yogh;t preche</L>
<L>he schal no gospel preche here ne teche<MILESTONE N="86b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>we leuyn alle in &thorn;e grete god quod he</L>
<L N="1182">He wolde schewen som difficulte</L>
<L>Or springen cokkil in our clene corn</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfor ost I warne &thorn;e byforn</L>
<L>My ioly body schal a tale telle</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>&para; Here endith &thorn;e man of lawe his tale.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="D" TYPE="group">

<PB REF="00000206.tif" N="194">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="334">
<HEAD>GROUP D. FRAGMENT V.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; 1. WIFE OF BATH'S PREAMBLE.</HEAD>
<HEAD>&para; Here bygynneth the prologe of the wyf of Bathe</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Experiens &thorn;ough noon auctorite</L>
<L>were in &thorn;is world. it were ynough for me</L>
<L>To speke of wo &thorn;at is in mariage</L>
<L N="4">For lordyngs syns I twelf &yogh;er was of age</L>
<L>I thank it god &thorn;at is eterne on lyue</L>
<L>housbondes atte chirch dore. I haue had fyue</L>
<L>For I so ofte might haue weddid be</L>
<L N="8">And alle were wor&thorn;y men in here degre</L>
<L>But me was taught nought longe tyme goon is</L>
<L>That synnes crist went neuer but onys</L>
<L>To weddyng in &thorn;e Cane of Galile</L>
<L N="12">That by &thorn;e same ensampul taught he me</L>
<L>That I ne weddid schulde be but ones</L>
<L>Herken such a scharp word for &thorn;e nones</L>
<L>Biside a welle Ihc god and man.</L>
<L N="16">Spak in reproef of &thorn;e Samaritan</L>
<L>Thou hast y-had fyue housbondes quod he</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ilk man which &thorn;at now ha&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L>Is nou&yogh;t &thorn;in housbond &thorn;us he sayd certayn</L>
<L N="20">what &thorn;at he ment &thorn;er by I can not sayn</L>
<L>But &thorn;at I axe why &thorn;e fyfte man</L>
<L>was nought housbond to &thorn;e Samaritan</L>
<L>How many might sche haue in mariage</L>
<L N="24">&YOGH;it herd I neuer tellen in myn age
<PB REF="00000207.tif" N="195"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="335"></L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;is noumbre diffinicioun</L>
<L>Men may diuine and glosen vp and doun</L>
<L>But wel I wot wi&thorn;outen eny lye</L>
<L N="28">God bad vs for to. wax and multiplie</L>
<L>That gentil tixt. can I wel vnderstonde</L>
<L>Ek wel I wot he sayd myn housebonde</L>
<L>Schuld lete fader and moder and folwe me<MILESTONE N="87a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="32">But of no noumber mencioun made he</L>
<L>Of Bygamye. or of Octogomye /</L>
<L>why schuld men speken of &thorn;at vilonye /</L>
<L>lo hier &thorn;e wise kyng Daun Salamon</L>
<L N="36">I trow he hadde wyfes mo &thorn;an oon.</L>
<L>As wold god it were leful vnto me</L>
<L>To be refreisshed half so oft as he</L>
<L>which &yogh;ift of god had he for alle his wyuys</L>
<L N="40">No man ha&thorn; such &thorn;at in &thorn;e world on lyue is</L>
<L>God wot &thorn;is nobil king as to my wit</L>
<L>The firste night had many a mery fit/</L>
<L>with ech of hem so wel was him on lyue</L>
<L N="44">I-blessid be god &thorn;at I haue weddid fyue</L>
<L>welcome &thorn;e sixte whan &thorn;at euer he schal</L>
<L>For sothe I nyl not kepe me chast in al</L>
<L>whan myn housbond is fro &thorn;e world I-gon</L>
<L N="48">Som cristne man schal wedde me anoon</L>
<L>For &thorn;an &thorn;apostil saith &thorn;at I am fre</L>
<L>To wedde a goddis haf wher so it be</L>
<L>he saith &thorn;at to be weddid is no synne</L>
<L N="52">Bet is to be weddid &thorn;an to brynne</L>
<L>what recchith me what folk sayn viloyne</L>
<L>Of schrewith lameth or of Bigamye /</L>
<L>I wot wel abram was an holy man</L>
<L N="56">And Iacob eek as ferforth as I can</L>
<L>And ech of hem had wyues mo than tuo</L>
<L>And many another holy man also</L>
<L>whan sawe &yogh;e in eny maner age</L>
<L N="60">That highe god defendid mariage
<PB REF="00000208.tif" N="196"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="336"></L>
<L>By expres word I pray &yogh;ow tellith me</L>
<L>Or wher comaunded he virginite</L>
<L>I wot as wel as &yogh;e it is no drede /</L>
<L N="64">Thapostil whan he spek&thorn; of maydenhede</L>
<L>he sayd &thorn;at precept &thorn;er of had he noon</L>
<L>Men may counseil a womman to be oon</L>
<L>But counselyng nys no comaundement</L>
<L N="68">He put it in our owne Iuggement /</L>
<L>For hadde god comaundid maydenhede /<MILESTONE N="87b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Than had he dampnyd weddyng with &thorn;e dede</L>
<L>And certes if &thorn;er were no seed I-sowe /</L>
<L N="72">Virginite &middot; wher-on schuld it growe</L>
<L>Poul ne dorst not comaunde atte lest</L>
<L>A &thorn;ing of which his maister &yogh;af non hest</L>
<L>The dart is set vpon virginite</L>
<L N="76">Cach who-so may who rennith best / let se</L>
<L>But &thorn;is word is not taken of euery wight</L>
<L>But &thorn;er as god list &yogh;iue it of his might/</L>
<L>I wot wel &thorn;at &thorn;apostil was a mayde</L>
<L N="80">But na&thorn;eles &thorn;ough &thorn;at he wrot or sayde</L>
<L>he wolde &thorn;at euery wight were such as he /</L>
<L>Al nys but counseil vnto virginite</L>
<L>And for to ben a wyf he &yogh;af me leue</L>
<L N="84">Of indigence . so nys it to repreue</L>
<L>to wedde me if &thorn;at my make deye</L>
<L>withoute excepcioun of bigamye</L>
<L>Al were it good to womman for to touche</L>
<L N="88">he mente in his bed or in his couche</L>
<L>For peril is bo&thorn;e fuyr an tow to assemble</L>
<L>&YOGH;e knowe what &thorn;is ensample wold resemble</L>
<L>This is al and som / he holdith virginite</L>
<L N="92">More parfit &thorn;an weddyng in frelte</L>
<L>Frelte clepe I &middot; but if &thorn;at he and sche</L>
<L>wold leden al her lif in chastite</L>
<L>I graunt it wel I haue noon enuye</L>
<L N="96">Though maidenhede preferre bygamye
<PB REF="00000209.tif" N="197"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="337"></L>
<L>It like&thorn; hem to be clene in body and gost</L>
<L>Of myn estate I nyl make no bost</L>
<L>For wel &yogh;e wot a lord in his houshold</L>
<L N="100">He nath not euery vessel ful of gold</L>
<L>Som ben of tre and don her lord seruise</L>
<L>God clepeth folk to him in sondry wise</L>
<L>And euery ha&thorn; of god a propre &yogh;ifte</L>
<L N="104">Som &thorn;is som &thorn;at as him likith to schifte</L>
<L>Virginite is gret perfeccioun</L>
<L>And continens eek wi&thorn; gret deuocioun</L>
<L>But crist &thorn;at of perfeccioun is welle<MILESTONE N="88a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="108">Bad nou&yogh;t euery wight schuld go and selle</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at he had and &yogh;iue it to &thorn;e pore</L>
<L>And in such wise folwe him and his fore /</L>
<L>he spak to hem &thorn;at wolde lyue parfytly</L>
<L N="112">But lordyngs by &yogh;our leue &thorn;at am not I</L>
<L>I wol bystowe &thorn;e flour of myn age /</L>
<L>In &thorn;e actes and in &thorn;e fruytes of mariage</L>
<L>Tel me also to what conclusioun</L>
<L N="116">were membres maad of generacioun</L>
<L>And in what wise was a wight y-wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Trustith right wel &thorn;ay were nou&yogh;t maad for nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Glose who-so wol and say bo&thorn;e vp and doun</L>
<L N="120">&thorn;at &thorn;ay were made for purgacioun</L>
<L>Oure bo&thorn;e vryn and &thorn;inges smale /</L>
<L>was eek to knowe a femel fro a male</L>
<L>And for non o&thorn;er cause say &yogh;e no</L>
<L N="124">Thexperiens wot wel it is not so /</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ese clerke ben not with me wro&thorn;e /</L>
<L>I say &thorn;is &thorn;at &thorn;ay makid ben for bo&thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to say for office and for ease</L>
<L N="128">Of engendrure &thorn;er we god nou&yogh;t displease</L>
<L>why schuld men ellis in her bokes sette</L>
<L>That man schal &yogh;elde to his wif his dette</L>
<L>Now wher-wi&thorn; schuld he paye his payement</L>
<L N="132">If he ne vsed his sely instrument
<PB REF="00000210.tif" N="198"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="338"></L>
<L>Than were &thorn;ay maad vp a creature</L>
<L>To purge vryn and eek for engendrure</L>
<L>By I say not &thorn;at euery wight is holde</L>
<L N="136">That ha&thorn; such harneys as I to &yogh;ow tolde</L>
<L>To gon and vsen hem in engendrure</L>
<L>Than schuld men take of chastite no cure</L>
<L>Crist was a mayde and schapen as a man</L>
<L N="140">And many a seynt sin &thorn;at &thorn;e world bygan</L>
<L>&YOGH;it lyued &thorn;ay euer in parfyt charite</L>
<L>I nyl enuye no virginite</L>
<L>let hem be bred of pured whete seed</L>
<L N="144">And let vs wyues eten barly breed</L>
<L>And &yogh;et wi&thorn; barly bred men telle can<MILESTONE N="88b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Oure lord refreisschid many a man</L>
<L>In such astaat as god ha&thorn; cleped ous</L>
<L N="148">I wil perseuer I am not precious</L>
<L>In wyfhode I wil vse myn instrument</L>
<L>Als frely as my maker ha&thorn; me it sent</L>
<L>If I be daungerous god &yogh;iue me sorwe</L>
<L N="152">Myn housbond schal han it at eue and at morwe</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at him list com forth and pay his dette</L>
<L>An housbond wol I haue I wol not lette /</L>
<L>which schal be bo&thorn;e my dettour and my &thorn;ral</L>
<L N="156">And haue his tribulacioun wi&thorn; al</L>
<L>vpon his fleissch whil &thorn;at I am his wyf</L>
<L>I haue &thorn;e power duryng al my lif</L>
<L>vpon his propre body and not he /</L>
<L N="160">Right &thorn;us &thorn;apostil told it vnto me /</L>
<L>And bad oure housbondes for to loue vs wel</L>
<L>Al &thorn;is sentence me likith euery del</L>
<L>&para; vp start &thorn;e pardoner and &thorn;at anoon</L>
<L N="164">Now dame quod he by god and by seint Iohn</L>
<L>&YOGH;e ben a noble prechour in &thorn;is caas</L>
<L>I was aboute to wedde a wif allaas</L>
<L>what schal I buy it on my fleisch so deere</L>
<L N="168">&YOGH;it had I leuer wedde no wif to &yogh;ere
<PB REF="00000211.tif" N="199"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="339"></L>
<L>Abyd quod sche my tale is not bygonne /</L>
<L>Nay &thorn;ou schalt drinke of ano&thorn;er tonne</L>
<L>Er &thorn;at I go schal sauere wors &thorn;an ale</L>
<L N="172">And whan &thorn;at I haue told &thorn;e for&thorn; my tale</L>
<L>Of tribulacioun in mariage</L>
<L>I which I am expert/ in al myn age</L>
<L>This is to say my self ha&thorn; ben &thorn;e whippe</L>
<L N="176">Than might &thorn;ou chese whe&thorn;ir &thorn;ou wilt sippe</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ilke tonne &thorn;at I schal abroche</L>
<L>Be war of it er &thorn;ou to neigh approche</L>
<L>For I schal telle ensamples mo &thorn;an ten</L>
<L N="180">who-so &thorn;at nyl be war by o&thorn;er men</L>
<L>By him schal o&thorn;er men corrected be</L>
<L>The same wordes writes protholome</L>
<L>Rede in his almagest and tak it &thorn;ere<MILESTONE N="89a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="184">Dame I wold pray &yogh;ow . if &thorn;at &yogh;oure wille were</L>
<L>Sayde &thorn;is pardoner as &yogh;e bigan</L>
<L>Tel forth &yogh;oure tale sparith for no man</L>
