<L N="840">&YOGH;e woltow so sir sompnour quod &thorn;e frere</L>
<L>Now by my fay I schal er &thorn;at I go</L>
<L>Telle of a sompnour such a tale or tuo</L>
<L>That alle &thorn;e folk/ schuln laughen in &thorn;is place /</L>
<L N="844">Now ellis frere I byschrew &thorn;y face</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;is Sompnour and I byschrewe me</L>
<L>But / if I telle tales tuo or &thorn;re</L>
<L>Of freres er I come to Sydingborne</L>
<L N="848">&THORN;at I schal make &thorn;in herte for to morne
<PB REF="00000230.tif" N="218"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="358"></L>
<L>For wel I wot &thorn;y paciens is goon</L>
<L>Oure hoste cride pees and &thorn;at anoon</L>
<L>And sayde let &thorn;e womman telle hir tale /</L>
<L N="852">&YOGH;e fare as folkes &thorn;at dronken ben of ale</L>
<L>Do dame tel forth &yogh;our tale and &thorn;at is best/</L>
<L>Al redy sir quod sche right as &yogh;ou lest/</L>
<L>If I haue licence of &thorn;is worthy frere</L>
<L N="856">&YOGH;is dame quod he tel for&thorn; and I schal heere<NOTE PLACE="end">[Break of two lines in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000231.tif" N="219">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="359">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN olde dayes of &thorn;e kyng arthour<MILESTONE N="97b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Narrat</NOTE></L>
<L>Of which &thorn;at britouns speken gret honour</L>
<L>Al was &thorn;is lond fulfilled of fayrie</L>
<L N="860">The elf queen wi&thorn; hir ioly compaignye</L>
<L>Daunced fuloft in many a grene mede</L>
<L>This was &thorn;e old oppynyoun as I rede</L>
<L>I speke of many hundrid &yogh;er ago</L>
<L N="864">But now can no man see noon elues mo</L>
<L>For now &thorn;e grete charite and prayeres</L>
<L>Of lymytours and o&thorn;er holy freres</L>
<L>That sechen euery lond and euery streem</L>
<L N="868">As thik as motis in &thorn;e sonne beem</L>
<L>Blessynge halles . chambres . kichenes . boures</L>
<L>Citees . burghes . castels . hihe and toures .</L>
<L>Thropes . bernes . schepnes . and dayeries</L>
<L N="872">That makith &thorn;at &thorn;er ben no fayeries</L>
<L>For &thorn;er as wont was to walken an elf</L>
<L>Ther walkith noon . but &thorn;e lymytour himself</L>
<L>In vndermeles and in morwenynges</L>
<L N="876">And saith his matyns and his holy &thorn;inges</L>
<L>As he go&thorn; in his lymytacioun</L>
<L>wommen may go saufly vp and doun</L>
<L>In euery bussch or vnder euery tre</L>
<L N="880">&THORN;er is non o&thorn;er incumbent but/ he /</L>
<L>And ne wol but doon hem dishonour</L>
<L>And so bifel it / &thorn;at &thorn;is king arthour</L>
<L>had in his hous a lusty bacheler</L>
<L N="884">That on a day com rydyng fro ryuer
<PB REF="00000232.tif" N="220"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="360"></L>
<L>And happed al alone as sche was born</L>
<L>he saugh a mayde walkyng him byforn</L>
<L>Of which mayden anoon maugre hir heed</L>
<L N="888">By verray fors byraft hir maydenhed</L>
<L>For such oppressioun was such clamour</L>
<L>And such pursuyte vnto kyng arthour</L>
<L>That dampned was &thorn;e knight and schuld be ded</L>
<L N="892">By cours of lawe and schuld haue lost his heed</L>
<L>Parauenture such was &thorn;e statut &thorn;o</L>
<L>But &thorn;at &thorn;e queen and o&thorn;er ladys mo</L>
<L>So longe preyeden &thorn;ay &thorn;e kyng of grace<MILESTONE N="98a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="896">Til he his lif ha&thorn; graunted in &thorn;e place</L>
<L>And &yogh;af him to &thorn;e queen al at hir wille</L>
<L>To chese wethir sche wolde him saue or spille</L>
<L>The queen thanked &thorn;e kyng wi&thorn; al hir might</L>
<L N="900">And after &thorn;us sche spak vnto &thorn;e knight</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at sche saugh hir tyme vpon a day</L>
<L>Thow stondest &yogh;et quod he in such array</L>
<L>&THORN;at of &thorn;y lyf hastow no sewerte</L>
<L N="904">I graunte &thorn;y lif if &thorn;ou canst telle me</L>
<L>what &thorn;ing is it &thorn;at wommen most desiren</L>
<L>Be war and keep &thorn;y nek bon fro &thorn;e Iren</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou canst not tellen it anoon</L>
<L N="908">&YOGH;et wol I &yogh;iue &thorn;e leue for to goon</L>
<L>A twelf month and a day it for to lere</L>
<L>An answar suffisaunt in &thorn;is matiere</L>
<L>And seurte wol I haue er &thorn;at &thorn;ou pace</L>
<L N="912">Thy body for to &yogh;elden in &thorn;is place</L>
<L>wo was &thorn;is knight and sorwfully he siked</L>
<L>But what. he may not doon al as him liked</L>
<L>And atte last he ches him for to wende</L>
<L N="916">And cam a&yogh;ein right at &thorn;e &yogh;eres ende</L>
<L>wi&thorn; swich answer as god him wolde purueye</L>
<L>And takith his leue and wendith for&thorn; his weye</L>
<L>He sekith euery hous and euery place</L>
<L N="920">wher-so he hopith for to fynde grace
<PB REF="00000233.tif" N="221"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="361"></L>
<L>To lerne what &thorn;ing wommen louen most</L>
<L>But he ne cou&thorn;e arryuen in no cost</L>
<L>wher as he mighte fynde &thorn;is matiere</L>
<L N="924">To &thorn;ese &thorn;inges accordyng in fere</L>
<L>Somme sayden womme louen best richesse</L>
<L>Somme sayde honour and some sayde iolynesse</L>
<L>Somme sayde riche array some sayden lust on bedde</L>
<L N="928">And ofte tyme to be wydow and wedde</L>
<L>Somme sayden oure herte is most I-eased</L>
<L>whan we ben y-flaterid and y-pleased</L>
<L>He go&thorn; ful neigh &thorn;e soth I wil not lye</L>
<L N="932">A man schal wynne vs best wi&thorn; flaterye</L>
<L>And with attendaunce and busynesse<MILESTONE N="98b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ben we y-limed bo&thorn;e more and lesse /</L>
<L>And somme sayen &thorn;at we louen best</L>
<L N="936">For to be fre and to doon as vs lest</L>
<L>And &thorn;at no man repreue vs of oure vice</L>
<L>But say &thorn;at we ben wys and no &thorn;ing nyce</L>
<L>For trewely &thorn;er is noon of vs alle</L>
<L N="940">If eny wight wold claw vs on &thorn;e galle /</L>
<L>That we nyl like for he saith vs so&thorn;</L>
<L>Assay and he schal fynd it &thorn;at so do&thorn;</L>
<L>For be we neuer so vicious wi&thorn;inne</L>
<L N="944">we schuln be holde wys and clene of synne</L>
<L>And somme sayn &thorn;at gret delit han we</L>
<L>For to be holden stabil and secre /</L>
<L>And in oon purpos stedfastly to duelle /</L>
<L N="948">And nought bywreye &thorn;ing &thorn;at men vs telle /</L>
<L>But &thorn;at tale is not . worth a rakes stele</L>
<L>Par dy we wymmen . can right no &thorn;ing hele</L>
<L>witnes on myda wil &yogh;e here &thorn;e tale /</L>
<L N="952">Ouyd among his o&thorn;er &thorn;inges smale</L>
<L>Sayde Myda had . vnder his lange heris</L>
<L>Growyng vpon his heed tuo asses eeris</L>
<L>The whiche vice he hid as he best might</L>
<L N="956">Ful subtilly fro euery mannes sight
<PB REF="00000234.tif" N="222"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="362"></L>
<L>That saue his wyf &thorn;er wist of &thorn;at no mo</L>
<L>he loued hir most . and trusted hir also /</L>
<L>he prayed hir . &thorn;at to no creature</L>
<L N="960">sche schulde tellen . of his disfigure /</L>
<L>Sche swor him nay for al &thorn;is world to wynne</L>
<L>Sche nolde do &thorn;at vilony or synne</L>
<L>To make hir housbond haue so foul a name</L>
<L N="964">Sche wold not tel it for hir oughne schame</L>
<L>But natheles hir &thorn;oughte &thorn;at sche dyde</L>
<L>That sche so long a counseil scholde hyde</L>
<L>hir &thorn;ought it swal . so sore about / hir hert</L>
<L N="968">That needely som word hir most astert</L>
<L>And sins sche dorst not tel it vn-to man</L>
<L>Doun to a marreys faste by sche ran</L>
<L>Til sche cam &thorn;er hir herte was on fuyre<MILESTONE N="99a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="972">And as a bytoure bumblith in &thorn;e myre</L>
<L>Sche layd hir mouth vnto &thorn;e water doun</L>
<L>Bywrey me not &thorn;ou watir with &thorn;i soun</L>
<L>Quod sche to &thorn;e I telle it and no mo</L>
<L N="976">Myn housbond ha&thorn; long asse eeris tuo</L>
<L>Now is myn hert al hool now is it oute</L>
<L>I might no lenger kepe it out of doute</L>
<L>Her may &yogh;e se &thorn;eigh we a tyme abyde</L>
<L N="980">&YOGH;et out it moot we can no counseil hyde</L>
<L>The remenaunt of &thorn;e tale if &yogh;e wil here /</L>
<L>Redith ovid . and &thorn;er &yogh;e mow it leere</L>
<L>&para; This knight of which my tale is specially</L>
<L N="984">whan &thorn;at he saugh he might nou&yogh;t come &thorn;erby</L>
<L>This is to say what wommen louen most</L>
<L>wi&thorn;inne his brest ful sorwful was &thorn;e gost/</L>
<L>But hom he go&thorn; . he might no lenger soiourne</L>
<L N="988">The day was come &thorn;at homward most he torne</L>
<L>And in his way it hapnyd him to ride</L>
<L>In al his care vnder a forest side</L>
<L>wher as he saugh vpon a daunce go</L>
<L N="992">Of ladys four and twenty and &yogh;it mo
<PB REF="00000235.tif" N="223"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="363"></L>
<L>Toward &thorn;is ilke daunce I drough ful &yogh;erne /</L>
<L>In hope &thorn;at som wisdom schuld I lerne /</L>
<L>But certeynly er I com fully &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="996">Vanysshid was &thorn;is daunce he nyste where /</L>
<L>No creature saugh he &thorn;at bar lif</L>
<L>Sauf on &thorn;e greene he saugh sittyng a wyf /</L>
<L>A fouler wight &thorn;er may no man deuyse</L>
<L N="1000">A&yogh;ens &thorn;e knight &thorn;is olde wyf gan ryse</L>
<L>And sayder sir knight heer forth lith no way</L>
<L>Tel me what . &yogh;e seekyn by &yogh;our fay</L>
<L>Par aduenture . it may &thorn;e better be /</L>
<L N="1004">Thise olde folk can mochil &thorn;ing quod sche</L>
<L>My lieue modir quod &thorn;is knight certayn</L>
<L>I am but ded but if &thorn;at I can sayn</L>
<L>what &thorn;ing is it . &thorn;at wommen most desire</L>
<L N="1008">Cou&thorn;e &yogh;e me wisse . I wold wel quyt &yogh;our huyre /</L>
<L>Plight me &thorn;y trouth . her in myn hond quod sche<MILESTONE N="99b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>The nexte &thorn;ing &thorn;at I require &thorn;e</L>
<L>Thou schalt it doo if it be in &thorn;y might</L>
<L N="1012">And I wol telle it &thorn;e er it be night</L>
<L>haue her my trou&thorn;e quod &thorn;e knight I graunte</L>
<L>Thanne quod sche I dar me wel auaunte</L>
<L>&THORN;y lif is sauf for I wol stonde &thorn;er by</L>
<L N="1016">vpon my lif &thorn;e queen wol say as I</L>
<L>let se which is &thorn;e proudest of hem alle</L>
<L>&THORN;at werith on a couerchief or a calle</L>
<L>&THORN;at dar say nay of &thorn;ing I schal &thorn;e teche</L>
<L N="1020">let vs go forth wi&thorn;outen more speche</L>
<L>Tho rowned sche a pistil in his eere</L>
<L>And bad him to be glad and haue no fere</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ay ben comen to &thorn;e court &thorn;is knight</L>
<L N="1024">Sayd he had holde . &thorn;at day &thorn;at he hight</L>
<L>Al redy was his answer as he sayde</L>
<L>Ful many a noble wyf and many a mayde</L>
<L>And many a wydow for &thorn;at &thorn;ay ben wyse</L>
<L N="1028">The queen hirself sittyng as a Iustise
<PB REF="00000236.tif" N="224"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="364"></L>
<L>Assemblid ben his answer for to hiere</L>
<L>And afterward &thorn;is knight was bode appiere</L>
<L>To euery wight comaundid was cilence</L>
<L N="1032">And &thorn;at &thorn;e knight schuld telle in audience</L>
<L>what &thorn;ing &thorn;at worldly wommen louen best</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e knight ne stood not stille as do&thorn; a best</L>
<L>But to &thorn;e questioun anoon answerde</L>
<L N="1036">wi&thorn; manly voys &thorn;at al the court it herde</L>
<L>My liege lady generally quod he</L>
<L>wommen desiren to haue soueraynte</L>
<L>As wel ouer hir housbond as ouer hir loue</L>
<L N="1040">And for to be in maystry him aboue</L>
<L>This is &thorn;e most desir &thorn;ough &yogh;e me kille /</L>
<L>Do&thorn; as &yogh;ow list I am heer at &yogh;our wille</L>
<L>In al &thorn;e court ne was &thorn;er wyf ne mayde</L>
<L N="1044">Ne wydow &thorn;at contraried &thorn;at he sayde</L>
<L>But sayden he . was wor&thorn;y haue his lif</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word vp start &thorn;at olde wif</L>
<L>which &thorn;at &thorn;e knight saugh sittyng on &thorn;e grene<MILESTONE N="100a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1048">Mercy quod sche my soueraigne lady queene</L>
<L>Er &thorn;at &yogh;our court departe do&thorn; me right</L>
<L>I taughte &thorn;is answer vnto &thorn;e knight</L>
<L>For which he plighte me his trou&thorn;e there</L>
<L N="1052">The firste &thorn;ing &thorn;at I wold him requere</L>
<L>he wold it do if it lay in his might</L>
<L>Bifore &thorn;e court &thorn;en pray I &thorn;e sir knight</L>
<L>Quod sche &thorn;at &thorn;ou me take vnto &thorn;y wif</L>
<L N="1056">For wel &thorn;ou wost &thorn;at I haue kept &thorn;y lif</L>
<L>If I say fals sey nay vpon &thorn;y fey</L>
<L>This knight answerd allas and waylawey</L>
<L>I wot right wel &thorn;at such was my byhest</L>
<L N="1060">For goddes loue as chese a ne request</L>
<L>Tak al my good and let my body go</L>
<L>Nay quod sche &thorn;an I schrew vs bo&thorn;e tuo</L>
<L>For &thorn;ough &thorn;at I be foule old and poure</L>
<L N="1064">I nolde for al &thorn;e metal ne for &thorn;e oure
<PB REF="00000237.tif" N="225"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="365"></L>
<L>That vnder erthe is graue or lith aboue</L>
<L>But I &thorn;y wife . were and eek &thorn;y loue</L>
<L>My loue quod he . nay nay . my dampnacioun</L>
<L N="1068">Allas &thorn;at eny of my nacioun</L>
<L>Schuld euer so foule disparagid be</L>
<L>But/ al for nought . &thorn;e ende is &thorn;is &thorn;at he</L>
<L>Constreigned was . he needes most hir wedde</L>
<L N="1072">And takith his wyf and go&thorn; wi&thorn; hir to bedde</L>
<L>&para; Now wolden som men say par aduenture</L>
<L>That for my necgligence I do no cure</L>
<L>To telle &yogh;ow &thorn;e ioye and tharray</L>
<L N="1076">That at &thorn;at fest was maad &thorn;at ilke day</L>
<L>To which &thorn;ing schortly answeren I schal</L>
<L>And say &thorn;er nas feste ne ioy at al</L>
<L>Ther nas but heuynes and mochil sorwe</L>
<L N="1080">For priuely he weddyd hir in a morwe</L>
<L>And alday hudde him . as do&thorn; an oule</L>
<L>So wo was him his wyf loked so foule</L>
<L>Gret was &thorn;e wo . &thorn;e knight had in his &thorn;ought</L>
<L N="1084">whan he was with his wyf on bedde brought</L>
<L>He walwith and he torneth to and fro<MILESTONE N="100b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>his olde wyf lay smylyng euer mo</L>
<L>And sayd o deere housbond benedicite<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. bndicite]</NOTE></L>
<L N="1088">Fareth euery knight wi&thorn; his wyf as &yogh;e /</L>
<L>Is &thorn;is &thorn;e lawe of king arthures hous</L>
<L>Is euery knight of his &thorn;us daungerous</L>
<L>I am &yogh;our oughne loue / and &yogh;our wyf</L>
<L N="1092">I am sche &thorn;at hath sauyd &yogh;our lyf</L>
<L>And certes ne dede I &yogh;ow neuer vnright</L>
<L>why fare &yogh;e &thorn;us with me &thorn;e firste night</L>
<L>&yogh;e fare lik a man &thorn;at had left his wit/</L>
<L N="1096">what is my gult . for godes loue tel me it</L>
<L>And it schal be amendid if &thorn;at I may</L>
<L>Amendid quod &thorn;is knight allas nay nay</L>
<L>It wol nought ben amendid neuer mo</L>
<L N="1100">Thow art so lo&thorn;ly and so old also
<PB REF="00000238.tif" N="226"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="366"></L>
<L>And &thorn;erto comen of so lowh a kynde</L>
<L>That litil wonder is &thorn;ough I walwe and wynde</L>
<L>So wolde god myn herte wolde brest</L>
<L N="1104">Is &thorn;is quod sche &thorn;e cause of &yogh;our vnrest;</L>
<L>&YOGH;e certeynly quod he no wonder is</L>
<L>Now sire quod sche I cou&thorn;e amende al &thorn;is</L>
<L>If &thorn;at me list er it were dayes &thorn;re /</L>
<L N="1108">So wel &yogh;e mighte bere &yogh;ow to me</L>
<L>But for &yogh;e speken of such gentilesse</L>
<L>As is descendit out of old richesse</L>
<L>Therfor schuld &yogh;e . ben holden gentil men</L>
<L N="1112">Such arrogaunce . is not worth an hen</L>
<L>lok who &thorn;at is most vertuous alway</L>
<L>Priue and pert and most entendi&thorn; ay</L>
<L>To do &thorn;e gentil dedes &thorn;at he can</L>
<L N="1116">Tak him for &thorn;e grettest gentil man</L>
<L>Crist wol we clayme of him oure gentilesse</L>
<L>Nought of oure eldres for our gret richesse</L>
<L>For &thorn;ough &thorn;ey &yogh;iue vs al her heritage</L>
<L N="1120">For which we clayme to be of high parage</L>
<L>&YOGH;it may &thorn;ay not bique&thorn;e for no &thorn;ing</L>
<L>To noon of vs so vertuous lyuyng</L>
<L>That made hem gentil men y-callid be<MILESTONE N="101a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1124">And bad vs folwe hem in such degre</L>
<L>wel can &thorn;e wyse poet of Florence</L>
<L>That hatte Daunt speke of &thorn;is sentence /</L>
<L>Lo in such maner of rym is Dauntes tale</L>
<L N="1128">Ful seeld vprisith by his braunchis smale /</L>
<L>Prowes of man . for god of his prowesse</L>
<L>wol &thorn;at we clayme of him our gentilesse</L>
<L>For of our auncestres . we no &thorn;ing clayme</L>
<L N="1132">But temporal &thorn;ing &thorn;at men may hurt and mayme</L>
<L>Ek euery wight wot &thorn;is as wel as I</L>
<L>If gentiles were plaunted naturelly</L>
<L>Vnto a certayn lignage doun &thorn;e line</L>
<L N="1136">Priue ne apert/. &thorn;ay wolde neuer fine
<PB REF="00000239.tif" N="227"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="367"></L>
<L>To don of gentilesce &thorn;e fair office</L>
<L>Thay might nought doon no vileny or vice</L>
<L>Tak fuyr and ber it in &thorn;e derkest hous</L>
<L N="1140">Bitwixe &thorn;is . and &thorn;e mount Cankasous</L>
<L>And let men schit . &thorn;e dores and go &thorn;enne</L>
<L>&YOGH;it wol &thorn;e fuyr as fair and lighte brenne</L>
<L>As twenty &thorn;ousand men might it biholde</L>
<L N="1144">his office naturel ay wol it holde</L>
<L>vp peril on my lif til &thorn;at it dye</L>
<L>her / may &yogh;e se wel how &thorn;at genterye</L>
<L>Is nought annexid to possessioun</L>
<L N="1148">Sithins folk ne doon her operacioun</L>
<L>Alway as doth &thorn;e fuyr lo in his kynde</L>
<L>For god it wot men may ful often fynde</L>
<L>A lordes sone do schame and vilonye</L>
<L N="1152">And he &thorn;at wol haue pris of his gentrie</L>
<L>For he was boren of a gentil hous</L>
<L>And had his eldres noble and vertuous</L>
<L>And nyl himselue . doo no gentil dedis</L>
<L N="1156">Ne folw his gentil aunceter &thorn;at deed is</L>
<L>he is nought gentil be he duk or erl .</L>
<L>For vileyn synful deedes make&thorn; a cherl .</L>
<L>For gentilnesse nys but renome</L>
<L N="1160">Of &thorn;in auncestres for her heigh bounte</L>
<L>which is a straunge &thorn;ing to &thorn;y persone<MILESTONE N="101b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Thy gentilesce come&thorn; fro god alloone</L>
<L>Than com&thorn; oure verray gentilesse of grace</L>
<L N="1164">It was no &thorn;ing biquethe vs wi&thorn; oure place</L>
<L>Thinke&thorn; how nobil as saith valerius</L>
<L>was &thorn;ilke tullius hostilius</L>
<L>That out of pouert / ros to high noblesse</L>
<L N="1168">Redith Senek/. and redith eek/ Boece .</L>
<L>Ther schuln &yogh;e se expresse &thorn;at no dred is</L>
<L>&THORN;at he is gentil &thorn;at do&thorn; gentil dedis</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfor lieue housbond I conclude</L>
<L N="1172">Al were it that myn auncetres wer rude
<PB REF="00000240.tif" N="228"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="368"></L>
<L>&YOGH;it may &thorn;e highe god and so hope I</L>
<L>Graunte me grace to lyue vertuously</L>
<L>Than am I gentil whan &thorn;at I bygynne</L>
<L N="1176">To lyue vertuously and weyuen synne</L>
<L>And &thorn;er as &yogh;e of povert me repreue</L>
<L>The heighe god on whom &thorn;at we bilieue</L>
<L>In wilful pouert ches to lese his lif</L>
<L N="1180">And certes euery man . mayden or wif</L>
<L>May vnderstonde &thorn;at Ihc heuen king</L>
<L>Ne wold not chese . a vicious lyuyng</L>
<L>Glad pouert is an honest &thorn;ing certayn</L>
<L N="1184">This wol Senek and o&thorn;er clerkes sayn</L>
<L>who &thorn;at holt him payd of his pouert</L>
<L>I hold him riche . al had he nou&yogh;t a schert</L>
<L>he &thorn;at coueitith is a pore wight</L>
<L N="1188">For he wold haue &thorn;at is not in his might</L>
<L>But he &thorn;at nou&yogh;t ha&thorn; . ne coueyteth nou&yogh;t/ to haue</L>
<L>Is riche al &thorn;ough &yogh;e hold him but a knaue</L>
<L>Verray pouert is synne proprely</L>
<L N="1192">Iuuenal saith of pouert merily</L>
<L>&para; The pore man whan he go&thorn; by &thorn;e way</L>
<L>Bifore &thorn;e theues he may synge and play</L>
<L>Pouert is hateful and as I gesse /</L>
<L N="1196">A ful gret brynger out of busynesse /</L>
<L>A gret amender eek of Sapiens</L>
<L>To him &thorn;at takith it in paciens</L>
<L>Pouert is &thorn;is al &thorn;ough it seme elenge<MILESTONE N="102a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1200">Possessioun &thorn;at no wight wil chalenge</L>
<L>&there4; Pouert ful often whan a man is lowe</L>
<L>Makith him his god and eek himself/ to knowe</L>
<L>&there4; Pouert a spectacle is as &thorn;inkith me</L>
<L N="1204">&THORN;urgh which he may his verray frendes se</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfor sir syth &thorn;at I &yogh;ow nought greue</L>
<L>Of my pouert no more &yogh;e me repreue</L>
<L>// Now sir of elde &yogh;e repreue me</L>
<L N="1208">And certes sir &thorn;ough noon auctorite
<PB REF="00000241.tif" N="229"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="369"></L>
<L>were in no book &yogh;e gentils of honour</L>
<L>Sayn &thorn;at men schuld an old wight doon fauour</L>
<L>And clepe him fader for &yogh;our gentilesse</L>
<L N="1212">And certes I schal fynden as I gesse</L>
<L>Than drede &yogh;ou nought to ben a cokewold</L>
<L>Now &thorn;er &thorn;at &yogh;e sayn I am foul and old</L>
<L>For filthe and elde also mot I the</L>
<L N="1216">Ben grete wardeyns vpon chastite /</L>
<L>But natheles sith I knowe &yogh;our delyt</L>
<L>I schal fulfille &yogh;oure worldly appetyt</L>
<L>Chese now quod sche oon of &thorn;ese &thorn;inges tweye</L>
<L N="1220">To haue me foul and old til &thorn;at I deye</L>
<L>And be to &yogh;ow a trewe humble wyf</L>
<L>And neuer &yogh;ow displease in al my lyf</L>
<L>Or elles &yogh;e wol haue me &yogh;ong and fair</L>
<L N="1224">And take &yogh;our auenture of &thorn;e repair</L>
<L>&THORN;at schal be to &yogh;our hous by cause of me</L>
<L>Or in som o&thorn;er place may wel be</L>
<L>Now chese &yogh;our seluen whethir &thorn;at &yogh;ow likith</L>
<L N="1228">This knight auysith him and sore sikith</L>
<L>But atte last he sayd in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>My lady and my loue . and my wif so deere</L>
<L>I putte me in &yogh;our wyse gouernaunce</L>
<L N="1232">Chesith &yogh;our self which may be most pleasaunce</L>
<L>And most honour to &yogh;ow and me also</L>
<L>I do no fors &thorn;e whe&thorn;er of &thorn;e tuo</L>
<L>For as &yogh;ow likith it suffisith me</L>
<L N="1236">Than haue I gete of &yogh;ow &thorn;e maystry quod sche /</L>
<L>Sith I may gouern and chese as me list/<MILESTONE N="102b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;e certis wyf quod he I hold it best</L>
<L>kys me quod sche we ben no lenger wro&thorn;e</L>
<L N="1240">For by my trou&thorn;e . I wol be to &yogh;ow bo&thorn;e</L>
<L>This is to say &yogh;e bo&thorn;e fair and good</L>
<L>I pray to god &thorn;at I mot sterue wood</L>
<L>But/ I be to &yogh;ow also good and trewe</L>
<L N="1244">As euer was wyf si&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;e world was newe
<PB REF="00000242.tif" N="230"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="370"></L>
<L>And but/ I be to morow as fair to seen</L>
<L>As eny lady emperesse or queen</L>
<L>That is bitwixe thest and eek &thorn;e west</L>
<L N="1248">Doth by my lyf . right euen as &yogh;ow lest</L>
<L>Cast vp &thorn;e cortyns and look what &thorn;is is</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;e knyght saugh verrayly al &thorn;is</L>
<L>That sche so fair was and so &yogh;ong &thorn;er to</L>
<L N="1252">For ioye he hent hir in hir armes tuo</L>
<L>his herte bathid in a bath of blisse</L>
<L>A thousand tyme on rowe he gan hir kisse</L>
<L>And sche obeyed him in euery &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="1256">That mighte doon him pleisauns or likyng</L>
<L>And &thorn;us &thorn;ay lyue vnto her lyues end</L>
<L>In parfyt ioye and ih&umacr; crist vs sende</L>
<L>housbondes meke &yogh;onge and freissche on bedde</L>
<L N="1260">And grace to ouerbyde hem &thorn;at we wedde</L>
<L>And eek I pray to Ih&umacr; schort her lyues</L>
<L>That wil nought be gouerned after her wyues</L>
<L>And old and angry nygardes of despense</L>
<L N="1264">God send hem sone verray pestilence /</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Here endith &thorn;e wif of Bathe hire tale<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000243.tif" N="231">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="371">
<HEAD>&para; Here bygynneth &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e Freres tale</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THis worthy lymytour &thorn;is noble Frere</L>
<L>he made alway a lourynge cheere</L>
<L>vpon the sompnour . but for honeste /</L>
<L N="1268">No vileyns worde . &yogh;it to him spak he</L>
<L>But atte last he sayd vnto &thorn;e wyf</L>
<L>Dame quod he . god &yogh;iue &yogh;ow good lyf</L>
<L>&YOGH;e han her touchid al so mot I the</L>
<L N="1272">In scole matier gret difficulte</L>
<L>&YOGH;e han sayd mochel &thorn;ing right wel I say<MILESTONE N="103a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But dame right as we ryden by &thorn;e way</L>
<L>Vs neede&thorn; nou&yogh;t but for to speke of game &middot;</L>
<L N="1276">And lete auctorites in goddes name</L>
<L>To preching and to scoles of clergie /</L>
<L>But if it like to &thorn;is companye /</L>
<L>I wil &yogh;ow of a sompnour telle a game</L>
<L N="1280">Par de &yogh;e may wel knowe by &thorn;e name</L>
<L>That of a sompnour may no good be sayd</L>
<L>I pray &yogh;ow &thorn;at noon of &yogh;ow be euel a-payd</L>
<L>A Sompnour is a renner vp and doun</L>
<L N="1284">wi&thorn; maundement&yogh; for fornicacioun</L>
<L>And is y-bete at euery tounes eende /</L>
<L>Our oste spak / a sir &yogh;e schold been heende /</L>
<L>And curteys as a man of &yogh;our estaat</L>
<L N="1288">In company we wol haue no debaat</L>
<L>Telle&thorn; &yogh;our tale and let &thorn;e sompnour be</L>
<L>Nay quo&thorn; &thorn;e sompnour let him say to me</L>
<L>what so him list whan it come&thorn; to my lot</L>
<L N="1292">By god I schal him quyten euery grot</L>
<L>I schal him telle which a gret honour</L>
<L>Is to ben a fals flateryng lymytour<NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>Lines</I> 1307-8 <I>follow wrongly here in the Six Texts.</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>And his offis I schal him telle I-wis</L>
<L N="1296">Our host answerd and sayd &thorn;e sompnour &thorn;is</L>
<L>And after &thorn;is he sayd vnto &thorn;e Frere</L>
<L>Telle&thorn; for&thorn; &yogh;our tale my maister deere<NOTE PLACE="end">[No gap in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000244.tif" N="232">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="372">
<P>&para; Narrat.</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whilom &thorn;er was duellyng in my countre</L>
<L N="1300">An erchedeken a man of gret degre</L>
<L>That boldely did execucioun</L>
<L>In punyschyng of fornicacioun</L>
<L>Of wicchecraft and eek of Bauderye</L>
<L N="1304">Of diffamacioun and auoutrie /</L>
<L>Of chirchereues and of testamentes</L>
<L>Of contractes and of lak of sacraments</L>
<L>And eek of many ano&thorn;er cryme<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>These</I> 2 <I>lines are misplaced, as</I> 1295-6, <I>in the Six Texts</I>.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="1308">which nedi&thorn; not to reherse at &thorn;is tyme</L>
<L>Of vsur and of Symony also</L>
<L>But certes lecchours did he grettest woo .</L>
<L>Thay schulde synge if &thorn;ay were hent<MILESTONE N="103b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1312">And smale ty&thorn;ers &thorn;ay were fouly schent</L>
<L>If eny persoun wold vpon hem pleyne</L>
<L>Ther might astert/ him no pecunial peyne</L>
<L>For smale ty&thorn;es and for smal offrynge</L>
<L N="1316">he made &thorn;e poeple pitously to synge</L>
<L>For er &thorn;e bisschop caught him in his hook</L>
<L>&THORN;ay weren in &thorn;e archedeknes book</L>
<L>And hadde &thorn;urgh his iurediccioun</L>
<L N="1320">Power to haue of hem correccioun</L>
<L>he had a sompnour redy to his hond</L>
<L>A slyer boy was noon in Engelond</L>
<L>Ful priuely he had his espiaile</L>
<L N="1324">That taughte him wher he might auayle</L>
<L>he cou&thorn;e spare of lecchours oon or tuo</L>
<L>And techen him to four and twenty mo</L>
<L>For &thorn;ough &thorn;is sompnour wood were as an hare</L>
<L N="1328">To telle his harlottry I wol not spare
<PB REF="00000245.tif" N="233"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="373"></L>
<L>For we ben out of here correccioun</L>
<L>Thay haue of vs no iurediccioun</L>
<L>Ne neuer schul to terme of alle her lyues</L>
<L N="1332">Peter so been &thorn;e wommen of &thorn;e styues</L>
<L>Thay be&thorn; I-put out of oure cures</L>
<L>Pees with meschaunce and wi&thorn; mesauentures</L>
<L>&THORN;us sayd our host and let him telle his tale /</L>
<L N="1336">Now telle&thorn; for&thorn; al &thorn;ough &thorn;e sompnour gale</L>
<L>Ne spare&thorn; nought myn owne maister deere</L>
<L>&THORN;is false &thorn;eef &thorn;e sompnour quo&thorn; &thorn;e frere ./</L>
<L>Had alway bawdes redy to his hond</L>
<L N="1340">As eny hauk to lure in engelond</L>
<L>&THORN;at told him al &thorn;e secre &thorn;at &thorn;ay knewe</L>
<L>For here acqueintaunce was not come of newe</L>
<L>&THORN;ay were his approwours priuely</L>
<L N="1344">He took himself a gret profyt &thorn;er by</L>
<L>His maister knew nat alway what he wan</L>
<L>wi&thorn;oute maundement/ a lewed man</L>
<L>He cou&thorn;e sompne vp peyne of cristes curs</L>
<L N="1348">And &thorn;ay were glad to fille wel his purs ./</L>
<L>And make him grete festis atte nale /<MILESTONE N="104a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And right as Iudas hadde purses smale /</L>
<L>And was a theef. right such a &thorn;eef was he</L>
<L N="1352">his maister had not half his duete</L>
<L>he was if I schal &yogh;iue him his laude .</L>
<L>A &thorn;eef a sompnour and eek a baude .</L>
<L>And he had wenches at his retenue</L>
<L N="1356">That whe&thorn;ir &thorn;at sir Robert or sir hughe</L>
<L>Or Iak or Rauf or who-so &thorn;at it were</L>
<L>That lay by hem &thorn;ay told it in his eere</L>
<L>Thus was &thorn;e wenche and he of oon assent</L>
<L N="1360">And he wold fecche a feyned maundement</L>
<L>And sompne hem to chapitre bo&thorn;e tuo</L>
<L>And pyle &thorn;e man and let &thorn;e wenche go</L>
<L>Than wold he sayn I schal frend for &thorn;y sake</L>
<L N="1364">Don strike &thorn;e out of oure lettres blake
<PB REF="00000246.tif" N="234"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="374"></L>
<L>The &thorn;ar no more as in &thorn;is cas trauayle</L>
<L>I am &thorn;y frend &thorn;er I &thorn;e may avayle</L>
<L>Certeynly he knew of bribours mo</L>
<L N="1368">Than possible is to telle in &yogh;eres tuo</L>
<L>For in &thorn;is world nys dogge for &thorn;e bowe</L>
<L>&THORN;at can an hurt deer from an hol y-knowe</L>
<L>Bet &thorn;an &thorn;is sompnour knew a leccheour</L>
<L N="1372">Or auoutier or ellis a paramour</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at was &thorn;e fruyt of al his rent</L>
<L>Therfore &thorn;er on he set al his entent</L>
<L>And so bifel &thorn;at oones on a day</L>
<L N="1376">This sompnour euer wayting on his pray</L>
<L>Rod forth to sompne a widew and old ribibe</L>
<L>Feynyng a cause for he wolde bribe</L>
<L>And happed &thorn;at he say bifore him ryde</L>
<L N="1380">A gay &yogh;eman vnder a forest syde</L>
<L>A bow he bar and arwes bright and kene</L>
<L>He had vpon a courtepy of grene</L>
<L>An hat vpon his heed wi&thorn; frenges blake</L>
<L N="1384">Sir quod &thorn;is sompnour heyl and wel ouertake</L>
<L>welcome quod he and euery good felawe</L>
<L>whider ridestow vnder &thorn;is grene schawe</L>
<L>Sayde &thorn;is &yogh;iman wiltow fer to day<MILESTONE N="104b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1388">This sompnour answerd and sayde nay</L>
<L>Her faste by quod he is myn entent</L>
<L>To ryden for to reysen vp a rent</L>
<L>That longith to my lordes duete</L>
<L N="1392">Artow &thorn;an a bayely quod he /</L>
<L>He durste not for verray filth and schame</L>
<L>Sayn &thorn;at he was a sompnour for &thorn;e name</L>
<L>De par dieux quod &thorn;e &yogh;eman lieue bro&thorn;er</L>
<L N="1396">Thou art a bayly . and I am another</L>
<L>I am vnknowen as in &thorn;is contre</L>
<L>Of &thorn;in acqueintance I wol praye &thorn;e</L>
<L>And eek of bro&thorn;erheed it &yogh;ow lest</L>
<L N="1400">I haue gold and siluer in my chest
<PB REF="00000247.tif" N="235"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="375"></L>
<L>If that &thorn;e happe come in to oure schire</L>
<L>Al schal be &thorn;in right as &thorn;ou wolt desire</L>
<L>Graunt mercy quod &thorn;is sompnour by my faith /</L>
<L N="1404">Euerich in otheres hond his trouthe laith</L>
<L>For to be sworne bre&thorn;eren til &thorn;ay deyen</L>
<L>In daliaunce for&thorn; &thorn;ay ride and pleyen</L>
<L>This Sompnour which &thorn;at was as ful of iangles</L>
<L N="1408">As ful of venym ben &thorn;ese wery-angles</L>
<L>And euer enquering vpon euery &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;er quod he wher now is &yogh;our dwellyng</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er day if &thorn;at I schuld &yogh;ow seeche</L>
<L N="1412">This &yogh;iman him answerd in softe speche</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;er quod he fer in &thorn;e nor&thorn; contre</L>
<L>wher as I hope somtyme I schal &thorn;e se</L>
<L>Er we depart I schal &thorn;e so wel wisse</L>
<L N="1416">That of myn hous ne schaltow neuer misse</L>
<L>Now bro&thorn;er quod &thorn;is sompnour I &yogh;ow pray</L>
<L>Teche me whil &thorn;at we ryden by &thorn;e way</L>
<L>Syn &thorn;at &yogh;e ben a baily as am I</L>
<L N="1420">Som subtilte as tel me faithfully</L>
<L>In myn office . how &thorn;at I may wynne.</L>
<L>And spare not for consciens or for synne /</L>
<L>But as my bro&thorn;er tel me how do &yogh;e</L>
<L N="1424">Now by my trouthe brothir myn sayd he /</L>
<L>As I schal telle &thorn;e a faithful tale<MILESTONE N="105a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>My wages ben ful streyt and eek ful smale</L>
<L>My lord to me is streyt and daungerous</L>
<L N="1428">And myn office is ful laborous</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfor by extorciouns I lyue</L>
<L>For so&thorn; I take al &thorn;at men wil me &yogh;iue</L>
<L>Algate by sleighte or by violence</L>
<L N="1432">Fro &yogh;er to &yogh;er I wynne my despence</L>
<L>I can no better telle faithfully</L>
<L>Now certes quod &thorn;is sompnour so fare I</L>
<L>I spare not to take god it woot</L>
<L N="1436">But if it be to heuy or to hoot
<PB REF="00000248.tif" N="236"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="376"></L>
<L>what I may gete . in counseil priuely</L>
<L>No more consciens of &thorn;at haue I</L>
<L>Nere myn extorcions I might not lyuen</L>
<L N="1440">Ne of such iapes I wil not be schriuen</L>
<L>Stomak ne conscience . know I noon</L>
<L>I schrew &thorn;es schriftefadres euerychoon</L>
<L>wel be we met by god and by seint Iame</L>
<L N="1444">But leue bro&thorn;er telle me &thorn;y name</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;is sompnour in &thorn;is mene while</L>
<L>This &yogh;eman gan a litel for to smyle</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;ir quod he woltow &thorn;at I &thorn;e telle</L>
<L N="1448">I am a feend my dwellyng is in helle</L>
<L>And her I ryde about my purchasyng</L>
<L>To wite wher men wol &yogh;iue me eny &thorn;ing</L>
<L>My purchas is &thorn;effect of al my rent</L>
