<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000257.tif" N="245">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="385">
<P>&para; Narrat</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LOrdyngs &thorn;er is . in Engelond I gesse</L>
<L>A mersschly lond called holdernesse</L>
<L>In which &thorn;er went a lymytour aboute</L>
<L N="1712">To preche and eek to begge it is no doubte</L>
<L>And so bifel it . on a day &thorn;is frere</L>
<L>had preched at a chirch in his manere</L>
<L>And specially abouen euery &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="1716">Excited he &thorn;e poepul in his preching</L>
<L>To trentals and to &yogh;iue for goddis sake</L>
<L>wher that men mighten holy soules make</L>
<L>Ther as diuine seruys is honoured</L>
<L N="1720">Nought &thorn;er as it is wasted and deuoured</L>
<L>Neither it neede&thorn; not for to be &yogh;iue</L>
<L>As to possessioneres &thorn;at mow lyue</L>
<L>Thanked be god in wele and abundaunce</L>
<L N="1724">Trentals sayd he delyuereth fro penaunce</L>
<L>her frendes soules as wel eld as &yogh;onge</L>
<L>&YOGH;e whanne &thorn;at &thorn;ay hastily ben songe</L>
<L>Nought for to hold a prest iolif and gay<MILESTONE N="109a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1728">he syngith not but oon masse in a day</L>
<L>Delyuerith out quod he &thorn;e soules</L>
<L>Ful hard it is wi&thorn; fleischhok or with oules</L>
<L>To ben y-clawed . or brend or I-bake</L>
<L N="1732">Now speed &yogh;ow hastily for cristes sake</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is frere had sayd al his entent</L>
<L>with Qui cum patre . for&thorn; he went</L>
<L>whan folk in chirch had &yogh;iue him what hem lest</L>
<L N="1736">he went his way no lenger wold he rest
<PB REF="00000258.tif" N="246"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="386"></L>
<L>with scrip and pyked staf y-touked hye</L>
<L>In euery hous and gan to pore and prye</L>
<L>And beggyd mele or chese or ellis corn</L>
<L N="1740">his felaw had a staf typped with horn</L>
<L>A payr of tablis al of yuory</L>
<L>And a poyntel y-polischt fetisly</L>
<L>And wroot &thorn;e names alway as he stood</L>
<L N="1744">Of alle folk that &yogh;af him eny good</L>
<L>Ascaunce &thorn;at he wolde for hem preye</L>
<L>&YOGH;if vs a busshel . whet or malt or reye</L>
