<HEAD>GROUP <B>E.</B> FRAGMENT VI.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; 1. THE CLERK'S HEAD-LINK.</HEAD>
<HEAD><B>HARLEIAN MS. 7334</B> (British Museum).</HEAD>
<HEAD>&para; And here bygynneth &thorn;e Clerk of Oxenford prologe</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SIr clerk of Oxenford our hoste sayde</L>
<L>&YOGH;e ryde as stille and coy as do&thorn; a mayde /</L>
<L>were newe spoused sittyng at a bord</L>
<L N="4">This day ne herd I of &yogh;our mouth a word</L>
<L>I trowe &yogh;e study aboute som sophime</L>
<L>But Salomon saith euery &thorn;ing hath tyme</L>
<L>For goddis sake as beth of better cheere</L>
<L N="8">It is no tyme for to stody hiere</L>
<L>Tel vs som mery tale by &yogh;our fay</L>
<L>For what man is entred vnto play</L>
<L>he moot nedes vnto &thorn;at play assent</L>
<L N="12">But prechith not as freres doon in lent</L>
<L>To make vs for our olde synnes wepe</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;at &thorn;y tale [<NOTE PLACE="marg">&thorn;y <I>scratcht out</I></NOTE>] tale make vs for to slepe</L>
<L>Tel vs som mery &thorn;ing of aduentures</L>
<L N="16">&YOGH;oure termes &yogh;our colours and &yogh;our figures</L>
<L>keep hem in stoor til so be &thorn;at &yogh;e endite</L>
<L>high style as whan &thorn;at men to kynges write</L>
<L>Spekith so playn at &thorn;is tyme we &yogh;ow pray</L>
<L N="20">That we may vnderstonde &thorn;at &yogh;e say /</L>
<L>This wor&thorn;y clerk benignely answerde /</L>
<L>Sir host quod he I am vnder &yogh;our &yogh;erde</L>
<L>&YOGH;e haue of vs as now &thorn;e gouernaunce /</L>
<L N="24">And &thorn;erfor wol I do &yogh;ow obeissaunce
<PB REF="00000275.tif" N="263"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="404"></L>
<L>Als fer as resoun askith hardily</L>
<L>I wil &yogh;ow telle a tale which &thorn;at I</L>
<L>lerned at Padowe of a wor&thorn;y clerk</L>
<L N="28">As prouyd by his wordes and his werk</L>
<L>he is now deed and nayled in his chest</L>
<L>Now god &yogh;iue his soule wel good rest</L>
<L>Fraunces petrark &thorn;e laureat poete<MILESTONE N="117a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="32">highte &thorn;is clerk/. whos rethorique swete</L>
<L>Enlumynd al ytail of poetrie</L>
<L>As linian did of philosophie</L>
<L>Or lawue or other art particulere</L>
<L N="36">But deth &thorn;at wol not suffre vs duellen heere</L>
<L>But as it were a twyncling of an ye</L>
<L>hem bo&thorn;e ha&thorn; slayn and alle schul dye</L>
<L>But forth to telle of this wor&thorn;y man</L>
<L N="40">That taughte me &thorn;is tale as I first bigan</L>
<L>I say &thorn;at he first with heigh stile enditith</L>
<L>Er he &thorn;e body of his tale writith</L>
<L>A proheme in the which descriuith he</L>
<L N="44">The mounde and of Saluces &thorn;e contre</L>
<L>And spekith of appenyne &thorn;e hulles hye</L>
<L>That ben &thorn;e boundes of al west lombardye</L>
<L>And of mount vesulus in special</L>
<L N="48">wher as &thorn;e poo out of a welle smal</L>
<L>Takith his firste springyng and his sours</L>
<L>That estward ay encresceth in his cours</L>
<L>To Emyl-ward &middot; to ferard and to venise</L>
<L N="52">The which a long &thorn;ing were to deuyse</L>
<L>And trewely as to my Iuggement</L>
<L>Me thinkith it a &thorn;ing Impertinent</L>
<L>Saue &thorn;at he wold conueyen his matiere</L>
<L N="56">But &thorn;is is &thorn;e tale which &thorn;at &yogh;e schuln heere</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Explicit prohemium<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS. here, or between the Stanzas following.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">


<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000276.tif" N="264">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="405">
<HEAD>&para; Incipit narrare</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="57">Ther is at &thorn;e west / ende of ytaile</L>
<L>Doun at &thorn;e root of vesulus &thorn;e colde</L>
<L>A lusty playn abundaunt of vitaile</L>
<L>wher many a tour and toun &thorn;ou maist byholde.</L>
<L N="61">That foundid were in tyme of fadres olde.</L>
<L>And many anothir delitable sight</L>
<L N="63">And Saluces &thorn;is noble contray hight</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="64">A marquys whilom duellid in &thorn;at lond</L>
<L>As were his wor&thorn;y eldris him bifore</L>
<L>And obeisaunt ay redy to his hond</L>
<L>were alle his liegis bothe lesse and more<MILESTONE N="117b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="68">Thus in delyt he lyueth and hath don &yogh;ore</L>
<L>Biloued and drad &thorn;urgh fauour and fortune</L>
<L N="70">Bo&thorn;e of his lordes and of his comune</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="71">Ther with he was as to speke of lynage</L>
<L>The gentileste born of lumbardye</L>
<L>A fair persone . and strong and &yogh;ong of age</L>
<L>And ful of honour and of curtesie</L>
<L N="75">Discret ynough his contre for to gye</L>
<L>Sauynge in som &thorn;ing he was to blame</L>
<L N="77">And wautier was &thorn;is &yogh;onge lordes name</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="78">I blame him thus that he considered nought</L>
<L>In tyme comyng what mighte bityde</L>
<L>But on his lust present was al his &thorn;ought</L>
<L>As for to hauke and hunte on euery syde</L>
<L N="82">wel neigh al o&thorn;ir cures let he slyde</L>
<L>And eek he nolde &thorn;at was [<NOTE PLACE="marg">&thorn;e was <I>erased</I></NOTE>] &thorn;e worst of al</L>
<L N="84">wedde no wyf for no &thorn;ing &thorn;at might bifal
<PB REF="00000277.tif" N="265"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="406"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="85">Only &thorn;at poynt his poeple bar so sore</L>
<L>That flokmel on a day to him &thorn;ay went</L>
<L>And oon of hem that wisest was of lore</L>
<L>Or elles &thorn;at &thorn;e lord wolde best assent</L>
<L N="89">That he schuld telle him what his poeple ment</L>
<L>Or ellis cou&thorn;e he schewe wel such matiere</L>
<L N="91">he to &thorn;e marquys sayd as &yogh;e schuln hiere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="92">O noble marquys . &yogh;oure humanite</L>
<L>Assureth vs and &yogh;iueth vs hardynesse</L>
<L>As ofte as tyme is of necessite</L>
<L>That we to &yogh;ow may telle oure heuynesse</L>
<L N="96">Acceptith lord now . of &yogh;our necessite</L>
<L>That we with pitous hert vnto &yogh;ow playne</L>
<L N="98">And let &yogh;oure eeris my vois not disdeyne</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="99">And haue I nought to doon in &thorn;is matere</L>
<L>More &thorn;an ano&thorn;er man ha&thorn; in &thorn;is place /</L>
<L>&YOGH;it for as moche as &yogh;e my lord so deere</L>
<L>han alway schewed me fauour and grace</L>
<L N="103">I dar &thorn;e better ask of &yogh;ow a space /</L>
<L>And audience to asken oure request/</L>
<L N="105">And &yogh;e my lord to doon right as &yogh;ow lest<MILESTONE N="118a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="106">For certes lord so wel vs likith &yogh;ow</L>
<L>And al &yogh;our werk and euer han doon &thorn;at we</L>
<L>Ne cou&thorn;en not deuysen how</L>
<L>we mighte lyue more in felicite</L>
<L N="110">Saue oon &thorn;ing lord if &thorn;at &yogh;our wille be</L>
<L>That for to be a weddid man &yogh;ow list/</L>
<L N="112">Than were &yogh;our peple in souereign hertes rest /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="113">Bowith &yogh;our neck . vndir &thorn;at blisful &yogh;ok</L>
<L>Of souereignete . nought of seruise</L>
<L>which &thorn;at men clepe spousail or wedlok</L>
<L>And thenkith lord among &yogh;our &thorn;oughtes wise /
<PB REF="00000278.tif" N="266"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="407"></L>
<L N="117">how &thorn;at our dayes passe in sondry wyse</L>
<L>For &thorn;ough we slepe or wake or rome aboute</L>
<L N="119">Ay fleth &thorn;e tyme it wil no man abyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="120">And though &yogh;our grene &yogh;ou&thorn;e floure as &yogh;it</L>
<L>In crepith age alway as stille as stoon</L>
<L>And deth manasith euery age and smyt</L>
<L>In ech estat for &thorn;er ascapith noon</L>
<L N="124">And as certeyn as as we knowe euerychon</L>
<L>That we schuln deye as vncerteyn we alle</L>
<L N="126">Ben of &thorn;at day &thorn;at de&thorn; schal on vs falle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="127">Acceptith thanne of vs &thorn;e trewe entent</L>
<L>That neuer &yogh;it/ refusid &yogh;oure hest</L>
<L>And we wil lord if &thorn;at &yogh;e wil assent</L>
<L>Chese &yogh;ow a wyf in schort tyme atte lest</L>
<L N="131">Born of &thorn;e gentilest and &thorn;e heighest</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;is lond so &thorn;at it oughte seme</L>
<L N="133">honour to god . and &yogh;ow as we can deme</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="134">Deliuer vs out of al &thorn;is busy drede</L>
<L>And tak a wyf fo hihe goddes sake /</L>
<L>For if it so bifel as god forbede</L>
<L>That &thorn;urgh &yogh;our de&thorn; &yogh;our lygnage schuld aslake</L>
<L N="138">And &thorn;at a straunge successour schuld take</L>
<L>&YOGH;our heritage . O . wo were vs on lyue</L>
<L N="140">wherfor we pray &yogh;ow hastily to wyue</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="141">Her meeke prayer . and her pitous chere</L>
<L>Made &thorn;e marquys for to han pite</L>
<L>&YOGH;e wolde quod he . myn owne poeple deere<MILESTONE N="118b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To &thorn;at I neuer erst &thorn;ought constreigne me.</L>
<L N="145">I me reioysid of my liberte</L>
<L>That selden tyme is founde in mariage</L>
<L N="147">Ther I was fre I mot ben in seruage
<PB REF="00000279.tif" N="267"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="408"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="148">But natheles I se of &yogh;ou &thorn;e trewe entent</L>
<L>And trust vpon &yogh;our witt and haue doon ay</L>
<L>wherfor of my fre wil I wil assent/</L>
<L>To wedde me as soon as euer I may</L>
<L N="152">But &thorn;er as &yogh;e haue profred me to day</L>
<L>To chese me a wyf I wol relese</L>
<L N="154">That choys and pray &yogh;ow of &thorn;at/ profre cesse /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="155">For god it woot &thorn;at childer ofte been</L>
<L>vnlik her worthy eldris hem bifore</L>
<L>Bounte come&thorn; al of god nought of &thorn;e streen</L>
<L>Of which thay ben engendrid and I-bore</L>
<L N="159">I trust in goddis bounte and &thorn;erfore</L>
<L>My mariage and myn estat and rest</L>
<L N="161">I him bytake . he may doon as him lest</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="162">Let me aloon . in chesyng of my wif</L>
<L>That charge vpon my bak I wil endure</L>
<L>But I &yogh;ow pray and charge vpon &yogh;our lyf</L>
<L>That wyf &thorn;at I take &yogh;e me assure /</L>
<L N="166">To worschip / whil . &thorn;at hir lif may endure</L>
<L>In word and werk . bo&thorn;e heer and euery where /</L>
<L N="168">As sche an Emperoures doughter were</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="169">And forthermor &thorn;us schul &yogh;e swer &thorn;at &yogh;e</L>
<L>A&yogh;eins my chois schuln neuer grucche ne stryue</L>
<L>For sins I schal forgo my liberte</L>
<L>At &yogh;our request as euer mot I &thorn;riue</L>
<L N="173">Ther as myn hert is set &thorn;er wil I wyue</L>
<L>And but &yogh;e wil assent in such manere</L>
<L N="175">I pray spek no more of &thorn;is matiere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="176">With hertly wil . &thorn;ay sworen and assentyn</L>
<L>To al &thorn;is &thorn;ing &thorn;er sayde no wight nay</L>
<L>Bysechyng him of grace er &thorn;at &thorn;ay wentyn</L>
<L>That he wol graunten hem a certeyn day
<PB REF="00000280.tif" N="268"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="409"></L>
<L N="180">Of his spousail as soone as euer he may</L>
<L>For &yogh;it alway &thorn;e peple som what dredde<MILESTONE N="119a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="182">lest that the marquys wolde no wyf wedde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="183">He graunted hem a day such as him lest</L>
<L>On which he wolde be weddid sicurly</L>
<L>And sayd he dede al &thorn;is at her requeste</L>
<L>And &thorn;ay with humble hert ful buxomly</L>
<L N="187">knelyng vpon her knees ful reuerently</L>
<L>him &thorn;anken alle and &thorn;us &thorn;ay haue an ende</L>
<L N="189">Of her entent . and hom a&yogh;ein &thorn;ay wende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="190">And her vpon he to his officeris</L>
<L>Comaundith for the feste to purueye</L>
<L>And to his priue knightes and squyeres</L>
<L>which charge &yogh;af as him list on hem leye</L>
<L N="194">And thay to his comaundement obeye /</L>
<L>And ech of hem doth his diligence</L>
<L N="196">To doon vnto &thorn;e feste reuerence</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Explicit prima pars.<NOTE PLACE="end">[No more break in the MS.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="197">NOught fer fro &thorn;ilke place honurable</L>
<L>wher as this marquys schop his mariage</L>
<L>Ther stood a thrope of sighte delitable</L>
<L>In which &thorn;at pore folk of &thorn;at vilage</L>
<L N="201">hadden her bestes and her herburgage /</L>
<L>And after her labour took her sustienaunce</L>
<L N="203">After the erthe &yogh;af hem abundaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="204">Among this pore folk there duelt a man</L>
<L>which &thorn;at was holden porest of hem alle</L>
<L>But heighe god som tyme sende can</L>
<L>his grace vnto a litel oxe stalle</L>
<L N="208">Ianicula men of &thorn;at throop him calle /</L>
<L>A doughter had he fair y-nough to sight</L>
<L N="210">And Crisildes &thorn;is &yogh;onge doughter hight
<PB REF="00000281.tif" N="269"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="410"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="211">But for to speke of hir vertuous beaute</L>
<L>Than was sche oon &thorn;e fayrest vnder sonne</L>
<L>For porely I-fostered vp was sche</L>
<L>No licorous lust was in his body ronne</L>
<L N="215">wel ofter of &thorn;e welle &thorn;an of &thorn;e tonne</L>
<L>She dronk and for sche wolde vertu please</L>
<L N="217">Sche knew wel labour but noon ydel ease</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="218">But &thorn;ough &thorn;is mayden tender were of age<MILESTONE N="119b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;et in &thorn;e brest of her virginite</L>
<L>Ther was enclosed rype and sad corrage</L>
<L>And in gret reuerence and charite</L>
<L N="222">Hir olde pore fader fostred sche /</L>
<L>A fewe scheep spynnyng on &thorn;e feld sche kept</L>
<L N="224">Sche nolde not ben ydel til sche slept</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="225">And whan sche com hom sche wolde brynge</L>
<L>wortis or o&thorn;er herbis tymes ofte</L>
<L>The which sche schred and seth for hir lyuyng</L>
<L>And made hir bed ful hard and no &thorn;ing softe</L>
<L N="229">And ay sche kept hir fadres lif on lofte</L>
<L>with euery obeissance and diligence</L>
<L N="231">That child may do to fadres reuerence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="232">Vpon Grisildes &thorn;e pore creature</L>
<L>Ful ofte sithes &thorn;is marquys set his ye</L>
<L>As he on huntyng rood par auenture</L>
<L>And whan it fel he mighte hir espye</L>
<L N="236">he not with wantoun lokyng of folye</L>
<L>his ey&yogh;en cast vpon hir but in sad wyse</L>
<L N="238">vpon hir cheer he wold him oft avise</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="239">Comendyng in his hert hir wommanhede</L>
<L>And eek hir vertu passyng any o&thorn;er wight</L>
<L>Of so &yogh;ong age as wel in cheer as dede</L>
<L>For &thorn;ough &thorn;e poeple haue no gret insight
<PB REF="00000282.tif" N="270"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="411"></L>
<L N="243">In vertu he considereth aright</L>
<L>Hir bounte and desposed &thorn;at he wolde</L>
<L N="245">wedde hir oonly if euer he wedde scholde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="246">The day of weddyng cam but no wight can</L>
<L>Telle what womman it schulde be /</L>
<L>For which meruayle wondrith many a man</L>
<L>And sayden whan &thorn;ay were in priuete</L>
<L N="250">wol nought our lord &yogh;it leue his vanite</L>
<L>wol he not wedde allas allas &thorn;e while</L>
<L N="252">why wol he &thorn;us himself and vs bigyle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="253">But natheles &thorn;is marquys ha&thorn; doon make</L>
<L>Of gemmes set in gold and in asure</L>
<L>Broches and rynges for Grisildes sake /</L>
<L>And of hir clothing took he &thorn;e mesure<MILESTONE N="120a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="257">By a mayde y-lik to hir of stature</L>
<L>And eek of o&thorn;er ornamentes alle /</L>
<L N="259">That vnto such a weddyng schulde falle /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="260">The tyme of vndern of &thorn;e same day</L>
<L>Approchith &thorn;at &thorn;is weddyng schulde be /</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e palys put was in array</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e halle an chambur . ylik here degre</L>
<L N="264">houses of office stuffid with plente</L>
<L>Ther maystow se of deynteuous vitayle</L>
<L N="266">That may be founde as fer as lastith Itaile /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="267">This real marquys really arrayd</L>
<L>lordes and ladyes in his compaignye</L>
<L>he which vnto &thorn;e feste were prayed</L>
<L>And of his retenu &thorn;e bachelerie</L>
<L N="271">with many a soun of sondry melodye</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e vilage of which I tolde</L>
<L N="273">In &thorn;is array &thorn;e right way han &thorn;ay holde
<PB REF="00000283.tif" N="271"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="412"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="274">Grysild of &thorn;is god wot ful Innocent /</L>
<L>That for hir schapen was al &thorn;is array /</L>
<L>To fecche water at a welle is went/</L>
<L>And cometh hom as soone as sche may</L>
<L N="278">For wel sche had herd sayd &thorn;at ilke day</L>
<L>The marquys schulde wedde and if sche might</L>
<L N="280">Sche wold haue seyen som what of &thorn;at sight</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="281">Sche sayd I wol with o&thorn;er maydenes stonde /</L>
<L>That ben my felawes . in oure dore and see /</L>
<L>The marquys and &thorn;erfore wol I fonde /</L>
<L>To don at hom as soone as it may be</L>
<L N="285">The labour which &thorn;at longeth vnto me</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne may I at leysir hir byholde</L>
<L N="287">And sche &thorn;e way in to &thorn;e castel holde /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="288">And as sche wold ouer &thorn;e &thorn;reisshfold goon</L>
<L>The marquys cam and gan hir for to calle</L>
<L>And sche set doun her water-pot anoon</L>
<L>Bisides &thorn;e &thorn;reischfold of &thorn;is oxe stalle /</L>
<L N="292">And doun vpon hir/ knees . sche gan falle</L>
<L>And with sad countenaunce knelith stille</L>
<L N="294">Til sche had herd what was &thorn;e lordes wille<MILESTONE N="120b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="295">This &thorn;oughtful marquys spak vnto &thorn;is mayde</L>
<L>Ful soberly and sayd in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>wher is &yogh;our fader Grisildes he sayde</L>
<L>And sche with reuerence and humble cheere</L>
<L N="299">Sayde lord he is al redy heere /</L>
<L>And in sche goth wi&thorn;outen lenger let</L>
<L N="301">And to &thorn;e marquys sche hir fader fet</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="302">He by &thorn;e hond &thorn;an takith &thorn;is olde man</L>
<L>And sayde &thorn;us . whan he him had on syde /</L>
<L>Ianicula I neither may ne can</L>
<L>lenger &thorn;e plesauns of myn herte hyde
<PB REF="00000284.tif" N="272"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="413"></L>
<L N="306">If &thorn;at &yogh;e vouche sauf what so betyde /</L>
<L>Thy doughter wil I take er &thorn;at I wende</L>
<L N="308">As for my wyf vnto hir lyues ende /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="309">Thow louest me I wot it wel certeyn</L>
<L>And art my faithful liege man I-bore /</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at likith me I dar wel sayn</L>
<L>It likith &thorn;e . and specially &thorn;erfore</L>
<L N="313">Tel me &thorn;at poynt . as &yogh;e haue herd bifore</L>
<L>If &thorn;at &thorn;ow wolt vnto &thorn;at purpos drawe /</L>
<L N="315">To take me as for &thorn;y &middot; sone in lawe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="316">The sodeyn caas &thorn;e man astoneyd &thorn;o</L>
<L>That reed he wax abaischt and al quakyng</L>
<L>he stood vnne&thorn;e sayd he wordes mo</L>
<L>But oonly &thorn;is . lord quod he my willyng</L>
<L N="320">Is as &yogh;e wol a&yogh;enst &yogh;oure likyng</L>
<L>I wol no &thorn;ing &yogh;e be my lord so deere</L>
<L N="322">Right as &yogh;ow list gouernith &thorn;is matiere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="323">&YOGH;it wol I quod &thorn;is markys softely</L>
<L>That in &thorn;y chambre I and &thorn;ou and sche /</L>
<L>haue a collacioun and wostow why</L>
<L>For I wol aske if it hir wille be</L>
<L N="327">To be my wyf and reule hir after me</L>
<L>And al &thorn;is schal ben doon in &thorn;y presence</L>
<L N="329">I wol nought speke out of &thorn;yn audience</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="330">And in &thorn;e chamber whil &thorn;ay were aboute</L>
<L>her tretys which as &yogh;e schul after hiere</L>
<L>The poeple cam vnto &thorn;e hous wi&thorn;oute<MILESTONE N="121a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And wondrid hem in how honest manere</L>
<L N="334">And tendurly sche kept hir fader deere</L>
<L>But outerly grisildes wonder might</L>
<L N="336">For neuer erst ne saugh sche such a sight
<PB REF="00000285.tif" N="273"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="414"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="337">No wonder is &thorn;ough &thorn;at sche were astoned</L>
<L>To seen so gret a gest come in to &thorn;at place /</L>
<L>Sche neuer was to suche gestes woned</L>
<L>For which sche loked with ful pale face /</L>
<L N="341">But schortly &thorn;is matiere forth to chace</L>
<L>These arn &thorn;e wordes &thorn;at &thorn;e marquys sayde /</L>
<L N="343">To this benigne verray faithful mayde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="344">Grisyld he sayde &yogh;e schul wel vnderstonde /</L>
<L>It liketh to &yogh;our fader and to me</L>
<L>That I &yogh;ow wedde and eek it may so stonde</L>
<L>As I suppose &yogh;e wil &thorn;at it so be /</L>
<L N="348">But &thorn;ese demaundes aske I first quod he /</L>
<L>That sith it schal be doon in hasty wyse</L>
<L N="350">wol &yogh;e assent or elles &yogh;ow auyse /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="351">I say &thorn;is be &yogh;e redy with good hert/</L>
<L>To al my lust and &thorn;at I frely may</L>
<L>As me best liste . do &yogh;ow laughe or smert</L>
<L>And neuer &yogh;e to gruch it night ne day</L>
<L N="355">And eek whan I say &yogh;e &yogh;e say not nay</L>
<L>Neyther by word ne frownyng contenaunce</L>
<L N="357">Swer &thorn;is and here swer I oure alliaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="358">Wondryng vpon &thorn;is word quakyng for drede</L>
<L>Sche sayde lord vndigne and vnworthy</L>
<L>I am to thilk honour . &thorn;at &yogh;e me bede</L>
<L>But as &yogh;e wil &yogh;our self right so wol I</L>
<L N="362">And here I swere &thorn;at neuer wityngly</L>
<L>In werk ne thought I nyl &yogh;ow disobeye</L>
<L N="364">For to be deed &thorn;ough me were loth to deye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="365">This is ynough Grisilde myn quod he /</L>
<L>And forth goth he wi&thorn; a ful sobre chere</L>
<L>Out at &thorn;e dore and after &thorn;at cam sche</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e pepul he sayd in &thorn;is manere &middot;
<PB REF="00000286.tif" N="274"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="415"></L>
<L N="369">This is my wyf quod he &thorn;at stondith heere</L>
<L>honoureth hir and loueth hir I &yogh;ow pray<MILESTONE N="121b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="371">who so me loueth &thorn;er is no more to say</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="372">And for &thorn;at no &thorn;ing of hir olde gere</L>
<L>Sche schulde brynge vnto his hous he bad</L>
<L>That wommen schuld despoilen hir right &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Of which &thorn;ese ladyes were nought ful glad</L>
<L N="376">To handle hir clo&thorn;es wher-in sche was clad</L>
<L>But natheles &thorn;is mayde bright of hew</L>
<L N="378">Fro foot to heed &thorn;ay schredde han al newe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="379">Hir heeres han &thorn;ay kempt &thorn;at lay vntressed</L>
<L>Ful rudely and with hir fyngres smale</L>
<L>A coroun on hir heed &thorn;ay han I-dressed</L>
<L>And set hir ful of nowches gret and smale</L>
<L N="383">Of hir array what schuld I make a tale /</L>
<L>Vnnethe &thorn;e poeple hir knew for hir fairnesse /</L>
<L N="385">whan sche translated was in such richesse /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="386">This marquis ha&thorn; hir spoused with a ryng</L>
<L>Brought for &thorn;e same cause and &thorn;an hir sette</L>
<L>vpon an hors snow-whyt and wel amblyng</L>
<L>And to his palys er he lenger lette</L>
<L N="390">with ioyful poeple &thorn;at hir ladde and mette</L>
<L>Conueyed hire and &thorn;us &thorn;e day &thorn;ay spende</L>
<L N="392">In reuel til &thorn;e sonne gan descende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="393">And schortly &thorn;is tale for to chace</L>
<L>I say &thorn;at to &thorn;is newe marquisesse</L>
<L>God hath schewed fauour and sent hir of his grace</L>
<L>That it semyd not by liklynesse</L>
<L N="397">That sche was born and fed in rudenesse</L>
<L>As in a cote or in an Oxe stalle</L>
<L N="399">But norischt in an emperoures halle
<PB REF="00000287.tif" N="275"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="416"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="400">To euery wight sche waxen is so deere</L>
<L>And worschipful &thorn;at folk &thorn;er sche was born</L>
<L>And from hir burthe knew hir &yogh;er by &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Vnneth trowed &thorn;ay but dorst han sworn</L>
<L N="404">That to Ianicle of which I spak biforn</L>
<L>Sche doughter were . for as by coniecture</L>
<L N="406">Hem &thorn;ought sche was ano&thorn;er creature</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="407">For &thorn;ough &thorn;at euer vertuous was sche</L>
<L>Sche was encresed in such excellence<MILESTONE N="122a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of thewes goode i-set in high bounte</L>
<L>And so discret and fair of eloquence</L>
<L N="411">So benigne and so digne of reuerence</L>
<L>And cou&thorn;e so &thorn;e poeples hert embrace</L>
<L N="413">That ech hir loue&thorn; &thorn;at lokith in hir face</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="414">Nought oonly of Saluce in &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>Puplissched was &thorn;e bounte of hir name</L>
<L>But eek byside in many a regioun</L>
<L>If oon sayd wel ano&thorn;er sayd &thorn;e same</L>
<L N="418">So sprad of hire heigh bounte &thorn;e fame /</L>
<L>That men and wommen as wel &yogh;ong as olde</L>
<L N="420">Gon to Saluce vpon hir to byholde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="421">This walter louly . nay but really</L>
<L>weddid with fortunat honestete</L>
<L>In goddes pees lyueth ful esily</L>
<L>At home and outward grace ynough ha&thorn; he</L>
<L N="425">And for he saugh &thorn;at vnder low degre</L>
<L>was ofte vertu y-hid &thorn;e poeple him helde</L>
<L N="427">A prudent man and &thorn;at is seint ful selde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="428">Nought oonly &thorn;is Grisildes &thorn;urgh hit witte</L>
<L>Couthe al &thorn;e feet of wifly humblesse /</L>
<L>But eek whan &thorn;at &thorn;e tyme required it</L>
<L>The comun profyt couthe sche redresse
<PB REF="00000288.tif" N="276"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="417"></L>
<L N="432">Ther nas discord rancour ne heuynesse /</L>
<L>In al &thorn;at lond &thorn;at sche ne cou&thorn;e appese /</L>
<L N="434">And wisly bryng hem alle in rest and ese</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="435">Though &thorn;at hir housbond absent were anoon</L>
<L>If gentil men or o&thorn;er of hir contre</L>
<L>were wroth sche wolde brynge hem at oon</L>
<L>So wyse and rype wordes hadde sche</L>
<L N="439">And Iuggement of so gret equite</L>
<L>That sche from heuen sent was as men wende /</L>
<L N="441">Poeple to saue and euery wrong to amende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="442">Nought longe tyme after &thorn;at &thorn;is Grisilde</L>
<L>was wedded sche a dou&yogh;ter ha&thorn; I-bore</L>
<L>Al had hir leuer han had a knaue childe</L>
<L>Glad was &thorn;is marquis and &thorn;e folk &thorn;erfore</L>
<L N="446">For though a mayden child come al byfore /<MILESTONE N="122b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sche may vnto a knaue child atteigne</L>
<L N="448">By liklihed and sche nys not bareigne<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; Incipit Tercia pars.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="449">Ther fel as fallith many tymes mo</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at &thorn;is child ha&thorn; souked but a &thorn;rowe</L>
<L>This marquys in his herte longith so</L>
<L>Tempte his wyf . hir sadnesse for to knowe</L>
<L N="453">That he ne might out of his herte &thorn;rowe</L>
<L>This meruaylous desir his wyf tassaye</L>
<L N="455">Now god wot he &thorn;ought hir to affraye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="456">He had assayed hir ynough bifore</L>
<L>And fond hir euer good what needith it/</L>
<L>hire to tempte . and alway more and more</L>
<L>Though som men prayse it for a subtil wit</L>
<L N="460">But as for me I say that euel it sit</L>
<L>Tassay a wyf whan &thorn;at it is no neede</L>
<L N="462">And putte hir in anguysch and in dreede
<PB REF="00000289.tif" N="277"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="418"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="463">For which &thorn;is marquis wrou&yogh;t in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>he com aloone a night &thorn;er as sche lay /</L>
<L>wi&thorn; sterne face and with ful trouble cheere</L>
<L>And sayde &thorn;us Grisild quod he &thorn;at day /</L>
<L N="467">&THORN;at I &yogh;ow took out of &yogh;our pore array /</L>
<L>And putte &yogh;ow in estat of heigh noblesse</L>
<L N="469">&YOGH;e haue not &thorn;at . forgeten as I gesse /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="470">I say Grisild &thorn;is present dignite</L>
<L>In which &thorn;at I haue put &yogh;ow as I trowe</L>
<L>Makith &yogh;ow not . for&yogh;etful for to be</L>
<L>&THORN;at I &yogh;ow took in pore estat ful lowe</L>
<L N="474">For eny wele &yogh;e moot &yogh;our selue knowe /</L>
<L>Tak heed of euery word &thorn;at/ I &yogh;ow say /</L>
<L N="476">Ther is no wight &thorn;at herith it but we tway /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="477">&YOGH;e wot &yogh;our self . how &yogh;e comen heere</L>
<L>In to &thorn;is hous it is nought long ago</L>
<L>And &thorn;ough to me &thorn;at &yogh;e be leef and deere</L>
<L>vnto my gentils &yogh;e be no &thorn;ing so</L>
<L N="481">Thay seyn to hem it is gret schame and wo</L>
<L>For to ben subiect/ . and ben in seruage /</L>
<L N="483">To the &thorn;at born art of a smal village<MILESTONE N="123a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="484">And namely syn &thorn;y doughter was I-bore</L>
<L>These wordes han &thorn;ay spoken douteles</L>
<L>But I desire as I haue doon byfore</L>
<L>To lyue my lif with hem in rest and pees</L>
<L N="488">I may not in &thorn;is caas be reccheles</L>
<L>I moot do with &thorn;y doughter for &thorn;e best/</L>
<L N="490">Not as I wolde but as my pepul lest</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="491">And &yogh;it god wot &thorn;is is ful loth to me</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles wi&thorn;oute &yogh;oure witynge</L>
<L>wol I not doon . but &thorn;is wold I quod he /</L>
<L>That &yogh;e to me assent as in &thorn;is &thorn;ing /
<PB REF="00000290.tif" N="278"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="419"></L>
<L N="495">Schew now &yogh;our paciens in &yogh;our wirching</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou me hightest and swor in &yogh;on village</L>
<L N="497">That day &thorn;at maked was oure mariage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="498">Whan sche had herd al &thorn;is sche nou&yogh;t ameeuyd</L>
<L>Ney&thorn;er in word in cheer or countenaunce</L>
<L>For as it semed sche was nought agreeued</L>
<L>She sayde lord al lith in &yogh;our plesaunce</L>
<L N="502">My child and I with hertly obeisaunce</L>
<L>Ben &yogh;oures al . and &yogh;e may saue or spille</L>
<L N="504">&YOGH;our oughne &thorn;ing . werki&thorn; after &yogh;our wille /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="505">Ther may no &thorn;ing so god my soule saue</L>
<L>liken to &yogh;ow &thorn;at may displesen me</L>
<L>Ne I desire no &thorn;ing for to haue</L>
<L>Ne drede for to lese saue oonly &yogh;e</L>
<L N="509">This wil is in myn hert and ay schal be</L>
<L>No length of tyme or de&thorn; may &thorn;is deface /</L>
<L N="511">Ne chaunge my corrage to o&thorn;er place /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="512">Glad was this marquis of hir answeryng</L>
<L>But &yogh;it he feyned as he were not so</L>
<L>Al dreery was his cheer and his lokyng</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at he schold out of &thorn;e Chambre go</L>
<L N="516">Soon after &thorn;is a forlong way or tuo</L>
<L>he priuely ha&thorn; told al his entent</L>
<L N="518">vnto aman . and vnto his wyf him sent</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="519">A maner Sergeant was &thorn;is priue man</L>
<L>The which &thorn;at faithful oft he founden hadde</L>
<L>In &thorn;inges grete . and eek such folk wel can<MILESTONE N="123b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Don execucioun in &thorn;inges badde</L>
<L N="523">The lord knew wel &thorn;at he him loued and dradde</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is sergeant wist his lordes wille</L>
<L N="525">In to &thorn;e chamber he stalked him ful stille.
<PB REF="00000291.tif" N="279"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="420"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="526">Ma dame he sayd &yogh;e most for&yogh;iue it me</L>
<L>Though I do &thorn;ing . to which I am constreynit.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e ben so wys &thorn;at ful wel knowe &yogh;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at lordes hestes mow not ben I-feynit</L>
<L N="530">Thay mowe wel biwayl it or compleyn it/</L>
<L>But men moot neede vnto her lust obeye</L>
<L N="532">And so wol I &thorn;er is no more to seye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="533">This child I am comaundid for to take /</L>
<L>And spak no more. but out &thorn;e child he hent</L>
<L>Dispitously and gan a chiere make</L>
<L>As &thorn;ough he wold han slayn it er he went</L>
<L N="537">Grisild moot al suffer and al consent</L>
<L>And as a lamb sche sitteth meeke and stille /</L>
<L N="539">And let &thorn;is cruel sergeant doon his wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="540">Suspecious was &thorn;e defame of &thorn;is man</L>
<L>Suspect his face. suspect his word also /</L>
<L>Suspect &thorn;e tyme. in which he &thorn;is bigan</L>
<L>Allas hir doughter &thorn;at she loued so</L>
<L N="544">Sche wend he wold han slayen it right &thorn;o</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles sche ney&thorn;er weep ne siked</L>
<L N="546">Conformyng hir to &thorn;at &thorn;e marquis liked</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="547">But atte last speke sche bigan</L>
<L>And mekely sche to &thorn;e sergeant preyde</L>
<L>So as he was a wor&thorn;y gentil man</L>
<L>That she most kisse hir child er &thorn;at it deyde</L>
<L N="551">And on hir arm &thorn;is litel child sche leyde</L>
<L>wi&thorn; ful sad face. and gan &thorn;e child to blesse</L>
<L N="553">And lullyd it and after gan it kesse /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="554">And &thorn;us sche sayd in hir benigne vois</L>
<L>Far wel my child I schal &thorn;e neuer see /</L>
<L>But sith I &thorn;e haue marked wi&thorn; &thorn;e croys /</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ilke fader blessed mot &thorn;ou be
<PB REF="00000292.tif" N="280"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="421"></L>
<L N="558">That for vs deyde vpon a cros of tre</L>
<L>Thy soule litel child. I him bytake<MILESTONE N="124a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="560">For &thorn;is night schaltow deyen for my sake /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="561">I trowe &thorn;at to a norice in &thorn;is caas</L>
<L>It had ben hard &thorn;is rewthe for to see</L>
<L>wel might a moder &thorn;an haue cryed allas</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles so sad stedefast was sche</L>
<L N="565">&THORN;at she endured al aduersite</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e sergeant mekely sche sayde /</L>
<L N="567">Haue her agayn &yogh;our litel &yogh;onge mayde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="568">Goth now quod sche and do&thorn; my lordes heste</L>
<L>But o &thorn;ing wil I pray &yogh;ow of &yogh;our grace</L>
<L>&THORN;at but my lord forbede &yogh;ow atte leste</L>
<L>Burieth &thorn;is litel body in som place</L>
<L N="572">That bestes ne no briddes it to-race /</L>
<L>But he no word wil to &thorn;e purpos say /</L>
<L N="574">But took &thorn;e child and went vpon his way</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="575">This sergeant com vnto &thorn;is lord agayn</L>
<L>And of Grisildes wordes and hir cheere</L>
<L>He tolde poynt for poynt in schort and playn</L>
<L>And him presentith with his dou&yogh;ter deere</L>
<L N="579">Som what &thorn;is lord hath rewthe in his manere</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles his purpos huld he stille /</L>
<L N="581">As lordes doon whan &thorn;ay woln haue her wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="582">And bad &thorn;e sergeaunt &thorn;at he priuely</L>
<L>Scholde &thorn;is childe softe wynde and wrappe /</L>
<L>with alle circumstaunces tendurly</L>
<L>And cary it in a cofre or in his lappe</L>
<L N="586">Vpon peyne his heed of for to swappe</L>
<L>That no man schulde knowe of &thorn;is entent</L>
<L N="588">Ne whens he com. ne whider &thorn;at he went
<PB REF="00000293.tif" N="281"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="422"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="589">But at Boloyne to his suster deere</L>
<L>That &thorn;ilke tyme of panik was Countesse</L>
<L>He schuld it take and schewe hir &thorn;is matiere</L>
<L>Byseching her to doon hir busynesse</L>
<L N="593">This child to fostre in alle gentilesse</L>
<L>And whos child &thorn;at it was he bad hir hyde</L>
<L N="595">From euery wight for ought &thorn;at mighte bytyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="596">The sergeant go&thorn; and ha&thorn; fulfild &thorn;is &thorn;ing</L>
<L>But to &thorn;is marquys now retourne we<MILESTONE N="124b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For now go&thorn; he ful fast ymaginyng</L>
<L>If by his wyues cher he mighte se</L>
<L N="600">Or by hir word apparceyue &thorn;at sche</L>
<L>were chaunged. but he hir neuer cou&thorn;e fynde</L>
<L N="602">But euer in oon y-like sad and kynde /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="603">As glad as humble as busy in seruise /</L>
<L>And eek in loue as sche was wont to be</L>
<L>was sche to him in euery maner wyse /</L>
<L>Ne of hir doughter nou&yogh;t o word spak sche</L>
<L N="607">Non accident/ for noon aduersite</L>
<L>was seyn in hir ne neuer hir doughter name</L>
<L N="609">Ne nempnyd sche. in ernest ne in game<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; Incipit. Quarta pars.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="610">IN &thorn;is estaat &thorn;er passed ben foure &yogh;er</L>
<L>Er sche wi&thorn; childe was. but as god wolde</L>
<L>A knaue child sche bar by &thorn;is waltier</L>
<L>Ful gracious and fair for to biholde</L>
<L N="614">And whan &thorn;at folk it/ to his fader tolde</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t oonly he. but al his contre merye</L>
<L N="616">was for &thorn;is child and god &thorn;ay &thorn;ank and herie</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="617">When it was tuo &yogh;er old and fro &thorn;e brest</L>
<L>Departed fro his noris vpon a day</L>
<L>This markys caughte &yogh;it another lest
<PB REF="00000294.tif" N="282"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="423"></L>
<L>To tempt his wif &yogh;it after if he may</L>
<L N="621">O needles was sche tempted in assay</L>
<L>But weddid men ne knowen no mesure</L>
<L N="623">whan &thorn;at &thorn;ay fynde. a pacient creature</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="624">Wyf quod &thorn;is marquys &yogh;e han herd er &thorn;is</L>
<L>My peple sekly berith oure mariage</L>
<L>And namly syn. my sone y-boren is</L>
<L>Now is it wors &thorn;an euer in al our age</L>
<L N="628">The murmur sle&thorn; myn hert and my corrage</L>
<L>For to myn eeris come&thorn; &thorn;e vois so smerte</L>
<L N="630">&THORN;at it wel neigh destroyed ha&thorn; myn herte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="631">Now say &thorn;ay &thorn;us whan wauter is a goon</L>
<L>Than schal &thorn;e blood of Ianicula succede</L>
<L>And ben our lord for o&thorn;er haue we noon&middot;</L>
<L>Suche wordes saith my poeple out/ of drede /<MILESTONE N="125a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="635">wel ought I of such murmur taken heede</L>
<L>For certeynly I drede such sentence</L>
<L N="637">&THORN;ough &thorn;ay not pleynly speke in myn audience /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="638">I wolde lyue in pees if &thorn;at I might</L>
<L>wher for I am disposid outrely</L>
<L>As I his suster seruede by night</L>
<L>Right so &thorn;ynk I to serue him priuely</L>
<L N="642">This warn I &yogh;ou &thorn;at &yogh;e not sodeinly</L>
<L>Out of &yogh;our self for no &thorn;ing schuld outraye</L>
<L N="644">Be&thorn; pacient and &thorn;er of I &yogh;ow pray</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="645">I haue quod sche sayd &thorn;us and euer schal</L>
<L>I wol no &thorn;ing ne nil no &thorn;ing certayn</L>
<L>But as &yogh;ow list. nought greueth me at al</L>
<L>Though &thorn;at my doughter and my sone be slayn.</L>
<L N="649">At &yogh;our comaundement &thorn;is is to sayne</L>
<L>I haue no had no part of children twayne</L>
<L N="651">But first syknes and after wo and payne /
<PB REF="00000295.tif" N="283"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="424"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="652">&YOGH;e ben oure lord doth with &yogh;our owne &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Right as &yogh;ow list axith no red of me</L>
<L>For as I left at hom al my clo&thorn;ing</L>
<L>whan I first com to &yogh;ow right so quod sche</L>
<L N="656">Left I my wille and my liberte /</L>
<L>And took &yogh;our clo&thorn;ing. wher for I &yogh;ow preye</L>
<L N="658">Do&thorn; &yogh;oure plesaunce. I wil &yogh;oure lust obeye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="659">And certes if I hadde prescience</L>
<L>&YOGH;our wil to knowe. er &yogh;e &yogh;oure lust me tolde</L>
<L>I wold it doon wi&thorn;oute negligence</L>
<L>But now I wot &yogh;our lust and what &yogh;e wolde</L>
<L N="663">Al &yogh;our plesaunce ferm and stable I holde</L>
<L>For wist I &thorn;at my deth wold don &yogh;ow ease</L>
<L N="665">Right gladly wold I deye &yogh;ow to please</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="666">Deth may make no comparisoun</L>
<L>vnto &yogh;our loue and whan &thorn;is marquys say</L>
<L>The constance of his wyf he cast a doun</L>
<L>His ey&yogh;en tuo and wondrith &thorn;at sche may</L>
<L N="670">In pacience suffre al &thorn;is array</L>
<L>And forth he go&thorn; with drery countenaunce</L>
<L N="672">But to his hert it was ful gret plesaunce<MILESTONE N="125b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="673">This Igly sergeaunt in &thorn;e same wise</L>
<L>That he hir doughter fette. right so he</L>
<L>Or worse if men worse can deuyse</L>
<L>hath hent hir sone &thorn;at ful was of beaute</L>
<L N="677">And euer in oon so pacient was sche</L>
<L>That sche no cheere made of heuynesse</L>
<L N="679">But kist hir sone. and after gan him blesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="680">Saue &thorn;is sche prayed him if &thorn;at he mighte</L>
<L>her litel sone he wold in eor&thorn;e graue</L>
<L>His tendre lymes delicate to sight</L>
<L>From foules and from bestes him to saue
<PB REF="00000296.tif" N="284"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="425"></L>
<L N="684">But sche noon answer of him mighte haue</L>
<L>he went his way as him no &thorn;ing ne rought</L>
<L N="686">But to Boloyne he tenderly it brought</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="687">This marquis wondreth euer &thorn;e lenger &thorn;e more</L>
<L>vpon hir pacience. and if &thorn;at he</L>
<L>Ne hadde so&thorn;ly knowen &thorn;er bifore</L>
<L>&THORN;at parfytly hir children loued sche</L>
<L N="691">he wold haue wend &thorn;at of som subtilte</L>
<L>And malice or of cruel corrage</L>
<L N="693">That sche had suffred &thorn;is wi&thorn; sad visage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="694">But wel he knew &thorn;at next himself certayn</L>
<L>Sche loued hir children best in euery wise</L>
<L>But now of wommen wold I aske fayn</L>
<L>If &thorn;ese assayes mighten not suffice</L>
<L N="698">what cou&thorn;e a stourdy housebonde more deuyse</L>
<L>To prove hir wyfhode and her stedefastnesse /</L>
<L N="700">And he contynuyng euer in stourdynesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="701">But &thorn;er ben folk of such condicioun</L>
<L>That whan &thorn;ay haue a certeyn purpos take</L>
<L>Thay can nought stynt of her entencioun</L>
<L>But right as &thorn;ay were bounden to a stake /</L>
<L N="705">&THORN;ay wil not of her firste purpos slake</L>
<L>Right so &thorn;is marquys fullich ha&thorn; purposed</L>
<L N="707">To tempt his wyf as he was first disposed</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="708">He wayteth if by word or countenaunce</L>
<L>That sche to him was chaunged of corage</L>
<L>But neuer cou&thorn;e he fynde variaunce<MILESTONE N="126a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sche was ay oon in hert and in visage</L>
<L N="712">And ay &thorn;e fer&thorn;er &thorn;at sche was in age /</L>
<L>The more trewe if &thorn;at it were possible /</L>
<L N="714">Sche was to him and more penyble.
<PB REF="00000297.tif" N="285"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="426"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="715">For which it semyd &thorn;is &thorn;at of hem tuo</L>
<L>&THORN;er nas but oo wil for as walter lest/</L>
<L>The same plesaunce was hir lust also</L>
<L>And god by thanked al fel for &thorn;e best/</L>
<L N="719">Sche schewed wel. for no worldly vnrest</L>
<L>A wyf as of hir self no &thorn;ing ne scholde</L>
<L N="721">wylne in effect. but as hir housbond wolde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="722">The sclaunder of walter ofte and wyde spradde</L>
<L>That of a cruel hert he wikkedly</L>
<L>For he a pore womman weddid hadde</L>
<L>hath morthrid bo&thorn;e his children priuely</L>
<L N="726">Such murmur was among hem comunly</L>
<L>No wonder is for to &thorn;e peples eere</L>
<L N="728">Ther com no word. but &thorn;at &thorn;ay mortherid were /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="729">For which wher as his peple &thorn;er byfore</L>
<L>had loued him wel &thorn;e sclaunder of his diffame</L>
<L>Made hem &thorn;at &thorn;ay him hatede &thorn;erfore</L>
<L>To ben a mordrer. is an hateful name</L>
<L N="733">But na&thorn;eles for ernest or for game</L>
<L>he of his cruel purpos nolde stente</L>
<L N="735">To tempt his wyf was set al his entente</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="736">Whan &thorn;at his doughter twelf &yogh;er was of age</L>
<L>he to &thorn;e court of Rome in suche wise</L>
<L>Enformed of his wille sent his message</L>
<L>Comaundyng hem. such bulles to deuyse</L>
<L N="740">As to his cruel purpos may suffise</L>
<L>how &thorn;at &thorn;e pope as for his peples reste</L>
<L N="742">Bad him to wedde ano&thorn;er if him leste</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="743">I say he bad &thorn;ay schulde countrefete</L>
<L>The popes bulles makyng mencioun</L>
<L>That he ha&thorn; leue his firste wyf to lete</L>
<L>As by &thorn;e popes dispensacioun
<PB REF="00000298.tif" N="286"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="427"></L>
<L N="747">To stynte rancour and discencioun</L>
<L>Bitwix his peple and him &thorn;us sayd &thorn;e bulle<MILESTONE N="126b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="749">The which &thorn;ay han publisshid atte fulle /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="750">The rude poepel as it no wonder is</L>
<L>wende ful wel &thorn;at it had be right so</L>
<L>But whan &thorn;ese tydynges come to Grisildis</L>
<L>I deeme &thorn;at hir herte was ful wo</L>
<L N="754">But sche y-like sad for euermo</L>
<L>Disposid was &thorn;is humble creature</L>
<L N="756">Thaduersite of fortun al tendure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="757">Abydyng euer his lust and his plesaunce</L>
<L>To whom &thorn;at sche was &yogh;iue hert and al</L>
<L>As to hir verray worldly suffisaunce</L>
<L>But schortly if I &thorn;is story telle schal</L>
<L N="761">This marquys writen ha&thorn; in special</L>
<L>A letter in which he schewith his entent</L>
<L N="763">And secrely he to Boloyne it sent /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="764">To therl of panyk/ which &thorn;at hadde &thorn;o</L>
<L>weddid his suster prayd he specially</L>
<L>To brynge hom a&yogh;ein his children tuo</L>
<L>In honurable estaat al openly</L>
<L N="768">But oon &thorn;ing he him prayde outerly</L>
<L>That he to no wight &thorn;ough men wold enquere</L>
<L N="770">Schuld not tellen. whos children &thorn;ay were</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="771">But say &thorn;e mayde. schuld I-weddid be</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e markys of Saluce anoon</L>
<L>And as &thorn;is eorl was prayd so dede he</L>
<L>For at day set. he on his way is goon</L>
<L N="775">Toward Saluce and lordes many oon</L>
<L>In riche array &thorn;is mayden for to guyde</L>
<L N="777">hir &yogh;onge bro&thorn;er rydyng by hir syde
<PB REF="00000299.tif" N="287"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="428"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="778">Arrayed was toward hir mariage</L>
<L>This freisshe may al ful of gemmes clere</L>
<L>hir bro&thorn;er which &thorn;at. seuen &yogh;er was of age</L>
<L>Arrayed eek. ful freissh in his manere /</L>
<L N="782">And thus in gret noblesse and with glad chere</L>
<L>Toward Saluces schapyng her iournay</L>
<L N="784">Fro day to day &thorn;ay ryden in her way<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="5" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; Incipit pars Quinta.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="785">AMong al &thorn;is after his wikked vsage<MILESTONE N="127a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>This marquis &yogh;it his wif to tempte more</L>
<L>To &thorn;e vttrest proef of hir corrage</L>
<L>Fully to han experiens and lore</L>
<L N="789">If &thorn;at sche were as stedefast as byfore</L>
<L>He on a day in open audience</L>
<L N="791">Ful boystously ha&thorn; sayd hir &thorn;is sentence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="792">Certes Grisildes I had ynough plesaunce</L>
<L>To haue &yogh;ow to my wif for &yogh;our goodnesse</L>
<L>And for &yogh;oure trou&thorn;e and for &yogh;our obeissaunce</L>
<L>Nought for &yogh;our lignage ne for &yogh;our richesse</L>
<L N="796">But now know I in verray sothfastnesse /</L>
<L>That in gret lordschip if I wel auyse /</L>
<L N="798">Ther is gret seruise in sondry wyse /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="799">I may not do as euery plough man may</L>
<L>My poeple me constreignith for to take</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er wyf and certeyn day by day</L>
<L>And eek &thorn;e popes rancour for to slake</L>
<L N="803">Consentith it &thorn;at dar I vndertake</L>
<L>And trewely &thorn;us moche I wol &yogh;ow say</L>
<L N="805">My newe wif is comyng by &thorn;e way</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="806">Be strong of hert and voyde anoon hir place</L>
<L>And &thorn;ilke dower &thorn;at &yogh;e broughten me</L>
<L>Tak it agayn I graunt it of my grace
<PB REF="00000300.tif" N="288"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="429"></L>
<L>Retourneth to &yogh;our fadres hous quod he</L>
<L N="810">No man may alway haue prosperite</L>
<L>with euen hert I rede &yogh;ow endure</L>
<L N="812">The strok of fortune or of aduenture</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="813">And sche agayn answerd in pacience</L>
<L>My lord quod sche I wot and wist/ alway</L>
<L>how &thorn;at bitwixe &yogh;our magnificence</L>
<L>And my pouerte no wight can ne may</L>
<L N="817">Make comparisoun it is no nay</L>
<L>&para; I. ne held me neuer digne in no manere</L>
<L N="819">To ben &yogh;our wyf ne &yogh;it &yogh;our Chamberere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="820">And in &thorn;is hous &thorn;er &yogh;e me lady made /</L>
<L>The highe god take I for my witnesse</L>
<L>And al so wisly he my soule glade</L>
<L>I neuer huld me lady ne maistresse /<MILESTONE N="127b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="824">But humble seruaunt to &yogh;our worthinesse</L>
<L>And euer schal whil &thorn;at/ my lyf may dure</L>
<L N="826">Abouen euery worldly creature</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="827">That &yogh;e so longe of &yogh;our benignite</L>
<L>han holden me in honour and nobleye</L>
<L>wher as I was not worthy for to be</L>
<L>That &thorn;onk I god and &yogh;ow to whom I preye</L>
<L N="831">For&yogh;eld it &yogh;ow &thorn;er is more to seye</L>
<L>vnto my fader gladly wil I wende</L>
<L N="833">And with him duelle vnto my lyues ende /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="834">Ther I was fostred as a child ful smal</L>
<L>Til I be deed my lyf ther wil I lede</L>
<L>A widow clene in body hert and al</L>
<L>For sith I &yogh;af to &yogh;ow my maydenhede</L>
<L N="838">And am &yogh;our trewe wyf it is no drede</L>
<L>God schilde such a lordes wyf to take</L>
<L N="840">Ano&thorn;er man to housbond or to make
<PB REF="00000301.tif" N="289"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="430"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="841">And of &yogh;our newe wif. god of his grace</L>
<L>So graunte &yogh;ow. wele and prosperite</L>
<L>For I wol gladly &yogh;elden hir my place</L>
<L>I which &thorn;at I was blisful wont to be</L>
<L N="845">For sith it liketh &yogh;ow my lord quod sche</L>
<L>That whilom were al myn hertes reste</L>
<L N="847">That I schal gon. I wil go whan &yogh;ow leste</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="848">But &thorn;er as &yogh;e profre me such dowayre /</L>
<L>As I ferst brought. it is wel in my mynde</L>
<L>It were my wrecchid clo&thorn;es no &thorn;ing faire</L>
<L>&THORN;e whiche to me were hard now for to fynde</L>
<L N="852">O goode god. how gentil and how kynde</L>
<L>&YOGH;e semed by &yogh;our speche and &yogh;our visage</L>
<L N="854">That day &thorn;at maked was our mariage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="855">But so&thorn; is sayd algate I fynd it trewe /</L>
<L>For in effect. it/ proued is on me</L>
<L>loue is nought old. as whan &thorn;at it is newe/</L>
<L>But certes lord for noon aduersite /</L>
<L N="859">To deyen in &thorn;e caas it schal not be /</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer in word or werk I schal repente</L>
<L N="861">That I &yogh;ow &yogh;af myn hert in hol entente<MILESTONE N="128a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="862">My lord &yogh;e wot &thorn;at in my fadres place</L>
<L>&YOGH;e dede me strippe out of my pore wede</L>
<L>And richely me cladden of &yogh;our grace</L>
<L>To &yogh;ow brought I nought elles out of drede</L>
<L N="866">But faith and mekenes and maydenhede /</L>
<L>And her agayn my clo&thorn;yng I restore</L>
<L N="868">And eek my weddyng ryng for euermore</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="869">The remenant of &yogh;our jewels redy be /</L>
<L>wi&thorn;in &yogh;our chambur dore dar I saufly sayn</L>
<L>Naked out of my fadres hous quod sche /</L>
<L>I com and naked moot I torne agayn
<PB REF="00000302.tif" N="290"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="431"></L>
<L N="873">Al &yogh;our pleisauns. wold I fulfille fayn</L>
<L>But &yogh;it I hope it be not &yogh;oure entent</L>
<L N="875">That I smocles out of &yogh;our chambre went</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="876">&YOGH;e cou&thorn;e not doon so dishonest a &thorn;ing</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ilke wombe in which &yogh;our children leye</L>
<L>Schulde byforn &thorn;e poeple in my walkyng</L>
<L>Be seye al bare wher-fore I &yogh;ow pray</L>
<L N="880">let me not lik a worm go by &thorn;e way /</L>
<L>Remembre &yogh;ow myn oughne lord so deere /</L>
<L N="882">I was &yogh;our wyf. &thorn;ough I vnwor&thorn;y were</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="883">Wherfor in guerdoun of my maydenhede</L>
<L>which &thorn;at I brought and nought agayn I bere</L>
<L>As voucheth sauf. as &yogh;eue me to my meede</L>
<L>Such a smok as I was wont to were</L>
<L N="887">That I &thorn;er with may wrye &thorn;e wombe of here /</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &yogh;our wif and here take I my leue</L>
<L N="889">Of &yogh;ow myn oughne lord. lest I &yogh;ow greue</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="890">The smok quod he &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast on &thorn;y bak</L>
<L>let it be stille and ber it for&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L>But wel vnnethes &thorn;ilke word he spak</L>
<L>But went his way for routhe and for pite</L>
<L N="894">Byforn &thorn;e folk hir seluen strippith sche /</L>
<L>And in hir smok. wi&thorn; heed and foot al bare</L>
<L N="896">Toward hir fader house forth is sche fare</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="897">The folk hir folwen wepyng in hir weye</L>
<L>And fortune ay &thorn;ay cursen as &thorn;ay goon</L>
<L>But/ sche fro wepyng kept hir eyen dreye<MILESTONE N="128b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ne in &thorn;is tyme word ne spak sche noon</L>
<L N="901">hir fader &thorn;at &thorn;is tyding herd anoon</L>
<L>Cursed &thorn;e day and tyme &thorn;at nature</L>
<L N="903">Schoop him to ben a lyues creature
<PB REF="00000303.tif" N="291"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="432"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="904">For out of doute &thorn;is olde &thorn;ore man</L>
<L>was euer in suspect of hir mariage</L>
<L>For euer he deemed sith &thorn;at it bigan</L>
<L>That whan &thorn;e lord fulfilled had his corrage</L>
<L N="908">him wolde &thorn;inke &thorn;at it were disparage</L>
<L>To his estate . so lowe for to light</L>
<L N="910">And voyden hire as sone as euer he might</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="911">Agayns his doughter hastily quod he</L>
<L>For he by noyse of folk knew hir comyng</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; hir olde cote as it might be /</L>
<L>he couered hir ful sorwfully wepynge</L>
<L N="915">But on hir body might he it nou&yogh;t bringe</L>
<L>For rude was &thorn;e cloth . and sche mor of age</L>
<L N="917">By deyes fele . &thorn;an hir mariage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="918">Thus with hir fader for a certeyn space</L>
<L>Dwellith &thorn;is flour of wifly pacience</L>
<L>That neyther by her wordes ne by hir face</L>
<L>Byforn &thorn;e folk nor eek in her absence</L>
<L N="922">Ne schewed sche that hir was doon offence</L>
<L>Ne of hir highe astaat no remembraunce</L>
<L N="924">Ne hadde sche . as by hir countenaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="925">No wonder is for in hir gret estate</L>
<L>hir gost was euer in playn humilite</L>
<L>Ne tender mouth noon herte delicate</L>
<L>Ne pompe . ne semblant of realte</L>
<L N="929">But ful of pacient benignite</L>
<L>Discrete and prideles ay honurable /</L>
<L N="931">And to hir housbond euer meke &middot; and stable</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="932">Men speke of Iob . and most for his humblesse /&middot;</L>
<L>As clerkes whan hem lust can wel endite</L>
<L>Namely of men . but as in sothfastnesse</L>
<L>&THORN;ough clerkes prayse wommen but a lite
<PB REF="00000304.tif" N="292"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="433"></L>
<L N="936">&THORN;er can no man in humblesse him acquyte</L>
<L>As wommen can . ne can be half so trewe<MILESTONE N="129a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="938">As wommen ben . but it be falle of newe<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="939">Fro boloyne is &thorn;is erl of panik y-come</L>
<L>Of which &thorn;e fame vp sprong to more and lasse</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e poeples eeres alle and some</L>
<L>was couth eek &thorn;at a newe marquisesse</L>
<L N="943">he wi&thorn; him brought in such pomp and richesse</L>
<L>That neuer was &thorn;er seyn with mannes ye</L>
<L N="945">So noble array in al west lombardye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="946">The marquys which &thorn;at schoop and knew al &thorn;is</L>
<L>Er &thorn;at &thorn;is erl was come sent his message /</L>
<L>After &thorn;ilk cely pore Grisildis</L>
<L>And sche wi&thorn; humble hert and good visage</L>
<L N="950">Not with so swollen hert in hir corrage</L>
<L>Cam at his hest . and on hir knees hir sette</L>
<L N="952">And reuerently and wyfly sche him grette</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="953">Grisild quod he . my wil is outrely</L>
<L>This mayden &thorn;at schal weddid be to me</L>
<L>Receyued be to morwe as really</L>
<L>As it possible is in myn hous to be</L>
<L N="957">And eek &thorn;at euery wight in his degre</L>
<L>haue his estaat in sittyng and seruyse</L>
<L N="959">In high plesaunce as I can deuyse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="960">I haue no womman suffisant certeyne</L>
<L>The chambres for tarray in ordinance</L>
<L>After my lust and &thorn;erfor wold I feyne /</L>
<L>That &thorn;in were al such maner gouernaunce</L>
<L N="964">Thow knowest/ eek of al my plesaunce</L>
<L>Though &thorn;yn array be badde and ille byseye</L>
<L N="966">Do &thorn;ou &thorn;y deuer atte leste weye
<PB REF="00000305.tif" N="293"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="434"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="967">Nought oonly lord &thorn;at I am glad quod sche /</L>
<L>To don &yogh;our lust . but I desire also /</L>
<L>&YOGH;ow for to serue and plese in my degre</L>
<L>wi&thorn;oute feynyng and schal euer mo</L>
<L N="971">Ne neuer for no wele ne for no wo</L>
<L>Ne schal &thorn;e gost wi&thorn;inne myn herte stente /</L>
<L N="973">To loue &yogh;ow best wi&thorn; al my trewe entent</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="974">And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word sche gan &thorn;e hous to dight</L>
<L>And tables for to sette and beddes make<MILESTONE N="129b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And peyned hir to doon al &thorn;at sche might</L>
<L>Preying &thorn;e chamberers for goddes sake</L>
<L N="978">To hasten hem and faste swepe and schake</L>
<L>And sche &thorn;e moste seruisable of alle /</L>
<L N="980">ha&thorn; euery chamber arrayed and his halle /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="981">Abouten vndern gan &thorn;is lord alight</L>
<L>&THORN;at with him brought &thorn;ese noble children tweye</L>
<L>For which &thorn;e peple ran to se &thorn;at sight</L>
<L>Of her array so richely biseye</L>
<L N="985">And &thorn;an at erst amonges hem &thorn;ay seye</L>
<L>That walter was no for&thorn; &thorn;ough that him lest</L>
<L N="987">To chaunge his wyf . for it was for &thorn;e best /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="988">For sche is fairer . as &thorn;ay demen alle /</L>
<L>Than is Grisild and more tender of age</L>
<L>And fairer fruyt bitwen hem schulde falle</L>
<L>And more plesaunt for hir high lynage</L>
<L N="992">hir bro&thorn;er eek . so fair was of visage</L>
<L>That hem to seen &thorn;e peple ha&thorn; caught plesaunce</L>
<L N="994">Comending now &thorn;e marquys gouernaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="995">O stormy poeple . vnsad and euer vntrewe</L>
<L>And vndiscret and chaungyng as a fane</L>
<L>Desyryng euer in rombel &thorn;at is newe</L>
<L>For lik &thorn;e moone ay wax &yogh;e and wane
<PB REF="00000306.tif" N="294"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="435"></L>
<L N="999">Ay ful of clappyng dere ynough a Iane</L>
<L>&yogh;oure doom is fals &yogh;our constaunce yuel preuith</L>
<L N="1001">A ful gret fool is he that on &yogh;ow leeuith</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1002">Thus sayde saad folk in &thorn;at Citee</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at &thorn;e poeple gased vp and doun</L>
<L>For &thorn;ay were glad right of &thorn;e nouelte</L>
<L>To han a newe lady of her toun</L>
<L N="1006">No more of &thorn;is now make I mencioun</L>
<L>But to Grisildes agayn wol I me dresse</L>
<L N="1008">And telle hir constance and hir busynesse /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1009">Ful busy was grisild in euery &thorn;ing</L>
<L>That to &thorn;e feste was appertinent</L>
<L>Right nought was sche abaissht of hir clo&thorn;ing</L>
<L>Though it were ruyde . and som del eek torent</L>
<L N="1013">But wi&thorn; glad cheer to &thorn;e &yogh;ate is sche went<MILESTONE N="130a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>with o&thorn;er folk to griete &thorn;e marquisesse</L>
<L N="1015">And after &thorn;at doth forth hir busynesse /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1016">With so glad chier his gestes sche receyueth</L>
<L>And so connyngly euerich in his degre /</L>
<L>That no defaute no man aparceyueth</L>
<L>But ay &thorn;ay wondren what sche mighte be</L>
<L N="1020">That in so pouer array was for to se</L>
<L>And cou&thorn;e such honour and reuerence</L>
<L N="1022">And worthily &thorn;ay prayse hir prudence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1023">In al &thorn;is mene while sche ne stent</L>
<L>This mayde and eek hir brother to comende</L>
<L>with al hir hert . in ful buxom entent</L>
<L>So wel &thorn;at no man cou&thorn;e hir pris amende</L>
<L N="1027">But atte last whan &thorn;at &thorn;ese lordes wende</L>
<L>To sitte doun to mete he gan to calle /</L>
<L N="1029">Grisild as sche was busy in his halle
<PB REF="00000307.tif" N="295"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="436"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1030">Grisyld quod he as it were in his play</L>
<L>how likith &thorn;e my wif and hir beaute</L>
<L>Right wel my lord quod sche for in good fay</L>
<L>A fairer saugh I neuer noon &thorn;an sche</L>
<L N="1034">I pray to god &yogh;iue hir prosperite</L>
<L>And so hope I . &thorn;at he wol to &yogh;ow sende</L>
<L N="1036">Plesaunce ynough vnto &yogh;our lyues ende /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1037">On &thorn;ing warn I &yogh;ow and biseke also /</L>
<L>That &yogh;e ne prike wi&thorn; no tormentynge</L>
<L>&THORN;is tendre mayden as &yogh;e haue do mo</L>
<L>For sche is fostrid in hir norischinge</L>
<L N="1041">More tendrely and to my supposynge /</L>
<L>Sche cou&thorn;e not aduersite endure</L>
<L N="1043">As cou&thorn;e a pore fostrid creature</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1044">And whan &thorn;is walter saugh hir pacience</L>
<L>hir glade cheer and no malice at al</L>
<L>And he so oft had doon to hir offence</L>
<L>And sche ay sad . and constant as a wal</L>
<L N="1048">Continuyng euer hir Innocence oueral</L>
<L>This sturdy marquys gan his herte dresse</L>
<L N="1050">To Rewen vpon hir wyfly stedefastnesse /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1051">This is ynough Grisilde myn quod he<MILESTONE N="130b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Be now no more agast ne yuel apayed</L>
<L>I haue thy faith and &thorn;y benignite</L>
<L>As wel as euer womman was assayed</L>
<L N="1055">In gret estate and propreliche arrayed</L>
<L>Now knowe I dere wyf &thorn;y stedefastnesse</L>
<L N="1057">And hir in armes took and gan hir kesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1058">And sche for wonder took of it no keepe</L>
<L>Sche herde not what &thorn;ing he to hir sayde</L>
<L>Sche ferd as sche had stert out of a sleepe</L>
<L>Til sche out of hir masidnesse abrayde
<PB REF="00000308.tif" N="296"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="437"></L>
<L N="1062">Grisild quod he by god &thorn;at for vs deyde</L>
<L>Thou art my wyf ne noon o&thorn;er I haue</L>
<L N="1064">Ne neuer had as god my soule saue</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1065">This is my doughter which &thorn;ou hast supposed</L>
<L>To be my wif &thorn;at o&thorn;er faithfully</L>
<L>Schal be myn heir as I haue ay purposed</L>
<L>Thow bar hem in &thorn;y body trewely</L>
<L N="1069">At Boloyne haue I kept hem priuely</L>
<L>Tak hem agayn for now maistow not seye</L>
<L N="1071">That &thorn;ou hast lorn noon of &thorn;y children tweye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1072">And folk &thorn;at o&thorn;er weyes han seyd of me</L>
<L>I warn hem wel &thorn;at I haue doon &thorn;is deede</L>
<L>For no malice ne for no cruelte</L>
<L>But for tassaye in &thorn;e &thorn;y wommanhede</L>
<L N="1076">And not to slen my children god forbede</L>
<L>But for to kepe hem priuely and stille</L>
<L N="1078">Til I &thorn;y purpos knowe and al &thorn;y wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1079">Whan sche &thorn;is herd a swoned doun sche fallith</L>
<L>For pitous ioy . and after her swownyng</L>
<L>Sche bothe hir &yogh;onge children to hir callith</L>
<L>And in hir armes pitously wepyng</L>
<L N="1083">Embraseth hem and tenderly kissyng</L>
<L>Ful lik a moder with hir salte teris</L>
<L N="1085">Sche bathis bo&thorn;e hir visage and hir eeris</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O such a pitous &thorn;ing it was to see<NOTE PLACE="marg">[This line is repeated in the MS., but has been scratcht out.]</NOTE></L>
<L>hir swownyng and hir humble vois to heere</L>
<L>Graunt mercy lord . god thank it &yogh;ow quod sche<MILESTONE N="131a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That &yogh;e han kept my children so deere</L>
<L N="1090">Now rek I neuer to be deed right heere</L>
<L>Sith I stond in &yogh;our loue and in &yogh;our grace</L>
<L N="1092">No fors of deth ne whan my spirit pace
<PB REF="00000309.tif" N="297"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="438"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1093">O tender deere . &yogh;onge children myne</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure woful moder wende stedefastly</L>
<L>That cruel houndes or som foul vermyne</L>
<L>had eten &yogh;ow but god of his mercy</L>
<L N="1097">And &yogh;our benigne fader tenderly</L>
<L>hath doon &yogh;ow kept and in &thorn;at same stounde</L>
<L N="1099">Al sodeinly sche swapped doun to grounde /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1100">And in hir swough so sadly holdith sche</L>
<L>hir children tuo . whan sche gan hem tembrace</L>
<L>That with gret sleight and gret difficulte</L>
<L>The children from her am &thorn;ay gonne arace</L>
<L N="1104">O many a teer . o many a pitous face.</L>
<L>Doun ran of hem &thorn;at stooden hir bisyde</L>
<L N="1106">Vnnethe aboute hir mighte &thorn;ay abyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1107">Waltier hir gladith and hir sorwe slakith</L>
<L>Sche rysith vp abaisshed from hir traunce</L>
<L>And euery wight hir ioy and feste makith</L>
<L>Til sche hath caught agayn hir continaunce</L>
<L N="1111">wauter hir doth so faithfully plesaunce</L>
<L>That it was daynte for to see &thorn;e cheere</L>
<L N="1113">Bitwix hem tuo . now &thorn;ay be met in feere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1114">These ladys whan &thorn;at &thorn;ay her tyme say</L>
<L>han taken hir and in to chambre goon</L>
<L>And strippen hir . out of hir rude array</L>
<L>And in a cloth of gold &thorn;at brighte schon</L>
<L N="1118">with a coroun of many a riche stoon</L>
<L>vpon hir heed &thorn;ay in to halle hir brought</L>
<L N="1120">And &thorn;er sche was honoured as hir ought</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1121">Thus hath &thorn;is pitous day a blisful ende</L>
<L>For euery man and womman doth his might</L>
<L>This day in mirth and revel to despende</L>
<L>Til on &thorn;e welken schon &thorn;e sterres bright
<PB REF="00000310.tif" N="298"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="439"></L>
<L N="1125">For more solempne in euery mannes sight</L>
<L>This feste was and gretter of costage<MILESTONE N="131b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1127">Than was &thorn;e reuel of hir mariage /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1128">Ful many a &yogh;er in heigh prosperite</L>
<L>lyuen &thorn;ese tuo in concord and in rest</L>
<L>And richeliche his doughter maried he</L>
<L>vnto a lord on of &thorn;e worthiest</L>
<L N="1132">Of al ytaile and &thorn;anne in pees and rest</L>
<L>His wyues fader in his court he kepith</L>
<L N="1134">Til &thorn;at &thorn;e soule out of his body crepith</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1135">His sone succedith in his heritage</L>
<L>In rest and pees . after his fader day</L>
<L>And fortunat . was eek in mariage</L>
<L>Al put he not his wyf in gret assay</L>
<L N="1139">This world is not so strong it is no nay</L>
<L>As it ha&thorn; ben in olde tymes &yogh;ore</L>
<L N="1141">And herknith what &thorn;is auctor saith &thorn;erfore</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1142">This story is sayd nat for &thorn;at wyues scholde</L>
<L>Folwe Grisild . as in humilite</L>
<L>For it were importable &thorn;ough &thorn;ay wolde</L>
<L>But for &thorn;at euery wight in his degre</L>
<L N="1146">Schulde be constant . in aduersite</L>
<L>As was Grisild . therfore Petrark writeth</L>
<L N="1148">This story which wi&thorn; high stile he enditeth</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1149">For swich a womman was so pacient</L>
<L>vnto a mortal man wel more vs oughte</L>
<L>Receyuen al in gre &thorn;at god vs sent</L>
<L>For gret skil is he proue &thorn;at he wroughte</L>
<L N="1153">But he ne temptith no man &thorn;at he boughte</L>
<L>As saith seint Iame if he his pistil rede</L>
<L N="1155">he prouith folk al day it is no drede
<PB REF="00000311.tif" N="299"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="440"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1156">And suffrith vs as for our exercise</L>
<L>wi&thorn; scharpe scourges of aduersite</L>
<L>Ful ofte to be bete in sondry wise</L>
<L>Nought for to knowe oure wille for certes he</L>
<L N="1160">Er we were born . knew al our frelte</L>
<L>And for oure best is al his gouernaunce</L>
<L N="1162">Leet vs &thorn;anne lyue in vertuous suffraunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1163">But oo word lordes herkneth er I go</L>
<L>It were ful hard to fynde now a dayes<MILESTONE N="132a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As Grisildes in al a toun &thorn;re or tuo</L>
<L>For if &thorn;at &thorn;ay were put to such assayes</L>
<L N="1167">The gold of hem ha&thorn; now so badde alayes</L>
<L>with bras &thorn;at &thorn;ough &thorn;e coyn be fair at ye</L>
<L N="1169">hit wolde ra&thorn;er brest in tuo &thorn;an plye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1170">For which heer for &thorn;e wyues loue of bathe</L>
<L>whos lyf and alle of hir secte god meyntene</L>
<L>In high maistry and elles were it scathe</L>
<L>I wil with lusty herte freisch and grene</L>
<L N="1174">Say &yogh;ow a song to glade . &yogh;ow I wene</L>
<L>And lat vs stynt of ernestful matiere</L>
<L N="1176">herknith my song . &thorn;at saith in &thorn;is manere /<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; Lenvoye . de Chaucer.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1177">GRisild is deed and eek hir pacience</L>
<L>And bothe at oones buried in Itayle</L>
<L N="1179">For whiche I crye in open audience /</L>
<L>No weddid man so hardy be to assayle</L>
<L>his wyues pacience in hope to fynde</L>
<L N="1182">Grisildes for in certeyn he schal fayl
<PB REF="00000312.tif" N="300"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="441"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1183">O noble wyues ful of heigh prudence /</L>
<L>let noon humilite &yogh;our tonges nayle</L>
<L N="1185">Ne lat no clerk haue cause or diligence</L>
<L>To write of &yogh;ow a story of such meruayle /</L>
<L>As of Grisildes pacience and kynde</L>
<L N="1188">Lest Chichiuache &yogh;ow swolwe in hir entraile</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1189">Folwith Ecco &thorn;at holdith no silence</L>
<L>But euer answereth at &thorn;e countretayle</L>
<L N="1191">Be&thorn; nou&yogh;t bydaffed for &yogh;our Innocence</L>
<L>But scharply tak on &yogh;ow &thorn;e gouernayle</L>
<L>Empryntith wel &thorn;is lessoun in &yogh;our mynde</L>
<L N="1194">For comun profyt sith it may auayle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1195">&YOGH;e archewyues stondith at defens</L>
<L>Syn &yogh;e ben strong as is a greet/ Chamayle</L>
<L N="1197">Ne suffre not &thorn;at men &yogh;ow don offens</L>
<L>And sclendre wydewes felle as in batayle</L>
<L>Beth egre as is a Tyger &yogh;ond in Inde</L>
<L N="1200">Ay clappith as a mylle I &yogh;ow counsaile</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1201">Ne drede hem not . do hem no reuerence<MILESTONE N="132b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For &thorn;ough &thorn;in housbond armed be in mayle</L>
<L N="1203">The arwes of &thorn;y crabbid eloquence</L>
<L>Schal perse his brest and eek his aduentayle /</L>
<L>In gelousy I rede eek &thorn;ou him bynde</L>
<L N="1206">And &thorn;ou schalt make him couche as doth a quayle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1207">If &thorn;ou be fair &thorn;er folk ben in presence</L>
<L>Schew &thorn;ou &thorn;y visage and &thorn;in apparaile</L>
<L N="1209">If &thorn;ou be foul be fre of &thorn;y despense</L>
<L>To gete &thorn;e frendes do ay &thorn;y trauayle /</L>
<L>Be ay of chier as light as lef on lynde /</L>
<L N="1212">And let hem care and wepe and wryng and wayle</L>
<TRAILER>Explicit.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000313.tif" N="301"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="442">
<HEAD>&para; here bygynneth &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e marchaundis tale.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WEpyng and wailyng care and o&thorn;er sorwe</L>
<L>I knowe ynough bo&thorn;e on euen &amp; on morwe</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;e marchaund . and so doon o&thorn;er mo</L>
<L N="1216">That weddid ben I trowe &thorn;at it be so</L>
<L>For wel I woot it fareth so with me</L>
<L>I haue a wyf . &thorn;e worste &thorn;at may be</L>
<L>For &thorn;ough &thorn;e feend to hir y-coupled were</L>
<L N="1220">Sche wold him ouer macche I dar wel swere</L>
<L>what schuld I &yogh;ow reherse in special</L>
<L>hir high malice . sche is a schrewe at al</L>
<L>Ther is a long and a large difference</L>
<L N="1224">Betwix Grisildes grete pacience</L>
<L>And of my wyf &thorn;e passyng cruelte</L>
<L>were I vnbounden also mot I the</L>
<L>I wolde neuer eft come in &thorn;e snare</L>
<L N="1228">we weddid men lyue in sorwe and care</L>
<L>Assay who-so wil and he schal fynde /</L>
<L>That I say soth by seint Thomas of Inde</L>
<L>As for &thorn;e more part . I say not alle</L>
<L N="1232">God schilde &thorn;at it scholde so byfalle /</L>
<L>A good sir host . I haue y-weddid be</L>
<L>Thise monthes tuo and more not par de</L>
<L>And &yogh;it I trowe he &thorn;at al his lyue</L>
<L N="1236">wyfles ha&thorn; ben &thorn;ough &thorn;at men wold him riue</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e hert ne cou&thorn;e in no manere /</L>
<L>Tellen so moche sorwe as I now heere<MILESTONE N="133a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Cou&thorn;e telle of my wyfes cursednesse /</L>
<L N="1240">No quod our ost; marchaunt so god &yogh;ow blesse</L>
<L>Sin &yogh;e so moche knowen of &thorn;at art</L>
<L>Ful hertily tellith vs a part</L>
<L>Gladly quod he of myn oughne sore</L>
<L N="1244">For sory hert I telle may na more<NOTE PLACE="end">[No gap in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000314.tif" N="302">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="443">
<P>&para; Narrat</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whilom &thorn;er was duellyng in lombardy</L>
<L>A wor&thorn;y knight &thorn;at born was of pauy</L>
<L>In which he lyued in gret prosperite</L>
<L N="1248">And fourty &yogh;er . a wifles man was he</L>
<L>And folwed ay his bodily delyt</L>
<L>On wommen . ther was his appetyt</L>
<L>As doon &thorn;ese fooles &thorn;at/ ben seculere</L>
<L N="1252">And whan &thorn;at he was passed fourty &yogh;ere</L>
<L>were it for holyness or for dotage</L>
<L>I can not say . but such a gret corrage</L>
<L>hadde &thorn;is knight . to ben a weddid man</L>
<L N="1256">That day and night . he do&thorn; al &thorn;at he can</L>
<L>Taspye wher &thorn;at he mighte weddid be</L>
<L>Praying our lord to graunte him &thorn;at he</L>
<L>Might oones knowen of &thorn;at blisful lif</L>
<L N="1260">&THORN;at is bitwix an housbond and his wyf</L>
<L>And for to lyue vnder &thorn;at holy bond</L>
<L>with which god first . man to womman bond</L>
<L>Noon o&thorn;er lif said he is worth a bene</L>
<L N="1264">For wedlok is so holy and so clene</L>
<L>That in &thorn;is world it is a paradis</L>
<L>Thus sayd &thorn;is olde knight &thorn;at was so wys</L>
<L>And certeinly as soth as god is king</L>
<L N="1268">To take a wyf . is a glorious &thorn;ing/</L>
<L>And namely whan a man is old and hoor</L>
<L>Than is a wyf &thorn;e fruyt of his tresor</L>
<L>Than schuld he take a &yogh;ong wif and a fair</L>
<L N="1272">On which he might engendre him an hair
<PB REF="00000315.tif" N="303"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="444"></L>
<L>And lede his lyf in mirthe and in solace</L>
<L>wher as &thorn;ese bachileres synge allas</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ay fynde eny aduersite</L>
<L N="1276">In loue which is but childes vanite<MILESTONE N="133b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And trewely it sit wel to be so</L>
<L>That bachilers haue ofte peyne and wo</L>
<L>On brutil ground &thorn;ay bulde brutelnesse /</L>
<L N="1280">&THORN;ay fynde whan &thorn;ay wene sikernesse</L>
<L>Thay lyue but as a brid o&thorn;er as a best</L>
<L>In liberte and vnder noon arrest</L>
<L>Ther as a weddid man in his estate</L>
<L N="1284">lyuith his lif busily and ordinate</L>
<L>vnder &thorn;e &yogh;ok of mariage I-bounde</L>
<L>wel may his herte in ioye and blisse abounde /</L>
<L>For who can be so buxom as a wyf /</L>
<L N="1288">who is so trewe and eek so ententyf</L>
<L>To kepe him seek and hool as is his make</L>
<L>For wele or woo sche wol him not forsake /</L>
<L>Sche is not wery him to loue and serue</L>
<L N="1292">Theigh &thorn;at he lay bedred. til &thorn;at he sterue</L>
<L>And &yogh;et som clerkes seyn it is not so</L>
<L>Of whiche theofrast/ is oon of &thorn;o</L>
<L>what fors &thorn;ough theofrast. liste lye</L>
<L N="1296">Ne take no wif quod he for housbondrye</L>
<L>As for to spare in houshold &thorn;y dispense</L>
<L>A trewe seruaunt doth more diligence</L>
<L>&THORN;y good to kepe &thorn;an &thorn;in oughne wif /</L>
<L N="1300">For sche wol clayme half part in al hir lif</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at &thorn;ou be seek so god me saue</L>
<L>&THORN;yne verray frendes or a trewe knaue</L>
<L>wol kepe &thorn;e bet&middot; &thorn;an sche &thorn;at waytith ay</L>
<L N="1304">After &thorn;y good and hath doon many day</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at &thorn;ou take a wif be war</L>
<L>Of oon peril. which declare I ne dar.</L>
<L>This entent and an hundrid si&thorn;e wors</L>
<L N="1308">writith &thorn;is Mas ther god his bones curs
<PB REF="00000316.tif" N="304"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="445"></L>
<L>But take no keep of al such vanite</L>
<L>Deffy theofrast and herkne me</L>
<L>A wyf is goddes &yogh;ifte verrayly</L>
<L N="1312">Al o&thorn;er maner &yogh;iftes hardily</L>
<L>As landes rentes pasture or comune</L>
<L>Or o&thorn;er moeblis ben &yogh;iftes of fortune<MILESTONE N="134a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That passen as a schadow on a wal</L>
<L N="1316">But dred not/ if I playnly telle schal</L>
<L>A wyf wil last and in &thorn;in hous endure</L>
<L>wel lenger &thorn;an &thorn;e lust/ par aduenture</L>
<L>Mariage is a ful gret sacrament</L>
<L N="1320">he which ha&thorn; no wif I hold him schent</L>
<L>he lyueth helples. and is al desolate</L>
<L>I speke of folk/ in seculer estate</L>
<L>And herken why I say not &thorn;is for nought</L>
<L N="1324">The womman is for mannes help I-wrought</L>
<L>The heighe god whan he had adam maked</L>
<L>And saugh him aloone body naked</L>
<L>God of his grete goodnes sayde &thorn;anne</L>
<L N="1328">Let vs now make an helpe to &thorn;is manne</L>
<L>lyk to himself/. and &thorn;an he made Eue</L>
<L>her may &yogh;e see. and here may &yogh;e preue</L>
<L>That wyf is mannes help and his comfort</L>
<L N="1332">his paradis terrestre and his desport</L>
<L>So buxom and so vertuous is sche /</L>
<L>Thay mosten neede lyue in vnite.</L>
<L>O fleisch &thorn;ay ben. and on blood as I gesse</L>
<L N="1336">haue but oon hert. in wele and in distresse /</L>
<L>&there4; A wyf; a seinte mary benedicite</L>
<L>how might a man haue eny aduersite</L>
<L>That ha&thorn; a wyf. certes I can not say</L>
<L N="1340">The ioye &thorn;at is betwixen hem tway</L>
<L>Ther may no tonge telle ne herte &thorn;ink</L>
<L>If he be pore sche helpith him to swynk</L>
<L>Sche kepith his good and wastith neuer a del</L>
<L N="1344">And al &thorn;at her housbond list. sche likith it wel
<PB REF="00000317.tif" N="305"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="446"></L>
<L>Sche saith nought oones nay whan he saith &yogh;e</L>
<L>Do &thorn;is saith he. al redy sir saith sche</L>
<L>O blisful ordre o wedlok precious</L>
<L N="1348">Thou art so mery and ek so vertuous</L>
<L>And so comendid and approued eek</L>
<L>That euery man &thorn;at holt him worth a leek</L>
<L>vpon his bare knees ought al his lyf</L>
<L N="1352">Thanken his god &thorn;at him ha&thorn; sent a wif<MILESTONE N="134b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Or pray to god oon him for to sende</L>
<L>To be with him vnto his lyues ende /</L>
<L>For &thorn;an his lyf is set in sikernesse /</L>
<L N="1356">he may not be deceyued as I gesse /</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he worche after his wyfes red</L>
<L>&THORN;an may be boldely bere vp his heed</L>
<L>Thay ben so trewe and also so wyse</L>
<L N="1360">For whiche if &thorn;ou wolt do as &thorn;e wyse</L>
<L>Do alway so &thorn;e womman wol &thorn;e rede</L>
<L>lo how &thorn;at Iacob as &thorn;e clerkes rede</L>
<L>By good counseil of his moder Rebecke</L>
<L N="1364">Band &thorn;e kydes skyn about his sones nekke</L>
<L>For which his fader benesoun he wan</L>
<L>Lo Iudith as &thorn;e story telle can</L>
<L>By wys counseil sche goddes poepel kept</L>
<L N="1368">And slough him oliphernus whil he slept</L>
<L>Lo abygaille by good counseil how sche /</L>
<L>Sauyd hir housbond Nacab whan &thorn;at he /</L>
<L>Schold han ben slayn And loke after also</L>
<L N="1372">By good counseil deliuered out of wo;</L>
<L>&THORN;e poeple of god. and made him mandoche</L>
<L>Of Assure enhaunsed for to be</L>
<L>Ther nys no &thorn;ing / in gre superlatif</L>
<L N="1376">As saith Senec aboue an humble wyf</L>
<L>Suffre &thorn;y wyues tonge as Catoun byt</L>
<L>She schal comaunde and &thorn;ou schalt suffre it</L>
<L>And &yogh;it sche wil obeye of curtesye</L>
<L N="1380">A wif is keper of &thorn;in housbondrye
<PB REF="00000318.tif" N="306"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="447"></L>
<L>wel may &thorn;e sike man wayle and wepe</L>
<L>Ther as &thorn;er is no wyf &thorn;e hous to kepe</L>
<L>I warne &thorn;e if wisly &thorn;ou wilt wirche</L>
<L N="1384">loue wel &thorn;y wyf as crist doth his chirche</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou louest &thorn;iself &thorn;ou louest &thorn;y wyf /</L>
<L>No man hatith his fleissch but in his lif /</L>
<L>he fostrith it and &thorn;erfore warne I &thorn;e</L>
<L N="1388">Cherissh &thorn;y wif. or &thorn;ou schalt neuer the</L>
<L>housbond &amp; wif what men iape or pleye</L>
<L>Of worldly folk holden &thorn;e righte weye<MILESTONE N="135a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Thay ben so knyt &thorn;er may noon harm bytyde</L>
<L N="1392">And nameliche vpon &thorn;e wyues syde</L>
<L>For which &thorn;is Ianuary of which I tolde</L>
<L>Considered hath Inwith his dayes olde /</L>
<L>The lusty lif the vertuous quiete</L>
<L N="1396">That is in mariage hony-swete</L>
<L>&para; And for his frendes on a day he sent</L>
<L>To tellen hem theffect of his entent</L>
<L>wi&thorn; face sad. he ha&thorn; hem this tale told</L>
<L N="1400">he sayde frendes I am hoor and old</L>
<L>And almost god woot at my pittes brinke</L>
<L>vpon my soule som what most I &thorn;ynke</L>
<L>I haue my body folily dispendid</L>
<L N="1404">Blessed be god that I schal be amendid</L>
<L>For I wil be certeyn a weddid man</L>
<L>And &thorn;at anoon in al &thorn;e hast I can</L>
<L>vnto som mayde fair and tender of age /</L>
<L N="1408">I pray &yogh;ow helpith for my mariage</L>
<L>Al sodeynly. for I wil not abyde</L>
<L>I wil fonde tespien on my syde</L>
<L>To whom I may be weddid hastily</L>
<L N="1412">But for als moche as &yogh;e ben mo than I.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e schul rather such a &thorn;ing aspien</L>
<L>&THORN;an I and wher me lust best to allien</L>
<L>But oo &thorn;ing warne I &yogh;ow my frendes deere /</L>
<L N="1416">I wil noon old wyf haue in no manere /
<PB REF="00000319.tif" N="307"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="448"></L>
<L>Sche schal not passe &middot; sixtene &yogh;er certayn</L>
<L>Old fleisch and &yogh;ong fleisch &thorn;at wold I haue ful fayn</L>
<L>Bet is quod he a pyk &thorn;an a pikerell</L>
<L N="1420">And bet &thorn;an olde boef is tendre vel</L>
<L>I wil no womman twenty &yogh;er of age</L>
<L>It nys but bene straw and gret forage</L>
<L>And eek &thorn;ese olde wydewes god it woot</L>
<L N="1424">Thay can so moche craft of wades boot</L>
<L>So moche broken harm whan &thorn;at hem list</L>
<L>That wi&thorn; hem schuld I neuer lyuen in rest</L>
<L>For sondry scolis maken subtil clerkes</L>
<L N="1428">womman of many a skile half a clerk is<MILESTONE N="135b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But certeyn a &yogh;ong &thorn;ing may men gye</L>
<L>Right as men may warm wax with hondes plye</L>
<L>wher for I say &yogh;ow plenerly in a clause</L>
<L N="1432">I wil noon old wyf han right for &thorn;at cause</L>
<L>For if so were I hadde so meschaunce</L>
<L>&THORN;at I in hir cou&thorn;e haue no plesaunce</L>
<L>Than schuld I lede my lyf in aduoutrie</L>
<L N="1436">And go streight to &thorn;e deuel whan I dye.</L>
<L>Ne children schuld I noon vpon hir geten</L>
<L>&YOGH;et were me leuer houndes had me eten</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;at myn heritage schulde falle</L>
<L N="1440">In straunge hond and &thorn;us I telle &yogh;ow alle</L>
<L>I doute not. I wot &thorn;e cause why</L>
<L>Men scholde wedde. and for&thorn;ermor woot I</L>
<L>Ther spekith many man of mariage</L>
<L N="1444">That wot nomore of it &thorn;an wot my page</L>
<L>For whiche causes. man schuld take a wyf</L>
<L>If he ne may not chast be by his lif</L>
<L>Take him a wif with gret deuocioun</L>
<L N="1448">By cause of lawful procreacioun</L>
<L>Of children to &thorn;onour of god aboue</L>
<L>And not oonly for paramour and for loue.</L>
<L>And for &thorn;ay schulde leccherye eschiewe</L>
<L N="1452">And &yogh;eld oure dettes whan &thorn;at it is due
<PB REF="00000320.tif" N="308"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="449"></L>
<L>Or for &thorn;at ilk man schulde helpen o&thorn;er</L>
<L>In meschief as suster schal to &thorn;e bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>And lyue in chastite ful heuenly</L>
<L N="1456">But sires by &yogh;our leue &thorn;at am not I</L>
<L>For by &thorn;anked I dar make auaunt</L>
<L>I fele my lemys stark and suffisaunt</L>
<L>To doon al &thorn;at a man bilongeth vnto</L>
<L N="1460">I wot my selue best what I may do</L>
<L>&para; Though I be hoor I fare as do&thorn; a tree<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota</NOTE></L>
<L>That blossemith er &thorn;at &thorn;e fruyt I-waxe be</L>
<L>A blossemy tre is neither drye ne deed</L>
<L N="1464">I fele me no-wher hoor but on myn heed</L>
<L>Myn herte and my lymes ben as greene.</L>
<L>As laurer &thorn;urgh &thorn;e &yogh;eer is for to seene<MILESTONE N="136a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And synnes &yogh;e han herd al myn entent</L>
<L N="1468">I pray &yogh;ow to my wille &yogh;e assent</L>
<L>Diuerse men diuersly him tolde</L>
<L>Of mariage many ensamples olde</L>
<L>Some blamed him some praised it certayn</L>
<L N="1472">But atte laste schortly for to sayn</L>
<L>As alday fallith altercacioun</L>
<L>Bitwixe frendes in despitesoun</L>
<L>Ther fel a strif bitwen his bretheren tuo<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota</NOTE></L>
<L N="1476">Of which &thorn;at oon was clepid Placebo</L>
<L>Iustinus so&thorn;ly cleped was &thorn;at o&thorn;er</L>
<L>Placebo sayde .o. Ianuary bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>Ful litel need had &yogh;e my lord so deere</L>
<L N="1480">Counseil to axe of eny &thorn;at is heere</L>
<L>But &thorn;at &yogh;e ben so ful of sapience</L>
<L>That &yogh;ow ne likith for &yogh;our heigh prudence /</L>
<L>To wayue fro &thorn;e word of Salamon</L>
<L N="1484">This word said he vnto vs euerychoon</L>
<L>werk/ al &thorn;ing by counsail &thorn;us sayd he /</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne schaltow nought repente &thorn;e</L>
<L>But &thorn;ough &thorn;at Salamon speke such a word</L>
<L N="1488">Myn owne deere bro&thorn;er and my lord
<PB REF="00000321.tif" N="309"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="450"></L>
<L>So wisly god bring my soule at ese and rest</L>
<L>I holde &yogh;our oughne counseil is &thorn;e best/</L>
<L>For bro&thorn;er myn of me tak &thorn;is motif</L>
<L N="1492">I haue now ben a court man al my lyf</L>
<L>And god wot &thorn;ough. &thorn;at I vnwor&thorn;y be</L>
<L>I haue standen in ful gret degre</L>
<L>Abouten lordes in ful gret estat</L>
<L N="1496">&YOGH;it had I neuer with noon of hem debaat</L>
<L>I neuer hem contraried trewely</L>
<L>I wot wel &thorn;at my lord can more &thorn;an I</L>
<L>what &thorn;at he saith I hold it ferm and stable</L>
<L N="1500">I say &thorn;e same or elles &thorn;ing semblable</L>
<L>A ful gret fool is eny counselour<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at seruith any lord of high honour</L>
<L>&THORN;at dar presume or oones &thorn;enken it /</L>
<L N="1504">That his counseil schuld passe his lordes wit<MILESTONE N="136b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Nay lordes ben no fooles by my fay</L>
<L>&YOGH;e haue &yogh;our self y-spoken heer to day</L>
<L>So heigh sentens so holly and so wel</L>
<L N="1508">&THORN;at I consente and conferme euery del</L>
<L>&YOGH;our wordes alle. and &yogh;oure oppinioun</L>
<L>By god &thorn;er is no man in al &thorn;is toun</L>
<L>Ne in ytaile cou&thorn;e better haue sayd</L>
<L N="1512">Crist holdith him of &thorn;is ful wel a-payd</L>
<L>And trewely it is an heigh corrage</L>
<L>Of any man &thorn;at stopen is in age /</L>
<L>To take a &yogh;ong wyf by my fader kyn</L>
<L N="1516">&YOGH;our herte hongith on a ioly pyn</L>
<L>Doth now in &thorn;is matier right as &yogh;ow lest</L>
<L>For fynally I hold it for &thorn;e best</L>
<L>Iustinus &thorn;at ay stille sat and herde /</L>
<L N="1520">Right in &thorn;is wise he to placebo answerde /</L>
<L>Now brother myn be pacient I &yogh;ow pray</L>
<L>Syns &yogh;e haue sayd. and herknith what I say</L>
