<TRAILER>Explicit prima pars //<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Incipit secunda pars</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The norice of digestioun &thorn;e sleep</L>
<L N="348">Gan to him wynk and bad of him take keep</L>
<L>That merthe and labour wol haue his reste</L>
<L>with a galpyng mouth he him keste</L>
<L>And sayd &thorn;at it was tyme to lye doun<MILESTONE N="153b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="352">For blood was in his dominacioun</L>
<L>Cherische&thorn; natures &thorn;anne quod he</L>
<L>They &thorn;ankyn him galpyng by two and &thorn;re</L>
<L>And euery wight gan drawe him to his rest</L>
<L N="356">As sleep hem bad &thorn;ey took it for &thorn;e best/
<PB REF="00000359.tif" N="347"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="489"></L>
<L>here dremes schul not now be told for me</L>
<L>Ful were here heedes of fumosite</L>
<L>That cause&thorn; drem of which &thorn;er is no charge /</L>
<L N="360">They slepen til it was prime large /</L>
<L>The moste part but it were Canace</L>
<L>Sche was ful mesurable as wommen be</L>
<L>For of hir fader ha&thorn; sche take hir leue</L>
<L N="364">To go to reste soon after it was eue /</L>
<L>hir luste not appalled for to be</L>
<L>Ne on &thorn;e morwe vnfestly for to se /</L>
<L>And kept hir firste sleep and &thorn;an awook</L>
<L N="368">For such a Ioye sche in herte took</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e of hir queynte ryng and hir myrrour</L>
<L>That twenty tyme chaunged hire colour</L>
<L>And in hire sleep right for impressioun</L>
<L N="372">Of hir myrrour sche had a visioun</L>
<L>wher-for er &thorn;at &thorn;e sonne vp gan glyde /</L>
<L>Sche cleped vpon her maistresse beside /</L>
<L>And sayde &thorn;at hire luste for to ryse</L>
<L N="376">These olde wommen &thorn;at ben gladly wise</L>
<L>As is here maystresse answered hir anoon</L>
<L>And sayd madame whider wold &yogh;e goon</L>
<L>Thus erly for folk ben alle in reste /</L>
<L N="380">I wil quod sche aryse for me leste</L>
<L>No lenger for to slepe and walke aboute</L>
<L>hir maistres clepeth wommen a gret route /</L>
<L>And vp &thorn;ey risen a ten o&thorn;er a twelue</L>
<L N="384">vp ryse&thorn; fresshe Canace hir selue</L>
<L>As rody and bright as is &thorn;e &yogh;onge sonne</L>
<L>That in &thorn;e Ram is ten degrees I-ronne</L>
<L>Non heiher was he<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>first</I>, 'sche']</NOTE> whan sche redy was</L>
<L N="388">And forth sche walked esily a pas</L>
<L>Arayed after &thorn;e lusty sesoun soote<MILESTONE N="154a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>lightly for to play and walke on foote</L>
<L>Nought but wi&thorn; fyue or six of hir meyne</L>
<L N="392">And a trench fer in &thorn;e park go&thorn; sche /
<PB REF="00000360.tif" N="348"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="490"></L>
<L>The vapour which &thorn;at of &thorn;e erthe glod</L>
<L>Make&thorn; &thorn;e sonne seme rody and sot</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles it was so fair a sight</L>
<L N="396">That it made alle here hertes for to light</L>
<L>what for &thorn;e sesoun what for &thorn;e mornyng</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e foules &thorn;at sche herde syng</L>
<L>For right anoon sche wiste what &thorn;ey ment</L>
<L N="400">Right by here song and knew al here entent /</L>
<L>&para; The knotte why &thorn;at euery tale is told</L>
<L>If that it be taryed til lust be cold</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at han hit after herkned &yogh;ore</L>
<L N="404">The sauour passeth euer lenger &thorn;e more</L>
<L>For fulsomnes of &thorn;e prolixite</L>
<L>And by &thorn;is same resoun thinketh me</L>
<L>I schulde to &thorn;e knotte condescende /</L>
<L N="408">And make of hir walkynge sone an ende&middot;</L>
<L>A-myddes a tree for-druye as whit as chalk</L>
<L>As Canace was pleyyng in hir walk</L>
<L>There sat a faukoun ouer hir heed ful hye</L>
<L N="412">&THORN;at with a pitous vois bigan to crye</L>
<L>I-beten hadde sche hir self so pitously</L>
<L>That al the woode resowned of hire cry</L>
<L>wi&thorn; bo&thorn;e hir wynges to &thorn;e reede blood</L>
<L N="416">Ran endelong &thorn;e tree &thorn;er as sche stood</L>
<L>And euer in oon sche cried and schryght</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; hir bek hir selue so sche pight</L>
<L>That &thorn;er nys tigre non ne cruel beste</L>
<L N="420">That dwelle&thorn; ey&thorn;er in wood or in foreste</L>
<L>That nold han wept if &thorn;at he cowde</L>
<L>For sorw of hir sche schright alwey so lowde</L>
<L>For &thorn;er nas neuer &yogh;it no man on lyue</L>
<L N="424">If that he cou&thorn;e a faukoun discriue</L>
<L>That herd of such ano&thorn;er of fairnesse</L>
<L>As wel of plumage as of gentillesse</L>
<L>Of schap of al &thorn;at might I-rekened be<MILESTONE N="154b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="428">A faukoun peregryn &thorn;an semed sche
<PB REF="00000361.tif" N="349"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="491"></L>
<L>Of fremde lond and euer as sche stood</L>
<L>Sche swowned now and now for lak of blood</L>
<L>Til wel neigh sche falle&thorn; fro &thorn;e tre</L>
<L N="432">This faire kynges doughter Canace</L>
<L>That on hir fynger bar &thorn;e queynte ryng</L>
<L>Thurgh which sche vnderstood wel euery &thorn;ing</L>
<L>That eny foul may in his lydne sayn</L>
<L N="436">And cou&thorn;e answer him in his lydne agayn</L>
<L>ha&thorn; vnderstonde what &thorn;e faukoun seyde</L>
<L>And wel neigh almost for rewthe sche deyde</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e tree sche goth ful hastily</L>
<L N="440">And on &thorn;is faukoun loke&thorn; pitously</L>
<L>And held hir lappe a-brod for wel sche wist</L>
<L>The faukoun moste falle fro &thorn;e twist</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at it swowned next for lak of blood</L>
<L N="444">A long while to wayten hir sche stood</L>
<L>Til atte last sche spak in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e hauk as &yogh;e schul after heere</L>
<L>&para; what is &thorn;e cause if it be for to telle</L>
<L N="448">That &yogh;e ben in &thorn;at furyall peyne of helle</L>
<L>Quod Canace vnto &thorn;is hauk aboue</L>
<L>Is &thorn;is for sorwe of deth or elles loue</L>
<L>For as I trowe &thorn;is ben causes tuo</L>
<L N="452">That causen most a gentil herte wo</L>
<L>Of o&thorn;er harm it neede&thorn; nou&yogh;t to speke</L>
<L>For &yogh;e &yogh;our self vpon &yogh;our self awreke</L>
<L>which &thorn;at preue&thorn; wel &thorn;at either Ire or drede</L>
<L N="456">Mote ben enchesoun of &yogh;our cruel dede</L>
<L>Sith &thorn;at I see noon o&thorn;er wight &yogh;ou chace</L>
<L>For loue of god so do&thorn; &yogh;our selue grace</L>
<L>Or what ben &yogh;our helpe for west ner Este</L>
<L N="460">Ne saugh I neuer er now no bryd ne beste</L>
<L>That ferde with himself so pitously</L>
<L>&YOGH;e sle me with &yogh;our sorwe so verrily</L>
<L>I haue of &yogh;ou so gret compassioun</L>
<L N="464">For goddes loue com fro &thorn;e tree a doun
<PB REF="00000362.tif" N="350"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="492"></L>
<L>And as I am a kynges doughter trewe<MILESTONE N="155a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>If &thorn;at I verrayly &thorn;e cause knewe</L>
<L>Of &yogh;our disese if it lay in my might</L>
<L N="468">I wold amenden it if &thorn;at I might</L>
<L>Als wisly help me grete god of kynde</L>
<L>And herbes schal I right ynowe fynde</L>
<L>To helen with &yogh;our hurtes hastyly</L>
<L N="472">Tho schright &thorn;is faukoun more pitously</L>
<L>Than euer sche did and fil to ground anoon</L>
<L>And lay a-swowne deed as eny stoon</L>
<L>Til Canace hath in hir lap y-take</L>
<L N="476">vnto &thorn;at tyme sche gan of swowne slake /</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at sche gan of swown abreyde</L>
<L>Right in hir haukes lydne thus sche seyde</L>
<L>That pite renneth sone in gentil hert</L>
<L N="480">Felyng his similitude in peynes smerte</L>
<L>Is proued alday as men may see</L>
<L>As wel by werk as by auctorite</L>
<L>For gentil herte kepeth gentillesse /</L>
<L N="484">I see wel &thorn;at &yogh;e haue on my distresse</L>
<L>Compassioun my faire Canace</L>
<L>Of verray wommanly benignite /</L>
<L>That nature in &yogh;our principles ha&thorn; set</L>
<L N="488">But noon hope for to fare &thorn;e bet</L>
<L>But for to obeye vnto &yogh;our herte fre</L>
<L>And for to make othere war by me</L>
<L>As by &thorn;e whelp chastised is &thorn;e lyoun</L>
<L N="492">And for &thorn;at cause and &thorn;at conclusioun</L>
<L>whiles &thorn;at I haue a leyser and a space</L>
<L>Myn harm I wil confessen er I pace</L>
<L>And whil sche euer of hir sorwe tolde</L>
<L N="496">That o&thorn;er wept as sche to water wolde /</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at &thorn;e faucoun bad hir to be stille /</L>
<L>And with a sighhe / &thorn;us sche sayd hir tille</L>
<L>&para; Ther I was allas &thorn;at ilke day</L>
<L N="500">And fostred in a Roch of marble gray
<PB REF="00000363.tif" N="351"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="493"></L>
<L>So tendrely that no&thorn;ing eyled me /</L>
<L>I wiste not / what was aduersite</L>
<L>Til I cou&thorn;e flee ful heigh vnder &thorn;e sky<MILESTONE N="155b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="504">Tho dwelled a tercelet me faste by</L>
<L>That semed welle of alle gentillesse</L>
<L>Al were he ful of tresoun and falsnesse</L>
<L>It was I-wrapped vnder humble cheere</L>
<L N="508">And vnder heewe of trou&thorn;e in such manere</L>
<L>Vnder plesaunce and vnder besy peyne</L>
<L>That no wight wende &thorn;at he cou&thorn;e feyne</L>
<L>So deep in greyn he deyed his colours</L>
<L N="512">Right as a serpent hut him vnder floures</L>
<L>Til he may see his tyme for to byte</L>
<L>Right so &thorn;is god of loue, &thorn;is ypocrite</L>
<L>Do&thorn; so his sermonys and his obseruaunce/</L>
<L N="516">vnder subtil colour and aqueyntaunce</L>
<L>That sowneth vnto gentilesse of loue</L>
<L>As in a thombe is al &thorn;e faire aboue</L>
<L>And vnder is &thorn;e corps whiche &thorn;at &yogh;e wot</L>
<L N="520">Such as was &thorn;is Ipocrite bo&thorn;e cold and hot</L>
<L>And in this wise he serued his entent</L>
<L>That sauf &thorn;e feend noon wiste what he ment</L>
<L>Til he so long had weped and compleyned</L>
<L N="524">And many a &yogh;eer his seruice to me feyned</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at myn hert to pitous and to nyce</L>
<L>Al Innocent of his crouned malice</L>
<L>For-fered of his deth as &thorn;oughte me</L>
<L N="528">vpon his othes and his sewerte</L>
<L>Graunted him loue vpon &thorn;is condicioun</L>
<L>That euermo myn honour and my renoun</L>
<L>were saued bo&thorn;e pryuy and apert</L>
<L N="532">This is to sayn &thorn;at after his desert</L>
<L>I &yogh;af him al myn hert and al my &thorn;ought</L>
<L>god woot and he &thorn;at o&thorn;er weye nought</L>
<L>And took his hert in chaunge of myn for ay</L>
<L N="536">But so&thorn; is sayd go si&thorn;ens many a day
<PB REF="00000364.tif" N="352"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="494"></L>
<L>A trew wight and a theef &thorn;enketh nou&yogh;t oon</L>
<L>And when he saugh &thorn;e &thorn;yng so fer I-goon</L>
<L>That I graunted him fully my loue /</L>
<L N="540">In such a wyse as I haue sayd aboue /</L>
<L>And &yogh;euen him my trewe hert as fre<MILESTONE N="156a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As he swor he &yogh;af his herte to me /</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;is Tigre ful of doublenesse</L>
<L N="544">Fil on his knees with so gret deuoutenesse</L>
<L>wi&thorn; high reuerence and as by his chere</L>
<L>So lyk a gentil louer of manere</L>
<L>So rauysched as it semede for Ioye</L>
<L N="548">That neuer Iason ne Parys of Troye</L>
<L>Iason certes ne noon o&thorn;er man</L>
<L>Si&thorn; lameth was &thorn;at al&thorn;er first bygan</L>
<L>To louen two as writen folk biforn</L>
<L N="552">Ne neuer si&thorn; &thorn;e firste man was born</L>
<L>Ne cou&thorn;e man by twenty &thorn;ousand part</L>
<L>Contrefete &thorn;e sophemes of his art</L>
<L>Ne were wor&thorn;y to vnbokel his galoche</L>
<L N="556">Ther doublenes of feynyng schold approche</L>
<L>Ne so cou&thorn;e &thorn;ankyn a knight as he did me</L>
<L>His maner was an heuen for to see</L>
<L>To eny womman were sche neuer so wys</L>
<L N="560">So peynteth he and kembeth poynt deuys</L>
<L>As wel his wordes as his continaunce</L>
<L>And I so loued him for his obeisaunce</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e trouthe I demed in his herte</L>
<L N="564">That if so were &thorn;at eny &thorn;ing him smerte</L>
<L>And were it neuer so litel and I it wist</L>
<L>Me &thorn;ought I felte deth at myn hert twist</L>
<L>And schortly so ferforth &thorn;is &thorn;ing went</L>
<L N="568">That my wil was his willes instrument</L>
<L>This is to say my wille obeied his wille</L>
<L>In alle &thorn;ing as fer as resoun fille</L>
<L>kepyng &thorn;e boundes of my worschip euer</L>
<L N="572">Ne neuer had I &thorn;ing so leef ne leuer
<PB REF="00000365.tif" N="353"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="495"></L>
<L>As him god woot ne neuer schal nomo</L>
<L>This laste lenger &thorn;an a &yogh;eer or two</L>
<L>That I supposed of him nought but good</L>
<L N="576">But fynally atte laste &thorn;us it stood</L>
<L>That fortune wolde &thorn;at he moste twynne</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e place which &thorn;at I was Inne</L>
<L>wher me was wo it is no questioun /<MILESTONE N="156b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="580">I can nat make of it descripcioun</L>
<L>For o &thorn;ing dar I telle boldely</L>
<L>I know what is &thorn;e peyne of deth &thorn;erby</L>
<L>which harm I felt for he ne mighte byleue</L>
<L N="584">So on a day of me he took his leue</L>
<L>So sorwful eek &thorn;at I went verrayly</L>
<L>That he had feled als moche as I</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at I herd him speke and saugh his hewe</L>
<L N="588">But na&thorn;eles I &thorn;ought he was vntrewe</L>
<L>And eek &thorn;at he schulde repeire a&yogh;eyn</L>
<L>wi&thorn;inne a litel while so&thorn; to seyn</L>
<L>And resoun wold eek &thorn;at he moste go: for his honour</L>
<L N="592">Wher-for I wold not ben ayein his honour<NOTE PLACE="marg">[spurious]</NOTE></L>
<L>Than I made vertu of necessite</L>
<L>And took it wel se&thorn;ens it moste be</L>
<L>As I best might I had for him my sorwe</L>
<L N="596">And took him by &thorn;e hand seint Iohn to borwe</L>
<L>And sayde &thorn;us / lo I am &yogh;our al</L>
<L>Be&thorn; such as I haue be to &yogh;ou and schal</L>
<L>what he answerd it neede&thorn; nat to reherse</L>
<L N="600">who can best say &thorn;an he, who can do werse //</L>
<L>whan he ha&thorn; al wel sayd &thorn;an ha&thorn; he doon</L>
<L>Therfor bihoue&thorn; him a ful long spoon</L>
<L>That schal ete wi&thorn; a feend &thorn;us herd I say</L>
<L N="604">So atte last he moste for&thorn; his way</L>
<L>And forth he fleeth til he cam &thorn;er him leste</L>
<L>whan it cam him to purpos for to reste</L>
<L>I trow he hadde &thorn;ilke text in mynde</L>
<L N="608">That alle &thorn;ing repeyryng to his kynde
<PB REF="00000366.tif" N="354"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="496"></L>
<L>Glade&thorn; himself &thorn;us sey men as I gesse</L>
<L>Men louen of kynde newefangilnesse</L>
<L>As briddes doon &thorn;at men in cage feede</L>
<L N="612">For &thorn;eigh &thorn;ou night and day take of hem heede</L>
<L>And straw her cage faire and soft as silk</L>
<L>And &yogh;eue hem sugre hony breed and mylk</L>
<L>&YOGH;et right anoon as his dore is vppe</L>
<L N="616">he with his feet wil sporne doun his cuppe</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e wode<NOTE PLACE="end">[Eight leaves are here missing from the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000367.tif" N="355">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="514">
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Brit. Mus. Harl.</I> 7334 <I>begins again, leaf</I> 157.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1224">lasse &thorn;an a &thorn;ousand pound he wolde nought haue</L>
<L>Ne gladly for &thorn;at somme he wolde not goon</L>
<L>Aurilius wi&thorn; blisful hert anoon</L>
<L>Answerde &thorn;us. fy on a &thorn;ousand pound</L>
<L N="1228">This wyde world which &thorn;at men say is round</L>
<L>I wold it &yogh;iue if I were lord of it/</L>
<L>This bargeyn is ful dryue for we ben knyt</L>
<L>&YOGH;e schal be payed trewly by my trou&thorn;e /</L>
<L N="1232">But loke&thorn; now for necligence or slou&thorn;e</L>
<L>&YOGH;e tarie vs heer no lenger &thorn;an to morwe /</L>
<L>Nay quod &thorn;is clerk haue her my faith to borwe</L>
<L>To bed is goon aurilius whan him leste</L>
<L N="1236">And wel neigh al night he had his reste
<PB REF="00000368.tif" N="356"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="515"></L>
<L>what for his labour and his hope of blisse</L>
<L>His woful hert of penaunce had a lisse /</L>
<L>vpon &thorn;e morwe whan &thorn;at it was day</L>
<L N="1240">To breteigne take &thorn;ei &thorn;e righte way</L>
<L>Aurilius and &thorn;is magicien bisyde</L>
<L>And ben descendid &thorn;er &thorn;ay wol abyde</L>
<L>And &thorn;is was as &thorn;ese bookes me remembre</L>
<L N="1244">The colde frosty seisoun of Decembre</L>
<L>Phebus wax old and hewed lyk latoun</L>
<L>That in his hoote declinacioun</L>
<L>Schon as &thorn;e burned gold with stremes bright</L>
<L N="1248">But now in Capricorn a-doun he light</L>
<L>wher as he schon ful pale I dar wel sayn</L>
<L>The bitter frostes with &thorn;e sleet and rayn</L>
<L>Destroyed ha&thorn; &thorn;e grene in euery &yogh;erd</L>
<L N="1252">Ianus sit by &thorn;e fuyr wi&thorn; double berd</L>
<L>And drynke&thorn; of his bugle horn &thorn;e wyn</L>
<L>Biforn him stont &thorn;e braun of toskid swyn</L>
<L>And Nowel crie&thorn; euery lusty man</L>
<L N="1256">Aurilius in al &thorn;at euer he can</L>
<L>Do&thorn; to his maister chier and reuerence</L>
<L>And peyne&thorn; him to doon his diligence</L>
<L>To bringen him out of his peynes smerte</L>
<L N="1260">Or wi&thorn; a swerd &thorn;at he wold slytte his herte</L>
<L>This subtil clerk such rou&thorn;e had of &thorn;is man</L>
<L>That night and day he spede&thorn; him &thorn;at he can<MILESTONE N="157b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To wayte a tyme of his conclusioun</L>
<L N="1264">This is to say to make Illusioun</L>
<L>By such an apparence of iogelrie</L>
<L>I can no termes of astrologie</L>
<L>That sche and euery wight schold wene and saye</L>
<L N="1268">That of Breteygn &thorn;e rokkes were a waye</L>
<L>Or elles &thorn;ey sonken were vnder &thorn;e grounde</L>
<L>So atte last he ha&thorn; a tyme I-founde</L>
<L>To make his iapes and his wrecchednesse /</L>
<L N="1272">Of such a supersticious cursednesse /
<PB REF="00000369.tif" N="357"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="516"></L>
<L>His tables tollitanes for&thorn; he brought</L>
<L>Ful wel corrected ne &thorn;er lakked nought</L>
<L>Nei&thorn;er his collect ne his expans yeeres</L>
<L N="1276">Ne his rootes ne his o&thorn;er geeres /</L>
<L>As ben his centris &amp; his argumentis</L>
<L>And his proporcionels conuenientis</L>
<L>For her equaciouns in euery &thorn;ing /</L>
<L N="1280">And by his &thorn;re speeres in his worching</L>
<L>he knew ful wel how fer alluath was schoue</L>
<L>For &thorn;e heed of &thorn;ilk fixe aries aboue</L>
<L>That in &thorn;e four&thorn;e speere considred is</L>
<L N="1284">Ful subtilly he calkild al &thorn;is</L>
<L>whan he had founde his firste mancioun</L>
<L>He knew &thorn;e remenaunt by proporcioun</L>
<L>And knew &thorn;e arisyng of &thorn;is moone wel</L>
<L N="1288">And in whos face and terme and euery del</L>
<L>And knew ful wel &thorn;e moones mancioun</L>
<L>Acordaunt to his operacioun</L>
<L>And knew also his other obseruaunces</L>
<L N="1292">For suche illusiouns and suche meschaunces</L>
<L>As hethen folk vsed in &thorn;ilke dayes</L>
<L>For which no lenger maked he delayes</L>
<L>But &thorn;urgh his magik for a wike or tweye</L>
<L N="1296">It semed &thorn;at &thorn;e rokkes were aweye</L>
<L>Aurilius which &yogh;et dispayred is</L>
<L>wher he schal haue his loue or fare amys</L>
<L>Awayte&thorn; night and day on &thorn;is miracle</L>
<L N="1300">And whan he knew &thorn;at &thorn;er was noon obstacle<MILESTONE N="158a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That voyded were &thorn;ese rokkes euerich oon</L>
<L>Doun to his maistres feet he fel anoon</L>
<L>And sayd I wrecched woful aurilius</L>
<L N="1304">Thanke &yogh;ou lord and my lady Venus</L>
<L>That me han holpe fro my cares colde /</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e temple his way for&thorn; he ha&thorn; holde</L>
<L>wher as he knew he schold his lady se</L>
<L N="1308">And whan he saugh his tyme anoon right he
<PB REF="00000370.tif" N="358"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="517"></L>
<L>with dredful hert and with ful humble cheere</L>
<L>Salued ha&thorn; his owne lady deere</L>
<L>My souerayn lady quod &thorn;is woful man</L>
<L N="1312">whom I most drede and loue as I can</L>
<L>And lo&thorn;est were of al &thorn;is world displese /</L>
<L>Nere it &thorn;at I for &yogh;ou haue such desese /</L>
<L>That I most deye her at &yogh;oure foot anoon</L>
<L N="1316">Nought wold I telle how me is wo bygoon</L>
<L>But certes ou&thorn;er most I dye or pleyne</L>
<L>&YOGH;e sleen me gulteles for verrey peyne</L>
<L>But of my de&thorn; &thorn;ough &thorn;at &yogh;e haue no rou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="1320">Auyseth &yogh;ow or &thorn;at &yogh;e breke &yogh;our trou&thorn;e</L>
<L>Repente&thorn; &yogh;ow for &thorn;ilke god aboue</L>
<L>&YOGH;e me sleen by cause &thorn;at I &yogh;ou loue</L>
<L>For madame wel &yogh;e woot what/ &yogh;e han hight</L>
<L N="1324">Nat &thorn;at I chalenge eny &thorn;ing of right</L>
<L>Of &yogh;ow my souerayn lady but &yogh;oure grace</L>
<L>But in a gardyn &yogh;onde at such a place</L>
<L>&YOGH;e wot right wel what &yogh;e byhighte me</L>
<L N="1328">And in myn hond &yogh;our trou&thorn;e plighte &yogh;e</L>
<L>To loue me best god woot/ &yogh;e sayde so</L>
<L>Al be &thorn;at I vnworthy am &thorn;erto</L>
<L>Ma dame I speke it for thonour of &yogh;ow</L>
<L N="1332">More &thorn;an to saue myn hertes lif right now</L>
<L>I haue do so as &yogh;e comaunded me</L>
<L>And if &yogh;e vouche sauf &yogh;e may go se</L>
<L>Do&thorn; as &yogh;ou list haue &yogh;oure byheste in mynde</L>
<L N="1336">For quyk or deed right &thorn;er &yogh;e schul me fynde</L>
<L>In &yogh;ow li&thorn; al to do me lyue or deye</L>
<L>But wel I wot &thorn;e rokkes ben aweye<MILESTONE N="158b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he take&thorn; his leue and he astoned stood</L>
<L N="1340">In alle hir face nas oon drop of blood</L>
<L>Sche wend neuer haue be in such a trappe</L>
<L>Allas quod sche &thorn;at euer &thorn;is schulde happe</L>
<L>For wend I neuer by possibilite</L>
<L N="1344">That such a monstre or merueyl mighte be /
<PB REF="00000371.tif" N="359"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="518"></L>
<L>It is agayns &thorn;e proces of nature</L>
<L>And hom sche go&thorn; a sorwful creature</L>
<L>For verray fere vnne&thorn;e may sche go</L>
<L N="1348">Sche wepe&thorn; wayle&thorn; al a day or tuo</L>
<L>And swowne&thorn; &thorn;at it rou&thorn;e was to see</L>
<L>But why it was to no wight tolde sche</L>
<L>For out of toune was goon aruegarius</L>
<L N="1352">But to hir self sche spak/ and sayde &thorn;us</L>
<L>wi&thorn; face pale and with ful sorwful chiere</L>
<L>In hir compleignt as &yogh;e schul after hiere</L>
<L>&para; Allas quod sche on &thorn;e fortune I pleyne</L>
<L N="1356">That vnwar, wrapped me hast, in &thorn;y cheyne</L>
<L>Fro which tescape woot I no socour</L>
<L>Saue oonly de&thorn; or elles dishonour</L>
<L>Oon of &thorn;ese tuo bihoueth me to chese /</L>
<L N="1360">But na&thorn;eles &yogh;et haue I leuer leese</L>
<L>My lif &thorn;an of my body to haue schame</L>
<L>Or knowe my-selue fals or lese my name /</L>
<L>And with my de&thorn; I may be quyt I-wys</L>
<L N="1364">Hath &thorn;er not many a noble wyf er &thorn;is /</L>
<L>And many a mayden slayn hir-self allas</L>
<L>Ra&thorn;er &thorn;an with her body doon trespas /</L>
<L>&YOGH;is certeynly lo stories beren witnes</L>
<L N="1368">whan &thorn;ritty tiraunt&yogh; ful of cursednes</L>
<L>hadde slayn phidon in athenes atte fest</L>
<L>Thay comaunded his doughtres to arest</L>
<L>And bryngen hem biforn hem in despit</L>
<L N="1372">And naked to fulfille her foule delyt</L>
<L>In her fadres blood &thorn;ey made hem daunce</L>
<L>vpon &thorn;e pauyment god &yogh;eue hem meschaunce</L>
<L>For which &thorn;ese woful maydens ful of drede</L>
<L N="1376">Ra&thorn;er &thorn;an &thorn;ey wolde lese her maydenhede<MILESTONE N="159a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>They priuely ben stert in to a welle /</L>
<L>And drenched hemselfen as &thorn;e bookes telle</L>
<L>&para; They of mecene leet enquere and seeke /</L>
<L N="1380">Of lacidomye fifty maydenes eeke /
<PB REF="00000372.tif" N="360"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="519"></L>
<L>On which &thorn;ay wolden doon her leccherie</L>
<L>But was &thorn;er noon of al &thorn;at companye</L>
<L>was slayn and wi&thorn; a good entente</L>
<L N="1384">Ches ra&thorn;er for to deye &thorn;an to assente</L>
<L>To ben oppressed of hir maydenhede</L>
<L>why schuld I &thorn;an to deyen ben in drede</L>
<L>&para; Lo eek &thorn;e Tyraunt/ aristoclides</L>
<L N="1388">That loued a mayden heet Stimphalides</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at hir father slayn was on a night</L>
<L>vnto dyanes temple go&thorn; sche right</L>
<L>And hent &thorn;e ymage in hir hondes tuo</L>
<L N="1392">Fro which ymage wold sche neuer go</L>
<L>No wight might of hit/ hir hondes race</L>
<L>Til sche was slayn right in &thorn;e selue place</L>
<L>Now si&thorn; &thorn;at maydens hadde such despit</L>
<L N="1396">To ben defouled with mannes foul delit</L>
<L>wel aught a wif rather hirself to sle</L>
<L>Than be defouled as it thenke&thorn; me</L>
<L>&para; what schal I seyn of hasdrubaldes wyf</L>
<L N="1400">That at Cartage byraft hir-self &thorn;e lyf</L>
<L>For whan sche saugh &thorn;at Romayns wan &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>Sche took hir children alle and skipte a doun</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e fuyr and ches ra&thorn;er to deye</L>
<L N="1404">Than eny romayn dide hir vilonye</L>
<L>&para; Ha&thorn; nought lucresse slayn hirself allas</L>
<L>At Rome whanne sche oppressid was</L>
<L>Of tarquyn for hir &thorn;ought it was a schame /</L>
<L N="1408">To lyuen whan sche hadde lost hir name</L>
<L>&para; The seuen maydens of milifie also</L>
<L>han slayn hemself for verray drede and wo</L>
<L>Ra&thorn;er &thorn;an folk of Gawle hem schulde oppresse</L>
<L N="1412">Mo &thorn;an a thousand stories as I gesse</L>
<L>Cou&thorn;e I now telle as touching &thorn;is matiere</L>
<L>&para; whan habradace was slayn his wif so deere<MILESTONE N="159b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>hir-seluen slough and leet hir blood to glyde /</L>
<L N="1416">In habradaces woundes deepe and wyde /
<PB REF="00000373.tif" N="361"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="520"></L>
<L>And seyde my body atte leste way</L>
<L>Ther schal no wight defoulen if I may</L>
<L>what schold I mo ensamples her of sayn</L>
<L N="1420">Se&thorn;&thorn;en so many han hemseluen slayn</L>
<L>wel ra&thorn;er &thorn;an &thorn;ey wolde defouled be /</L>
<L>I wol conclude &thorn;at it is best for me</L>
<L>To slen myself &thorn;an be defouled &thorn;us</L>
<L N="1424">I wol be trewe vnto aruegarius</L>
<L>Or rather sle myself in som manere</L>
<L>As dede Democionis dou&yogh;ter deere</L>
<L>By cause sche wolde nought defouled be /</L>
<L N="1428">O cedasus it is ful gret pite</L>
<L>To reden how &thorn;y doughteren dyed allas</L>
<L>That slowe hemself for suche maner caas</L>
<L>As gret a pite was it or wel more</L>
<L N="1432">The theban mayden &thorn;at for nichonore</L>
<L>hir-seluen slough right for such maner wo</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er Theban mayden dede right so</L>
<L>For oon of macidone had hir oppressed</L>
<L N="1436">Sche with hire de&thorn; maydenhede redressed</L>
<L>what schal I sayn of Niceratis wif</L>
<L>That for such caas biraft hir self hir lyf</L>
<L>how trewe eek was cito alcebiades</L>
<L N="1440">his loue. &thorn;at rather to dyen ches</L>
<L>Than for to suffre his body vnburied be</L>
<L>Lo which a wif was alceste quod sche</L>
<L>what sai&thorn; omer of good penolope</L>
<L N="1444">Al grece knowe&thorn; of hir chastite</L>
<L>Par di of laodomya is writen &thorn;us</L>
<L>That whan out of Troye was Protheselaus</L>
<L>No lenger wol sche lyue after his day</L>
<L N="1448">The same of noble porcia telle I may</L>
<L>wi&thorn;oute brutes kynde sche my&yogh;t not lyue</L>
<L>To whom sche had al hool hir herte &yogh;yue</L>
<L>The parfyt wyfhod of artemesye</L>
<L N="1452">honoured is &thorn;urgh al &thorn;e Barbarie<MILESTONE N="160a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000374.tif" N="362"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="521"></L>
<L>O thena queen &thorn;y wifly chastite</L>
<L>To alle wyues may a mirour be</L>
<L>. . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.: these lines are</NOTE></L>
<L N="1456">. . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">known only in the Ellesmere MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thus playned Dorigen a day or tweye</L>
<L>Purposyng euer &thorn;at sche wolde deye</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles vpon &thorn;e thridde night</L>
<L N="1460">hom cam arueragus &thorn;is wor&thorn;y knight</L>
<L>And asked hir why &thorn;at sche wept so sore /</L>
<L>And sche gan wepe euer lenger &thorn;e more</L>
<L>Allas quod sche &thorn;at euer was I born</L>
<L N="1464">Thus haue I sayd quod sche &thorn;us haue I sworn</L>
<L>And told him al as &yogh;e han herd biforn</L>
<L>It nede&thorn; nought reherse it you no more</L>
<L>&para; This housbond wi&thorn; glad chiere in good wise</L>
<L N="1468">Answerd and sayde as I schal &yogh;ou deuyse</L>
<L>Is &thorn;er aught elles Dorigen but &thorn;is</L>
<L>Nay nay quod sche god me so rede &amp; wis</L>
<L>This is to moche and it were goddes wille</L>
<L N="1472">&YOGH;e wyf quod he let slepe &thorn;at may be stille</L>
<L>It may be wel peraunter &yogh;et to day</L>
<L>&YOGH;e schal &yogh;our trou&thorn;e holden by my fay</L>
<L>For god so wisly haue mercy on me</L>
<L N="1476">I hadde wel leuer I-stekid for to be</L>
<L>For verray loue which I to &yogh;ou haue /</L>
<L>But if &yogh;e scholde &yogh;our trou&thorn;e kepe and saue</L>
<L>Trou&thorn;e is &thorn;e heighest &thorn;ing &thorn;at men may kepe</L>
<L N="1480">But wi&thorn; &thorn;at word he gan anoon to wepe</L>
<L>And sayde I &yogh;ow forbede vp peyne of de&thorn;</L>
<L>That neuer whil &thorn;e lasteth lyf or breth</L>
<L>To no wight telle &thorn;ou of &thorn;is auenture</L>
<L N="1484">As I may best I wil my woo endure</L>
<L>Ne make no contenaunce of heuynesse</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk of &yogh;ou may deme harm or gesse</L>
<L>And for he cleped a squyer and a mayde</L>
<L N="1488">Go&thorn; for&thorn; anoon wi&thorn; Dorigen he sayde
<PB REF="00000375.tif" N="363"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="522"></L>
<L>And brynge&thorn; hir to such a place anoon</L>
<L>Thay take her leue and on her wey &thorn;ey gon</L>
<L>But &thorn;ay ne wiste why sche &thorn;ider went</L>
<L N="1492">He nolde no wight tellen his entent<MILESTONE N="160b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="1496">. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.: these lines are</NOTE></L>
<L>. . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">known only in the Ellesmere MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>This squyer which &thorn;at hight aurelius</L>
<L N="1500">On dorigen &thorn;at was so amerous</L>
<L>Of aduenture happed hire to mete</L>
<L>Amyd &thorn;e toun right in &thorn;e quyke strete</L>
<L>As sche was boun to goon &thorn;e wey for&thorn;-right</L>
<L N="1504">Toward &thorn;e Gardyn &thorn;er as sche had hight</L>
<L>And he was to &thorn;e gardynward also /</L>
<L>For wel he spyed whan sche wolde go</L>
<L>Out of hir hous to eny maner place</L>
<L N="1508">But &thorn;us &thorn;ay mette of aduenture or grace</L>
<L>And he salueth hir with glad entent</L>
<L>And askith hire whiderward sche went/</L>
<L>And sche answered half as sche were mad</L>
<L N="1512">vnto &thorn;e gardyn as myn housbond bad</L>
<L>My trou&thorn;e for to holde allas allas</L>
<L>Aurilius gan wondren on &thorn;is caas</L>
<L>And in his hert had gret compassioun</L>
<L N="1516">Of hire and of hir lamentacioun</L>
<L>And of Arueragus &thorn;e wor&thorn;y knight</L>
<L>That bad hir hold al &thorn;at sche hadde hight</L>
<L>So lo&thorn; him was his wif schuld breke hir trou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="1520">And in his hert he caught of this gret rou&thorn;e</L>
<L>Consideryng &thorn;e best on euery syde</L>
<L>That fro his lust &yogh;et were him leuer abyde</L>
<L>Than doon so high a cheerlissch wrecchednesse</L>
<L N="1524">Agayns fraunchis of alle gentilesce
<PB REF="00000376.tif" N="364"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="523"></L>
<L>For which in fewe wordes sayd he &thorn;us</L>
<L>Madame saith to &yogh;our lord arueragus</L>
<L>That si&thorn; I se his grete gentilesse</L>
<L N="1528">To &yogh;ou. and eek I se wel &yogh;our distresse</L>
<L>That him were leuer haue schame and &thorn;at were rou&thorn;e /</L>
<L>Than &yogh;e to me schulde breke &yogh;oure trou&thorn;e</L>
<L>I haue wel leuer euer to suffre woo</L>
<L N="1532">Than I departe &thorn;e loue bytwix &yogh;ow tuo</L>
<L>I &yogh;ow relesse madame in to &yogh;our hond</L>
<L>Quyt euery seurement and euery bond</L>
<L>That &yogh;e han maad to me as her biforn</L>
<L N="1536">Sith &thorn;ilke tyme which &thorn;at &yogh;e were born<MILESTONE N="161a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>My trou&thorn;e I plight I schal &yogh;ow neuer repreue</L>
<L>Of no byhest and her I take my leue</L>
<L>As of &thorn;e trewest and &thorn;e beste wif</L>
<L N="1540">That euer &yogh;it I knew in al my lyf</L>
<L>But euery wyf be war of hir byhest</L>
<L>On Dorigen remembre&thorn; atte lest</L>
<L>Thus can a squyer doon a gentil dede</L>
<L N="1544">As wel as can a knyght wi&thorn;outen drede</L>
<L>Sche &thorn;anke&thorn; him vpon hir knees al bare /</L>
<L>And hoom vnto hir housbond is sche fare /</L>
<L>And told him al as &yogh;e han herd me sayd</L>
<L N="1548">And be &yogh;e siker he was so wel a-payd</L>
<L>That it were impossible me to write</L>
<L>what schuld I lenger of &thorn;is caas endite</L>
<L>Arueragus and Dorigen his wif</L>
<L N="1552">In souereyn blisse leden for&thorn; here lyf</L>
<L>Neuer eft ne was &thorn;er anger hem bytwen</L>
<L>he cherissche&thorn; hir as &thorn;ough sche were a queen</L>
<L>And sche was to him trewe for euermore /</L>
<L N="1556">Of &thorn;ese tuo folk &yogh;e gete for me nomore /</L>
<L>&para; Aurilius &thorn;at his cost ha&thorn; al forlorn</L>
<L>Curse&thorn; &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at euer he was born</L>
<L>Allas quod he allas &thorn;at I byhight</L>
<L N="1560">Of pured gold a thousand pound of wight
<PB REF="00000377.tif" N="365"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="524"></L>
<L>vnto &thorn;is philosophre how schal I doo</L>
<L>I se no more but &thorn;at I am for-doo</L>
<L>Myn heritage moot I needes selle /</L>
<L N="1564">And ben a begger her may I not duelle</L>
<L>And schamen al my kynrede in &thorn;is place</L>
<L>But I of him may gete better grace</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles I wol of him assay</L>
<L N="1568">At certeyn dayes &yogh;eer by &yogh;er to pay</L>
<L>And &thorn;anke him of his grete curtesye</L>
<L>My trou&thorn;e wol I kepe I wol nou&yogh;t lye</L>
<L>with herte soor he go&thorn; vn to his cofre</L>
<L N="1572">And broughte gold vnto &thorn;is philosophre</L>
<L>The value of fyf hundred pound I gesse</L>
<L>And him bysecheth of his gentilesce<MILESTONE N="161b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To graunte him dayes of &thorn;e remenaunt</L>
<L N="1576">And sayde maister I dar wel make auaunt</L>
<L>I fayled neuer of my trou&thorn;e as &yogh;it</L>
<L>For sikerly my dettes schal be quyt</L>
<L>Towardes &yogh;ow how &thorn;at euer I fare</L>
<L N="1580">To goon a begge in my kurtil bare</L>
<L>But wolde &yogh;e vouche sauf vpon seurte</L>
<L>Tuo &yogh;er or &thorn;re for to respite me</L>
<L>Than were I wel for elles most I selle</L>
<L N="1584">Myn heritage &thorn;er is nomore to telle</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is philosophre sobrely answerde /</L>
<L>And seyde &thorn;us whan he &thorn;ese wordes herde</L>
<L>Haue I not holden couenaunt vnto &thorn;e;</L>
<L N="1588">&YOGH;is certes wel and trewely quod he /</L>
<L>Hastow nou&yogh;t had &thorn;y lady as &thorn;e liketh</L>
<L>No no quod he and sorwfully he sike&thorn;</L>
<L>what was &thorn;e cause tel me if &thorn;ou can</L>
<L N="1592">Aurilius his tale anoon bygan</L>
<L>And told him al as &yogh;e han herd bifore</L>
<L>It neede&thorn; nat to &yogh;ou reherse it more</L>
<L>he sayde arueragus of gentilesse</L>
<L N="1596">had leuer dye in sorwe and in distresse
<PB REF="00000378.tif" N="366"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="525"></L>
<L>Than &thorn;at his wyf were of hir trou&thorn;e fals</L>
<L>The sorwe of Dorigen he tolde him als</L>
<L>how lo&thorn; hir was to ben a wikked wikked wyf</L>
<L N="1600">And &thorn;at sche leuer had han lost hir lyf</L>
<L>And &thorn;at hir trou&thorn;e sche swor &thorn;urgh Innocence</L>
<L>Sche neuer erst hadde herd speke of apparence</L>
<L>That made me han of hir so gret pyte</L>
<L N="1604">By cause hir housebond sente hir to me</L>
<L>And right as frely sent I hir to him agayn</L>
<L>&THORN;is is al and som &thorn;er is no more to sayn</L>
<L>The philosopher answerde leue bro&thorn;er</L>
<L N="1608">Euerich of &yogh;ow dede gentilly to o&thorn;er</L>
<L>Thow art a squyer and he is a knight</L>
<L>But god forbede for his blisful might</L>
<L>But if a clerk cou&thorn;e doon as gentil dede</L>
<L N="1612">As wel as eny of &yogh;ou it is no drede<MILESTONE N="162a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sire I relesse &thorn;e &thorn;y &thorn;ousond pound</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou right now were crope out of &thorn;e ground</L>
<L>Ne neuer er now ne haddest knowen me</L>
<L N="1616">For sire I wol not take a peny of &thorn;e</L>
<L>For al my craft ne nought for my trauayle /</L>
<L>Thou hast y-payed wel for my vitayle /</L>
<L>It is ynough and far wel haue good day</L>
<L N="1620">And took his hors and for&thorn; he go&thorn; his way</L>
<L>&para; Lordynges &thorn;is questioun wolde I axe now /</L>
<L>which was &thorn;e moste free as &thorn;inketh &yogh;ow</L>
<L>Now telle&thorn; me or &thorn;at I fer&thorn;er wende /</L>
<L N="1624">I can no more my tale is at an ende /</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Here endeth &thorn;e Frankeleynes tale<NOTE>[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="G" TYPE="group">


<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000379.tif" N="367">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="527">
<HEAD>&para; And here bygynneth &thorn;e Secounde Nounes tale /<NOTE PLACE="head">[No gap in the MS.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[THE PROEM.]</HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">THe minister and &thorn;e norice vnto vices</L>
<L>which &thorn;at men clepe in englisch ydelnesse /</L>
<L>The porter at &thorn;e gates is of delicis</L>
<L>To eschiewe and by her contrary hire oppresse</L>
<L N="5">That is to say by leful besynesse /</L>
<L>wel oughte we to do al oure entente</L>
<L N="7">Lest &thorn;at &thorn;e fend &thorn;urgh ydelnesse vs hente /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">For he &thorn;at wi&thorn; his &thorn;ousand cordes slye /</L>
<L>Continuelly vs wayteth to byclappe/</L>
<L>whan he may man in ydelnes espye /</L>
<L>He can so lightly cacche him in his trappe /</L>
<L N="12">Til &thorn;at a man be hent right by &thorn;e lappe /</L>
<L>He is nou&yogh;t war &thorn;e fend ha&thorn; him in honde /</L>
<L N="14">wel oughte we wirche and ydelnes wi&thorn;stonde /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">And &thorn;ough men dredde neuer for to deye</L>
<L>&YOGH;et seen men wel by resoun douteles</L>
<L>That ydelnes is roten sloggardye</L>
<L>Of which &thorn;er come&thorn; neuer good encres</L>
<L N="19">And sin &thorn;at slou&thorn; her holde&thorn; in a lees</L>
<L>Oonly to sleep and for to ete and drynke</L>
<L N="21">And to deuoure al &thorn;at o&thorn;er swynke
<PB REF="00000380.tif" N="368"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="528"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="22">And for to put vs from such ydelne</L>
<L>That cause is of so gret confusioun</L>
<L>I haue her doon my faithful busynes<MILESTONE N="162b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>After &thorn;e legende in translacioun</L>
<L N="26">Right of &thorn;is glorious lif and passioun</L>
<L>Thou with &thorn;i garlond wrought wi&thorn; rose and lylye</L>
<L N="28">The mene I mayde and martir cecilie</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="29">And &thorn;ou &thorn;at flour of virgines art alle /<NOTE PLACE="marg">Inuocacio ad marium</NOTE></L>
<L>Of whom &thorn;at Bernard lust so wel to write /</L>
<L>To &thorn;e at my bygynnyng first I calle</L>
<L>Thou comfort of vs wrecches do me endite</L>
<L N="33">Thy maydenes de&thorn; &thorn;at whan &thorn;urgh hire merite</L>
<L>Theternal lif and of &thorn;e feend victorie</L>
<L N="35">As man may after reden in hir storie</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L N="36">Thou mayde and moder doughter of &thorn;i sone /</L>
<L>Thow welle of mercy synful soules cure</L>
<L>In whom &thorn;at god of bountes chees to wone</L>
<L>Thou humble and heyh ouer euery creature</L>
<L N="40">Thow nobelest so ferfor&thorn; oure nature</L>
<L>That no disdeyn &thorn;e maker had of kynde /</L>
<L N="42">his sone in blood and fleissh to clo&thorn;e and wynde /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L N="43">Wi&thorn;inne &thorn;e cloyster of &thorn;i blisful sydes</L>
<L>Took mannes schap &thorn;e eternal loue and pees</L>
<L>That of &thorn;e trine compas lord and guyde is</L>
<L>whom er&thorn;e and see and heuen out of relees</L>
<L N="47">Ay herien and &thorn;ou virgine wemmeles</L>
<L>Bar of &thorn;y body and dwellest mayden pure</L>
<L N="49">The creatour of euery creature /
<PB REF="00000381.tif" N="369"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="529"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L N="50">Assembled is in &thorn;y magnificence</L>
<L>with mercy goodnes and with such pitee</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou &thorn;at art &thorn;e soune of excellence</L>
<L>But oonly helpist hem &thorn;at prayen &thorn;e</L>
<L N="54">But often tyme of &thorn;y benignite</L>
<L>Ful frely er &thorn;at men &thorn;in help biseche</L>
<L N="56">Thou gost biforn and art her lyfes leche /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L N="57">Now help &thorn;ou meke and blisful faire mayde /</L>
<L>Me flemed wrecche in &thorn;is desert of galle</L>
<L>Thenk on &thorn;e womman canace &thorn;at sayde</L>
<L>That whelpes ete some of &thorn;e crommes alle</L>
<L N="61">That from her lordes table ben I-falle /</L>
<L>And &thorn;ough &thorn;at I vnworthy sone of Eue<MILESTONE N="163a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="63">Be synful / &yogh;ett accepte my bileue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L N="64">And for &thorn;at faith is deth wi&thorn;outen werkis</L>
<L>So for to werken &yogh;iue me witt and space /</L>
<L>That I be quit fro &thorn;ennes &thorn;at most derk is</L>
<L>O &thorn;ou &thorn;at art so fair and ful of grace /</L>
<L N="68">Be myn aduocat in &thorn;at hihe place /</L>
<L>Ther as wi&thorn;outen ende is songe Osanne</L>
<L N="70">Thou cristes moder dou&yogh;ter deere of Anne</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L N="71">And of &thorn;i light my soule in prisoun light</L>
<L>That troubled is by &thorn;e contagioun</L>
<L>Of my body and also by &thorn;e wight</L>
<L>Of euerich lust and fals affeccioun</L>
<L N="75">O heuen of refuyt O sauacioun</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at ben in sorwe and in destresse /</L>
<L N="77">Now help for to my werk I wil me dresse /
<PB REF="00000382.tif" N="370"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="530"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L N="78">&YOGH;et pray I &yogh;ou &thorn;at reden &thorn;at I write /</L>
<L>For&yogh;eue me &thorn;at I doo no diligence</L>
<L>This ilke story subtilly to endite</L>
<L>For bo&thorn;e haue I &thorn;e wordes and sentence</L>
<L N="82">Of him &thorn;at at &thorn;e seintes reuerence</L>
<L>The story wroot and folwen hir legende /</L>
<L N="84">And pray &yogh;ow &thorn;at &yogh;e wol my werk amende /</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13) [<I>THE TALE</I>.]</HEAD>
<L N="85">First wol I &yogh;ow &thorn;e name of seint Cecile</L>
<L>Expoune as men may in hir story se /</L>
<L>It is to say on englisch heuenes lilie</L>
<L>For pure chastenesse of virginite</L>
<L N="89">Or for sche witnesse hadde of honeste</L>
<L>And grene of conscience and of good fame /</L>
<L N="91">The soote sauour lilie was her name</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L N="92">Or cecile is to say &thorn;e way of blynde /</L>
<L>For sche ensample was by way of techynge</L>
<L>Or elles Cecily as I writen fynde</L>
<L>Is ioyned by a maner of conioynynge</L>
<L N="96">Of heuen and lya and here in figurynge</L>
<L>The heuen is sette for &thorn;ought of holynesse /</L>
<L N="98">And lya for hir lastyng besynesse /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L N="99">Cecili may eek be seyd in &thorn;is manere /</L>
<L>wantyng of blyndnes for hir grete light<MILESTONE N="163b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of sapience and of &thorn;ilke &thorn;ewes cleere /</L>
<L>Or elles lo &thorn;is maydenes name bright</L>
<L N="103">Of heuen and loos comes of which by right</L>
<L>Men might hir wel &thorn;e heuen of peple calle /</L>
<L N="105">Ensample of goode and wise werkes alle
<PB REF="00000383.tif" N="371"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="531"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L N="106">For leos peple in englissh is to say</L>
<L>And righ as men may in &thorn;e heuen see</L>
<L>The sonne and moone and sterres euery way</L>
<L>Right so men gostly in &thorn;is mayden free</L>
<L N="110">Seen of fai&thorn; &thorn;e magnanimite /</L>
<L>And eek &thorn;e clernes hool of sapience</L>
<L N="112">And sondry werkes bright of excellence</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L N="113">And right so as &thorn;ese philosofres wryte</L>
<L>That heuen is swyft and round and eek brennynge</L>
<L>Right so was faire Cecily &thorn;e whyte</L>
<L>Ful swyft and besy euer in good werkynge /</L>
<L N="117">And round and hool in good perseuerynge</L>
<L>And brennyng euer in charite ful bright</L>
<L N="119">Now haue I &yogh;ow declared what sche hight</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L N="120">This mayden bright Cecilie as hir lyf sai&thorn;</L>
<L>was comen of Romayns and of noble kynde /</L>
<L>And from hir cradel vp fostred in &thorn;e fai&thorn;</L>
<L>Of crist and bar his gospel in hir mynde</L>
<L N="124">Sche neuer cessed as I writen fynde</L>
<L>Of hire prayer and god to loue and drede</L>
<L N="126">Byseching him to kepe hir maydenhede</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L N="127">And whan &thorn;is mayde schuld vnto a man</L>
<L>Y-wedded be. &thorn;at was ful &yogh;ong of age</L>
<L>which &thorn;at I-cleped was walirian</L>
<L>And day was comen of hir mariage</L>
<L N="131">Sche ful deuout and humble in hir currage</L>
<L>vnder hir robe of gold &thorn;at sat ful faire</L>
<L N="133">Hadde next hir fleissh I-clad hir in an heire
<PB REF="00000384.tif" N="372"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="532"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L N="134">And whil &thorn;e organs made melodie /</L>
<L>To god alloon in herte &thorn;us sang sche /</L>
<L>O lord my soule and eek my body gye</L>
<L>Vnwemmed. lest &thorn;at I confounded be /</L>
<L N="138">And for his loue &thorn;at deyde vpon a tre<MILESTONE N="164a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Euery secound or &thorn;ridde day sche faste</L>
<L N="140">Ay biddyng in hire orisouns ful faste /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L N="141">The nyght cam and to bedde most sche goon</L>
<L>with hir housbond as oft is &thorn;e manere</L>
<L>And priuely to him sche sayde anoon</L>
<L>O swete and wel biloued spouse deere /</L>
<L N="145">Ther is a counseil and &yogh;e wold it heere /</L>
<L>which &thorn;at right fayn I wold vnto &yogh;ou saye</L>
<L N="147">So that &yogh;e swere &yogh;e schul it not bywraye</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L N="148">Valirian gan fast/ vnto hir swere</L>
<L>That for no caas ne &thorn;ing &thorn;at mighte be</L>
<L>he scholde neuer mo bywreye hire</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne at erst &thorn;us sayde sche</L>
<L N="152">I haue an aungel which &thorn;at loue&thorn; me</L>
<L>That wi&thorn; gret loue wher so I wake or slepe</L>
<L N="154">Is redy ay my body for to kepe</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L N="155">. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">No gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Iff &yogh;e me touche or loue in vilonye</L>
<L>he right anoon wil sle &yogh;ou wi&thorn; &thorn;e dede</L>
<L>And in &yogh;oure &yogh;ou&thorn;e &thorn;us schulde &yogh;e dye</L>
<L N="159">And if &thorn;at &yogh;e in clene loue me gye</L>
<L>he wol &yogh;ow loue as me for &yogh;our clennesse /</L>
<L N="161">And schewe to &yogh;ou his ioye and his brightnesse/
<PB REF="00000385.tif" N="373"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="533"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L N="162">Valirian corrected as god wolde /</L>
<L>Answerde agayn if I schal truste &thorn;e /</L>
<L>Let me &thorn;at aungel se and him biholde</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at it a verray aungel be /</L>
<L N="166">Than wol I doon as &thorn;ou hast prayed me</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou loue ano&thorn;er man forso&thorn;e</L>
<L N="168">Right wi&thorn; &thorn;is swerd &thorn;an wol I slee &yogh;ou bo&thorn;e /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<L N="169">Cecilie answerd anoon right in &thorn;is wise</L>
<L>If &thorn;at &yogh;ow list &thorn;e aungel schul &yogh;e see</L>
<L>So that &yogh;e trowe on crist and &yogh;ou baptise</L>
<L>Go&thorn; for&thorn; to Via apia quod sche /</L>
<L N="173">That fro &thorn;is toun ne stant but myles &thorn;re</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e pore folkes &thorn;at &thorn;er duelle</L>
<L N="175">Saith hem right &thorn;us. as &thorn;at I schal &yogh;ou telle /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)</HEAD>
<L N="176">Telle hem I cecilie. &yogh;ow vnto hem sent</L>
<L>To schewen &yogh;ow &thorn;e good vrban &thorn;e olde /<MILESTONE N="164b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For secre needes and for good entente /</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at &yogh;e seint vrban han byholde /</L>
<L N="180">Tel him &thorn;e wordes which &thorn;at I to &yogh;ow tolde /</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at he ha&thorn; purged &yogh;ou fro synne</L>
<L N="182">Than schul &yogh;e se &thorn;at aungel er &yogh;e twynne /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27)</HEAD>
<L N="183">Valirian is to &thorn;e place y-goon</L>
<L>And right as him was taught by his lernynge</L>
<L>He fond &thorn;is holy old vrban anoon</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e seyntes buriels lotynge</L>
<L N="187">And he anoon wi&thorn;oute taryinge</L>
<L>Did his message and whan &thorn;at he it tolde</L>
<L N="189">vrban for ioye his handes gan vp holde
<PB REF="00000386.tif" N="374"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="534"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(28)</HEAD>
<L N="190">The teres from his ey&yogh;en let he falle</L>
<L>Almy&yogh;ty lord O. ih&umacr; crist quod he /</L>
<L>Sower of chaste counseil herde of vs alle</L>
<L>The fruyt of &thorn;ilke seed of chastite</L>
<L N="194">That &thorn;ou hast sowe to Cecilie tak to &thorn;e</L>
<L>loo lik a busy bee wi&thorn;outen gyle /</L>
<L N="196">The serue&thorn; ay &thorn;in owne &thorn;ral Cecile</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(29)</HEAD>
<L N="197">For &thorn;ilke spouse &thorn;at sche took right now</L>
<L>Ful lyk a fers lyoun sche sende&thorn; here</L>
<L>As meek as euer was eny lamb to &yogh;ow</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word anoon &thorn;er gan appere /</L>
<L N="201">An old man clad in white clo&thorn;es clere</L>
<L>That had a book wi&thorn; lettres of gold in honde /</L>
<L N="203">And gan to-forn Valirian to stonde /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(30)</HEAD>
<L N="204">Valirian as deed fyl doun for drede</L>
<L>whan he him say / and he him vp hente &thorn;o</L>
<L>And on his book right &thorn;us he gan to rede /</L>
<L>O lord. o feith oon god wi&thorn;outen mo</L>
<L N="208">On cristendom and oon fader of alle also</L>
<L>Abouen alle and ouer alle euery where</L>
<L N="210">. . . . .</L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(31)</HEAD>
<L N="211">. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="215">. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="217">And pope vrban him cristened right &thorn;ere
<PB REF="00000387.tif" N="375"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="535"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(32)</HEAD>
<L N="218">Valirian go&thorn; home and fint Cecilie</L>
<L>wi&thorn;inne his chambre with an aungel stonde /</L>
<L>This aungel had of Roses and of lilie</L>
<L>Corounes tuo &thorn;e which he bar in honde</L>
<L N="222">And first to Cecilie as I vnderstonde<MILESTONE N="165a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he &yogh;af &thorn;at oon and after can he take /</L>
<L N="224">That o&thorn;er to valerian hir make</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(33)</HEAD>
<L N="225">Wi&thorn; body clene and wi&thorn; vnwemmed &thorn;ought</L>
<L>kepe&thorn; ay wel &thorn;ese corounes &thorn;re</L>
<L>Fro paradys to &yogh;ou I haue hem brought</L>
<L>Ne neuer moo ne schul &thorn;ey roten be</L>
<L N="229">Ne leese here soote sauour truste&thorn; me</L>
<L>Ne neuer wight schal seen hem wi&thorn; his ye</L>
<L N="231">But/ he be chast and hate vilonye</L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(34)</HEAD>
<L N="232">And &thorn;ou valirian for &thorn;ou so soone</L>
<L>Assentedist to good counseil also</L>
<L>Say what &thorn;e list and &thorn;ou schalt haue &thorn;i boone</L>
<L>I haue a bro&thorn;er quod Valirian &thorn;o</L>
<L N="236">That in &thorn;is world I loue no man so</L>
<L>I pray &yogh;ow &thorn;at my bro&thorn;er may haue grace</L>
<L N="238">To knowe &thorn;e trou&thorn;e as I doo in &thorn;is place</L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(35)</HEAD>
<L N="239">The aungel sayde god liketh &thorn;y request</L>
<L>And bo&thorn;e with &thorn;e palme of martirdom</L>
<L>&YOGH;e schullen come vnto his blisful feste /</L>
<L>And with &thorn;at word tiburce his bro&thorn;er com</L>
<L N="243">And whan &thorn;at he &thorn;e sauour vndernom</L>
<L>which &thorn;at &thorn;e roses and &thorn;e lilies cast</L>
<L N="245">wi&thorn;inne hir hert/ he gan to wondre fast /
<PB REF="00000388.tif" N="376"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="536"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(36)</HEAD>
<L N="246">And sayde I wondre &thorn;is tyme of &thorn;e &yogh;er</L>
<L>whennes &thorn;at soote sauour come&thorn; so</L>
<L>Of Rose and lilies &thorn;at I smelle her</L>
<L>For &thorn;ough I had hem in myn hondes tuo</L>
<L N="250">The sauour might in me no depper go</L>
<L>The swete smel &thorn;at in myn hert I fynde</L>
<L N="252">Hath chaunged me al in ano&thorn;er kynde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(37)</HEAD>
<L N="253">Valirian sayd tuo corouns haue we</L>
<L>Snow whyt and rose reed &thorn;at schinen cleere /</L>
<L>whiche &thorn;at &thorn;ine ey&yogh;en han no might to see /</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou smellest hem &thorn;urgh my prayere</L>
<L N="257">So schalt &thorn;ou seen hem my lieue bro&thorn;ere deere</L>
<L>If so be &thorn;ou wilt wi&thorn;outen slou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="259">Bilieuen aright and knowen verray trouthe /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(38)</HEAD>
<L N="260">Tyburce answerde says &thorn;ou &thorn;us to me<MILESTONE N="165b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In so&thorn;enes or in drem I herkne &thorn;is</L>
<L>In dremes quod valirian han we be</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;is tyme bro&thorn;er myn I-wys</L>
<L N="264">As now at erst in trou&thorn;e oure duellyng is</L>
<L>how wost &thorn;ou &thorn;is quod tyburce and in what wise</L>
<L N="266">Quod valirian &thorn;at schal I &thorn;e deuyse</L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(39)</HEAD>
<L N="267">The aungel of god ha&thorn; me trou&thorn;e y-taught</L>
<L>which &thorn;ou schalt seen if &thorn;at &thorn;ou wilt reneye</L>
<L>The ydols and be clene and elles nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e miracles of &thorn;ese corones tweye</L>
<L N="271">Seynt ambrose in his prefas list to seye</L>
<L>Solempnely &thorn;is noble doctour deere</L>
<L N="273">Comende&thorn; it and sai&thorn; in &thorn;is maneere
<PB REF="00000389.tif" N="377"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="537"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(40)</HEAD>
<L N="274">The palme of martirdom for to receyue /</L>
<L>Seynt Cecilie fulfilled of goddes &yogh;ifte</L>
<L>The world and eek hir chamber gan sche weyue /</L>
<L>witnes tyburces and Cecilies schrifte</L>
<L N="278">To whiche god of his bounte wolde schifte</L>
<L>Corounes tuo of floures wel smellynge</L>
<L N="280">And made his aungel home &thorn;e croune brynge</L>
</LG>
<LG N="41" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(41)</HEAD>
<L N="281">The mayde ha&thorn; brought &thorn;is men to blisse aboue /</L>
<L>The world ha&thorn; wist what it is wor&thorn; certeyn</L>
<L>Deuocioun of chastite to loue</L>
<L>Tho schewed him Cecilie al open and pleyn</L>
<L N="285">That alle ydoles nys but &thorn;ing in veyn</L>
<L>For &thorn;ay ben doumbe and &thorn;erto &thorn;ey ben deue</L>
<L N="287">And charge&thorn; him his ydoles for to leue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(42)</HEAD>
<L N="288">Who so trowe&thorn; not &thorn;is a best he is</L>
<L>Quod tyburce if &thorn;at I schal not lye</L>
<L>And sche gan kisse his brest &thorn;at/ herde &thorn;is</L>
<L>And was ful glad he cou&thorn;e trou&thorn;e espye</L>
<L N="292">This day I take &thorn;e for myn allye</L>
<L>Sayde &thorn;is blisful faire mayde deere /</L>
<L N="294">And after &thorn;at sche sayde as &yogh;e may heere</L>
</LG>
<LG N="43" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(43)</HEAD>
<L N="295">Lo right so as &thorn;e loue of crist/ quod sche</L>
<L>Made me &thorn;y brotheres wyf right in &thorn;at wyse</L>
<L>Anoon for myn allye heer take I &thorn;e /</L>
<L>Sin &thorn;at &thorn;ou wilt thyne ydoles despise<MILESTONE N="166a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="299">Go with &thorn;i bro&thorn;er now and &thorn;e baptise</L>
<L>And make &thorn;e clene so &thorn;at &thorn;ou mowe biholde</L>
<L N="301">The aungeles face of which &thorn;y bro&thorn;er tolde
<PB REF="00000390.tif" N="378"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="538"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="44" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(44)</HEAD>
<L N="302">Tyburce answerde and sayde bro&thorn;er dere/</L>
<L>First tel me whider I schal and to what man</L>
<L>To whom quod he / com forth with good cheere /</L>
<L>I wol &thorn;e lede vnto &thorn;e pope vrban</L>
<L N="306">Til vrban bro&thorn;er myn quod valirian</L>
<L>Quod tyburce wilt &thorn;ou me &thorn;ider lede /</L>
<L N="308">Me &thorn;enke&thorn; &thorn;at it were a wonder dede /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="45" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(45)</HEAD>
<L N="309">Ne menist &thorn;ou nat vrban quod he &thorn;o</L>
<L>That is so ofte dampned to be deed</L>
<L>And wone&thorn; in halkes alway to and fro</L>
<L>And dar nou&yogh;t oones putte for&thorn; his heed</L>
<L N="313">Men schold him brenne in a fuyr so reed</L>
<L>If he were founde or if men might him spye</L>
<L N="315">And we also to bere him companye</L>
</LG>
<LG N="46" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(46)</HEAD>
<L N="316">And whil we seken &thorn;ilke diuinite</L>
<L>That is I-hyd in heuen priuely</L>
<L>Algate I-brent in &thorn;is world schal we be</L>
<L>To whom Cecilie answerde bodyly</L>
<L N="320">Men mighten wel and skilfully</L>
<L>This lyf to lese myn oughne dere brother</L>
<L N="322">If &thorn;is were lyuyng oonly and noon o&thorn;er</L>
</LG>
<LG N="47" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(47)</HEAD>
<L N="323">But &thorn;er is better lif in o&thorn;er place</L>
<L>That neuer schal be lost drede &thorn;e nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>which goddes sone vs tolde &thorn;urgh his grace</L>
<L>The fadres sone &thorn;at alle &thorn;ing hath wrought</L>
<L N="327">And al &thorn;at wrought is wi&thorn; a skilful &thorn;ought</L>
<L>The gost &thorn;at fro &thorn;e fader gan procede</L>
<L N="329">ha&thorn; sowled hem wi&thorn;outen eny drede
<PB REF="00000391.tif" N="379"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="539"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="48" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(48)</HEAD>
<L N="330">By word and miracle hihe goddes sone</L>
<L>whan he was in &thorn;is world declared heere /</L>
<L>That &thorn;er was o&thorn;er lyf &thorn;er men may wone /</L>
<L>To whom answerde Tyburce of suster deere</L>
<L N="334">Ne seydest &thorn;ou right now in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>Ther nys but oo god. o .lord. in so&thorn;fastnesse</L>
<L N="336">And now of &thorn;re how maystow bere witnesse<MILESTONE N="166b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="49" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(49)</HEAD>
<L N="337">That schal I telle quod sche er &thorn;at I go</L>
<L>Right as a man ha&thorn; sapiences &thorn;re</L>
<L>Memorie eyen and intellect also</L>
<L>So in oo being in diuinite</L>
<L N="341">Thre persones may &thorn;er right wel be</L>
<L>Tho gan sche him ful besily to preche /</L>
<L N="343">Of cristes come and of his peynes teche /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="50" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(50)</HEAD>
<L N="344">And many pointes of his passioun</L>
<L>how goddes sone in &thorn;is world was wi&thorn;holde</L>
<L>To doon mankynde pleyn remissioun</L>
<L>That was I-bounde in synne and cares colde /</L>
<L N="348">Al &thorn;is &thorn;ing sche vnto Tyburce tolde /</L>
<L>And after &thorn;is thiburce in good entente</L>
<L N="350">wi&thorn; valirian to pope vrban he wente /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="51" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(51)</HEAD>
<L N="351">That &thorn;anked god and wi&thorn; glad hert and light</L>
<L>he cristened him and made him in &thorn;at place /</L>
<L>Parfyt in his lernynge goddes knyght</L>
<L>And after &thorn;is thiburce gat such grace /</L>
<L N="355">That euery day he say in tyme and space /</L>
<L>The aungel of god and euery maner boone /</L>
<L N="357">That he god asked / it were sped ful soone
<PB REF="00000392.tif" N="380"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="540"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="52" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(52)</HEAD>
<L N="358">IT were ful hard by ordre for to sayne</L>
<L>how many wondres Ihc for hem wroughte</L>
<L>But atte last to tellen schort and playne &middot;</L>
<L>The sergeant&yogh; of &thorn;e toun of Rome hem soughte</L>
<L N="362">And hem byforn almache &thorn;e prefect broughte</L>
<L>which hem apposed and knew alle here entente</L>
<L N="364">And to &thorn;e ymage of Iubiter hem sente</L>
</LG>
<LG N="53" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(53)</HEAD>
<L N="365">And saide who-so wil not sacrifise</L>
<L>Swope of his heued &thorn;is my sentence heere</L>
<L>Anoon &thorn;ese martires &thorn;at I &yogh;ou deuyse</L>
<L>Oon maximus &thorn;at was an officere /</L>
<L N="369">Of &thorn;e prefectes and his counceilere /</L>
<L>hem hent . and whan he for&thorn; &thorn;e seyntes ladde</L>
<L N="371">him self he wept for pite &thorn;at he hadde /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="54" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(54)</HEAD>
<L N="372">Whan maximus had herd &thorn;e seintes lore</L>
<L>he gat him of his tormentoures leue</L>
<L>And bad hem to his hous wi&thorn;outen more<MILESTONE N="167a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And with her preching er &thorn;at it were eue</L>
<L N="376">Thay gonne fro &thorn;e tormentoures to reue</L>
<L>And fro maxime and fro his folk echoone</L>
<L N="378">The false faith to trowe in god alloone</L>
</LG>
<LG N="55" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(55)</HEAD>
<L N="379">Cecilie cam whan it was waxen night</L>
<L>with prestis &thorn;at hem cristenid alle in feere /</L>
<L>And afterward whan day was waxen light</L>
<L>Cecilie hem sayde with a ful stedefast chere /</L>
<L N="383">Now cristes owne kny&yogh;tes leef and deere</L>
<L>Cast al away &thorn;e werkes of derknes</L>
<L N="385">And armith &yogh;ou in armur of brightnes
<PB REF="00000393.tif" N="381"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="541"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="56" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(56)</HEAD>
<L N="386">&YOGH;e han forso&thorn;e y-doon a greet batayle /</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure cours is doon &yogh;oure faith han &yogh;e conserued</L>
<L>Go&thorn; to &thorn;e coroun of lyf &thorn;at may not fayle /</L>
<L>The rightful iugge which &thorn;at &yogh;e han serued</L>
<L N="390">Schal &yogh;eue it &yogh;ow as &yogh;e han it deserued</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is &thorn;ing was sayd as I deuyse</L>
<L N="392">Men ladde hem for&thorn; to doon &thorn;e sacrifise /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="57" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(57)</HEAD>
<L N="393">But/ whan &thorn;ey were to &thorn;e place y-brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>To telle schortly &thorn;e conclusioun</L>
<L>They nolde encense ne sacrifice right nought</L>
<L>But on her knees &thorn;ey setten hem adoun</L>
<L N="397">wi&thorn; humble hert and sad deuocioun</L>
<L>And leften bo&thorn;e her heedes in &thorn;e place</L>
<L N="399">here soules wenten to &thorn;e king of grace /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="58" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(58)</HEAD>
<L N="400">This maximus &thorn;at say &thorn;is king betyde /</L>
<L>wi&thorn; pitous teeres tolde it anoon right</L>
<L>That he here soules saugh to heuen glyde</L>
<L>with aungels ful of clernes and of light</L>
<L N="404">And with his word conuerted many a wight</L>
<L>For which almachius dede him so bete</L>
<L N="406">with whippes of leed til he his lif gan lete /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="59" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(59)</HEAD>
<L N="407">Cecilie him took and buried him anoon</L>
<L>By Thiburce and valirian softely</L>
<L>wi&thorn;inne hire berieng place vnder &thorn;e stoon</L>
<L>And after &thorn;is almachius hastily</L>
<L N="411">Bad his ministres fecchen openly</L>
<L>Cecilie. so &thorn;at sche might in his presence<MILESTONE N="167b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="413">Doon sacrifice and Iubiter encense /
<PB REF="00000394.tif" N="382"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="542"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="60" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(60)</HEAD>
<L N="414">But &thorn;ey conuerted at hir wise lore</L>
<L>wepten ful sore and &yogh;auen ful credence</L>
<L>Vnto hir word and cryden more and more</L>
<L>Crist goddes sone wi&thorn;outen difference</L>
<L N="418">Is verray god &thorn;is is al oure sentence /</L>
<L>That ha&thorn; so good a seruaunt him to serue</L>
<L N="420">This with oon vois we trowen &thorn;ough we sterue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="61" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(61)</HEAD>
<L N="421">Almachius &thorn;at herd of &thorn;is doynge</L>
<L>Bad fecchen Cecilie &thorn;at he might hir se</L>
<L>And al&thorn;er first lo &thorn;is was his axinge</L>
<L>what maner womman art &thorn;ou quod he</L>
<L N="425">I am a gentil womman born quod sche</L>
<L>I axe &thorn;e quod he though &thorn;e it greue</L>
<L N="427">Of &thorn;i religioun and of &thorn;i byleue /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="62" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(62)</HEAD>
<L N="428">&YOGH;e han bygonne &yogh;our questioun folily</L>
<L>Quod sche &thorn;at wolden tuo answers conclude /</L>
<L>In oo demaunde &yogh;e axen lewedly</L>
<L>Almache answerde to &thorn;at similitude</L>
<L N="432">Of whens come&thorn; &thorn;in answering so rude</L>
<L>Of whens quod sche whan sche was I-freyned</L>
<L N="434">Of conscience and good faith vnfeyned</L>
</LG>
<LG N="63" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(63)</HEAD>
<L N="435">Almachius sayde takest &thorn;ou noon heede /</L>
<L>Of my power and sche answerde him &thorn;is /</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure might quod sche ful litel is to drede /</L>
<L>For euery mortal mannes power nys</L>
<L N="439">But lyk a bladder ful of wynd I-wis</L>
<L>For with a nedeles poynt what it is blowe /</L>
<L N="441">May al &thorn;e bost of it be layd ful lowe /
<PB REF="00000395.tif" N="383"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="543"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="64" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(64)</HEAD>
<L N="442">Ful wrongfully bygan &thorn;ou quod he /</L>
<L>And &yogh;et in wrong is &thorn;y perseueraunce</L>
<L>wostow nough how oure mighty princes fre</L>
<L>han &thorn;us comaunded and maad ordinaunce</L>
<L N="446">That euery cristen wight schal haue penaunce /</L>
<L>But if &thorn;at he his cristendom wi&thorn;seye</L>
<L N="448">And goon al quyt if he wil it reneye /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="65" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(65)</HEAD>
<L N="449">&para; &YOGH;oure princes erre as &yogh;oure nobleye do&thorn;</L>
<L>Quo&thorn; &thorn;o Cecilie and with a wood sentence /<MILESTONE N="168a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;e make vs gulty and it is nou&yogh;t so&thorn;</L>
<L>For &yogh;e &thorn;at knowen wel oure Innocence</L>
<L N="453">For as moche as we doon reuerence /</L>
<L>To crist and for we bere a cristen name</L>
<L N="455">&yogh;e putten on vs a crym and eek a blame /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="66" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(66)</HEAD>
<L N="456">But we &thorn;at knowen &thorn;ilke name so</L>
<L>For vertuous we may it not wi&thorn;seye</L>
<L>Almache sayde cheese oon of &thorn;ese tuo</L>
<L>Do sacrifice and cristendom reneye</L>
<L N="460">&thorn;at &thorn;ou mow now eschapen by &thorn;at weye</L>
<L>At which &thorn;e holy blisful faire mayde /</L>
<L N="462">Gan for to laughe and to &thorn;e Iugge sayde /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="67" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(67)</HEAD>
<L N="463">O Iugge confus in &thorn;is nycete</L>
<L>wilt &thorn;ou &thorn;at I refuse Innocence</L>
<L>To make me a wikked wight quod sche /</L>
<L>lo he dissimule&thorn; heer in audience</L>
<L N="467">he starith and woodith in his aduertence</L>
<L>To whom almachius sayde vnsely wrecche /</L>
<L N="469">Ne wostow nought how fer my might may strecche
<PB REF="00000396.tif" N="384"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="544"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="68" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(68)</HEAD>
<L N="470">Han nought our mighty princes to me y-&yogh;iuen</L>
<L>&YOGH;e bothe power and eek auctorite</L>
<L>To make folk to deyen or to lyuen</L>
<L>why spekestow so proudly &thorn;an to me</L>
<L N="474">I speke not but stedefastly quod sche</L>
<L>Nought proudly for I say as for my syde /</L>
<L N="476">we haten deedly &thorn;ilke vice of pryde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="69" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(69)</HEAD>
<L N="477">And if &thorn;ou drede nou&yogh;t a so&thorn; to heere</L>
<L>Than wol I schewe al openly by right</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou hast maad a ful greet lesyng heere</L>
<L>Thou saist &thorn;y princes han I-&yogh;iue &thorn;e might</L>
<L N="481">Bo&thorn;e for to sleen and eek to quike a wight</L>
<L>Thou &thorn;at ne maist but oonly lif byreue</L>
<L N="483">Thou hast noon o&thorn;er power ne no leue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="70" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(70)</HEAD>
<L N="484">But &thorn;ou maist sayn &thorn;i princes han &thorn;e maked</L>
<L>Minister of de&thorn; for if &thorn;ou speke of moo</L>
<L>Thow liest for &thorn;y power is ful naked</L>
<L>Do way &thorn;y lewednes sayd almachius &thorn;o</L>
<L N="488">And do sacrifice to oure goddes er &thorn;ou go<MILESTONE N="168b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I recche nought what wrong &thorn;at &thorn;ou me profre /</L>
<L N="490">For I can suffre it as a philosophre</L>
</LG>
<LG N="71" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(71)</HEAD>
<L N="491">But &thorn;ilke wronges may I not endure</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou spekis of oure goddis her quod he</L>
<L>Cecilie answered. O nice creature</L>
<L>Thou saydest no word sins &thorn;ou spak to me /</L>
<L N="495">That I ne knew &thorn;er-wi&thorn; &thorn;y nicete /</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ou were in euery maner wise /</L>
<L N="497">A lewed officer a vein Iustise/
<PB REF="00000397.tif" N="385"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="545"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="72" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(72)</HEAD>
<L N="498">Ther lakketh no &thorn;ing to &thorn;in outer eyen</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou art blynd for &thorn;ing &thorn;at we seen alle</L>
<L>That it is stoon &thorn;at men may wel aspien /</L>
<L>That ilke stoon a god &thorn;ou wilt it calle /</L>
<L N="502">I rede &thorn;e let &thorn;in hond vpon it falle /</L>
<L>And tast it wel and stoon &thorn;ou schalt it fynde</L>
<L N="504">Si&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ou seest / not wi&thorn; &thorn;in ey&yogh;en blynde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="73" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(73)</HEAD>
<L N="505">IT is a schame &thorn;at &thorn;e poeple schal</L>
<L>So scorne &thorn;e and laughe at &thorn;i folye /</L>
<L>For comunly men woot it wel ouer al</L>
<L>That mighty god is in his heuen hye</L>
<L N="509">And &thorn;ese ymages wel &thorn;ou mayst espie</L>
<L>To &thorn;e ne to hemself may nought profyte</L>
<L N="511">For in effect. &thorn;ey ben nou&yogh;t wor&thorn; a myte</L>
</LG>
<LG N="74" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(74)</HEAD>
<L N="512">Thise wordes and such o&thorn;er sayde sche</L>
<L>And he wax wro&thorn; and bad men schold hir lede</L>
<L>hom to hir hous / and in hir hous quod he /</L>
<L>Brenne hir right in a bath of flammes rede /</L>
<L N="516">And as he bad right so was doon &thorn;e dede /</L>
<L>For in a bath &thorn;ay gonne hir faste schetten</L>
<L N="518">And nyght and day great fuyr &thorn;ey vnder betten</L>
</LG>
<LG N="75" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(75)</HEAD>
<L N="519">The longe night and eek a day also</L>
<L>For al &thorn;e fuyr and eek &thorn;e ba&thorn;es hete</L>
<L>Sche sat al cold and felte of no woo</L>
<L>Hit made hir not. oon drope for to swete</L>
<L N="523">But in &thorn;at bath hir lif sche moste lete</L>
<L>For he almachius with ful wikke entente</L>
<L N="525">To sleen hir in &thorn;e ba&thorn; his sondes sente
<PB REF="00000398.tif" N="386"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="546"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="76" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(76)</HEAD>
<L N="526">Thre strokes in &thorn;e nek he smot hir &thorn;o<MILESTONE N="169a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>The tormentour but for no maner chaunce /</L>
<L>he might nou&yogh;t smyte hir faire necke a-tuo /</L>
<L>And for &thorn;er was &thorn;at tyme an ordinaunce</L>
<L N="530">That no man scholde do man such penaunce</L>
<L>The fer&thorn;e strok to smyten softe or sore /</L>
<L N="532">This tormentour ne dorste do no more /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="77" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(77)</HEAD>
<L N="533">But half deed with hir nekke coruen there</L>
<L>he laft hir lye and on his way he went</L>
<L>The cristen folk which &thorn;at about hir were /</L>
<L>wi&thorn; scheetes han &thorn;e body ful faire y-hent</L>
<L N="537">&thorn;re dayes lyued sche in &thorn;is torment</L>
<L>And neuer cessed hem &thorn;e faith to teche /</L>
<L N="539">That sche had suffred hem sche gan to preche</L>
</LG>
<LG N="78" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(78)</HEAD>
<L N="540">And hem sche &yogh;af hir moebles and hir &thorn;ing</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e pope Vrban bytook hem &thorn;o /</L>
<L>And sayd I axe &thorn;is of heuen kyng</L>
<L>To haue respit &thorn;re dayes and no mo</L>
<L N="544">To recomende to &yogh;ow er &thorn;at I go</L>
<L>These soules lo and &thorn;at I mighte do wirche</L>
<L N="546">heer of myn hous perpetuelly a chirche</L>
</LG>
<LG N="79" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(79)</HEAD>
<L N="547">Seynt vrban wi&thorn; his Dekenes priuely</L>
<L>The body fette and buried it by nighte /</L>
<L>Among his o&thorn;er seyntes honestely</L>
<L>hir hous &thorn;e chirch of seynt Cecily &yogh;it highte</L>
<L N="551">Seynt vrban halwed it as he wel mighte</L>
<L>In which in to &thorn;is day in noble wyse</L>
<L N="553">Men doon to crist and to his seint seruise /</L>
<L>Here endeth &thorn;e secounde Nonne hir tale of &thorn;e lif of seint Cecilie<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000399.tif" N="387">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="547">
<HEAD>And here bygynneth &thorn;e tale of &thorn;e Chanouns &yogh;eman<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; prologus</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan ended was &thorn;e lif/ of seynt Cecile</L>
<L>Er we fully had riden fyue myle</L>
<L>At/ Boughtoun vnder blee vs gan atake</L>
<L N="557">A man &thorn;at clo&thorn;ed was in clo&thorn;es blake</L>
<L>And vnder &thorn;at he had a whit surplice</L>
<L>his hakeney &thorn;at was a pomely grice</L>
<L>So swete &thorn;at it wonder was to se</L>
<L N="561">It semed he hadde priked myles &thorn;re /</L>
<L>The hors eek &thorn;at his &yogh;yman rood vpon<MILESTONE N="169b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So swette &thorn;at vnne&thorn;es might he goon</L>
<L>Aboute &thorn;e peytrel stood &thorn;e foom ful hye</L>
<L N="565">he was of foom as flekked as a pye</L>
<L>A male tweyfold on his croper lay</L>
<L>It semed &thorn;at he caried litel array</L>
<L>And light for somer rood &thorn;is wor&thorn;y man</L>
<L N="569">And in myn herte wondren I bigan</L>
<L>what &thorn;at he was til &thorn;at I vnderstood</L>
<L>how &thorn;at his cloke was sowed vnto his hood</L>
<L>For which whan I long had auysed me /</L>
<L N="573">I demed him som chanoun for to be</L>
<L>his hat heng at his bak doun by a laas</L>
<L>For he had riden more &thorn;an trot or paas /</L>
<L>He had I-pryked lik as he were wood</L>
<L N="577">A cloote leef he had vnder his hood</L>
<L>For swoot and for to kepe his heed from hete</L>
<L>But it was ioye for to se him swete</L>
<L>His forhed dropped as a stillatorie</L>
<L N="581">were ful of plantayn and of peritorie
<PB REF="00000400.tif" N="388"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="548"></L>
<L>And whanne &thorn;at he was com he gan to crie</L>
<L>God saue quod he &thorn;is ioly compaignye/</L>
<L>Fast haue I priked quod he for &yogh;our sake /</L>
<L N="585">By cause &thorn;at I wolde &yogh;ou atake</L>
<L>To ryden in &thorn;is mery companye /</L>
<L>his &yogh;eman eek was ful of curtesye /</L>
<L>He seid sires now in &thorn;e morwe tyde /</L>
<L N="589">Out of &yogh;our ostelry I saugh &yogh;ou ryde /</L>
<L>And warned heer my lord and my souerayn</L>
<L>which &thorn;at to ryden with &yogh;ow is ful fayn</L>
<L>For his desport/ he loueth daliaunce</L>
<L N="593">Frend for &thorn;y warnyng god &yogh;eue &thorn;e good chaunce</L>
<L>Sayde oure host for certes it wolde seme</L>
<L>Thy lord were wys and so I may wel deme</L>
<L>he is ful iocound also dar I leye</L>
<L N="597">Can he ought telle a mery tale or tweye</L>
<L>with which he glade may &thorn;is companye</L>
<L>who sire my lord / &yogh;e &yogh;e / wi&thorn;oute lye /</L>
<L>He can of merthe and eek of Iolite<MILESTONE N="170a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="601">Not but ynough also sir truste&thorn; me</L>
<L>And &yogh;e him knewe / as wel as do I</L>
<L>&yogh;e wolde wonder how wel and &thorn;riftily</L>
<L>he cou&thorn;e werke and &thorn;at in sondry wise</L>
<L N="605">he ha&thorn; take on him many sondry emprise /</L>
<L>which were ful hard for eny &thorn;at is heere</L>
<L>To bringe aboute but &thorn;ay of him it leere /</L>
<L>As homely as he ryt amonges &yogh;ow</L>
<L N="609">If &yogh;e him knewe it wolde be &yogh;oure prow</L>
<L>&YOGH;e nolde nought forgon his aqueyntaunce</L>
<L>For moche good I dar lay in balaunce</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at haue in my possessioun</L>
<L N="613">he is a man of heigh discressioun</L>
<L>I warne &yogh;ow wel he is a passyng man</L>
<L>&para; wel quod our oost/ I pray &thorn;e tel me &thorn;an</L>
<L>Is he a clerk / or noon tel what he is</L>
<L N="617">Nay he is gretter &thorn;an a clerk I-wis;
<PB REF="00000401.tif" N="389"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="549"></L>
<L>Sayde &thorn;e &yogh;yman and in wordes fewe /</L>
<L>Ost and of his craft somwhat I wil &yogh;ou schewe</L>
<L>I say my lord can such subtilite</L>
<L N="621">But al his craft &yogh;e may nought wite of me /</L>
<L>And somwhat helpe I &yogh;it to his worchynge</L>
<L>That al &thorn;is ground on which we ben ridynge</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at we comen ro Caunterbury toun</L>
<L N="625">he cou&thorn;e al clene turnen vp so doun</L>
<L>And paue it al of siluer and of gold</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is &yogh;eman hadde &thorn;us I-told</L>
<L>vnto oure oost / he seyde benedicite</L>
<L N="629">This is wonder merueylous to me</L>
<L>Syn &thorn;at &thorn;is lord is of so heigh prudence</L>
<L>By cause of which men schuld him reuerence /</L>
<L>That of his worchip rekke&thorn; he so lite</L>
<L N="633">his ouer slop it is not wor&thorn; a myte</L>
<L>As in effect/ to him so mot / I go</L>
<L>It is al bawdy and to-tore also</L>
<L>why is &thorn;i lord so slottisch I &thorn;e preye</L>
<L N="637">And is of power better clo&thorn;is to beye /</L>
<L>If &thorn;at his dede accorde with &thorn;y speehe /<MILESTONE N="170b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Telle me &thorn;at and &thorn;at I &thorn;e biseche /</L>
<L>&para; why quod &thorn;is &yogh;yman / wher-to axe &yogh;e me</L>
<L N="641">God help me so for he schal neuer &thorn;e</L>
<L>But I wol nought avowe &thorn;at I say</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfor kep it secre I &yogh;ou pray</L>
<L>he is to wys in faith as I bileue</L>
<L N="645">That at is ouer-don it wil nou&yogh;t preue /</L>
<L>a right. as clerkes sein it is a vice</L>
<L>wherfore in &thorn;at I holde him lewed and nyce</L>
<L>For whan a man ha&thorn; ouer greet a witte</L>
<L N="649">Ful ofte him happeth to mysvsen itte</L>
<L>So doth my lord and &thorn;at me greue&thorn; sore</L>
<L>God it amende I can say now nomore</L>
<L>Ther-of no fors good &yogh;eman quod oure Ost</L>
<L N="653">Syn of &thorn;e connyng of &thorn;i lord &thorn;ou wost
<PB REF="00000402.tif" N="390"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="550"></L>
<L>Tel how he do&thorn; I pray &thorn;e hertily</L>
<L>Sin &thorn;at he is so crafty and so sly</L>
<L>wher duellen &yogh;e if it to telle be</L>
<L N="657">In &thorn;e subarbes of a toun quod he /</L>
<L>lurking in hirnes and in lanes blynde</L>
<L>wher as &thorn;ese robbours and &thorn;eues by kynde /</L>
<L>holden here prive ferful residence</L>
<L N="661">As &thorn;ay &thorn;at dor nou&yogh;t schewen her presence /</L>
<L>So faren we if I schal say &thorn;e so&thorn;e</L>
<L>Now quod oure ost &yogh;it let me talke to&thorn;e</L>
<L>why artow discoloured on &thorn;y face</L>
<L N="665">Peter quod he god &yogh;iue it harde grace</L>
<L>I am so vsed in &thorn;e fuyr to blowe</L>
<L>That it ha&thorn; chaunged my colour I trowe</L>
<L>I am not wont in no mirour to prie</L>
<L N="669">But swynke sore and lerne to multiplie</L>
<L>we blondren euer and pouren in &thorn;e fuyr</L>
<L>And for al &thorn;at we faile of oure desir</L>
<L>For euer we lacken oure conclusioun</L>
<L N="673">To moche folk we ben illusioun</L>
<L>And borwe gold be it a pound or tuo</L>
<L>Or ten or twelue or many sommes mo</L>
<L>And make hem wenen atte leste weye<MILESTONE N="171a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="677">That of a pound we conne make tweye</L>
<L>&YOGH;it is it fals and ay we han good hope</L>
<L>It for to doon and after it we grope /</L>
<L>But &thorn;at science is so fer vs biforn</L>
<L N="681">we mowen nou&yogh;t al &thorn;ough we had it sworn</L>
<L>It ouertake it slyt away so fast</L>
<L>It wol vs make beggers atte last</L>
<L>Whil &thorn;is &yogh;eman was &thorn;us in his talkyng</L>
<L N="685">This chanoun drough him ner and herd al &thorn;ing</L>
<L>which &thorn;at &thorn;is &yogh;iman spak for suspeccioun</L>
<L>Of mennes speche euer hadde &thorn;is chanoun</L>
<L>For Catoun sai&thorn; &thorn;at he &thorn;at gulty is</L>
<L N="689">Deme&thorn; al &thorn;ing be spoke of him I-wis
<PB REF="00000403.tif" N="391"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="551"></L>
<L>By cause of &thorn;at / he gan so neigh to drawe</L>
<L>his &yogh;eman &thorn;at he herde al his sawe /</L>
<L>And &thorn;us he sayd vnto his &yogh;eman &thorn;o</L>
<L N="693">Hold now &thorn;i pees and spek no wordes mo</L>
<L>For if &thorn;ou do &thorn;ou schalt it deere abye</L>
<L>Thow sclaundrest me here in &thorn;is companye</L>
<L>And eek discouerest &thorn;at &thorn;ou schuldest hide</L>
<L N="697">&YOGH;e quod oure ost tel on what so bytyde</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;is thretyng recche &thorn;e nought a myte</L>
<L>In fai&thorn; quod he no more do I but lite</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is chanoun seih it wold not be</L>
<L N="701">But his &yogh;eman wold telle his priuete</L>
<L>He fledde a way for verray sorwe and schame</L>
<L>A quod &thorn;is &yogh;eman her schal arise game</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at I can anoon now wol I telle</L>
<L N="705">Sin he is goon &thorn;e foule feend him quelle</L>
<L>For neuer her after wol I wi&thorn; him meete</L>
<L>For peny ne for pound I wol byheete</L>
<L>he &thorn;at me broughte first vnto &thorn;at game</L>
<L N="709">Er &thorn;at he deye sorwe haue he and schame</L>
<L>For it is ernest to me by my fayth</L>
<L>That fele I wel what so eny man saith</L>
<L>And &yogh;et for al my smert and al my greef</L>
<L N="713">For al my sorwe and labour and mescheef</L>
<L>I cou&thorn;e neuer leue it in no wise<MILESTONE N="171b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Now wolde god my wyt mighte suffise</L>
<L>To tellen al &thorn;at longe&thorn; to &thorn;at art/</L>
<L N="717">But na&thorn;eles &yogh;et wil I telle &yogh;ou part</L>
<L>Sin &thorn;at my lord is goon I wol nought spare</L>
<L>Such &thorn;ing al &thorn;at I knowe I wol declare<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">


<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000404.tif" N="392">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="552">
<HEAD>[THE PREAMBLE.]<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Narrat</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WIth &thorn;is Chanoun I duelled haue seuen &yogh;er</L>
<L N="721">And of his science am I neuer &thorn;e ner</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at I hadde I haue lost &thorn;er by</L>
<L>And god wot/ so ha&thorn; many mo &thorn;an I /</L>
<L>Ther I was wont to be right freisch and gay</L>
<L N="725">Of clo&thorn;ing and of o&thorn;er good array /</L>
<L>Now may I were an hose vpon myn heed</L>
<L>And where my colour was bo&thorn;e freissch and reed</L>
<L>Now it is wan and of a leden hewe</L>
<L N="729">who-so it vse&thorn; sore schal he rewe</L>
<L>And of my swynk &yogh;et blended is myn ye</L>
<L>Lo such auauntage it is to multiplie</L>
<L>That slydynge science had me made so bare /</L>
<L N="733">That I haue no good wher &thorn;at euer I fare</L>
<L>And &yogh;it I am endetted so &thorn;er by</L>
<L>Of gold I haue borwed trewely</L>
<L>That whil I lyue I schal it quite neuer</L>
<L N="737">lat euery man be war by me for euer</L>
<L>what maner man &thorn;at caste&thorn; him &thorn;erto</L>
<L>If he continue I holde his &thorn;rift I-do</L>
<L>For so help me god &thorn;er by schal he not wynne</L>
<L N="741">But empte his purs and make his wittes &thorn;ynne</L>
<L>And whan he &thorn;urgh his madnes and folye /</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; lost his owne good in ieupardie /</L>
<L>Than he excite&thorn; o&thorn;er men &thorn;er-to</L>
<L N="745">To leese her good as he himself ha&thorn; do</L>
<L>For vnto schrewes ioye it is and ese /</L>
<L>To haue here felawes in peyne and desese /
<PB REF="00000405.tif" N="393"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="553"></L>
<L>Thus was I oones lerned of a clerk /</L>
<L N="749">Of &thorn;at no charge I wol speke of oure werk</L>
<L>whan we ben &thorn;er as we schul exercise</L>
<L>Oure eluyssh craft we seme wonder wyse</L>
<L>Oure termes ben so clergeal and queynte /<MILESTONE N="172a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="753">I blowe &thorn;e fuyr til &thorn;at/ myn herte feynte /</L>
<L>what schulde I telle ech proporcioun</L>
<L>Of &thorn;inges which &thorn;at we werke vp and doun</L>
<L>As an fyue or six ounces may wel be /</L>
<L N="757">Of siluer or som o&thorn;er quantite</L>
<L>And besy me to telle &yogh;ow &thorn;e names</L>
<L>Of Orpiment brent bones yren squames</L>
<L>That in to poudre grounden ben ful smal</L>
<L N="761">And in an erthen pot/ how &thorn;at put is al</L>
<L>And salt y-put in and also paupere</L>
<L>Biforn these poudres &thorn;at I speke of heere</L>
<L>And wel I-couered wi&thorn; a lamp of glas /</L>
<L N="765">And of moche o&thorn;er &thorn;ing what &thorn;at &thorn;er was</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e pot . and glas enlutyng</L>
<L>That of &thorn;e aier mighte passe no &thorn;ing</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e esy fuyr and smert also</L>
<L N="769">which &thorn;at was maad and of &thorn;e care and wo</L>
<L>That we hadde in oure matiers sublymynge</L>
<L>And amalgamynge and calcenynge</L>
<L>Of quyksiluer y-clept mercury crude /</L>
<L N="773">For alle oure sleightes we can nought conclude /</L>
<L>Oure orpiment and sublyment mercurie</L>
<L>Oure grounde litarge / eek on &thorn;e porfurye</L>
<L>Of ech of &thorn;ese of ounces a certayn</L>
<L N="777">Nat helpe&thorn; vs oure labour is in vayn</L>
<L>Ne eek oure spirites ascencioun</L>
<L>Ne eek our matiers &thorn;at lyn al fix a doun</L>
<L>Mowe in oure werkyng vs no &thorn;ing auayle</L>
<L N="781">For lost is al oure labour and trauayle</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e cost on twenty deuelway</L>
<L>Is lost also which we vpon it lay
<PB REF="00000406.tif" N="394"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="554"></L>
<L>Ther is also ful many ano&thorn;er &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="785">That is to oure craft appertenyng</L>
<L>Though I by ordre hem here reherse ne can</L>
<L>By cause &thorn;at I am a lewed man</L>
<L>&YOGH;et wil I telle hem as &thorn;ey come to mynde /</L>
<L N="789">Though I ne conne nought sette hem in her kynde /</L>
<L>As bol armoniak verdegres boras<MILESTONE N="172b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And sondry vessels maad of er&thorn;e and glas</L>
<L>Oure vrinals and oure descensories</L>
<L N="793">Viols Croslets. and sublimatories</L>
<L>Concurbites and alembikes eeke</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ere suche deere ynough a leeke</L>
<L>Nat needith it to rehersen hem alle</L>
<L N="797">watres rubisyng and boles galle</L>
<L>Arsnek Sal armoniak and brimstoon</L>
<L>And herbes cou&thorn;e I telle eek many oon</L>
<L>As Egrimoigne Valirian and lunarie,</L>
<L N="801">And o&thorn;er suche if &thorn;at me list to tarie /</L>
<L>Oure lampes brennyng bo&thorn;e night and day</L>
<L>To bringe aboute oure craft if &thorn;at we may</L>
<L>Oure fournies<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>or</I> fourmes]</NOTE> eek of Calcinacioun</L>
<L N="805">And of watres albificacioun</L>
<L>Vnslekked lym salt and glayre of an ey</L>
<L>Poudres dyuers aissches dong pisse and cley</L>
<L>Cered poketts. Sal petre vitriole</L>
<L N="809">And dyuers fuyres maad of woode and cole /</L>
<L>Salt tartre. alcaly and salt preparat</L>
<L>And combust matieres. and coagulat</L>
<L>Cley maad wi&thorn; hors or mannes her and oyle</L>
<L N="813">Of tartre alym. glas. berm wort and argoyle</L>
<L>Resalgar and oure matiers enbibing</L>
<L>And eek of oure matiers encorporing</L>
<L>And siluer citrinacioun</L>
<L N="817">Oure cementynge and fermentacioun</L>
<L>Oure yngottes testes and many mo</L>
<L>I wol &yogh;ou telle as was me taught also
<PB REF="00000407.tif" N="395"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="555"></L>
<L>The foure spirit&yogh; and &thorn;e bodies seuen</L>
<L N="821">By ordre as ofte herd I my lord neuen</L>
<L>The firste spirit quyksiluer called is</L>
<L>The secound orpiment &thorn;e &thorn;ridde I-wis</L>
<L>Sal armoniac. and &thorn;e fer&thorn;e bremstoon</L>
<L N="825">The bodies seuen eek lo hem heer anoon</L>
<L>Sol gold is and luna siluer we &thorn;repe</L>
<L>Mars yren. Mercurie quyksiluer we clepe</L>
<L>Saturnus leed and Iubiter is tyn<MILESTONE N="173a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="829">And Venus coper by my fader kyn</L>
<L>This cursed craft who so wol excercise</L>
<L>he schal no good han &thorn;at may him suffise /</L>
<L>For al &thorn;e good he spende&thorn; &thorn;er aboute</L>
<L N="833">he lese schal &thorn;er of haue I no doute /</L>
<L>who-so &thorn;at list/ outen his folye</L>
<L>let him come for&thorn; and lerne multiplie</L>
<L>And euery man that ha&thorn; ought in his cofre</L>
<L N="837">Let him appiere and wexe a philosofre</L>
<L>Ascauns &thorn;at craft is so light to lere /</L>
<L>Nay nay god wot al be he monk or frere</L>
<L>Prest Chanoun or eny o&thorn;er wight</L>
<L N="841">Though he sit at his book bo&thorn;e day and night</L>
<L>In lernyng of &thorn;is eluysch nice lore</L>
<L>Al is in vayn and parde moche more</L>
<L>Is to lerne a lewed man &thorn;is subtilte</L>
<L N="845">Fy spek not &thorn;erof. for it it wil not be</L>
<L>Al cou&thorn;e he letterure or cou&thorn;e he noon</L>
<L>As in effect he schal fynd it al oon</L>
<L>For bo&thorn;e tuo by my sauacioun</L>
<L N="849">Concluden in multiplicacioun</L>
<L>I-liche wel whan &thorn;ay han al y-do /</L>
<L>This is to sayn &thorn;ay fayle bo&thorn;e tuo</L>
<L>&YOGH;et for&yogh;at I to moche rehersayle</L>
<L N="853">Of watres corosif and of lymayle</L>
<L>And of bodyes mollificacioun</L>
<L>And also of here enduracioun
<PB REF="00000408.tif" N="396"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="556"></L>
<L>Oyles ablucioun and metal fusible /</L>
<L N="857">To tellen al wold passen eny bible</L>
<L>That owher is wherfore as for &thorn;e best</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;ese names now wil I me rest/</L>
<L>For as I trowe I haue &yogh;ow told ynowe</L>
<L N="861">To reyse a feend al loke he neuer so rowe /</L>
<L>A nay let be &thorn;y philosophre stoon</L>
<L>Elixir clept . we sechen fast echoon</L>
<L>For had we him &thorn;an were we syker ynough</L>
<L N="865">But vnto god of heuen I make avow</L>
<L>For al oure craft whan we han al y-do<MILESTONE N="173b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And al oure sleight he wol not come vs to</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; I-made vs spende moche good</L>
<L N="869">For sorwe of which almost we wexen wood</L>
<L>But &thorn;at good hope crepe&thorn; in oure hert</L>
<L>Supposing euer &thorn;ough we sore smerte /</L>
<L>To ben relieued by him afterward</L>
<L N="873">Supposing and hope is scharp and hard</L>
<L>I warne &yogh;ou wel it is to seken euer</L>
<L>That future temps ha&thorn; made men disseuere</L>
<L>In trust &thorn;erof from al &thorn;at euer &thorn;ey hadde /</L>
<L N="877">&YOGH;et of &thorn;at art &thorn;ay conne nou&yogh;t wexe sadde /</L>
<L>For vnto hem it is a bitter swete</L>
<L>So seme&thorn; it for nad &thorn;ay but a scheete</L>
<L>which &thorn;ay mighte wrappe hem in a night</L>
<L N="881">And a bak to walke Inne by day light</L>
<L>They wolde hem selle and spenden on &thorn;is craft</L>
<L>Thay can nought stinte til no &thorn;ing be laft</L>
<L>And euermore wher &thorn;at euer &thorn;ey goon</L>
<L N="885">Men may hem knowe by smel of bremston</L>
<L>For al &thorn;e world &thorn;ay stynken as a goot</L>
<L>her sauour is so rammyssch and so hoot</L>
<L>That &thorn;ough a man fro hem a myle be /</L>
<L N="889">The sauour wol infecte him truste&thorn; me</L>
<L>Lo &thorn;us by smellyng and by &thorn;redbare array</L>
<L>If &thorn;at men list &thorn;is folk &thorn;ey knowe may /
<PB REF="00000409.tif" N="397"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="557"></L>
<L>And if a man wol aske hem priuely</L>
<L N="893">why &thorn;ay ben clo&thorn;ed so vn&thorn;riftily</L>
<L>Right anoon &thorn;ay rounen in his eere /</L>
<L>And say if &thorn;at &thorn;ay espied were</L>
<L>Men wold hem slee by cause of here science</L>
<L N="897">Lo &thorn;us &thorn;is folk bytrayen Innocence</L>
<L>Passe ouer &thorn;is I go my tale vnto</L>
<L>Er &thorn;an &thorn;e pot be on &thorn;e fuyr y-do</L>
<L>Of metals with a certeyn quantite</L>
<L N="901">My lord hem tempre&thorn; and no man but he</L>
<L>Now he is goon I dar say boldely</L>
<L>For as men sayn he can doon craftily</L>
<L>Algate I wot wel he ha&thorn; such a name<MILESTONE N="174a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="905">And &yogh;et ful ofte he renne&thorn; in blame</L>
<L>&para; And wite &yogh;e how ful ofte it happe&thorn; so</L>
<L>The pot tobreke&thorn; and far wel al is goo</L>
<L>These metals been of so gret violence /</L>
<L N="909">Oure walles may not make hem resistence</L>
<L>But if &thorn;ay were wrought of lym and stoon</L>
<L>Thay percen so and &thorn;urgh &thorn;e wal &thorn;ay goon</L>
<L>And some of hem synken in to &thorn;e grounde/</L>
<L N="913">Thus haue we lost by tymes many a pounde</L>
<L>And some are skatered al &thorn;e floor aboute</L>
<L>Some lepe in to &thorn;e roof wi&thorn;outen doute</L>
<L>Though &thorn;at &thorn;e feend nought in oure sight him schewe /</L>
<L N="917">I trowe &thorn;at he wi&thorn; vs be &thorn;at schrewe /</L>
<L>In helle wher &thorn;at he is lord and sire</L>
<L>Nis &thorn;er no more woo ne anger ne Ire /</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at oure pot is broke as I haue sayd</L>
<L N="921">Euery man chyt and halt him euel a payd</L>
<L>Som sayd it was long on &thorn;e fuyr-makyng</L>
<L>Some sayde nay it was on &thorn;e blowyng</L>
<L>Than was I ferd for &thorn;at was myn office /</L>
<L N="925">Straw quod &thorn;e &thorn;ridde / &yogh;e been lewed and nyce</L>
<L>It was nou&yogh;t tempred as it oughte be /</L>
<L>Nay quod &thorn;e fer&thorn;e stynt and herkne me /
<PB REF="00000410.tif" N="398"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="558"></L>
<L>By cause oure fuyr was nought y-maad of Beech</L>
<L N="929">That is &thorn;e cause and o&thorn;er noon so &thorn;eech</L>
<L>I can not telle wher-on it was long</L>
<L>But wel I woot gret stryf is vs among</L>
<L>What quod my lord &thorn;er is no more to doone /</L>
<L N="933">Of &thorn;ese periles I wol be war eft soone /</L>
<L>I am right siker &thorn;at &thorn;e pot was crased</L>
<L>Be as be may be &yogh;e no &thorn;ing amased</L>
<L>As vsage is let swoope &thorn;e floor as swi&thorn;e</L>
<L N="937">Pluk vp &yogh;our hertes and be&thorn; glad and bli&thorn;e</L>
<L>The mullok on an heep I-swoped was</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e floor y-cast a caneuas</L>
<L>And al &thorn;is mulloc in a syue I-&thorn;rowe /</L>
<L N="941">And sifted and y-plukked many a &thorn;rowe</L>
<L>Par de quod oon somwhat of oure metal<MILESTONE N="174b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;et is &thorn;er heer &thorn;ough &thorn;at we haue nought al</L>
<L>And &thorn;ough &thorn;is &thorn;ing myshapped ha&thorn; a now</L>
<L N="945">Ano&thorn;er tyme it may be wel ynow</L>
<L>Vs moste putte oure good in aduenture</L>
<L>A marchaun / par de may not ay endure</L>
<L>Truste&thorn; me wel in his prosperite</L>
<L N="949">Somtyme his good is drowned in &thorn;e see /</L>
<L>And som tyme come&thorn; it sauf vn-to &thorn;e londe /</L>
<L>Pees quod my lord &thorn;e nexte tyme I wol fonde /</L>
<L>To bringe oure craft al in ano&thorn;er plyte</L>
<L N="953">And but I do sire let me haue &thorn;e wyte</L>
<L>Ther was defaute in som what wel I woot</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er sayde &thorn;e fuyr was ouer hoot</L>
<L>But be it hoot or cold I dar say &thorn;is</L>
<L N="957">That we concluden euermor amys</L>
<L>we faile of &thorn;at which &thorn;at we wolden haue</L>
<L>And in oure madnesse euermore we raue</L>
<L>And whan we ben togideres euerichon</L>
<L N="961">Eueriche man seme&thorn; a Salamon</L>
<L>But al &thorn;ing which &thorn;at schine&thorn; as &thorn;e gold /</L>
<L>Is nought gold as &thorn;at I haue herd told
<PB REF="00000411.tif" N="399"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="559"></L>
<L>Ne euery appel &thorn;at is fair at ye</L>
<L N="965">Ne is not good what so men clappe or crye</L>
<L>Right so lo fareth it amonges vs</L>
<L>He &thorn;at seme&thorn; wisest by Iesus</L>
<L>Is most fool whan it/ come&thorn; to &thorn;e preef</L>
<L N="969">And he &thorn;at semeth trewest is a &thorn;eef</L>
<L>That schul &yogh;e knowe er &thorn;a I fro &yogh;ow wende /</L>
<L>By &thorn;at I of my tale haue maad an ende /<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">


<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000412.tif" N="400">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="560">
<HEAD>[THE TALE.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ther is a chanoun of religioun</L>
<L N="973">Amonges vs wold infecte al a toun</L>
<L>Though it as gret were as was Niniue</L>
<L>Rome alisaundre troye and o&thorn;er &thorn;re /</L>
<L>his sleight and his infinite falsnesse /</L>
<L N="977">Ther cou&thorn;e no man writen as I gesse</L>
<L>Though &thorn;at he mighte lyuen a &thorn;ousand &yogh;eer</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;is world of falsheed nys his peer</L>
<L>For in his termes he wol him so wynde<MILESTONE N="175a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="981">And speke his wordes in so sleygh a kynde</L>
<L>whan he comune schal wi&thorn; eny wight</L>
<L>That he wil make him dote anoon right</L>
<L>But it a feend be as himseluen is</L>
<L N="985">Ful many a man hath he bygiled er this</L>
<L>And wol if &thorn;at/ he lyue may a while /</L>
<L>And &yogh;et men ryde and goon ful many a myle /</L>
<L>Him for to seeke and haue his aqueintaunce /</L>
<L N="989">Nought knowyng of his false gouernaunce</L>
<L>And if &yogh;ow list to &yogh;eue me audience</L>
<L>I wol it telle here in &yogh;oure presence</L>
<L>But worschipful chanouns religious</L>
<L N="993">Ne deme&thorn; nought &thorn;at I sclaundre &yogh;oure hous</L>
<L>Al &thorn;ough my tale of a chanoun be /</L>
<L>Of euery ordre som schrewe is par dee /</L>
<L>And god forbede &thorn;at al a companye</L>
<L N="997">Schulde rewe a singuler mannes folye</L>
<L>To sclaundre &yogh;ow is no &thorn;ing myn entent/</L>
<L>But to correcten &thorn;at is mys I-ment
<PB REF="00000413.tif" N="401"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="561"></L>
<L>This tale was not oonly told for &yogh;ow</L>
<L N="1001">But eek for o&thorn;er moo &yogh;e woot wel how</L>
<L>That among criste apostles twelue /</L>
<L>Ther was no traytour but Iudas himselue</L>
<L>Than why schulde &thorn;e remenaunt haue a blame</L>
<L N="1005">That gulteles were by &yogh;ow I say &thorn;e same</L>
<L>Saue oonly &thorn;is if ye wol herkene me</L>
<L>If any Iudas in &yogh;oure couent be</L>
<L>Remewe him by tyme I &yogh;ow rede /</L>
<L N="1009">If schame or los may causen eny drede /</L>
<L>And be&thorn; no &thorn;ing displesed I &yogh;ou pray</L>
<L>But in &thorn;is caas herkene&thorn; what I say<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Narrat</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN londoun was a prest an annueler</L>
<L N="1013">That &thorn;er In duelled hadde many a &yogh;er</L>
<L>which was so plesaunt and so seruisable /</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e wyf wher as he was at table</L>
<L>That sche wolde suffre him no &thorn;ing for to pay</L>
<L N="1017">For bord ne clo&thorn;ing went he neuer so gay</L>
<L>And spendyng siluer had he right ynough<MILESTONE N="175b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ther-of no force I wol procede as now</L>
<L>And telle for&thorn; my tale of &thorn;e chanoun</L>
<L N="1021">That brought &thorn;is prest to confusioun</L>
<L>This false chanoun cam vpon a day</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e prestes chambre wher he lay</L>
<L>Biseching him to lene him a certeyn</L>
<L N="1025">Of gold and he wold quyt hit him ageyn</L>
<L>Lene me a mark quod he but dayes &thorn;re /</L>
<L>And at my day I wil it quyte &thorn;e /</L>
<L>And if so be &thorn;at &thorn;ou fynde me fals</L>
<L N="1029">Ano&thorn;er day hong/ me vp by &thorn;e hals</L>
<L>This prest him took a mark and &thorn;at as swithe</L>
<L>And &thorn;is Chanoun him &thorn;ankid ofte si&thorn;e</L>
<L>And took his leue and wente for&thorn; his wey</L>
<L N="1033">And atte &thorn;ridde day brought his money /</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e prest he took &thorn;is gold agayn</L>
<L>wher-of &thorn;is prest was wonder glad and fayn
<PB REF="00000414.tif" N="402"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="562"></L>
<L>Certes quod he no &thorn;ing annoye&thorn; me</L>
<L N="1037">To lene a man a noble or tuo or &thorn;re/</L>
<L>Or what &thorn;ing/ were in my possessioun</L>
<L>whan he so trewe is of condicioun</L>
<L>That in no wise he breke wol his day</L>
<L N="1041">To such a man I can neuer say nay</L>
<L>what quod &thorn;is chanoun schold I be vntrewe;</L>
<L>Nay &thorn;at were &thorn;ing I-fallen of &thorn;e newe /</L>
<L>Trou&thorn;e is a &thorn;ing &thorn;at I wol euer kepe /</L>
<L N="1045">Vnto &thorn;at day in which &thorn;at I schal crepe</L>
<L>In to my graue and elles god forbede /</L>
<L>Bilieueth &thorn;is as siker as &yogh;our crede /</L>
<L>God &thorn;ank I and in good tyme be it sayd</L>
<L N="1049">That &thorn;er was neuer man &yogh;et euel a-payd</L>
<L>For gold ne siluer &thorn;at he to me lent</L>
<L>Ne neuer falshed in myn hert I ment</L>
<L>And sire quod he now of my priuete</L>
<L N="1053">Syn &yogh;e so goodlich haue be vnto me</L>
<L>And ky&thorn;ed to me so gret gentilesce</L>
<L>Som-what to quyte wi&thorn; &yogh;oure kyndenesse</L>
<L>I wil &yogh;ow schewe and if &yogh;ow lust/ to lere<MILESTONE N="176a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1057">[<SUP>1</SUP>I wil &yogh;ow teche pleynly the manere<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">[<SUP>1_1</SUP> <I>In a later hand.</I>]</NOTE>]</L>
<L>how I kan werken in philosophie</L>
<L>Takith good heed. &yogh;e schul seen wel at ye</L>
<L>That I wol doon a maystry er I go</L>
<L N="1061">&YOGH;e quod &thorn;e prest . &yogh;e sire and wol &yogh;e so</L>
<L>Mary &thorn;er of I pray &yogh;ow hertily</L>
<L>At &yogh;oure comaundement sire trewely</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;e chanoun and elles god forbede</L>
<L N="1065">Lo how &thorn;is &thorn;eef cou&thorn;e his seruise beede /</L>
<L>Ful soth it is &thorn;at such profred seruise</L>
<L>Stynke&thorn; as witnessen &thorn;ese olde wise</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ful soone I wol it verefye /</L>
<L N="1069">In &thorn;is chanoun roote of al treccherie</L>
<L>That euermor delit ha&thorn; and gladnesse /</L>
<L>Such feendly &thorn;oughtes in his hert empresse
<PB REF="00000415.tif" N="403"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="563"></L>
<L>How cristes poeple he may to meschief bringe</L>
<L N="1073">God kepe vs from his fals dissimilynge /</L>
<L>what wiste &thorn;is prest/ wi&thorn; whom &thorn;at he delte</L>
<L>Ne of his harm comyng he no &thorn;ing felte</L>
<L>O seely prest . o sely Innocent /</L>
<L N="1077">wi&thorn; coueytise anoon &thorn;ou schalt be blent/</L>
<L>O graceles ful blynd is &thorn;y conceyt</L>
<L>No &thorn;ing art &thorn;ou war of &thorn;e deceyt</L>
<L>which &thorn;at &thorn;is fox I-schapen ha&thorn; to &thorn;e</L>
<L N="1081">his wily wrenches y-wis &thorn;ou maist not fle</L>
<L>wherfor to go to &thorn;e conclusioun</L>
<L>That referreth to &thorn;y confusioun</L>
<L>Vnhappy man anoon I wil me hie /</L>
<L N="1085">To tellen &thorn;in vnwitte and &thorn;y folye /</L>
