<L>This multiplying blent so many oon</L>
<L>That in good faith I trowe &thorn;at it be /</L>
<L N="1393">The cause grettest of which skarsete</L>
<L>Philosophres speken so mistyly</L>
<L>In &thorn;is craft &thorn;at men conne not come &thorn;er by
<PB REF="00000424.tif" N="412"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="572"></L>
<L>For any witt &thorn;at men han now on dayes</L>
<L N="1397">They may wel chiteren as doon &thorn;ese iayes</L>
<L>And in here termes sette lust and peyne</L>
<L>But to her purpos schul &thorn;ay neuer atteyne<MILESTONE N="180b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A man may lightly lerne if he haue ought</L>
<L N="1401">To multiplie and bringe his good to nought</L>
<L>Lo such a lucre is in &thorn;is lusty game/</L>
<L>A mannes mir&thorn;e it wol torne in to grame /</L>
<L>And empte also grete and heuy purses</L>
<L N="1405">And make folk to purchace curses</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at han her good &thorn;er-to I-lent</L>
<L>O fy for schame &thorn;ay &thorn;at haue be brent</L>
<L>Allas can &thorn;ay not fle &thorn;e fuyres hete</L>
<L N="1409">&yogh;e &thorn;at it vsen I rede &yogh;e it lete</L>
<L>lest &yogh;e lesen al for bet &thorn;an neuer is late</L>
<L>Neuer to &thorn;riue were to long a date /</L>
<L>Though &yogh;e prolle ay &yogh;e schul it neuer fynde</L>
<L N="1413">&YOGH;e ben as bolde as is bayard &thorn;e blynde</L>
<L>That blundre&thorn; for&thorn; and peril casteth noon</L>
<L>he is as bold to renne a-gayn a stoon</L>
<L>As for to go bysides in &thorn;e wey /</L>
<L N="1417">So fare &yogh;e &thorn;at multiplie I sey</L>
<L>If &thorn;at &yogh;oure y&yogh;en can nought seen aright</L>
<L>loke &thorn;at &yogh;oure mynde lakke nought his sight</L>
<L>For &thorn;ough &yogh;e loke neuer so brode and stare /</L>
<L N="1421">&YOGH;e schul nought wynne vpon &thorn;at chaffare /</L>
<L>But wasten al &thorn;at &thorn;ay may rape and renne</L>
<L>wi&thorn;drawe &thorn;e fuyr lest it so faste brenne</L>
<L>Medle&thorn; no more wi&thorn; &thorn;at art I mene /</L>
<L N="1425">For &yogh;if &yogh;e doon &yogh;oure &thorn;rift is goon ful clene</L>
<L>And right as swithe I wol &yogh;ow telle heere</L>
<L>what &thorn;at &thorn;e philosophres sein in &thorn;is mateere /</L>
<L>&para; lo &thorn;us sai&thorn; arnold of &thorn;e newe toun</L>
<L N="1429">As his Rosarie maketh mencioun</L>
<L>He saith right &thorn;us wi&thorn;outen eny lye</L>
<L>Ther may no man mercury mortifye
<PB REF="00000425.tif" N="413"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="573"></L>
<L>But hit be with his bro&thorn;er knowleching</L>
<L N="1433">how &thorn;at he which &thorn;at first sayd &thorn;is &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Of philosophres fader was hermes</L>
<L>he sai&thorn; how &thorn;e dragoun douteles</L>
<L>he dye&thorn; nought but if &thorn;at he be slayn</L>
<L N="1437">wi&thorn; his bro&thorn;er and &thorn;at is for to sayn<MILESTONE N="181a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>By &thorn;e dragoun mercury and noon o&thorn;er</L>
<L>he vnderstood and brimstoon be his bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>That out of sol and luna were I-drawe</L>
<L N="1441">And &thorn;erfore sayde he take heed to my sawe /</L>
<L>Let no man besy him &thorn;is art to seche /</L>
<L>But &thorn;at he thentencioun and speche /</L>
<L>Of philosophres vnderstonde can</L>
<L N="1445">And if he do he is a lewed man</L>
<L>For &thorn;is sciens and &thorn;is connyng quod he</L>
<L>Is of &thorn;e secre of secret&yogh; par de</L>
<L>Also &thorn;er was a disciple of plato</L>
<L N="1449">That on a tyme sayde his maister to</L>
<L>As his book somer wil bere witnesse</L>
<L>And &thorn;is was his demaunde in sothfastnesse /</L>
<L>Tel me &thorn;e name of &thorn;e priue stoon</L>
<L N="1453">And plato answered vnto him anoon</L>
<L>Take &thorn;e stoon &thorn;at titanos men name /</L>
<L>which is &thorn;at quod he magnasia is &thorn;e same</L>
<L>Sayde plato &yogh;e sire and is it &thorn;us</L>
<L N="1457">This ignotus per ignotius</L>
<L>what is magnasia good sir I &yogh;ou pray</L>
<L>It is a water &thorn;at is maad I say</L>
<L>Of elementes foure quod plato</L>
<L N="1461">Telle me &thorn;e rooche good sire quod he &thorn;o</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at water if it be &yogh;our wille</L>
<L>Nay nay quod plato certeyn &thorn;at I nylle</L>
<L>The philosophres sworn were euerich oon</L>
<L N="1465">That thay scholde discouere it vnto man noon</L>
<L>Ne in no book it write in no manere /</L>
<L>For vnto crist it is so leef and deere
<PB REF="00000426.tif" N="414"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="574"></L>
<L>That he wil not &thorn;at it discouered be /</L>
<L N="1469">But wher it like&thorn; to his deite /</L>
<L>Man to enspire and eek for to defende</L>
<L>whom &thorn;at him like&thorn; lo &thorn;is is &thorn;e ende</L>
<L>Than conclude I &thorn;us syn god of heuene /</L>
<L N="1473">Ne wol not &thorn;at &thorn;e philosophres neuene /</L>
<L>how &thorn;at a man schal come vnto &thorn;is stoon</L>
<L>I rede as for &thorn;e beste let it goon<MILESTONE N="181b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For who-so make&thorn; god his aduersarie</L>
<L N="1477">As for to werke eny &thorn;ing in contrarie</L>
<L>Vnto his wil certes neuer schal he &thorn;riue</L>
<L>Though &thorn;at he multiplie terme of al his lyue</L>
<L>And &thorn;er a poynt for ended is my tale</L>
<L N="1481">God send euery trewe man boote of his bale /</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>&para; Here endeth &thorn;e chanouns &yogh;eman his tale<NOTE>[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="C" TYPE="group">

<PB REF="00000427.tif" N="415">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="303">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>C.</B> FRAGMENT IV.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; 1. THE DOCTOR'S TALE.</HEAD>
<HEAD><B>HARLEIAN MS. 7334</B> (British Museum).</HEAD>
<HEAD>&para; And here bygynneth &thorn;e tale of &thorn;e Doctor of of phisik</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1">Ther was as telle&thorn; Thitus lyuius</L>
<L>A knight &thorn;at cleped was virginieus</L>
<L>Fulfild of honours and of wor&thorn;ines</L>
<L N="4">And strong of frendes and of gret riches</L>
<L>A doughter he hadde by his wyf</L>
<L>And neuer ne hadde he mo in al his lyf</L>
<L>Fair was &thorn;is mayde in excellent beaute</L>
<L N="8">Aboue euery wight that men may se</L>
<L>For nature ha&thorn; wi&thorn; souereyn diligence</L>
<L>I-formed hir in so gret excellence</L>
<L>As &thorn;ough sche wolde say lo I nature</L>
<L N="12">&thorn;us can I forme and peynte a creature</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at/ me lust who can me counterfete</L>
<L>Pigmalion nou&yogh;t &thorn;ough he alwey forge and bete /</L>
<L>Or graue or peynte for I dar wel sayn</L>
<L N="16">appollus &yogh;epherus schulde wirche in vayn</L>
<L>To graue or paynte or forge &amp; bete</L>
<L>If &thorn;ay presumed me to counterfete</L>
<L>For he &thorn;at is &thorn;e former principal</L>
<L N="20">ha&thorn; maad me his viker general</L>
<L>To forme and peynte er&thorn;ely creature</L>
<L>Right as me lust al &thorn;ing is in my cure</L>
<L>Vnder &thorn;e moone &thorn;at may wane and waxe</L>
<L N="24">And for my werke no&thorn;ing wol I axe
<PB REF="00000428.tif" N="416"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="304"></L>
<L>My lord and I ben fully at accord</L>
<L>I made hir to &thorn;e worschip of my lord</L>
<L>So do I alle myn o&thorn;er creatures</L>
<L N="28">what colour &thorn;at &thorn;ay been or what figures /</L>
<L>Thus seme&thorn; me &thorn;at nature wolde say</L>
<L>This mayde was of age twelf &yogh;er and tway<MILESTONE N="182a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In which &thorn;at nature ha&thorn; suche delite</L>
<L N="32">For right as sche can peynte a lili white</L>
<L>And rody a rose right with such peynture</L>
<L>Sche peynted ha&thorn; &thorn;is noble creature</L>
<L>Er sche was born vpon her limes fre</L>
<L N="36">were als bright as such colour schulde be</L>
<L>And phebus deyed hadde hire tresses grete</L>
<L>I-lyk to &thorn;e stremes of his borned hete</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at excellent was hir beaute</L>
<L N="40">A &thorn;ousand fold more vertuous was sche</L>
<L>And hire ne lakke&thorn; no condicioun</L>
<L>That is to preyse as by discrecioun</L>
<L>As wel in body as goost chaste was sche</L>
<L N="44">For which sche floured in virginite</L>
<L>with alle humilite and abstinence</L>
<L>with alle attemperaunce and pacience</L>
<L>with mesure eek and beryng of array</L>
<L N="48">Discret sche was in answeryng alway</L>
<L>Though sche were wis pallas dar I sayn</L>
<L>hir facound eek ful wommanly and playn</L>
<L>Noon countrefeted termes hadde sche</L>
<L N="52">To seme wys but after hir degre</L>
<L>Sche spak and alle hire wordes more and lesse</L>
<L>Sovnyng in vertu and in gentilesse</L>
<L>Schamefast sche was in maydenes schamfastnesse</L>
<L N="56">Constant in hert. and euer in besynesse</L>
<L>To dryue hire out of hir slogardye</L>
<L>Bachus had of hir mou&thorn; no maistrye</L>
<L>For wille and &thorn;ought doon venus encrece</L>
<L N="60">As men in fuyr wil caste oyle or grece
<PB REF="00000429.tif" N="417"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="305"></L>
<L>And of hir oughne vertu vnconstreigned</L>
<L>Sche ha&thorn; ful ofte tyme hire seek y-feyned</L>
<L>For &thorn;at sche wolde fleen &thorn;e companye</L>
<L N="64">wher likly was to treten of folye</L>
<L>As is at festes reueles and at daunces</L>
<L>That ben occasiouns of daliaunces</L>
<L>Such &thorn;inges maken children for to be /</L>
<L N="68">To soone rype and bold . as men may se /<MILESTONE N="182b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>which is ful perilous and ha&thorn; ben &yogh;ore</L>
<L>For al to soone may sche lerne lore</L>
<L>Of boldenesse whan sche is a wyf</L>
<L N="72">And &yogh;e maystresses in &yogh;oure olde lyf</L>
<L>That lordes doughtres han in gouernaunce</L>
<L>Ne take&thorn; of my word no displesaunce /</L>
<L>Thinges &thorn;at ben set in gouernynges</L>
<L N="76">Of lordes dou&yogh;tres oonly for tuo &thorn;inges /</L>
<L>Ou&thorn;er for &yogh;e han kept &yogh;our honeste</L>
<L>O&thorn;er elles for &yogh;e han falle in frelete</L>
<L>And knowe wel y-nough &thorn;e olde daunce</L>
<L N="80">And conne forsake fully meschaunce</L>
<L>For euermo &thorn;erfore for cristes sake /</L>
<L>kepe&thorn; wel &thorn;o &thorn;at &yogh;e vndertake</L>
<L>A &thorn;eof of venesoun &thorn;at ha&thorn; forlaft</L>
<L N="84">his licorousnesse and al his theues craft</L>
<L>Can kepe a forest best of eny man</L>
<L>Now kepe hir wel for and &yogh;e wil &yogh;e can</L>
<L>loke wel to no vice &yogh;e assent</L>
<L N="88">lest &yogh;e be dampned for &yogh;our wikked entent</L>
<L>For who-so do&thorn; a traytour is certayn</L>
<L>And take&thorn; keep of &thorn;at &thorn;at sche schal sayn</L>
<L>Of al tresoun souereyn pestilence</L>
<L N="92">Is whan a wight bytrayeth Innocence</L>
<L>&YOGH;e fadres and &yogh;e modres eek also</L>
<L>Though &yogh;e han children be it oon or mo</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure is &thorn;e charge of al her sufferaunce</L>
<L N="96">whiles &thorn;ay be vnder &yogh;our gouernaunce /
<PB REF="00000430.tif" N="418"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="306"></L>
<L>Beth war &thorn;at by ensample of &yogh;oure lyuynge</L>
<L>Ou&thorn;er by necgligence in chastisynge</L>
<L>That &thorn;ay ne perische for I dar wel seye</L>
<L N="100">If &thorn;at &thorn;ay doon &yogh;e schul ful sore abeye</L>
<L>vnder a schepherd softe and necligent</L>
<L>The wolf ha&thorn; many a schep and lamb torent</L>
<L>Suffice&thorn; oon ensample now as here</L>
<L N="104">For I moot turne a&yogh;ein to my matiere</L>
<L>This mayde of which I telle my tale expresse</L>
<L>So kept hir self hir neded no maystresse<MILESTONE N="183a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For in hir lyuyng maydens mighte rede</L>
<L N="108">As in a book euery good word and dede /</L>
<L>That longe&thorn; vnto a mayden vertuous</L>
<L>Sche was so prudent and so bounteous</L>
<L>For &thorn;e which out sprong on euery syde /</L>
<L N="112">Bo&thorn;e of hir beaute and bounte wyde</L>
<L>That &thorn;urgh &thorn;e lond &thorn;ay praysed hir ilkoone /</L>
<L>That louede vertu saue enuye alloone /</L>
<L>That sory is of o&thorn;er mennes wele /</L>
<L N="116">And glad is of his sorwe and vnhele</L>
<L>The doctor made &thorn;is descripcioun</L>
<L>This mayde wente vpon a day in to &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e temple with hir moder deere</L>
<L N="120">As is of &yogh;onge maydenes &thorn;e manere</L>
<L>Now was &thorn;er a Iustice in &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>That gouernour was of &thorn;at Regioun</L>
<L>And so bifel &thorn;is Iuge his ey&yogh;en cast</L>
<L N="124">Vpon &thorn;is mayde auysing hir ful fast</L>
<L>As sche cam forby &thorn;er &thorn;e Iuge stood</L>
<L>Anoon his herte chaunged and his mood</L>
<L>So was he caught wi&thorn; beaute of &thorn;is mayde</L>
<L N="128">And to himself ful priuely he sayde</L>
<L>This mayde schal be myn for any man</L>
<L>Anoon &thorn;e feend in to his herte ran</L>
<L>And taughte him sodeinly by what slighte</L>
<L N="132">This mayde to his purpos wynne he mighte /
<PB REF="00000431.tif" N="419"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="307"></L>
<L>For certes by no fors ne by no meede</L>
<L>him &thorn;ought he was not able for to speede /</L>
<L>For sche was strong of frendes and eek sche</L>
<L N="136">Conformed was in such souerayn bounte</L>
<L>That wel he wist he might hir neuer wynne</L>
<L>As for to make hir with hir body synne</L>
<L>For which wi&thorn; gret deliberacioun</L>
<L N="140">he sent after a clerk was in &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>The which he knew for subtil and for bold</L>
<L>This Iuge vnto &thorn;e clerk his tale ha&thorn; told</L>
<L>In secre wyse and made him to assure</L>
<L N="144">He schulde telle it to no creature<MILESTONE N="183b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And if he dede he schulde lese his heed</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at assented was &thorn;is cursed reed</L>
<L>Glad was the Iuge and made glad cheere /</L>
<L N="148">And &yogh;af him &yogh;iftes precious and deere /</L>
<L>whan schapen was al &thorn;is conspiracye /</L>
<L>Fro poynt to poynt how &thorn;at his lecherie</L>
<L>Parformed scholde be ful subtilly</L>
<L N="152">As &yogh;e schul here afterward openly /</L>
<L>hom go&thorn; &thorn;is clerk &thorn;at highte Claudius</L>
<L>This false Iuge &thorn;at highte apius</L>
<L>So was his name for it is no fable</L>
<L N="156">But knowen for a storial &thorn;ing notable</L>
<L>The sentence of hit so&thorn; is out of doute</L>
<L>This false iugge go&thorn; now fast aboute /</L>
<L>To hasten his delit al &thorn;at he may /</L>
<L N="160">And so bifel soone after on a day</L>
<L>This false Iuge as telle&thorn; vs &thorn;e story</L>
<L>As he was wont sat in his consistory</L>
<L>And &yogh;af his domes vpon sondry caas</L>
<L N="164">This false clerk com forth a ful good paas</L>
<L>And saide lord if &thorn;at it be &yogh;our wille</L>
<L>As do&thorn; me right vpon &thorn;is pitous bille</L>
<L>In which I pleyne vpon virgilius</L>
<L N="168">And if he wile seyn it is nou&yogh;t &thorn;us
<PB REF="00000432.tif" N="420"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="308"></L>
<L>I wil proue hit and fynde good witnesse</L>
<L>That so&thorn; is &thorn;at my bulle wol expresse /</L>
<L>The Iuge answerd of &thorn;is in his absence</L>
<L N="172">I may not &yogh;iue diffinityf sentence</L>
<L>let do him calle and I wol gladly hiere</L>
<L>Thou schalt haue alle right and no wrong heere</L>
<L>Virginius com to wite &thorn;e Iugges wille /</L>
<L N="176">And right anoon was red &thorn;is cursed bille</L>
<L>The sentence of hit was as &yogh;e schul heere</L>
<L>&para; To &yogh;ow my lord sire apius so deere</L>
<L>Schewe&thorn; &yogh;oure pore seruaunt Claudius</L>
<L N="180">how &thorn;at a knight called Virginius</L>
<L>A&yogh;eins &thorn;e lawe a&yogh;ens alle equyte /</L>
<L>holdeth expresse a&yogh;einst &thorn;e wille of me<MILESTONE N="184a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>My seruaunt which &thorn;at my thral is by right</L>
<L N="184">which fro myn hous was stolen on a night</L>
<L>whiles sche was ful &yogh;ong &thorn;at wol I preue</L>
<L>By witnesse lord so &thorn;at &yogh;e &yogh;ow not greue</L>
<L>Sche is nought his dou&yogh;ter what so he say</L>
<L N="188">wherfore to &yogh;ow my lord &thorn;e Iugge I pray</L>
<L>&YOGH;elde me my &thorn;rall if &thorn;at it be &yogh;our wille</L>
<L>lo &thorn;is was al &thorn;e sentence of &thorn;e bille</L>
<L>Virgineus gan vpon &thorn;e clerk byholde</L>
<L N="192">But hastily er he his tale tolde</L>
<L>he wolde haue proued it as schold a knight</L>
<L>And eek by witnessyng of many a wight</L>
<L>That al was fals &thorn;at sayde his aduersarie</L>
<L N="196">This cursed Iuge wold no lenger tarye /</L>
<L>Ne heere a word more of virgineus</L>
<L>But &yogh;af his Iugement and saide &thorn;us</L>
<L>I deme anoon &thorn;is clerk his seruaunt haue</L>
<L N="200">Thou schalt no lenger in &thorn;in hous hir haue</L>
<L>Go bringe hir for&thorn; and put hir in oure warde</L>
<L>This clerk schal haue his thral thus I a-warde</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is wor&thorn;y knight virgineus</L>
<L N="204">Thurgh &thorn;assent of &thorn;is Iuge apius
<PB REF="00000433.tif" N="421"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="309"></L>
<L>Moste by force his deere dou&yogh;ter &yogh;iuen</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e Iuge in lecchery to lyuen</L>
<L>he go&thorn; him hom and sette him in his halle /</L>
<L N="208">And leet anoon his deere dou&yogh;ter calle /</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; a face deed as aisshen colde</L>
<L>vpon hir humble face he gan byholde</L>
<L>with fadres pite stiking &thorn;orugh his herte</L>
<L N="212">Al wolde he from his purpos not conuerte /</L>
<L>Doughter quod he virginea by &thorn;y name</L>
<L>Ther ben tuo weyes ey&thorn;er de&thorn; or schame</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou most suffre allas &thorn;at I was bore</L>
<L N="216">For neuer &thorn;ou deseruedest wherfore</L>
<L>To deyen with a swerd or with a knyf</L>
<L>O deere doughter ender of my lif</L>
<L>which I haue fostred vp with such plesaunce&middot;</L>
<L N="220">That &thorn;ou nere oute of my remembraunce<MILESTONE N="184b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>O doughter which . &thorn;at art my laste wo</L>
<L>And in &thorn;is lif my laste ioye also</L>
<L>O gemme of chastite in pacience</L>
<L N="224">Tak &thorn;ou &thorn;y deth for &thorn;is is my sentence</L>
<L>For loue and not for hate &thorn;ou most be deed</L>
<L>My pitous hond mot smyten of &thorn;in heed</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;at euer apius &thorn;e say</L>
<L N="228">Thus ha&thorn; he falsly iugged &thorn;e to day</L>
<L>And told hir al &thorn;e caas as &yogh;e bifore</L>
<L>han herd . it nedeth nought to telle it more</L>
<L>Mercy deere fader quod &thorn;is mayde</L>
<L N="232">And with &thorn;at word sche bo&thorn;e hir armes layde /</L>
<L>Aboute his nekke as sche was wont to doo</L>
<L>The teeres brast out of hir ey&yogh;en tuo</L>
<L>And sayde goode fader schal I dye</L>
<L N="236">Is ther no grace is &thorn;er no remedye</L>
<L>No certeyn deere doughter myn quod he /</L>
<L>Than &yogh;eue me leue fader myn quod sche /</L>
<L>My de&thorn; for to compleyne a litel space /</L>
<L N="240">For par dy Ieffa &yogh;af his dou&yogh;ter grace
<PB REF="00000434.tif" N="422"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="310"></L>
<L>For to compleyne er he hir slough allas</L>
<L>And God it woot no &thorn;ing was hir trespas</L>
<L>But &thorn;at sche ran hir fader first/ to se</L>
<L N="244">To welcome him with gret solempnite</L>
<L>And with &thorn;at word a swoun sche fel anoon /</L>
<L>And after whan hir swownyng was agoon</L>
<L>Sche rise&thorn; vp and to hir fader sayde /</L>
<L N="248">Blessed be god &thorn;at I schal deye a mayde /</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue me my deth er &thorn;at I haue a schame</L>
<L>Do with &yogh;our child &yogh;our wille a goddes name</L>
<L>And with &thorn;at word sche prayed him ful ofte</L>
<L N="252">That wi&thorn; his swerd he schulde smyte hir softe</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word on swoune doun sche fel</L>
<L>hir fader with ful sorwful hert and fel</L>
<L>hir heed of smoot and by &thorn;e top it hente</L>
<L N="256">And to &thorn;e Iuge bigan it to presente</L>
<L>As he sat in his doom in concistory</L>
<L>whan the Iuge it say as sai&thorn; the story<MILESTONE N="185a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he bad take him and honge him faste</L>
<L N="260">But right anoon alle &thorn;e poeple in &thorn;raste /</L>
<L>To saue &thorn;e knight for rou&thorn;e and for pite</L>
<L>For knowen was &thorn;e fals iniquite /</L>
<L>The poeple anoon had suspect in &thorn;is &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="264">By moner of &thorn;is clerkes chalengyng</L>
<L>That it was by thassent of apius</L>
<L>That wiste wel &thorn;at he was leccherous</L>
<L>For which vnto &thorn;is Apius &thorn;ay goon</L>
<L N="268">And casten him in prisoun right anoon</L>
<L>wher as he slough himself and Claudius</L>
<L>That servaunt was vnto &thorn;is Apius</L>
<L>was demed for to honge vpon a tree</L>
<L N="272">But virgineus of his grete pite</L>
<L>Prayde for him &thorn;at he was exiled</L>
<L>And elles certes he had ben bigiled</L>
<L>The remenaunt were anhanged more and lesse /</L>
<L N="276">That were consented to &thorn;is cursednesse /
<PB REF="00000435.tif" N="423"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="311"></L>
<L>Her may men se how synne hath his merite</L>
<L>Be war for no man woot how god wol smyte /</L>
<L>In no degre ne in which maner wise</L>
<L N="280">The worm of conscience wol arise</L>
<L>Of wicked lyf &thorn;ough it so pryue be</L>
<L>That no man woot of it but god and he</L>
<L>wher &thorn;at he be lewed man or lered</L>
<L N="284">He not how soone &thorn;at he may be afered</L>
<L>Therfore I rede &yogh;ow this counseil take</L>
<L>Forsakith synne / er synne yow forsake</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Here endeth &thorn;e Doctor of phisique his tale<NOTE>[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000436.tif" N="424">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="312">
<HEAD>&para; And here bygynneth &thorn;e prologe of the Pardoner /</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Owre ost gan swere as he were wood</L>
<L N="288">harrow quod he by nayles and by blood</L>
<L>This was a cursed &thorn;ef a fals Iustice</L>
<L>As schendful de&thorn; as herte can deuise</L>
<L>So falle vpon his body and his boones</L>
<L N="292">The deuel I bykenne him al at oones</L>
<L>Allas to deere boughte sche hir beaute</L>
<L>wherfore I say &thorn;at alle men may se<MILESTONE N="185b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That &yogh;iftes of fortune or of nature /</L>
<L N="296">Ben cause of deth of many a creature /</L>
<L>hir beaute was hir de&thorn; I dar wel sayn</L>
<L>Allas so pitously as he was slayn</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="300">. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>But trewely myn owne maister deere</L>
<L>This was a pitous tale for to heere</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles pas ouer &thorn;is is no fors</L>
<L N="304">I pray to god to saue &thorn;i gentil corps</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>And euery boist ful of &thorn;i letuarie</L>
<L N="308">God blesse hem and oure lady seinte marie /</L>
<L>So mot I &thorn;en &thorn;ou art a propre man</L>
<L>And y-lik a prelat by seint Runyan</L>
<L>Sayde I wel can I not speke in terme</L>
<L N="312">But wel I woot &thorn;ou dost myn herte erme</L>
<L>I haue almost y-caught a cardiacle</L>
<L>By corpus boones but I haue triacle</L>
<L>O&thorn;er elles a draught of moyst and corny ale</L>
<L N="316">O&thorn;er but/ I hiere anoon a mery tale
<PB REF="00000437.tif" N="425"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="313"></L>
<L>Myn hert is brost. for pite of &thorn;at mayde</L>
<L>Thow pardoner &thorn;ou belamy he sayde /</L>
<L>Tel vs a tale for &thorn;ou canst many oon</L>
<L N="320">It schal be doon quod he and &thorn;at anoon</L>
<L>But first quod he her at &thorn;is ale stake /</L>
<L>I wil first drynke and byt on a cake</L>
<L>But right anoon &thorn;e gentils gan to crie</L>
<L N="324">Nay let him tellen vs no ribaudye</L>
<L>Tel vs som moral &thorn;ing &thorn;at we may leere /</L>
<L>Gladly quod he and sayde as &yogh;e schal heere</L>
<L>But in &thorn;e cuppe wil I me be&thorn;inke</L>
<L N="328">vpon some honest tale whil I drinke /<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000438.tif" N="426">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="314">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LOrdyngs quod he in chirche whan I preche<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Narrat</NOTE></L>
<L>I peyne me to haue an hauteyn speche /</L>
<L>And ryng it out as lowd as do&thorn; a belle</L>
<L N="332">For I can al by rote &thorn;at I telle</L>
<L>My teeme is alway oon and euer was</L>
<L>Radix omnium malorum est Cupiditas</L>
<L>First I pronounce whennes &thorn;at I come</L>
<L N="336">And &thorn;anne my bulles schewe I alle and some<MILESTONE N="186a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Oure liege lordes seal vpon my patent</L>
<L>That schewe I first my body to warent/</L>
<L>That no man be so hardy prest ne clerk</L>
<L N="340">Me to destourbe of cristes holy werk</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at &thorn;an tel I forth my tales</L>
<L>Bulles of popes and of Cardynales /</L>
<L>Of patriarkes and of bisshops I schewe</L>
<L N="344">And in latyn speke I wordes fewe /</L>
<L>To sauore with my predicacioun</L>
<L>And for to stere hem to deuocioun</L>
<L>Thanne schewe I forth my longe cristal stoones</L>
<L N="348">I-crammed ful of cloutes and of boones</L>
<L>Reliks &thorn;ay ben as wene &thorn;ei echoon</L>
<L>Than haue I in latoun a schulder boon</L>
<L>which &thorn;at was of an holy Iewes scheep</L>
<L N="352">Good men say I tak of my wordes keep</L>
<L>If &thorn;at &thorn;is boon be waische in eny welle /</L>
<L>If cow or calf or scheep or oxe swelle</L>
<L>That eny worm ha&thorn; ete or worm I-stonge</L>
<L N="356">Tak water of &thorn;at welle and waisch his tonge
<PB REF="00000439.tif" N="427"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="315"></L>
<L>And it is hool anoon and for&thorn;er-more</L>
<L>Of pokkes and of scabbe and euery sore /</L>
<L>Schal euery scheep be hool &thorn;at of &thorn;is welle</L>
<L N="360">That drynketh a draught tak heed eek what I telle</L>
<L>If &thorn;at &thorn;e goode man &thorn;at &thorn;e beest owe&thorn;</L>
<L>wol euery wike er &thorn;at &thorn;e cok him crowe&thorn;</L>
<L>Fastynge drynke / of &thorn;is welle a draught</L>
<L N="364">As &thorn;ilke holy Iew oure eldres taught</L>
<L>His beestes and his stoor schal multiplie</L>
<L>And sires also it kelith Ialousie</L>
<L>For &thorn;ough a man be ful in ialous rage</L>
<L N="368">let make wi&thorn; &thorn;is water his potage</L>
<L>And neuer schal he more his wyf mys trist</L>
<L>&thorn;ough he &thorn;e so&thorn; of hir defaute wist</L>
<L>Al hadde sche take prestes tuo or &thorn;re</L>
<L N="372">her is a meteyn eek &thorn;at &yogh;e may see</L>
<L>he &thorn;at his honde put in &thorn;is metayn</L>
<L>he schal haue multiplying of grayn<MILESTONE N="186b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>whan he ha&thorn; sowen. be it whete or otes</L>
<L N="376">So &thorn;at &yogh;e offre pans or elles grootes</L>
<L>And men and wommen oon &thorn;ing warne I &yogh;ow</L>
<L>If eny wight be in &thorn;is chirche now</L>
<L>That ha&thorn; doon synne orrible &thorn;at he</L>
<L N="380">Dar nought for schame of it schryuen be</L>
<L>Or ony womman be sche &yogh;ong or old</L>
<L>That hath y-maad hir housbond cokewold</L>
<L>which folk schal haue no power ne grace</L>
<L N="384">To offre to my relikes in &thorn;is place</L>
<L>And who so fint him out of suche blame</L>
<L>Thay wol come vp and offre in goddes name</L>
<L>And I assoile hem by &thorn;e auctorite</L>
<L N="388">which &thorn;at by bulle. was I-graunted me</L>
<L>By &thorn;is gaude haue I wonne euery &yogh;eer</L>
<L>An hundred mark syn I was pardoner</L>
<L>I stonde lik a clerk in my pulpit</L>
<L N="392">And whan &thorn;e lewed poeple is doun I-set
<PB REF="00000440.tif" N="428"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="316"></L>
<L>I preche so as &yogh;e haue herd bifore</L>
<L>And telle hem an hondred Iapes more</L>
<L>Than peyne I me to strecche for&thorn; my necke</L>
<L N="396">And est and west vpon &thorn;e poeple I bekke</L>
<L>As do&thorn; a dowfe syttyng on a berne</L>
<L>Myn hondes and my tonge goon so &yogh;erne</L>
<L>That it is ioye to se my busynesse</L>
<L N="400">Of auarice and of such cursednesse</L>
<L>Is al my preching for to make hem fre</L>
<L>To &yogh;eue here pans and namely vnto me</L>
<L>For myn entent is nought but for to wynne</L>
<L N="404">And no &thorn;ing for correccioun of synne</L>
<L>I rekke neuer. when &thorn;ay ben I-beryed</L>
<L>Though &thorn;at here soules gone a blakeberyed</L>
<L>For certes many a predicacioun</L>
<L N="408">Come&thorn; ofte tyme of euel entencioun</L>
<L>Som for plesauns of folk and flaterie</L>
<L>To ben auaunced by ypocrisie</L>
<L>And som for veine gloir and som for hate</L>
<L N="412">For whan I dar not o&thorn;er weys debate<MILESTONE N="187a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Than wil I stynge him with my tonge smerte</L>
<L>In preching so &thorn;at he schal not astert</L>
<L>To be diffamed falsly if &thorn;at he</L>
<L N="416">ha&thorn; trespast to my bre&thorn;eren or to me</L>
<L>For &thorn;ough I telle not his propre name</L>
<L>Men schal wel knowe &thorn;at it is &thorn;e same /</L>
<L>By signes and by o&thorn;er circumstaunces</L>
<L N="420">Thus quyt I folk &thorn;at doon vs displesaunces</L>
<L>Thus put I out my venym vnder hiewe</L>
<L>Of holynes. to seme holy and trewe /</L>
<L>But schortly myn entent I wol deuyse</L>
<L N="424">I preche no &thorn;ing but of coueityse</L>
<L>Therfor my teem is &yogh;it and euer was</L>
<L>Radix omnium. malorum est Cupiditas</L>
<L>Thus can I preche agayn &thorn;e same vice</L>
<L N="428">which &thorn;at I vse and &thorn;at is auarice
<PB REF="00000441.tif" N="429"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="317"></L>
<L>But though my self be gulty in &thorn;e synne</L>
<L>&YOGH;it can I make o&thorn;er folk to twynne /</L>
<L>From auarice and soone to repent</L>
<L N="432">But &thorn;at/ is not my principal entent</L>
<L>I preche no &thorn;ing but for coueitise</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is matier it ought Inough suffise</L>
<L>Than telle I hem ensamples many oon</L>
<L N="436">Of olde &thorn;inges longe tyme agoon</L>
<L>For lewed poeple louen tales olde</L>
<L>which &thorn;inges can &thorn;ay wel report and holde /</L>
<L>what trowe &yogh;e whiles I may preche</L>
<L N="440">And wynne gold and siluer for I teche</L>
<L>That I wil lyue in pouert wilfully</L>
<L>Nay nay I &thorn;ought it/ neuer trewly</L>
<L>For I wol preche and begge in sondry londes</L>
<L N="444">I wil do no labour wi&thorn; myn hondes</L>
<L>Ne make basketis and lyue &thorn;er by</L>
<L>By cause I wil nought begge ydelly</L>
<L>I wol noon of thapostles counterfete</L>
<L N="448">I wol haue money. wolle chese and whete /</L>
<L>Al were it &yogh;euen of &thorn;e prestes page</L>
<L>Or of &thorn;e porest wydow in a village<MILESTONE N="187b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And schold hir children sterue for famyn</L>
<L N="452">Nay I wol drinke licour of &thorn;e wyn</L>
<L>And haue a ioly wenche in euery toun</L>
<L>But herkne&thorn; lordynges my conclusioun</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure likyng is. &thorn;at I schal telle a tale</L>
<L N="456">Now haue I dronk a draught of corny ale /</L>
<L>By god I hope I schal telle &yogh;ow a &thorn;ing</L>
<L>That schal by resoun be at &yogh;our liking</L>
<L>For &thorn;ough myself be a ful vicious man</L>
<L N="460">A moral tale &yogh;it I &yogh;ow telle can</L>
<L>which I am wont to preche for to wynne</L>
<L>Now hold &yogh;our pees my tale I wol byginne<NOTE PLACE="end">[Partial break of one line in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000442.tif" N="430">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="318">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN Flaundres whilom was a companye /<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Narrat</NOTE></L>
<L N="464">Of &yogh;onge folkes &thorn;at haunted folye</L>
<L>As ryot hasard stywes and tauernes</L>
<L>wher as wi&thorn; lutes harpes and gyternes</L>
<L>Thay daunce and play at dees bo&thorn;e day &amp; night</L>
<L N="468">And ete also and drynk ouer her might</L>
<L>Thurgh which &thorn;ay doon &thorn;e deuyl sacrifise</L>
<L>wi&thorn;inne &thorn;e deueles temple in cursed wise</L>
<L>By superfluite abhominable</L>
<L N="472">her othes been so greet and so dampnable</L>
<L>That it is grisly for to hiere hem swere</L>
<L>Our blisful lordes body &thorn;ay totere</L>
<L>hem &thorn;oughte Iewes rent him nou&yogh;t y-nough</L>
<L N="476">And ech of hem at o&thorn;eres synne lough</L>
<L>And right anoon &thorn;er come tombesteris</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="480">Whiche &thorn;at ben verray &thorn;e deueles officeres</L>
<L>To kyndle and blowe &thorn;e fuyr of leccherie</L>
<L>&THORN;at is anexid vnto glotonye</L>
<L>The holy wryt take I to my witnesse<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; nolite inebriare vino in quo &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L N="484">That luxury is in wyn and dronkenesse</L>
<L>lo how &thorn;at dronken loth vnkyndely</L>
<L>lay by his doughtres tuo vnwityngly</L>
<L>So dronk he was he niste what he wrought</L>
<L N="488">herodes who-so wel &thorn;e story sought</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inter">no spurious lines in this MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>
<PB REF="00000443.tif" N="431"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="319">
whan he of wyn was repleet at his fest<MILESTONE N="188a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Right at his oughne table &yogh;af his hest</L>
<L>To sle &thorn;e baptist Iohn ful gilteles</L>
<L N="492">Seneca sei&thorn; a good word douteles</L>
<L>he sai&thorn; he can no difference fynde</L>
<L>Bituyx a man &thorn;at is out of his mynde</L>
<L>And a man &thorn;e which is dronkelewe</L>
<L N="496">But &thorn;at woodnes fallen in a schrewe</L>
<L>Perseuereth lenger &thorn;an doth dronkennesse</L>
<L>O glutonye ful of corsidnesse</L>
<L>O cause first of oure confusioun</L>
<L N="500">O origiual of oure dampnacioun</L>
<L>Til crist had bought out wi&thorn; his blood agayn</L>
<L>lo how dere schortly for to sayn</L>
<L>Abought was first/ &thorn;is cursed felonye</L>
<L N="504">Corupt was al &thorn;is world for glotonye</L>
<L>Adam our fader and his wyf also</L>
<L>Fro paradys to labour and to wo<NOTE PLACE="marg">Quam diu ieiunauit adam in paradyso fuit comedit et eiectus est statim duxit vxorem &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>were dryuen for &thorn;at vice it is no drede</L>
<L N="508">For whils &thorn;at adam fasted as I rede</L>
<L>he was in paradis and whan &thorn;at he</L>
<L>Eet of &thorn;e fruyt defendit of a tre</L>
<L>he was out cast to wo and in-to peyne</L>
<L N="512">O. glotony. wel ought vs on &thorn;e pleyne</L>
<L>O. wist a man how many maladyes</L>
<L>Folwith of excesse and of glotonyes</L>
<L>he wolde be &thorn;e more mesurable</L>
<L N="516">Of his diete sittyng at his table</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;e schorte &thorn;rote &thorn;e tendre mou&thorn;</L>
<L>Make&thorn; &thorn;at Est. West. north and south</L>
<L>In er&thorn;e in watir in ayer man to swynke</L>
<L N="520">To gete a sely glotoun mete and drynke.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is matier o poul wel canstow trete</L>
<L>Mete vnto wombe and wombe vnto mete<NOTE PLACE="marg">Esca ventris &amp; venter escis deus autem hunc &amp; illam destruet &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Schal god destroyen bo&thorn;e as powel sai&thorn;</L>
<L N="524">Allas a foul &thorn;ing is it by my fai&thorn;
<PB REF="00000444.tif" N="432"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="320"></L>
<L>To say &thorn;is word / and fouler is &thorn;e dede</L>
<L>whan men so drynke / of &thorn;e whyt and rede<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ad philipenses capitulo 3<SUP>o</SUP></NOTE></L>
<L>That of his &thorn;rote he maki&thorn; his priue<MILESTONE N="188b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="528">Thurgh &thorn;ilke cursed superfluite</L>
