<L>Ther is no man &thorn;at lyueth vnder &thorn;e troone</L>
<L>Of gold &thorn;at schulde lyue so mery as I</L>
<L N="844">And atte last &thorn;e feend oure enemy</L>
<L>Put in his &thorn;ought &thorn;at he schuld poysoun beye</L>
<L>wi&thorn; which he mighte sle his felaws tweye</L>
<L>For-why &thorn;e feend fond him in such lyuynge</L>
<L N="848">That he had leue to sorwe him to brynge
<PB REF="00000453.tif" N="441"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="329"></L>
<L>For &thorn;is witterly . was his entent</L>
<L>To slen hem bo&thorn;e and neuer to repent/</L>
<L>And forth he go&thorn; no lenger wold he tary</L>
<L N="852">In to &thorn;e toun vnto a potecary /</L>
<L>And prayde him &thorn;at he him wolde selle</L>
<L>Som poysoun &thorn;at he might his rattis quelle</L>
<L>And eek &thorn;er was a polkat in his hawe /</L>
<L N="856">As he sayde his capouns had I-slawe /</L>
<L>And said he wold him wreke if &thorn;at he might</L>
<L>On vermyn &thorn;at destroyed him by night</L>
<L>Thapotecary answerd and &thorn;ou schalt haue</L>
<L N="860">A &thorn;ing &thorn;at also god my soule saue</L>
<L>In al &thorn;is world &thorn;er nys no creature</L>
<L>That ete or dronk had of &thorn;is confecture</L>
<L>Nought but &thorn;e mountaunce of a corn of whete</L>
<L N="864">That he ne schuld his lif anoon forlete /</L>
<L>&YOGH;e sterue he schal and &thorn;at in lasse while</L>
<L>Than &thorn;ou wilt goon a paas not but a myle /</L>
<L>The poysoun is so strong and violent<MILESTONE N="193a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="868">This cursed man ha&thorn; in his hond I-hent</L>
<L>This poysoun in a box &amp; sins he ran</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e nexte stret vnto a man</L>
<L>And borwed him large botels &thorn;re</L>
<L N="872">And in &thorn;e two his poysoun poured he</L>
<L>The &thorn;rid he keped clene for his drynke</L>
<L>For al &thorn;e night he schop him for to swynke</L>
<L>In carying the gold out of &thorn;at place</L>
<L N="876">And whan &thorn;is riotour with sory grace</L>
<L>had fillid with wyn his botels &thorn;re</L>
<L>To his felaws a&yogh;ein repaireth he</L>
<L>what nedith it to sermoun it more</L>
<L N="880">For right as &thorn;ay had cast/ his deth bifore</L>
<L>Right so &thorn;ay han him slayn and &thorn;at anoon</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is was I-doon &thorn;an spak &thorn;at oon</L>
<L>Now let vs drynk and sitte and make vs mery</L>
<L N="884">And si&thorn;&thorn;en we wil his body bery
<PB REF="00000454.tif" N="442"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="330"></L>
<L>And afterward it happed hem par cas</L>
<L>To take &thorn;e botel &thorn;er &thorn;e poysoun was</L>
<L>And drank and &yogh;af his felaw drink also</L>
<L N="888">For which &thorn;ay sterued bo&thorn;e tuo</L>
<L>But certes I suppose &thorn;at amycen</L>
<L>wrot neuer in Canoun ne in non fen</L>
<L>Mo wonder sorwes of empoisonyng</L>
<L N="892">Thus hadde &thorn;ese wrecches tuo here endyng</L>
<L>Thus endid been &thorn;ese homicides tuo</L>
<L>And eek &thorn;e fals empoysoner also /</L>
<L>O cursed synne ful of cursednesse</L>
<L N="896">O traytorous homicidy o wikkednesse</L>
<L>O glotony luxurie and hasardrye /</L>
<L>Thou blasphemour of crist with vilanye</L>
<L>And o&thorn;es grete of vsage and of pride</L>
<L N="900">Allas mankynde how may it bytyde</L>
<L>Ther to &thorn;y creatour which &thorn;at &thorn;e wrought</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his precious herte blood &thorn;e bought</L>
<L>Thou art so fals and so vnkynde allas</L>
<L N="904">Now good men god for&yogh;eue &yogh;ow &yogh;our trespas</L>
<L>And ware &yogh;ow fro &thorn;e synne of auarice<MILESTONE N="193b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Myn holy pardoun may &yogh;ou alle warice</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &yogh;e offren noblis or starlinges</L>
<L N="908">Or elles siluer spones broches or rynges</L>
<L>Bowi&thorn; &yogh;our hedes vnder &thorn;is holy bulle</L>
<L>Come&thorn; for&thorn; &yogh;e wyues and offre&thorn; &yogh;our wolle</L>
<L>&YOGH;our names I entre her in my rolle anoon</L>
<L N="912">In to &thorn;e blis of heuen schul &yogh;e goon</L>
<L>I &yogh;ow assoile by myn heyh power</L>
<L>If &yogh;e woln offre as clene and eek als cler</L>
<L>As &yogh;e were born . and sires lo &thorn;us I preche /</L>
<L N="916">And Ih&umacr; crist &thorn;at is oure soules leche</L>
<L>So graunte &yogh;ow his pardoun to receyue</L>
<L>For &thorn;at is best I wil not &yogh;ow disceyue</L>
<L>But sires o word for&yogh;at I in my tale /</L>
<L N="920">I haue reliks and pardoun in my male /
<PB REF="00000455.tif" N="443"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="331"></L>
<L>As fair as eny man in Engelond</L>
<L>which were me I-&yogh;eue by popes hond</L>
<L>If eny of &yogh;ow wol of deuocioun</L>
<L N="924">Offren and haue myn absolucioun</L>
<L>Cometh forth anon knelith her a-doun</L>
<L>And &yogh;e schul haue here my pardoun</L>
<L>Or elles takith pardoun as &yogh;e wende</L>
<L N="928">Al newe and freissch at euery townes ende</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &yogh;e offren alway new and newe /</L>
<L>Nobles and pens which &thorn;at ben good and trewe /</L>
<L>It is an honur to euery &thorn;at is heer</L>
<L N="932">That may haue a suffisaunt pardoner</L>
<L>Tassoile &yogh;ow in contre as &yogh;e ryde</L>
<L>For auentures which &thorn;at may bytyde</L>
<L>For paraunter&middot; &thorn;er may falle oon or tuo</L>
<L N="936">Doun of his hors and breke his nekke a-tuo</L>
<L>loke such a seurete is to &yogh;ou alle</L>
<L>That I am in &yogh;our felaschip I-falle</L>
<L>That may assoyle &yogh;ou bo&thorn;e more and lasse</L>
<L N="940">whan &thorn;at &thorn;e soule schal fro &thorn;e body passe</L>
<L>I rede &thorn;at oure hoste schal bygynne</L>
<L>For he is most enuoliped in synne</L>
<L>Com for&thorn; sire ost and offer first anoon<MILESTONE N="194a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="944">And &thorn;ou schalt kisse &thorn;e reliquis euerichoon</L>
<L>&YOGH;e for a grote vnbocle &thorn;i purs</L>
<L>Nay nay quod he &thorn;an haue I cristes curs</L>
<L>let be quod he it schal not be so theech</L>
<L N="948">Thou woldest make me kisse &thorn;in olde breech</L>
<L>And swere it were a relik of a seynt</L>
<L>Though it were wi&thorn; &thorn;i foundement depeynt</L>
<L>But by &thorn;e cros which &thorn;at seynt heleyn fond</L>
<L N="952">I wold I had &thorn;y coylons in myn hond</L>
<L>In stede of reliks or of seintuary /</L>
<L>let cut hem of I wol help hem to cary</L>
<L>Thay schul be schryned in an hogges tord</L>
<L N="956">This pardoner answerde nat o word
<PB REF="00000456.tif" N="444"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="332"></L>
<L>So wro&thorn; he was he wolde no word say</L>
<L>Now quod oure host I wol no lenger play</L>
<L>wi&thorn; &thorn;e ne with noon o&thorn;er angry man</L>
<L N="960">But right anoon &thorn;is worthy knight bygan</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at he saugh &thorn;at al &thorn;e peple lough</L>
<L>No more of &thorn;is for it is right ynough</L>
<L>Sir pardoner be glad and mery of cheere</L>
<L N="964">And &yogh;e sir host &thorn;at ben to me so deere</L>
<L>I pray &yogh;ow &thorn;at &yogh;e kisse &thorn;e pardoner</L>
<L>And pardoner I pray &yogh;ow drawe&thorn; &yogh;ow ner</L>
<L>And as we dede let vs laugh and play</L>
<L N="968">Anoon &thorn;ay kisse and riden for&thorn; her way /</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Here endeth &thorn;e pardoneres tale<NOTE>[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="B" TYPE="group">

<PB REF="00000457.tif" N="445">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="168">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>B.</B> (&beta;. FRAGMENT III.)</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; 4. THE SHIPMAN'S TALE.</HEAD>
<HEAD>&para; Here bygynneth &thorn;e Schipman his tale/</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A Marchaunt whilom dwelled at seint Denys</L>
<L>That riche was for which men hild him wys</L>
<L>A wyf he had of excellent beaute</L>
<L>And companable and reuerent was sche</L>
<L>which is a &thorn;ing &thorn;at causeth more despence</L>
<L N="1196">Than worth is al &thorn;e cher and reuerence</L>
<L>That men doon hem at festes or at daunces</L>
<L>Such salutaciouns and continaunces</L>
<L>Passeth as do&thorn; &thorn;e schadow on a wal</L>
<L N="1200">But wo is him &thorn;at paye moot for al</L>
<L>The sely housbond algat moste pay<MILESTONE N="194b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He most vs clo&thorn;e . in ful good array</L>
<L>Al for his oughne worschip richely</L>
<L N="1204">In which array we daunce iolily</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at he may not parauenture</L>
<L>Or elles wil not/ such dispens endure</L>
<L>But &thorn;ynke&thorn; it is wasted and I-lost</L>
<L N="1208">Than moot ano&thorn;er paye for oure cost</L>
<L>Or lene vs gold and &thorn;at is perilous</L>
<L>The wor&thorn;y marchaunt huld a noble hous/</L>
<L>For which he hadde alday gret repair</L>
<L N="1212">For his largesce and for his wyf was fair</L>
<L>what wonder is but herkne&thorn; to my tale</L>
<L>Amonges al &thorn;ese gestes gret and smale /</L>
<L>Ther was a monk a fair man and a bold</L>
<L N="1216">I trowe &thorn;ritty wynter he was old</L>
<L>That euer in oon was drawyng to &thorn;at place /</L>
<L>This &yogh;onge monk &thorn;at was so fair of face
<PB REF="00000458.tif" N="446"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="169"></L>
<L>Aqueynted was so wi&thorn; &thorn;e goode man</L>
<L N="1220">Si&thorn; &thorn;at her firste knowleche bygan</L>
<L>That in his hous as familier was he /</L>
<L>As it possibil is a frend to be</L>
<L>And for as mochil as &thorn;is goode man</L>
<L N="1224">And eek &thorn;is monk of which &thorn;at I bygan</L>
<L>were bo&thorn;e tuo I-born in oon village /</L>
<L>The monk him claymeth as for cosynage</L>
<L>And he a&yogh;ein he saith nat oones nay</L>
<L N="1228">But was as glad &thorn;er of as foul of day</L>
<L>For to his hert it was a gret plesaunce /</L>
<L>Thus ben &thorn;ay knyt wi&thorn; eterne alliaunce</L>
<L>And ilk of hem gan o&thorn;er to assure /</L>
<L N="1232">Of bro&thorn;erhed whil &thorn;at her lif may dure</L>
<L>Fre was daun Iohn and manly of despence /</L>
<L>As in &thorn;at hous and ful of diligence</L>
<L>To do plesaunce and also gret costage</L>
<L N="1236">He nought for&yogh;at to &yogh;eue &thorn;e leste page</L>
<L>In al &thorn;at hous but after her degre /</L>
<L>He &yogh;af &thorn;e lord and si&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;e meyne /</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at he com som maner honest &thorn;ing<MILESTONE N="195a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1240">For which &thorn;ay were as glad of his comyng</L>
<L>As foul is fayn . whan &thorn;at &thorn;e sonne vprise&thorn;</L>
<L>No mor of &thorn;is as now for it suffise&thorn;</L>
<L>But so bifel &thorn;is marchaunt on a day /</L>
<L N="1244">Schop him to make redy his array /</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e toun of Bruges for to fare /</L>
<L>To byen &thorn;er a porcioun of ware</L>
<L>For which he hath to paris sent anoon</L>
<L N="1248">A messanger and prayed had dan Iohn</L>
<L>That he schuld come to seint Denys and play</L>
<L>with him and wi&thorn; his wyf a day or tway</L>
<L>Er he to brigges went . in alle wise</L>
<L N="1252">This nobil monk/ of which I &yogh;ow deuyse</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; of his abbot as him list licence</L>
<L>By cause he was a man of heih prudence
<PB REF="00000459.tif" N="447"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="170"></L>
<L>And eek an officer out/ for to ryde /</L>
<L N="1256">To se her graunges and her bernes wyde /</L>
<L>And vnto seint denys he come&thorn; anoon</L>
<L>who was so welcome as my lord dan Iohn</L>
<L>Oure deere cosyn ful of curtesie /</L>
<L N="1260">with him brought he a Iubbe of maluesie</L>
<L>And eek/ ano&thorn;er ful of wyn vernage</L>
<L>And volantyn as ay was his vsage</L>
<L>And &thorn;us I lete hem ete and drynk and play</L>
<L N="1264">This marchaunt and &thorn;is monk a day or tway</L>
<L>The &thorn;ridde day &thorn;is marchaund vp he riseth</L>
<L>And on his needes sadly him auyseth</L>
<L>And vp in to his countour hous go&thorn; he</L>
<L N="1268">To rekyn wi&thorn; himself as wel may be /</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ilke &yogh;er how &thorn;at it with him stood</L>
<L>And how &thorn;at he dispended had his good</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at he encresced were or noon</L>
<L N="1272">His bookes and his bagges many oon</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; byforn him on his counter bord</L>
<L>For riche was his tresor and his hord</L>
<L>For which ful fast his countour dore he schette</L>
<L N="1276">And eek he wolde no man schold him lette</L>
<L>Of his accomptes for &thorn;e mene tyme /<MILESTONE N="195b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;us he sat til it was passed prime</L>
<L>Dan Iohn was risen in &thorn;e morn also</L>
<L N="1280">And in the gardyn walkith to and fro</L>
<L>And ha&thorn; his &thorn;inges said ful curteisly</L>
<L>This good wyf com walkyng ful priuely</L>
<L>In to a gardyn &thorn;er he walke&thorn; softe</L>
<L N="1284">And him salue&thorn; as sche ha&thorn; doon ful ofte</L>
<L>A mayde child com in hir compaignie</L>
<L>which as hir list sche may gouerne and gye</L>
<L>For &yogh;it vnder &thorn;e &yogh;erde was &thorn;e mayde</L>
<L N="1288">O dere cosyn myn dan Iohn sche sayde</L>
<L>what ayle&thorn; &yogh;ow so ra&thorn;e to arise</L>
<L>Nece quod he it aught ynough suffise
<PB REF="00000460.tif" N="448"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="171"></L>
<L>Fyue houres for to slepe a night</L>
<L N="1292">But it were for eny old palled wight</L>
<L>As ben &thorn;ese weddid men &thorn;at lye and dare</L>
<L>As in a forme li&thorn; a wery hare</L>
<L>were al forstraught with houndes gret and smale</L>
<L N="1296">But dere nece why be &yogh;e so pale /</L>
<L>I trowe certis &thorn;at oure goode man</L>
<L>hath on &yogh;ow laborid sith &thorn;e night bygan</L>
<L>That &yogh;ow were nede to resten hastiliche</L>
<L N="1300">And with &thorn;at word he lowgh ful meriliche</L>
<L>And of his owne &thorn;ought he was al reed</L>
<L>This faire wyf bygan to schake hir heed</L>
<L>And sayde &thorn;us &yogh;e god wot al quod sche /</L>
<L N="1304">Nay cosyn myn it stant not so wi&thorn; me</L>
<L>For by &thorn;at god &thorn;at &yogh;af me soule and lif</L>
<L>In al &thorn;e reme of Fraunce is &thorn;er no wif</L>
<L>That lasse lust ha&thorn; to &thorn;at sory play</L>
<L N="1308">For I may synge / allas and waylaway</L>
<L>That I was born but to no wight quod sche</L>
<L>Dar I not telle how it stont wi&thorn; me</L>
<L>Wherfor I &thorn;ink out of &thorn;is lond to wende</L>
<L N="1312">Or elles of my self to make an ende</L>
<L>So ful am I of drede and eek of care</L>
<L>This monk bygan vpon &thorn;is wif to stare</L>
<L>And sayd allas my nece god forbede<MILESTONE N="196a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1316">That &yogh;e for eny sorw or eny drede /</L>
<L>Fordo &yogh;our self but telle&thorn; me &yogh;our greef</L>
<L>Parauenture I may in &yogh;oure mescheef</L>
<L>Councel or help and &thorn;erfor telle&thorn; me</L>
<L N="1320">Al &yogh;our annoy for it schal be secre</L>
<L>For on my portos I make an oth</L>
<L>That neuer in my lif for lief ne lo&thorn;</L>
<L>Schal I of no counseil &yogh;ou bywray</L>
<L N="1324">The same a&yogh;ein quod sche to &yogh;ow I say</L>
<L>By god and by &thorn;is portos wil I swere</L>
<L>Though men me wolde al in peces tere
<PB REF="00000461.tif" N="449"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="172"></L>
<L>Ne schal I neuer for to go to helle /</L>
<L N="1328">Bywreye word . of &thorn;ing &thorn;at &yogh;e me telle</L>
<L>Not for no cosynage ne alliaunce</L>
<L>But verrayly for loue and affiaunce</L>
<L>Thus ben &thorn;ay sworn and her-vpon I-kist</L>
<L N="1332">And ilk of hem told o&thorn;er what hem list</L>
<L>Cosyn quod sche if &thorn;at I had a space /</L>
<L>As I haue noon and namly in &thorn;is place</L>
<L>Then wold I telle a legend of my lyf</L>
<L N="1336">what I haue suffred si&thorn; I was a wyf</L>
<L>wi&thorn; myn housbond &thorn;ough he be &yogh;our cosyn</L>
<L>Nay quod &thorn;is monk by god and seint martyn</L>
<L>He is no more cosyn vnto me</L>
<L N="1340">Than is &thorn;is leef &thorn;at honge&thorn; on &thorn;e tre</L>
<L>I clepid him so by seint Denis of Fraunce</L>
<L>To haue &thorn;e more cause of acqueyntaunce</L>
<L>Of &yogh;ow which I haue loued specially</L>
<L N="1344">Abouen alle wommen sikerly</L>
<L>This swere I &yogh;ow on my professioun</L>
<L>Tellith &yogh;oure greef lest &thorn;at he come a doun</L>
<L>And hasteth &yogh;ow and go&thorn; &yogh;our way anoon</L>
<L N="1348">My deere loue quod sche . O dan Iohn</L>
<L>Ful leef me were &thorn;is counseil to hyde</L>
<L>But out it moot it may no more abyde</L>
<L>Myn housbond is to me &thorn;e worste man</L>
<L N="1352">That euer was si&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;e world bigan</L>
<L>But si&thorn; I am a wif it sit nought me<MILESTONE N="196b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To telle eny wight of oure priuete</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1356">God schilde I scholde telle it for his grace /</L>
<L>A wyf ne schal not say of hir housbonde</L>
<L>But al honour as I can vnderstonde</L>
<L>Saue vnto &yogh;ow &thorn;us moche telle I schal</L>
<L N="1360">As help me god he is not wor&thorn; at al</L>
<L>In no degre &thorn;e valieu of a flie</L>
<L>But &yogh;it me greueth most his nigardye
<PB REF="00000462.tif" N="450"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="173"></L>
<L>And wel &yogh;e wot &thorn;at wymmen naturelly</L>
<L N="1364">Desiren sixe &thorn;inges as wel as I</L>
<L>They wolde &thorn;at here housbondes scholde be</L>
<L>hardy and wys and riche and fre /</L>
<L>And buxom to his wyf and freisch on bedde</L>
<L N="1368">But by &thorn;e lord &thorn;at for vs alle bledde</L>
<L>For his honour my seluen to array</L>
<L>A sonday next comyng &yogh;it most I pay</L>
<L>An hundred frank or elles I am lorn</L>
<L N="1372">&YOGH;it were me leuer &thorn;at I were vnborn</L>
<L>Than me were doon a sclaunder or vilenye &middot;</L>
<L>And if myn housbond eek might it espie</L>
<L>I ner but lost and &thorn;erfor I &yogh;ow pray</L>
<L N="1376">. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1380">For a certein day I wol &yogh;ow pay</L>
<L>And do to &yogh;ow what pleasaunce and seruise</L>
<L>That I may do right as &yogh;ou list deuyse</L>
<L>And but I do god take on me vengeaunce</L>
<L N="1384">As foul as hadde Geneloun of Fraunce</L>
<L>This gentil monk answard in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>Now trewely myn owne lady deere /</L>
<L>I haue on &yogh;ow so gret pite and reuthe /</L>
<L N="1388">That I &yogh;ow swere and plighte &yogh;ow my treu&thorn;e</L>
<L>That whan &yogh;our housbond is to Flaundres fare</L>
<L>I schal deliuer &yogh;ow out of &yogh;oure care</L>
<L>For I wol bringe &yogh;ow an hundred frankes /</L>
<L N="1392">And with &thorn;at word he caught hir by &thorn;e schankes</L>
<L>And hir embraced hard and kist hir ofte</L>
<L>Goth now &yogh;our way quod he al stille and softe /</L>
<L>And let vs dyne as sone as &yogh;e may</L>
<L N="1396">For by my chilindre it is prime of day<MILESTONE N="197a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Goth now and beth as trew as I schal be /</L>
<L>Now elles god forbede sire quod sche /
<PB REF="00000463.tif" N="451"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="174"></L>
<L>And for&thorn; sche goth as ioly as a pye /</L>
<L N="1400">And bad &thorn;e cookes &thorn;at &thorn;ai schold hem hye /</L>
<L>So &thorn;at men myghte dyne and &thorn;at anoon</L>
<L>vp to hir housbond &thorn;is wif is goon</L>
<L>And knokke&thorn; at / his dore boldely</L>
<L N="1404">Qy la quod he. peter it am I</L>
<L>Quod sche how longe sire wol &yogh;e fast</L>
<L>how longe tyme wol &yogh;e reken and cast</L>
<L>&yogh;our sommes and &yogh;our bokes and &yogh;our &thorn;inges /</L>
<L N="1408">The deuel haue part of alle such rekenynges</L>
<L>&yogh;e haue I-nough par dy of goddes sonde /</L>
<L>Com doun to day and let &yogh;our bagges stonde</L>
<L>Ne be &yogh;e not aschamed that Daun Iohn</L>
<L N="1412">Schal al day fastyng &thorn;us elenge goon</L>
<L>what let vs hiere masse and gowe dyne</L>
<L>wif quod &thorn;is man litel canstow diuine</L>
<L>The curious besynesse &thorn;at we haue</L>
<L N="1416">For of vs chapmen so god me saue</L>
<L>And by &thorn;at lord that cleped is seint Iue</L>
<L>Scarsly among twelue two schuln &thorn;riue</L>
<L>Continuelly lastyng in to her age</L>
<L N="1420">we may wel make cheer and good visage</L>
<L>And dryue forth &thorn;e world as it may be</L>
<L>And kepen our estat in priuete</L>
<L>Til we be deed or elles &thorn;at we play</L>
<L N="1424">A pilgrimage or goon out of &thorn;e way</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfor haue I / gret necessite</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;is queynte world to auyse me</L>
<L>For euermor we moste stond in drede</L>
<L N="1428">Of hap and fortun / in our chapmanhede</L>
<L>To Flaundres to morw at day</L>
<L>And come agayn as soone as I may</L>
<L>For which my deere wif I &thorn;e byseeke</L>
<L N="1432">And be to euery wight buxom and meeke</L>
<L>And for to kepe oure good be curious</L>
<L>And honestly gouerne wel our hous<MILESTONE N="197b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000464.tif" N="452"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="175"></L>
<L>Thou hast ynough in euery maner wise</L>
<L N="1436">That to a thrifty housbond may suffise</L>
<L>The lakke&thorn; noon array ne no vitaile</L>
<L>Of siluer in &thorn;y purs &thorn;ou mayst not faile</L>
<L>And with &thorn;at word his contour dore he schitte</L>
<L N="1440">And doun he go&thorn; no lenger wold he lette</L>
<L>And hastily a masse was &thorn;er sayd</L>
<L>And spedily &thorn;e tables were I-layd</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e dyner faste &thorn;ay hem spedde /</L>
<L N="1444">And rychely &thorn;is Chapman &thorn;e monk fedde /</L>
<L>And after dyner daun Iohn sobrely</L>
<L>This chapman took on part and priuely /</L>
<L>Sayd him &thorn;us. cosyn it stondeth so</L>
<L N="1448">That wel I se to brigges wol &yogh;e go /</L>
<L>God and seint austyn spede &yogh;ou and gyde /</L>
<L>I pray &yogh;ow cosyn wisly &thorn;at &yogh;e ryde</L>
<L>Gouerneth &yogh;ow also of &yogh;our diete</L>
<L N="1452">Al temperelly and namely in &thorn;is hete</L>
<L>Bitwix vs tuo nedeth no straunge fare</L>
<L>Far wel cosyn . god schilde &yogh;ou fro care</L>
<L>If eny &thorn;ing &thorn;er be by day or night</L>
<L N="1456">If it lay in my power and my might</L>
<L>That &yogh;e wil me comaunde in eny wise</L>
<L>It schal be doon right as &yogh;e wol deuyse /</L>
<L>O thing er &thorn;at &yogh;e goon if it might be /</L>
<L N="1460">I wolde pray &yogh;ow for to lene me</L>
<L>An hundred frankes for a wyke or tweye</L>
<L>For certeyn bestis &thorn;at I moste beye /</L>
<L>To store with a place &thorn;at is oures</L>
<L N="1464">God help me so I wolde it were &yogh;oures</L>
<L>I schal not faile seurly of my day</L>
<L>Nought for a &thorn;ousand frankes a myle way</L>
<L>But let &thorn;is &thorn;ing be secre I &yogh;ow pray /</L>
<L N="1468">For for &thorn;e bestis &thorn;is night most I pay</L>
<L>And fare now wel myn owne cosyn deere</L>
<L>Graunt mercy of &yogh;our cost and of &yogh;our cheere
<PB REF="00000465.tif" N="453"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="176"></L>
<L>This noble marchaunt gentilly anoon</L>
<L N="1472">Answerd and sayde. O cosyn daun Iohn<MILESTONE N="198a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Now sikerly &thorn;is is a smal request</L>
<L>My gold is &yogh;oures whanne &thorn;at &yogh;ow lest/</L>
<L>And nought oonly gold but my chaffare /</L>
<L N="1476">Tak what &yogh;ow liste / god schilde &yogh;e spare</L>
<L>But oon &thorn;ing is &yogh;e know it wel ynough</L>
<L>Of chapmen &thorn;at her money is here plough</L>
<L>we may creaunce whils we haue a name</L>
<L N="1480">But goldles for to be it is no game</L>
<L>Pay it agayn whan it li&thorn; in &yogh;our ese /</L>
<L>After my might ful fayn wold I &yogh;ow plese /</L>
<L>This hundred frankes he fet forth anoon</L>
<L N="1484">And priuely he took hem to daun Iohn</L>
<L>No wight in al &thorn;is world wist of &thorn;is loone</L>
<L>Sauyng &thorn;e marchaund and dan Iohn alloone</L>
<L>Thay drynke &amp; speke and rome a while and play</L>
<L N="1488">Til &thorn;at dan Iohn ryde&thorn; to his abbay</L>
<L>The morwe cam and forth &thorn;e marchaund rideth</L>
<L>To Flaundres-ward his prentis wel him gydeth</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at/ he cam to Brigges merily</L>
<L N="1492">Now goth &thorn;is marchaund faste and busily</L>
<L>Aboute his neede and bieth and creaunceth</L>
<L>He neither pleyeth atte dys ne daunce&thorn;</L>
<L>But as a marchaund schortly for to telle</L>
<L N="1496">he lad his lyf / and &thorn;er I let him duelle</L>
<L>The sonday next &thorn;e marchaund is agoon</L>
<L>To seint denys I-come is daun Iohn</L>
<L>with croune and berd al freisch and newe I-schaue</L>
<L N="1500">In al &thorn;e hous &thorn;er nas so litel a knaue</L>
<L>Ne no wight elles &thorn;at he nas ful fayn</L>
<L>For &thorn;at my lord dan Iohn was come agayn</L>
<L>And schortly to &thorn;e poynte for to gon</L>
<L N="1504">This faire wif acordith with dan Iohn</L>
<L>That for &thorn;ese hundred frank he schuld al night</L>
<L>Haue hir in his armes bolt/ vpright
<PB REF="00000466.tif" N="454"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="177"></L>
<L>And &thorn;is acord parformed was in dede /</L>
<L N="1508">In mirth al night a bisy lif &thorn;ay lede /</L>
<L>Til it was day &thorn;at dan Iohn went his way</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;e meigne far wel haue good day<MILESTONE N="198b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For noon of hem ne no wight in &thorn;e toun</L>
<L N="1512">Hath of dan Iohn right noon suspeccioun</L>
<L>And forth he rideth hom to his abbay</L>
<L>Or wher him list/ no more of him I say /</L>
<L>&para; This marchaund whan &thorn;at endid was &thorn;e faire</L>
<L N="1516">To seynt denys. he gan to repeire /</L>
<L>And with his wif he make&thorn; fest and cheere</L>
<L>And tellith hir &thorn;at chaffar is so deere</L>
<L>That needes most he make a cheuisaunce</L>
<L N="1520">For he was. bounde in a reconisaunce</L>
<L>To paye twenty &thorn;ousand scheldes anoon</L>
<L>For which &thorn;is marchaund is to paris goon</L>
<L>To borwe of certeyn frendes &thorn;at he hadde /</L>
<L N="1524">A certein frankes and some with him he ladde /</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at he was come in to &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>For gret chiertee and gret affeccioun</L>
<L>Vnto Dan Iohn he first goth him to play</L>
<L N="1528">Nought for to borwe of him no kyn monay</L>
<L>But for to wite and se of his wel fare</L>
<L>And for to telle him of his chaffare</L>
<L>As frendes doon whan &thorn;ay ben met in fere</L>
<L N="1532">Dan Iohn him maketh fest and mery cheere</L>
<L>And he him told agayn ful specially</L>
<L>How he had bought right wel and graciously</L>
<L>Thanked be god / al his marchaundise</L>
<L N="1536">Saue &thorn;at he most in alle maner wise /</L>
<L>Maken a cheuyssauns as for his best</L>
<L>And &thorn;an he schulde be in ioye and rest</L>
<L>Dan Iohn answerde certis I am fayn</L>
<L N="1540">That &yogh;e in hele are comen hom agayn</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at I were riche as haue I blisse</L>
<L>Of twenty &thorn;ousand scheld schuld &yogh;e not mysse
<PB REF="00000467.tif" N="455"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="178"></L>
<L>For &yogh;e so kyndely &thorn;is o&thorn;er day</L>
<L N="1544">lente me gold and as I can and may</L>
<L>I &thorn;anke &yogh;ow by god and by seint Iame /</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles I took it to oure dame</L>
<L>&yogh;oure wif &thorn;e same gold a&yogh;ein</L>
<L N="1548">vpon &yogh;our bench . sche wot it wel certeyn<MILESTONE N="199a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>By certein toknes &thorn;at I can hir telle</L>
<L>Now by &yogh;our leue I may no lenger duelle</L>
<L>Oure abbot wol out of toun anoon</L>
<L N="1552">And in his compaignye moot I goon</L>
<L>Grete wel oure dame my nece swete</L>
<L>And far wel dere cosyn til &thorn;at we meete</L>
<L>This marchaund which &thorn;at was bo&thorn;e war and wys /</L>
<L N="1556">Creaunced ha&thorn; and payed eek in parys/</L>
<L>To certeyn lombardes redy in her hond</L>
<L>This somme of gold and took of hem his bond</L>
<L>And hom he go&thorn; a mery as a popin iay</L>
<L N="1560">For wel he knew he stood in such array</L>
<L>That needes most he wynne in such viage</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand frankes aboue al his costage</L>
<L>His wyf redy mette him at &thorn;e gate</L>
<L N="1564">As sche was wont of old usage algate</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at night in mir&thorn;e &thorn;ay ben sette</L>
<L>For he was riche and clerly out of dette</L>
<L>whan it was day &thorn;is marchaund gan embrace</L>
<L N="1568">his wyf al newe and kist hir on hir face</L>
<L>And vp he goth and maked it ful tough</L>
<L>No more quod sche by god &yogh;e haue ynough</L>
<L>And wantounly with him sche lay and playde</L>
<L N="1572">Till atte laste &thorn;us &thorn;is marchaund sayde</L>
<L>By god quod he I am a litel wro&thorn;</L>
<L>with &yogh;ow my wyf al&thorn;ough it be me loth</L>
<L>And wite &yogh;e why by god as &thorn;at I gesse</L>
<L N="1576">&yogh;e han I-maad a maner straungenesse /</L>
<L>Bitwixe me and my cosyn dan Iohn</L>
<L>&yogh;e schold haue warned me er I had goon
<PB REF="00000468.tif" N="456"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="179"></L>
<L>That he &yogh;ow had an hundred frankes payd</L>
<L N="1580">By redy tokne and huld him euel appayd</L>
<L>For &thorn;at I to him spak of cheuysaunce</L>
<L>Me semed so as by his countenaunce</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles by god of heuen king</L>
<L N="1584">I &thorn;oughe nought to axe him no &thorn;ing</L>
<L>I pray &thorn;e wif do no more so</L>
<L>Tel me alway er &thorn;at I fro &thorn;e go<MILESTONE N="199b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>If eny dettour haue in myn absence</L>
<L N="1588">I-payed &thorn;e lest in &thorn;y necgligence</L>
<L>I may him axe a &thorn;ing &thorn;at he ha&thorn; payed</L>
<L>This wyf was not affered ne affrayed</L>
<L>But holly sche sayde and &thorn;at anoon</L>
<L N="1592">Mary I diffy &thorn;at false monk dan Iohn</L>
<L>I kepe not of his tokenes neuer a del</L>
<L>he took me a certeyn gold/ &thorn;at wot I wel</L>
<L>what euel thedom on his monkes snowte/</L>
<L N="1596">For god it wot I wende wi&thorn;oute doute</L>
<L>That he had &yogh;eue it me by cause of &yogh;ow</L>
<L>To do &thorn;er with myn honour and my prow</L>
<L>For cosynage and eek for bele cheer</L>
<L N="1600">That he ha&thorn; had ful ofte tyme heer</L>
<L>But synnes &thorn;at I stonde in &thorn;is disioynt</L>
<L>I wol answer &yogh;ow schortly to &thorn;e poynt</L>
<L>&YOGH;e han mo slakke dettours &thorn;an am I</L>
<L N="1604">For I wol pay &yogh;ow wel and redily</L>
<L>Fro day to day and if so be I faile</L>
<L>I am &yogh;our wif score it vpon my taile</L>
<L>And I schal paye it as soone as I may</L>
<L N="1608">For by my trou&thorn;e I haue on myn array</L>
<L>And nought on wast bistowed it euery del</L>
<L>And for I haue bistowed it so wel</L>
<L>To &yogh;oure honour for goddes sake I say</L>
<L N="1612">As be&thorn; nought wro&thorn; but let vs laugh and play /</L>
<L>&YOGH;e schul my ioly body haue to wedde/</L>
<L>By god I wol not pay &yogh;ow but on bedde /
<PB REF="00000469.tif" N="457"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="180"></L>
<L>For&yogh;eue it me myn owne spouse deere /</L>
<L N="1616">Turne hiderward and make better cheere</L>
<L>This marchaund saugh noon o&thorn;er remedy</L>
<L>And for to chide. it nas but foly</L>
<L>Si&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;ing may not amendid be /</L>
<L N="1620">wif he sayde / and I for&yogh;iue it &thorn;e</L>
<L>But by &thorn;i lif ne be no more so large</L>
<L>keep better my good &thorn;is &yogh;iue I &thorn;e in charge</L>
<L>Thus ende&thorn; now my tale and god vs sende</L>
<L N="1624">Talyng ynough vnto our lyues ende / Amen /<NOTE PLACE="end">[Foot of page. No other break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
