<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000470.tif" N="458">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="181">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WEl sayd by corpus boones quod oure host<MILESTONE N="200a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Now longe mot &thorn;ou sayle by &thorn;e cost</L>
<L>Sir gentil maister gentil mariner</L>
<L N="1628">God &yogh;iue &thorn;e monk a &thorn;ousand last quade&yogh;er</L>
<L>haha felaws be war for such a iape</L>
<L>The monk put in &thorn;e mannes hood an ape</L>
<L>And in his wyues eek by seint austyn</L>
<L N="1632">Drawe&thorn; no monkes more vnto &yogh;our In</L>
<L>But now pasouer and let vs loke aboute</L>
<L>who schal telle first of al &thorn;is route /</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er tale / and wi&thorn; &thorn;at wi&thorn; &thorn;at word he sayde /</L>
<L N="1636">As curteisly as it had ben a mayde /</L>
<L>My lady prioresse by &yogh;our leue</L>
<L>So &thorn;at I wist I scholde &yogh;ow not greue</L>
<L>I wolde deme &thorn;at &yogh;e telle scholde</L>
<L N="1640">A tale next if so were &thorn;at &yogh;e wolde /</L>
<L>Now wol &yogh;e vouche sauf my lady deere /</L>
<L>Gladly quod sche / and sayd in &thorn;is manere<NOTE PLACE="end">[Break of one line in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">


<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000471.tif" N="459">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="182">
<HEAD>[THE PROEM.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O Lord oure lord &thorn;y name how merueylous<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Domine domi|nus noster.</NOTE></L>
<L>Is in &thorn;is large world I-sprad quod sche</L>
<L>For nought oonly &thorn;y laude precious</L>
<L>Parformed is by men of heih degre</L>
<L N="1647">But by mouthes of children &thorn;y bounte<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ex ore infancium</NOTE></L>
<L>Parformed is on oure brest soukynge</L>
<L N="1649">Som tyme schewe &thorn;ay &thorn;in heriynge<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No stanza-breaks in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1650">Wherfore in laude as I best can or may</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e and of &thorn;y white lily flour</L>
<L>which &thorn;at &thorn;e bar and is a mayde alway</L>
<L>To telle a story I wil do my labour</L>
<L N="1654">Nought &thorn;at I may encresce &yogh;oure honour</L>
<L>For sche hir silf / is honour and roote</L>
<L N="1656">Of bounte next hir sone and soules boote/</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1657">O modir mayde. O mayde mooder fre /</L>
<L>O bussh vnbrent/ brennyng in Moises sight/</L>
<L>That rauysshedest / doun fro &thorn;e deite</L>
<L>Thurgh &thorn;in humblesse &thorn;e gost &thorn;at in &thorn;e alight</L>
<L N="1661">Of whos vertu he in &thorn;in herte pigh</L>
<L>Conceyued was &thorn;e fadres sapience<MILESTONE N="200b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1663">help me to telle it in &thorn;y reuerence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1664">Lady &thorn;i bounte and &thorn;y magnificence</L>
<L>Thy vertu and &thorn;i gret humilite</L>
<L>Ther may no tonge expres in no science</L>
<L>For som tyme lady er men pray to &thorn;e /</L>
<L N="1668">Thow gost biforn of &thorn;y benignite</L>
<L>And getist vs &thorn;e light &thorn;urgh &thorn;y prayere /</L>
<L N="1670">To gyden vs &thorn;e way to &thorn;y sone sone so deere/
<PB REF="00000472.tif" N="460"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="183"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1671">My connyng is to weyk o blisful queene</L>
<L>For to declare &thorn;y grete wor&thorn;inesse</L>
<L>That I may not &thorn;is in my wyt susteene</L>
<L>But as a child of twelf month old or lesse</L>
<L N="1675">Than can vnnethes eny word expresse</L>
<L>Right so fare I and &thorn;erfor I &yogh;ou pray</L>
<L N="1677">Endith my song &thorn;at I schal of &yogh;ow say<NOTE PLACE="end">[A break of one line in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[THE TALE.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1678">THer was in acy in a greet Citee</L>
<L>Amonges cristen folk a Iewerye</L>
<L>Susteyned by a lord of &thorn;at contre</L>
<L>For foul vsure and lucre of felonye /</L>
<L N="1682">Hateful to crist and to his compaignye /</L>
<L>And &thorn;urgh &thorn;e strete men might ride and wende /</L>
<L N="1684">For it was fre and open at euerich ende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1685">A litel scole of cristen folk &thorn;er stood</L>
<L>Doun at &thorn;e for&thorn;er ende in which &thorn;er were</L>
<L>Children an heep ycomen of cristes blood</L>
<L>That lered in &thorn;at scole &yogh;er by &yogh;ere</L>
<L N="1689">Such maner doctrine as men vsed &thorn;ere</L>
<L>This is to say to synge and to rede</L>
<L N="1691">As smale childer doon in her childhede /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1692">Among &thorn;ese children was a widow sone</L>
<L>A litel clergeoun &thorn;at seue &yogh;er was of age</L>
<L>That day by day to scole was his wone</L>
<L>And eek also wher-so he saugh &thorn;ymage</L>
<L N="1696">Of cristes moder had he in vsage</L>
<L>As him was taught to knele a doun and say /</L>
<L N="1698">His Aue maria as he go&thorn; by &thorn;e way<MILESTONE N="201a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000473.tif" N="461"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="184"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1699">Thus ha&thorn; &thorn;is widow hir litel child I-taught</L>
<L>Oure blisful lady cristes moder deere</L>
<L>To worschip ay and he for&yogh;at it nought</L>
<L>For cely child wil alway soone leere</L>
<L N="1703">But ay whan I remembre of &thorn;is matiere</L>
<L>Seint Nicholas stont euer in my presence</L>
<L N="1705">For he so &yogh;ong to crist dede reuerence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1706">This litil child his litel book lernynge</L>
<L>As he sat in &thorn;e scole at his primere</L>
<L>He O alma redemptoris herde synge/</L>
<L>As children lerned her antiphonere</L>
<L N="1710">And as he durst he drough hem ner and neere</L>
<L>And herkned euer &thorn;e wordes and &thorn;e note</L>
<L N="1712">Til he &thorn;e firste vers cou&thorn;e al by rote</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1713">Nought wist he what &thorn;is latyn was to say /</L>
<L>For he so &yogh;ong and tender was of age</L>
<L>But on a day his felaw gan he pray /</L>
<L>To expoune him &thorn;e song in his langage/</L>
<L N="1717">Or telle him what &thorn;is song was in vsage /</L>
<L>This prayd he him to construe and declare</L>
<L N="1719">Ful often tyme vpon his knees bare /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1720">His felaw which &thorn;at elder was &thorn;an he</L>
<L>Answerd him &thorn;us. &thorn;is song I. haue herd seye</L>
<L>was maked of our blisful lady fre</L>
<L>Hire to saluen and eek hire to preye</L>
<L N="1724">To ben our help and socour whan we deye</L>
<L>I can no more expoune in this matere</L>
<L N="1726">I lerne song I can no more gramer</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1727">And is &thorn;is song I-maad in reuerence</L>
<L>Of cristes moder sayde &thorn;is Innocent</L>
<L>Now certes I wol do my diligence</L>
<L>To conne it al er cristemasse be went
<PB REF="00000474.tif" N="462"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="185"></L>
<L N="1731">Though &thorn;at I for my primer schal be schent /</L>
<L>And schal be betyn &thorn;ries in an hour</L>
<L N="1733">I wol it conne oure lady to honoure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1734">His felaw taught him homward priuely</L>
<L>From day by day til he cou&thorn;e it by rote</L>
<L>And &thorn;an he song it wel and boldely<MILESTONE N="201b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Twyes on &thorn;e day it passed &thorn;urgh his &thorn;rote</L>
<L N="1738">From word to word accordyng to &thorn;e note</L>
<L>To scoleward and homward whan he went</L>
<L N="1740">On cristes moder was set al his entent</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1741">As I haue sayd &thorn;urghout &thorn;e Iewrye</L>
<L>This litel child as he cam to and fro</L>
<L>Ful merily &thorn;an wold he synge and crie /</L>
<L>O alma Redemptoris euer mo</L>
<L N="1745">The swetnes ha&thorn; his herte persed so</L>
<L>Of cristes moder that to hir to pray</L>
<L N="1747">he can not stynt of syngyng by &thorn;e way /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1748">Oure firste foo &thorn;e serpent Sathanas</L>
<L>That hath in Iewes hert his waspis nest</L>
<L>Vpswal and sayde / o ebreik peple allas</L>
<L>Is &thorn;is a &thorn;ing to &yogh;ow &thorn;at is honest</L>
<L N="1752">That such a boy schal walken as him lest</L>
<L>In &yogh;oure despyt and synge of such sentence</L>
<L N="1754">which is a&yogh;ens &yogh;our lawes reuerence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1755">Fro &thorn;ennes forth &thorn;e Iewes han conspired</L>
<L>This Innocent out of &thorn;is world to enchace</L>
<L>An homicide &thorn;er to han &yogh;e &thorn;ay hired</L>
<L>That in an aley had a priue place</L>
<L N="1759">And as &thorn;e childe gan for&thorn; by to pace</L>
<L>This false iewe him hent and huld ful faste /</L>
<L N="1761">And kut his &thorn;rote and &thorn;rewe him in atte laste
<PB REF="00000475.tif" N="463"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="186"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1762">I say in a wardrobe &thorn;ay him &thorn;rew</L>
<L>wher as the Iewes purgen her entraile</L>
<L>O cursed folk O herodes al newe</L>
<L>what may &yogh;our euyl entente &yogh;ou auaile</L>
<L N="1766">Morther wol out certeyn it wil nought faile</L>
<L>And namly &thorn;er &thorn;onour of god schuld sprede</L>
<L N="1768">The blood out crie&thorn; on &yogh;our cursed dede /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1769">O martir soudit to Virginite</L>
<L>Now maystow synge folowyng euer in oon</L>
<L>The white lomb celestial quod sche /</L>
<L>Of which &thorn;e grete euaungelist seint Iohn</L>
<L N="1773">In pathmos wroot which seith &thorn;at &thorn;ay goon</L>
<L>Bifore &thorn;e lamb and synge a song al newe<MILESTONE N="202a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1775">That neuer fleischly wommen &thorn;ay knewe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1776">This pore widowe wayte&thorn; al &thorn;is night</L>
<L>After &thorn;is litel child but he cometh nought</L>
<L>For which as soone as it was dayes light</L>
<L>with face pale in drede and busy &thorn;ought</L>
<L N="1780">Sche ha&thorn; at scole and elles-wher him sought</L>
<L>Til fynally sche gan of hem aspye</L>
<L N="1782">That he was last/ seyn in &thorn;e Iewerie</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1783">With moodres pite in hir brest enclosed</L>
<L>Sche go&thorn; as sche were half out of hir mynde</L>
<L>To euery place wher sche ha&thorn; supposed</L>
<L>By liklihede hir child for to fynde</L>
<L N="1787">And euer on cristes mooder meke and kynde</L>
<L>Sche cried and atte laste &thorn;us sche wrought</L>
<L N="1789">Among &thorn;e cursed Iewes sche him sought</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1790">Sche freyned and sche prayed pitously</L>
<L>To euery Iew &thorn;at dwelled in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>To telle hir if hir child wente &thorn;er by</L>
<L>Thay sayden nay but Ih&umacr; of his grace
<PB REF="00000476.tif" N="464"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="187"></L>
<L N="1794">&YOGH;af in hir &thorn;ought wi&thorn;inne a litel space</L>
<L>That in &thorn;at place after hir sone sche cryde</L>
<L N="1796">wher as he was cast in a put besyde /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1797">O grete god &thorn;at parformedist &thorn;in laude</L>
<L>by mouth of Innocent&yogh; lo here &thorn;y might</L>
<L>This gemme of chastite &thorn;is emeraude</L>
<L>And eek of martirdom &thorn;e ruby bright</L>
<L N="1801">Ther he with &thorn;rote I-kut lay vpright</L>
<L>He . Alma redemptoris gan to synge</L>
<L N="1803">So lowde &thorn;at al &thorn;e place bigan to rynge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1804">The cristen folk &thorn;at &thorn;urgh &thorn;e strete went/</L>
<L>In comen for to wonder vpon &thorn;is &thorn;ing</L>
<L>And hastily for the prouost &thorn;ay sent</L>
<L>He cam anoon wi&thorn;oute tarying</L>
<L N="1808">And heriede crist &thorn;at is of heuen kyng</L>
<L>And eek his moder honour of mankynde</L>
<L N="1810">And after &thorn;at &thorn;e Iewes let he bynde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1811">This child with pitous lamentacioun</L>
<L>vp taken was syngyng his song alway<MILESTONE N="202b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And with honour of gret processioun</L>
<L>Thay caried him vnto &thorn;e next abbay</L>
<L N="1815">His modir swownyng by &thorn;e beere lay</L>
<L>Vnne&thorn;e might &thorn;e poeple &thorn;at was &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="1817">This newe Rachel bringe fro &thorn;e beere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1818">With torment and with schamful deth echon</L>
<L>This prouost do&thorn; &thorn;ese Iewes for to sterue</L>
<L>That of &thorn;is moerder wist and &thorn;at anoon</L>
<L>he wolde no such cursednesse obserue</L>
<L N="1822">Euel schal haue &thorn;at euyl wol deserue</L>
<L>Therfore with wilde hors he dede hem drawe</L>
<L N="1824">And after &thorn;at he heng hem by &thorn;e lawe
<PB REF="00000477.tif" N="465"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="188"></L>
<L N="1825">Vpon his beere ay lith &thorn;is Innocent</L>
<L>Biforn &thorn;e chief auter whiles &thorn;e masse last</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at &thorn;abbot with his couent</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; sped him for to burie him ful fast</L>
<L N="1829">And whan &thorn;ay halywater on him cast</L>
<L>&YOGH;et spak &thorn;is child. whan spreynde was &thorn;e water</L>
<L N="1831">And song O alma redemptoris mater</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1832">This abbot which &thorn;at was an holy man</L>
<L>As monkes ben or elles oughte be</L>
<L>This &yogh;onge child to coniure he bigan</L>
<L>And sayd O deere child I halse &thorn;e</L>
<L N="1836">In vertu of &thorn;e holy trinite</L>
<L>Tel me what is &thorn;y cause for to synge</L>
<L N="1838">Sith &thorn;at &thorn;y throte is kit at my semynge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1839">My &thorn;rote is kit vnto my nekke boon</L>
<L>Sayde &thorn;is child and as by way of kynde</L>
<L>I schulde han ben deed long tyme a goon</L>
<L>But Ih&umacr; crist as &yogh;e in bookes fynde</L>
<L N="1843">wol &thorn;at his glorie laste and be in mynde</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e worschip of his moder deere</L>
<L N="1845">&YOGH;et may I synge. O alma lowde and cleere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1846">This welle of mercy cristes moder swete</L>
<L>I loued alway as after my connynge</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at I my lyf schulde leete</L>
<L>To me sche cam and bad me for to synge</L>
<L N="1850">This antym verraily in my deyinge<MILESTONE N="203a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As &yogh;e haue herd and whan &thorn;at I had songe</L>
<L N="1852">Me &thorn;ought sche layde a grayn vnder my tonge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1853">Wherfor I synge and synge moot certeyne</L>
<L>In honour of &thorn;at blisful mayden fre</L>
<L>Til fro my tonge taken is &thorn;e greyne</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at &thorn;us saide sche to me
<PB REF="00000478.tif" N="466"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="189"></L>
<L N="1857">My litil child now wil I fecche &thorn;e</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at &thorn;e grayn is fro &thorn;i tonge I-take</L>
<L N="1859">Be nought agast I wol &thorn;e nought forsake</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1860">This holy monk this abbot him mene I</L>
<L>His tonge out caught and took awey &thorn;e greyn</L>
<L>And he &yogh;af vp &thorn;e gost ful softely</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;e abbot hath &thorn;is wonder seyn</L>
<L N="1864">His salte teres striken doun as reyn</L>
<L>And gruf he fel a doun vnto &thorn;e grounde</L>
<L N="1866">And stille he lay as he had ben y-bounde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1867">The couent eek lay on &thorn;e pauyment</L>
<L>wepyng and herying cristes moder deere</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at &thorn;ay rise and for&thorn; &thorn;ay went</L>
<L>And took away &thorn;is martir fro his beere /</L>
<L N="1871">In a tombe of marble stoones cleere</L>
<L>Enclosed &thorn;ay &thorn;is litil body sweete</L>
<L N="1873">Ther he is now god leue vs for to meete</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1874">O &yogh;onge hughe of lyncoln slayn also</L>
<L>wi&thorn; cursed iewes as it is notable /</L>
<L>For it nys but a litel while ago</L>
<L>Pray eek for vs we synful folk vnstable</L>
<L N="1878">That of his mercy god so merciable</L>
<L>On vs his grete mercy multiplie</L>
<L N="1880">For reuerence of his modir marie Amen<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000479.tif" N="467">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="190">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1881">Whan sayd was &thorn;is miracle euery man</L>
<L>As sober was &thorn;at wonder was to se</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at oure host to iape bigan</L>
<L>And &thorn;an at erst/ he loked vpon me</L>
<L N="1885">And sayde &thorn;us what man art &thorn;ou quod he</L>
<L>Thou lokest as &thorn;ou woldest fynde an hare</L>
<L N="1887">For euer vpon &thorn;e ground I se &thorn;e stare /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1888">Approche ner and loke merily<MILESTONE N="203b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Now ware &yogh;ou sires and let &thorn;is man haue space</L>
<L>He in &thorn;e wast is schape as wel as I</L>
<L>This were a popet in an arm to embrace</L>
<L N="1892">For any womman smal and fair of face /</L>
<L>He semeth eluisch by his countenaunce</L>
<L N="1894">For vnto no wight doth he daliaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1895">Say now som what sins other folk han said</L>
<L>Telle vs a tale and &thorn;at of mirthe anoon</L>
<L>host quod I ne be&thorn; nought euel apayd</L>
<L>For other tale certes can I noon</L>
<L N="1899">But of a rym I lerned &yogh;ore agoon</L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;at is good quod he now schul we heere</L>
<L N="1901">Som deynte &thorn;ing me &thorn;inketh by his cheere<NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>Break of</I> 1 <I>line in the MS.</I>]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">


<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000480.tif" N="468">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="191">
<HEAD>[The First Fit.]<NOTE PLACE="head">[No stanza-gaps are in the MS., and no lines are inset.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LEstene&thorn; lordyngs . in good entent</L>
<L>And I wol telle verrayment</L>
<L N="1904">Of myrthe and solas</L>
<L>Of a knyght was fair and gent</L>
<L>In batail and in tornament</L>
<L N="1907">His name was sir Thopas</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I-bore he was in fer conntre</L>
<L>In Flaundres al by&yogh;onde &thorn;e se</L>
<L N="1910">At Poperyng in &thorn;e place</L>
<L>His fader was a man ful fre</L>
<L>And lord he was of &thorn;at contre</L>
<L N="1913">As it was goddes grace</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sir Thopas wax a doughty swayn</L>
<L>whyt was his face as payndemayn</L>
<L N="1916">His lippes reed as Rose /</L>
<L>His rode is lik / scarlet en grayn</L>
<L>And I &yogh;ow telle in good certayn</L>
<L N="1919">He had a semly nose</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His heer his berd was lik/ safroun</L>
<L>That to his girdil raught a doun</L>
<L N="1922">His schoon of Cordewane</L>
<L>Of Brigges were his hosen broun</L>
<L>His robe was of Sicladoun</L>
<L N="1925">That coste many a Iane<MILESTONE N="204a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000481.tif" N="469"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="192"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He cou&thorn;e hunt at wilde deer</L>
<L>And ride on haukyng for ryuer</L>
<L N="1928">with gray goshauk on honde</L>
<L>Therto he was a good archeer</L>
<L>Of wrastelyng was noon his peer</L>
<L N="1931">Ther eny Ram schal stonde /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ful many mayde bright in bour</L>
<L>&THORN;ay mourne for him paramour</L>
<L N="1934">whan hem were bet to slepe</L>
<L>But he was chast and no lecchour</L>
<L>And sweet as is &thorn;e brembre flour</L>
<L N="1937">That bere&thorn; &thorn;e reede heepe /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And so it fel vpon a day</L>
<L>For so&thorn; as I &yogh;ow telle may /</L>
<L N="1940">Sir Thopas wold out ryde</L>
<L>he worth vpon his steede gray</L>
<L>And in his hond a launcegay</L>
<L N="1943">A long sword by his syde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>he priketh &thorn;urgh a fair forest/</L>
<L>Ther In is many a wilde best/</L>
<L N="1946">&YOGH;e bo&thorn;e buk / and hare</L>
<L>And as he prike&thorn; north and Est</L>
<L>I tel it &yogh;ow hym had almest</L>
<L N="1949">Bityd a sory care</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ther springen herbes greet and smale</L>
<L>The licorys and &thorn;e Cetewale /</L>
<L N="1952">And many a clow gilofre</L>
<L>And notemuge to put in ale</L>
<L>whe&thorn;ir it be moist or stale</L>
<L N="1955">Or for to lay in cofre
<PB REF="00000482.tif" N="470"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="193"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The briddes synge it is no nay</L>
<L>The sperhauk and &thorn;e popiniay</L>
<L N="1958">That ioye it was to heere</L>
<L>The &thorn;rostilcok maad eek his lay</L>
<L>The woode dowue vpon &thorn;e spray</L>
<L N="1961">So song ful lowde and cleere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sir Thopas fel in loue-longing</L>
<L>whan that he herde &thorn;e briddes synge<MILESTONE N="204b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1964">And priked as he were wood</L>
<L>His faire steede in his prikynge</L>
<L>So swette &thorn;at men might him wrynge</L>
<L N="1967">His sydes were al blood</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sir Thopas eek so wery was</L>
<L>For priking on &thorn;e softe gras</L>
<L N="1970">So feers was his corrage</L>
<L>That doun he layd him in &thorn;e place</L>
<L>To make his steede som solace</L>
<L N="1973">And &yogh;af him good forage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O seinte Mary benedicite</L>
<L>what eylith &thorn;is loue at me</L>
<L N="1976">To bynde me so sore</L>
<L>My dremed al this night par de</L>
