<DIV2 TYPE="tale" N="Melibee">

<PB REF="00000490.tif" N="478">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="201">
<HEADNOTE><P>[There are no line-numbers or paragraph-breaks in the MS. Tyrwhitt's breaks are kept here, as they were in the Six-Text, to prevent slight differences in the Texts throwing out many lines.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<P>[2157] A &yogh;ong man called Melibeus mighty and riche<MILESTONE N="207a" UNIT="folio"> bygat vpon his wif &thorn;at called was prudens. a doughter; which &thorn;at called was Sophie //</P>
<P>[2158] Vpon a day byfel &thorn;at for his desport he is went in to &thorn;e feldes him to / play. [2159] his wif and his dou&yogh;ter eek ha&thorn; he laft in-with his hous of which &thorn;e dores were fast I-schitte. [2160] &thorn;re of his olde foos han it espyed. and setten laddres to &thorn;e walles of his hous and by &thorn;e wyndowes ben entred [2161] and beetyn his wyf and woundid his dou&yogh;ter wi&thorn; fyue mortal woundes in fyue sondry places [2162] &thorn;at is to sayn in here feet in here hondes in here eeres in here nose and in here mouth and lafte her for deed and went away</P>
<P>[2163] &para; whan Melibeus retourned was in to his hous and seigh al &thorn;is meschief he lik a man mad rendyng his clo&thorn;es gan wepe and crie.</P>
<P>[2164] Prudens his wyf as ferforth as sche dorste bisou&yogh;t him of his wepyng to stynte / [2165] But not for &thorn;i he gan to crie euer lenger &thorn;e more</P>
<P>[2166] &para; this noble wyf prudence remembred hire vpon &thorn;e sentens of Ovide in his book that cleped is &thorn;e remedy of loue / wher as he sei&thorn; [2167] &para; he is a fool<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ouidius de remedio amoris</NOTE> &thorn;at destourbe&thorn; &thorn;e moder to wepe in &thorn;e deth of hir childe til sche haue I-wept hir fille as for a certeyn tyme [2168] and &thorn;an schal man doon his diligence as with amyable wordes hire to recomforte and praye hire of 
<PB REF="00000491.tif" N="479"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="202"> hire wepyng to stinte [2169] &para; For which resoun &thorn;is noble wif prudens suffred hir housbonde for to wepe and crie / as for a certeyn space. [2170] and whan sche seigh hir tyme; sche sayd him in &thorn;is wise &para; Allas my lord quod sche why make &yogh;e &yogh;oure self for to be lik a fool. [2171] For so&thorn;e it apperteyne&thorn; not to a wys man to make such sorwe. [2172] &YOGH;oure dou&yogh;ter wi&thorn; &thorn;e grace of god schal warischt be and eschape. [2173] and al were it so &thorn;at sche right now were deed; &yogh;e ne oughte nou&yogh;t as for hir de&thorn; &yogh;oure silf destroye [2174] &para; Senec sai&thorn;. &thorn;e wise man schal not take to gret discomfort for &thorn;e deth of his children; [2175] but certes he schulde suffren it in pacience as wel as he abyde&thorn; &thorn;e de&thorn; of his owne persone</P>
<P>[2176] &para; This melibeus answerde anoon &amp; sayde &para; what man quod he schuld of his wepynge stynte &thorn;at ha&thorn; a cause for to wepe [2177] &para; Ih&umacr; crist<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Qualiter ihe <I>christus</I> fleuit propter mortem lazari</NOTE> oure lord himself wepte for &thorn;e deth of la&yogh;arus his frend [2178] &para; Prudens answerde Certes wel I wot/ attemperel wepyng is no &thorn;ing defended to him &thorn;at sorwful is. amonges folk in sorwe. But it is ra&thorn;er graunted him to wepe / [2179] &thorn;e apostel poule vnto &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">Apostolus ad romanos</NOTE> Romayns write&thorn;. A man schal reioyce with hem &thorn;at maken ioye / And wepe with such folk as wepen [2180] &para; But &thorn;ough attemperel <MILESTONE N="207b" UNIT="folio">wepyng be graunted; Outrageous wepynge certes is defended // [2181] Mesure of wepynge be conserued. after &thorn;e lore of crist &thorn;at teche&thorn; vs senec [2182] &para; whan &thorn;at &thorn;i frend is deed quod he; let nought &thorn;in yen to moyste ben of teres ne to moche drye &para; Al &thorn;ough the teeres come out of &thorn;ine ey&yogh;en; let he not falle [2183] &para; And whan &thorn;ou hast forgon &thorn;y frend; do dili|gence to gete ano&thorn;er frende &para; And &thorn;is is more wisedom &thorn;an to wepe for &thorn;y frend which &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast lorn. For &thorn;er in is no boote [2184] &para; And &thorn;erfore if &yogh;e gouerne &yogh;ow by sapience put away sorwe out of &yogh;oure hert [2185] &para; Remembreth &yogh;ow &thorn;at Ihc Sirac sai&thorn; 
<PB REF="00000492.tif" N="480"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="203"> &para; A man &thorn;at is ioyous and glad in herte; it him con|serveth florischinge in his age &para; But so&thorn;ly sorweful herte make&thorn; his boones drye [2186] &para; he sai&thorn; eek &thorn;us. &thorn;at sorwe in herte sle&thorn; ful many a man [2187] &para; Sa|lamon sai&thorn; &thorn;at right as motthes in schepes flees annoyeth &thorn;e clothes. and &thorn;e smale wormes to &thorn;e tre; Right / so annoye&thorn; sorwe to &thorn;e herte [2188] &para; wherfore vs oughte as wel in &thorn;e de&thorn; of oure children as in &thorn;e losse of oure goodes temporales haue pacience</P>
<P>[2189] &para; Remembreth &yogh;ow vpon &thorn;e pacien Iop &para; whan he hadde lost his children and his temporal sub|stance and in his body endured and receyued ful many a greuous tribulacioun; &yogh;it sayde he &thorn;us [2190] &para; Oure lord it/ sent/ vnto me Oure lord it ha&thorn; raft fro me. Right so as oure lord wil; ri&yogh;t so be it doon &para; I-blessed be &thorn;e name of oure lord [2191] To &thorn;ese forsayde &thorn;inges answerith Melibeus vnto his wif Prudens Alle &thorn;ine wordes ben so&thorn; quod he and &thorn;erto pro|fytable &para; But so&thorn;ly myn herte is so troubled wi&thorn; &thorn;is sorwe; &thorn;at I noot/ what to doone [2192] &para; Let calle quod prudence &thorn;y trewe frendes alle and &thorn;y linage whiche &thorn;at ben trewe &amp; wise. telleth hem &yogh;oure greuaunce and herken what &thorn;ay say in counseilynge. and &yogh;ow gouerne after here sentence. [2193] &para; Salomon saith &para; werke al &thorn;i &thorn;ing by counseil and &thorn;e &thorn;ar neuer rewe</P>
<P>[2194] &para; &THORN;an by &thorn;e counseil of his wyf prudens this melibeus let calle a gret congregacioun of peple [2195] as Surgiens. phisiciens olde and &yogh;onge and some of his olde enemyes recounsiled as by her semblaunt to his loue and to his grace. [2196] and &thorn;er wi&thorn; al &thorn;er come some of his neighebours &thorn;at deden him reuerence more for drede &thorn;an for loue as happe&thorn; ofte [2197] &para; Ther comen also ful many subtil flaterers and wise aduoketes lerned in &thorn;e lawe</P>
<P>[2198] &para; And whan &thorn;ese folk togidere assemblid were; This melibeus in sorwful wyse schewed hem his caas. 
<PB REF="00000493.tif" N="481"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="204"> [2199] and by &thorn;e maner of his speche; it semed &thorn;at in <MILESTONE N="208a" UNIT="folio">herte he bar a cruel Ire redy to do venge|ance vpon his foos. and sodeynly desirede &thorn;at &thorn;e werre schulde bygynne. [2200] but natheles &yogh;it axed he her counseil in &thorn;is matier. [2201] &para; A Sirurgien by licens and assent of suche as were wyse vp ros and to melibeus sayde as &yogh;e may hiere</P>
<P>[2202] &para; Sire quod he as to vs Sirurgiens appertieneth &thorn;at we do to euery wight &thorn;e beste &thorn;at we can wher as we ben withholde and to oure pacient &thorn;at we do no damage [2203] &para; wherfore it happe&thorn; many tyme and ofte &thorn;at whan tweye han euerich wounded o&thorn;er; oo. same surgien hele&thorn; hem bo&thorn;e. [2204] where vnto oure art it is not perteyned to norische werre ne parties to supporte; [2205] but certes as to warisching of &yogh;oure dou&yogh;ter al be it so &thorn;at sche perilously be woundid; we schullen do so tentyf besynes fro day to night &thorn;at with &thorn;e grace of god sche schal be hool and sound als soone as it is possible [2206] &para; Almost right in &thorn;e same wise &thorn;e phisiciens answerden; saue &thorn;at &thorn;ay sayden a fewe wordes more [2207] &para; That ryght as maladies ben cured by her contraries; Right so schal men warissch werre by vengeaunce [2208] &para; His neyhe|boures ful of enuye his feyned freendes &thorn;at semede recounsiled his flatereres [2209] maden semblaunt of wepyng and appaired and aggregged moche of &thorn;is matiere in preisyng gretly melibe of might. of power of Riches. and of frendes despisinge &thorn;e power of his aduersaries [2210] and sayden outerly &thorn;at he anoon schulde wreke him on his aduersaries be bygynnynge of werre</P>
<P>[2211] vp roos &thorn;anne an aduocate &thorn;at was wys. by leue and by counseil of o&thorn;ere &thorn;at were wise and sayde / [2212] &para; Lordynges. &thorn;e needes for whiche we ben assemblit in &thorn;is place is ful heuy &thorn;ing and an heigh matier [2213] by cause of &thorn;e wrong &amp; of &thorn;e wikkednes &thorn;at ha&thorn; ben doon and eek of &thorn;e grete damages &thorn;at 
<PB REF="00000494.tif" N="482"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="205"> in tyme comyng ben possible to falle for &thorn;e same [2214] and eek by cause of &thorn;e grete richesse and power of &thorn;e partes bothe [2215] for &thorn;e whiche resouns it were a ful gret peril to erren in these materes [2216] &para; wherfore melibeus &thorn;is is oure sentence &para; we counseile &yogh;ow abouen alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at ri&yogh;t anoon &thorn;ou do diligence in kepyng of &thorn;y body in such a wyse &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne wante noon espye ne wacche &thorn;y body for to saue [2217] &para; And after &thorn;at we counseile &thorn;at in &thorn;in hous &thorn;ou sette sufficaunt garnisoun So &thorn;at &thorn;ay may as wel &thorn;y body as &thorn;in hous defende [2218] &para; But certes for to moeue werre ne sodeynly for to do vengeance; we may not deme in so litel tyme &thorn;at it were profit|able [2219] &para; wherfore we axen leysir <MILESTONE N="208b" UNIT="folio">and a space [. . . .] in &thorn;is caas to demen [2220] &para; For &thorn;e comune prouerbe sai&thorn; &thorn;is &para; he &thorn;at soone deme&thorn; soone schal repente [2221] &para; And eek men sayn &thorn;at &thorn;ilke Iuge is wys &thorn;at soone vnderstonde&thorn; a matier and Iugge&thorn; by leysir. [2222] &para; For al be it so &thorn;at / alle taryinge is anoyful; algates it is no reproef in &yogh;euynge of Iuggement. ne of ve[n]gaunce takyng whan it is suffisaunt and resonable [2223] and &thorn;at schewed oure lord ih&umacr; crist by en|sample &para; For whan &thorn;at &thorn;e womman &thorn;at was I-take in aduoutrie was brou&yogh;t in his presence to knowen what schulde be doon of hir persone Al be it &thorn;at he wist him self what &thorn;at he wolde answere; &yogh;it wolde he not answere sodeynly. but he wolde haue deliberacioun and in &thorn;e ground hem wrot twyes. [2224] and by &thorn;ese causes we axe deliberacioun. and we schul &thorn;anne by &thorn;e grace of god counseile &thorn;e &thorn;ing &thorn;at schal be profytable</P>
<P>[2225] &para; Vpstarten &thorn;enne &thorn;e &yogh;onge folkes anoon at oones; and &thorn;e moste part of &thorn;at companye han skorned &thorn;ese olde wise men and bygonne to make noyse and sayden [2226] &para; Right so as whil &thorn;at/ Iren is hoot men scholden smyte; Right so schulde men wreke here wronges whil 
<PB REF="00000495.tif" N="483"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="206"> &thorn;at &thorn;ay ben freische and newe &para; And with lowde vois &thorn;ay cryde. werre. werre.</P>
<P>[2227] &para; Vproos &thorn;o oon of &thorn;ese olde wise and with his hond made countenaunce &thorn;at men schulde holde hem stille and &yogh;iuen him audience [2228] &para; lordyngs quod he ther is ful many a man &thorn;at crieth werre werre wot ful litel what werre amounteth. [2229] werre at his bygynnyng ha&thorn; so greet and entre and so large &thorn;at euery wight may entre whan him like&thorn; and lightly fynde werre [2230] &para; But certes what ende schal falle &thorn;erof; it is not lightly to knowe [2231] For so&thorn;ly whan &thorn;at werre is oones bygonne; &thorn;er is ful many a child vnbore of his mooder &thorn;at schal sterue &yogh;ong by cause of &thorn;ilke werre or elles lyue in sorwe and deye in wrecchidnes [2232] &para; &amp; &thorn;erfore er &thorn;at eny werre be bygonne. men moste haue gret counseil and gret deliberacioun. [2233] &para; And whan &thorn;is olde man wende to enforce his tale by resouns wel neigh alle at oones bygonne &thorn;ay to rise for to breke his tale and beden him fulofte his wordes to abrigge. [2234] For so&thorn;ly he &thorn;at preche&thorn; to hem that liste not to heere his wordes his sermoun hem anoyeth [2235] &para; For Ihesus Sirac saith &thorn;at wepyng in musik is a noyous &thorn;ing. &thorn;is is to say &para; As moche auayle&thorn; to speke tofore folk/ to whiche his speche annoye&thorn;; as it is to synge byfore hem whiche &thorn;at wepith [2236] <MILESTONE N="209a" UNIT="folio">&para; And whan &thorn;is wise man saugh him wanted audience; al schamefast he sette him doun agayn [2237] &para; For Salamon saith. ther as &thorn;ou may haue noon audience; enforce &thorn;e not to speke [2238] &para; I se wel quod &thorn;is wise man &thorn;at &thorn;e comune prouerbe is so&thorn; &para; That good counseil wantith whan it is most neede</P>
<P>[2239] &para; &YOGH;it hadde &thorn;is melibeus in his counseil many folk &thorn;at priuely in his eere han counseled him certein &thorn;inges and counseled him &thorn;e contrarie in general audience</P>
<P>[2240] &para; whan melibeus hadde herd &yogh;et &thorn;e grettest 
<PB REF="00000496.tif" N="484"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="207"> party of his counseil were accorded &thorn;at he schulde make werre. Anoon he consented to here counseilyng and fully affermed here sentence [2241] &para; Thanne dame Prudence whan &thorn;at sche saugh &thorn;at hir housbonde schop him to wreke him of his enemyes and to gynne werre; / Sche in ful humble wise whan sche saugh hire tyme sayde him &thorn;ese wordes [2242] &para; My lord quod sche I &yogh;ow biseche as hertily as I dar and kan ne haste &yogh;ow nought to faste and for alle guerdouns as &yogh;eue me audience [2243] &para; For Peres Alfons saith &para; who &thorn;at do&thorn; to &thorn;e ou&thorn;er good or harm; haste &thorn;e nought to quyten him. For in &thorn;is wise &thorn;y freend wil abyde; and &thorn;in enemy schal &thorn;e lenger lyue in drede [2244] &para; The prouerbe sai&thorn; &para; he hastith wel &thorn;at wisly can abyde and in wikked haste is no profyt</P>
<P>[2245] &para; This melibeus answerde vn to his wyf prudens &para; I purpose not quod he to werke by &thorn;y counseil for many causes and resouns &para; For certes euery wight wolde holde me &thorn;anne a fool [2246] &para; &thorn;is is to sayn &para; If I for &thorn;y counseil wolde chaunge &thorn;inges &thorn;at affermed ben by so many wise; [2247] I say &thorn;at alle wommen be wikked and noon good of hem alle &para; For of a &thorn;ousand men sai&thorn; Salomon I fond oon good man; But certes of alle wommen good womman fond I neuer noon [2248] &para; And also certes if I gouernede me by &thorn;y counseil it schulde seme that I hadde &yogh;iuen to &thorn;e ouer me &thorn;e maistry and god forbeede er it so were [2249] &para; For Ihc Syrac sai&thorn; &thorn;at if a wif haue maistrie sche is contrarious to hir housbond [2250] &para; and Salomon saith &para; Neuer in &thorn;y lif to &thorn;y wyf ne to &thorn;y child ne to &thorn;y freend ne &yogh;eue no power ouer &thorn;iself &para; For better it were &thorn;at &thorn;y children axen of &thorn;y persone &thorn;inges &thorn;at been needful to hem &thorn;an &thorn;ou se &thorn;iself in &thorn;e hondes of &thorn;y children [2251] &para; And also if I wolde werke by &thorn;y counselynge certes it most som tyme be secre til it were tyme &thorn;at it moste be 
<PB REF="00000497.tif" N="485"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="208"> knowe and &thorn;is ne may not be [2252] . . . . .[2253] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></P>
<P>[2254] whan dame Prudence ful debonerly and with gret pacience hadde herd al &thorn;at hir housbonde liked for to seye &para; Than axed sche of him licence <MILESTONE N="209b" UNIT="folio">for to speke and sayde in &thorn;is wise [2255] &para; My lord quod sche as to &yogh;oure firste resoun certes it may lightly be answered. For I say it is no foly to chaunge counsel whan &thorn;e &thorn;ing/ is chaungid. For elles whan &thorn;e &thorn;ing seme&thorn; o&thorn;erwise &thorn;an it was biforn [2256] And moreouer I say &thorn;ough &thorn;at &yogh;e han sworn and I-hight to parforme &yogh;oure emprise And na&thorn;eles &yogh;e wayue to parforme &thorn;ilke same emprise by iuste cause men schulde not say &thorn;erfore &thorn;at/ &yogh;e were a lyere ne forsworn [2257] For &thorn;e book/ sei&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e wise man make&thorn; no lesyng whan he torneth his corrage to &thorn;e better [2258] &para; And al be it so &thorn;at &yogh;oure emprise be establid and ordeyned by gret multitude of poeple; &yogh;it thar &yogh;e not accomplise &thorn;ilke same ordinaunce but &yogh;ou like / [2259] For &thorn;e trou&thorn;e of &thorn;ing and &thorn;e profyt ben rather founde in fewe folk &thorn;at ben wise and ful of resoun &thorn;an by gret multitude of folk &thorn;at euery man crieth and clatere&thorn; what &thorn;at him like&thorn; so&thorn;ely such multitude is not honest [2260] &para; An to &thorn;e secounde resoun wher as &yogh;e sayn &thorn;at alle wommen ben wikke; Saue &yogh;oure grace. Certis &yogh;e despise alle wommen in &thorn;is wise and &thorn;at alle despysith sai&thorn; &thorn;e book / [2261] And senec saith who-so wil haue Sapi|ence schal no man desprayse but he schal gladly teche &thorn;e science &thorn;at he can wi&thorn;oute presumpcioun of pryde [2262] and suche &thorn;inges as he nought can he schal not ben aschamed to lerne hem and enquere of lasse 
<PB REF="00000498.tif" N="486"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="209"> folk &thorn;an himself [2263] &para; And sire &thorn;er ha&thorn; be ful many a good womman . . . . .[2264] . . . . .if alle wommen hadde ben wikke [2265] after &thorn;at for &thorn;e grete bounte &thorn;at is in wommen; Oure lord ihu crist/ whan he was risen fro de&thorn; to lyue apperede ra&thorn;er to a womman &thorn;an to his apostles. [2266] &para; And &thorn;ough &thorn;at Salamon say he fond neuer good womman It folwith nou&yogh;t &thorn;erfore &thorn;at alle wommen ben wikke. [2267] For &thorn;ough &thorn;at he fonde noone goode wommen certes many a no&thorn;er man ha&thorn; founden many a womman ful goode and trewe [2268] &para; Or elles parauenture &thorn;entent of Salamon was &thorn;is as in souereyn bounte. he fond no womman [2269] &thorn;is is to say &thorn;at &thorn;er is no wight &thorn;at ha&thorn; souerein bounte saue god aloone as he himself recorde&thorn; in his euaun|gelie. [2270] For &thorn;er nys no creature so good &thorn;at him wantith som-what of &thorn;e perfeccioun of god &thorn;at is his makere [2271] &para; &YOGH;oure &thorn;ridde resoun is &thorn;is. &yogh;e seyn. &thorn;at if &yogh;e gouerned &yogh;ow by counsel of me it schulde seme &thorn;at &yogh;e hadde yeue me the maystry and &thorn;e lordschipe ouer &yogh;oure persone. [2272] sire saue &yogh;oure grace it is not so. For if so were &thorn;at no man schulde be counseiled but by hem &thorn;at hadde maystrie and lordschipe of his persone; men wolde nought be counseiled so ofte [2273] &para; For so&thorn;ly &thorn;ilke man &thorn;at axeth <MILESTONE N="210a" UNIT="folio">counseil of a purpos. &yogh;et ha&thorn; he fre chois whe&thorn;er he wil werke by &thorn;at purpos or noon [2274] &para; And so to &yogh;oure fer&thorn;e resoun &thorn;er &yogh;e sayn &thorn;at the ianglerie of wommen can hyde &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;ey wot not of as who saith &thorn;at a womman can nought hyde &thorn;at at sche woot; [2275] Sire &thorn;ese wordes ben vnder|stonde of wommen &thorn;at ben iangelers and wikke. [2276] of whiche wommen men sayn &thorn;at &thorn;re &thorn;inges dryuen a man out of his oughne hous &thorn;at is to say. smoke. droppyng of reyn and wikked wyfes. [2277] of 
<PB REF="00000499.tif" N="487"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="210"> suche wommen sai&thorn; salomon &thorn;at it were better to a man to dwelle in desert &thorn;an with a womman &thorn;at is riotous [2278] and sire by &yogh;oure leue &thorn;at am not I [2279] &para; For &yogh;e han ful ofte assayed my grete scilence and my grete pacience and eek how wel &thorn;at I can hyde and hele &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben secrely to hyde [2280] &para; And so&thorn;ly as to &yogh;oure fyfte resoun wher as &yogh;e sayn &thorn;at in wikkede coun|seil wommen venquisscheth men. god wot &thorn;ilke resoun stont here in no stede / [2281] For vnderstondith now &yogh;e a&yogh;ein counseil to do wickidnes [2282] and if &yogh;e wil wirke wickidnes and &yogh;oure wyf restreyne &thorn;ilke wicked purpos and ouercome &yogh;ou by resoun and by good counseil; [2283] Certes &yogh;oure wyf oweth ra&thorn;er be preised than y-blamed / [2284] &para; Thus schulde &yogh;e vnder|stonde &thorn;e philosopher &thorn;at sei&thorn; in wicked counseil wommen venquyschen her housbondes [2285] &para; And &thorn;er as &yogh;e blame alle wymmen and here resouns; I schal schewe by many resouns and ensamples &thorn;at many a womman hath ben ful good and &yogh;it been and here counseiles ful holsome and profitable [2286] &para; Eke some men han sayd &thorn;at &thorn;e counseilyng of wommen is ou&thorn;er to dere or to litel of pris [2287] But al be it so &thorn;at ful many a womman is badde and hir counseil vile and not wor&thorn;; &yogh;et han men founde many a ful good womman and ful discret and wys in counseilyng [2288] &para; lo Iacob by counseil of his moder Rebecca wan &thorn;e blessyng of his fader ysaak and &thorn;e lordschipe of alle his bre&thorn;eren [2289] &para; Iudith by hire goode counseil delyuered &thorn;e Citee of Bethulie in which sche dwellid out of &thorn;e hous of Olophernus &thorn;at had it byseged and wolde it al destroye [2290] &para; Abigayl deliuered Nabal hir housbond fro Dauid &thorn;e king &thorn;at wolde haue I-slayn him and appesed &thorn;e Ire of &thorn;e kyng by hir witte and by hir good counseil|ynge [2291] &para; Hester by good counseil enhaunsed gretly &thorn;e poeple of god In &thorn;e regne of assuerus &thorn;e kyng [2292] and &thorn;e same bounte in good counseilyng of many 
<PB REF="00000500.tif" N="488"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="211"> a good womman may men rede and telle [2293] And more ouer whan oure lord had creat adam oure forme fader; he sayde in &thorn;is wise [2294] &para; Hit is not goode to be a man aloone. make we to him an help semblable to him self [2295] &para; here may &yogh;e se &thorn;at if &thorn;at a womman were not <MILESTONE N="210b" UNIT="folio">good and hir counseil good and profytable; [2296] oure lord god of heuen wolde neither haue wrou&yogh;t hem ne called hem help of man but ra&thorn;er confusioun to man [2297] &para; And &thorn;er sayde oones a clerk in tuo versus &para; what is better than gold. Iasper. And what is better &thorn;an Iasper; wisedom. [2298] and what is better than wisedom; womman. and what is better than good womman; No &thorn;ing [2299] &para; And sire by many o&thorn;er resouns may &yogh;e se &thorn;at many wommen ben goode and . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in MS.</NOTE> profitable [2300] and &thorn;erfore if &yogh;e wil truste to my counseil; I schal restore &yogh;ou &yogh;oure dou&yogh;ter hool and sound [2301] &para; and eek I wil doon &yogh;ou so moche &thorn;at &yogh;e schul haue honour in &thorn;is cause</P>
<P>[2302] &para; whan Melibe had herd &thorn;ese wordes of his wif prudens; he seide &thorn;us. [2303] &para; I se wel &thorn;at &thorn;e word of Salomon is so&thorn; &para; he seith &thorn;at &thorn;e wordes &thorn;at ben spoken discretly by ordinaunce been hony combes. For &thorn;ay &yogh;euen swetnes to &thorn;e soule. and holmes to &thorn;e body [2304] &para; And wyf bycause of &thorn;y swete wordes and eek for I haue assayed and proued &thorn;i grete sapiens &amp; &thorn;i grete trou&thorn;e; I wil gouerne me by &thorn;y counseil in alle &thorn;inges</P>
<P>[2305] &para; Now sire quod dame prudens and syn &yogh;e vouchen sauf to be gouerned by my counseilyng; I wil enforme &yogh;ou how &yogh;e schul gouerne &yogh;oure self in chesyng of &yogh;oure counseil [2306] &para; &yogh;e schul first/ in alle &yogh;oure werkes mekely biseche to &thorn;e hihe god &thorn;at he wol be &yogh;our counseilour [2307] &amp; schape &yogh;ou to &thorn;at entent &thorn;at he &yogh;iue &yogh;ou counseil and confort as taughte Toby his sone [2308] &para; At alle tymes &thorn;ou schalt blesse 
<PB REF="00000501.tif" N="489"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="212"> god and pray him to dresse &thorn;y wayes. and loke &thorn;at alle &thorn;i counseiles be in him for euermore [2309] &para; Seint Iame eek saith &para; If eny of &yogh;ow haue neede of sapiens axe it of god. [2310] and aftirward &thorn;anne schul &yogh;e take counseil in &yogh;oure self. and examine wel &yogh;oure &thorn;ou&yogh;tes of suche &thorn;inges as &yogh;ou &thorn;inki&thorn; &thorn;at is best for &yogh;oure profyt [2311] and &thorn;anne schul &yogh;e dryue fro &yogh;oure hertes &thorn;o &thorn;at ben contrarie to good counseil. [2312] &thorn;at is to say . Ire . coueytise . and hastynes</P>
<P>[2313] &para; First he &thorn;at axe&thorn; counseil of himself . certes he moste be wi&thorn;oute Ire . for many cause [2314] &para; The first is &thorn;is &para; He &thorn;at ha&thorn; gret Ire and wra&thorn;&thorn;e in himself . he weneth alwey he may do &thorn;ing &thorn;at he may not doo [2315] &para; And secoundly he &thorn;at is Irous and wro&thorn; . he may not wel deme [2316] &para; and he &thorn;at may not wel deme; may nought wel counseile [2317] &para; The &thorn;ridde is &thorn;is . &thorn;at he &thorn;a is Irous and wroth as sai&thorn; Senec may not speke but blameful &thorn;inges [2318] and with his vicious wordes he stire&thorn; o&thorn;er folk to anger and to Ire [2319] &para; And eek sire &yogh;e moste dryue coueitise out of &yogh;oure herte / [2320] &para; For &thorn;apostil saith &thorn;at coueytise is roote of alle harmes. [2321] And trusteth wel &thorn;at a coueitous man ne can not deme ne &thorn;inke <MILESTONE N="211a" UNIT="folio">but oonly to fulfille &thorn;e ende of his coueitise [2322] &para; And certes &thorn;at may neuer ben accomplised &para; For euer &thorn;e more abundaunce &thorn;at he hath of riches . &thorn;e more he desireth [2323] And sire &yogh;e moste also dryue out of &yogh;our herte hastynes . [2324] For certes &yogh;e may nought deme for &thorn;e beste a sodein &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at falle&thorn; in &yogh;oure herte &para; But &yogh;e moste auyse &yogh;ou on it ful ofte [2325] &para; For as &yogh;e herde here biforn &thorn;e comune prouerbe is &thorn;is; &thorn;at he &thorn;at soone demeth soone repentith;</P>
<P>[2326] &para; Sire &yogh;e ben not alway in lik disposicioun [2327] For certis som &thorn;ing &thorn;at som tyme seme&thorn; to &yogh;ow &thorn;at it is good for to doo; ano&thorn;er tyme it seme&thorn; to &yogh;ou &thorn;e contrarie
<PB REF="00000502.tif" N="490"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="213"></P>
<P>[2328] whan &yogh;e han taken counseil in &yogh;oure seluen . and han demed by good deliberacioun such &thorn;ing as &yogh;ow seme&thorn; best [2329] &para; &thorn;anne rede I &yogh;ou &thorn;at &yogh;e kepe it secre . [2330] Bywreye nought &yogh;oure counseil to no persone but it so be &thorn;at &yogh;e wene sicurly that &thorn;urgh &yogh;oure bywreyinge &yogh;oure condicioun schal be to &yogh;ow &thorn;e more profytable [2331] &para; For Ihc Syrac sai&thorn; &para; Nei&thorn;er to &thorn;i foo ne to &thorn;i freend discouere not &thorn;y secre ne &thorn;y foly [2332] &para; For &thorn;ey wil &yogh;iue &yogh;ou audience and lokyng and supportacioun in &thorn;i presence and scorn in thin absence [2333] &para; ano&thorn;er clerk sai&thorn; &thorn;at skarsly schalt &thorn;ou fynde eny persone &thorn;at may kepe counseil secreely [2334] &para; The book saith &para; whil &thorn;ou kepist &thorn;i counsail in &thorn;in herte &thorn;ou kepest it in &thorn;i prisoun [2335] &para; and whan &thorn;ou bywreyest &thorn;i counseil to any wight; he holde&thorn; &thorn;e in his snare [2336] &para; And &thorn;erfore &yogh;ow is better hyde &yogh;oure counseil in &yogh;oure herte &thorn;an prayen him to whom &yogh;e haue bywryed &yogh;oure counseil &thorn;at he wol kepe it clos and stille [2337] &para; For Seneca seith &para; If so be &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne maist not &thorn;in owne counsel hyde; how darst &thorn;ou preven any o&thorn;er wight &thorn;i counseil secreely to kepe; [2338] &para; But na&thorn;eles if &thorn;ou wene securly &thorn;at &thorn;y bywreying of &thorn;y counsel to a persone wol make &thorn;y condicioun stonde in &thorn;e better plite; &thorn;anne schalt &thorn;ou telle him &thorn;y counsel in &thorn;is wise [2339] &para; First &thorn;ou shalt make no semblaunt wher &thorn;e were leuer werre or pees . or &thorn;is or &thorn;at . ne schewe him not &thorn;i wille and &thorn;in entent . [2340] For truste wel &thorn;at comunly &thorn;ese counseilours ben flaterers [2341] and namely &thorn;e counselours of grete lordes [2342] &para; For &thorn;ay enforcen hem alway ra&thorn;er to speke plesaunt wordes enclynyng to &thorn;e lordes lust &thorn;an wordes &thorn;at been trewe and profitable [2343] &para; And &thorn;erfore men say &thorn;at &thorn;e riche man ha&thorn; selden good coun|seil. but if he haue it of him self [2344] &para; And after &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt consider &thorn;y frendes and &thorn;ine enemyes . [2345] And as touching &thorn;y frendes; &thorn;ou schalt con|sidere 
<PB REF="00000503.tif" N="491"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="214"> which of hem be&thorn; most faithful and most wise and eldest and most approuyd in counsaylinge [2346] &para; And of hem schalt &thorn;ou axe &thorn;y counsail as &thorn;e caas <MILESTONE N="211b" UNIT="folio">requireth</P>
<P>[2347] &para; I say &thorn;at first &yogh;e schul clepe to &yogh;our coun|seil &yogh;oure frendes that ben trewe [2348] &para; For Salomon sai&thorn; For right as &thorn;e hert of a man delitith in sauour &thorn;at is soote; Right so . &thorn;e counseil of trewe frendes &yogh;eue&thorn; swetnes to &thorn;e soule [2349] &para; he saith also ther may no &thorn;ing be likened to &thorn;e trewe freend [2350] &para; For certes gold ne siluer be&thorn; nought so moche wor&thorn; as &thorn;e goode wil of a trewe freend . [2351] &para; And eek he sayde &thorn;at a trewe frend is a strong defens who &thorn;at it fynde&thorn; certes he fynde&thorn; a gret tresour [2352] &para; &thorn;anne schul &yogh;e eek considere if &thorn;at &yogh;oure trewe frendes ben discrete and wyse For &thorn;e book saith . axe &thorn;i counseil alwey of hem &thorn;at ben wyse . [2353] and by &thorn;is same resoun shul &yogh;e clepe to &yogh;oure counseil of &yogh;oure frendes &thorn;at ben of age suche as haue I-seye sightes and ben expert in many &thorn;inges and ben approuyd in counseylinges [2354] &para; For &thorn;e book saith &thorn;at in olde men is &thorn;e sapience and in longe tyme &thorn;e prudence [2355] &para; And tullius sai&thorn; &thorn;at grete &thorn;inges ben not ay accompliced by streng&thorn;e ne by delyuernes of body; but by good counseil by auctorite of persones and by science . the whiche &thorn;re &thorn;inges ne been not feble by age; but certis &thorn;ay enforsen and en|cresen day by day [2356] and thanne schul &yogh;e kepe &thorn;is for a general reule &para; First schul &yogh;e clepe to &yogh;oure counseil a fewe of &yogh;oure frendes &thorn;at ben especial [2357] For Salomon sai&thorn; &para; Many frendes haue &thorn;ou but among a &thorn;ousand chese &thorn;e oon to be &thorn;y counseil|our . [2358] For al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;ou first ne telle &thorn;y counseil but to a fewe; &thorn;ou mayst afterward telle it to mo folk if it be neede [2359] But loke alwey &thorn;at &thorn;y counseilours haue &thorn;ilke &thorn;re condiciouns &thorn;at I haue sayd 
<PB REF="00000504.tif" N="492"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="215"> bifore &thorn;at is to say &thorn;at &thorn;ay ben trewe and olde and of wys experiens [2360] &para; And werke nou&yogh;t alwey in euery neede by oon counseilour alloone &para; For som tyme byhoue&thorn; it be counseiled by many [2361] &para; For Salomon saith &para; Saluacioun of &thorn;inges is wher as &thorn;ere be&thorn; many counseilours.</P>
<P>[2362] Now si&thorn; &thorn;at I haue told &yogh;ow of which folk &yogh;e schul be counseled &para; Now wil I telle &yogh;ow which counseil &yogh;e ought eschiewe. [2363] First &yogh;e schal espie &thorn;e counseil of fooles &para; For Salomon sei&thorn; take no coun|seil of a fool For he ne can not counseile but after his oughne lust and his affeccioun [2364] &para; The book sei&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e proprete of a fool is &thorn;is he trowe&thorn; lightly harm of euery wight &amp; lightly trowe&thorn; alle bounte in himself [2365] &para; Thow schalt eschiewe eek &thorn;e counseil of alle flaterers suche as enforcen hem ra&thorn;ere to prayse &yogh;oure persone by flaterie &thorn;an for to telle &yogh;ow &thorn;e so&thorn;|fastnesse of &thorn;inges</P>
<P>[2366] &para; wherfore Tullius saith Amonges alle pestilences &thorn;at <MILESTONE N="212a" UNIT="folio">ben in frendschipe &thorn;at is &thorn;e grettest flaterie. &para; And &thorn;erfore is it more neede &thorn;at &thorn;ou eschiewe and drede flaterers more &thorn;an eny o&thorn;er peple [2367] &para; The book sai&thorn;. &THORN;ou schalt ra&thorn;er drede and flee fro &thorn;e swete wordes of flaterers. &thorn;en fro &thorn;e egre wordes of &thorn;y frend &thorn;at sai&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;i so&thorn;es [2368] &para; Salamon sai&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e wordes of a flaterer is a snare to cacche in Innocent&yogh; [2369] &para; He sai&thorn; also. he &thorn;at speke&thorn; to his frend wordes of swetnesse and of plesaunce sette&thorn; a nette byfore his feet to cacchen him [2370] and &thorn;erfore sai&thorn; Tullius &para; Encline not &thorn;in eeres to flaterers ne tak no confort of &thorn;e wordes of flaterers [2371] &para; And Catoun sai&thorn; Auyse the wel and eschiewe wordes of swetnes and of plesaunce [2372] and eek &thorn;ou schalt eschiewe &thorn;e counselyng of &thorn;in olde enemyes &thorn;at ben recounsiled. [2373] &THORN;e book sai&thorn;. that wight retorneth soone in to &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000505.tif" N="493"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="216"> grace of his olde enemyes [2374] &para; And ysope saith. Ne truste not to hem wi&thorn; which &thorn;ou hast had som tyme werre or enmyte. ne telle not hem &thorn;y counseil [2375] And Seneca telle&thorn; &thorn;e cause why it may not be saith he &thorn;at wher as a greet fuyr ha&thorn; longe tyme endured; &thorn;at &thorn;ere ne leue&thorn; som vapour of hete [2376] &para; And &thorn;erfore saith Salomon &para; In &thorn;in olde enemy truste &thorn;ou neuere [2377] &para; For sicurly &thorn;ough &thorn;in enemy be reconsiled and make &thorn;e cheer of humilite and lowte&thorn; to &thorn;e his heed; ne trist him neuer [2378] For certes he maki&thorn; &thorn;ilke feyned humilite more for his profyt &thorn;an for eny loue of &thorn;i persone by cause he dem|yth to haue victorie ouer &thorn;i persone &para; By such feyned countynaunce the whiche victorie he might nou&yogh;t haue by stryf and werre [2379] &para; And Petir Alfons sai&thorn; &para; Make no felaschipe with &thorn;ine olde enemyes. for if &thorn;ou do hem bounte; &thorn;ey wil peruerten it in to wikkednes [2380] &amp; eek &thorn;ou most eschiewe &thorn;e counseilynge of hem &thorn;at ben &thorn;y seruaunt&yogh; and beren &thorn;e gret reuerence. For par auenture &thorn;ai say it more for drede &thorn;an for loue [2381] And &thorn;erfore saith a philosophre in &thorn;is wise &para; Ther is no wight parfytly trewe to him &thorn;at he to sore dredeth [2382] &para; And Tullius saith &para; &thorn;er is no wight so gret of eny emperour &thorn;at onge may endure but if he haue more loue of &thorn;e peple than drede [2383] &para; Thow also eschiewe &thorn;e counseil of folk &thorn;at ben dronkelewe For &thorn;ay ne can no counsel hyde [2384] &para; For Salomon saith &para; Ther regne&thorn; no priuete &thorn;er as is dronkenesse [2385] &para; &yogh;e schul also haue in suspect &thorn;e counseil of such folk as counseile&thorn; &yogh;ou oon &thorn;ing priuely and counseile &yogh;ow &thorn;e contrarie openly [2386] &para; For Cassiodorie saith it is a maner sleighte to hindre whan he schewi&thorn; to doon oon &thorn;ing openly and werkith priuely &thorn;e contrarie. [2387] &para; &thorn;ou schalt also <MILESTONE N="212b" UNIT="folio">eschiewe &thorn;e counseil of wikked folkes &para; For &thorn;e book saith. &para; The counselyng of wikked folk is alway ful 
<PB REF="00000506.tif" N="494"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="217"> of fraude [2388] &para; and Dauid saith &para; Blisful is &thorn;at man &thorn;at ha&thorn; not folwed &thorn;e counseilyng of wikked men or schrewes [2389] &para; Thow schalt also eschiewe &thorn;e counseilynge of &yogh;onge folkes for here counseil is nought/ rype</P>
<P>[2390] &para; Now sire syn I haue schewed &yogh;ou of what folk &yogh;e schul take &yogh;oure counsail and of whiche folk &yogh;e schullen folwe &thorn;e counseil [2391] &para; Now schal I teche &yogh;ow how &yogh;e schul examyne &yogh;oure counseil after &thorn;e doctrine of tullius [2392] &para; In the examynyng of &yogh;oure counseiloures; &yogh;e schul considre many &thorn;inges [2393] &para; Al-thir first &yogh;e schul considre &thorn;at in &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing that &thorn;ou proposist and vp what &thorn;ing &thorn;ou wilt haue counseil that verray trouthe be sayd and considerid. &thorn;is is to sayn. telle trewely &thorn;y tale [2394] &para; For he &thorn;at saith fals may not wel be counseled in &thorn;at cas of which he lyeth [2395] &para; And after &thorn;is &thorn;ou schalt considere the &thorn;inges &thorn;at accorden to &thorn;at purpos. for to do by &thorn;y counseil if resoun accorde &thorn;er to [2396] &para; and eek if &thorn;y might may accorde &thorn;er to. and if &thorn;e more part and &thorn;e better part of &thorn;y counseilours accorde &thorn;er-to or noon [2397] &para; Thanne schalt &thorn;ou considere what &thorn;ing schal folwe of &thorn;at counsailynge. as hate. pees. werre. grace. profyt/. or damage and many o&thorn;er &thorn;inges [2398] &para; And in alle &thorn;ese &thorn;inges &thorn;ou schalt chese &thorn;e beste and weyue alle o&thorn;er &thorn;inges [2399] &THORN;anne schalt &thorn;ou considre of what roote engendred is &thorn;y matier of &thorn;y counseil and what fruyt may conserue and engendre / [2400] &para; Thow schalt also consider alle &thorn;ese causes from whens &thorn;ai ben spronge. / [2401] And whan &yogh;e haue examined &yogh;oure counseil as I haue said and which party is &thorn;e better and more profitable and han approued by many wise folkes and olde; [2402] Than schalt thow considre if &thorn;ou maist performe it and make of it a good ende [2403] &para; For resoun wol nought &thorn;at any man schuld bygynne a thing; but if he mighte parforme it and make &thorn;er-of a good ende. [2404] ne no wight 
<PB REF="00000507.tif" N="495"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="218"> schulde take vpon him so heuy a charge &thorn;at he mighte not bere it [2405] &para; For &thorn;e prouerbe sei&thorn; &para; He &thorn;at moche embrasith destroye&thorn; litel [2406] &para; And Catoun sei&thorn; Assay to do such &thorn;ing as &thorn;ou hast power to doon. lest &thorn;at &thorn;y charge oppresse &thorn;e so sore. &thorn;at &thorn;e bihoue to wayue &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast bygonne [2407] &para; And if so be &thorn;at &thorn;ou be in doubte<MILESTONE N="213a" UNIT="folio"> wher &thorn;ou maist parforme a &thorn;ing or noon chese rather to suffre &thorn;an bygynne [2408] &para; And petre alfons saith If &thorn;ou hast might to doon a &thorn;ing of which &thorn;ou most repente it is better nay &thorn;an &yogh;ee / [2409] &thorn;is is to sayn &thorn;at &thorn;e is better holde &thorn;y tongue stille &thorn;an to speke [2410] &para; Than may &yogh;e vnderstonde by strenger resouns. &thorn;at if &thorn;ou hast power to parforme a werk of which &thorn;ou schalt repente; &thorn;anne is it better &thorn;at &thorn;ou suffre &thorn;an bigynne. [2411] wel seyn &thorn;ay &thorn;at defenden euery wight to assaie &thorn;ing of which he is in doute whe&thorn;ir he may parforme it or noon [2412] &para; And after whan &yogh;e han examyned &yogh;oure counseil as I haue sayd biforn and knowen wel &yogh;e may par|forme &yogh;oure emprise; conferme it &thorn;anne sadly til it be at an ende</P>
<P>[2413] &para; Now is it tyme and resoun &thorn;at I schewe &yogh;ow whanne and wherfore &thorn;at &yogh;e may chaunge &yogh;oure coun|seil wi&thorn;outen reproef / [2414] &para; Sothly a man may chaunge his purpos and his counseil if &thorn;e cause cesse&thorn; or whan a newe cause bytyde&thorn; [2415] &para; For &thorn;e lawe seith &para; vpon &thorn;inges &thorn;at newely bityde&thorn; bihoue&thorn; newe counseil. [2416] and Seneca seith &para; If &thorn;y counseil be comen to &thorn;e eeres of &thorn;in enemy; chaunge &thorn;y counsail [2417] &para; Thow maist/ also chaunge &thorn;y counseil if so be &thorn;at &thorn;ou fynde &thorn;at by errour or by o&thorn;er processe harm or damage may bytyde [2418] &para; Also &thorn;ou chaunge &thorn;y counseil if &thorn;ay be dishonest or elles comuneth of dishoneste. [2419] For &thorn;e lawes sayn &para; That alle &thorn;e hestes &thorn;at ben dishoneste ben of no valieu 
<PB REF="00000508.tif" N="496"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="219"> [2420] and eek if it so be &thorn;at it be impossible. or may not goodly be parformed or kept</P>
<P>[2421] and take &thorn;is for a general reule &para; That euery counseil &thorn;at is affermed or streng&thorn;ed so strongly &thorn;at it may not be chaunged for no condicioun &thorn;at may bitide &para; I say &thorn;at &thorn;ilke counseil is wikked</P>
<P>[2422] &para; &thorn;is melibeus whan he had herd &thorn;e doctrine of his wyf dame prudens answerde in &thorn;is wise [2423] &para; Dame quod he &yogh;it as in to &thorn;is tyme &yogh;e han wel and couenably taught me as in general how I schal gouerne me in chesynge and in wi&thorn;holdynge of my counseiloures [2424] &para; But now wold I fayn &yogh;e wolde condescende as in especial [2425] &amp; telle&thorn; me what seme&thorn; or how like&thorn; &yogh;ow by oure counseiloures &thorn;at we han chosen in oure present neede</P>
<P>[2426] &para; My lord quod sche I byseke &yogh;ow in al hum|blesce &thorn;at &yogh;e wil not wilfully repplye a&yogh;einst my resouns ne distempre &yogh;oure herte &thorn;ough I say or speke &thorn;ing &thorn;at &yogh;ow displesith [2427] &para; For god woot &thorn;at as in myn entent I speke it for &yogh;oure beste. for &yogh;oure honour. and for &yogh;our <MILESTONE N="213b" UNIT="folio">profyt eek [2428] &para; And so&thorn;ly I hope &thorn;at &yogh;our be|nignite wol take it in to pacience [2429] &para; For truste&thorn; me wel quod sche &thorn;at &yogh;oure counseil as in &thorn;is caas ne schulde not as for to speke propurly be called a counseilyng; but / a mocioun or a moeuynge of foly [2430] in which counseil &yogh;e han erred in many a sondry wise</P>
<P>[2431] &para; First and forward &yogh;e han erred in &thorn;e gader|yng of &yogh;oure counseilours [2432] For &yogh;e schulde first han cleped a fewe folkes . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> if it hadde be neede [2433] &para; But certes &yogh;e han sodeinly cleped to &yogh;our coun|seil a gret multitude of poeple ful cha[r]geous and ful anoyous for to hiere [2434] &para; Also &yogh;e han erred for &thorn;er as &yogh;e schulde oonly haue clepid to &yogh;oure counseil &yogh;oure trewe frendes olde and wise; [2435] &yogh;e haue I-cleped straunge folk &yogh;onge folk. false flatereres and enemyes 
<PB REF="00000509.tif" N="497"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="220"> reconsiled and folk &thorn;at doon &yogh;ow reuerence wi&thorn;oute loue [2436] &para; Eke also &yogh;e han erred; For &yogh;e han brou&yogh;t with &yogh;ow to &yogh;oure counseil. Ire. Coueitise and Hastynes. [2437] &thorn;e whiche &thorn;re &thorn;inges ben contra|rious to euery counsail honest and profitable [2438] &para; The whiche &thorn;re &thorn;inges &yogh;e haue nought annentissched or destroyed ney&thorn;er in &yogh;oure self ne in &yogh;oure counseiloures as &yogh;e oughte [2439] &para; Also &yogh;e haue erred. For &yogh;e haue schewed to &yogh;oure counseilours &yogh;oure talent and &yogh;oure affeccioun to make werre and for to doon vengeaunce anoon [2440] &para; &thorn;ay han espyed by &yogh;oure wordes to what &thorn;inge &yogh;e ben enclined [2441] and &thorn;erfore haue &thorn;ay counseiled &yogh;ow rather to &yogh;oure talent &thorn;an to &yogh;oure profyt [2442] &para; &YOGH;e haue erred also; For it seme&thorn; &thorn;at &yogh;ow suffice&thorn; to haue been coun|seiled by &thorn;ese counseilours only and wi&thorn; litel auys [2443] wher-as in so gret and so heigh a neede it hadde be necessarious mo counseilours and more deliberacioun to parforme &yogh;oure emprise [2444] &yogh;e have erred also &para; For . . . . .[2445] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> &yogh;e haue maked no diuisioun bytwixe &yogh;oure counsailours &thorn;is is to seyn bitwix &yogh;oure frendes and &yogh;oure feyned counseilours. [2446] ne &yogh;e ne haue nought I-knowe &thorn;e wille of &yogh;oure frendes olde and wise. [2447] But &yogh;e haue cast alle here wordes in an hochepoche / and enclyned &yogh;oure herte to &thorn;e more part and to &thorn;e gretter nombre and &thorn;ere be &yogh;e condescendid [2448] &para; And syn &yogh;e wot wel men schal alway fynde a gretter nombre of fooles &thorn;an of wyse men; [2449] and &thorn;erfore &thorn;e counsailes &thorn;at ben at congregaciouns and mul|titudes of folk. &thorn;er as men taken more reward to &thorn;e <MILESTONE N="214a" UNIT="folio">nombre &thorn;an to &thorn;e sapience of persones. [2450] &yogh;e se wel &thorn;at in suche counseilynges fooles haue maystrie [2451] &para; Melibeus answerde agayn and sayde &para; I graunte wel &thorn;at I haue erred; [2452] But &thorn;ere as &thorn;ou hast told me toforn &thorn;at he is nought to blame &thorn;at chaunge&thorn; his coun|seilours 
<PB REF="00000510.tif" N="498"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="221"> in certeyn caas and for certeyn iuste causes [2453] &para; I am al redy to chaunge my counseilours right as &thorn;ou wilt deuyse [2454] &para; The prouerbe saith &thorn;at for to do synne is mannysch. But/ certes for to perseuere longe in synne is werk of &thorn;e deuyl</P>
<P>[2455] &para; To &thorn;is sentence anoon answerde dame pru|dens and saide [2456] &para; Examineth quod sche &yogh;oure coun|sail and let vs se which of hem ha&thorn; spoke most resonably and taught &yogh;ou best counsail [2457] And for as moche as &thorn;e examinacioun is necessarie; let vs byginne at &thorn;e Surgiens and at &thorn;e phisiciens &thorn;at first speken in &thorn;is matiere [2458] &para; I say &yogh;ou &thorn;at &thorn;e surgiens and &thorn;e physiciens han sayd &yogh;ow in &yogh;oure counseil discretly as hem ought [2459] and in here speche sayden ful wisely &thorn;at to &thorn;e office of hem appendith to doon to euery wight honour and profyt. and no wi&yogh;t to annoye [2460] and after here craft to do gret diligence vn to &thorn;e cure of hem which &thorn;at &thorn;ay haue in here gouern|aunce [2461] And sire right as &thorn;ay answerde wisely and discretly; [2462] Right so rede I &thorn;at &thorn;ay be heihly and soueraignly guerdoned for here noble speche / [2463] and eek for &thorn;ey schullen do &thorn;e more ententyf besynes in &thorn;e curyng of &yogh;oure dou&yogh;ter dere [2464] &para; For al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;ai be &yogh;oure frendes; &thorn;erfore schul &yogh;e nought suffre &thorn;at &thorn;ay schul serue &yogh;ow for nou&yogh;t / [2465] But &yogh;e oughte &thorn;e ra&thorn;ere to guerdoune hem and schewe hem &yogh;oure largesse [2466] &para; &amp; as touchynge &thorn;e proposiciouns whiche &thorn;e phisiciens han schewed &yogh;ou in &thorn;is caas &thorn;is is to sayn [2467] &thorn;at in maladyes oon contrarie is warisshed by ano&thorn;er contrarie. [2468] I wolde fayn knowe &thorn;ilke text and how &thorn;ay vnderstonde it and what is &yogh;oure entente [2469] &para; Certes quod Melibeus vnderstonden it is in &thorn;is wise [2470] &thorn;at right as &thorn;ay han do me a contrarie; right so schold I do hem ano&thorn;er [2471] &para; For right as &thorn;ai han venged hem on me and doon me wrong; Right so schal I venge me vp on hem 
<PB REF="00000511.tif" N="499"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="222"> and doon hem wrong [2472] and &thorn;anne haue I cured oon contrarie by ano&thorn;er</P>
<P>[2473] &para; lo lo quod Dame prudence how lightly is euery man enclyned to his oughne plesaunce and to his oughne desir [2474] &para; Certes quod sche &thorn;e wordes of &thorn;e phisiciens<MILESTONE N="214b" UNIT="folio"> ne schulde nou&yogh;t haue ben vnderstonde sone in &thorn;at wise [2475] &para; For certes wikkednesse is no contrarie to wickednesse. ne vengauns to vengeaunce. ne wrong to wrong; but &thorn;ai ben semblable [2476] And &thorn;er|fore on vengeaunce is nou&yogh;t warisshed by ano&thorn;er venge|aunce. ne oon wrong by ano&thorn;er wrong. [2477] but euerych of hem encreseth and engreggith o&thorn;er [2478] &para; But certes &thorn;e wordes of &thorn;e phisiciens schul ben vnderstonde in &thorn;is wise. [2479] For good and wikked|nesse ben tuo contraries. and pees and werre. venge|aunce &amp; sufferaunce. Discord and accord and many o&thorn;er &thorn;inges [2480] &para; but certes wikkednes schal be warrisshed by goodnesse. Discord by accord. werre by pees and so forth of o&thorn;er &thorn;inges [2481] &para; And her-to accordith seint paul &thorn;e apostil in many places [2482] &para; He saith . ne &yogh;eldith nou&yogh;t harm for harm. ne wikked speche for wikked speche [2483] &para; But do wel to him &thorn;at do&thorn; &thorn;e harm and blesse him that do&thorn; &thorn;e harm [2484] and in many o&thorn;er places he amonesteth pees and accord [2485] &para; But now wil I speke to &yogh;ow of &thorn;e coun|seil which was &yogh;iue to &yogh;ow by &thorn;e men of lawe &amp; &thorn;e wise folkes [2486] &thorn;at sayde alle by oon accord as &yogh;e haue herd byfore [2487] That ouer alle &thorn;inges &yogh;e schal do &yogh;oure diligence to kepe &yogh;oure persone and to warmstore &yogh;oure hous. [2488] and seyden also &thorn;at in &thorn;is &yogh;ow aughte for to wirche ful auysily and with gret deliberacioun. [2489] &para; And sire as to &thorn;e firste poynt &thorn;at touched to &thorn;e kepinge of &yogh;oure persone; [2490] &yogh;e schul vnderstonde. &thorn;at he &thorn;at ha&thorn; werre; schal euermore deuoutly and mekely prayen biforn alle &thorn;inges [2491] &thorn;at Ih&umacr; crist wil of his mercy 
<PB REF="00000512.tif" N="500"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="223"> haue him in his proteccioun and ben his souerayn helpyng at his neede / [2492] &para; For certes in &thorn;is world &thorn;er nys no wight &thorn;at may be counseiled or kept sufficaun[t]ly wi&thorn;|oute &thorn;e kepinge of oure lord ih&umacr; crist [2493] &para; To &thorn;is sentence accorde&thorn; &thorn;e prophete Dauid &thorn;at seith [2494] &para; If god ne kepe not &thorn;e citee. in ydel wakith he &thorn;at kepith hit [2495] &para; Now sire &thorn;anne schul &yogh;e committe &thorn;e keping of &yogh;oure persone to &yogh;oure trewe frendes &thorn;at ben approued and y-knowe [2496] and of hem schul &yogh;e axen help &yogh;oure persone to kepe &para; For Catoun saith &para; If &thorn;ou haue neede of help; axe it of &thorn;y freendes. [2497] For &thorn;er is noon so good a phisicien at neede; as is a trewe frend. [2498] &para; And after &thorn;is; &thorn;an schal &yogh;e kepe &yogh;ou fro alle straunge folkes and fro lyeres and haue alway in suspect/ here compaignye [2499] &para; For Pieres alfons saith &para; Ne take no compaignie by the<MILESTONE N="215a" UNIT="folio">way of a straunge man. but/ so be &thorn;at &thorn;ou knowe him of a lenger tyme [2500] And if so be he falle in to &thorn;y compaignye par auenture wi&thorn;outen &thorn;in assent; [2501] enquere &thorn;anne as subtilly as &thorn;ou maist of his conuersacioun and of his lyf bifore and feyne &thorn;y way and say &thorn;at &thorn;ou wilt go &thorn;ider as &thorn;ou wolt nought goon [2502] &para; And if he bere a spere &para; hold &thorn;e on the right syde &para; And if he bere a swerd; holde &thorn;e on &thorn;e lyft syde. [2503] and so after &thorn;is. &thorn;anne schul &yogh;e kepe &yogh;ou wisely from al such peple as I haue sayd bifore / and hem and here counseil eschiewe [2504] &para; And after &thorn;is. &thorn;anne schul &yogh;e kepe &yogh;ow in such manere [2505] &thorn;at for eny presumpcioun of &yogh;oure streng&thorn;e &thorn;at &yogh;e despise not &thorn;e might of &yogh;oure aduersarie so lite &thorn;at &yogh;e lete &thorn;e kepinge of &yogh;oure persone for &yogh;oure presumpcioun. [2506] For eny wis man drede&thorn; his enemy [2507] &para; And Salomon saith &para; weleful is he &thorn;at of alle ha&thorn; drede. [2508] For certes he &thorn;at &thorn;urgh hardynes of his herte and &thorn;urgh &thorn;e hardinesse of himself. ha&thorn; to gret presumpcioun; him schal euyl bitide [2509] &para; &thorn;anne 
<PB REF="00000513.tif" N="501"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="224"> schal &yogh;e euermore counterwayte enbusshement&yogh; and alle espiaille [2510] &para; For Senec saith &thorn;at &thorn;e wise man &thorn;at dredi&thorn; harmes / eschiewith harmes. [2511] ne he ne falli&thorn; in to noone perils &thorn;at perils eschiewe&thorn; [2512] &para; And al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;e seme &thorn;at &thorn;ou art in sikur place; &yogh;it schaltow alway do &thorn;y diligence in kepyng of &thorn;y persone [2513] &para; This is to say &para; Be not necgligent to kepe &thorn;y persone nought oonly for &thorn;y gretteste enemyes; but fro &thorn;y lest enemyes [2514] &para; Senec saith &para; A man &thorn;at is wel auysed; he dredi&thorn; his lest enemy [2515] &para; Ovide sei&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e litel wesil wol sle &thorn;e grete bole and &thorn;e wilde hert. [2516] &para; And &thorn;e book sai&thorn;. a litel &thorn;orn wol prikke a &thorn;ing ful sore. &para; And an hound wol holde &thorn;e wilde boore [2517] &para; But na&thorn;eles I say not &thorn;at &yogh;e schul be so moche a coward &thorn;at &yogh;e doute where is no neede or drede [2518] &para; &thorn;e book sai&thorn; &thorn;at som folk haue gret lust to disceyue &para; but &yogh;it &thorn;ay dreden hem to be de|ceyued [2519] &para; &YOGH;et schal &yogh;e drede to ben empoisoned &para; And kepe &thorn;e fro &thorn;e companye of scorners [2520] For &thorn;e book saith with scorners make no compaignye but flee hem and here wordes as venym</P>
<P>[2521] &para; Now as to &thorn;e secounde poynt where as &yogh;oure wise counseilours warnede &yogh;ow to warmstore &yogh;oure hous with gret diligence; [2522] I wolde fayn wite <MILESTONE N="215b" UNIT="folio">how &thorn;at &yogh;e vnderstoode &thorn;ilke wordes what is &yogh;oure sentence</P>
<P>[2523] &para; Melibeus answerde and saide &para; Certes I vnder|stonde it in &thorn;is wise &thorn;at I schal warmstore myn hous with toures suche as han castiles and o&thorn;er maner edifices and armure and artilries [2524] by suche &thorn;inges I may my persone &amp; myn hous so kepen and edifien and defenden &thorn;at myn enemyes schul be in drede myn hous to approche</P>
<P>[2525] &para; To &thorn;is sentence answerde dame prudence &para; warmstorynge quod sche of heihe toures and grete edifices . . . . .[2526] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> wi&thorn; grete 
<PB REF="00000514.tif" N="502"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="225"> costages and gret trauaile and whan &thorn;at &thorn;ay ben accomplised &yogh;it be&thorn; &thorn;ay nou&yogh;t worth a straw but if &thorn;ey be defended by trewe frendes &thorn;at be&thorn; olde and wise [2527] &para; And vnderstonde&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e grettest strength or garnisoun that &thorn;e riche man may haue as wel to kepe his persone as his goodes is [2528] &thorn;at he be biloued wi&thorn; his subgites and wi&thorn; his neighebours [2529] &para; For &thorn;us saith tullius &para; That &thorn;er is a maner garnisoun &thorn;at no man may venquisshe ne discomfite and &thorn;at is [2530] a lord to be biloued with his cite&yogh;eins and of his peple</P>
<P>[2531] &para; Now &thorn;anne as to &yogh;oure &thorn;ridde poynt where as &yogh;oure olde and wyse counseillours sayde. &yogh;e oughte nought sodeinly ne hastily procede in &thorn;is neede. [2532] but &thorn;at &yogh;e oughte purueyen &yogh;ow and apparaile &yogh;ow in &thorn;is caas wi&thorn; greet diligence and gret deliberacioun; [2533] trewely I trowe &thorn;at &thorn;ay sayden so&thorn; and right wisely [2534] &para; For Tullius saith &para; In euery nede er &thorn;ou bigynne it/ apparaile &thorn;e wi&thorn; gret diligence [2535] &para; Thanne say I &thorn;at in vengeance takinge in werre in bataile and in warmstoringe of &thorn;in hous [2536] er &thorn;ou bygynne I rede &thorn;at &thorn;ou apparaille &thorn;e &thorn;erto and do it with gret deliberacioun. [2537] For tullius saith &para; That long apparaylyng byfore &thorn;e bataille; make&thorn; schort victorie [2538] &para; And Cassidorus sai&thorn; &para; The garnisoun is strenger whan it is long tyme auysed</P>
<P>[2539] &para; But now let vs speke of &thorn;e counseil &thorn;at was accorded by &yogh;oure neighebours suche as doon &yogh;ou reuerence wi&thorn;oute loue. [2540] &para; &YOGH;oure olde enemyes recoun|siled [2541] &thorn;at counseile &yogh;ow cer|teyn &thorn;inges pryuely and openly counseile &yogh;ow &thorn;e contrarie [2542] &para; &THORN;e &yogh;onge also &thorn;at counsaile &yogh;ow to make werre and venge &yogh;ow anoon [2543] &para; And certes sire as I haue sayd byforn &yogh;e haue gretly erred to haue cle<MILESTONE N="216a" UNIT="folio"> ped such maner folk to &yogh;oure counseil [2544] whiche be now repreued by &thorn;e resouns byfore sayd [2545] &para; But na&thorn;eles let vs now descende to 
<PB REF="00000515.tif" N="503"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="226"> &thorn;e purpose special &para; &YOGH;e schul first procede after &thorn;e doctrine of Tullius [2546] &para; Certes &thorn;e trou&thorn;e of &thorn;is or &thorn;is counseil nede&thorn; nought diligently enquere [2547] For it is wel wist whiche it ben &thorn;at doon to &yogh;ow &thorn;is trespas and vilonye [2548] &amp; how many trespasoures and in what maner &thorn;ay han to &yogh;ow doon al &thorn;is wrong and al &thorn;is vilonye [2549] &para; And after &thorn;at schul &yogh;e examyne &thorn;e secounde condicioun which Tullius addi&thorn; &thorn;er to in &thorn;is matier [2550] &para; Tullius put a &thorn;ing which &thorn;at he clepeth couetynge. &thorn;is is to sayn [2551] who ben &thorn;ay and whiche ben &thorn;ay and how many &thorn;at consentid to &thorn;is matiere and to &thorn;y counsail in &thorn;y wilfulnesse to do hasty vengeaunces [2552] &amp; let vs considere also who ben &thorn;o and how many ben &thorn;o . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> &thorn;at ben counseilours to &yogh;oure aduersaries. [2553] and certes as to &thorn;e first poynt it is wel knowen whiche folk ben &thorn;ay &thorn;at consentid to &yogh;oure first/ wilful|nes. [2554] For trewly alle &thorn;o &thorn;at counsailled &yogh;ow to make sodeyn werre be&thorn; nou&yogh;t &yogh;oure frendes [2555] &para; let vs considre whiche ben &thorn;o &thorn;at &yogh;e holde so gretly &yogh;oure frendes as to &yogh;oure persone [2556] &para; For al be it so &thorn;at &yogh;e be mighty and riche; certes &yogh;e been alloone. [2557] for certes &yogh;e haue no childe but a dou&yogh;ter. [2558] ne &yogh;e haue no bre&thorn;eren ne cosins germayns ne noon o&thorn;er neigh kynrede / [2559] wherfore &thorn;at &yogh;oure enemyes for drede schulden stynte for to plede wi&thorn; &yogh;ou and stryue &yogh;oure persone [2560] &para; &YOGH;e knowe also &thorn;at &yogh;oure richesses mooten in diuers parties be departed. [2561] and whan euery wight ha&thorn; his part; &thorn;ay wol take but litel reward to venge &thorn;y deth [2562] &para; But &thorn;yne enemyes ben &thorn;re and haue many children bre&thorn;eren. cosynes and o&thorn;ere neigh kynrede. [2563] and &thorn;ough it so were &yogh;e hadde slayn of hem tuo or thre; &yogh;et dwellen &thorn;ere ynowe to wreke here deth and sle &thorn;i persone [2564] &para; And &thorn;ough so were &thorn;at &yogh;oure kynrede were more sekir and stedefast &thorn;an 
<PB REF="00000516.tif" N="504"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="227"> &thorn;e kynrede of &yogh;oure aduersaries; [2565] &yogh;it na&thorn;eles &yogh;oure kynrede nis but litel kinrede and litel sib to &yogh;ow [2566] and &thorn;e kyn of &yogh;oure enemyes ben neigh sibbe to hem. and certes as in &thorn;at here condicioun is bet &thorn;an &yogh;oures [2567] &para; &THORN;anne let vs considere also if &thorn;e counseilynge of hem &thorn;at counseiled &yogh;ow to take sodein vengeance whe&thorn;ir it accorde to resoun [2568] &amp; certes <MILESTONE N="216b" UNIT="folio">&yogh;e knowe wel nay [2569] &para; For as by right and resoun &thorn;er may no man take vengeaunce vpon no wight but &thorn;e Iugge &thorn;at/ ha&thorn; iurediccioun of it [2570] whan it is y-graunted him to take &thorn;ilke vengeaunce hastily or at|temperelly as &thorn;e lawe requireth. [2571] and &yogh;it more|ouer of &thorn;ilke word &thorn;at Tullius clepith consentynge [2572] &thorn;ou schalt considre if &thorn;y might and &thorn;y power may consente and suffice to &thorn;y wilfulnes and to &thorn;y counseilours. [2573] and certes &thorn;ou maist/ wel say &thorn;at nay / [2574] For sicurly as for to speke properly we may doo no &thorn;ing but oonly oon &thorn;ing/ which we may do rightfully [2575] &para; And certes rightfully may &yogh;e take no vengeance as of &yogh;oure owne auctorite [2576] &para; Than may &yogh;e se &thorn;at &yogh;oure power consentith not ne accordith not wi&thorn; &yogh;oure wilfulnesse [2577] &para; let vs now examyne &thorn;e &thorn;ridde poynt &thorn;at Tullius clepe&thorn; consequente. [2578] &thorn;ou schalt vnderstonde &thorn;at &thorn;e vengeance &thorn;at &thorn;ou purposiddest for to take is conse|quent. [2579] and &thorn;er of folwe&thorn; ano&thorn;er vengeaunce. peril and werre and o&thorn;er damages wi&thorn;oute nombre of whiche we be not war as at &thorn;is tyme [2580] &para; And as touching &thorn;e four&thorn;e poynt that tullius clepe&thorn; en|gendrynge; [2581] &thorn;ou schalt considre &thorn;at &thorn;is wrong which &thorn;at is doon to &thorn;e is engendred of &thorn;e hate of &thorn;in enemyes [2582] and of &thorn;e vengeaunce takinge vp &thorn;at wolde engendre ano&thorn;er vengeaunce &amp; moche sorwe and wastyng of riches as I sayde</P>
<P>[2583] &para; Now sire as to &thorn;e poynt &thorn;at Tullius clepith causes whiche &thorn;at &thorn;e laste poynt [2584] &thorn;ou 
<PB REF="00000517.tif" N="505"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="228"> schalt vnderstonde &thorn;at &thorn;e wrong &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast receyued ha&thorn; certeyn causes [2585] whiche &thorn;at clerkes calle Orience and Officience. and causa longinqua. and causa propinqua. &thorn;is is to say. &thorn;e fer cause. and &thorn;e neigh cause. [2586] for &thorn;e fer cause is almighty god &thorn;at is cause of alle &thorn;inges. [2587] &thorn;e nere cause is &thorn;e &thorn;re enemyes. [2588] &thorn;e cause accidental was hate. [2589] &thorn;e causes materiales been &thorn;e fyue woundes of &thorn;y doughter. [2590] the cause formal is &thorn;e maner of here werkyng &thorn;at brought in laddres and clombe in at &thorn;in wyndowes. [2591] &thorn;e cause final was for to sle &thorn;y doughter hit letted nou&yogh;t in as moche as was in hem [2592] &para; But for to speke of &thorn;e fer cause as to what ende &thorn;ay schal come or what schal finally betyde of hem in &thorn;is cause. can I not deme but by comittyng and by supposyng. [2593] For we schul suppose &thorn;at &thorn;ay schul come to a wikked ende [2594] by cause &thorn;at &thorn;e book of degrees saith &para; Seelden or wi&thorn; gret peyne ben causes I-brought to <MILESTONE N="217a" UNIT="folio">a good ende. whan &thorn;ay ben euyl bygonne</P>
<P>[2595] Now sire if men wolde axe me why &thorn;at &yogh;e suffrede men to do &yogh;ow &thorn;is wrong and vilonye; Certes I can not wel answere as for no so&thorn;fastnes [2596] For &thorn;e apostil saith. &thorn;at &thorn;e sciences and &thorn;e Iuggements of oure lord god almyghty ben ful deepe [2597] &para; Ther may no man comprehende ne serchen hem sufficiauntly [2598] &para; Natheles by certeyn presumpciouns and coniectinges I holde and bilieue [2599] &thorn;at god which &thorn;at is ful of iustice and of rightwisnesse ha&thorn; suffred &thorn;is to betyde by iuste cause resonable</P>
<P>[2600] &para; Thy name Melibe is to say a man &thorn;at drynke&thorn; hony. [2601] &thorn;ou hast y-dronke so moche hony of sweete temperel richesses and delices and hon|ours of &thorn;is world [2602] &thorn;at &thorn;ou art dronke and hast for&yogh;ete Ih&umacr; crist &thorn;y creatour. [2603] &thorn;ou hast not doon him such honour and reuerence as &thorn;e oughte to doone. [2604] ne &thorn;ou hast nou&yogh;t wel taken keep to 
<PB REF="00000518.tif" N="506"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="229"> &thorn;e wordes of Ovide &thorn;at saith [2605] &para; vnder &thorn;e hony of &thorn;y goodes of &thorn;y body is hid &thorn;e venym &thorn;at slee&thorn; &thorn;i soule [2606] &para; And Salomon saith &para; If &thorn;ou haue fouunde hony. ete of it &thorn;at suffice&thorn;. [2607] For if &thorn;ou ete of it out of mesure; &thorn;ou schalt spewe and be nedy and pouere. [2608] and perauenture crist ha&thorn; &thorn;e in despit. and hath torned away fro &thorn;e his face and his eeres of misericorde [2609] &para; And also he ha&thorn; suffred &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast ben punysshed in &thorn;e maner &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast I-trespassed [2610] &para; Thou hast doon synne a&yogh;einst oure lord crist. [2611] for certes &thorn;i &thorn;re enemyes of man|kinde &thorn;at is to say &thorn;y flessch &thorn;e feend and &thorn;e world. [2612] &thorn;ou hast y-suffred hem to entre in to &thorn;in herte wilfully by &thorn;e wyndow of &thorn;y body [2613] and hast nou&yogh;t defended &thorn;iself sufficiently agayns here asceutis and here temptaciouns So &thorn;at &thorn;ay haue woundid &thorn;i soule in fyue places [2614] This is to sayn &thorn;e dedly synnes &thorn;at ben entred in to &thorn;in herte by &thorn;y fyue wyndowes [2615] &para; And in &thorn;e same maner oure lord crist hath wolde and suffred &thorn;at &thorn;y &thorn;re enemyes ben entred in to &thorn;in hous by &thorn;o wyndowes [2616] and haue I-woundid &thorn;i doughter in &thorn;e forsayde maner</P>
<P>[2617] &para; Certes quod Melibeus I se wel &thorn;at &yogh;e en|force &yogh;ow moche by wordes to ouercome me. in such manere &thorn;at I schal not venge me on myn enemyes [2618] schewynge me &thorn;e perils and &thorn;e yueles &thorn;at mighten falle of &thorn;is vengeaunce [2619] &para; But who-so wolde considre in alle vegeaunces &thorn;e periles and &thorn;e yueles &thorn;at mighten folwe of vengeaunces takynge. [2620] a man wolde neuer take vengeaunce and &thorn;at were harm. [2621] For by venge|aunce takynge be <MILESTONE N="217b" UNIT="folio">wikked men destruyed and disseuered fro &thorn;e goode men. [2622] and &thorn;ay &thorn;at haue wille to wikked|nes restreignen here wikked purpos whan &thorn;ay seen &thorn;e punysshyng and &thorn;e chastisyng of trespasours [2623] . . . . .
<PB REF="00000519.tif" N="507"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="230"> [2624] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [2625] &para; And &yogh;it say I more &thorn;at right so as a sengle persone synne&thorn; in taking of vengeaunce; [2626] Right so &thorn;e Iugge synne&thorn; if he doo no vengeaunce on him &thorn;at it ha&thorn; deserued [2627] &para; For Senec saith &thorn;us &para; he &thorn;at maister is he saith good to reproue schrewes [2628] And as Cassoder saith &para; A man drede&thorn; to doon outrage whan he woot and knowe&thorn; &thorn;at it displese&thorn; to &thorn;e Iugges and &thorn;e soueraynes. [2629] and ano&thorn;er saith &para; The Iugge &thorn;at drede&thorn; to demen right make&thorn; schrewes // [2630] And seint poul &thorn;appostoil saith in his epistil whan he write&thorn; to &thorn;e romayns &para; The Iugges bere not &thorn;e spere wi&thorn;oute cause. [2631] but &thorn;ay beren it to punysshe &thorn;e schrewes and mys doers and for to defende wi&thorn; &thorn;e goode men. [2632] If &yogh;e wol take vengeaunce on &yogh;oure enemyes &yogh;e schul retourne or haue recours to &thorn;e Iugges &thorn;at haue iurediccioun vpon hem [2633] and he schal pun[i]ssche hem as &thorn;e law axe&thorn; and require&thorn;</P>
<P>[2634] &para; A quod melibeus &thorn;is vengeaunce like&thorn; me no &thorn;ing [2635] I by&thorn;enke me now and take heed how fortune ha&thorn; norissched me fro my childhode and ha&thorn; holpe me to passen many a strayt passage [2636] &para; Now wol I aske her &thorn;at sche schal wi&thorn; goddes help helpe me my schame for to venge</P>
<P>[2637] &para; Certes quod prudence if &yogh;e wil wirche by my counseil. &yogh;e schul not assaye fortune by no maner way [2638] ne schul not lene ne bowe vnto hire after &thorn;e word of Senec [2639] &para; For &thorn;inges &thorn;at be&thorn; folye and &thorn;at be&thorn; in hope of fortune schul neuer come to good ende [2640] &para; And as &thorn;e same Senek sai&thorn; &para; The more cleer&middot; and &thorn;e more schynynge &thorn;at fortune is &thorn;e more brutil and &thorn;e sonner breke&thorn; sche. [2641] so truste&thorn; nought in hire For sche is nou&yogh;t stedefast ne stable [2642] &para; For whan &thorn;ou wenest or trowest to be most seur of hir 
<PB REF="00000520.tif" N="508"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="231"> help. sche wol fayle &thorn;e and deceyue &thorn;e. [2643] And wher as &yogh;e say &thorn;at fortune ha&thorn; norisshed &yogh;ow fro &yogh;oure childhode [2644] I say &thorn;at in so mochel &yogh;e schul &thorn;e lasse truste in hire and in hire witte [2645] &para; For Senek saith &para; what man &thorn;at is norissched by fortune; sche make&thorn; him to gret a fool [2646] &para; Now si&thorn;&thorn;e &yogh;e desire and axe vengeaunce and &thorn;e vengeaunce &thorn;at is doon . . . . .[2647] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> in hope of fortune is peril|ous and vncerteyn [2648] &thorn;anne haue&thorn; noon <MILESTONE N="218a" UNIT="folio">o&thorn;er remedye but for to haue recours vnto &thorn;e soueraigne Iugge &thorn;at vengith alle vilonies and wronges [2649] and he schal venge &yogh;ow after &thorn;at himself witnesse&thorn; where as he saith [2650] &para; leue&thorn; &thorn;e ve[n]geaunce to me and I schal &yogh;elde it</P>
<P>[2651] &para; Melibeus answerd. If I ne venge me nou&yogh;t of &thorn;e vilonye &thorn;at men haue doon vnto me. [2652] I schal sounere warne hem &thorn;at han doon to me &thorn;at vilonye and alle o&thorn;ere to doo me ano&thorn;er vilonye [2653] For it is writen &para; Tak no vengeaunce of an old vilonye &thorn;ou suf|frest &thorn;in aduersarie do &thorn;e a newe vilonye. [2654] and also for my suffraunce men wolde do me so moche vilonye &thorn;at I mighte neither bere it ne sus|teyne it. [2655] and so schulde I be put over lowe [2656] For men say In moche sufferynge schal many &thorn;inges falle vnto whiche &thorn;ou schal nou&yogh;t mowe suffre</P>
<P>[2657] &para; Certes quod prudence I graunte &yogh;ow wel &thorn;at ouer mochil suffraunce is nou&yogh;t good; [2658] but &yogh;it folwi&thorn; it nought &thorn;erof &thorn;at euery persone to whom men doon vilonye take of it vengeaunce. [2659] For it apper|tiene&thorn; and longe&thorn; al oonly to &thorn;e Iugges. For &thorn;ay schul venge &thorn;e vilonyes and &thorn;e iniuries. [2660] and &thorn;erfore &thorn;e auctoritees &thorn;at &yogh;e haue sayd aboue been oonly vnderstonden in &thorn;e Iugges [2661] &para; For whan &thorn;ay suffre to mochil &thorn;e wronges and &thorn;e vilonyes that ben doon 
<PB REF="00000521.tif" N="509"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="232"> wi&thorn;oute punysshyng [2662] &thorn;ay somne not a man oonly to doo newe wronges; but &thorn;ay comaunde hit. [2663] also &thorn;e wise man saith &para; The Iugge &thorn;at correct|e&thorn; not &thorn;e synnere comaundith him and byddith him doon ano&thorn;er synne [2664] &para; And &thorn;e Iugges and souereignes mighten in here lond so mochil suffren of &thorn;e schrewes and mys-doeres [2665] &thorn;at &thorn;ay schulde by such suffraunce by proces of tyme wexen of such power and might &thorn;at &thorn;ay schulde put out &thorn;e Iugges and &thorn;e souereignes from here places [2666] &amp; atte laste do hem lese here lordschipes</P>
<P>[2667] But lete vs now putte &thorn;at &yogh;e han leue to venge &yogh;ow. [2668] I say &yogh;e ben nou&yogh;t of might ne power as now to venge &yogh;ou [2669] &para; For if he wolde make comparisoun as to &thorn;e might &para; Of &yogh;oure aduersaries &yogh;e schulde fynde in many &thorn;inges &thorn;at I haue I-schewed &yogh;ow er &thorn;is &thorn;at here condicioun is bettre &thorn;an &yogh;oures [2670] And &thorn;erfore say I &thorn;at it is good as now &thorn;at &yogh;e suffre and be pacient</P>
<P>[2671] &para; For&thorn;ermore &yogh;e knowe &thorn;at after <MILESTONE N="218b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;e comune sawe it is a woodnesse a man to stryue with a strenger or a more mighty man &thorn;an him-seluen is [2672] And for to stryue wi&thorn; a man of euene streng&thorn;e &thorn;at is to say with as strong a man as he is. it is peril. [2673] and for to stryue with a weykere it is folye [2674] and &thorn;erfore schulde a man fle stryuynge as moche as he mighte [2675] &para; For Salomon seith &para; It is a gret worschipe a man to kepe him fro noyse and stryf [2676] &para; And if it so bifalle or happe &thorn;at a man of gretter might and strengthe &thorn;an &thorn;ou art do &thorn;e greuaunce [2677] stude and busye &thorn;e ra&thorn;er to stille &thorn;e same greuaunce &thorn;an for to venge &thorn;e [2678] &para; For Senec saith. he putte&thorn; him in a gret peril &thorn;at stryueth wi&thorn; a gretter man &thorn;an he himseluen is [2679] &para; And Catoun saith &para; If a man of heiher estat or degre or more mighty &thorn;en &thorn;ou do &thorn;e ano&thorn;er grieuaunce; Suffre him. [2680] For he &thorn;at ha&thorn; oones don &thorn;e a grieuaunce 
<PB REF="00000522.tif" N="510"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="233"> may ano&thorn;er tyme relieue &thorn;e and helpe &thorn;e. [2681] &YOGH;it sette I a caas &yogh;e haue bothe might and licence to venge &yogh;ow; [2682] I say &thorn;er ben ful many &thorn;inges &thorn;at schulde restreinge &yogh;ow of vengeaunce takynge [2683] and make &yogh;ow to encline to suffre and to haue pacience of &thorn;e wronges &thorn;at han ben doon to &yogh;ow. [2684] First and forward &yogh;e wol considre &thorn;e defautes &thorn;at been in &yogh;oure owne persone. [2685] for whiche defautes god ha&thorn; suffred &yogh;ow to haue &thorn;is tribulacioun as I haue sayd &yogh;ow her byfore [2686] &para; For &thorn;e poete saith // we oughten paciently to suffre &thorn;e tribu|lacioun &thorn;at cometh to vs whan &thorn;at we &thorn;enken and consideren &thorn;at we han deserued to haue hem [2687] &para; And seint poul saith &thorn;at whan a man considere&thorn; wel &thorn;e nombre of his defautes and of his synnes: [2688] &thorn;e peynes and &thorn;e tribulaciouns &thorn;at he suffere&thorn; semen &thorn;e lasse vnto him [2689] &para; and in as moche as him &thorn;enk|ith his synnes &thorn;e more heuy and greuous; [2690] in so moche his peyne is &thorn;e lighter and &thorn;e more esier vn-to him [2691] &para; Also &yogh;e oughten to encline and bowe &yogh;oure herte to take &thorn;e pacience of oure lord ih&umacr; crist. as sei&thorn; seint peter in his epistles [2692] &para; Ih&umacr; crist he sei&thorn; ha&thorn; suffred for vs and &yogh;iuen ensample vnto euery man to folwe and sewe him. [2693] For he dede neuer synne ne neuer cam vileyns worde out of his mou&thorn; [2694] whan men cursed him; he cursed hem not &para; And whan men beete him; he manased hem not. [2695] &para; Also &thorn;e grete pacience which &thorn;at seintes &thorn;at been in paradys <MILESTONE N="219a" UNIT="folio">han had in tribulaciouns &thorn;at &thorn;ay haue had and suffred withoute desert/ or gult [2696] oughte moche stire &yogh;ow to pacience [2697] &para; For&thorn;er|more &yogh;e schul enforce &yogh;ow to haue pacience [2698] consideringe &thorn;at &thorn;e tribulaciouns of &thorn;is world but litel while enduren &amp; soone passed ben and goon [2699] &para; And &thorn;e ioye &thorn;at a man seche&thorn; to haue by pacience in tribulaciouns is perdurable after &thorn;at &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000523.tif" N="511"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="234"> apostil sei&thorn; in his epistil [2700] &para; The ioye of god he sai&thorn; is perdurable &thorn;at is to say euer-more lastynge [2701] &para; Also troweth and bilieue&thorn; stedefastly &thorn;at he is not wel norisched and taught &thorn;at can nought haue pacience or wil nou&yogh;t receyue pacience [2702] &para; For Salomon saith &thorn;at &thorn;e doctrine and &thorn;e witte of a man is I-knowe by pacience [2703 &para; And in ano&thorn;er place he sei&thorn; &para; he &thorn;at hath pacience; gouerne&thorn; him by gret prudence [2704] &para; And &thorn;e same salamon sei&thorn;. &thorn;at &thorn;e wra&thorn;ful and &thorn;e angry man make&thorn; noyses. and &thorn;e pacient man attempereth and stille&thorn; him. [2705] he sei&thorn; also &para; It is more worth to be pacient &thorn;an for to be right strong. [2706] And And he &thorn;at may haue his lordschipe of his oughne herte; is more wor&thorn; and more to preise &thorn;an he &thorn;at by his force &amp; by his strengthe take&thorn; grete citees [2707] &para; And &thorn;erfore saith seint Iame in his epistil &thorn;at pacience is a gret vertu of perfeccioun.</P>
<P>[2708] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> [2709] but euery man may not haue &thorn;e perfeccioun &thorn;at &yogh;e seekyn [2710] ne I am not of &thorn;e nombre of right par|fyte men; [2711] For myn herte may neuer be in pees vnto &thorn;e tyme it be venged [2712] &para; And al be it/ so that it was a gret peril to myne enemyes to don me a vilonye in takinge vengeaunce vpon me; [2713] &yogh;it tooken &thorn;ay noon heede of &thorn;e peril but filden here wikked desir and her corrage. [2714] and &thorn;erfore me &thorn;enkith men oughten nought repreue me &thorn;ough I putte me in a litel peril for to venge me [2715] &para; And &thorn;ough I do a gret excesse &thorn;at is to say &thorn;at I venge oon outrage by ano&thorn;er</P>
<P>[2716] &para; A quod dame prudence &yogh;e say &yogh;oure wille and as &yogh;ow likith. [2717] but in noon caas in &thorn;e world a man ne schulde nou&yogh;t doon outrage ne excesse for to venge him. [2718] &para; For Cassidore sai&thorn;. as euel do&thorn; he &thorn;at auengith him by outrage as he &thorn;at doth &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000524.tif" N="512"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="235"> outrage / [2719] and &thorn;erfore &yogh;e schul venge &yogh;ow after &thorn;e ordre of right &thorn;at is to sayn by &thorn;e lawe and nou&yogh;t by excesse ne by outrage [2720] &para; And also if &yogh;e wil venge &yogh;ow of &thorn;e outrage of &yogh;oure aduersaries in o&thorn;er maner &thorn;an right comaunde&thorn;; &yogh;e synnen [2721] &para; And &thorn;erfore sai&thorn; Senec / that <MILESTONE N="219b" UNIT="folio">a man schal neuer venge schrewednes by schrewednes. [2722] &para; And if &yogh;e say &thorn;at axe&thorn; a man to defende violence by vyolence. and fightyng by fightynge [2723] &para; Certes &yogh;e say so&thorn; whan &thorn;e defence is doon anoon wi&thorn;outen interualle or wi&thorn;outen taryinge or dilay [2724] for to defenden him and nought for to venge him [2725] &para; And it bihoue&thorn; a man putte such attemperance in his defence; [2726] &thorn;at men haue no cause ne matiere to repreuen him that defendith him of excesse and outrage . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> [2727] &para; Parde &yogh;e knowe wel &thorn;at &yogh;e make no defence as now for to defende &yogh;ow but for to venge &yogh;ow [2728] and so seme&thorn; it / &thorn;at &yogh;e haue no wille to do &yogh;oure wille attemperelly [2729] &amp; &thorn;erfore me &thorn;enki&thorn; &thorn;at pacience is good &para; For Salamon saith &thorn;at he &thorn;at is not pacient schal haue gret harm.</P>
<P>[2730] &para; Certes quod melibeus I graunte &yogh;ou wel &thorn;at whan a man is inpacient and wroth. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> [2731] for &thorn;e lawe saith &thorn;at he is coupable &thorn;at entremettith him or mellith him with such &thorn;ing as aperteyne&thorn; not vnto him [2732] &para; Dan Salamon sai&thorn;. he &thorn;at entremette&thorn; him of &thorn;e noyse or stryf of ano&thorn;er man. is lik him &thorn;at takith &thorn;e hound by &thorn;e eeres. [2733] For right as he &thorn;at taki&thorn; &thorn;e strong hound by &thorn;e eeres is o&thorn;er while biten with &thorn;e hound; [2734] ri&yogh;t in &thorn;e same wise it is resoun &thorn;at he haue harm &thorn;at by his impacience melle&thorn; him of &thorn;e noise of ano&thorn;er man where it aperteyne&thorn; not to him [2735] &para; But/ &yogh;e schul knowe wel &thorn;at &thorn;is dede &thorn;at 
<PB REF="00000525.tif" N="513"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="236"> is to sayn myn disease and my grief touche&thorn; me right neigh. [2736] and &thorn;erfore &thorn;ough I be wro&thorn;; it is no meruayle. [2737] and sauynge &yogh;our grace I can not see &thorn;at it mighte gretly harme me &thorn;ough I toke vengeaunce. [2738] For I am richer and more mighty &thorn;an myne enemyes been / [2739] And wel knowe &yogh;e &thorn;at by money and by hauynge of grete posses|siouns ben alle &thorn;e &thorn;inges of &thorn;is world gouernede [2740] &para; And Salamon saith &thorn;at alle &thorn;inges obeyen to moneye / dispraisynge &thorn;e power of his aduersaries</P>
<P>[2741] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> &para; Tho sche spak and sayde in &thorn;is wyse [2742] &para; Certes deere sire I graunte &yogh;ow &thorn;at &yogh;e ben riche and mighty [2743] and &thorn;at richesse is good to hem &thorn;at wel haue geten it/ and &thorn;at wel conne vse it [2744] For right as &thorn;e body of a man may not be wi&thorn;oute &thorn;e soule; no more may a man lyue wi&thorn;oute temperel goodes [2745] and by rich|esse may a man gete him greet frendschipe / [2746] <MILESTONE N="220a" UNIT="folio">&para; And &thorn;erfore saith Pamphilles. If a neet-hurdes dou&yogh;ter he sai&thorn; be riche; sche may cheese of a &thorn;ousand men which she wol take to hir housbonde [2747] &para; For of a &thorn;ousand men oon wil not forsake hir ne refuse hire [2748] &para; And &thorn;is pamphilles sei&thorn; also &para; If &thorn;ou be right happy &thorn;at is to sayn if &thorn;ou be right riche; &thorn;anne schalt &thorn;ou fynde a gret nombre of felawes and frendes [2749] &para; And if &thorn;y fortune chaunge &thorn;at &thorn;ou wax pore; fare wel frendschipe. [2750] For &thorn;ou schalt ben aloone wi&thorn;outen eny companye but if it be &thorn;e compaignye of pore folk // [2751] And &yogh;it saith &thorn;is pamphillus more ouer &para; That &thorn;ey &thorn;at/ ben &thorn;ral and bonde of linage schullen ben maad wor&thorn;y and noble by richesse [2752] &para; And right so as by richesse &thorn;er come many goodes; Right so by pouert comen &thorn;er many harmes.[. . . .] [2753] . . . . .
<PB REF="00000526.tif" N="514"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="237"> . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> [2754] And &thorn;er|fore clepe&thorn; Cassidore pouert. . . . .] ruyne. [2755] &thorn;at is to sayn &thorn;e moder of ouer&thorn;rowyng or fallynge doun [2756] &para; &amp; &thorn;erfore Pieres alphons oon of &thorn;e grettest aduersites of &thorn;is world is; [2757] whan a free man by kyn or burthe is constreigned by pouert to eten &thorn;e almes of his enemyes [2758] &para; And &thorn;e same sei&thorn; Innocent in oon of his bookes &para; &thorn;at sorweful &amp; vnhappy is &thorn;e condicioun of a pouere begger. [2759] for if he axe nou&yogh;t his mete; he deyeth for hungir; [2760] and if he axe; he deye&thorn; for schame. And algates &thorn;e necessite constreigne&thorn; hym to axe. [2761] And &thorn;erfore sai&thorn; Salamon &thorn;at bettre it is to deye &thorn;an to haue such pouert [2762] And as &thorn;e same Sala|mon saith Bettir is to deye on bitter deth &thorn;an for to lyue in such a wyse [2763] &para; By &thorn;ese resouns &thorn;at I haue sayd vnto &yogh;ow and by many ano&thorn;er resoun &thorn;at I knowe and cou&thorn;e say [2764] I graunte &yogh;ow &thorn;at richesses ben goode to hem &thorn;at gete hem wel. &amp; to hem &thorn;at hem wel vsen [2765] &para; And &thorn;erfore wol I schewe &yogh;ow how &yogh;e schulde bere &yogh;ow in getyng of riches and in what maner &yogh;e schulde vse hem</P>
<P>[2766] &para; First &yogh;e schulde gete hem wi&thorn;oute gret desir by good leysir sokyngly and nought ouer hastily [2767] &para; For a man &thorn;at is to desirynge for to gete riches abandoneth him first to &thorn;efte and to alle o&thorn;ere yueles [2768] &para; And &thorn;erfore sai&thorn; Salamon &para; he &thorn;at hastith him to bisyly to waxe riche; schal ben noon Innocent [2769] &para; He sai&thorn; also &thorn;at &thorn;e riches &thorn;at hastily come&thorn; to a man; soone &amp; lightly goth and passeth fro a man [2770] &para; But &thorn;at richesse &thorn;at <MILESTONE N="220b" UNIT="folio">come&thorn; alway litel and litel waxe&thorn; alway and multiplie&thorn; [2771] &para; And sire &yogh;e schal gete richesse by &yogh;oure witte and by &yogh;oure trauayle vnto &yogh;oure profyt [2772] and &thorn;at wi&thorn;oute wrong or harm doynge to eny o&thorn;er persone [2773] &para; For &thorn;e lawe 
<PB REF="00000527.tif" N="515"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="238"> saith &thorn;at no man make&thorn; himself riche &thorn;at do&thorn; harm to ano&thorn;er wight. [2774] &thorn;is is to say. &thorn;at nature defende&thorn; and forbedith by right &thorn;at no man make himself riche vnto &thorn;e harm of ano&thorn;er persone. [2775] Tullius saith. &thorn;at no sorwe ne drede of deth. ne thought &thorn;at may falle to a man [2776] is so moche a&yogh;einst nature as a man to encresce his oughne profyt to &thorn;e harm of ano&thorn;er man [2777] &para; And &thorn;ough &thorn;e grete men and &thorn;e riche men gete richesse more lightly &thorn;an &thorn;ou; [2778] &yogh;it schalt &thorn;ou not be ydil ne slowe to &thorn;y profyt/ For &thorn;ou schalt in alle wise flee ydil|nes. [2779] For Salamon saith &thorn;at ydelnesse techi&thorn; a man to do many yueles [2780] &para; And &thorn;e same salamon sai&thorn; &thorn;at he &thorn;at trauaileth and besie&thorn; him to tilye &thorn;e lond schal ete &thorn;e breed. [2781] But he &thorn;at is ydil and caste&thorn; him to no busynesse ne occupacioun schal falle in to pouert and deye for hunger [2782] &para; And he &thorn;at is ydel and slough can neuer fynde him tyme for to do his profyt [2783] &para; For &thorn;er is a versifiour saith; &thorn;e ydel man excuse&thorn; him in wynter by cause of &thorn;e grete colde. And in somer by enchesoun of &thorn;e grete hete. [2784] &para; For &thorn;ese causes saith Catoun &para; waketh and encline&thorn; &yogh;ow nou&yogh;t ouer moche for to slepe. For ouermoche reste norische&thorn; and cause&thorn; many vices [2785] &para; And &thorn;erfore saith seint Ierom; Do&thorn; some goode deedes &thorn;at &thorn;e deuel which &thorn;at is oure enemy ne fynde &yogh;ow vnoccupied [2786] &para; For &thorn;e deuel ne taki&thorn; not lightly vnto his werkes suche as he fyndeth occupied in goode werkes</P>
<P>[2787] &para; &thorn;anne &thorn;us in getynge of riches &yogh;e moot flee ydelnesse / [2788] &para; and afterward &yogh;e schul vse &thorn;e richesses &thorn;e whiche &yogh;e han geten by &yogh;oure witte and by &yogh;oure trauaile [2789] in such a maner &thorn;at men holde &yogh;ow not skarce / ne to sparynge ne to fool large &thorn;at is to say ouer large a spender [2790] For right as men blamen an auerous man by cause of his skarsete and chyncherie [2791] in &thorn;e same manere is he to blame 
<PB REF="00000528.tif" N="516"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="239"> &thorn;at spendeth ouer largely [2792] &para; And &thorn;erfore saith Catoun &para; Vse he saith &thorn;i richesses &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast y-geten [2793] in such a manere &thorn;at &thorn;ay haue no matier ne cause to calle &thorn;e nei&thorn;er wrecche ne chynche [2794] &para; For it is gret schame to a man to <MILESTONE N="221a" UNIT="folio">haue a pouer herte and a riche purse [2795] &para; He saith also &thorn;e goodes &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast I-geten vse hem by mesure &thorn;at is to say spende hem mesurably [2796] For &thorn;ay &thorn;at folily wasten and spenden &thorn;e goodes &thorn;at &thorn;ay haue; [2797] whan &thorn;ay haue no more propre of here oughne; &thorn;ay schape hem to take &thorn;e goodes of ano&thorn;er man [2798] &para; I say thanne &yogh;e schul flee auarice [2799] vsynge &yogh;our richesse in such manere &thorn;at . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> &yogh;oure [. . . .] be buried. [2800] but &thorn;at &yogh;e haue &thorn;anne in &yogh;oure might and in &yogh;oure weldynge. [2801] For &thorn;e wise man reproue&thorn; &thorn;e auerous man and saith &thorn;us in tuo versus [2802] &para; wher-to and why burieth a man his goodes by his auarice and knowi&thorn; wel &thorn;at needes most he deye. [2803] for deth is &thorn;e ende of euery man as in this present lif. [2804] And for what cause or enchesoun ioyne&thorn; he him or knette&thorn; him so fast vnto his goodes [2805] &thorn;at alle his wittes mowe nought disseuer him or departe him fro his goodes [2806] &amp; knowi&thorn; wel or oughte knowe wel &thorn;at whan he is deed he schal no &thorn;ing bere with him out of &thorn;is world. [2807] &para; And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; seint/ Austyn &thorn;at &thorn;e auerous man is likned vnto helle. [2808] &thorn;at &thorn;e more &thorn;at it swolwith &thorn;e more it desire&thorn; to swolwe and deuoure [2809] &para; And as wel as &yogh;e wolde eschewe to be cleped an auerous man or chinche; [2810] as wel schulde &yogh;e kepe &yogh;ow and gouerne &yogh;ow in such a wise &thorn;at men cleped &yogh;ow nou&yogh;t fool large [2811] &para; Therfore sai&thorn; Tullius &para; The goodes he sai&thorn; of &thorn;in hous schulde nought ben hidde ne kepte so clos; but &thorn;at &thorn;ay might ben opened by pite and by bonairete [2812] &thorn;at is to sayn to &yogh;iue hem part &thorn;at han gret neede. [2813] 
<PB REF="00000529.tif" N="517"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="240"> ne &thorn;y goodes schul not be so open to be euery mannes goodes [2814] &para; Aftirward in getynge of &yogh;oure richesses and in vsynge hem &yogh;e schul alway haue &thorn;re &thorn;inges in &yogh;oure herte [2815] &thorn;at is to say Oure lord god. Conscience. and good name. [2816] First &yogh;e schul haue god in &yogh;oure herte [2817] and for no riches &yogh;e schul in no manere doo no &thorn;ing which might displese god &thorn;at is &yogh;our creatour and &yogh;oure maker. [2818] For after &thorn;e word of Salamon. It is better to haue litil good wi&thorn; loue of god. [2819] &thorn;an to haue mochil good and tresor and lese &thorn;e loue of his lord god. [2820] And &thorn;e prophete saith. Better is to ben a good man and haue litel good &thorn;an tresore [2821] &thorn;e to ben holden a schrewe and haue gret riches [2822] &para; And &yogh;it say I for&thorn;er more &thorn;at &yogh;e schuln alway doon &yogh;oure businesse to gete &yogh;ow riches. [2823] so &thorn;at &yogh;e gete hem with good conscience [2824] &para; And &thorn;e apostil seith. ther <MILESTONE N="221b" UNIT="folio">nys &thorn;ing in &thorn;is world of which we schuln haue so gret ioye as whan oure conscience bere&thorn; vs good witnes [2825] &para; And &thorn;e wise man saith substaunce of a man is ful good whan synne is not in his conscience. [2826] Afterward in getynge of &yogh;oure richesses and in vsynge of hem [2827] &thorn;ou most haue gret busynesse &amp; gret diligence &thorn;at &yogh;oure good name be alway kept and conserued [2828] &para; For Sala|mon sai&thorn;. better it is and more abelith a man for to haue a good name &thorn;an for to haue gret riches [2829] and &thorn;erfore he saith in ano&thorn;er place. Do gret diligence sai&thorn; Salamon in kepyng of &thorn;y frend and of &thorn;y good name. [2830] For it schal lenger abyde wi&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;an eny tresor be it neuer so precious [2831] &para; And certes he schulde nou&yogh;t be cleped a gentil man &thorn;at after god and good conscience alle &thorn;inges left ne do&thorn; his diligence and busynesse to kepe his good name. [2832] And Cassidore saith &thorn;at it is signe of a good man &amp; a gentil or of a gentil herte whan a man loue&thorn; or desire&thorn; to 
<PB REF="00000530.tif" N="518"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="241"> haue a good name . [2833] and &thorn;erfore saith seint augustyn &thorn;at &thorn;er ben tuo &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben necessarie and needful [2834] and &thorn;at is good conscience and good loos [2835] &thorn;at is to sayn. good conscience in &thorn;in oughne persone inward. and good loos of &thorn;in neghebor outward. [2836] and he &thorn;at truste&thorn; him so moche in his good conscience [2837] &thorn;at he displese&thorn; and setti&thorn; at nought his good name or loos and rekke&thorn; nought &thorn;ough he kepe not his good name; nys but a cruel churl</P>
<P>[2838] &para; Sire now haue I schewed &yogh;ow how &yogh;e schulde doon in getyng of good and riches and how &yogh;e schuld vse hem [2839] I see wel &thorn;at for &thorn;e trust &thorn;at &yogh;e haue in &yogh;oure riches; &yogh;e wolde meue werre and bataile [2840] &para; I counseile &yogh;ow &thorn;at &yogh;e bygynne no werre in trust of &yogh;oure riches. for thanne suffisen not werres to mayn|tene [2841] &para; And &thorn;erfore saith a philosophre &para; That man &thorn;at desire&thorn; and wol algate haue werre; schal neuer haue sufficeaunce. [2842] For &thorn;e richere &thorn;at he is; &thorn;e gretter dispense most he make if he wol haue wor|schipe or victorie [2843] &para; And Salamon saith. &thorn;e gretter riches &thorn;at a man ha&thorn;; &thorn;e moo despendours he ha&thorn;. [2844] And deere sire al be it so &thorn;at for &yogh;oure riches &yogh;e mowe haue moche folk; [2845] &yogh;it byhoue&thorn; it not ne it is not good to bygynne werre &thorn;er as &yogh;e may in o&thorn;er maner haue pees vnto &yogh;oure worschipe and profyt. [2846] For &thorn;e victorie of batailles &thorn;at ben in &thorn;is world lith not in gret nombre or multitude of poeple ne in vertu of man; [2847] but it <MILESTONE N="222a" UNIT="folio">lith in &thorn;e wille &amp; in &thorn;e hond of oure lord god almighty [2848] And Iudas machabeus which was goddes knight [2849] whan he schulde fighte a&yogh;einst his aduersaries &thorn;at hadde a gretter nombre &amp; a gretter mul|titude of folk and strengere &thorn;an was &thorn;e poeple of &thorn;is macha|be. [2850] &yogh;it he reconforted his litel poeple / and sayde ry&yogh;t in &thorn;is wise [2851] &para; As lightly quod he may oure lord god almighty &yogh;iue victory to fewe folk. 
<PB REF="00000531.tif" N="519"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="242"> . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> [2852] For &thorn;e victorie of batailles come&thorn; nou&yogh;t by &thorn;e grete nombre of poeple; [2853] but it come&thorn; fro oure lord god of heuen [2854] &para; And dere sire for as moche as &thorn;er is no man certeyn if it be wor&thorn;i &thorn;at god &yogh;iue him victorie . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> or nou&yogh;t after &thorn;at &thorn;at Salamon sai&thorn;. [2855] &thorn;erfore euery man schulde gretly drede werres to bygynne . [2856] And by cause &thorn;at in batailles falle many meruayles and periles [2857] and happe&thorn; o&thorn;er while &thorn;at as soone is &thorn;e grete man slayn as &thorn;e litel man . [2858] and as it is writen in &thorn;e secounde book of kynges &thorn;e deedes of batayles be auenturous and no thing certeyn [2859] For as lightly is oon hurt with a spere as ano&thorn;er. [2860] and &thorn;erfore is gret peril in werre . &thorn;erfore schulde a man flee and eschewe werre in as moche as a man may goodly [2861] &para; For Salamon saith . &para; he &thorn;at loueth peril schal falle in peril</P>
<P>[2862] &para; After &thorn;at dame prudens hadde spoke in &thorn;is maner; Mellibe answerde and sayde [2863] &para; I se wel dame &thorn;at by &yogh;oure faire wordes and by &yogh;oure resouns &thorn;at &yogh;e haue schewed me &thorn;at &thorn;e werre like&thorn; &yogh;ow no &thorn;ing . [2864] but/ I haue not/ &yogh;it/ herd &yogh;oure coun|seil how I schal doo in &thorn;is neede</P>
<P>[2865] &para; Certes quod sche I counseile &yogh;ow &thorn;at &yogh;e accorde wi&thorn; &yogh;oure aduersaries and &thorn;at &yogh;e haue pees with hem [2866] &para; For seint Iame sai&thorn; in his epistles &thorn;at by concord and pees &thorn;e smale ryches wexen grete . [2867] and by debaat and discord &thorn;e gret richesses fallen doun [2868] &para; And &yogh;e knowe wel &thorn;at oon of &thorn;e moste grettest and soueraign &thorn;inges &thorn;at is in &thorn;is world is vnite &amp; pees [2869] &para; And &thorn;erfore saith oure lord ih&umacr; crist to his aposteles in &thorn;is wise [2870] &para; wol happy and blessed be &thorn;ay &thorn;at louen and purchacen pees . for &thorn;ay ben called children of crist [2871] &para; A quod Melibe. Now se I wel &thorn;at &yogh;e louen not myn honour ne my worschipe [2872] and knowe&thorn; wel &thorn;at myne 
<PB REF="00000532.tif" N="520"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="243"> aduersaries han bygonne &thorn;is debate and brige by here outrage [2873] And &yogh;e see wel &thorn;at &thorn;ay require ne praye me not of pees. ne &thorn;ay askyn nou&yogh;t to be recounseild; [2874] wol &yogh;e &thorn;anne &thorn;at I goo &amp; <MILESTONE N="222b" UNIT="folio">meke me vnto hem and crie hem mercy . [2875] for so&thorn;e &thorn;at were not my worschipe [2876] &para; For right as men seyn &thorn;at ouer gret pryde engendre&thorn; despisyng. so fare&thorn; it by to gret humblete or mekenesse</P>
<P>[2877] &para; Thanne bygan dame prudence to make sem|blant of wra&thorn;&thorn;e and sayde. [2878] Certes sire saue &yogh;oure grace. I loue &yogh;oure honour and &yogh;oure profyt as I doo myn owne and euer haue doon [2879] &yogh;e ne mowe noon o&thorn;er seyn [2880] &para; And &yogh;it if I hadde sayd &yogh;e scholde haue purchaced pees and &thorn;e reconsiliacioun. I ne hadde not moche mys-take me ne seyd amys; [2881] For &thorn;e wise man saith. &thorn;e dis|cencioun bigynne&thorn; by ano&thorn;er man and &thorn;e reconsilynge bygynne&thorn; by &thorn;yself [2882] &para; And &thorn;e prophete saith &para; Flee schame and schrewednesse and doo goodnesse. [2883] Seeke pees and folwe it as moche as in &thorn;e is. [2884] &YOGH;et sei&thorn; he not &thorn;at &yogh;e schul ra&thorn;er pursewe to &yogh;oure aduersaries for pees &thorn;an &thorn;ei schul to &yogh;ow. [2885] For I knowe wel &thorn;at &yogh;e be so hard-herted &thorn;at &yogh;e wil doo no &thorn;ing for me [2886] &para; And salamon saith . he &thorn;at is ouer hard herted atte laste he schal mys happe and my[s]-tyde</P>
<P>[2887] &para; whan melibe had seyn dame prudence make semblaunce of wra&thorn;&thorn;e; he sayde in &thorn;is wise . [2888] dame I pray &yogh;ow &thorn;at &yogh;e be not displesed of &thorn;inges &thorn;at I say [2889] For &yogh;e knoweth wel &thorn;at I am angry and wro&thorn; and &thorn;at is no wonder. [2890] and &thorn;ay &thorn;at ben wro&thorn; wot not wel what &thorn;ay doon ne what &thorn;ay say [2891] &thorn;erfore &thorn;e prophete sai&thorn; &thorn;at troublit eyen haue no cleer sight [2892] &para; But sayeth and counsaile&thorn; me for&thorn; as &yogh;ow like&thorn; For I am redy to doo right as &yogh;e wol desire. [2893] and if &yogh;e reproue me of my folye; I am &thorn;e more holde to loue &yogh;ow and to prayse 
<PB REF="00000533.tif" N="521"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="244"> &yogh;ow [2894] &para; For Salamon sai&thorn; &thorn;at he &thorn;at repreue&thorn; him &thorn;at doth folie; [2895] he schal fynde gretter grace &thorn;an he &thorn;at deceyueth him by swete wordes</P>
<P>[2896] &para; Thanne sayde dame prudence I make no semblant of wra&thorn;&thorn;e ne of anger but for &yogh;oure grete profyt [2897] &para; For Salamon saith . he is more worth &thorn;at re|proue&thorn; or chyde&thorn; a fool for his folie schewynge him semblant of wra&thorn;&thorn;e [2898] &thorn;an he &thorn;at supporte&thorn; him and prayse&thorn; him in his mysdoyng . and laughe&thorn; at his folie [2899] &para; And &thorn;is same Salomon sai&thorn; afterward &thorn;at by &thorn;e sorweful visage of a man &thorn;at is to sayn by sory and heuy countenaunce of a man [2900] &thorn;e fool correcte&thorn; himself and amende&thorn;</P>
<P>[2901] &para; &thorn;anne sayde Melibeus. I schal not conne an|swere to so many resouns as &yogh;e putten to me and schewen. [2902] sayeth schortly &yogh;oure wille and &yogh;oure<MILESTONE N="223a" UNIT="folio">coun|seil. and I am al redy to fulfille and parfourme it</P>
<P>[2903] &para; Thanne dame prudence discouered al here coun|sail and hire wille vn-to him and sayde [2904] &para; I counseile &yogh;ow quod sche aboue alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at &yogh;e make pees bitwen god and &yogh;ow [2905] and be&thorn; reconsiled vnto him and to his grace. [2906] for I haue sayd &yogh;ow her biforn. God hath suffred &yogh;ow haue &thorn;is . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> disease for &yogh;oure synnes [2907] and if &yogh;e do as I say &yogh;ow god wol sende &yogh;oure aduersaries vnto &yogh;ow [2908] and make hem falle at &yogh;oure feet al redy to doo &yogh;oure wille and &yogh;oure co|maundement [2909] &para; For Salamon saith. whan &thorn;e con|dicioun of man is plesant and likyng to god; [2910] he chaunge&thorn; &thorn;e hertes of &thorn;e mannes aduersaries and con|streigne&thorn; hem to biseke him of pees &amp; of grace. [2911] and I pray &yogh;ow let me speke wi&thorn; &yogh;oure aduersaries in priue place [2912] for &thorn;ay schul not knowe it by &yogh;oure wille or &yogh;oure assent [2913] &para; And &thorn;anne whan I knowe here wille and here assent; I may counseile &yogh;ow &thorn;e more seurly</P>
<P>[2914] &para; Dame quod Melibeus do&thorn; &yogh;oure wille and 
<PB REF="00000534.tif" N="522"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="245"> &yogh;oure likyng [2915] For I putte me holly in &yogh;oure disposicioun and ordinaunce</P>
<P>[2916] &para; Thanne Dame prudence whan sche seih &thorn;e good wille of hir housbond . sche deliuered and took a vis by hir self [2917] &thorn;enkynge how sche mighte bringe &thorn;is neede vnto a good conclusioun and to a good ende [2918] &para; And whan sche saugh hire tyme; sche sente for &thorn;ese aduersaries to come vnto hire in to a priue place [2919] and schewed wysly vnto hem &thorn;e grete goddes &thorn;at comen of pees [2920] and &thorn;e grete harmes and perils &thorn;at ben in werre [2921] and sayde to hem in goodly manere how &thorn;at hem aughte to haue gret re|pentaunce [2922] of &thorn;e iniurie &amp; wrong &thorn;at &thorn;ay hadde doon to Melibe hire lord and vnto hire and hire dou&yogh;ter.</P>
<P>[2923] and whan &thorn;ay herden &thorn;e goodly wordes of dame prudence [2924] &thorn;ey were &thorn;o surprised and rauyssched and hadden so gret ioye of hire &thorn;at wonder was to telle [2925] &para; A lady quod thay . &yogh;e haue schewed vnto vs &thorn;e blessyng of swetnes after &thorn;e sawe of Dauid &thorn;e prophete [2926] for &thorn;e recounsilyng which we be nou&yogh;t wor&thorn;y to haue in no manere. [2927] But we oughten require it wi&thorn; gret contricioun and humilite. [2928] &yogh;e of &yogh;oure grete goodnes haue presented vnto vs [2929] &para; Now we se wel &thorn;at &thorn;e science of Salamon is ful trewe [2930] he saith &thorn;at swete wordes multiplien and encrescen frendes and maken schrewes to ben debonaire and meke.</P>
<P>[2931] certes quod &thorn;ay we putten oure deede and al oure matier and cause al holly in &yogh;oure good wille [2932] and ben redy to obeye to &thorn;e speche <MILESTONE N="223b" UNIT="folio">and to &thorn;e comaundement of my lord Melibe. [2933] and &thorn;erfore deere &amp; benigne lady we pray &yogh;ow and byseke &yogh;ow as meekely as we conne and may [2934] &thorn;at it like to &yogh;owre grete goodnes to fulfille in deede &yogh;oure good|liche wordes. [2935] For we considere and knowleche wel 
<PB REF="00000535.tif" N="523"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="246"> &thorn;at we haue offended and greued my lord Melibe out of resoun and out of mesure [2936] so ferforth &thorn;at we ben nou&yogh;t/ of power to make his amendes. [2937] and &thorn;erfore we oblie vs and bynde vs and oure frendes for to doo al his wille and his comaundement&yogh;. [2938] But perauenture he ha&thorn; such heuynes &amp; such wra&thorn;&thorn;e to vs ward by cause of oure offence; [2939] &thorn;at he wol enioyne vs such peyne as we mow not bere ne susteyne [2940] &para; and &thorn;erfore noble lady we biseke to &yogh;oure wommanly pite [2941] to take such auysement in &thorn;is neede &thorn;at we ne oure frendes ben not disherited and destroyed &thorn;urgh oure folye</P>
<P>[2942] &para; Certes quod dame prudence it is an hard &thorn;ing and right a perilous [2943] &thorn;at a man put him al outrely in &thorn;e arbitracioun and Iuggement and &thorn;e might and power of his enemyes [2944] &para; For Salamon sai&thorn; leeue&thorn; and &yogh;iueth credence to &thorn;at &thorn;at I schal say. I say quod he &yogh;eue poeple and gouernours of holy chirche [2945] to &thorn;y sone to &thorn;i wyf/. and to &thorn;y frend ne to &thorn;y brother [2946] ne &yogh;eue &thorn;ou neuer might ne maystry of &thorn;y body whil &thorn;ou lyuest [2947] &para; Now sith he defendith a man schulde not &yogh;iue to his bro&thorn;er ne to his frend &thorn;e might of his body. [2948] by a strenger resoun he defende&thorn; and forbedith a man to &yogh;iue his body to his enemye. [2949] but na&thorn;e|les I counseile &yogh;ow &thorn;at &yogh;e mystruste nou&yogh;t my lord. [2950] For I wot wel and knowe verraily &thorn;at he is debonaire and meke. large curteys [2951] and no &thorn;ing desirous ne coueytous of good ne richesse. [2952] For &thorn;er nys no &thorn;ing in &thorn;is world &thorn;at he desireth saue oonly worschipe and honour. [2953] For&thorn;ermore I knowe and am right seure &thorn;at he wol no &thorn;ing doo in &thorn;is neede wi&thorn;oute counsail of me [2954] and I schal so worche in this cause &thorn;at by &thorn;e grace of oure lord god &yogh;e schul be recounsiled vnto vs</P>
<P>[2955] &para; Thanne sayde &thorn;ay with oon voys worschipful 
<PB REF="00000536.tif" N="524"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="247"> lady we putte vs and oure goodes al fully in &yogh;oure wille and disposicioun [2956] and ben redy to come what day &thorn;at it like &yogh;ow and vnto &yogh;oure noblesse / to limite vs or assigne vs [2957] for to make oure obligacioun and bond as strong as it like&thorn; to &yogh;oure goodnes [2958] &thorn;at we mowe fulfille &thorn;e wille of &yogh;ow and of my lord Melibe</P>
<P>[2959] &para; whan dame prudence had <MILESTONE N="224a" UNIT="folio">herd &thorn;e an|sweres of &thorn;ise men. sche bad hem go agayn pryuely [2960] and sche retourned to hir lord Melibe and tolde him how sche fond his aduersaries ful repentant [2961] knowlechinge ful lowely here synnes and trespasses and how &thorn;ay were redy to suffre alle peyne [2962] requiring and praying him of mercy and pite</P>
<P>[2963] &para; &thorn;anne saide Melibeus. he is wel wor&thorn;y to haue pardoun and for&yogh;euenes of his synne &thorn;at excusith not his synne [2964] but knowleche&thorn; and repentith him axinge indulgence. [2965] For Senek saith. &thorn;ere is &thorn;e remissioun and for&yogh;euenesse wher as &thorn;e confessioun is [2966] &para; For confessioun is neighebor to Innocence [2967] And he saith in ano&thorn;er place. he &thorn;at hath schame of his synne knowlechith it/ . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> and &thorn;erfore I assente and conferme me to haue pees. [2968] but it is good &thorn;at we doo it nou&yogh;t wi&thorn;oute assent &amp; &thorn;e wille of oure frendes</P>
<P>[2969] &para; Thanne was prudence right glad &amp; iolyf and sayde. [2970] Certes sire quod sche &yogh;e ben wel and goodly auysed. [2971] for right as by &thorn;e counsail and assent and help of &yogh;oure frendes &yogh;e haue be stired to venge &yogh;ow &amp; make werre; [2972] Right so wi&thorn;|oute here counseil schul &yogh;e nought acorde &yogh;ow ne haue pees wi&thorn; &yogh;oure aduersaries. [2973] For &thorn;e lawe saith. Ther nys no &thorn;ing so good by way of kinde as &thorn;ing to be vnbounde by him &thorn;at it was bounde</P>
<P>[2974] And &thorn;anne dame prudence wi&thorn;oute delay or taryinge sente anoon messageres for here kyn and for here olde frendes whiche &thorn;at were trewe and wyse [2975] 
<PB REF="00000537.tif" N="525"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="248"> and tolde hem by ordre in &thorn;e presence of Melibe of &thorn;is matier as it is aboue expressed and declared [2976] and praide hem &thorn;at &thorn;ay wolde &yogh;iue here avys and coun|seil what best were to doon in &thorn;is matiere [2977] &para; And whan melibeus frendes hadde take here auys and deliber|acioun of &thorn;e forsayde matier [2978] and hadden examyned it by greet besynes and gret diligence [2979] &thorn;ey &yogh;afe him ful counsail to haue pees and reste. [2980] and &thorn;at Melibeus schulde wi&thorn; good hert resceyue his aduersaries to for&yogh;iuenes and mercy</P>
<P>[2981] &para; And whan dame prudence had herd thassent of hir lord Melibeus and counseil of his frendes [2982] accorde wi&thorn; hire wille &amp; hire entencioun; [2983] sche was wonderly glad in herte and sayde [2984] &para; Ther is a noble prouerbe &thorn;at saith &para; The goodnesse &thorn;at &thorn;ou maist do &thorn;is day; [2985] abyde not ne delaye it nou&yogh;t/ vnto to morwe. [2986] and &thorn;erfore I counseile &yogh;ow &yogh;e sende &yogh;oure messageres <MILESTONE N="224b" UNIT="folio">whiche &thorn;at ben discrete and wise [2987] vnto &yogh;oure aduersaries tellynge hem on &yogh;oure bihalue [2988] &thorn;at if &thorn;ay wol trete of pees and of accord [2989] &thorn;at &thorn;ay schape hem wi&thorn;oute dilay or taryinge to come vnto vs. [2990] which &thorn;ing was parformed in dede [2991] and whan &thorn;ese trespasours and repentynge folk/ of here folies &thorn;at is to sayn &thorn;e aduersaries of Melibe [2992] hadden herd what &thorn;e messangeres sayden vnto hem; [2993] &thorn;ay were right glad and iolif and answerden ful mekely and benignely [2994] &yogh;eldynge graces &amp; &thorn;ankinges to here lord Melibe and to al his compaignye [2995] and schope hem wi&thorn;out delay to go wi&thorn; &thorn;e messangeres and obeye hem to &thorn;e comaundement of here lord Melibe</P>
<P>[2996] &para; And right anoon &thorn;ay token here way to &thorn;e court of Melibe / [2997] and token wi&thorn; hem some of here trewe frendes to make faith for hem and for to ben here borwes [2998] &para; And whan &thorn;ay were comen to 
<PB REF="00000538.tif" N="526"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="249"> &thorn;e presence of Melibeus he seyde hem &thorn;ise wordes [2999] &para; It stondith &thorn;us quod Melibeus and so&thorn; it is &thorn;at &yogh;e [3000] causeles and wi&thorn;outen skile and resoun [3001] haue doon gret iniuries and wronges to me and to my wyf prudence and to my dou&yogh;ter also. [3002] For &yogh;e haue entred in to myn hous by violence [3003] and haue doon such outrage &thorn;at alle men knowe wel &thorn;at &yogh;e haue deserued &thorn;e deth. [3004] And &thorn;erfore wil I knowe and wite of &yogh;ow [3005] whe&thorn;er &yogh;e wol putte &thorn;e punyschment and &thorn;e chastisement and &thorn;e vengeaunce/ of &thorn;is outrage in &thorn;e wille of me and of my wif dame prudence or &yogh;e wil not</P>
<P>[3006] &para; &THORN;anne &thorn;e wisest of hem &thorn;re answerde for hem alle &amp; sayde [3007] &para; Sire quod he we knowe wel &thorn;at we be vnwor&thorn;y to come to &thorn;e court of so gret a lord and so wor&thorn;y as &yogh;e be [3008] &para; For we han so gretly mystake vs and haue offendid and giltid in such a wise ageins &yogh;oure heighe lordschipe [3009] &thorn;at trewely we haue deserued &thorn;e de&thorn; [3010] &para; But &yogh;it/ for &thorn;e greete goodnes and debonairete &thorn;at al &thorn;e world witnesse&thorn; of &yogh;oure persone; [3011] we submitten vs to &thorn;in excellence and benignite of &yogh;oure gracious lordschipe [3012] and ben redy to obeye to alle &yogh;oure comaundement&yogh; [3013] bisekynge &yogh;ow &thorn;at of &yogh;oure merciable pite &yogh;e wol considre oure grete repentaunce and lowe submissioun [3014] and graunte vs for&yogh;iuenes of oure outrage trespas and offence. [3015] For wel &yogh;e knowen &thorn;at &yogh;oure liberal grace and mercy strechen for&thorn;ere in to good|nesse &thorn;an do&thorn; oure outrage gilt and trespas in to wikkednes [3016] al be it &thorn;at cursedly &amp; damp|nably we <MILESTONE N="225a" UNIT="folio">haue agilt a&yogh;einst &yogh;oure highe lordschipe</P>
<P>[3017] &para; Thanne Melibe took hem vp fro &thorn;e ground ful benignely [3018] and resceyued here obligaciouns and here londes by here o&thorn;es vpon here plegges &amp; borwes [3019] and assigned hem a certeyn day to retourne vnto his court [3020] for to accepte and receyue &thorn;e sentence and 
<PB REF="00000539.tif" N="527"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="250"> iuggement &thorn;at Melibe wolde comaunde to be doon on hem by &thorn;ese causes aforn sayde. [3021] which &thorn;ing ordeyned; euery man retourned home to his hous</P>
<P>[3022] &para; And whan &thorn;at Dame prudence saugh hire tyme; sche feyned and axed hire lord Melibe [3023] what vengeance he &thorn;oughte to take vpon his aduersaries.</P>
<P>[3024] to which Melibeus answerd and saide. Certes quod he I &thorn;enke and purpose me fully [3025] to dis|herite hem of al &thorn;at euer &thorn;ay haue and for to putte hem in exil for euermore</P>
<P>[3026] Certes quod dame prudence &thorn;is were a cruel sentence and mochil a&yogh;einst resoun [3027] For &yogh;e ben riche ynough &amp; haue noon neede of o&thorn;er mennes good [3028] and &yogh;e mighte lightly gete &yogh;ow a coueitous name [3029] which is vicious &thorn;ing and oughte to ben eschewed of euery man [3030] for after &thorn;e sawe of &thorn;e word of &thorn;apostil; Couetise is roote of alle harmes. [3031] And &thorn;erfore it were bettre for &yogh;ow to lese so moche good of &yogh;oure oughne &thorn;an for to take of here good in &thorn;is manere. [3032] For bettir it is to lese good wi&thorn; worschipe &thorn;an it is to wynne good with vilonye and schame. [3033] and euer a man oughte to do his diligence and his busynesse to gete him a good name. [3034] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> [3035] but he schulde enforce him alway to do som &thorn;ing by which he may renouele his good name. [3036] for it is writen &thorn;at &thorn;e olde goode loos of a man is soone doon or goon and passed whan it is not newed ne re|noueled. [3037] And as touchinge &thorn;at &yogh;e sayn &thorn;at &yogh;e wol exile &yogh;oure aduersaries; [3038] &thorn;at &thorn;inketh me mochil a&yogh;einst resoun and out of mesure [3039] con|sideri&thorn; &thorn;e power &thorn;at &thorn;ay han &yogh;yue to &yogh;ow vpon here body and on hemself [3040] &para; And it is writen &thorn;at he is wor&thorn;y to lese his priuelege &thorn;at mys vseth &thorn;e might and &thorn;e power &thorn;at is &yogh;eue to him [3041] &para; And &yogh;it I sette &thorn;e caas &yogh;e mighte en|ioyne hem &thorn;at peyne by right and lawe [3042] which I 
<PB REF="00000540.tif" N="528"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="251"> trowe &yogh;e mow nou&yogh;t do [3043] I say &yogh;e mighte nou&yogh;t putte it to execucioun perauenture [3044] and &thorn;anne were it likly to torne to &thorn;e werre as it was biforn [3045] And &thorn;erfore if &yogh;e wol &thorn;at men do &yogh;ow obeis|saunce; &yogh;e moste deme more curteisly [3046] &thorn;is is to sayn. &yogh;e moste &yogh;iue more esyere sentence &amp; iuggement [3047] &para; For <MILESTONE N="225b" UNIT="folio">it is writen. he &thorn;at most curteysly comaundeth to him men most obeyen. [3048] and &thorn;er|fore I pray &yogh;ow &thorn;at in &thorn;is necessite and in &thorn;is neede &yogh;e caste &yogh;ow to ouercome &yogh;oure herte [3049] &para; For Senek sai&thorn;. he &thorn;at ouercome&thorn; his herte ouercome&thorn; twyes [3050] &para; And thullius saith. &thorn;er is no &thorn;ing so comendable in a gret lord [3051] as whan he is debon|aire and meeke and appesith him li&yogh;tly [3052] &para; And I pray &yogh;ow &thorn;at &yogh;e wol forbere now to do vengeaunce [3053] in such a manere &thorn;at &yogh;oure goode name may be kept/ &amp; conserued. [3054] and &thorn;at men mowe haue cause / and matiere to prayse &yogh;ow of pite and of mercy [3055] and &thorn;at &yogh;e haue noon cause to repente &yogh;ow of &thorn;ing &thorn;at &yogh;e doon [3056] &para; For senec saith &para; he ouercome&thorn; in an euel manere &thorn;at repente&thorn; him of his victorie [3057] &para; wher|fore I pray &yogh;ow let mercy be in &yogh;oure herte [3058] to theffect and thentent &thorn;at god almighty haue mercy and pite vpon &yogh;ow in his laste iuggement [3059] &para; For seint Iame saith in his Epistil; Iuggement wi&thorn; oute mercy schal be doon to him &thorn;at ha&thorn; no mercy vpon another wight</P>
<P>[3060] whan Melibe had herd &thorn;e grete skiles and resouns of dame prudens and wys informacioun and techynge; [3061] his herte gan enclyne to &thorn;e wille of his wyf consideryng hir trewe entent; [3062] con|fermed him anoon and consented fully to werke after hir reed and counseil [3063] &para; And &thorn;ankid god of whom pro|cedeth al goodnes &thorn;at him sente a wif of so gret discrecioun [3064] &para; And whan &thorn;e day cam &thorn;at his aduer|saries schulden appere in his presence; [3065] he spak 
<PB REF="00000541.tif" N="529"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="252"> ful goodly and sayde in &thorn;is wise. [3066] &para; Al be it so &thorn;at of &yogh;oure pryde and heigh presumpcioun and folye and of &yogh;oure negligence/ and vnconnynge [3067] &yogh;e haue mys-bore &yogh;ow and trespassed vnto me; [3068] &yogh;it/ for as moche as I se and biholde &yogh;oure humilite [3069] &thorn;at &yogh;e ben sory and repentaunt of &yogh;oure giltes; [3070] hit constreigneth me to do &yogh;ow grace. and mercy. [3071] wherfore I receyue &yogh;ow to my grace [3072] and for&yogh;eue &yogh;ow outerly alle &thorn;e offenses iniuries and wronges &thorn;at &yogh;e haue don to me and agayns me and myne / [3073] this is &thorn;effect &amp; to &thorn;is ende &thorn;at god of his endeles mercy [3074] wole at &thorn;e tyme of oure deyinge for&yogh;iue vs oure giltes &thorn;at we haue trespased to him in &thorn;is wrecched world. [3075] for douteles &amp; we ben sory &amp; repentaunt of &thorn;e synnes &amp; giltes whiche we haue trespassed Inne in &thorn;e sight of oure lord god; [3076] he is so free and <MILESTONE N="226a" UNIT="folio">so merci|able [3077] &thorn;at he wil for&yogh;iue vs oure gultes [3078] and bringe vs to &thorn;e blisse &thorn;at neuer ha&thorn; ende AmeN</P>
<TRAILER>&para; Here endith Chaucer his tale of Melibe</TRAILER>
