<PB REF="00000542.tif" N="530">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="253">
<HEAD>&para; And here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e monkes tale /<NOTE PLACE="head">[Break of one line in the MS.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3079">Whan ended was my tale of Melibe</L>
<L>And of prudence and hire benignite</L>
<L>Oure hoste sayde as I am faithful man</L>
<L>And by &thorn;e precious corpus Madryan</L>
<L>I hadde leuer &thorn;an a barel ale</L>
<L N="3084">That godeleef my wyf had herd &thorn;is tale</L>
<L>For sche is no &thorn;ing of such pacience</L>
<L>As was &thorn;is melibeus wyf dame prudence</L>
<L>By goddes boones whan I bete my knaues</L>
<L N="3088">Sche bringeth me forth &thorn;e grete clobbet staues</L>
<L>And crie&thorn; slee &thorn;e dogges euerychon</L>
<L>And breke of hem bo&thorn;e bak and bon</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at eny neghebour of myne</L>
<L N="3092">wol nought to my wyf in chirche enclyne</L>
<L>Or be so hardy to hir to trespace</L>
<L>whan sche com&thorn; hom sche rampeth in my face</L>
<L>And crie&thorn; false coward wreke &thorn;y wyf</L>
<L N="3096">By Corpes bones I wil haue &thorn;y knyf</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou schalt/ haue my distaf and go spynne</L>
<L>Fro day to night &thorn;us sche wil bygynne /</L>
<L>Allas sche saith &thorn;at euer I was I-schape</L>
<L N="3100">To wedde a mylk-sop or a coward ape</L>
<L>That wil be ouer-lad wi&thorn; euery wight</L>
<L>&thorn;ou darst nought stonde by &thorn;y wyues right</L>
<L>This is my lif but if &thorn;at I wil fight</L>
<L N="3104">And out atte dore anoon I most me dight /</L>
<L>And ellis I am lost / but if &thorn;at I</L>
<L>Be lik a wilde leoun fool-hardy</L>
<L>I wot wel sche wol do me sle som day</L>
<L N="3108">Som neighebor and &thorn;anne renne away</L>
<L>For I am perilous with knyf in honde</L>
<L>Al be it &thorn;at I dar not hir wi&thorn;-stonde
<PB REF="00000543.tif" N="531"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="254"></L>
<L N="3111">For sche is big in armes by my faith</L>
<L>That schal he fynde &thorn;at hire mys doth or saith<MILESTONE N="226b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But let vs passe a way fro &thorn;is matiere</L>
<L>My lord &thorn;e monk quod he be mery of chere /</L>
<L>For &yogh;e schul telle a tale trewely</L>
<L N="3116">Lo Rowchestre stant heer faste by</L>
<L>Ryde for&thorn; myn oughne lord brek nou&yogh;t oure game</L>
<L>But by my trou&thorn;e I can not &yogh;oure name</L>
<L>whether schal I calle &yogh;ow my lord dan Iohn</L>
<L N="3120">Or da&umacr;n Thomas or elles dan albon</L>
<L>Of what hous be &yogh;e by &yogh;our fader kyn</L>
<L>I vow to god &thorn;ou hast a ful fair skyn</L>
<L>It is a gentil pasture &thorn;er &thorn;ou gost</L>
<L N="3124">Thow art not lik a penaunt or a goost</L>
<L>vpon my faith &thorn;ou art an officer</L>
<L>Som wor&thorn;y sexteyn or som Celerer</L>
<L>For by my fader soule as to my doome</L>
<L N="3128">Thou art an officer whan &thorn;ou art at hoom</L>
<L>No pouer cloysterer ne non nouys</L>
<L>But a gouernour wily and wys</L>
<L>And &thorn;er wi&thorn; al of brawne and of bones</L>
<L N="3132">A wel faryng persone for &thorn;e noones</L>
<L>I praye god &yogh;iue him confusioun</L>
<L>&THORN;at first/ &thorn;e brou&yogh;te to religioun</L>
<L>Thow woldist han be a tredefoul aright</L>
<L N="3136">haddist &thorn;ou as gret a leue as might</L>
<L>To parforme al &thorn;i wil in engendrure</L>
<L>Thow haddist bigeten many a creature</L>
<L>Allas why werest &thorn;ou so wyd a cope</L>
<L N="3140">God &yogh;if me sorwe and I were a pope</L>
<L>Nought only &thorn;ou but euery mighty man</L>
<L>Though he were schore brode vpon his pan</L>
<L>Schuld han a wif for al &thorn;is world is lorn</L>
<L N="3144">Religioun hath take vp al &thorn;e corn</L>
<L>Of tredyng and we burel men ben schrympes</L>
<L>Of feble trees &thorn;er come&thorn; feble ympes
<PB REF="00000544.tif" N="532"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="255"></L>
<L>This maki&thorn; &thorn;at oure heires ben so sclender</L>
<L N="3148">And feble &thorn;at &thorn;ay may not wel engender</L>
<L>This make&thorn; &thorn;at our wyfes wol assaye</L>
<L>Religious folk for &thorn;ay may bettre paye<MILESTONE N="227a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of venus payementes &thorn;an may we</L>
<L N="3152">God woot no lusscheburghes paye &yogh;e /</L>
<L>be&thorn; nou&yogh;t wro&thorn; my lorde &thorn;ough I play</L>
<L>For oft in game a soth I haue herd say</L>
<L>This wor&thorn;y monk took al in pacience /</L>
<L N="3156">And saide I wol doon al my diligence</L>
<L>Als fer as soune&thorn; in to honeste /</L>
<L>To telle &yogh;ow a tale or tuo or &thorn;re</L>
<L>And if &yogh;ow lust to herken hiderward</L>
<L N="3160">I wil &yogh;ow say &thorn;e lif of seint Edward</L>
<L>Or elles first tredis wil I &yogh;ow telle /</L>
<L>Of which I haue an hundred in my celle /</L>
<L>Tregedis is to sayn a certeyn storie</L>
<L N="3164">As olde bookes maken vs memorie</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at stood in greet prosperite</L>
<L>And is fallen out of heigh degre</L>
<L>In to miserie and endith wrecchedly</L>
<L N="3168">And &thorn;ay ben versifyed comunly</L>
<L>Of six feet which men clepe exametron</L>
<L>In prose ben eek endited many oon</L>
<L>And in metre eek and in sondry wise</L>
<L N="3172">Lo &thorn;is declaryng ought ynough suffise /</L>
<L>Now herkne&thorn; if &yogh;ow likith for to heere</L>
<L>But first I &yogh;ow biseche in &thorn;is matiere /</L>
<L>&thorn;ough I by ordre telle not &thorn;ise &thorn;inges</L>
<L N="3176">Be it of popes emperours or kynges</L>
<L>After her age as men may write fynde</L>
<L>But telle hem som bifore. and som byhynde /</L>
<L>As it come&thorn; now / to my remembraunce</L>
<L N="3180">haue&thorn; me excused of myn ignoraunce<NOTE PLACE="end">[Break of one line in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">


<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000545.tif" N="533">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="256">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Iwol bywaile in maner of tregedye</L>
<L>The harm of hem &thorn;at stood in heigh degre</L>
<L>And fallen so &thorn;e is no remedye</L>
<L N="3184">To bring hem out of her aduersite</L>
<L>For certeynly whan fortune lust to flee</L>
<L>Ther may no man &thorn;e cours of hir whiel holde</L>
<L>let no man truste in blynd prosperite<MILESTONE N="227b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3188">Be&thorn; war by &thorn;ese ensamples trewe and olde /<NOTE PLACE="end">[No stanza-breaks in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Lucifer.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT lucifer &thorn;ough he an aungil were<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; <B>Lucifer</B></NOTE></L>
<L>And no man at/ him wil I bygynne</L>
<L>For &thorn;ough fortune may non aungel dere</L>
<L N="3192">From heigh degre &yogh;it/ fel he for his synne</L>
<L>Doun in to helle. wher he &yogh;et is Inne</L>
<L>O lucifer brightest of aungels alle</L>
<L>Now art &thorn;ou Sathanas &thorn;at maist nou&yogh;t twynne</L>
<L N="3196">Out of miserie in which &thorn;ou art falle</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Adam.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lo adam in &thorn;e feld of Damassene<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; <B>Adam</B></NOTE></L>
<L>wi&thorn; goddes oughne fynger wrought was he /</L>
<L>And nought bigeten of mannes sperma vnclene</L>
<L N="3200">And welt al paradys sauyng oon tre</L>
<L>had neuer worldly man suche degre</L>
<L>As adam til he for mys gouernance</L>
<L>was dryuen out of heigh prosperite</L>
<L N="3204">To labour and to helle and to meschaunce
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000546.tif" N="534"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="257">
<HEAD>[Sampson.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lo Sampson . &thorn;at was annunciate<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Sampson</NOTE></L>
<L>By &thorn;angel long er his natiuite /</L>
<L>And was to god almighty consecrate</L>
<L N="3208">And stood in nobles whil &thorn;at he might se</L>
<L>was neuer such ano&thorn;er as was he</L>
<L>To speke of streng&thorn; . and &thorn;erto hardynesse</L>
<L>But to his wyfes tolde he his secre</L>
<L N="3212">Thurgh which he slough himself for wrecchidnesse /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="3216">. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="3220">. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thre hundred foxis . tok Sampson for Ire</L>
<L>And alle her tayles he togider bond</L>
<L>And sette &thorn;e foxes tailes alle on fuyre</L>
<L N="3224">For he in euery tail hath knyt a brond</L>
<L>And &thorn;ay brent alle &thorn;e cornes of &thorn;at lond</L>
<L>And alle her Olyuers . and vynes eeke</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand men he slough eek wi&thorn; his hond</L>
<L N="3228">And hadde no wepen but an asses cheeke</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan &thorn;ay were slayn so &thorn;ursted him &thorn;at he</L>
<L>was wel ner lorn for which he gan to preye</L>
<L>That god wolde of his peyne haue som pite</L>
<L N="3232">And send him drynk and elles most he deye</L>
<L>And out of his asses cheke &thorn;at was so dreye<MILESTONE N="228a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Out of a woung to&thorn; sprong anon a welle</L>
<L>Of which he dronk ynough schortly to seye</L>
<L N="3236">Thus halp him god as Iudicum can telle
<PB REF="00000547.tif" N="535"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="258"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>By verray fors of algason on a night</L>
<L>Maugre &thorn;e philistiens of &thorn;at cite</L>
<L>The gates of &thorn;e toun he ha&thorn; vp plight/</L>
<L N="3240">And on his bak caried hem ha&thorn; he /</L>
<L>heigh vpon an hil wher men might hem se /</L>
<L>O noble almighty Sampson leef and deere</L>
<L>haddest &thorn;ou nought to wommen told &thorn;y secre</L>
<L N="3244">In al &thorn;e world ne hadde be &thorn;y peere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This sampson neyther siser dronk ne wyn /</L>
<L>Ne on his heed com rasour noon ne schere</L>
<L>By precept of &thorn;e messager diuyn</L>
<L N="3248">For alle his streng&thorn;es in his heres were</L>
<L>And fully twenty wynter &yogh;er by &yogh;ere/</L>
<L>he hadde of Ierusalem &thorn;e gouernaunce</L>
<L>But soone he schal wepe many a teere</L>
<L N="3252">For wymmen schuln him bringe to meschaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vn-to his lemman Dalida he tolde</L>
<L>That in his heres al his streng&thorn;e lay</L>
<L>And falsly to his foomen sche him solde</L>
<L N="3256">And slepyng in hir barm vpon a day</L>
<L>Sche made to clippe or schere his heres away</L>
<L>And made his foomen al his craft espien</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;ay fond him in &thorn;is array</L>
<L N="3260">Thay bound him fast and put out bo&thorn;e his yen</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But er his heer clipped was or I-schaue</L>
<L>Ther was no bond wi&thorn; which men might him bynde</L>
<L>But now is he in prisoun in a caue</L>
<L N="3264">Ther as &thorn;ay made him at &thorn;e querne grynde</L>
<L>O noble Sampson strengest of al man kynde</L>
<L>O whilom iugge in glory and in richesse /</L>
<L>Now maystow wepe wi&thorn; &thorn;ine ey&yogh;en blynde</L>
<L N="3268">Sith &thorn;ou fro wele art falle to wrecchednesse
<PB REF="00000548.tif" N="536"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="259"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thend of &thorn;is caytif was as I schal say</L>
<L>his foomen made a fest vpon a day</L>
<L>And made him as here fool biforn hem play<MILESTONE N="228b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3272">And &thorn;is was in a temple of gret array</L>
<L>But/ atte last he made a foul affray</L>
<L>For he two pilers schook and made hem falle</L>
<L>And doun fel temple and al and &thorn;er it lay</L>
<L N="3276">And slough himsilf and eek his fomen alle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This is to sayn &thorn;e princes euer ichon</L>
<L>And eek &thorn;re &thorn;ousand bodies were &thorn;er slayn</L>
<L>with fallyng of &thorn;e grete temple of stoon</L>
<L N="3280">Of Sampson wil I no more sayn</L>
<L>Be war by &thorn;ese ensamples olde and playn</L>
<L>That no man telle his counseil to his wyf</L>
<L>Of such &thorn;ing as he wold haue secre fayn</L>
<L N="3284">If/ &thorn;at/ it touche his lymes or his lif</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Hercules.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of Ercules &thorn;e souereyn conquerour<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Ercule</NOTE></L>
<L>Singing his werkes laude and heigh renoun</L>
<L>For in his tyme of strength he bar &thorn;e flour</L>
<L N="3288">he slough and rafte &thorn;e skyn fro &thorn;e leoun</L>
<L>he of Centaures layde &thorn;e bost a doun</L>
<L>he arpies slough &thorn;e cruel briddes felle</L>
<L>The gold appul he raft fro &thorn;e dragoun</L>
<L N="3292">he drof out cerbures &thorn;e fend of helle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He slough &thorn;e cruel tyrant bupherus</L>
<L>And made his hors to frete him fleisch and boon</L>
<L>he slough &thorn;e verray serpent venencus</L>
<L N="3296">Of Adiloyus tuo hornes he raft oon</L>
<L>he slough Catus in a caue of stoon</L>
<L>he slough &thorn;e geaunt adeus &thorn;e stronge</L>
<L>he slough &thorn;e grisly leoun and &thorn;at anoon</L>
<L N="3300">And bar &thorn;e heed vpon his necke longe
<PB REF="00000549.tif" N="537"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="260"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Was neuer wight / si&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;e world bigan</L>
<L>That slough so many monstres as dede he</L>
<L>Thurgh-out &thorn;e wide world his name ran</L>
<L N="3304">what for his streng&thorn;e and for his bounte</L>
<L>And euery roialme went he for to se</L>
<L>he was so strong &thorn;er might no man him lette</L>
<L>At bo&thorn;e &thorn;e worldes endes as saith trophe</L>
<L N="3308">In stede of boundes he a piler sette</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A lemman hadde &thorn;is noble campioun<MILESTONE N="229a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That highte Deianire freissh as may</L>
<L>And as &thorn;ese clerkes maken mencioun</L>
<L N="3312">Sche ha&thorn; him sent a schurte fresch and gay</L>
<L>Alas &thorn;is schirt allas and wailaway</L>
<L>Enuenymed was so&thorn;ly with alle</L>
<L>That er he hadde wered it half a day</L>
<L N="3316">It made his fleisch al fro his bones falle /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But natheles som clerkes hir excusen</L>
<L>By oon &thorn;at highte Nessus &thorn;at it makyd</L>
<L>Be as be may I wil nou&yogh;t hir accusyn</L>
<L N="3320">But on his bak/ he wered &thorn;is schirt al naked</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at his fleisch was for &thorn;e venym blaked</L>
<L>And whan he saugh noon o&thorn;er remedye</L>
<L>In hote colis he ha&thorn; himself I-raked</L>
<L N="3324">For no venym deyned him to dye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thus starf &thorn;is mighty and worthy Ercules</L>
<L>lo who may truste fortune eny &thorn;rowe</L>
<L>For him &thorn;at folwe&thorn; al &thorn;is world of pres</L>
<L N="3328">Er he be war is oft y-layd ful lowe /</L>
<L>Ful wys is he &thorn;at/ can himseluen knowe /</L>
<L>Be war for whan &thorn;at fortune lust to glose /</L>
<L>Than waytith sche hir man to ouer&thorn;rowe /</L>
<L N="3332">By suche way as he wolde lest suppose
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000550.tif" N="538"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="261">
<HEAD>[Nebuchadnezzar.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The mighty trone &thorn;e precious tresor<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De rege Nabugodonosor</NOTE></L>
<L>The glorious ceptre and real mageste</L>
<L>That had &thorn;e king Nabugodonosore</L>
<L N="3336">wi&thorn; tonge vnnethes may descryued be</L>
<L>he twyes wan ierusalem &thorn;at Cite</L>
<L>The vessel out of &thorn;e temple he wi&thorn; him ladde /<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Danielis 4<SUP>to</SUP> regum &amp;c</NOTE></L>
<L>At Babiloyne was his souereyn see</L>
<L N="3340">In which his glorie and his delyt he ladde /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The fairest children of &thorn;e blood roial</L>
<L>Of Israel he dede gelde anoon</L>
<L>And made ylk of hem to ben his &thorn;ral</L>
<L N="3344">Amonges o&thorn;re Daniel was oon</L>
<L>That was &thorn;e wisest/ child of euerychoon</L>
<L>For he &thorn;e dremes of &thorn;e king expouned</L>
<L>Ther as in Caldeyn was &thorn;er clerkes noon<MILESTONE N="229b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3348">That wiste to what fyn his dremes souned</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This proude king let make a statu of gold</L>
<L>Sixty cubites long and seuen in brede</L>
<L>To which ymage bo&thorn;e &yogh;onge and olde /</L>
<L N="3352">Comaunded he to loue and haue in drede</L>
<L>Or in a fornays ful of flames rede</L>
<L>he schulde be brent &thorn;at wolde not obeye /</L>
<L>But neuer wolde assente to &thorn;at dede</L>
<L N="3356">Danyel ne his felawes tweye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This king of kinges preu was elate</L>
<L>he wende god &thorn;at sit in mageste</L>
<L>Ne might him nought / bireue of his estate</L>
<L N="3360">But sodeynly he left/ his dignite</L>
<L>I-lik a best him semed for to be</L>
<L>And eet hay as an oxe and lay &thorn;er-oute /</L>
<L>In rayn with wilde bestes walkyd he.</L>
<L>[til certein tyme was i-come aboute<NOTE PLACE="marg">[In margin, in a later hand.]</NOTE>]
<PB REF="00000551.tif" N="539"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="262"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And lik/ an Eglis fetheres were his heres</L>
<L>his hondes like a briddes clowes were</L>
<L>Til god relessed him a certeyn &yogh;eres</L>
<L N="3368">And &yogh;af him witte and &thorn;anne with many a tere</L>
<L>he &thorn;anked god and euer he is afere</L>
<L>To doon amys or more to trespace</L>
<L>And er &thorn;at tyme he layd was on bere</L>
<L N="3372">he knew wel god was ful of might and grace</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His sone which &thorn;at highte Baltha&yogh;ar</L>
<L>That huld &thorn;e regne after his fader day</L>
<L>he by his fader cou&thorn;e nought be war</L>
<L N="3376">For proud he was of hert/ and of array</L>
<L>And eek an ydolaster was he ay</L>
<L>his heigh astate assured him in pryde</L>
<L>But fortune cast him doun and &thorn;er he lay</L>
<L N="3380">And sodeynly his regne gan diuide</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A fest he made vnto his lordes alle</L>
<L>vpon a tyme he made hem bli&thorn;e be</L>
<L>And &thorn;an his officeres gan he calle</L>
<L N="3384">Go&thorn; bringeth forth &thorn;e vessealx quod he</L>
<L>The which my fader in his prosperite</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e temple of ierusalem byraft<MILESTONE N="230a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And to oure hihe goddis &thorn;anke we/</L>
<L N="3388">Of honours &thorn;at oure eldres with vs laft</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His wif his lordes and his concubines</L>
<L>Ay dronken whiles her arriont last</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is noble vesseals sondry wynes</L>
<L N="3392">And on a wal &thorn;is king his yhen cast /</L>
<L>And saugh an hond armles &thorn;at wroot fast /</L>
<L>For fere of which he quook and siked sore</L>
<L>&thorn;is hond &thorn;at baltha&yogh;ar so sore agast</L>
<L N="3396">wrot. mane. techel. phares. and no more /
<PB REF="00000552.tif" N="540"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="263"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In al &thorn;e lond magicien was noon</L>
<L>That cou&thorn;e expounde what &thorn;is lettre ment</L>
<L>But Daniel expoundi&thorn; it anoon</L>
<L N="3400">And sayde king god &thorn;y fader sent</L>
<L>Glori and honour. regne tresor and rent</L>
<L>And he was proud and no &thorn;ing god ne dredde</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfor god gret wreche vpon him sent</L>
<L N="3404">And him biraft &thorn;e regne &thorn;at he hadde /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He was out cast of mannes compaignye</L>
<L>with asses was his habitacioun</L>
<L>And eete hay in wet and eek in drye</L>
<L N="3408">Til &thorn;at he knew by grace and by resoun</L>
<L>That god of heuen had dominacioun</L>
<L>Ouer euery regne and euery creature</L>
<L>And &thorn;an had god of him compassioun</L>
<L N="3412">And him restored to his regne and his figure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Eke &thorn;ou &thorn;at art his sone art proud also</L>
<L>And knowest al &thorn;is &thorn;ing so verrayly</L>
<L>And art rebel to god and art his fo</L>
<L N="3416">&thorn;ou dronk eek of his vessel bodily</L>
<L>Thy wyf eek and &thorn;y wenche sinfully</L>
<L>Dronke of &thorn;e same vessel sondry wynes</L>
<L>And heriest false goddes cursedly</L>
<L N="3420">Therfore to &thorn;e schapen ful gret pyne es</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This hond was send fro god &thorn;at on &thorn;e wal</L>
<L>wrot. mane. techel. phares truste me</L>
<L>Thy regne is doon &thorn;ou weist nou&yogh;t at al</L>
<L N="3424">Diuidid is &thorn;y regne and it schal be<MILESTONE N="230b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To meedes and to perses &yogh;euen quod he</L>
<L>And &thorn;ilke same night &thorn;e king was slawe</L>
<L>And Darius occupied his degre</L>
<L N="3428">&thorn;ough &thorn;erto ney&thorn;er had he right ne lawe /
<PB REF="00000553.tif" N="541"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="264"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lordyngs ensample her-by may &yogh;e take</L>
<L>how &thorn;at in lordschip is no sikernesse</L>
<L>For whan fortune wil a man forsake</L>
<L N="3432">Sche bere&thorn; a-way his regne and his richesse /</L>
<L>And eek his frendes bo&thorn;e more and lesse /</L>
<L>And what man hath of frendes &thorn;e fortune</L>
<L>Mishap wil make hem enemyes I gesse</L>
<L>[&thorn;is prouerbe is ful soth &amp; ful comune<NOTE PLACE="marg">[In a later hand in the margin.]</NOTE>]<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Cenobia of palmire &thorn;e queene</L>
<L>As writen parciens of hir noblesse</L>
<L>So wor&thorn;y was in armes and so keene</L>
<L N="3440">That no wight passed hir in hardynesse</L>
<L>Ne in lynage ne in o&thorn;er gentilesse /</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e kinges blood / of pers sche is descendid</L>
<L>I say &thorn;at sche had not most/ fairnesse</L>
<L N="3444">But of hir schap sche might not ben amendid</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fro hir childhod / I fynde &thorn;at sche fledde</L>
<L>Office of wommen and to woode sche went</L>
<L>And many a wilde hertes blood sche schedde</L>
<L N="3448">with arwes brode &thorn;at sche to hem sent /</L>
<L>Sche was so swyft &thorn;at sche anoon hem hent</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at sche was elder sche wolde kille</L>
<L>Leouns / lebardes / and beres alto-rent</L>
<L N="3452">And in hir armes weld hem at hir wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche dorste wilde bestes dennes seke/</L>
<L>And renne in &thorn;e mounteyns al &thorn;e night</L>
<L>And slepe vnder a bussh and sche cou&thorn;e eeke</L>
<L N="3456">wrastil by verray fors and verray might</L>
<L>wi&thorn; eny &yogh;ong man were he neuer so wight</L>
<L>Ther mighte no &thorn;ing in hir armes stonde</L>
<L>She kept hir maydenhed from euery wight</L>
<L N="3460">To no man deyned hire to be bonde
<PB REF="00000554.tif" N="542"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="265"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But atte last hir frendes han hir maried</L>
<L>To Odenake a prince of &thorn;at Citee</L>
<L>Al were it so &thorn;at sche him longe taried<MILESTONE N="231a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3464">And &yogh;e schul vnderstonde how &thorn;at he</L>
<L>had suche fantasies as hadde sche /</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles whan &thorn;ay were knyt in fere</L>
<L>Thay lyued in ioye and in felicite</L>
<L N="3468">For ech of hem had o&thorn;er leef and deere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Saue oon &thorn;ing sche wolde neuer assent</L>
<L>By no way &thorn;at he schulde by hir lye</L>
<L>But oones for it was hir playn entent</L>
<L N="3472">To haue a child &thorn;e world to multiplie</L>
<L>And also soone as she might aspye /</L>
<L>That sche was not wi&thorn; childe &yogh;it in dede /</L>
<L>Than wold sche suffre him doon his fantasie</L>
<L N="3476">Eft sones and nought but oones out of drede /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And if sche were wi&thorn; child at &thorn;ilke cast</L>
<L>No more schuld he playe &thorn;ilke game</L>
<L>Til fully fourty dayes were y-past</L>
<L N="3480">Than wold sche suffre him to do &thorn;e same</L>
<L>Al were &thorn;is Odenake wilde or tame</L>
<L>he gat no more of hir for &thorn;us sche sayde</L>
<L>hit nas but wyues lecchery and schame /</L>
<L N="3484">In o&thorn;er caas if &thorn;at/ men with hem playde /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Tuo sones by &thorn;is Odenak had sche</L>
<L>The which sche kept/ in vertu and lettrure</L>
<L>But now vnto our purpos torne we</L>
<L N="3488">I say so worschipful a creature</L>
<L>And wys. wor&thorn;y. and large with mesure</L>
<L>So penyble in &thorn;e werre and curteys eeke</L>
<L>Ne more labour might in werre endure /</L>
<L N="3492">was no wher noon in al &thorn;is world to seeke
<PB REF="00000555.tif" N="543"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="266"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hir riche array if it might be told</L>
<L>As wel in vessel as in hir clo&thorn;ing</L>
<L>Sche was al clo&thorn;ed in perre and gold</L>
<L N="3496">And eek sche lafte nought for hir huntyng</L>
<L>To haue of sondry tonges ful knowing</L>
<L>whan sche had leyser // and might &thorn;erto entent</L>
<L>To lerne bookes was al hir likyng</L>
<L N="3500">How sche in vertu might hir lif despent</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And schortly of &thorn;is story for to trete<MILESTONE N="231b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So doughty was hir housbond and eek sche</L>
<L>That &thorn;ay conquered many regnes grete</L>
<L N="3504">In thorient with many a fair citee</L>
<L>Appurtienant vnto that mageste /</L>
<L>Of Rome. and with strong hond hulden hem fast</L>
<L>Ne neuer might her fomen doon hem fle</L>
<L N="3508">Ay while Odenakes dayes last/</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Her batails who / so lust hem for to rede</L>
<L>Agayn Sapor &thorn;e king and o&thorn;er mo</L>
<L>And how &thorn;at &thorn;is processe fel in dede</L>
<L N="3512">why sche conquered and what title had &thorn;erto</L>
<L>And after of hir meschief and hir woo /</L>
<L>how &thorn;at sche was deceyued and I-take /</L>
<L>let hem vnto my mayster perark go</L>
<L N="3516">That writeth of &thorn;is ynough I vndertake /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan Odenake was deed sche mightily</L>
<L>The regnes huld and wi&thorn; hir propre hond</L>
<L>A&yogh;eins hir foos sche faught ful trewely</L>
<L N="3520">That &thorn;er nas king ne prince in &thorn;at lond</L>
<L>That he nas glad if he &thorn;at grace fond</L>
<L>That sche ne wold vpon his lond werraye</L>
<L>with hir &thorn;ay made alliaunce by bond</L>
<L N="3524">To ben in pees and let hir ryde and play
<PB REF="00000556.tif" N="544"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="267"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The emperour of Rome Claudius</L>
<L>Ne him biforn &thorn;e romayn&middot; Galiene</L>
<L>Ne dorste neuer be so corrageous</L>
<L N="3528">Ne noon ermine ne Egipciene</L>
<L>No Surrien ne noon arrabiene</L>
<L>wi&thorn;inne &thorn;e feld &thorn;at durste with hir fight</L>
<L>Lest &thorn;at sche wold hem wi&thorn; her hondes sleen</L>
<L N="3532">Or wi&thorn; hir meyne putten hem to flight</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In kinges abyt went hir sones tuo</L>
<L>As heires of her fadres regnes alle</L>
<L>And hermanno and Themaleo</L>
<L N="3536">here names were and Parciens men hem calle /</L>
<L>But ay fortune hath in hir hony galle</L>
<L>This mighty queene may no while endure</L>
<L>Fortune out of hir regne made hir falle<MILESTONE N="232a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3540">To wrecchednesse and to mys aduenture</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Aurilian whan &thorn;at &thorn;e gouernaunce</L>
<L>Of Rome cam in-to his hondes tway /</L>
<L>he schop him of &thorn;is queen to do vengeaunce /</L>
<L N="3544">And with his legiouns he took &thorn;e way</L>
<L>Toward Cenoby and schortly to say</L>
<L>he made hir flee and atte last hir hent</L>
<L>And feterid hir and eek hir children tweye</L>
<L N="3548">And wan &thorn;e lond and home to Rome he went</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Amonges o&thorn;er &thorn;inges &thorn;at he wan</L>
<L>hir chaar &thorn;at was wi&thorn; gold wrou&yogh;t and perre</L>
<L>This grete Romayn &thorn;is aurilian</L>
<L N="3552">hath with him lad for &thorn;at men schulde se</L>
<L>Bifore &thorn;is triumphe walkith sche /</L>
<L>And gilte cheynes in hir necke hongynge</L>
<L>Coroun sche was as aftir hir degre</L>
<L>[and ful of perre chargid here clothynge<NOTE PLACE="marg">[In a later hand in the margin.]</NOTE>]
<PB REF="00000557.tif" N="545"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="268"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Allas fortune. sche that whilom was</L>
<L>Dredful to kinges and to Emperoures</L>
<L>Now gaulith al &thorn;e pepul on hir alas</L>
<L N="3560">And sche &thorn;at helmyd was in starke stoures /</L>
<L>And wan bifore tounes stronge and toures</L>
<L>Schal on heed now were a wyntermyte</L>
<L>And sche &thorn;at bar &thorn;e cepter ful of floures</L>
<L N="3564">Schal bere a distaf hir self for to quyte<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O noble petro. &thorn;e glori of Spayne /<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; <B>De petro his|pannie rege</B></NOTE></L>
<L>whom fortune held so heigh in mageste</L>
<L>wel oughte men &thorn;y pitous de&thorn; complayne</L>
<L N="3568">Thy bastard bro&thorn;er made &thorn;e to fle</L>
<L>And after / at a sege by subtilte</L>
<L>&thorn;ow were bytrayed and lad to his tent</L>
<L>wher / as he with his oughne hond slough &thorn;e</L>
<L N="3572">Succedyng in &thorn;y lond and in &thorn;y rent</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The feld of snow with thegle of blak &thorn;er-Inne</L>
<L>Caught wi&thorn; &thorn;e leoun reed coloured as is &thorn;e gleede</L>
<L>he brewede &thorn;e cursednesse and synne</L>
<L N="3576">The wikked nest werker of &thorn;is neede</L>
<L>Nought Oliuer ne Charles &thorn;at ay took heede</L>
<L>Of trouthe and honour but/ of armoryk<MILESTONE N="232b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Geniloun oliuer corruptid for nede</L>
<L N="3580">Broughte &thorn;is wor&thorn;y king in such a bryk<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O wor&thorn;y petro king of Cipres also<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De petro Cipre rege</NOTE></L>
<L>That alisaunder wan by heigh maistrye /</L>
<L>Ful many an hethen wroughtest &thorn;ou ful wo</L>
<L N="3584">Of which &thorn;in oughne lieges had enuye</L>
<L>And for no &thorn;ing but for &thorn;y chiualrie</L>
<L>&thorn;ay in thy bed han slayn &thorn;e by &thorn;e morwe</L>
<L>Thus can fortune &thorn;e whel gouerne and gye</L>
<L N="3588">And out of ioye bringe men in to sorwe<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000558.tif" N="546"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="269"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of Melayn grete Barnabo viscount<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Barnabo Co|mite Mediolano</NOTE></L>
<L>God of delyt and strength of lumbardye</L>
<L>why schuld &thorn;yn infortune I nought accounte</L>
<L N="3592">Syn in astaat &thorn;ou clombe were so hye</L>
<L>Thy bro&thorn;er sone &thorn;at was &thorn;y double allie</L>
<L>For he &thorn;y neuew was and sone in lawe</L>
<L>wi&thorn;inne his prisoun made &thorn;e to dye</L>
<L N="3596">But why ne how not I &thorn;at &thorn;ou were slawe /<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of erl hugilin of pise &thorn;e langour<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De hugilino Comite Pise</NOTE></L>
<L>Ther may no tonge telle &thorn;e pite</L>
<L>But litel out of pise stant a tour</L>
<L N="3600">In whiche tour / in prisoun put was he /</L>
<L>And with him been his litil children &thorn;re</L>
<L>Theldest skarsly fyf &yogh;er was of age /</L>
<L>Allas fortune it was gret cruelte</L>
<L N="3604">Suche briddes to put in such a cage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Dampnyd he was to deye in &thorn;at prisoun</L>
<L>For Roger which &thorn;at bisschop was of pise</L>
<L>Had on him maad a fals suggestioun</L>
<L N="3608">Thurgh which &thorn;e peple gan on him arise</L>
<L>And putte him in prisoun in such wise</L>
<L>As &yogh;e han herd and mete and drynk he hadde</L>
<L>So smal &thorn;at wel vnne&thorn;e it may suffise</L>
<L N="3612">And &thorn;er wi&thorn; al it was ful pore and badde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And on a day bifel &thorn;at in &thorn;at hour</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at his mete was wont to be brought</L>
<L>The gayler schet &thorn;e dores of &thorn;at tour</L>
<L N="3616">He herd it wel but he saugh it nought<MILESTONE N="233a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And in his hert anoon &thorn;er fel a &thorn;ought</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ay for hungir wolde doon him dyen</L>
<L>Alas quod he allas &thorn;at I was wrought</L>
<L N="3620">Ther-wi&thorn; &thorn;e teeres felle fro his eyen
<PB REF="00000559.tif" N="547"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="270"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His &yogh;ongest sone &thorn;at &thorn;re &yogh;er was of age</L>
<L>Vnto him sayde fader why do ye wepe</L>
<L>whan wil &thorn;e gayler bringen oure potage</L>
<L N="3624">Is &thorn;er no morsel bred &thorn;at &yogh;e doon kepe</L>
<L>I am so hongry &thorn;at I may not sleepe</L>
<L>Now wolde god &thorn;at I might slepe euer</L>
<L>Than schuld not hunger in my wombe crepe</L>
<L N="3628">Ther is no &thorn;ing saue bred &thorn;at me were leuer</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thus day by day &thorn;is child bigan to crie</L>
<L>Til in his fadres barm a-doun he lay</L>
<L>And sayde far wel fader I moot dye</L>
<L N="3632">And kist his fader and dyde &thorn;e same day</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;e woful fader deed it say</L>
<L>For wo his armes tuo he gan to byte</L>
<L>And sayde fortune alas and waylaway</L>
<L N="3636">Thin false querel al my woo I wyte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His childer wende &thorn;at it for hongir was</L>
<L>That he his armes gnew and nought for wo</L>
<L>And sayden fader do nought so allas</L>
<L N="3640">But rather et &thorn;e fleisch vpon vs tuo</L>
<L>Oure fleisch &thorn;ou &yogh;aue vs / oure fleisch &thorn;ou take vs fro</L>
<L>And ete ynough right &thorn;us &thorn;ay to him seyde</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at wi&thorn;inne a day or tuo</L>
<L N="3644">Thay layde hem in his lappe a-doun and deyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Himself despeired eek for honger starf</L>
<L>Thus ended is &thorn;is mighty eorl of pise</L>
<L>For his estate fortune fro him carf</L>
<L N="3648">Of &thorn;is tegrede it ought ynough suffise /</L>
<L>who-so wil it hiere in lenger wise</L>
<L>Rede &thorn;e gret poet of Itaile</L>
<L>That highte Daunt for he can it deuise</L>
<L N="3652">Fro poynt to poynt nou&yogh;t oon word wil he fayle<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000560.tif" N="548"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="271"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Al &thorn;ough Nero were als vicious<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Nerone</NOTE></L>
<L>As any fend that lith ful lowe adoun<MILESTONE N="233b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;it as tellith vs Swethoneus</L>
<L N="3656">This wyde world had in subieccioun</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e Est and west and Septemtrioun</L>
<L>Of rubies. safers. and of perles white</L>
<L>were alle his clo&thorn;es embroudid vp and doun</L>
<L N="3660">For he in gemmis / gretly gan delite</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>More delyt. more pomp of array</L>
<L>Mor proud was neuer Emperour &thorn;an he</L>
<L>That ylke cloth &thorn;at he had wered a day</L>
<L N="3664">After &thorn;at tyme he nolde it neuer se</L>
<L>Nettis of gold &thorn;red. had he gret plente</L>
<L>To fissche in tyber whan him lust to pleye</L>
<L>his willes were as lawe in his degre</L>
<L N="3668">For fortune as his frend wold him obeye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He Rome brent for his delicacie</L>
<L>The senatours he slough vpon a day</L>
<L>To here how men wolde wepe and crye</L>
<L N="3672">And slough his bro&thorn;er . and by his suster lay</L>
<L>his modir made he in pitous array</L>
<L>For hir wombe slyt he to byholde</L>
<L>wher he conceyued so waylaway /</L>
<L N="3676">&thorn;at he so litel of his moodir tolde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>No teer out of his eyen for &thorn;at sight/</L>
<L>Ne cam but sayde a fair womman was sche</L>
<L>Gret wonder is &thorn;at he cou&thorn;e or might</L>
<L N="3680">Be domesman on hir beaute</L>
<L>The wyn to bringen him comaundid he</L>
<L>And drank anoon noon o&thorn;er wo he made</L>
<L>whan might is torned vnto cruelte</L>
<L N="3684">Allas to deepe wil &thorn;e venym wade /
<PB REF="00000561.tif" N="549"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="272"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN &yogh;ou&thorn;e a maister had &thorn;is emperour</L>
<L>To teche him letterure and curtesye</L>
<L>For of moralite he was &thorn;e flour</L>
<L N="3688">And in his tyme but if &thorn;e book lye</L>
<L>And whil his maister had of him maistrie</L>
<L>he made him so connyng and so souple /</L>
<L>That long tyme it was or tyrranye</L>
<L N="3692">Or ony vice dorst on him vncouple /<MILESTONE N="234a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This Seneca of which &thorn;at I deuyse<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Seneca</NOTE></L>
<L>By cause Nero had of him such drede</L>
<L>For fro vices he wolde him chastise</L>
<L N="3696">Discretly by word and nou&yogh;t by dede /</L>
<L>Sir wold he sayn an emperour mot neede /</L>
<L>Be vertuous and hate tyrannye</L>
<L>For which he in a bath made him to bleede</L>
<L N="3700">On bo&thorn;e his armes til he moste dye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The nero hadde eek a custumance /</L>
<L>No &yogh;ou&thorn;e a&yogh;ein his maister for to ryse /</L>
<L>which afterward him &thorn;ought a gret greuaunce</L>
<L N="3704">Therfore he made him deye in &thorn;is wise</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles &thorn;is Seneca &thorn;e wise</L>
<L>Ches in bath to deye in &thorn;is manere /</L>
<L>Ra&thorn;er &thorn;an to haue ano&thorn;er tyrannye</L>
<L N="3708">And &thorn;us ha&thorn; Nero slayn his maister deere /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now fel it so &thorn;at fortune lust no lenger</L>
<L>The highe pride of Nero to cherice</L>
<L>For &thorn;ough he were strong &yogh;it was sche strenger</L>
<L N="3712">Sche &thorn;oughte &thorn;us by god I am to nyce</L>
<L>To set a man &thorn;at is ful sad of vice</L>
<L>In high degre and emperour him calle /</L>
<L>By god out of his cite I wil him trice</L>
<L N="3716">whan he lest wene&thorn; sonnest schal byfalle
<PB REF="00000562.tif" N="550"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="273"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The poeple ros on him vpon a night</L>
<L>For heigh defaute and whan he it aspyed</L>
<L>Out of his dores anoon he ha&thorn; him dight</L>
<L N="3720">Aloone and &thorn;er he wende haue ben allyed</L>
<L>he knokked fast and ay &thorn;e more he cried</L>
<L>The faster schette &thorn;ay &thorn;e doores alle/</L>
<L>Than wist he wel he had himself mysgyed</L>
<L N="3724">And went his way no lenger durst he calle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The peple cried and rumbled vp and doun</L>
<L>That with his eris herd he how &thorn;ay sayde</L>
<L>Wher is &thorn;is fals traitour &thorn;is neroun</L>
<L N="3728">For fere almost out of his witte he brayde /</L>
<L>And to his goddes pitously he prayde /</L>
<L>For socour but it mighte nought betyde /<MILESTONE N="234b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For drede of &thorn;is him &thorn;oughte &thorn;at he dyde</L>
<L N="3732">And ran in to a gardyn hym to hyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And in &thorn;is gardyn fond he cherlis twaye</L>
<L>Sittyng by a fuyr ful greet and reed</L>
<L>And to &thorn;ese che[r]les tuo he gan to pray</L>
<L N="3736">To sleen him and to girden of his heed</L>
<L>That to his body whan he were deed</L>
<L>were despyt y-doon for his defame</L>
<L>himself he slough he cou&thorn;e no better reed</L>
<L N="3740">Of which fortune &thorn;ai lough and hadde game /<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Was neuer Capitaigne vnder a king /<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Olipherno</NOTE></L>
<L>Thas regnes mo put in subieccioun</L>
<L>Ne strenger was in feld of alle &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="3744">As in his tyme ne gretter of renoun</L>
<L>Ne more pompous in heih presumpcioun</L>
<L>Than Oliphern . which &thorn;at fortune ay kist</L>
<L>So licorously . and ladde him vp and doun</L>
<L N="3748">Til that his heed was of er he it wist
<PB REF="00000563.tif" N="551"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="274"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nought oonly &thorn;at &thorn;e world had of him awe /</L>
<L>For lesyng of riches and liberte</L>
<L>But made euery man reneye his lawe /</L>
<L N="3752">Nabugodonosor was lord sayde he /</L>
<L>Noon o&thorn;er god schuld honoured be</L>
<L>A&yogh;einst his heste dar no wight trespace<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Et fecerunt filij israel secundum quod constituit eis dominus sacerdos Elyachym</NOTE></L>
<L>Saue in Betholia a strond cite</L>
<L>wher Eliachim a prest of &thorn;at place</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But tak keep of &thorn;at day of Olipherne</L>
<L>Amyd his ost/ he dronke lay on night</L>
<L>wi&thorn;inne his tente large as is a berne</L>
<L N="3760">And &yogh;it for al his pomp and al his might</L>
<L>Iudith a womman as he lay vpright</L>
<L>Slepyng his heed of smot and fro his tent</L>
<L>Ful priuely sche stal from euery wight</L>
<L N="3764">And with his heed vnto hir toun sche went<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>What needith it of king antiochius<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Rege Anti|ochie illustri.</NOTE></L>
<L>To telle his heye real mageste /</L>
<L>his heyhe pride his werke venemous</L>
<L N="3768">For such ano&thorn;er was &thorn;er noon as he<MILESTONE N="235a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Rede&thorn; which &thorn;at he was in machabe</L>
<L>And redith &thorn;e proude wordes &thorn;at he sayde</L>
<L>And why he fel fro his prosperite</L>
<L N="3772">And in an hil . how wrecchidly he deyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fortune him ha&thorn; enhaunced so in pryde</L>
<L>That verraily he wend he might han teyned</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e sterris vpon euery syde /</L>
<L N="3776">And in a balaunce weyen what ech mounteyned</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e floodes of &thorn;e see restreyne</L>
<L>And goddes peple had he most in hate</L>
<L>hem wold he slee in torment and in peyne</L>
<L N="3780">wenyng &thorn;at god ne might his pride abate
<PB REF="00000564.tif" N="552"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="275"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And for &thorn;at Nichosor and Thimothe /</L>
<L>with Iewes were venquist/ mightily</L>
<L>Vn to &thorn;e Iewes such an hate had he /</L>
<L N="3784">That he bad graithe his chaar hastily</L>
<L>And swor and sayde ful despitously</L>
<L>Vnto Ierusalem he wold eft soone</L>
<L>To wreke his Ire on it ful cruelly</L>
<L N="3788">But of his purpos he was let ful soone</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>God for his manace him so sore smoot</L>
<L>wi&thorn; inuisible wounde. incurable</L>
<L>That in his guttes carf so and bot</L>
<L N="3792">That his peynes were importable</L>
<L>And certeynly &thorn;e wreche was resonable</L>
<L>For on many a man. dede he peyne</L>
<L>But fro his purpos cursed and dampnable /</L>
<L N="3796">For al his smert he nolde him nought restreyne /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But bad anoon apparailen his host</L>
<L>And sodeynly er he was of it ware</L>
<L>God dampned al his pride and al his bost</L>
<L N="3800">For he so sore fel out of his chare</L>
<L>That his lymes and his skyn to-tare /</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he no more might go ne ryde /</L>
<L>But in a chare men aboute him bare /</L>
<L N="3804">Al forbrosed bo&thorn;e bak and syde /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The wreche of god him smot so cruely</L>
<L>That in his body wicked wormes crept<MILESTONE N="235b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;er with al he stonk/ so orribly</L>
<L N="3808">That noon of his meyne &thorn;at him kep[t]e</L>
<L>whe&thorn;er &thorn;at he wook or elles slepte</L>
<L>Ne mighte nought &thorn;e stynk of him endure</L>
<L>In &thorn;is meschief he weyled and eek wepte /</L>
<L N="3812">And knew god lord of euery creature
<PB REF="00000565.tif" N="553"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="276"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To al his host and to himself also</L>
<L>Ful wlatsom was &thorn;e stynk and &thorn;e carayne</L>
<L>No man might him bere to ne fro</L>
<L N="3816">And in stynk/ and orrible payne</L>
<L>he starf ful wrecchedly in a mountayne</L>
<L>Thus ha&thorn; &thorn;is robbour and &thorn;is homicide /</L>
<L>That many a man made wepe and playne /</L>
<L N="3820">Swich guerdoun is &thorn;at longe&thorn; vnto pryde<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The story of alisaunder is so comune<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De alexandro magno philip|pi regis mace|donie filio &amp;c /</NOTE></L>
<L>That every wight &thorn;at ha&thorn; discrecioun</L>
<L>ha&thorn; herd som what or al of this fortune</L>
<L N="3824">Thys wyde world as in conclusioun</L>
<L>he wan by streng&thorn;e or for his heigh renoun</L>
<L>Thay were glad for pees vnto him sende</L>
<L>The pride of man and bost he layd a doun</L>
<L N="3828">Wher-so he cam. vnto &thorn;e worldes ende /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Comparisoun &yogh;it mighte neuer be maked</L>
<L>Bitwen him and noon o&thorn;er conquerour</L>
<L>For al &thorn;is world for drede of him ha&thorn; quaked</L>
<L N="3832">he was of knyghthod and of fredam flour</L>
<L>Fortune him made &thorn;e heir of hir honour</L>
<L>Saue wyn and wymmen no &thorn;ing might aswage</L>
<L>his heigh entent in armes and labour</L>
<L N="3836">So was he ful of lumyne corage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>What pite were it to him &thorn;ough I &yogh;ow tolde</L>
<L>Of Darius and an hundred &thorn;ousand mo</L>
<L>Of kynges princes Dukes and eorles bolde /</L>
<L N="3840">which he conquered and brou&yogh;t/ vnto wo</L>
<L>I say as fer as men may ryde or go</L>
<L>The world was his what schold I more deuyse /</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3844">Of his knighthood it mighte nou&yogh;t suffise /
<PB REF="00000566.tif" N="554"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="277"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Twelf &yogh;er he regned as saith machabe<MILESTONE N="236a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Philippes son of Macedon he was</L>
<L>That first was king in Crece &thorn;at contre</L>
<L N="3848">O wor&thorn;y gentil alisaundre alas</L>
<L>That euer schulde falle such a caas</L>
<L>Empoysoned of &thorn;in oughne folk &thorn;ou were</L>
<L>Thyn fortune is torned in to an aas</L>
<L N="3852">And right for &thorn;e ne wepte sche neuer a teere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Who schal me &yogh;iue teeres to compleigne</L>
<L>The de&thorn; of gentiles and of fraunchise</L>
<L>That al &thorn;e worlde had in his demeigne</L>
<L N="3856">And &yogh;it him &thorn;ought it mighte nou&yogh;t suffice</L>
<L>So ful was his corage of high emprise /</L>
<L>Allas who schal helpe me to endite/</L>
<L>Fals infortune and poysoun to deuyse</L>
<L N="3860">The whiche two al &thorn;is wo I wyte<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>By wisedom manhod and gret labour</L>
<L>Fro humble bed to royal mageste /</L>
<L>Vp roos he Iulius &thorn;e conquerour</L>
<L N="3864">That wan al thoccident by land and see</L>
<L>By streng&thorn;e of hond or elles by trete /</L>
<L>And vnto Rome made hem contributarie</L>
<L>And si&thorn;&thorn;e of Rome &thorn;emperour was he</L>
<L N="3868">Til &thorn;at fortune wax his aduersarie /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O mighty Cesar &thorn;at in Thessalie</L>
<L>Agains pompious fader &thorn;in in lawe</L>
<L>That of &thorn;e orient had al &thorn;e chiualrie</L>
<L N="3872">Als fer as &thorn;at &thorn;e day bigynnes to dawe</L>
<L>Thorugh &thorn;i knighthod &thorn;ou hast him take and slawe</L>
<L>Saue fewe folk &thorn;at with pompeus fledde</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh which &thorn;ou puttist al &thorn;orient in awe</L>
<L N="3876">Thanke fortune &thorn;at so wel &thorn;e spedde
<PB REF="00000567.tif" N="555"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="278"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But now a litel while I wil bywaile</L>
<L>This pompeus &thorn;e noble gouernour</L>
<L>Of Rome which &thorn;at flowe fro &thorn;is bataile</L>
<L N="3880">Alas I say oon of his men a fals traitour</L>
<L>his heed of smoot to wynne his fauour</L>
<L>Of Iulius and him &thorn;e heed he brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Alas pomp of &thorn;e orient conquerour<MILESTONE N="236b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3884">That fortune to such a fyn &thorn;e brought</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To Rome agayn repaire&thorn; Iulius</L>
<L>wi&thorn; his triumphe laurial ful hye</L>
<L>But on a tyme brutus Cassius</L>
<L N="3888">That euer had to his estat enuye /</L>
<L>Ful priuely ha&thorn; made conspiracie /</L>
<L>Agains &thorn;is Iulius in subtil wise /</L>
<L>Cast the place . in which he schulde dye</L>
<L N="3892">with boydekyns as I schal &yogh;ow deuyse /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This Iulius to &thorn;e Capitoile went</L>
<L>vpon a day as he was wont to goon</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e Capitoil anoon him hent</L>
<L N="3896">This false brutus and his o&thorn;er foon</L>
<L>And stiked him wi&thorn; boydekyns anoon</L>
<L>with many a wounde and &thorn;us &thorn;ay let him lye</L>
<L>But neuer gront he at no strook but oon</L>
<L N="3900">Or elles at tuo but if &thorn;e storie lye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So manly was &thorn;is Iulius of hert/</L>
<L>And so wel loued estatly honeste</L>
<L>That &thorn;ough his deedly woundes sore smert</L>
<L N="3904">his mantil ouer his hipes caste he</L>
<L>For no man schulde seen his priuete</L>
<L>And as he lay deyinge in a traunce</L>
<L>And wiste wel &thorn;at verrayly deed was he</L>
<L N="3908">Of honeste &yogh;et had he remembraunce /
<PB REF="00000568.tif" N="556"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="279"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lucan to &thorn;e &thorn;is story I recomende</L>
<L>And to Swetoun and to Valirien also</L>
<L>That al &thorn;e story writen word and ende /</L>
<L N="3912">how to &thorn;ese grete conqueroures tuo</L>
<L>Fortune was first frend and si&thorn;&thorn;en fo</L>
<L>No man trust vpon hir favour longe /</L>
<L>But haue hir in awayt for euermo</L>
<L N="3916">witnesse on alle &thorn;ise conqueroures stronge<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Off riche gresus whilom king of lyde<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Gresus leuit|ici capitulo .ij<SUP>o</SUP> de spiritu phitonisse ha|bendo octos' iiij<SUP>o</SUP> libro Re|gum capitulo primo</NOTE></L>
<L>Of which gresus . Cirus him sore dradde /</L>
<L>&YOGH;et was he caught amyddes al his pride</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e fuyr to brenne him men him ladde</L>
<L>But such a rayn doun fro &thorn;e heuen schadde<MILESTONE N="237a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That slough &thorn;e fuyr and made him to eschape</L>
<L>But to be war &yogh;et grace noon he hadde /</L>
<L N="3924">Til fortune on &thorn;e galwes made him gape</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan he was eschaped he cou&thorn;e nou&yogh;t/ stent</L>
<L>For to bygynne a newe werre agayn</L>
<L>he wende wel for &thorn;at fortune him sent</L>
<L N="3928">Such hap &thorn;at he eschaped &thorn;urgh &thorn;e rayn</L>
<L>That of his foos he mighte not be slayn</L>
<L>And eek a sweuen vpon a night he mette</L>
<L>Of which he was so proud and eek so fayn</L>
<L N="3932">That in vengeaunce he al his herte sette /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vpon a tree he was set as him &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>wher Iubiter him wissch bo&thorn;e bak and side</L>
<L>And phebus eek a fair towail him brou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="3936">To drye him with and &thorn;erfore wax his pride</L>
<L>And to his dou&yogh;ter &thorn;at stood him biside</L>
<L>which &thorn;at he knew in heigh science abounde /</L>
<L>And bad hire telle what it signifyde</L>
<L N="3940">And sche his dreem right &thorn;us gan expounde /
<PB REF="00000569.tif" N="557"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="280"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The tree quod sche &thorn;e galwes is to mene</L>
<L>And Iubiter likenith snow and rayn</L>
<L>And phebus with his towail so clene</L>
<L N="3944">Tho ben &thorn;e sonne stremes so&thorn; to sayn</L>
<L>Thow schalt enhangid ben fader certayn</L>
<L>Rayn schal &thorn;e wasch and sonne schal &thorn;e drye</L>
<L>Thus warned sche him ful plat and ek ful playn</L>
<L N="3948">his doughter which &thorn;at called was phanie</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And hanged was Gresus &thorn;is proude king</L>
<L>his real tour might him not auaile /</L>
<L>Tegredis ne noon o&thorn;er maner &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="3952">Ne can in I synge crie ny biwayle</L>
<L>But for &thorn;at fortune wil alway assayle</L>
<L>wi&thorn; vnwar strook &thorn;e regnes &thorn;at ben proude</L>
<L>For whan men trusteth hir than wil sche faile</L>
<L N="3956">And couer hir brighte face with a clowde</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>&para; Here ende&thorn; &thorn;e monk his tale<NOTE>[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000570.tif" N="558">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="281">
<HEAD>&para; &amp; here bygynne &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e Nonne prestes tale . of &thorn;e kok and &thorn;e hen.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HO sire quod the knight no more of &thorn;is<MILESTONE N="237b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That &yogh;e han said is right ynough y-wys</L>
<L>And mochil mor . for litel heuynesse</L>
<L N="3960">Is right I-nough for moche folk I gesse</L>
<L>I say for me it is a gret disease</L>
<L>wher as men han ben in gret wel&thorn;e and ease</L>
<L>To hieren of her sodeyn fal allas</L>
<L N="3964">And &thorn;e contraire is ioye and gret solas</L>
<L>As whan a man ha&thorn; ben in pore estate</L>
<L>And clymbith vp and wexe&thorn; fortunate</L>
<L>And &thorn;er abyde&thorn; in prosperite</L>
<L N="3968">Such &thorn;ing is gladsom as &thorn;inkith me</L>
<L>And of such &thorn;ing were goodly for to telle</L>
<L>&yogh;e quod our host by seinte paules belle</L>
<L>&yogh;e say right so&thorn; &thorn;is monk ha&thorn; clappid lowde</L>
<L N="3972">he spak how fortune was clipped with a clowde</L>
<L>I not neuer what and als of tregedie</L>
<L>Right now &yogh;e herd and pardy no remedye</L>
<L>It is for to bywayle or compleyne</L>
<L N="3976">That &thorn;at is doon and also it is a peyne</L>
<L>As &yogh;e han said to hiere of heuynesse /</L>
<L>Sire monk no more of &thorn;is . so god &yogh;our soule blesse</L>
<L>&YOGH;our tale anoyeth al &thorn;is compaignie</L>
<L N="3980">Such a tale is nou&yogh;t worth a boterflye</L>
<L>For &thorn;er Inne is noon disport ne game</L>
<L>wherfor sir monk . damp Pieres by &yogh;our name</L>
<L>I pray &yogh;ow hertly tel vs som what ellis</L>
<L N="3984">For sicurly ner gingling of &thorn;e bellis
<PB REF="00000571.tif" N="559"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="282"></L>
<L>&THORN;at on &yogh;our bridil hong on euery syde</L>
<L>By heuen king &thorn;at for vs alle dyde</L>
<L>I schold er &thorn;is han falle doun for sleep</L>
<L N="3988">Al &thorn;ough &thorn;e slough had neuer ben so deep</L>
<L>Than had &yogh;our tale . haue be told in vayn</L>
<L>For certeynly as &thorn;ese clerkes sayn</L>
<L>wher as a man may haue noon audience</L>
<L N="3992">Nought helpith it to tellen his sentence</L>
<L>And wel I wot &thorn;e substance is in me</L>
<L>If eny &thorn;ing schal wel reported be</L>
<L>Sir say som what of huntyng I &yogh;ow pray<MILESTONE N="238a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3996">Nay quod &thorn;e monk I haue no lust to play</L>
<L>Now let another telle as I haue told //</L>
<L>Than spak our ost wi&thorn; rude speche and bold //</L>
<L>And said vnto the nonnes prest anoon //</L>
<L N="4000">Come ner &thorn;ou prest . come ner &thorn;ou sir Iohn //</L>
<L>Tel vs such &thorn;ing as may our hertes glade</L>
<L>Be bli&thorn;e al &thorn;ough &thorn;ou ryde vpon a iade //</L>
<L>what &thorn;ough &thorn;in hors be bo&thorn;e foul and lene //</L>
<L N="4004">If he wil serue &thorn;e rek not a bene //</L>
<L>lok &thorn;at &thorn;in hert be mery euer mo //</L>
<L>&YOGH;is sire &yogh;is hoste . also mot I go //</L>
<L>But I be mery I-wis I wol be blamed //</L>
<L N="4008">And right anoon he ha&thorn; his tale tamyd //</L>
<L>And &thorn;us he sayd vnto vs euerich oon //</L>
<L>This sweete prest this goodly man sir Iohn</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Explicit prologus<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000572.tif" N="560">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="283">
<HEAD>&para; Here bygynneth the Nonne prest his tale</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>APore wydow . som del stope in age</L>
<L N="4012">was whilom duellyng in a pore cotage</L>
<L>Bisyde a groue stondyng in a dale</L>
<L>This wydow of which I telle &yogh;ow my tale</L>
<L>Syn &thorn;ilke day &thorn;at sche was last a wif /</L>
<L N="4016">In paciens ladde . a ful symple lyf</L>
<L>For litel was hir catel and hir rent</L>
<L>By housbondry . of such as god hir sent</L>
<L>Sche fond hir self and eek hir doughtres tuo</L>
<L N="4020">Thre large sowes had sche and no mo</L>
<L>Thre kyn . and eek a scheep &thorn;at highte malle.</L>
<L>Ful sooty was hir bour and eek hir halle</L>
<L>In which she eet ful many a sclender meel</L>
<L N="4024">Of poynaunt saws hir needid neuer a deel</L>
<L>Noon deynteth morsel passid &thorn;orugh hir &thorn;rote</L>
<L>Hir dyete was accordant to hir cote</L>
<L>Repleccioun ne made hir neuer sik</L>
<L N="4028">Attempre dyete was al hir phisik</L>
<L>And exercise and hertes suffisaunce</L>
<L>The goute lette hir no &thorn;ing for to daunce</L>
<L>Ne poplexie schente not hir heed</L>
<L N="4032">No wyn ne drank he no&thorn;er whit ne reed<MILESTONE N="238b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Hir bord seruyd bo&thorn;e with whit and blak</L>
<L>Milk and broun bred in which sche fond no lak</L>
<L>Saynd bacoun and som tyme an ey or tweye</L>
<L N="4036">For sche was as it were a maner deye</L>
<L>A &yogh;erd sche had enclosed al aboute</L>
<L>wi&thorn; stikkes and a drye dich wi&thorn;oute</L>
<L>In which she had a Cok &thorn;at hight Chaunteclere</L>
<L N="4040">In al &thorn;e lond of crowyng was noon his peere
<PB REF="00000573.tif" N="561"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="284"></L>
<L>His vois was merier &thorn;an &thorn;e mery Orgon</L>
<L>On masse dayes &thorn;at in &thorn;e chirche goon</L>
<L>wel sikerer was his crowyng in his logge</L>
<L N="4044">&thorn;an is a Clok or an abbay Orologge</L>
<L>By nature knew he ech ascensioun</L>
<L>Of equinoxial in &thorn;ilke toun</L>
<L>For whan degrees fyftene were ascendid</L>
<L N="4048">Thanne crew he it might not ben amendid</L>
<L>His comb was redder &thorn;an &thorn;e fyn coral</L>
<L>And batayld as it were a castel wal</L>
<L>his bile was blak and as &thorn;e geet it schon</L>
<L N="4052">lik asur were . his legges and his ton</L>
<L>His nayles whitter &thorn;an &thorn;e lily flour</L>
<L>And lik &thorn;e burnischt gold was his colour</L>
<L>This gentil cok had in his gouernaunce</L>
<L N="4056">Seuen hennes for to do al his plesaunce</L>
<L>whiche were his sustres and his paramoures</L>
<L>And wonder lik to him as of coloures</L>
<L>Of whiche &thorn;e fairest hiewed on hir &thorn;rote</L>
<L N="4060">was cleped fayre damysel pertilote</L>
<L>Curteys sche was discret and debonaire</L>
<L>And companable and bar hir self ful faire</L>
<L>Syn &thorn;ilke day &thorn;at sche was seuen &yogh;er old</L>
<L N="4064">That sche ha&thorn; trewely &thorn;e hert in hold</L>
<L>Of chaunteclere loken in euery lith</L>
<L>He loued hir so &thorn;at wel him was &thorn;er-with</L>
<L>But such a ioye was it to here him synge</L>
<L N="4068">whan &thorn;at &thorn;e brighte sonne gan to springe</L>
<L>In swete accord my lief is faren on londe</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;ilke tyme as I haue vnderstonde<MILESTONE N="239a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bestis and briddes cowde speke and synge</L>
<L N="4072">And so byfel &thorn;at in a dawenynge</L>
<L>As Chaunteclere among his wyues alle /</L>
<L>Sat on his perche &thorn;at was in his halle</L>
<L>And next him sat &thorn;is faire pertelote</L>
<L N="4076">This Chauntecler gan gronen in his &thorn;rote
<PB REF="00000574.tif" N="562"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="285"></L>
<L>As man &thorn;at in his dreem is drecched sore /</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at Pertelot &thorn;us herd him rore</L>
<L>Sche was agast and sayde herte deere</L>
<L N="4080">what eylith &yogh;ow to grone in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>&YOGH;e ben a verray sleper fy for schame</L>
<L>And he answerd and sayde &thorn;us ma dame</L>
<L>I pray &yogh;ow &thorn;at &yogh;e take it nou&yogh;t agreef</L>
<L N="4084">By god me mette I was in such meschief</L>
<L>Right now &thorn;at &yogh;it myn hert/ is sore afright</L>
<L>Now god quod he my sweuen rede aright</L>
<L>And keep my body out of foul prisoun</L>
<L N="4088">Me mette how &thorn;at I romed vp and doun</L>
<L>wi&thorn;inne oure &yogh;erd wher as I saugh a beest/</L>
<L>was lik an hound and wold haue maad arrest/</L>
<L>Vpon my body and wold han had me deed</L>
<L N="4092">His colour was bitwixe &yogh;olow and reed</L>
<L>And tipped was his tail and bo&thorn;e his eeres</L>
<L>with blak/. vnlik &thorn;e remenaunt of his heres</L>
<L>His snowt was smal with glowynge yen tweye</L>
<L N="4096">&YOGH;et of his look/ for fer almost I deye</L>
<L>This caused me my gronyng douteles</L>
<L>A way quod sche. fy on &yogh;ow herteles</L>
<L>Allas quod sche for by &thorn;at god aboue</L>
<L N="4100">Now haue &yogh;e lost myn hert and al my loue</L>
<L>I can nought loue a coward by my feith</L>
<L>For certis what so eny womman seith</L>
<L>we alle desiren if it mighte be</L>
<L N="4104">To haue housbondes hardy riche and fre</L>
<L>And secre and no nygard ne no fool</L>
<L>Ne him &thorn;at is agast of euery tool</L>
<L>Ne noon auaunter by &thorn;at god aboue</L>
<L N="4108">How dorst &yogh;e sayn for schame vnto &yogh;our loue<MILESTONE N="239b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That any &thorn;ing might make &yogh;ow afferd</L>
<L>haue &yogh;e no mannes hert and han a berd</L>
<L>Allas and can &yogh;e ben agast of sweuenys</L>
<L N="4112">Nought god wot / but vanite in sweuen is
<PB REF="00000575.tif" N="563"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="286"></L>
<L>Sweuens engendrid ben of replecciouns</L>
<L>And often of fume and of complexiouns</L>
<L>whan humours ben to abundaunt in a wight</L>
<L N="4116">Certes &thorn;is dreem which &yogh;e han met to-night</L>
<L>Come&thorn; of &thorn;e grete superfluite</L>
<L>Of &yogh;oure reede Colera parde</L>
<L>which causeth folk to dremen in here dremes</L>
<L N="4120">Of arwes and of fuyr with reede beemes</L>
<L>Of rede bestis &thorn;at &thorn;ai wil him byte /</L>
<L>Of Contek and of whelpis greet and lite</L>
<L>Right as &thorn;e humour of malencolie</L>
<L N="4124">Cause&thorn; in sleep ful many a man to crye</L>
<L>For fere of beres or of boles blake</L>
<L>Or elles blake deueles wol hem take</L>
<L>Of o&thorn;er humours cou&thorn;e I telle also</L>
<L N="4128">That wirken many a man in slep ful woo</L>
<L>But I wol passe as light[l]y as I can</L>
<L>lo Catoun which &thorn;at was so wis a man</L>
<L>Sayde he nou&yogh;t &thorn;us ne do no force of dremes</L>
<L N="4132">Now sire quod sche whan we fle fro &thorn;ise beemes</L>
<L>For goddis loue as tak som laxatyf</L>
<L>Vp peril of my soule and of my lyf</L>
<L>I counsel &yogh;ow &thorn;e best I wol not lye</L>
<L N="4136">. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Though in &thorn;is toun is noon apotecarie</L>
<L>I schal my-self tuo herbes techyn &yogh;ow</L>
<L N="4140">That schal be for &yogh;our hele and for &yogh;oure prow</L>
<L>And in oure &yogh;erd &thorn;o herbes schal I fynde</L>
<L>The whiche han of her proprete by kynde</L>
<L>To purgen &yogh;ow byne&thorn;e and eek aboue</L>
<L N="4144">Forget not &thorn;is for goddis oughne loue</L>
<L>&yogh;e ben ful colerik of complexioun</L>
<L>ware &thorn;e sonne in his ascencioun</L>
<L>Ne fynd &yogh;ow not/ replet in humours hote</L>
<L N="4148">And if it do I dar wel lay a grote<MILESTONE N="240a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000576.tif" N="564"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="287"></L>
<L>That &yogh;e schul haue a feuer terciane</L>
<L>Or an agu &thorn;at may be &yogh;oure bane</L>
<L>A day or tuo &yogh;e schul haue digestiues</L>
<L N="4152">Of wormes er &yogh;e take &yogh;our laxatiues</L>
<L>Of lauriol Century and fumytere</L>
<L>Or elles of Elder bery &thorn;at growith &thorn;ere /</L>
<L>Of Catapus or of gaytre berijs</L>
<L N="4156">Of erbe yue growe&thorn; in our &yogh;erd &thorn;er mery is</L>
<L>Pike hem vpright as &thorn;ay growe and et hem In &middot;</L>
<L>Be mery housbond for &yogh;our fader kyn</L>
<L>Dredi&thorn; non dremes I can say no more</L>
<L N="4160">Ma dame quod he graunt mercy of &yogh;our lore</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles as touching daun Catoun</L>
<L>That hath of wisdom such a gret renoun</L>
<L>Though &thorn;at he bad no dremes for to drede</L>
<L N="4164">By god men may in olde bookes rede</L>
<L>Of many a man more of auctorite</L>
<L>That euer catoun was so mot I the</L>
<L>That al &thorn;e reuers sayn of his sentence</L>
<L N="4168">And han wel founden by experience</L>
<L>That dremes ben significaciouns</L>
<L>As wel of ioye as of tribulaciouns</L>
<L>That folk enduren in &thorn;is lif present</L>
<L N="4172">Ther nedeth make of &thorn;is noon argument</L>
<L>The verray preue schewith it in dede</L>
<L>Oon of &thorn;e grettest auctorite &thorn;at men rede</L>
<L>Saith &thorn;us &middot; &thorn;at whilom tway felawes wente</L>
<L N="4176">On pylgrimage in a ful good entente /</L>
<L>And happed so &thorn;ay com in to a toun</L>
<L>wher as &thorn;er was such congregacioun</L>
<L>Of people and eek so streyt of herbergage</L>
<L N="4180">&thorn;at &thorn;ay fond nou&yogh;t as moche as oon cotage /</L>
<L>In which &thorn;at &thorn;ay might bo&thorn;e I-logged be</L>
<L>wherfor &thorn;ay mosten of necessite</L>
<L>As for &thorn;at night depart her compaignye</L>
<L N="4184">And ech of hem go&thorn; to his hostelrye
<PB REF="00000577.tif" N="565"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="288"></L>
<L>And took his loggyng as it wolde falle</L>
<L>That oon of hem was loggid in a stalle<MILESTONE N="240b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Fer in a &yogh;erd with oxen of &thorn;e plough</L>
<L N="4188">That o&thorn;er man was logged wel ynough</L>
<L>As was his aduenture or fortune</L>
<L>That vs gouernith alle in comune</L>
<L>And so bifel &thorn;at long er it were day</L>
<L N="4192">This oon met in his bed &thorn;er as he lay</L>
<L>how &thorn;at his felaw gan vpon him calle</L>
<L>And sayd allas for in an oxe stalle /</L>
<L>This night I schal be murdrid &thorn;er I lye</L>
<L N="4196">Now help me deere bro&thorn;er or I dye</L>
<L>In alle cum to me he sayde</L>
<L>This man out of his slep for fer abrayde</L>
<L>But whan &thorn;at he was waked out of his sleep</L>
<L N="4200">he torned him and took of &thorn;is no keep</L>
<L>him &thorn;ought him dreem nas but a vanite /</L>
<L>Thus twies in his sleepe dremed he</L>
<L>And at/ &thorn;e &thorn;ridde tyme &yogh;et his felawe</L>
<L N="4204">Com as him &thorn;ought and sayd I am now slawe</L>
<L>Bihold my bloody woundes deep and wyde</L>
<L>Arise vp erly in &thorn;e morwe tyde /</L>
<L>And at the west gate of &thorn;e toun quod he /</L>
<L N="4208">A cart of donge &thorn;ere schalt &thorn;ou see</L>
<L>In which my body is hyd priuely</L>
<L>Do &thorn;ilke cart arresten boldely</L>
<L>My gold caused my mourdre so&thorn; to sayn</L>
<L N="4212">And told him euery poynt how he was slayn</L>
<L>with a ful pitous face pale of hewe</L>
<L>And truste wel his dreem he fond ful trewe /</L>
<L>For on &thorn;e morwe as sone as it was day</L>
<L N="4216">To his felawes In he took &thorn;e way</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at he cam to &thorn;is oxe stalle</L>
<L>After his felaw he bigan to calle /</L>
<L>The hostiller answered him anoon</L>
<L N="4220">And sayde sire &yogh;our felaw is agoon
<PB REF="00000578.tif" N="566"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="289"></L>
<L>Als soone as day he went/ out of &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>This man gan falle in a suspeccioun</L>
<L>Remembring on his dremes &thorn;at he mette /</L>
<L N="4224">And forth he goth no lenger wold he lette<MILESTONE N="241a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e west gate of &thorn;e toun and fond</L>
<L>A dong cart went as it were to donge lond</L>
<L>That was arrayed in &thorn;e same wise</L>
<L N="4228">As &yogh;e han herd &thorn;e deede man deuise /</L>
<L>And with an hardy hert he gan to crie</L>
<L>Vengeaunce and iustice of &thorn;is felonye</L>
<L>My felaw mordrid is &thorn;is same night</L>
<L N="4232">And in &thorn;is carte . he lith heer vpright</L>
<L>I crye out on &thorn;e ministres quod he /</L>
<L>That schulde kepe and reule &thorn;is Cite</L>
<L>harrow allas her lith my felaw slayn</L>
<L N="4236">what schold I more vnto &thorn;is tale sayn</L>
<L>The peple vpstert and caste &thorn;e carte to grounde /</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e myddes of &thorn;e dong &thorn;ay founde</L>
<L>The dede man &thorn;at mordred was al newe /</L>
<L N="4240">O blisful god &thorn;ou art ful iust and trewe</L>
<L>Lo how &thorn;ow bywreyest mordre al day</L>
<L>Mordre wil out certes it is no nay</L>
<L>Morder is so wlatsom and abhominable</L>
<L N="4244">To god that is so iust and resonable</L>
<L>That he ne wold nou&yogh;t suffre it hiled be</L>
<L>Though it abyde a &yogh;eer or tuo or &thorn;re</L>
<L>Morder wil out &thorn;is is my conclusioun</L>
<L N="4248">And right anoon &thorn;e mynistres of &thorn;at toun</L>
<L>Han hent &thorn;e carter and so sore him pyned</L>
<L>And eek the hostiller so sore engyned</L>
<L>That &thorn;ay biknew her wikkednes anoon</L>
<L N="4252">And were anhonged by &thorn;e nekke boon</L>
<L>Here may men se &thorn;at dremys ben to drede</L>
<L>And Certes in &thorn;e same book I rede</L>
<L>Right in &thorn;e nexte Chapitre after &thorn;is</L>
<L N="4256">I gabbe nought so haue I ioye or bliss
<PB REF="00000579.tif" N="567"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="290"></L>
<L>Tuo men &thorn;at wolde haue passed ouer see /</L>
<L>For certeyn causes in-to fer cuntre</L>
<L>If &thorn;at &thorn;e wynd ne hadde ben contrarie</L>
<L N="4260">That/ made hem in a Cite for to tarie</L>
<L>That stood ful mery vpon an hauen syde /</L>
<L>But on a day agayn &thorn;e euen tyde<MILESTONE N="241b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>The wynd gan chaunge and [blew] right as him list</L>
<L N="4264">Iolyf and glad &thorn;ey wenten vnto rest</L>
<L>And casten hem ful erly for to sayle</L>
<L>But herkne&thorn; to &thorn;at oon man fel a gret meruayle</L>
<L>That oon of hem in his slepyng as he lay</L>
<L N="4268">him met a wonder drem a-gayn &thorn;e day</L>
<L>him &thorn;ought a man stood by his beddes syd</L>
<L>And him comaunded &thorn;at he schuld abyde</L>
<L>And sayd him &thorn;us if &thorn;ou to morwe wende</L>
<L N="4272">Thow schalt be dreynt my tale is at an ende</L>
<L>&para; He wook and told his felaw what he mette</L>
<L>And prayde him his viage to lette</L>
<L>As for &thorn;at day he prayd him to abyde</L>
<L N="4276">his felaw &thorn;at lay by his beddis syde</L>
<L>Gan to lawgh and scorned him ful fast</L>
<L>No dreem quod he may so myn herte gaste /</L>
<L>That I wil lette for to do my &thorn;inges</L>
<L N="4280">I sette not a straw by &thorn;y dremynges</L>
<L>For sweuens been but vanitees and iapes</L>
<L>Men dreme al day of owles and of apes</L>
<L>And eke of many a mase &thorn;er with al</L>
<L N="4284">Men dreme of &thorn;inges &thorn;at neuer be schal</L>
<L>But sith I see &thorn;at &thorn;ou wilt her abyde /</L>
<L>And &thorn;us forslouthe wilfully &thorn;y tyde</L>
<L>God wot it reweth me and haue good day</L>
<L N="4288">And &thorn;us he took his leue and went his way</L>
<L>But er he hadde half his cours I-sayled</L>
<L>Noot I nou&yogh;t why. ne what meschaunce it ayled</L>
<L>But casuelly &thorn;e schippes bothom rent</L>
<L N="4292">And schip and man vnder &thorn;e watir went
<PB REF="00000580.tif" N="568"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="291"></L>
<L>In sight of o&thorn;er schippes &thorn;er byside</L>
<L>That with him sailed at &thorn;e same tyde</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore faire pertelot so deere</L>
<L N="4296">By such ensamples olde maistow leere</L>
<L>That no man scholde be to recheles</L>
<L>Of dremes for I say &thorn;e douteles</L>
<L>That many a dreem ful sore is for to drede</L>
<L N="4300">Lo in &thorn;e lif of seint/ kenelm I rede<MILESTONE N="242a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That was kenulphus sone &thorn;at noble king</L>
<L>Of mertinrike how kenilm mette a &thorn;ing</L>
