<L>If &thorn;ou bigile me. any ofter &thorn;an oones</L>
<L>Thou schalt no more &thorn;urgh &thorn;y flaterye</L>
<L N="4620">Do me to synge and wynke with myn ye</L>
<L>For he &thorn;at wynkith whan he scholde se</L>
<L>Al wilfully god let him neuer the</L>
<L>Nay quod &thorn;e Fox but god &yogh;iue him meschaunce /</L>
<L N="4624">&thorn;at is so vndiscret of gouernaunce /</L>
<L>&thorn;at iangleth whan he scholde holde his pees</L>
<L>Lo such it is for to be recheles</L>
<L>And necligent and trust on flaterie /</L>
<L N="4628">But &yogh;e &thorn;at holde / &thorn;is tale a folye /</L>
<L>As of a Fox. or of a cok or of an hen</L>
<L>Takith &thorn;e moralite goode men</L>
<L>For seint poul sai&thorn; &thorn;at al &thorn;at writen is</L>
<L N="4632">To oure doctrine it is I-write I-wys</L>
<L>Takith &thorn;e fruyt and let &thorn;e chaf be stille</L>
<L>Now goode god. if &thorn;at it be &thorn;y wille</L>
<L>As saith my lor so make vs alle good men</L>
<L N="4636">And bring vs alle. to his blisse ameN</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Here ende&thorn; &thorn;e tale of Chaunteclere and pertelote<NOTE>[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
