<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000590.tif" N="578">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="576">
<HEAD>&para; Here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e maunciples tale</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WOt &yogh;e not wher &thorn;er stont a litel toun</L>
<L>which &thorn;at cleped is Bob vp and doun</L>
<L>vnder &thorn;e Ble in Caunterbury way</L>
<L N="4">Ther gan our hoste for to iape and play</L>
<L>And sayde sires what dun is in &thorn;e myre</L>
<L>Is &thorn;er no man for prayer ne for hyre<MILESTONE N="246b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Thal wol awake our felawes al by-hynde</L>
<L N="8">A theef mighte ful lightly robbe and bynde</L>
<L>Se how he nappith se for goddes boones</L>
<L>That he wol falle fro his hors at ones</L>
<L>Is &thorn;at a Cook of londoun wi&thorn; meschaunce /</L>
<L N="12">Do him come forth he knoweth his penaunce /</L>
<L>For he schal telle a tale by my fay</L>
<L>Al &thorn;ough it be nou&yogh;t wor&thorn; a botel hay</L>
<L>Awake &thorn;ou Cook sit vp god &yogh;if &thorn;e sorwe</L>
<L N="16">what eyle&thorn; &thorn;e to slepe by &thorn;e morwe /</L>
<L>Hast &thorn;ou had fleen al night or artow dronke</L>
<L>Or hastow with some quen al night I-swonke</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ou maist not holden vp &thorn;yn heed</L>
<L N="20">This cook &thorn;at was pale and no &thorn;ing reed</L>
<L>Sayd to our host so god my soule blesse /</L>
<L>As &thorn;er is falle on me such heuynesse</L>
<L>Not I nou&yogh;t why &thorn;at me were leuer slepe /</L>
<L N="24">Than &thorn;e beste galoun wyn in Chepe /
<PB REF="00000591.tif" N="579"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="577"></L>
<L>&para; wel quod &thorn;e maunciple if &thorn;at I may doon ease /</L>
<L>To &thorn;e sir Cook and to no wi&yogh;t displease /</L>
<L>which &thorn;at her ryde&thorn; in &thorn;is compaignye</L>
<L N="28">And our host wolde of his curteisie</L>
<L>I wol as now excuse &thorn;e of &thorn;y tale</L>
<L>For in good faith &thorn;i visage is ful pale</L>
<L>&thorn;yn eyen daswen eek. also me &thorn;inkith</L>
<L N="32">And wel I woot &thorn;y breth ful foule stynkith</L>
<L>That schewe&thorn; eek &thorn;ou art nought wel disposid</L>
<L>Of me certeyn &thorn;ou schalt nou&yogh;t ben I-glosed</L>
<L>Se how he ganith. lo &thorn;is dronken wight</L>
<L N="36">As &thorn;ough he wolde swolwe vs anoon right</L>
<L>hold clos &thorn;y mouth by &thorn;y fader kynne</L>
<L>The deuel of helle sette his foot &thorn;er Inne</L>
<L>Thy cursed breth effecte wil vs alle</L>
<L N="40">Fy stynkyng swyne foule mot &thorn;e falle</L>
<L>A. taki&thorn; heed sires of &thorn;is lusty man</L>
<L>Now swete sir. wol &yogh;e ioust atte fan</L>
<L>Therto me &thorn;ink&thorn;. &yogh;e be&thorn; right wel I-schape</L>
<L N="44">I trowe &thorn;a &yogh;e dronken han wyn ape<MILESTONE N="247a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;at whan men playen with a straw</L>
<L>And with his speche &thorn;e cook wax angry &amp; wraw</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e maunciple bygan he nodde fast</L>
<L N="48">For lak of speche. and doun &thorn;e hors him cast</L>
<L>wher as he lay til &thorn;at men him up took</L>
<L>This was a fair Chiuache of a cook</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;at he nad hold him by his ladil</L>
<L N="52">And er &thorn;at he agayn were in his sadil</L>
<L>Ther was gret schowuyng bo&thorn;e to and fro</L>
<L>To lift him vp and moche care and wo</L>
<L>So vnwelde was &thorn;is sory pallid gost</L>
<L N="56">And to &thorn;e maunciple &thorn;anne spak oure host</L>
<L>By cause drink hath dominacioun</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;is man by my sauacioun</L>
<L>I trow he lewedly tel wol his tale</L>
<L N="60">For were it wyn or old moysty ale
<PB REF="00000592.tif" N="580"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="578"></L>
<L>&thorn;at he ha&thorn; dronk. he speki&thorn; in his nose /</L>
<L>And fnesith fast. and eek he ha&thorn; &thorn;e pose</L>
<L>he also to do more &thorn;an ynough</L>
<L N="64">To kepe him and his Capil out of &thorn;e slough</L>
<L>And if he falle fro his capil eft sone;</L>
<L>&thorn;an schal we alle haue ynough to doone</L>
<L>In liftyng vp his heuy dronken cors</L>
<L N="68">Tel on thy tale of him make I no fors</L>
<L>But &yogh;it maunciple in faith &thorn;ou art to nyce</L>
<L>Thus openly reproeue him of his vice</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er day he wil par aduenture</L>
<L N="72">Reclayme &thorn;e and bringe &thorn;e to lure</L>
<L>I mene he speke wol of smale &thorn;inges</L>
<L>As for to pynchyn at &thorn;y rekenynges</L>
<L>That were not honest if it cam to pref</L>
<L N="76">Quod &thorn;e maunciple &thorn;at were a gret meschief</L>
<L>So might he lightly bringe me in &thorn;e snare</L>
<L>&YOGH;it had I leuer payen for &thorn;e mare</L>
<L>which he ryt on. &thorn;an he schulde with me stryue</L>
<L N="80">I wil not wrath him al so mot I &thorn;riue</L>
<L>That at I spak I sayd it in my bourde</L>
<L>And wite &yogh;e what I haue heer in a gourde<MILESTONE N="247b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A draught of wyn. is of a ripe grape /</L>
<L N="84">And right anoon &yogh;e schal se a good iape</L>
<L>&thorn;is Cook schal drinke &thorn;er-of if I may</L>
<L>vp peyn of deth he wol nou&yogh;t say me nay</L>
<L>And certeinly to tellen as it was /</L>
<L N="88">Of &thorn;is vessel &thorn;e cook dronk fast allas</L>
<L>what needid it. he drank ynough biforn</L>
<L>And whan he hadde pouped in his horn</L>
<L>To &thorn;e maunciple he took &thorn;e gourd agayn</L>
<L N="92">And of &thorn;at draught &thorn;e cook was wonder fayn</L>
<L>And &thorn;anked him in such wise as he cou&thorn;e /</L>
<L>Than gan our host to laughe wonder louthe /</L>
<L>And sayd I se wel it is necessarie</L>
<L N="96">wher &thorn;at we go good drynk wi&thorn; vs to carie
<PB REF="00000593.tif" N="581"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="579"></L>
<L>For &thorn;at wol torne rancour and desese</L>
<L>To accord and loue and many racour pese /</L>
<L>O &thorn;ou bacus I-blessid be &thorn;in name</L>
<L N="100">That so canst torne ernest in to game</L>
<L>worschip and &thorn;onke. be to &thorn;y deite</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at matier &yogh;e get no more of me</L>
<L>Tel on &thorn;i tale mauncipel I &thorn;e pray</L>
<L N="104">wel sir quod he. now herkyn what I say<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Narrat</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000594.tif" N="582">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="580">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan phebus duelt her in &thorn;is er&thorn;e a doun</L>
<L>As olde bookes maken mencioun</L>
<L>He was &thorn;e moste lusty bachiler</L>
<L N="108">Of al &thorn;is world and eek &thorn;e best archer</L>
<L>He slough phiton &thorn;e serpent as he lay</L>
<L>Slepyng agayn &thorn;e sonne vpon a day</L>
<L>And many another noble wor&thorn;y dede</L>
<L N="112">He with his bowe wrought as men may rede /</L>
<L>Pleyen he cou&thorn;e on euery mynstralcye</L>
<L>And syngen &thorn;at it was a melodye</L>
<L>To heren of his cleere vois &thorn;e soun</L>
<L N="116">Certes &thorn;e kyng of Thebes amphioun</L>
<L>That with his singyng wallid &thorn;at citee</L>
<L>Cou&thorn;e neuer synge half so wel as he /</L>
<L>Ther-to he was &thorn;e semlieste man</L>
<L N="120">That is or was si&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;e world bigan<MILESTONE N="248a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>what nedi&thorn; it his fortune to descriue</L>
<L>For in &thorn;is worlde is noon such on lyue</L>
<L>he was &thorn;er with fulfild of gentilesce</L>
<L N="124">Of honour and of parfyt wor&thorn;inesse</L>
<L>This phebus &thorn;at was flour of bachilerie</L>
<L>Als wel in fredom as in chiualrie</L>
<L>For to disport in signe of victorie</L>
<L N="128">Of phiton so as telle&thorn; vs &thorn;e storie</L>
<L>was wont to bere in his hond a bowe</L>
<L>Now had &thorn;is phebus in his hous a crowe</L>
<L>which in a cage he fostred many a day</L>
<L N="132">And taught it speken as men doon a iay
<PB REF="00000595.tif" N="583"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="581"></L>
<L>whit was &thorn;is crowe as is a snow-whyt swan</L>
<L>And countrefete the speche of euery man</L>
<L>he cou&thorn;e whan he schulde telle a tale</L>
<L N="136">Ther is wi&thorn;inne &thorn;is world no nightingale</L>
<L>Ne cou&thorn;e by an hundred &thorn;ousend del</L>
<L>Singe so wonder merily and wel</L>
<L>Now had &thorn;is phebus in his hous a wyf</L>
<L N="140">which &thorn;at he loued. more &thorn;an his lif</L>
<L>And night and day. did euermor diligence /</L>
<L>hir for to please. and doon hir reuerence</L>
<L>Sauf oonly if &thorn;e so&thorn; &thorn;at I schal sayn</L>
<L N="144">Ialous he was and wold haue kept hir fayn</L>
<L>For him were loth biiaped for to be /</L>
<L>And so is euery wight in such degre</L>
<L>But al for nought for it auaileth nou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="148">A good wyf &thorn;at is clene of werk and thought</L>
<L>Schuld not be kept in noon awayt certayn</L>
<L>And trewely &thorn;e labour is in vayn</L>
<L>To kepe a schrewe for it wil nought be</L>
<L N="152">This hold I for a verray nycete</L>
<L>To spille labour for to kepe wyues</L>
<L>Thus olde clerkes writen in her lyues</L>
<L>But now to purpos as I first bigan</L>
<L N="156">This wor&thorn;i phebus do&thorn; al &thorn;at he can</L>
<L>To pleasen hir wenyng by such plesaunce /</L>
<L>And for his manhod and his gouernaunce<MILESTONE N="248b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That no man schuld han put him fro hir grace</L>
<L N="160">But god it woot. &thorn;er may no man embrace</L>
<L>As to destroy a &thorn;ing. &thorn;e which nature</L>
<L>ha&thorn; naturelly. set in a creature</L>
<L>Tak any brid and put him in a cage</L>
<L N="164">And do al &thorn;in entent and &thorn;y corrage</L>
<L>To foster it tenderly wi&thorn; mete and drynk</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; alle &thorn;e deyntees &thorn;ou canst &thorn;ink</L>
<L>And keep it al so kyndly as &thorn;ou may</L>
<L N="168">Al &thorn;ough his cage of gold be neuer so gay
<PB REF="00000596.tif" N="584"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="582"></L>
<L>&YOGH;it ha&thorn; &thorn;is brid by twenty &thorn;ousand fold</L>
<L>Leuer to be. in forest wyd and cold</L>
<L>Gon ete wormes and such wrecchidnes</L>
<L N="172">For euer &thorn;is brid wil doon his busynes</L>
<L>To scape out of his cage whan he may</L>
<L>his liberte &thorn;e brid desireth ay</L>
<L>let take a cat and foster him wel wi&thorn; mylk/</L>
<L N="176">And tender fleisch and mak his bed of silk/</L>
<L>And let him see a mous go by &thorn;e wal</L>
<L>Anoon he wayueth mylk and fleisch and al</L>
<L>And euery deynte which is in &thorn;at hous</L>
<L N="180">Such appetit ha&thorn; he to ete &thorn;e mous</L>
<L>lo heer ha&thorn; lust his dominacioun</L>
<L>And appetit. flemeth discr[e]scioun</L>
<L>Also a sche wolf ha&thorn; a vilayns kynde /</L>
<L N="184">The lewidest. wolf &thorn;at sche may fynde</L>
<L>Or lest of reputacioun him wol sche take</L>
<L>In tyme whan hir lust/ to haue a make/</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;is ensamples. tel I by &thorn;is men</L>
<L N="188">That ben vntrewe and no &thorn;ing by wommen</L>
<L>For men han euer a licorous appetit</L>
<L>On lower &thorn;ing to parforme her delit</L>
<L>Than on her wyues ben &thorn;ay neuer so faire</L>
<L N="192">Ne neuer so trewe ne so debonaire</L>
<L>Fleissch is so newfangil with meschaunce</L>
<L>That we can in no &thorn;inge haue plesaunce</L>
<L>That soune&thorn; in to vertu eny while</L>
<L N="196">This phebus which &thorn;at &thorn;ought vpon no gile<MILESTONE N="249a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Deceyued was for al his iolite</L>
<L>For vnder him ano&thorn;er hadde sche/</L>
<L>A man of litil reputacioun</L>
<L N="200">Nought wor&thorn; to phebus in comparisoun</L>
<L>Mor harm it is it happeth ofte so</L>
<L>Of which &thorn;er come&thorn; bo&thorn;e harm and woo</L>
<L>And so bifel whan phebus was absent</L>
<L N="204">His wif anoon hath for hir lemman sent
<PB REF="00000597.tif" N="585"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="583"></L>
<L>hir lemman certes. &thorn;is is a knauisch speche</L>
<L>For&yogh;iue&thorn; it me and &thorn;at I &yogh;ow biseche</L>
<L>The wise plato saith as &yogh;e may rede</L>
<L N="208">&thorn;e word mot neede accorde wi&thorn; &thorn;e dede</L>
<L>If men schal telle propurly a &thorn;ing</L>
<L>The word mot corde wi&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;ing werkyng</L>
<L>I am a boystous [man] right thus say I</L>
<L N="212">There is no difference trewely</L>
<L>Bytwix a wyf &thorn;at is of heigh degre /</L>
<L>If of hir body dishonest sche be</L>
<L>And a pore wenche o&thorn;er &thorn;en &thorn;is</L>
<L N="216">If so be &thorn;ay werke bo&thorn;e amys</L>
<L>But the gentil in estat aboue</L>
<L>Sche schal be cleped his lady as in loue</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at o&thorn;er is a pore womman</L>
<L N="220">Sche schal be cleped his wenche and his lemman</L>
<L>And god it wot my goode lieue bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>Men layn &thorn;at oon as lowe as &thorn;at o&thorn;er</L>
<L>Right so betwixe atticles tirant</L>
<L N="224">And an outlawe or a &thorn;ef erraunt</L>
<L>The same I say &thorn;er is no difference</L>
<L>To alisaunder told was &thorn;is sentence</L>
<L>&thorn;at for &thorn;e tiraunt is of gretter might</L>
<L N="228">Bi force of meyne for to sle doun right</L>
<L>And brenne hous and home and make al playn</L>
<L>Lo &thorn;erfor is he cleped a Captayn</L>
<L>And for an outlawe ha&thorn; so smal meyne</L>
<L N="232">And may not doon so gret an harm as he</L>
<L>Ne bringe a contre to so gret meschief /</L>
<L>Men clepen him an outlawe or a &thorn;eef<MILESTONE N="249b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But for I am a man not texted wel</L>
<L N="236">I wil not telle of textes neuer a del</L>
<L>I wol go to my tale as I bigan</L>
<L>whan phebus wyf had sent for hir lemman</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;ay wrou&yogh;ten al her wil volage</L>
<L N="240">This white crow / &thorn;at heng alway in cage
<PB REF="00000598.tif" N="586"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="584"></L>
<L>Bihild her werk and sayde neuer a word</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at hom was come phebus &thorn;e lord</L>
<L>This Crowe song. Cuckow. Cockow. Cuckow</L>
<L N="244">what bird quod phebus what song syngistow</L>
<L>Ne were &thorn;ou wont so merily to synge</L>
<L>That to myn hert it was a reioysynge</L>
<L>To here &thorn;i vois. allas what song is &thorn;is</L>
<L N="248">By god quod he I synge not amys</L>
<L>Phebus quod he for al &thorn;y wor&thorn;ynes</L>
<L>For al &thorn;y beaute and &thorn;y gentiles</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;y songes and &thorn;y menstralcie /</L>
<L N="252">For al &thorn;y waytyng blered is &thorn;in ye /</L>
<L>with oon of litel reputacioun</L>
<L>Nought worth to &thorn;e as in comparisoun</L>
<L>The mountauns of a gnat so mot I &thorn;riue</L>
<L N="256">For on &thorn;y bed &thorn;y wif I saugh him swyue</L>
<L>what wol &yogh;e more &thorn;e crowe anoon him tolde /</L>
<L>By sadde toknes and by wordes bolde</L>
<L>how &thorn;at his wyf had doon hir leccherie</L>
<L N="260">him to gret schame and to gret vilonye</L>
<L>And told him oft/ he saugh it wi&thorn; his yen</L>
<L>This phebus gan awayward for to wryen</L>
<L>him &thorn;ought his sorwful herte brast on tuo</L>
<L N="264">his bowe he bent and sett &thorn;er-In a flo</L>
<L>And in his ire he ha&thorn; his wif I-slayn</L>
<L>&thorn;is is &thorn;effect &thorn;er is no more to sayn</L>
<L>For sorw of which he brak his menstralcye</L>
<L N="268">Bo&thorn;e harp. gitern. and sauterie</L>
<L>And eek he brak his arwes and his bowe</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at &thorn;us spak he to &thorn;e crowe</L>
<L>Traytour quod he wi&thorn; tunge of scorpioun</L>
<L N="272">Thow hast me brought to my confusioun<MILESTONE N="250a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Allas &thorn;at I was born why nere I deed</L>
<L>O dere wyf O gemme of lustyhed</L>
<L>That were to me so sad and eek so trewe</L>
<L N="276">Now list &thorn;ou deed with face pale of hewe
<PB REF="00000599.tif" N="587"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="585"></L>
<L>Ful gulteles &thorn;at dorst I swere I-wis</L>
<L>O racle hond to do so foule amys</L>
<L>O trouble wit O Ire recheles</L>
<L N="280">That vnauysed smytest gulteles</L>
<L>O wantrust ful of fals suspeccioun</L>
<L>wher was &thorn;y wit and &thorn;y discrecioun</L>
<L>O euery man be war of raclenesse</L>
<L N="284">Ne trowe no &thorn;ing wi&thorn;oute gret witnesse</L>
<L>Smyt nou&yogh;t to soone. er &thorn;at &thorn;ou wite why /</L>
<L>And be auysed wel and sobrely</L>
<L>Er &yogh;e doon eny execucioun</L>
<L N="288">Vpon &yogh;our Ire for suspeccioun</L>
<L>Allas a &thorn;ousand folk ha&thorn; racle Ire</L>
<L>Fordoon. or dun hath brou&yogh;t hem in &thorn;e myre</L>
<L>Allas for sorw / I wil my seluen sle</L>
<L N="292">And to &thorn;e crowe o false &thorn;eef sayd he</L>
<L>I wyl &thorn;e quyt anoon &thorn;y false tale /</L>
<L>Thow songe whilom as any nightyngale /</L>
<L>Now schaltow false &thorn;ef &thorn;y song forgoon</L>
<L N="296">And eek &thorn;y white fetheres euerich oon</L>
<L>Ne neuer in al &thorn;y lyf ne schaltow speke</L>
<L>Thus schal men on a fals &thorn;eef ben a-wreke</L>
<L>Thou and &thorn;in o[f]spring euer schuln be blake</L>
<L N="300">Ne neuer sweete noyse schul &yogh;e make</L>
<L>But euer crye agayn tempest and rayn</L>
<L>In tokenyng &thorn;at &thorn;urgh &thorn;e my wyf was slayn</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e crowe he stert and &thorn;at anoon</L>
<L N="304">And puld his white fe&thorn;eres euerychoon</L>
<L>And made him blak and raft him al his song</L>
<L>And eek his speche and out at dore him slong</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e deuel which I him bytake</L>
<L N="308">And for &thorn;is cause ben alle crowes blake</L>
<L>Lordyngs by &thorn;is ensample I &yogh;ow pray</L>
<L>Beth war and take&thorn; kepe what &yogh;e say /<MILESTONE N="250b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ne tellith neuer man in al &yogh;oure lif</L>
<L N="312">how &thorn;at ano&thorn;er man ha&thorn; dight his wyf
<PB REF="00000600.tif" N="588"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="586"></L>
<L>he wol &yogh;ou hatin mortelly certeyn</L>
<L>Daun Salamon as wise clerkes seyn</L>
<L>Teche&thorn; a man to kepe his tonge wel</L>
<L N="316">But as I sayd. I am nought tixted wel</L>
<L>But/ na&thorn;eles &thorn;us taughte me my dame</L>
<L>My sone thenk on &thorn;e crowe in goddes name</L>
<L>My son keep wel &thorn;y tonge and kep &thorn;y frend</L>
<L N="320">A wicked tonge. is worse &thorn;an a feend</L>
<L>My sone fro a feend men may hem blesse</L>
<L>My sone god of his endeles goodnesse</L>
<L>wallid a tonge wi&thorn; tee&thorn; and lippes eek</L>
<L N="324">For man schal him auyse what he speek</L>
<L>My sone ful ofte for to mochil speche /</L>
<L>ha&thorn; many a man be spilt as clerkes teche</L>
<L>But for a litil speche auisily</L>
<L N="328">Is no man schent to speke generally</L>
<L>My sone &thorn;y tonge scholdest &thorn;ou restreigne</L>
<L>At alle tyme but whan &thorn;ou dost &thorn;y peyne /</L>
<L>To speke of god in honour and prayere</L>
<L N="332">The firste vertu sone if &thorn;ou wilt lere</L>
<L>Is to restreigne and kepe wel &thorn;y tonge</L>
<L>Thus lerne clerkes whan &thorn;at &thorn;ay ben &yogh;onge</L>
<L>My sone of mochil speking euel auised</L>
<L N="336">Ther lasse speking had ynough suffised</L>
<L>Come&thorn; mochil harm &thorn;us was me told and taught</L>
<L>In mochel speche synne wanti&thorn; nought</L>
<L>wost wher of a racle tonge serue&thorn;</L>
<L N="340">Right a swerd for-kutte&thorn; and kerue&thorn;</L>
<L>An arm a tuo my dere sone right so</L>
<L>A tonge cutteth frendschip al a tuo</L>
<L>A iangler is to god abhominable</L>
<L N="344">Red Salamon so wys and honurable</L>
<L>Red Dauid in his psalmes reed Senek</L>
<L>My sone spek not. but wi&thorn; &thorn;y heed &thorn;u bek</L>
<L>Dissimul as &thorn;ou were deed if &thorn;at &thorn;ou heere</L>
<L N="348">A iangler speke of perilous mateere<MILESTONE N="251a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000601.tif" N="589"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="587"></L>
<L>The flemyng sai&thorn; and lere it if &thorn;e lest /</L>
<L>That litil iangling cause&thorn; mochil rest</L>
<L>My sone if &thorn;ou no wikked word hast sayd</L>
<L N="352">The thar not drede for to be bywrayd</L>
<L>But he &thorn;at ha&thorn; mys sayd I dar wel sayn</L>
<L>he may by no way clepe his word agayn</L>
<L>Thing &thorn;at is sayd. is sayd. and for&thorn; it go&thorn;</L>
<L N="356">Though him repent or be him neuer so lo&thorn;</L>
<L>He is his &thorn;ral to whom &thorn;at/ he ha&thorn; sayd</L>
<L>A tale of which he is now yuel a payd</L>
<L>My sone be war and be noon auctour newe /</L>
<L N="360">Of tydyngs whe&thorn;er &thorn;ay ben fals or trewe /</L>
<L>wher-so &thorn;ou comest amonges heih or lowe /</L>
<L>kep wel &thorn;y tonge / and thenk vpon &thorn;e crowe</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Here endith &thorn;e tale of &thorn;e crowe<NOTE>[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
