<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000610.tif" N="598">

<PB REF="00000611.tif" N="599">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="593">
<HEADNOTE><P>[There are no paragraph-breaks or line-numbers in the MS., but Tyrwhitt's breaks are kept in the print for convenience sake.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<EPIGRAPH>
<BIBL>&para; Ier. 6<SUP>o</SUP>.</BIBL>
<Q>State super vias &amp; videte et interrogate de semitis antiquis que sit via bona et ambulate in ea et inuenietis &para; refrigerium animabus vestris, &amp;c.</Q></EPIGRAPH>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<P>[75] Owre swete lord god of heuen &thorn;at no man wil perische but wol &thorn;at we comen alle to &thorn;e knowleche of him and to &thorn;e blisful lif &thorn;at is perdurable / [76] ammonestith vs by &thorn;e prophet Ieremye &thorn;at saith in &thorn;is wise [77] &para; Stondeth vpon &thorn;e weyes and see&thorn; &amp; axe&thorn; of olde pathes &thorn;at is to sayn of old sentence which is &thorn;e good way. [78] . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> and &yogh;e schul fynde refresshyng for &yogh;oure soules &amp;c. [79] &para; Many ben &thorn;e wayes espirituels &thorn;at leden folk to oure lord Ih&umacr; crist/. and to &thorn;e regne of glorie. [80] Of whiche weyes &thorn;er is a ful noble way and ful couenable which may not faile to man ne to womman &thorn;at &thorn;orugh synne ha&thorn; mysgon fro &thorn;e right way of Ierusalem celestial [81] and &thorn;is wey is cleped penitence &para; Of which men schulden gladly herken and enquere wi&thorn; al here herte [82] to wyte what is penitence and whens it is cleped penitence and in what maner and in how many maners been &thorn;e acciones or workynges of pe|naunce [83] and how many spieces ben of penitences &amp; whiche &thorn;inges apperteynen and byhouen to penitence. and whiche &thorn;inges destourben penitence
<PB REF="00000612.tif" N="600"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="594"></P>
<P>[84] &para; Seint ambrose sai&thorn;. &thorn;at penitence is &thorn;e pleynyng <MILESTONE N="252b" UNIT="folio">of man for &thorn;e gult &thorn;at he ha&thorn; doon. and no more to do ony &thorn;ing for which him oughte to pleigne [85] &para; And som doctour saith. penitence is wayment|ynyge of man &thorn;at sorwe&thorn; for his synne and peyne&thorn; himself for he ha&thorn; mysdoon [86] &para; Penitence wi&thorn; certeyn circumstaunces; is verray repentaunce of man &thorn;at holt himself in sorwe and in woo for his giltes [87] &para; And for he schal be verray penitent; he schal first/ bywaile &thorn;e synnes &thorn;at he ha&thorn; do and stedfastly purposen in his hert to hauen schrifte of mouth. and to doon satisfaccioun [88] and neuer to do &thorn;ing for which him oughte more to bywayle or to complayne. and to con|tinue in goode werkes or elles his repentaunce may nou&yogh;t auayle [89] For as saith seint Isidre &para; he is a iapere and a gabbere and no verray repentaunt &thorn;at eft soone do&thorn; &thorn;ing for which him oughte to repente; [90] wepynge. and nou&yogh;t for to stynte to doon synne may nou&yogh;t auayle [91] &para; But na&thorn;eles men schal hope &thorn;at at euery tyme &thorn;at men fallith. be it neuer so ofte; &thorn;at he may arise &thorn;orugh peni|tence if he haue grace &para; But certeyn it is a gret doute. [92] For as saith seint Gregory. Vnne&thorn;e arist he out of his synne &thorn;at is charged wi&thorn; &thorn;e charge of yuel vsage [93] &para; And &thorn;erfore repentaunt folk &thorn;at stinte for to synne and forlete synne er &thorn;at synne forlete hem. holy chirche holt hem siker of her sauacioun. [94] And he &thorn;at synneth and verraily repentith him in his last ende; holy chirche &yogh;it hope&thorn; his sauacioun by &thorn;e grete mercy of oure lord ih&umacr; crist/ for his repentaunce. but take &thorn;e siker way</P>
<P>[95] &para; And now si&thorn; &thorn;at I haue declared &yogh;ow what &thorn;ing is penitence. now schul &yogh;e vnderstonde &thorn;at &thorn;er ben &thorn;re acciouns of penitence [96] &para; The first is &thorn;at if a man be bapti&yogh;ed after &thorn;at he ha&thorn; synned. [97] Seint augustyn saith but if he be penitent for his olde synful lif; he may not bygynne &thorn;e newe 
<PB REF="00000613.tif" N="601"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="595"> clene lif [98] &para; For certes if he be bapti&yogh;ed wi&thorn;oute penitence of his olde gilt. he receyueth &thorn;e mark of baptisme; but nou&yogh;t &thorn;e grace ne &thorn;e remissioun of his synnes til he haue repentaunce verray [99] &para; Ano&thorn;er defaute is &thorn;is &thorn;at men doon deedly synne after &thorn;at &thorn;ay haue receyued baptisme [100] &para; &thorn;e &thorn;ridde defaute is &thorn;at men fallen in to venial synne after here baptisme fro day to day. [101] &thorn;er of sai&thorn; seint austyn &para; That penitence of goode men and of humble <MILESTONE N="253a" UNIT="folio">folk is &thorn;e penitens of euery day</P>
<P>[102] &para; The spices of penitence ben thre &para; That oon of hem is solempne &para; Ano&thorn;er is comune &para; And &thorn;e &thorn;ridde is pryue [103] &para; Thilke penaunce &thorn;at is so|lempne is in tuo maners as is to be put out of holy chirche in lente for slau&yogh;tre of childre and such maner &thorn;ing [104] &para; Ano&thorn;er is whan a man ha&thorn; synned openly. of which synne &thorn;e fame is openly spoken in &thorn;e contre. and &thorn;anne holy chirche by iugge|ment streyneth him to doon open penaunce [105] &para; Comune penaunce is &thorn;at prestes enioynen men comunly in certeyn caas. as for to goon per aduenture naked in pilgrimage or barfot [106] &para; Priue penaunce is &thorn;ilk &thorn;at men doon alday for priue synnes of whiche we schryue vs priuely and receyuen priue penaunce</P>
<P>[107] &para; Now schalt &thorn;ou vnderstonde what bihoueth and is necessarie to verray parfyt penitence. and &thorn;is stondith in &thorn;re &thorn;inges [108] &para; Contricioun of hert &para; Con|fessioun of mouth &para; And satisfaccion. [109] &para; For whiche saith seint Iohan Crisostom &para; penitence distreyneth a man to accepte benignely euery peyne &thorn;at him is enioyned with contricioun of herte and schrift of mouth with satis|faccioun and in werking of alle maner humblete [110] and &thorn;is is fruytful penitence. agayn &thorn;re &thorn;inges in whiche we wra&thorn;&thorn;e our lord ih&umacr; crist/. [111] &thorn;is is to sayn by delit in &thorn;inking &para; By rechelesnes in speking &para; By wicked synful werkyng [112] &para; Again &thorn;ese 
<PB REF="00000614.tif" N="602"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="596"> &thorn;re wickid gultes is penitence &thorn;at may be likned vnto a tre</P>
<P>[113] &para; The roote of &thorn;is tre is contricioun &thorn;at hydi&thorn; him in &thorn;e hert/ of him &thorn;at is verray repentaunt &para; Right as &thorn;e roote of a tree hide&thorn; him in &thorn;e eor&thorn;e. [114] of &thorn;e roote of contricioun springeth a stalk &thorn;at bereth braunches and leeues of confessioun and fruyt of satisfaccioun [115] &para; For whiche crist saith in his gospel &para; Doth digne fruyt of penitence. For by &thorn;is fruyt may men knowe &thorn;is tree and nou&yogh;t by &thorn;e roote &thorn;at is hyd in &thorn;e hert of a man ne by &thorn;e braunches ne the leuys of confessioun [116] &para; And &thorn;erfore oure lord ih&umacr; crist sai&thorn; &thorn;us &para; By &thorn;e fruyt of hem schul &yogh;e knowe hem [117] &para; Of &thorn;is roote eek springe&thorn; a seed of grace. &thorn;e which seed is mooder of sikurnes &para; And &thorn;is seed is egre and hoot [118] &para; The grace of &thorn;is seed springeth of god &thorn;orugh re|membraunce of &thorn;e day of doom and of &thorn;e peynes of helle [119] &para; Of &thorn;is matier saith Salomon &thorn;at in &thorn;e drede of god man forleteth his synne [120] <MILESTONE N="253b" UNIT="folio">&para; The hete of &thorn;is seed is &thorn;e loue of god &amp; &thorn;e desiring of &thorn;e ioye perdurable [121] &para; &THORN;is hete draweth &thorn;e hert of man to god and do&thorn; him hate his synne [122] &para; For so&thorn;e &thorn;er is no &thorn;ing &thorn;at serue&thorn; so wel to a child as &thorn;e mylk of his norice &para; Ne no &thorn;ing is to him more abhom|inable &thorn;an &thorn;e milk whan it is melled mete. [123] &para; Right so &thorn;e synful man &thorn;at/ loue&thorn; his synne. him semeth it is to him most swete of eny &thorn;ing [124] &para; But fro &thorn;at tyme he loue&thorn; sadly oure lord ih&umacr; crist and desire&thorn; &thorn;e lif perdurable. &thorn;er nys to him no &thorn;ing more abhominable / [125] for so&thorn;ly &thorn;e lawe of god is &thorn;e loue of god &para; For which<NOTE PLACE="marg">Dilexi legem tuam &amp;c.</NOTE> Dauyd saith &para; I haue loued &thorn;y lawe and hated wikkednesse and hate &para; he &thorn;at loue&thorn; god kepeth his lawe and his word [126] &para; This tree saugh the prophete daniel in spirit vpon &thorn;e auysioun of Nabugodonosor whan he coun|seiled him to do penaunce. [127] &para; Penaunce is tre of lif to hem &thorn;at it receyuen and &thorn;at holdeth him 
<PB REF="00000615.tif" N="603"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="597"> in verray penitence is blessed after &thorn;e sentence of Salomon</P>
<P>[128] In &thorn;is penitence or contricioun; men schal vn|derstonde foure &thorn;inges that is to sayn what is contricioun and whiche ben &thorn;e causes &thorn;at moeuen men to con|tricioun and how he schulde be contrit and what con|tricioun auaileth to &thorn;e soule [129] &para; &THORN;anne it is &thorn;us &thorn;at contricioun is &thorn;e verray sorwe &thorn;at a man receyue&thorn; in his herte for his synnes wi&thorn; sad purpos to schryue him and to doo penaunce and neuer more to don synne. [130] &para; And &thorn;is sorwe schal be in &thorn;is maner as saith seint Bernad &para; It schal ben heuy and greuous and ful scharp and poynaunt in herte [131] &para; First for man ha&thorn; agilted his lord and his creatour and more scharp and poynaunt. For he ha&thorn; agiltid his fader celestial. [132] and &yogh;it more scharp and poynaunt for he ha&thorn; wratthed and agilt him &thorn;at bou&yogh;t him wi&thorn; his precious blood and ha&thorn; delyuered vs fro &thorn;e bondes of synne and fro &thorn;e cruelte of &thorn;e deuel and fro &thorn;e peynes of helle //</P>
<P>[133] &para; &thorn;e causes &thorn;at oughten to moeue a man to con|tricioun<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Sex sunt cause que mouent homine&yogh; ad con|tricionem</NOTE> ben .vj. &para; First a man schal remembre him of his synnes. [134] but loke &thorn;at &thorn;ilke remem|brance be to no delyt of him by no way but gret schame and sorwe for his gilt. For Iob. saith &thorn;at synful men doon werkes wor&thorn;y of confessioun [135] and &thorn;erfor saith E&yogh;echiel &para; I wol remembre alle &thorn;e &yogh;eres of my lyf in bitternesse of myn hert. [136] and god saith in thapocalips. <MILESTONE N="254a" UNIT="folio">Remembre &yogh;ow from whens &thorn;at &yogh;e ben falle. For biforn &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at &yogh;e synned. &yogh;e were &thorn;e children of god . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> [137] &para; But for &yogh;oure synne &yogh;e be woxe &thorn;ral and foul and membres of &thorn;e feend. hate of aungels. sclaunder of holy chirche &amp; foode of &thorn;e fals serpent. perpetual matier of &thorn;e fuyr of helle [138] &para; and &yogh;et more foule and abhom|inable For &yogh;e trespassen so ofte tyme as do&thorn; &thorn;e hound &thorn;at torne&thorn; to ete his spewyng. [139] &amp; &yogh;et 
<PB REF="00000616.tif" N="604"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="598"> &yogh;e ben fouler for &yogh;oure longe continuyng in synne and &yogh;oure synful vsage. for whiche &yogh;e ben roten in &yogh;oure synne as a beest in his donge [140] &para; Suche maner of &thorn;oughtes make a man haue schame of his synne and no delit. and god sai&thorn; by &thorn;e prophete I&yogh;echiel [141] &para; &YOGH;e schul remembre &yogh;ow of &yogh;oure weyes. &amp; &thorn;ay schal displese &yogh;ow so&thorn;ly &para; Synnes ben &thorn;e way &thorn;at leden folk to helle</P>
<P>[142] &para; The secounde cause &thorn;at oughte make a man to haue desdeyn of his synne is &thorn;is. &thorn;at as sei&thorn; seint petre / &para; who so doth synne is &thorn;ral of synne. and synne put a man in gret &thorn;raldom. [143] and &thorn;er|fore saith &thorn;e prophete. E&yogh;echiel. I wente sorwful in desdeyn of myself &para; Certes wel oughte a man haue desdeyn of synne and wi&thorn;drawe him fro &thorn;at &thorn;raldom and vilonye. [144] and lo what sai&thorn; Seneca. in &thorn;is matiere. he sai&thorn; &thorn;us &para; Though I wiste &thorn;at god nere god. man schulde neuer knowe it: &yogh;it wold I haue disdeyn for to do synne [145] and &thorn;e same Seneca also saith &para; I am born to gretter &thorn;inges &thorn;an to be &thorn;ral to my body or &thorn;an for to make of my body a &thorn;ral [146] &para; Ne a fouler &thorn;ral may no man ne womman make of his body &thorn;an &yogh;iue his body to synne [147] &para; And were it &thorn;e foulest cherl or &thorn;e foulest womman &thorn;at lyue&thorn; and lest of value; &yogh;et is &thorn;anne synne more foul and more in seruitute [148] Euer fro &thorn;e heigher dege &thorn;at man falli&thorn; &thorn;e more he is &thorn;ral and more to god vile and abhomin|able [149] &para; O goode god wel oughte a man haue gret disdayn o such a &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;orugh synne &thorn;er he was free now is he maked bonde. [150] an &thorn;erfore sai&thorn; seint austyn &para; If &thorn;ou hast disdayn . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;iself schuldest doon synne; haue &thorn;ou &thorn;anne desdeyn &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;iself schuldist do synne. [151] tak reward of &thorn;y value &thorn;at &thorn;ou be nou&yogh;t to foul in &thorn;iself [152] Allas wel oughte men haue disdeyn to be 
<PB REF="00000617.tif" N="605"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="599"> seruauntes &amp; &thorn;ralles to synne. &amp; sore ben aschamed of hemself [153] &thorn;at god of his endeles <MILESTONE N="254b" UNIT="folio">goodnes ha&thorn; set hem in heigh estate or &yogh;euen hem witte. streng&thorn; of body. hele. beaute. prosperite. [154] and bought hem fro &thorn;e de&thorn; wi&thorn; his herte blood &thorn;at &thorn;ay so vnkyndely a&yogh;einst his gentilesce quyten so vileynsly to slau&yogh;ter of her oughne soules [155] &para; O goode god &yogh;e wommen &thorn;at ben of so gret beaute remembre&thorn; &yogh;ow of &thorn;e prouerbe of Salamon &thorn;at saith. [156] he likeneth a fair womman &thorn;at is a fool of hir body. to a ryng of gold &thorn;at were in &thorn;e groyn of a sowe [157] &para; For right as a sowe wrote&thorn; in euerich ordure; so wrootith sche hir beaute in stynkyng ordure of synne</P>
<P>[158] &para; The &thorn;ridde cause &thorn;at ou&yogh;te moeue a man to contricioun is drede of &thorn;e day of doome. &amp; of &thorn;e orrible peynes of helle [159] &para; For as seint Ierom saith. At euery tyme &thorn;at I remembre of &thorn;e day of doom; I quake [160] &para; For whan I ete or drinke or what so &thorn;at I doo euer semeth me &thorn;at &thorn;e trompe sowne&thorn; in myn eere. [161] Riseth &yogh;e vp &thorn;at ben deede / and come&thorn; to &thorn;e Iuggement [162] &para; O goode god. mochil ought a man to drede such a iuggement. &thorn;er as we schul be alle as sei&thorn; seint poul Biforn &thorn;e sete of our lord ih&umacr; crist [163] wher as he schal make a general con|gregacioun wher as no man may ben absent. [164] for certes &thorn;er auayle&thorn; non essoyne ne excusacioun [165] &para; And nou&yogh;t oonly &thorn;at oure defaute schal be . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> openly knowen. [166] and as seint Bernard sai&thorn; &para; Ther schal no pleynyng auayle ne no sleight &para; we schuln &yogh;iue rekenyng of euery ydel word [167] &para; Ther schulle we haue a Iuge &thorn;at may nou&yogh;t be disceyued ne corupt. and why; For certes alle oure &thorn;oughtes ben descouered as to him ne for prayer ne for meede he nyl not / be corupt [168] &para; And &thorn;erfor sai&thorn; Salamon &para; The wra&thorn;&thorn;e of god ne wol not be corrupt &para; And &thorn;erfor sai&thorn; Salomon &para; The wra&thorn; of 
<PB REF="00000618.tif" N="606"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="600"> god ne wol nou&yogh;t spare no wight for praier ne for &yogh;ifte &para; And &thorn;erfore at &thorn;e day of doome &thorn;er is noon hope to eshcape [169] wherfor as seint anselm sei&thorn; &para; Ful greet anguisch schuln &thorn;e synful folk haue at &thorn;at tyme [170] &para; &thorn;ere schal &thorn;e sterne and &thorn;e wro&thorn; Iugge sitte aboue and vnder him &thorn;e horrible put of helle open to de|stroye him &thorn;at mot byknowe his synnes which synnes openly ben schewed byforn god and biforn euery creature [171] &para; and on &thorn;e lift syde mo deuelis &thorn;an herte may &thorn;ynke for to hary and to drawe &thorn;e synful to pyne of helle [172] &para; And wi&thorn;|inne &thorn;e hertes of folk schal be &thorn;e bytyng <MILESTONE N="255a" UNIT="folio">conscience and wi&thorn;oute for&thorn; schal be &thorn;e world al brennyng [173] &para; whider schal &thorn;anne &thorn;e wrecche synful man. Flee to hyden him; Certes he may not hyde him. he moot come for&thorn; and schewe him [174] &para; For certes as seith seynt Ierom &para; The er&thorn;e schal caste him out/ of him and &thorn;e see also and &thorn;e aer also &thorn;at schal be ful of &thorn;under-clappes and lightnynges [175] &para; Now so&thorn;ly who-so wel remembrith him of &thorn;ese tydynges; I gesse his synne schal not torne him to delit but/ to gret sorw for drede of &thorn;e peyne of helle. [176] and &thorn;er|fore sai&thorn; Iob. to god &para; Suffre lord &thorn;at I may a while biwayle and wepe or I go wi&thorn; oute retournynge to &thorn;e derk lond couered wi&thorn; derknes of de&thorn; [177] to &thorn;e lond of mysese and of derknesse wher as is &thorn;e schadow of deth. wher as is noon order [ne] ordinaunce but grislich drede &thorn;at euer schal last [178] &para; loo her may &yogh;e see &thorn;at Iob prayde respit a while to wepe and biwayle his trespas &para; For forso&thorn;e oon day of respit is bettre &thorn;an al &thorn;e tresor in &thorn;is world. [179] and for as moche as a man may aquyte himself byforn god by penaunce in &thorn;is world and not by tresor; &thorn;erfore schuld he praye to god &yogh;iue him respit a while to wepe and to waile his trespas. [180] for certes al . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> 
<PB REF="00000619.tif" N="607"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="601"> &thorn;e world nys but a litel &thorn;ing at regard of &thorn;e sorwe of helle [181] &para; The cause why &thorn;at Iob. calle&thorn; helle &thorn;e lond of derknes; [182] vnderstondith &thorn;at he clepith it lond or eor&thorn;e for it is stable and neuer schal fayle. derk; for he &thorn;at is in helle hat defaut/ of light material. [183] for certes &thorn;e derke light &thorn;at schal come out of &thorn;e fuyr &thorn;at euer schal brenne / schal torne him to peyne &thorn;at is in helle for it schewi&thorn; him to &thorn;orrible deueles &thorn;at him tormenten [184] couered wi&thorn; the derknes of deth &thorn;at is to sayn &thorn;at he &thorn;at is in helle schal haue defaute of &thorn;e sight of god &para; For certes &thorn;e sight of god is &thorn;e lif perdurable. [185] &thorn;e derk|nes of deth ben &thorn;e synnes &thorn;at &thorn;e wrecchid man ha&thorn; doon whiche &thorn;at stourben him to see &thorn;e face of god right as a derk cloude do&thorn; bitwixe vs and &thorn;e sonne [186] &para; lond of myseyse; By cause &thorn;at &thorn;ere ben &thorn;re maner of defautes agains &thorn;re &thorn;inges &thorn;at folk of &thorn;is world han in &thorn;is present lif &thorn;at is to sayn. honures. delices. and richesses [187] &para; Agayns honours. han &thorn;ey in helle / schame and confusioun. [188] For wel &yogh;e witen &thorn;at men clepyn honure &thorn;e reuerence &thorn;at men doon to &thorn;e man. but in helle is <MILESTONE N="255b" UNIT="folio">noon honour ne reuerence. for certes no more reuerence schal ben doon to a kyng &thorn;an to a knaue [189] &para; For which god sai&thorn; by &thorn;e prophete Ieremie &para; Thilke folk / &thorn;at me displesen schul be despit [190] &para; Honour is eke cleped gret lord|schipe. &thorn;ere schal no wight seruen o&thorn;ir but of harm and of torment &para; honour eek is cleped gret dignite and heigh|nes; but in helle schulle &thorn;ay be al fortrode of deueles [191] &para; And god saith. thorrible deueles schuln goon and comen vpon &thorn;e heedes of dampned folk. And &thorn;is is for als moche as &thorn;e heyher &thorn;at &thorn;ay were in &thorn;is present lif; &thorn;e more schuln &thorn;ay ben abatid and defouled in helle [192] &para; Agayns riches of &thorn;is world schuln &thorn;ay han mysese of pouert. A &thorn;is pouert schal be in .iiij. &thorn;inges [193] In defaut of tresor of which as 
<PB REF="00000620.tif" N="608"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="602"> dauid saith &para; The riche folk &thorn;at embraseden and onedin in al here herte &thorn;e tresor of &thorn;is world. schuln slepen in &thorn;e slepyng of deth and no &thorn;ing schuln &thorn;ay fynde in her hondes of al her tresor [194] &para; &amp; more-ouer &thorn;e mysease of helle schal be in &thorn;e defaut of mete and drink. [195] For god saith &thorn;us by moyses &para; Thay schul be wasted by hunger and &thorn;e briddes of helle schuln deuoure hem wi&thorn; bittir teeth and &thorn;e galle of &thorn;e dragoun schal be her drink &amp; &thorn;e venym of &thorn;e dragoun here morsels [196] &para; And for&thorn;er more ouer her misease schal be in defaut of clo&thorn;ing/ for &thorn;ay schul be naked in body as of clo&thorn;ing &para; For &thorn;ay schuln be nakid of body saue of fuyr in which &thorn;ay brenne and o&thorn;er fil&thorn;is. [197] and naked schuln &thorn;ay be of soule. of alle maner vertues which &thorn;at is clo&thorn;ing of soule &para; wher ben &thorn;anne &thorn;e gaye robes. and &thorn;e softe scheetis and &thorn;e smale schirtes. [198] lo what sai&thorn; of hem &thorn;e prophete Isaye &para; vnder hem schuln be strawed motthis and here couertours schuln ben of wormes of helle [199] &para; And for&thorn;er mor ouer here disease schal be in defaute of frendes. for he is not pouere that ha&thorn; goode frendes. but here is no frend. [200] For ney&thorn;er god ne no creature schal be frend vnto hem. and euerich of hem schal hate o&thorn;er wi&thorn; dedly hate [201] &para; The sones and the dou&yogh;tres schuln rebellen agayns &thorn;e fader and &thorn;e mooder and kynrede agayns kynrede and chiden and despisen euerich of hem o&thorn;er bo&thorn;e day and night. as god saith by &thorn;e prophete Michias [202] &para; And &thorn;e louyng children &thorn;at whilom <MILESTONE N="256a" UNIT="folio">loueden so fleisschliche euerych o&thorn;er; wolden euerych of hem eten o&thorn;er if &thorn;ay mi&yogh;ten [203] for how schulden &thorn;ay louen hem togider in &thorn;e peyne of helle; whan &thorn;ay hated euerych of hem o&thorn;er in &thorn;e prosperite of &thorn;is lif. [204] For trustith wel her fleisshly loue was dedly hate as sai&thorn; &thorn;e prophete dauid. who-so &thorn;at loueth wickid|nes hate&thorn; his soule. [205] And who-so hati&thorn; his oughne soule. certis he may loue noon o&thorn;er wight 
<PB REF="00000621.tif" N="609"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="603"> in no manere [206] &para; And &thorn;erfore in helle is no solace ne frendschipe. but euer &thorn;e more flesshly kynredes &thorn;at ben in helle; &thorn;e more cursynges &thorn;e more chyd|ynges and &thorn;e more deedly hate &thorn;er is among hem [207] And for&thorn;er ouer &thorn;ay schul haue defaute of alle manere delices &para; For certis delices ben &thorn;e appetites of &thorn;y fyue wittes as sight hieryng. smellyng. sauor|ing and touching [208] &para; But in helle here sight schal be ful of derknesse / and of smoke and &thorn;erfore ful of teeris. and her hieryng ful of waymentynge and of gruntynge of teeth as sai&thorn; ih&umacr; crist // [209] &para; here nose &thorn;urles schuln ben ful of stynkyng stynk. and as saith ysaye &thorn;e prophete &para; here sauoringe schal be ful of bitter galle. [210] and touchyng of al here body y-couered with fuyr &thorn;at neuer schal quenche / and wi&thorn; wormes &thorn;at neuer schuln deyen / as god sai&thorn; by &thorn;e mou&thorn; of ysaie [211] &para; And for al so moche as &thorn;ay schuln nou&yogh;t/ wene/ &thorn;at &thorn;ay may deyen for peyne / and by here deth fle fro peyne. &thorn;at may &thorn;ay vnderstonde in &thorn;e word of Iob / &thorn;at sai&thorn; &para; Ther as is &thorn;e schadow of deth [212] &para; Certes a schadow ha&thorn; &thorn;e liknesse of the &thorn;ing of which it is a schadow. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> [213] Right so fareth &thorn;e peyne of helle. it is lik de&thorn;. for &thorn;e horrible anguisshe. And why; for it peyne&thorn; hem euer as though men scholden deye anon. But certes &thorn;ay schul not deye. [214] For as saith Seint GreGory &para; To wrecchid caytifs shal be &yogh;iue deth wi&thorn;oute deth and ende wi&thorn;outen ende / and defaute withouten faylinge. [215] For here deth schal alway lyuen. and here ende schal euermore bygynne. and here defaute schal not fayle [216] &para; And &thorn;erfor sai&thorn; seint Iohan &thorn;e euaungelist &para; &thorn;ay schul folwe de&thorn;. and &thorn;ay schuln nou&yogh;t fynde him. and &thorn;ay schul desire to deyen And deth schal flee fro hem. [217] &para; and eek Iob. sai&thorn;. &thorn;at in helle is noon ordre of rule [218] &para; And al be it &thorn;at god ha&thorn; creat al &thorn;ing in right ordre and no &thorn;ing wi&thorn;|oute 
<PB REF="00000622.tif" N="610"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="604"> ordre. but <MILESTONE N="256b" UNIT="folio">alle &thorn;inges ben ordeyned and noum|bred; &yogh;it na&thorn;eles &thorn;ay &thorn;at ben dampned been nou&yogh;t in ordre ne holden non ordre [219] For &thorn;e eor&thorn;e schal bere hem no fruyt [220] &para; For as &thorn;e prophete dauid sai&thorn;. God schal destroye &thorn;e fruyt of &thorn;e eor&thorn;e as for hem. ne watir schal &yogh;iue hem no moysture ne &thorn;e aier non refreisching. ne fuyr no light. [221] For as sei&thorn; seint Basile &para; The brennyng of &thorn;e fuyr of &thorn;is world schal god &yogh;iue in helle to hem &thorn;at ben dampnyd. [222] But &thorn;e light and &thorn;e clernesse / schal be &yogh;eue to heuene to his children. Right as &thorn;e goode man &yogh;eue fleisch to his children and bones to his houndes / [223] &para; And for &thorn;ay schul haue noon hope to eschape. sai&thorn; seint Iob. atte laste &thorn;at &thorn;er schal horrour and grisly drede duelle wi&thorn;outen ende [224] &para; horrour is alway drede of harm &thorn;at is to come. and &thorn;is drede schal euer duelle in &thorn;e hertes of hem &thorn;at ben dampnyd. And &thorn;erfore han &thorn;ay lorn al here hope for vij. causes [225] &para; First / for god &thorn;at is here Iugge schal be wi&thorn;oute mercy to hem ne &thorn;ay may not please him ne noon of his halwes Ne &thorn;ey may &yogh;iue no &thorn;ing for here raunsoun / [226] ne &thorn;ay haue no voice to speke to him. ne &thorn;ay may not fle fro peyne. ne &thorn;ay haue no goodnes in hem. &thorn;at &thorn;ay may schewe to deliuere hem fro peyne [227] &para; And &thorn;erfore sai&thorn; Salomon / The wikked man deyeth. and whan he is deed; he schal haue noon hope to eschape fro peyne [228] &para; who-so wolde &thorn;anne wel vn|derstonde &thorn;ese peynes and bythynk him wel &thorn;at he ha&thorn; deserued &thorn;ilke peynes for his synnes &para; Certes he schulde haue more talent to sikyn and to wepe &thorn;an for to synge or pleye [229] &para; For as &thorn;at Salamon sai&thorn; &para; who-so &thorn;at &thorn;e science to knowe &thorn;e peynes &thorn;at ben establid and ordeynt for synne; he wolde make sorwe [230] &para; Thilke science as sai&thorn; seint austyn make&thorn; a man to wayment in his herte</P>
<P>[231] &para; The four&thorn;e poynt &thorn;at oughte make a man 
<PB REF="00000623.tif" N="611"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="605"> haue contricioun is &thorn;e sorwful remembraunce of &thorn;e good &thorn;at he hath left to doon heer in eor&thorn;e. and eek &thorn;e good &thorn;at he ha&thorn; lorn [232] &para; So&thorn;ly &thorn;e goode werkes &thorn;at he hath left; ey&thorn;er &thorn;ay been &thorn;e goode werkes &thorn;at he wrought er he fel in to deedly synne; or elles &thorn;ai ben &thorn;e goode werkes &thorn;at he . . . . .[233] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> dede er he fel into synne ben amortised. and astoneyed and dullid by ofte synnynge. [234] &thorn;at o&thorn;ere goode werkes that he wrou&yogh;te whil he lay in dedly synne been outrely deede <MILESTONE N="257a" UNIT="folio">as to &thorn;e lif perdurable in heuen. [235] &thorn;anne &thorn;ilke goode werkes &thorn;at ben mortified by ofte synnyng whiche goode werkes he dede whiles he was in charite ne mowe neuer quyken agayn withouten verray penitence. [236] And &thorn;erof saith god by &thorn;e mouth of E&yogh;echiel &para; That if &thorn;e rightful man re|tourne agayn fro his rightwisnesse and werke wikked|nesse. schal he liue; [237] nay. For alle &thorn;e goode werkes &thorn;at he ha&thorn; wrought ne schuln neuer be in remembrance for he schal dye in his synne. [238] And vpon &thorn;ilke chapitre saith seint Gregory &thorn;us. &thorn;at we schuln vnder|stonde &thorn;is principally. [239] That whan we doon dedly synne it is for nou&yogh;t &thorn;anne to reherse or to drawe in to memorie &thorn;e goode werkes &thorn;at we han wrought biforn. [240] For certis in &thorn;e werkyng of &thorn;e dedly synne &thorn;er is no trust to no good werkes that we han don biforne &thorn;is tyme. &thorn;at is to say as for to haue &thorn;erby &thorn;e lif per|durable in heuen. [241] But na&thorn;eles &thorn;e goode werkes quiken agayn and comen again and helpen and auailen to haue &thorn;e lif perdurable in heuen whan we han contricioun [242] &para; But so&thorn;ly &thorn;e goode werkes &thorn;at men doon whil &thorn;at &thorn;ai ben in deedly synne. for as moche as &thorn;ay were doon in dedly synne; &thorn;ay may neuer quyken . . [243] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> &para; And al be it &thorn;at &thorn;ay auailen not to haue &thorn;e lif perdurable; &yogh;it auaylen 
<PB REF="00000624.tif" N="612"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="606"> &thorn;ay to abbrigging of &thorn;e peyne of helle or elles to gete temporal riches. [244] Or elles &thorn;at god wol &thorn;e ra&thorn;er enlumyne and lightene &thorn;e hert of &thorn;e synful man to haue repentaunce. [245] and eek &thorn;ey auailen for to vsen a man to do goode werkes &thorn;at &thorn;e feend haue &thorn;e lasse power of his soule. [246] &para; And &thorn;us &thorn;e curteys lord ih&umacr; crist ne wolde nou&yogh;t no good werk be lost. For in som what it schal auaile. [247] But for als moche as &thorn;e goode werkes &thorn;at men don whil &thorn;ay ben in good lif ben amortised by synne folwyng and eek sith &thorn;at alle the goode werkes &thorn;at men doon whil &thorn;ay ben in dedly synne been outrely deede as for to haue &thorn;e lif perdurable; [248] wel may &thorn;at man &thorn;at no goode werkes werki&thorn; synge &thorn;ilke newe freisch song. Iay tout perdu moun temps et moun labour [249] For certis synne byreueth a man bo&thorn;e goodnes of nature and eek &thorn;e goodnes of grace [250] &para; For so&thorn;ly &thorn;e grace of &thorn;e holy gost fare&thorn; lik fyre &thorn;at may not ben ydel. For fuyr as it forleti&thorn; his werk|yng it faileth anoon &para; And right so whan &thorn;e grace faile&thorn;; [251] &thorn;an lesith &thorn;e synful man &thorn;e goodnes of glorie &thorn;at oonly is byhight <MILESTONE N="257b" UNIT="folio">to goode men &thorn;at labouren and werken [252] &para; wel may he be sory &thorn;anne &thorn;at oweth al his lif to god as longe as he ha&thorn; lyued and eek as longe as he schal lyue. &thorn;at no goodnes ne hath to paye wi&thorn; his dette to god to whom he oweth al his lyf. [253] For truste&thorn; wel he schal &yogh;iue accompt as sai&thorn; seint Bernard of alle &thorn;e goodes &thorn;at han be &yogh;euen him in &thorn;is present lif. &amp; how he hath hem dispendid. [254] nat so moche &thorn;at &thorn;er ne schal not perische an heer of his heed ne a moment of an hour ne schal not perische of his tyme &thorn;at he ne schal &yogh;iue of it a rekenyng.</P>
<P>[255] &para; The .v<SUP>te</SUP>. maner of contricioun &thorn;at moeue&thorn; a man &thorn;erto is &thorn;e remembraunce of &thorn;e passioun &thorn;at oure lord ih&umacr; crist suffred for. vs and for our synnes [256] &para; For as sei&thorn; seint Bernard whil &thorn;at I lyue I schal haue remem|braunce 
<PB REF="00000625.tif" N="613"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="607"> of &thorn;e passioun &thorn;at oure lord ih&umacr; crist suffred for vs in preching. [257] his werynesse in trauayling his tempt|acioun whan he fastid. his longe wakinges whan he prayde his teeres whan he wepte for pite of good peple [258] &thorn;e wo and &thorn;e schame and &thorn;e filthe &thorn;at men saide to him ofte foul spittyng &thorn;at men spitten on his face. Of &thorn;e buffettis &thorn;at men &yogh;af him of &thorn;e foule mowes and of &thorn;e re|proues &thorn;at men to him saiden [259] of &thorn;e nayles with whiche he was nayled to &thorn;e cros and of al &thorn;e remenaunt of his passioun &thorn;at he suffred for my synnes and no &thorn;ing for his gilt [260] &para; And &yogh;e schal vnder|stonde &thorn;at in mannes synne is euery maner ordre of ordinaunce turned vpso-doun. [261] &para; For it is so&thorn; &thorn;at god &amp; resoun and sensualite and &thorn;e body of man be so ordeyned that euerich of &thorn;ese .iiij. schulde haue lordschipe ouer . . [262] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> resoun and resoun ouer sensualite. and sensualite ouer &thorn;e body of man. [263] &para; But so&thorn;ly whan man synne&thorn; al &thorn;is ordre or ordinaunce is torned vpso-doun [264] and &thorn;anne for as moche as &thorn;e resoun of a man ne wol not be subiect ne obeissant to god &thorn;at is his lord by right; &thorn;er|fore lesith it &thorn;e lordschipe &thorn;at it schulde haue in sensualite and eek ouer &thorn;e body of man. [265] And why; For sensualite rebellith &thorn;anne agayns resoun. And by &thorn;at way lesith resoun &thorn;e lordschipe ouer sensualite and ouer &thorn;e body. [266] For right as resoun is rebel to god; Right so is bo&thorn;e sensualite rebel to resoun and &thorn;e body also [267] And certis &thorn;is disordynaunce and &thorn;is rebellioun oure lord ih&umacr; crist bought vpon his precious body ful deere &para; And herkeneth in which wise [268] <MILESTONE N="258a" UNIT="folio">&para; For as moche as resoun is rebel to god; &thorn;er|fore is man wor&thorn;y to haue sorwe and to be deed. [269] &thorn;is suffred oure lord ih&umacr; crist for man and after &thorn;at he was bytraysed of his disciple and destreyned and 
<PB REF="00000626.tif" N="614"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="608"> bounde so &thorn;at &thorn;e blood brast out at euery nayl of his hondes as saith seint austyn [270] &para; And for&thorn;er ouer for as mochil as resoun of man wol nought daunte sensu|alite whan it may &thorn;erfore is man wor&thorn;y to haue schame &para; And &thorn;is suffred oure lord ih&umacr; crist for man whan &thorn;ay spitten in his face [271] And for&thorn;er ouer &thorn;anne for as moche as &thorn;e caytif body of man is rebelle bo&thorn;e to resoun and to sensualite. &thorn;erfore it is wor&thorn;y &thorn;e deth [272] &para; And &thorn;is suffred oure lord ih&umacr; crist for vs vpon &thorn;e croys wher as &thorn;er was no part of his body fre wi&thorn;oute gret peyne and bitter passioun [273] &para; And al &thorn;is suffred ih&umacr; crist &thorn;at neuer forfeted. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> So mochil am I streyned for &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at I neuer deseruyd and to moche defouled for schendschip &thorn;at man is worthy to haue [274] And &thorn;er|fore may &thorn;e synful man wel saye as saith sent Bernard &para; Acursed be &thorn;e bitternesse. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [275] For certis after &thorn;e dyuers discordaunces of oure wickednes was &thorn;e passioun of oure lord ih&umacr; crist/ ordeyned in diuers &thorn;inges [276] &para; As &thorn;us. Certis sinful mannes soule is bytraysid of &thorn;e deuel by coueitise of temporal prosperite and scorned by disceyt whan he chese&thorn; fleischly delytes and &yogh;it is it tormentid by impacience of aduersite and byspit by seruage and subieccioun of synne. and atte last it is slayn finally [277] &para; For &thorn;is discordaunce of synful man was Ih&umacr; crist first bytraised and after was he bounde that com for to vnbynden vs fro synne and of peyne [278] &para; Than was he scorned; &thorn;at oonly schulde be honoured in alle &thorn;ing of alle &thorn;inges. [279] &para; Than was his visage &thorn;at oughte be desired to be say of al man-kynde. In which visage aungels desiren to loke vileynsly byspit. [280] Thanne was he scorned &thorn;at no &thorn;ing had agilt. and fynally &thorn;anne was he crucified and slayn [281] Thanne was accomplised &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000627.tif" N="615"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="609"> word of ysaye &para; He was woundid for oure mysdede and defouled by oure felonyes [282] &para; Now sith ih&umacr; crist tok vpon him &thorn;ilke peyne of alle oure wikkednes; Mochil oughte synful men wepe and bywayle &thorn;at for his synnes schulde goddes sone of heuene al &thorn;is endure [283] &para; The .vj<SUP>te</SUP>. &thorn;ing &thorn;at ou&yogh;te to moeue a man to contricioun is &thorn;e hope of &thorn;re &thorn;inges. &thorn;at is to sayn. for&yogh;euenes of synne and &thorn;e &yogh;ifte of grace wel <MILESTONE N="258b" UNIT="folio">for to do. and &thorn;e glorie of heuen wi&thorn; which god schal guerdoun man for his goode deedis [284] &para; And for als moche as ih&umacr; crist &yogh;eueth vs &thorn;ese &yogh;iftes of his largesse and of his souerayn bounte; &thorn;erfore is he cleped. Ihc na&yogh;arenus rex Iudeorum [285] &para; Ih&umacr; is for to say saueour or sa|uacioun of whom me schal hope to haue for&yogh;euenes of synnes which &thorn;at is proprely sauacioun of synnes [286] &para; And &thorn;erfore seyde &thorn;e aungel to Ioseph &para; Thow clepe his name Ihc &thorn;at schal saue his poeple of here synnes [287] &para; And her of saith Seint petir &para; Ther is noon o&thorn;er name vnder heuen &thorn;at is &yogh;eue to any man by which a man may be sauyd. but oonly Ihc [288] na&yogh;arenus is as moche to say as florisching in which a man schal hope &thorn;at he &thorn;at &yogh;eueth him remissioun of synnes schal &yogh;iue him grace wel wel to doo &para; For in &thorn;e flour is hope of fruyt / in tyme comynge. And in for&yogh;iuenes hope of grace wel to do [289] &para; I was at &thorn;e dore of &thorn;in herte sai&thorn; Ihc and cleped for to entre. he &thorn;at openith to me. schal haue for&yogh;euenes of synne. [290] I wol entre into him by my grace and soupe with him by &thorn;e goode workes &thorn;at he schal doon whiche werkes ben &thorn;e foode of god &para; And he schal soupe wi&thorn; me by &thorn;e grete ioye &thorn;at I schal &yogh;iue him [291] &para; Thus schal man hope &thorn;at for his werkis of penaunce god schal &yogh;iue him his regne as he bihetith him in &thorn;e gospel</P>
<P>[292] Now schal man vnderstonde in what 
<PB REF="00000628.tif" N="616"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="610"> maner schal be his contricioun &para; I say it schal be vniuersal and total &para; &thorn;is is to say. a man schal be verray repentaunt for alle his synnes &thorn;at he ha&thorn; doon in delyt of his &thorn;ought for delit is ful perilous [293] &para; For &thorn;er ben tuo maners of consentynge . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> of affeccioun whan a man is moeued to synne &amp; delitith him longe for to &thorn;inke on &thorn;at synne. [294] and his resoun aparceyueth wel &thorn;at it is synne agayns &thorn;e lawe of god. &amp; &yogh;it his resoun refreyne&thorn; not his foule delit or talent &thorn;ough he seth wel apertly &thorn;at it is a&yogh;enst/ &thorn;e reuerence of god al &thorn;ough his resoun consente not to do &thorn;e synne in dede; [295] &yogh;it sayn some doctours delyt &thorn;at duellith longe it is ful perilous al be it neuer so lite [296] &para; And also a man schulde sorwe namely for al &thorn;at he ha&thorn; desired agayn &thorn;e lawe of god wi&thorn; parfyt consentynge of his hert and of his resoun &para; For &thorn;erof is no doute &thorn;at it is dedly synne [297] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> &thorn;at it nas first in mannes &thorn;ought. &amp; after &thorn;at in his delit/ and so for&thorn; in to consentyng and in to dede [298] &para; wherfore say I &thorn;at many men repente hem neuer <MILESTONE N="259a" UNIT="folio">of suche &thorn;oughtes and delitis. ne neuer schriue hem of hit. but oonly of &thorn;e dede of grete synnes outward [299] &para; wherfore I say &thorn;at suche wickid delitis and wickid &thorn;ou&yogh;tes ben subtile bigilours of hem &thorn;at schuln be dampned [300] &para; More ouer man oughte to sorwe for his wicked wordes as wel as his wikked dedes. For certis &thorn;e repentaunce of a singuler synne &amp; nou&yogh;t repente of alle his o&thorn;er synnes . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> may nou&yogh;t auaile [301] &para; For certis god almighty is al good and &thorn;erfore he for&yogh;eueth al or elles right nou&yogh;t [302] &para; And here-of sei&thorn; seint augustin &para; I wot certeynly &thorn;at god is enemy to euery synnere [303] &para; And how &thorn;anne he &thorn;at obseruith oon synne schal he haue remissioun of &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000629.tif" N="617"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="611"> remenant of his o&thorn;er synnes; Nay. [304] And for&thorn;er ouer contricioun schulde be woundes sorwful and an|guisschous and &thorn;erfore &yogh;iueth him god pleinly his mercy &para; And &thorn;erfore whan my soule was anguissheous wi&thorn;inne me; I hadde remembraunce of god &thorn;at my prayer mighte come to him [305] &para; And for&thorn;er ouer. contricioun moste be continuelly and &thorn;at a man haue stede|fast purpos to schryue him and for to amende him of his lyf [306] &para; For so&thorn;ly whil contricioun lastith man may euer hope of for&yogh;euenes and of &thorn;is come&thorn; hate of synne &thorn;at destroyeth synne bo&thorn;e in himself and eek in o&thorn;er folk at his power [307] &para; And &thorn;erfore saith dauid. &yogh;e &thorn;at louen god; hatith wikkidnesse. For trusti&thorn; wel for to loue god. is for to loue &thorn;at he loue&thorn;. and hate &thorn;at he hati&thorn;</P>
<P>[308] &para; The laste &thorn;ing &thorn;at a man schuld vnderstonde in contricioun is &thorn;is. wher of auailith contricioun &para; I say &thorn;at som tyme contricioun deliuere&thorn; man fro synne [309] of which &thorn;at dauid saith &para; I say quod dauid. &thorn;at is to say. I purposid fermely to schryue me and &thorn;ou lord relesedist my synne [310] &para; And right so as contricioun auailith nat wi&thorn;oute sad purpos of schrift if man haue oportunite; Right so. litil worth is shrifte or satisfaccioun wi&thorn;oute contricioun [311] &para; And more ouer contricioun destruye&thorn; &thorn;e prisoun of helle and maki&thorn; wayk and feble &thorn;e strengthes of &thorn;e deueles and restorith &thorn;e &yogh;ift of &thorn;e holy gost/ and of alle vertues [312] and it clensith &thorn;e soule of synnes and deliuere&thorn; &thorn;e soule fro &thorn;e peynes of helle and fro &thorn;e companye of &thorn;e deuel and fro &thorn;e seruage of synne and restorith to alle goode espiritueles in to &thorn;e companye &amp; communioun of holy chirche [313] &para; And for&thorn;er ouer it makith him &thorn;at som tyme was sone of Ire; <MILESTONE N="259b" UNIT="folio">sone of grace &para; And alle &thorn;ese &thorn;inges he prouith by holy writte. [314] And &thorn;erfore he &thorn;at wil sette his herte to &thorn;ese &thorn;inges; he were ful 
<PB REF="00000630.tif" N="618"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="612"> wys &para; For so&thorn;e he scholde not &thorn;anne in al his lyf haue corrage to synne. but &yogh;iuen his body and al his herte to &thorn;e seruice of Ih&umacr; crist and &thorn;erof do him homage [315] &para; For certis oure swete lord ih&umacr; crist ha&thorn; sparid vs so debonerly in oure folyes. &thorn;at if he ne hadde pite of mannes soule; sory songe mighte we alle synge.</P>
<TRAILER>&para; Explicit prima pars</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Incipit secunda pars eiusdem<NOTE PLACE="head">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>[316]</P>
<P>THe secounde partye of penitence is confessioun. &thorn;at is signe of contricioun [317] &para; Now schul &yogh;e vnderstonde what is confessioun and whe&thorn;ir it oughte needes be doon or noon. A whiche ben conuenable to verray confessioun</P>
<P>[318] &para; First schalt &thorn;ou vnderstonde &thorn;at confessioun is verrey schewyng of synnes to &thorn;e prest [319] &thorn;is is to sayn verray. For he moot schewe him of alle &thorn;e condiciouns &thorn;at ben longynge to his synne as ferforth as he can [320] al mot be sayd and nou&yogh;t excused ne hyd ne forwrappid and nou&yogh;t auaunte him of his goode werkis [321] &para; And for&thorn;ermore it is necessary to vnder|stonde whens &thorn;at synnes springe and how &thorn;ay exersen. and whiche &thorn;er ben</P>
<P>[322] of &thorn;e springing of synnes as seint poul sai&thorn; in &thorn;is wise &para; That right as by a man synne entred first in to &thorn;is world. and &thorn;orugh &thorn;at synne deth; Right so &thorn;ilke deth entred in to alle men &thorn;at synneden. [323] and &thorn;is man was adam by whom &thorn;at synne entred in to &thorn;is world whan he brak &thorn;e comaundement of god. [324] And &thorn;erfore he &thorn;at first was so mighty &thorn;at he schulde not haue deyed bicam si&thorn;&thorn;e on &thorn;at he moste needis deye whe&thorn;ir he wolde or noon and al his progenie &thorn;at is in &thorn;is world &thorn;at in &thorn;ilke manner synneden [325] &para; loke &thorn;at in &thorn;e / . testate of Innocence whan adam and Eue 
<PB REF="00000631.tif" N="619"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="613"> makid were in paradys and no &thorn;ing schame ne hadden of her nakidnesse. [326] how &thorn;at &thorn;e serpent &thorn;at was most wyly of alle o&thorn;er bestis &thorn;at god hadde makid sayde to &thorn;e womman &para; why comaundid god to &yogh;ow &yogh;e schulde nou&yogh;t ete of euery tree in paradys [327] &para; The womman answerde &para; Of &thorn;e fruyt quod sche of &thorn;e trees in paradys we feede vs &para; But so&thorn;ly of &thorn;e fruyt of &thorn;e tre &thorn;at is in &thorn;e myddil of paradis. god forbad vs for to eten ne not touche it lest perauenture we schulde <MILESTONE N="260a" UNIT="folio">deye [328] &para; The serpent sayde to &thorn;e womman. Nay nay. &yogh;e schal not drede of deth for so&thorn;e god wot &thorn;at what day &yogh;e ete &thorn;erof &yogh;oure eyen schal open and &yogh;e schul ben as goddis knowing good and harm [329] &para; The womman saugh &thorn;e tree was good to feedyng. and fair to eyen and delitable to sight. She tok of &thorn;e fruyt of &thorn;e tree and eet it and &yogh;af it to hir housbond And he eet it &para; And anoon &thorn;e eyen of hem bo&thorn;e openeden [330] And whan &thorn;at &thorn;ay knewe &thorn;at &thorn;ay were naked; &thorn;ay sowede of fige leues in maner of breches to hiden here membris [331] &para; here may &yogh;e see &thorn;at dedly synne ha&thorn; first suggestioun of &thorn;e feend as schewe&thorn; here by &thorn;e neddir. and aftirward &thorn;e delit of &thorn;e fleisch as scheweth here by eua. and after &thorn;at &thorn;e consentyng of resoun as schewith by adam [332] &para; For trusti&thorn; wel &thorn;ough so were &thorn;at &thorn;e feend temptid oon. &thorn;at is to sayn &thorn;e fleissch hadde delit in &thorn;e beaute of &thorn;e fruyt defendid. &yogh;it certes til &thorn;at resoun &thorn;at is to say adam con|sentid to &thorn;e etyng of &thorn;e fruyt/ . &yogh;it stood he in &thorn;astaat of Innocence [333] &para; Of &thorn;ilk adam took we &thorn;ilke synne original. for of him flesschly descendit be we alle. and engendrit of vile and corrupt m[a]tiere [334] &para; And whan &thorn;e soule is put in oure body right anoon is con|tract original synne. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> [335] and &thorn;erfore be we alle I-born sones of 
<PB REF="00000632.tif" N="620"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="614"> wra&thorn;&thorn;e and of dampnacioun perdurable if it nere baptisme &thorn;at we resceyuen which bynyme&thorn; vs &thorn;e culpe &para; But for|so&thorn;e &thorn;e peyne duelli&thorn; wi&thorn; vs as to temptacioun which peyne highte concupiscence [336] &para; And &thorn;is concupiscence whan it is wrongfully disposed or ordeyned in man; hit makith him to coueyte couetise of fleisschly synne by sight of his ey&yogh;en as to er&thorn;ely &thorn;inges. and eek coueityse of heigh|nesse as by pride of herte</P>
<P>[337] Now as to speke of &thorn;e firste coueitise &thorn;at is concupiscence after &thorn;e lawe of oure membris &thorn;at is . . . . .[338] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> nou&yogh;t obeissant to god &thorn;at is lord &thorn;erfore is fleissch to him disobeisant &thorn;urgh concupiscence which &thorn;at &yogh;it is clepid norisshing of synne . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> [339] &para; Therfore al &thorn;e while &thorn;at a man ha&thorn; in him &thorn;e peyne of concupiscence it is impossible but he be tempted som tyme and moeued in his fleisch to synne /. [340] &para; And &thorn;is may not faile as longe as he lyue&thorn; &para; hit may wel wexe feble and faille by vertu of baptisme and by &thorn;e grace of god &thorn;orugh penitence. [341] but fully schal it neuer <MILESTONE N="260b" UNIT="folio">quenche &thorn;at he schal som tyme be moeued in himself but if he were al refreydit by siknes or by malice of sorserye or colde drinkes [342] &para; For what sai&thorn; seint poul &para; The fleissh coueitith agayn &thorn;e spirit. and &thorn;e spirit agayn &thorn;e fleisch &thorn;ay ben so contrarie and so stryuen &thorn;at a man may nou&yogh;t alwey do as he wolde [343] &para; The same seint poul after his penaunce in watir and in lond. in watir by night and by day in gret peril and in gret peyne in lond and in famyne. and in &thorn;urst and colde. and clo&thorn;les oones almost stoned al to &thorn;e deth [344] &para; &yogh;it saide he allas I caytif man. who schal delyuere me fro &thorn;e prisoun of my caytif body [345] And seint Ierom. whan he long tyme had woned in desert here wher as he hadde no compaignye but of wilde bestes wher as he hadde 
<PB REF="00000633.tif" N="621"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="615"> no mete but herbes &amp; water to his drink. ne non bed but &thorn;e nakid er&thorn;e. For which his fleisch was as blak as an Ethiopen for hete and neigh destroyed for cold [346] &para; &yogh;it sayde he &thorn;at &thorn;e brennyng of lecchery boylid in al his body [347] &para; wherfore I wot wel sicurly &thorn;at &thorn;ay be desceyued &thorn;at say &thorn;ay ben not temptid in here body. [348] &para; witnesse on seint Iame thapostil &thorn;at saith. &thorn;at euery wight is tempted in his oughne con|cupiscence &thorn;at is to sayn &thorn;at euerych of vs hath matere and occasioun to be tempted of &thorn;e norischyng of synne &thorn;at is in his body [349] &para; And &thorn;erfore seint Iohan &thorn;e Euaungelist saith &para; If &thorn;at we sayn we be wi&thorn;oute synne; we deceyue oure silf and trou&thorn;e is nought in vs</P>
<P>[350] &para; Now schal &yogh;e vnderstonde in what maner &thorn;at synne waxi&thorn; and encresceth in a man &para; The firste &thorn;ing is &thorn;ilke norisching of synne of which I spak byforn &thorn;ilke concupiscence. [351] And after &thorn;at cometh &thorn;e Subieccioun of &thorn;e deuel. &thorn;is is to sayn &thorn;e deueles bely with which he blowe&thorn; in man &thorn;e fuyr of fleisschly concupiscence [352] And after &thorn;at a man by|think him whe&thorn;ir he wol don it/ or non. &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing to which he is tempted. [353] &para; and &thorn;anne if &thorn;at a man wi&thorn;stonde and wayue &thorn;e firste entisynges of his fleisshe and of &thorn;e feend it is no synne. and if so be he do not so; &thorn;anne fleeth he anoon a flame of delit/ [354] and &thorn;anne it is good to be war and kepe him wel or ellis he wil falle anoon in to consentyng of synne / and &thorn;anne wol he do it if he may haue tyme and space and place [355] &para; And of &thorn;is matere saith Moyses by &thorn;e deuel in &thorn;is manere &para; &thorn;e feend <MILESTONE N="261a" UNIT="folio">saith. // I wol chace and pursewe &thorn;e man by wickid suggestiouns and I wil hent him by moeuyng or steryng of synne and I wil parte my prise or my pray by de|liberacioun and my lust schal be accomplisit in delit. I wil drawe my sword in consentynge [356] &para; For certes right as a swerd departi&thorn; a &thorn;ing in tuo parties right 
<PB REF="00000634.tif" N="622"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="616"> so consentynge departe&thorn; god fro man and &thorn;anne wol I sle him with my hond in dede of synne. &thorn;us saith &thorn;e feend. [357] For certis &thorn;anne is a man al deed in soule and &thorn;us is synne accomsid by tempt|acioun by delit and by consentyng and &thorn;anne is &thorn;e synne cleped actuel</P>
<P>[358] &para; For so&thorn;e synne is in two maneres. ou&thorn;er it is venial or dedly synne. Sothly whan man louith any creature more &thorn;an ih&umacr; crist/ oure creatour; &thorn;anne it is dedly synne. And venial synne is. if a man loue ih&umacr; crist lasse &thorn;an him oughte [359] &para; For so&thorn;e &thorn;e dede of &thorn;is venial synne is ful perilous. For it amenisith &thorn;e loue &thorn;at men schulde haue to god more and more [360] &para; And &thorn;erfore if a man charge more himself with many suche venial synnes. Certes but if so be &thorn;at he som tyme discharge him of hem by schrifte; &thorn;ay may ful lightly amenise in him al &thorn;e loue &thorn;at he hath to ih&umacr; crist [361] and in &thorn;is wise skippith venial in to dedly synne. &para; For certes &thorn;e more &thorn;at a man chargith his soule wi&thorn; venial synnes; &thorn;e more is he enclyned to falle in deedly synne [362] &para; And &thorn;erfore let vs nou&yogh;t be negligent to descharge vs of venial synnes &para; For the prouerbe saith. &thorn;at many smale makith a gret [363] &para; And herken &thorn;is ensample &para; A greet wawe of &thorn;e see come&thorn; som tyme wi&thorn; so gret a violence &thorn;at it drenchith &thorn;e schip. and &thorn;e same harm doon som tyme smale droppis of water &thorn;at entrith &thorn;urgh a litil creues in to &thorn;e thurrok and in to &thorn;e bothum of a schip if men be so neggligent &thorn;at &thorn;ay descharge it nought by tyme [364] &para; And &thorn;erfore al &thorn;ough &thorn;er be differrence bitueen &thorn;ese tuo causes of drenching. algates the schip is dreynt [365] &para; Right so farith it som tyme of deedly synne and of anoyous venial synnes whan &thorn;ay multiplien in a man so gretly &thorn;at &thorn;ilke worldly &thorn;ynges &thorn;at he loueth &thorn;urgh which he sinneth venially is as gret in his herte as &thorn;e loue of god or more [366] 
<PB REF="00000635.tif" N="623"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="617"> &para; And &thorn;erfore &thorn;e loue of euery &thorn;ing &thorn;ere is not byset in god ne doon principally for goddes sake / al &thorn;ough a man loue it lasse &thorn;an god. &yogh;it is it venial synne [367] <MILESTONE N="261b" UNIT="folio">And deedly synne whan &thorn;e loue of eny &thorn;ing weyeth in &thorn;e hert of a man as moche as &thorn;e loue of god or more [368] &para; Dedly synne is as saith seint austyn. whan man torneth his hert from god which &thorn;at is verray souerayn bounte &thorn;at may not chaunge and flitte. and &yogh;iue his herte to a &thorn;ing &thorn;at may chaunge and flitte. [369] and certes &thorn;at is euery &thorn;ing saue god of heuen &para; For so&thorn;e if &thorn;at a man &yogh;iue his loue &thorn;e which that he owi&thorn; to god wi&thorn; al his herte vnto a creature. certes as moche of loue as he &yogh;iueth to &thorn;ilke creature; so moche he reueth fro god. [370] and &thorn;er|fore doth he synne. &para; For he &thorn;at is dettour to god and &yogh;eldeth not his dette &thorn;at is to sayn al &thorn;e loue of his hert</P>
<P>[371] &para; Now si&thorn;&thorn;e man vnderstondith generally which is venial synne; &thorn;anne is it couenable to telle specially of synnes whiche &thorn;at many man perauenture ne demith hem no synnes and schryueth him not of &thorn;e same &thorn;inges and &yogh;it na&thorn;eles &thorn;ay ben synnes [372] &para; And so&thorn;ly as clerkes writen &thorn;is is to say. at euery tyme &thorn;at man etith or drinkith more &thorn;an suffise&thorn; to &thorn;e sustienaunce of his body in certeyn he do&thorn; synne; [373] and eek whan he spekith more &thorn;an it needith he do&thorn; synne. and eek whan he herkeneth nou&yogh;t be|nignely &thorn;e pleynt of &thorn;e pore [374] eek whan he is in hele of body and wil not faste whan o&thorn;er folk fasten wi&thorn;outen cause resonable. / eek whan he slepith more &thorn;an needith or whan he come&thorn; by &thorn;ilk enchesoun to late to holy chirche or to o&thorn;er werkes of charite [375] Eke whan he vse&thorn; his wyf wi&thorn;oute souerayn desir of engendrure to thonour of god and for &thorn;entent to &yogh;elde to his wyf &thorn;e dette of his body. [376] eek whan he wil not visite &thorn;e sike and &thorn;e prisoner if he may 
<PB REF="00000636.tif" N="624"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="618"> &para; eek if he loue wyf or child or o&thorn;er worldly &thorn;ing more &thorn;an resoun requireth. eek if he flatere or blaundisshe more &thorn;an him oughte for eny necessite [377] ek if a man menuse or wi&thorn;drawe &thorn;e almesse of &thorn;e pouere eek if he apparaylith his body more deliciously &thorn;an it nedith or ete it to hastily by licoures|nes. [378] eek if he talke of vanitees at chirche or at goddis seruice. or &thorn;at he be a talkere of ydil wordes of vanite or of vilonye / for he schal &yogh;elde of hem acount at &thorn;e day of doome. [379] eek whan he heetith or assureth to do &thorn;inges &thorn;at he may nou&yogh;t performe. eek whan &thorn;at by lightnes or foly he myssaith or scorne&thorn; his <MILESTONE N="262a" UNIT="folio">neighebor. [380] eek whan he ha&thorn; any wicked suspeccioun of &thorn;ing &thorn;at he wot of it no soth|fastnesse. [381] &thorn;ese &thorn;inges and mo wi&thorn;oute nombre ben synnes as saith seint austyn</P>
<P>[382] &para; Now schal men vnderstonde &thorn;at al be it so &thorn;at noon er&thorn;ely man may eschiewe alle venial synnes; &yogh;it may he refreyne hem by &thorn;e brennyng loue &thorn;at he ha&thorn; to oure lord ih&umacr; crist and by prayeres and by confessioun and o&thorn;er goode werkes. so &thorn;at it schal but litil greue [383] &para; For as saith seint austyn &para; &yogh;if a man loue god in such a maner &thorn;at al &thorn;at euer he doth is in &thorn;e loue of god or for &thorn;e loue of god verraily for he brenne&thorn; in &thorn;e loue of god [384] &para; loke how moche &thorn;at a drope of watir &thorn;at fallith in a furneys ful of fuyr annoyeth of greueth; So moche annoye&thorn; a venial synne vnto a man &thorn;at is perfyt in &thorn;e loue of ih&umacr; crist [385] &para; Men may also refreyne venial synne vnto a man by resceyuyng of &thorn;e precious body of ih&umacr; crist/ [386] by receyuyng eek of holy water. by almes dede. by general confessioun of Confiteor at masse and at complyn and blessing of bisschops and of prestes and by other goode werkis<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000637.tif" N="625"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="619"></P>
<P>[387] &para; Now it is bihouely &thorn;ing to telle whiche ben dedly synnes &thorn;at is to sayn chiueteyns of synnes. alle &thorn;ay renne in oon loos. but in diuers maners now ben &thorn;ay cleped chiueteyns. For als moche as &thorn;ay ben chief and springers of alle o&thorn;ere synnes [388] &para; Of &thorn;e roote of &thorn;ese seuen synnes; &thorn;anne is pride &thorn;e general synne and roote of alle harmes &para; For of &thorn;is roote springen general braunches. As Ire. Enuye. accidie or sleuthe. auarice or coueitise. to commune vnderstondynge. glotonye and leccherie [389] &para; And euerich of &thorn;ese synnes hath his braunches and his twigges as schal be declarid in here chapitres folwinge.<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></P>
<P>[390] and &thorn;ough so be &thorn;at no man can telle vtterly &thorn;e nombre of &thorn;e twigges and of &thorn;e harm &thorn;at come&thorn; of pride; &yogh;it wol I schewe a party of hem as &yogh;e schul vnderstonde [391] &para; Ther is Inobedience. auauntyng. ypocrisye. despit. arragaunce. Imprudence. Swellyng of hert. Insolence. Elacioun. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> pertinacie. veinglorie. and many ano&thorn;er twigge &thorn;at I can not telle ne declare [392] Ino|bedient is he &thorn;at disobeieth for despyt to &thorn;e comaunde|ment&yogh; of god and to his souereigns. and to his gostly fader. [393] Auauntour is he &thorn;at bosteth of &thorn;e harm or of &thorn;e bounte &thorn;at he ha&thorn; don [394] &para; ypocrisy is &thorn;at <MILESTONE N="262b" UNIT="folio">hydeth to schewe him such as he is and schewe&thorn; him such as he not is [395] &para; Despitous is he &thorn;at ha&thorn; desdayn of his neighebour &thorn;at is to say of his euen cristen or ha&thorn; despit to doon &thorn;at him ought to doon [396] &para; Arragaunt is he &thorn;at &thorn;inke&thorn; &thorn;at he hath &thorn;ilke bountees in him &thorn;at he ha&thorn; not or 
<PB REF="00000638.tif" N="626"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="620"> weneth &thorn;at he schulde haue hem by desert/. or elles he demeth &thorn;at he is &thorn;at he is not. [397] &para; Im|pudent is he &thorn;at for his pride hath no schame of his synne. [398] &para; Swellyng of hert is whan a man reioysith him of harm &thorn;at he ha&thorn; don [399] &para; Inso|lent is he &thorn;at dispisith in his iuggement alle o&thorn;er folk as to regard of his valieu and of his connyng &amp; of his spekyng and of his beryng [400] &para; Elacioun is whan he may neuer suffre to haue maister ne felawe [401] &para; Impacient is he; &thorn;at wil not ben I-taught ne vnder|nome of his vices and by stryf werre&thorn; trou&thorn;e witynge and defende&thorn; his folie [402] &para; Contimax is he &thorn;at &thorn;orugh his indignacioun and agains euerych auctorite or power of hem &thorn;at been his souerayns [403] &para; Pre|sumpcioun is whan a man vndertakith and emprisith &thorn;at him oughte not to do. or elles &thorn;at he may not doo. and &thorn;at is cleped surquidrye &para; Irreuerence is. whan men doon not honour &thorn;er as hem ought to doon. and wayteth to be reuerenced [404] &para; Pertinacie is. whan man defendith his folye and truste&thorn; to moche to his owne witte [405] &para; Vayn glorie is. for to haue pomp and delit in temporal heighnes and glorifie him in worldly estaat [406] &para; Iangelyng is whan a man spekith to moche biforn folk &amp; clappith as a mille and take&thorn; no keep what he sai&thorn;</P>
<P>[407] and &yogh;it is &thorn;er a priue spice of pride &thorn;at wayteth first/ to be saluet er he saliewe al be he lasse worth &thorn;an &thorn;at o&thorn;er is par aduenture. and eek wayte&thorn; or desire&thorn; to sitte aboue him or to go aboue him in &thorn;e way. or kisse pax. or ben encensed or gon to &thorn;e offringe biforn his neighebore [408] and ha&thorn; such . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> a proud desir to be magnified and honoured toforn &thorn;e poeple</P>
<P>[409] &para; now ben tuo maners of pride. &thorn;at oon is heighnes wi&thorn;inne &thorn;e hert/ of a man and &thorn;at 
<PB REF="00000639.tif" N="627"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="621"> o&thorn;er is wi&thorn;oute. [410] of which so&thorn;ly &thorn;ese for|sayde &thorn;inges and mo &thorn;an I haue said aperteynen to pride &thorn;at is in &thorn;e hert of a man. and &thorn;at o&thorn;er spices of pride ben wi&thorn;oute [411] &para; But natheles &thorn;at oon of &thorn;ise spices of pride is signe of &thorn;at o&thorn;er. Right as gay leuesselle at &thorn;e tauerne is signe of wyn &thorn;at is in &thorn;e celer. [412] and &thorn;is is in many &thorn;inges <MILESTONE N="263a" UNIT="folio">as in speche and countienaunce and in outrageous array of clo&thorn;ing [413] &para; For certis if &thorn;er hadde be no synne in clo&thorn;ing; crist wolde not so soone haue notid and spoke of &thorn;e clo&thorn;ing of &thorn;ilke riche man in &thorn;e gospel. [414] And saith seint Gregorie &thorn;at precious clo&thorn;ing is cou|pable for derthe of it and for his schortnes. and for his straungenes and disgisines. and for &thorn;e super|fluite. or for &thorn;e inordinat skantnes of it/ [415] Allas many man may sen as in oure dayes &thorn;e synful costlewe array of clo&thorn;ing . . . . .</P>
<P>[416] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> which &thorn;at makid is so dere to harm of &thorn;e poeple. [417] not oonly &thorn;e cost of embrowdyng &thorn;e guyse endentyng of barryng. / Swandyng. palyng. or bendyng. and semblable wast of clo&thorn; in vanite [418] &para; But &thorn;er is also costlewe furring in here gownes so mochil pounsyng of chiseles to make holes so moche daggyng of scheris. [419] for with &thorn;e superfluite in leng&thorn;e of the forsaide gownes trayl|inge in &thorn;e donge and in &thorn;e myre on hors and eek on foote as wel of man as of womman &thorn;at al &thorn;ilke traylyng is verray as in effect/ wasted consumed &thorn;red|bare and rotyn with donge ra&thorn;er &thorn;an it is &yogh;euen to &thorn;e pore to gret damage of &thorn;e forsaide pore folk. [420] and &thorn;at in sondry wise. &thorn;is is to sain &thorn;at &thorn;e more &thorn;at clo&thorn; is wastid &thorn;e more most it/ coste to &thorn;e poeple for &thorn;e scarsenes [421] and for&thorn;ermore if it so be &thorn;at &thorn;ay wolde &yogh;iue suche pounsed and 
<PB REF="00000640.tif" N="628"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="622"> daggid clo&thorn;ing to &thorn;e pore folk. it is not conuenient to were to the pore folk ne suffisaunt to beete here necessite to kepe hem fro &thorn;e desperance of &thorn;e firmament [422] &para; vpon &thorn;at o&thorn;er syde to speke of &thorn;e horrible disordinat scantnes of clo&thorn;ing. as ben &thorn;ese cuttid sloppis or Anslets &thorn;at &thorn;urgh her schortnes ne couereth not &thorn;e schamful membre of man to wickid entent [423] Alas som men of hem schewen &thorn;e schap and &thorn;e boce of the horrible swollen membres &thorn;at semeth like to &thorn;e maledies of hirnia in &thorn;e wrapping of here hose / [424] and eek &thorn;e buttokes of hem &thorn;at faren as it were &thorn;e hinder part of a sche ape in &thorn;e fulle of &thorn;e moone [425] &para; And more ouer &thorn;e wrecchid swollen membres &thorn;at &thorn;ay schewe &thorn;urgh desgysyng in departyng of here hoses in whyt and reed seemith &thorn;at half &thorn;e schame|ful priue membres were flayn. [426] And if it so be &thorn;at &thorn;ay departe here hosen in o&thorn;er colours. as it whit and bliew. or whit and blak and reed and so forth; [427] &thorn;anne semith it <MILESTONE N="263b" UNIT="folio">as by variaunce of colour &thorn;at half &thorn;e party of his priuy membris ben corrupt by &thorn;e fuyr of seint antony or by cancre or by other such meschaunce [428] &para; And &yogh;it of &thorn;e hynder partye of here buttokes it is ful horrible for to see. For certis in &thorn;at partie of here body &thorn;er as &thorn;ay purgen her stynkyng ordure [429] &thorn;at foule party schewe &thorn;ay to &thorn;e poeple proudly in despyt of honeste which honeste &thorn;at ih&umacr; crist and his frendes obserueden to schewen in his lif [430] &para; Now as of &thorn;e outrageous array of wommen. God wot. &thorn;at &thorn;ough &thorn;e visage of some of hem seme ful chaste and debonaire; &yogh;it notifye &thorn;ay in here array of attyre licorousnesse and pride [431] I say not &thorn;at honeste in clo&thorn;ing of man or womman is vncouen|able &para; But certis &thorn;e superfluite or disordinat skantnes of clo&thorn;ing is repreuable [432] &para; Also &thorn;e synne of here ornament or of apparaile as in &thorn;inges &thorn;at aperteynen to rydyng as in to many delicat horses &thorn;at ben hold|en 
<PB REF="00000641.tif" N="629"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="623"> for delyt &thorn;at &thorn;ay ben so faire fat and costlewe [433] and also many a vicious knaue mayntened by cause of hem and in to curious harnoys as in sadelis and bridlis cropours and peytrelle couered with precious clo&thorn;ing and riche barres and plates of gold and of siluer [434] For whiche god saithe by &yogh;acharie &thorn;e prophete &para; I wol confounde &thorn;e ryders of such horsis [435] &para; These folk take litil reward of &thorn;e ryding of goddes sone of heuen and of his harneys whan he rode vpon an asse. and hadde noon o&thorn;er harneys but &thorn;e clo&thorn;ing of his disciples newe. &para; Ne rede I not &thorn;at euer he rode on o&thorn;er beest [436] &para; I speke &thorn;is for &thorn;e synne of superfluite and nou&yogh;t for resonable honeste whan resoun it requirith [437] &para; And for&thorn;er ouer certes pride is gretly notified in holdyng of gret meyne whan &thorn;ay ben of litil profyt or of right no profyt. [438] and namely whan &thorn;at meyne is felenous and daun|gerous to &thorn;e poeple by hardynesse of lordschipe or by way of offices [439] Fo[r] certes suche lordes selle &thorn;anne here lordschipe to &thorn;e deuel of helle whan &thorn;ay susteyne &thorn;e wickidnes of here meyne [440] or elles whan &thorn;ese folk of lowe degre as is &thorn;ilke &thorn;at holden hostilries and susteyne &thorn;e &thorn;efte of here hostilers and &thorn;at is in many maneres of disceytes. [441] &thorn;ilke maner of folk ben &thorn;e flyes &thorn;at folwen &thorn;e hony or elles &thorn;e houndes <MILESTONE N="264a" UNIT="folio">&thorn;at folwen &thorn;e carayn. suche forsayde folk / strangelen spirituelly here lordschipes [442] for whiche &thorn;us saith dauid &thorn;e prophete &para; wikked deth moot come vpon such lordschipes. &amp; god &yogh;eue &thorn;at &thorn;ay moot descende in to helle a doun. For in here houses ben iniquites and schrewednesses and not god of heuen. [443] and certes but &thorn;ay do amende|ment. right so as god &yogh;af his benisoun to pharao by &thorn;e seruice of Iacob and to balan &thorn;e seruice of Ioseph. Right so god wil &yogh;eue his malisoun to such lordschipes as susteynen &thorn;e wikkednes of her seruauntes but &thorn;ay 
<PB REF="00000642.tif" N="630"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="624"> come to amendement [444] &para; Pride of &thorn;e table apperith ful ofte. for certes riche men ben cleped to feste and pore folk ben put away and rebuked [445] &para; Also in excesse of diuers metis and drinkis and namely of suche maner of bake metis brennyng of wilde fuyr and peynted and castelid wi&thorn; papire and semblable wast. / so &thorn;at it is abusioun for to &thorn;inke [446] and eek in greet preciousnes of vessel &amp; in curiousnesse of vessel and of mynstralcye by &thorn;e whiche a man is stired &thorn;e more to delitis of luxurie [447] if so be that &thorn;ay sette her herte &thorn;e lasse vpon oure lord ih&umacr; crist &para; Certeyn it is a synne. and certeinly &thorn;e delites mighte be so grete in &thorn;e caas &thorn;at men mighte lightly falle by hem in to dedly synne [448] &para; &thorn;e espices &thorn;at sourdren of pride so&thorn;ely whan &thorn;ay sourdren of malice ymagined and auised. aforn cast or elles of vsage ben dedly synnes it is no doute. [449] and whan &thorn;ay sourden by frelte vn|auysed sodeinly and sodeinly wi&thorn;drawe agayn al be &thorn;ay greuous synnes I gesse &thorn;ay ben not dedly [450] Now mighte men axe wher-of pride sourdeth and springeth &para; I say som tyme it springith of &thorn;e goodes of nature / and som tyme of &thorn;e goodes of . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> grace. [451] certes goodes of nature stonden ou&thorn;er in goodes of body or goodes of soule [452] &para; Certis &thorn;e goodes of body ben hele of body. streng&thorn;e. deliuerance. beaute. gentrie. fraunchises. [453] &para; Goodes of nature of &thorn;e soule. ben goodes with scharp vnderstondyng subtil engyn vertu naturel. good memorie [454] &para; Goodes of fortune been richesses. highe degrees of lordschipes preisyng of &thorn;e poeple [455] &para; Goodes of grace been science. power to suffre spirituel trauaile. benignite. vertuous contemplacioun. wi&thorn;stondyng of temptacioun and semblable &thorn;inges. [456] of whiche forsayde goodes certe it is a ful gret <MILESTONE N="264b" UNIT="folio">foly a man to pryden him in any of hem alle [457] 
<PB REF="00000643.tif" N="631"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="625"> &para; Now as for to speke of goodes of nature; god wot &thorn;at som tyme we haue hem in nature as moche as to oure damage as to oure profit [458] &para; As for to speke of hele of body. certes it passith ful lightly. and eek it is ful ofte enchesoun of &thorn;e siknesse of &thorn;e soule . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> &para; And &thorn;erfore &thorn;e more &thorn;at oure body is hool &thorn;e more be we in peril to falle [459] &para; Eke for to pride him in his streng&thorn;e of body it is a foly. for certes &thorn;e fleisch coueytith again &thorn;e spirit. and ay &thorn;e more strong &thorn;at &thorn;e fleisch is &thorn;e sorier may &thorn;e soule be / [460] and ouer al &thorn;is streng&thorn;e of body and worldly hardynes cause&thorn; ful ofte many man to peril and meschaunce [461] Eek for to pride him of his gentrie is ful gret folye; For often tyme &thorn;e gentrie of &thorn;e body bynymeth &thorn;e gentery of &thorn;e soule &para; And we ben alle of oon fader and of oon moder &amp; alle we ben of oon nature roten and corrupt riche and pore [462] &para; For so&thorn;e oon maner gentry is for to prayse &thorn;at apparaille&thorn; mannes corrage with vertues and moralitees and makith him cristes child [463] &para; For trusti&thorn; wel ouer what man &thorn;at synne ha&thorn; maistry; he is verray cherl to synne</P>
<P>[464] &para; Now ben &thorn;er general synnes of gentilesce as schewyng of vice &amp; rybaudrie and seruage of synne. in word in werk and contenaunce [465] &para; And vsinge vertu curtesie and clennes / and to be liberal &thorn;at is to sayn large by mesure. for &thorn;ilke &thorn;at passith mesure is foly and synne [466] &para; And ano&thorn;er is to remembre him of bounte &thorn;at he of o&thorn;er folk ha&thorn; resceyued [467] &para; Another is to be benigne to his goode subiectis &para; wherfore as sai&thorn; senek. &para; Ther is no &thorn;ing more couenable to a man of heigh estate &thorn;an debonairte and pite [468] &para; And &thorn;erfore &thorn;ise flies &thorn;at men clepen bees whan &thorn;ay make here king; &thorn;ay chesen oon &thorn;at ha&thorn; no pricke wher wi&thorn; he may stynge [469] 
<PB REF="00000644.tif" N="632"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="626"> &para; Ano&thorn;er is. a man to haue a noble herte &amp; a diligent to atteigne to hihe vertuous &thorn;inges [470] &para; Certis also who &thorn;at prideth him in &thorn;e deedes of grace; is eek an outrageous fool &para; For &thorn;ilke &yogh;iftes of grace &thorn;at schulde haue I-torned him to goodnes and medicyne; torneth him to venym and to confusioun as sai&thorn; seint gregory [471] &para; Certis also. who-so pridith him in &thorn;e goodes of fortune. he is a ful gret fool &para; For som tyme is a man a gret lord by &thorn;e morwe &thorn;at is a caytif and a wrecche er it be night./ [472] &para; And som tyme &thorn;e riches of a man is cause of his deth. / <MILESTONE N="265a" UNIT="folio">&para; Som tyme &thorn;e delice is cause of his greuous maledye &thorn;urgh which he deieth [473] &para; Certis &thorn;e commendacioun of &thorn;e poeple is som|tyme ful fals and ful brutil for to truste. &thorn;is day &thorn;ay prayse; to morwe &thorn;ay blame [474] &para; God woot desir to haue commendacioun of &thorn;e poeple ha&thorn; causid deth of many a busy man [475] &para; Now sith so is. &thorn;at &yogh;e han herd and vnderstonde what is pride. And whiche ben &thorn;e spices of it / and whens pride sourdeth and springe&thorn;;<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No gap in the MS.]</NOTE></P>
<P>[476] Now schul &yogh;e vnderstonde. which is &thorn;e remedy agayns pride &para; And &thorn;at is humilite or meekenes [477] &thorn;at is a vertue &thorn;urgh which a man ha&thorn; verray knowleche of himself and holdith of him|self no pride ne pris ne deynte as in regard of his desertes considering euermore his frelte. [478] &para; Now ben &thorn;er &thorn;re maners of humilite. As humilite in hert/ ano&thorn;er is humilite in his mouth. &thorn;e &thorn;ridde in his workes // [479] &para; &thorn;e humilite in his herte. is in foure maners; &thorn;at oon is whan a man holdith him self not worth biforn god of heuen. ano&thorn;er is whan he despise&thorn; 
<PB REF="00000645.tif" N="633"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="627"> no man [480] &para; The &thorn;rid is. whan he ne rekki&thorn; nought &thorn;ough a man holde him nou&yogh;t worth &para; The fer&thorn;e is whan he holde&thorn; him nought sory of his humiliacioun [481] &para; Also &thorn;e humilite of mouth is in foure &thorn;inges. In attempre speche. and in humbles of speche. and he byknowith wi&thorn; his owne mouth &thorn;at he is such as him &thorn;enkith &thorn;at he is in herte. Ano&thorn;er is whan he praisith &thorn;e bounte of ano&thorn;er man and no &thorn;ing &thorn;erof amenusith [482] &para; Humilite eek in werk is in foure maneres &para; The first is whan he puttith o&thorn;er men toforn him &para; &thorn;e secounde is to chese &thorn;e lewedest place ouer al &para; &thorn;e &thorn;rid is gladly to assente to good counseil [483] &para; &thorn;e fer&thorn;e is gladly to stonde to thaward of his souereyns or of him &thorn;at is in heigher degre. certeyn &thorn;is is a gret werk of humilite<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; <B>De Inuidia.</B>[<I>in margin</I>]</HEAD>
<P>[484]</P>
<P>AFter pride now wol I speke of &thorn;e foule synne of Envye which &thorn;at is as by &thorn;e word of &thorn;e philosophre. sorwe of other mennes prosperite &para; And after &thorn;e word of seint austyn. is it sorwe of o&thorn;er mennes wele &amp; ioye of o&thorn;er mennes harm [485] &para; This foule synne is platly agayns &thorn;e holy gost. al be it so &thorn;at euery synne is agayn the holy gost; &yogh;it natheles for as moche as bounte aperteyneth proprely to &thorn;e holy gost. and enuye proprely is malice; &thorn;er|fore is it proprely agayns &thorn;e bounte of &thorn;e holy gost [486] &para; Now ha&thorn; malice <MILESTONE N="265b" UNIT="folio">tuo spices . &thorn;at is to sayn hardnes of hert in wickednes or ellis &thorn;e fleisch of man is blynd &thorn;at he considereth not &thorn;at he is in synne . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> which is &thorn;e hardnes of the deuyl [487] &para; That o&thorn;er spice of enuye is . whan a man warieth trou&thorn;e and wot &thorn;at it is trou&thorn;e. and eek whan he warieth &thorn;e grace &thorn;at god ha&thorn; &yogh;eue to his 
<PB REF="00000646.tif" N="634"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="628"> neighebor and al &thorn;is is by enuye [488] &para; Certes &thorn;an is enuye &thorn;e worste synne &thorn;at is &para; For sothely alle o&thorn;er synnes ben somtyme oonly agains oon special vertu [489] &para; But certes enuye is agayns alle vertues and agayns al goodnes. for it is sory of alle &thorn;e bountees of his neighebor &para; And in &thorn;is maner it is diuers from alle &thorn;e synnes. [490] &para; For wel vnne&thorn;e is &thorn;er any synne &thorn;at he ne hath som delit in himself sauf oonly enuye &thorn;at euer hath in it self anguisch and sorwe [491] &para; The spices of enuye ben &thorn;ese &para; Ther is first sorwe of o&thorn;er mennes goodnes and of her pros|perite. and prosperite is kyndely matier of ioye. &thorn;anne is enuye a synne agayns kynde [492] &para; The secounde spice of enuye. is ioye of o&thorn;er mennes harm. and &thorn;at is proprely lik to the deuyl &thorn;at euer reioyeth him of mennes harm [493] &para; Of &thorn;ese tuo spices come&thorn; bacbityng. and &thorn;is synne of bakbytyng or detraccioun hath certein spices as &thorn;us &para; Som man praiseth his neighebor by a wickid entent. [494] For he makith alway a wickid knotte atte last ende. alway he makith a but. at &thorn;e last ende &thorn;at is &thorn;ing of more blame &thorn;an worth is al &thorn;e praysing [495] &para; The secounde spice is &thorn;at if a man be good and doth or sai&thorn; a &thorn;ing to good entent; &thorn;e bacbiter wol torne al &thorn;ilke goodnes vpso-doun to his schrewed entent. [496] &THORN;e &thorn;ridde is to amenuse &thorn;e bounte of his neighe|bor. [497] &thorn;e fer&thorn;e spiece of bakbytyng is &thorn;is. &thorn;at if men speke goodnes of a man; &thorn;an wil &thorn;e bakbiter seyn . par fay &yogh;it such a man is bet &thorn;an he in dispraysynge of him &thorn;at men praise. [498] &thorn;e fifte spice is &thorn;is for to consente gladly and herken gladly to &thorn;e harm &thorn;at men speke of o&thorn;er folk . &thorn;is synne is ful gret and ay encresith after thentent of &thorn;e bakbiter [499] &para; After bakbytyng come&thorn; grucching or murmuracioun. And som tyme it springith of Insapiens agayns god. and somtyme agains man. 
<PB REF="00000647.tif" N="635"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="629"> [500] agayns god is it. whan a man grucchith agayn pyne of helle or agayns pouerte. or of losse of catel. or agayn reyn or tempest <MILESTONE N="266a" UNIT="folio">or elles grucchi&thorn; &thorn;at schrewes han prosperite or ellis &thorn;at goode men han ad|uersite. [501] and alle &thorn;ese &thorn;inges schulde men suffre paciently. for &thorn;ay come by rightful iuggement and ordinaunce of god [502] &para; Som tyme cometh grucching of auarice as Iudas grucched a&yogh;ens &thorn;e Maudeleyn whan sche anoynted &thorn;e hed of oure lord ih&umacr; crist with hir precious oynement. [503] &thorn;is maner murmur is swich as man grucchith of goodnes &thorn;at himself do&thorn; or &thorn;at o&thorn;er folk doon of here owne catel [504] &para; Som tyme come&thorn; murmur of pride. as whan Symon &thorn;e pharise grucchid agayn &thorn;e maudeleyn whan sche approchid to ih&umacr; crist and wepte at his feet for hir synnes. [505] And somtyme it sourdith of enuye whan men discoueren a mannes harm &thorn;at was priue or bere&thorn; him on hond &thorn;ing &thorn;at is fals [506] &para; Murmuryng eek is ofte among seruaunt&yogh; &thorn;at grucchen whan here souerayns bidden hem to doon leeful &thorn;inges. [507] and for as moche as &thorn;ay dar nou&yogh;t openly wi&thorn;stonde the comaundement&yogh; of here souerayns; &yogh;it wol thay sayn harm and grucche and murmure priuely for verray despit / [508] whiche wordes men clepe &thorn;e deueles pater noster. &thorn;ough so be &thorn;at &thorn;e deuel hadde neuer pater noster but &thorn;at lewed men calle it so [509] &para; Som tyme it come&thorn; of Ire of priue hate &thorn;at norischeth rancour in herte as I schal declare. [510] &thorn;anne come&thorn; eek bitternes of herte. &thorn;orugh which bitternesse euery good deede of his neighebore seme&thorn; to him bitter and vnsauery [511] &para; But &thorn;anne come&thorn; discord &thorn;at vnbyndeth alle maner of frendschipe. &thorn;anne come&thorn; scornynge. of . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> his neighe|bor al do he neuer so wel. [512] &thorn;anne come&thorn; accusyng. as whan man seketh occasioun to annoyen his 
<PB REF="00000648.tif" N="636"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="630"> neighebore which &thorn;at is lik &thorn;e craft of &thorn;e deuel &thorn;at waytith bo&thorn;e night and day to accuse vs alle [513] &para; &THORN;anne come&thorn; malignite &thorn;urgh which a man annoyeth his neighebor priuely if he may. [514] And if he not may algate his wikkid while schal nought wante as for to brenne his hous priuely or empoysone or sleen his bestis priuely and semblable &thorn;inges<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; Remedium contra Inuidiam. [<I>from the margin</I>]</HEAD>
<P>[515]</P>
<P>NOw wol I speke of &thorn;e remedies agayns &thorn;ise foule &thorn;inges and &thorn;is foule synne of enuye &para; First is &thorn;e loue of god principal and louynge of his neighebor as himself. &para; So&thorn;ely &thorn;at oon ne may nought ben wi&thorn;oute &thorn;at o&thorn;er [516] &para; And truste wel &thorn;at in &thorn;e name of &thorn;y neighebour &thorn;ou <MILESTONE N="266b" UNIT="folio">schalt vnderstonde &thorn;e name of &thorn;y bro&thorn;er. For alle we haue oon fader fleisschly and oon mooder &thorn;at is to sain adam and eua and eek oon fader spirituel &amp; &thorn;at is god of heuen. [517] &THORN;y neghhebor artow holden for to loue. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> &thorn;at is to sayn bo&thorn;e to sauacioun of lif and of soule [518] and more ouer. &thorn;ou schalt loue hym in word and in benigne amonestyng and chastising &amp; conforte him in his annoyes and praye for him with al &thorn;in herte [519] &para; &amp; in dede &thorn;ou schalt loue him in such wise &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt do to him charite as &thorn;ou woldist it were doon to &thorn;in oughne persone [520] and &thorn;erfore &thorn;ou schalt doon him noon harme in wikked word ne damage him in his body ne in his catel ne in his soule by wicked entising of ensample [521] &para; &thorn;ou schalt nou&yogh;t desiren his wif/ ne noone of his &thorn;inges &para; vnderstonde eek &thorn;at in the name of &thorn;y neighebor is com|prehendid his enemy [522] &para; Certes man schal loue his enemy by &thorn;e comaundement of god. and so&thorn;ly &thorn;y frend schalt &thorn;ou loue in god [523] &para; I sayde &thorn;in enemy schaltow loue for goddes sake by his comaunde|ment 
<PB REF="00000649.tif" N="637"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="631"> for if it were resoun that man schulde hate his enemy For-so&thorn;e god nolde nou&yogh;t receyue vs to his loue &thorn;at ben his enemys [524] &para; Agains &thorn;re maner of wronges &thorn;at his enemy do&thorn; to him he schal do &thorn;re &thorn;inges as &thorn;us. [525] agayns hate and rancour of herte he schal loue him in herte. Agayns chydyng and wicked wordes he schal pray for his enemye. agains wikked dede of his enemy he schal doon him bounte [526] &para; For crist saith loue&thorn; &yogh;oure enemyes and praye&thorn; for hem &thorn;at &yogh;ow chacen and pursewen. and do&thorn; bounte to hem &thorn;at &yogh;ow haten. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap.</NOTE> [527] For sothely nature driue&thorn; vs to loue oure frendes / and par fay oure enemyes han more neede to loue &thorn;an oure frendes &para; For sothely to hem &thorn;at more neede haue certis to hem schul men do good|nes. [528] And certis in &thorn;ilke dede haue we by remem|braunce of &thorn;e loue of ih&umacr; crist &thorn;at dyed for his enemys [529] &para; And in als moche as &thorn;ilke loue is more greuous to parforme; so moche is &thorn;e more gret remedye &amp; meryt &para; And &thorn;erfore &thorn;e louyng of oure enemy ha&thorn; confoundid the venym of &thorn;e deuel. [530] For right as &thorn;e deuel is confoundid by humilite; Right so is he woundid to &thorn;e deth by loue of oure enemy [531] &para; Certes &thorn;anne is loue &thorn;e medicine &thorn;at castith out &thorn;e venym of enuye fro mannes hert. [532] the spices of &thorn;is part<MILESTONE N="267a" UNIT="folio"> schuln be more largely declared in here chapitres folwynge<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; <B>De Ira.</B>[<I>from the margin</I>]</HEAD>
<P>[533]</P>
<P>AFter enuye wol I descryuen &thorn;e synne of Ire. For so&thorn;ely who so ha&thorn; enuye vpon his neighebor; anoon he wol comunly fynde him a matiere of wra&thorn;&thorn;e in word or in dede agayns him to whom he ha&thorn; envie. [534] and as wel come&thorn; Ire of pride 
<PB REF="00000650.tif" N="638"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="632"> as of enuye &para; For so&thorn;ly he &thorn;at is proud or enuyous is lightly wroth.</P>
<P>[535] &thorn;is synne of Ire after &thorn;e descryuyng of seint austyn is wikked wille to ben auengid by word or by dede [536] &para; Ire afte &thorn;e philosofer is &thorn;e feruent blood of man I-quiked in his hert &thorn;urgh which he wolde harm to him &thorn;at him hati&thorn; [537] &para; For certes &thorn;e hert of man by eschawfyng and mornyng of his blood waxith so trouble / &thorn;at he is out of alle Iuggements of resoun [538] &para; But &yogh;e schal vnder-stonde &thorn;at ire is in tuo maneres. &thorn;at oon of hem is good. &thorn;at o&thorn;er is wikke [539] &para; The good Ire is by ialousy of goodnesse &thorn;urgh which a man is wro&thorn; wi&thorn; wikkidnes. and . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> &thorn;er|fore saith a wise man &thorn;at ire is bet &thorn;an play. [540] This Ire is with deboneirete. and it is wro&thorn; wi&thorn;|oute bitternes. not wroth with &thorn;e man; but wro&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e mys dedes of &thorn;e man as sai&thorn; &thorn;e prophet dauid &para; Irascimini &amp; nolite peccare. &amp;c [541] &para; Now vnderstonde &thorn;at wikked Ire is in tuo maners &thorn;at is to sayn sodeyn Ire or hastif Ire wi&thorn;oute auysement and consenting of resoun. [542] the menynge and &thorn;e sentence of &thorn;is is &thorn;at &thorn;e resoun of a man ne con|sentith not to &thorn;ilke sodein Ire. And &thorn;anne is it venial [543] &para; ano&thorn;er Ire is ful wicked &thorn;at come&thorn; of felony of herte auysed &amp; cast biforn with wickid wille to do vengeaunce and &thorn;erto his resoun consentith. and sothely &thorn;is is deedly synne. [544] &thorn;is ire is so dis|plesaunt to god &thorn;at it troublith his hous and chaceth &thorn;e holy gost out of mannes soule and wastith and de|stroyeth &thorn;e liknes of god . &thorn;at is to say &thorn;e vertu &thorn;at is in mannes soule [545] and put in him &thorn;e like|nes of &thorn;e deuel and bynymeth &thorn;e man fro god &thorn;at is his rightful lord [546] &para; This Ire is a ful greet plesaunce to &thorn;e deuel. for it is &thorn;e deueles fornays &thorn;at is eschaufid wi&thorn; &thorn;e fuyr of helle [547] &para; For certes 
<PB REF="00000651.tif" N="639"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="633"> right so as fuyr is more mighty to destroye er&thorn;ely &thorn;inges &thorn;an eny o&thorn;er element; Right so Ire is mighty to destroye alle spirituel &thorn;inges [548] &para; loke how &thorn;at fuyr of smale gledis &thorn;at ben almost dede vnder asshen wolden quiken agayn whan &thorn;ay ben touched . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> <MILESTONE N="267b" UNIT="folio">by pride &thorn;at is couered in mannes herte [549] &para; For certes fuyr may nou&yogh;t come out of no &thorn;ing . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> naturelly as fuyr is drawe out of flintes with steel [550] &para; Right so as pride is often tyme mater of Ire; Right so is Rancour norice and keper of Ire [551] &para; Ther is a maner tree as sai&thorn; seint Isydre . &thorn;at whan men maken fuyr of &thorn;ilke tree and couer &thorn;e colis wi&thorn; asshen; so&thorn;ly &thorn;e fuyr of it wol lasten al a &yogh;er or more. [552] And right so fare&thorn; it of rancour whan it oones is conceyued in &thorn;e hertis of som men; certein it wol lasten fro oon estren day vntil ano&thorn;er ester day and more. [553] but certis &thorn;ilke man is ful fer fro &thorn;e mercy of god al &thorn;ilke while</P>
<P>[554] &para; In &thorn;is forsaide deueles fornays &thorn;er forgen &thorn;re schrewes. pride &thorn;at/ ay blowith &amp; encresith &thorn;e fuyr by chidyng and wickid wordis [555] &para; &thorn;anne stont enuye and blowith &thorn;e hoote Iren vpon &thorn;e hert/ of man wi&thorn; a paire of longe tonges of rancour [556] and &thorn;anne &thorn;e sinne of contumelie or strif and cheste and baterith and forgeth by vileyns repreuynges [557] &para; Certes &thorn;is cursed synne annoyeth bo&thorn;e to &thorn;e man himsilf and eek to his neighebor &para; For so&thorn;ely almost al &thorn;e harm &thorn;at eny man doth to his neighebour come&thorn; &thorn;urgh wra&thorn;&thorn;e [558] &para; For certis outrageous wra&thorn;&thorn;e do&thorn; al &thorn;at euer &thorn;e deuyl him comaundeth. For he ne spare&thorn; ney&thorn;er crist ne his moodir. [559] and in his out|rage anger and Ire. allas ful many oon at &thorn;at tyme felith in his herte ful wikkedly 
<PB REF="00000652.tif" N="640"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="634"> bo&thorn;e of crist and eek of alle his halwes. [560] Is nat &thorn;is a cursed vice; yis certis. it bynymeth fro man his witte and his resoun and al his deboneire lyf spirituel &thorn;at scholde kepen his soule [561] &para; Certes it bynyme&thorn; eek goddis dewe lordschipe and &thorn;at is mannes soule. and &thorn;e loue of his neighebor. hit stryue&thorn; eek alday agayns trou&thorn;e &para; It reueth him eek &thorn;e quiete of his hert and subuertith his herte and his soule</P>
<P>[562] &para; Of ire come&thorn; &thorn;ese stynkynge engendrures &para; First hate &thorn;at is old wra&thorn;&thorn;e discord &thorn;urgh which a man forsaki&thorn; his olde frend &thorn;at he ha&thorn; loued ful longe. [563] and &thorn;anne come&thorn; werre and euery maner of wronge &thorn;at man doth to his neighebor in body or catel [564] &para; Of &thorn;is cursed synne of Ire come&thorn; eek manslaughter. And vnderstonde wel &thorn;at homicidie &thorn;at is man-slaughter is in diuers wise. &para; Som maner of homicidie is spirituel and som is bodily. [565] <MILESTONE N="268a" UNIT="folio">Spirituel manslaughter is in sixe &thorn;inges &para; First by hate as saith seint Iohan &para; he &thorn;at hate&thorn; his bro&thorn;er is an homicide. [566] homicide is eek by bak-bytyng of whiche bakbiters saith Salamon &thorn;at &thorn;ay haue twaye swerdes with whiche &thorn;ay slen here neighebors. For so&thorn;ely as wikke is to bynyme his good name as his lif. [567] homicidy is eek in &yogh;euyng of wikkid counseil by fraude as for to &yogh;eue counseil to areyse wicked and wrongful custumes and taliages [568] of whiche sai&thorn; Salomon &para; leoun roryng and bere hungry ben like to &thorn;e cruel lordschipes in wi&thorn;holdyng or abbrigging of &thorn;e schipe or the hyre or &thorn;e wages of seruauntes or ellis in vsure or in withdrawyng of almes of pore folk [569] For whiche &thorn;e pore man saith &para; Feedith him &thorn;at almost dyeth for hunger. for so&thorn;ely but if &thorn;ou feede him; &thorn;ou slest him and eek &thorn;ese ben dedly synnes. [570] bodily manslaughter is. whan &thorn;ou sleest him wi&thorn; &thorn;y tonge in o&thorn;er manere as whan &thorn;ou comaundist to slen a man or elles &yogh;iuest counseil to slee a 
<PB REF="00000653.tif" N="641"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="635"> man [571] &para; Manslau&yogh;ter in dede is in foure maneres &para; That oon is by lawe. Right as a Iustice dampnith him &thorn;at is coupable to &thorn;e deth. But let &thorn;e Iustice be war &thorn;at he do it rightfully and &thorn;at he do it nought for delit to spille blood; but for keping of rightwis|nes [572] &para; Ano&thorn;er homicidy is doon for necessite. as whan a man sle&thorn; ano&thorn;er him defendaunt. and &thorn;at he may noon o&thorn;er wise eschape fro his deth. [573] but certeynly if he may escape wi&thorn;|oute slaughter of his aduersarie and sleth him he doth synne and he schal bere penaunce as for dedly synne. [574] &para; Ek if a man by caas or aduenture schete an arwe or cast a stoon wi&thorn; which he sle&thorn; a man; he is an homicide. [575] Eke if a womman by negligence ouerlye hir child in hir sleping it is homicide and deedly synne [576] &para; Eke whan man distourbith con|cepcioun of a child and makith a womman ou&thorn;er bareyn by drinke of venenous herbis &thorn;urgh whiche sche may nou&yogh;t conceyue or sleth a child by drynkes. or elles putte&thorn; certeyn material &thorn;inges in secre place to slee &thorn;e child. [577] or elles do&thorn; vnkyndely synne by which man or womman schedith here nature in ma[n] or in place &thorn;er as &thorn;e child may nought be con|ceyued. or ellis if a womma[n] haue conceyued and hurt hirself and sleth &thorn;e child &yogh;it is it homycidie [578] <MILESTONE N="268b" UNIT="folio">&para; What say we eek of wommen &thorn;at mordren here children for drede of worldly schame. Certes an horrible homicidy. [579] homicidy is eek if a man ap|proche to a womman by desir of lecchery &thorn;urgh &thorn;e which &thorn;e child is perischt or elles smitith a womman wytyngly &thorn;urgh which sche sleeth hir child. alle &thorn;ese ben homi|cides . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> [580] &para; &YOGH;it cometh &thorn;er of Ire many mo synnes as wel in word as in werk &amp; &thorn;ought. As he &thorn;at arettith vpon god and blamith god of &thorn;ing of which he is himself gulty or despisith god and alle his halwes as doon &thorn;ese cursed hasardours 
<PB REF="00000654.tif" N="642"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="636"> in diuers cuntrees. [581] &thorn;is cursed synne don &thorn;ay whan &thorn;ay felen in here herte ful wickidly of god and his halwes [582] &para; also whan &thorn;ay treten vnreuerently &thorn;e sacrament of &thorn;e auter. &thorn;ilke synne is so gret &thorn;at vnne&thorn;e may it be relessed but &thorn;at &thorn;e mercy of god passith alle his werkes. and is so gret and so benigne [583] &para; Thanne come&thorn; of Ire attry anger whan a man is scharply amonested in his schrifte to for|lete synne; [584] &thorn;anne wol he be angry and answere hokerly and angrily and defenden or excusen his synne by vnstedefastnesse of his fleisch. or elles he dede it to holde companye with his felawes. or ellis he saith &thorn;e fend entised him. [585] or elles he dide it for his &yogh;outhe. or ellis his complexioun is so corrageous &thorn;at he may not forbere. or ellis it is desteny. as he saith. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> it come&thorn; him of gentilesce of his auncetrie and semblable &thorn;inges [586] &para; Alle &thorn;ese maner of folk so wrappen hem in here synnes &thorn;at &thorn;ay wol nou&yogh;t deliuer hemself &para; For so&thorn;ely no wight &thorn;at excuseth him wilfully of his synne may nought / be deliuered of his synne til &thorn;at he mekely biknowe&thorn; his synne. [587] &para; After &thorn;is &thorn;anne . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> &thorn;at is expres agayns &thorn;e comaundement&yogh; of god &amp; &thorn;is bifallith often of angir and of Ire [588] &para; God saith. &thorn;ou schalt not take &thorn;e name of &thorn;y lord god in vayn or in ydil. &para; Also oure lord ih&umacr; crist saith by &thorn;e word of seint. Mathew . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [589] &para; Ne wol &yogh;e not swere in alle manere. neither by heuen for it is goddes trone. ne by &thorn;e eor&thorn;e for it is &thorn;e benche of his feet. ne by ierusalem; for it is &thorn;e cite of a gret king. ne by &thorn;in heed; &thorn;ou may nought make an her whit ne blak. [590] but sayeth by &yogh;oure word &yogh;e. &yogh;e. and nay. nay. and what it is more; it / is of euel. &thorn;us saith ih&umacr; crist [591] &para; For cristes sake swere&thorn; not so synfully in dismembring of crist. for cristes sake. bi 
<PB REF="00000655.tif" N="643"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="637"> soule. <MILESTONE N="269a" UNIT="folio">herte. boones and body. For certes it seme&thorn; &thorn;at &yogh;e &thorn;enke &thorn;at cursed Iewes ne dismembrit nought ynough&middot; &thorn;e precious persone of crist. but &yogh;e dismembre him more. [592] and if so be &thorn;at &thorn;e lawe com|pelle &yogh;ow to swere. &thorn;anne reule &yogh;ow after &thorn;e lawe of god in &yogh;oure swering as sai&thorn;. Ieremie capitulo .iiij<SUP>to</SUP> . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> &para; Thou schalt kepe &thorn;re condiciouns. &thorn;ou schalt swere in trou&thorn;e in doom and in rightwisnes [593] &thorn;is is to sayn. &thorn;ou schalt swere soth. For euery lesyng is agayns crist. for crist is verray trou&thorn;e and &thorn;ink wel &thorn;is &thorn;at euery gret swerer not compellid lawfully to swere &thorn;e wonder schal not departe fro his hous whil he vseth such vnleful sweringe [594] &para; &thorn;ou schalt eek swere in doom whan &thorn;ou art constreigned by &thorn;y domes|man to witnesse &thorn;e trou&thorn;e. [595] eek &thorn;ou schalt not swere for enuye ne for fauour ne for meede but / for rightwisnesse for declaring of it to worschip of god and helping of &thorn;in euen|cristen [596] and &thorn;erfore euery man &thorn;at taki&thorn; goddes name in ydil or falsly sweri&thorn; with his mouth or elles taki&thorn; on him &thorn;e name of crist and callith himself a cristen man and lyueth agayn cristes lyuyng and his teching alle &thorn;ay take cristes name in ydel [597] &para; loke eek what saith seint peter Actuum ca<SUP>o</SUP>. iiij<SUP>to</SUP> &para; Non est aliud nomen sub celo &amp;c &para; Ther is noon o&thorn;er name saith seint peter vnder heuen ne &yogh;euen to noon men in which &thorn;ay mowe be saued &thorn;at is to sayn but in &thorn;e name of ih&umacr; crist [598] &para; Tak heede eek how &thorn;e precious name of crist as saith seint poule ad philippenses .ij<SUP>o</SUP>. In nomine ih&umacr; &amp;c &para; That in &thorn;e name of ih&umacr; euery kne of heuenly creatures or er&thorn;ely or of helle schulde bowe and . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> tremble to heeren it nempned. [599] &para; Thanne seme&thorn; it &thorn;at men &thorn;at sweren so horribly by his 
<PB REF="00000656.tif" N="644"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="638"> blessed name &thorn;at &thorn;ay despise it more bodyly &thorn;an dede &thorn;e cursed Iewes or elles &thorn;e deuel &thorn;at tremblith whan he heerith his name</P>
<P>[600] &para; Now certis sith &thorn;at swering but it be lawfully doon is so heihly defendid; moche wors is forswering falsly and &yogh;it needeles</P>
<P>[601] what say we eek of hem &thorn;at deliten hem in swering and holden it a gentery or manly dede / to swere grete othis. and what of hem &thorn;at of verray vsage / ne cessen nou&yogh;t to swere grete o&thorn;is al be not &thorn;e cause wor&thorn; a strawe; certes &thorn;is is horrible synne [602] &para; Sweryng sodeynly wi&thorn;out auysement is eek a synne [603] &para; But let vs now go to &thorn;ilke horrible sweryng of adiuracioun and coniuraciouns as <MILESTONE N="269b" UNIT="folio">doon &thorn;ese false en|chauntours or nigromanciens in bacines ful or in a bright swerd in a churche or in a fuyr or in &thorn;e schulder bon of a scheep [604] &para; I can not sayn but &thorn;at &thorn;ay doon cursedly and dampnably agains &thorn;e faith of holy chirche</P>
<P>[605] what say we of hem &thorn;at bilieuen on diuinailes as by flight or by nois of briddes or of bestes or by sort by geomancie. by dremes. by chirkyng of dores or crakking of howses. by gnawyng of rattis and such maner wrecchidnes [606] &para; Certes al &thorn;is &thorn;ing is defended by god and holy chirche for whiche &thorn;ay ben accursed til &thorn;ay come to amendement &thorn;at on such filthe bisetten here bileeue. [607] Charmes for woundes or malady of men or of bestes if &thorn;ay take eny effect. it may be paraduenture &thorn;at god suffre&thorn; hit for folk schulde &yogh;eue &thorn;e more fai&thorn; and reuerence to his name</P>
<P>[608] &para; Now wol I speke of lesynge whiche gener|ally is fals signifiaunce of word in entent to desceyuen his euencristen [609] Som lesyng is of whiche &thorn;er cometh noon auauntage to noon wight and som lesyng torne&thorn; to &thorn;e ease or profit of som man. 
<PB REF="00000657.tif" N="645"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="639"> and to damage of an o&thorn;er man [610] &para; Ano&thorn;er lesyng for to saue his lif or his catel . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> come&thorn; of delit/ for to lye. in which delit &thorn;ay wol forge a long tale and paynte it with alle circumstaunces wher as &thorn;e ground of &thorn;e tale is fals [611] &para; Som lesyng come&thorn;. For he wolde susteyne his word &para; Som lesyng cometh of rechelesnes wi&thorn;oute auisement and sem|blable &thorn;inges</P>
<P>[612] &para; lat vs now touche &thorn;e vice of flaterie which cometh not gladly but for drede or for coueitise [613] &para; Flaterie is generally wrongful preysing. Flater|ers ben &thorn;e deueles norices &thorn;at norisshen his children wi&thorn; mylk of &thorn;e losingerie. [614] forso&thorn;e Salamon saith &thorn;at flaterie is worse &thorn;an detraccioun. for som tyme de|traccioun makith an hawteyn man be &thorn;e more humble for he dredith detraccioun &para; But certes flaterie makith a man to enhaunsen his hert/ and his countenaunce [615] &para; Flaterers ben &thorn;e deueles enchauntours. For &thorn;ay maken man to wene of himself &thorn;at he is like to &thorn;at he is nou&yogh;t like. [616] &THORN;ay ben like Iudas &thorn;at bitraised . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> to selle him to his enemy &thorn;at is &thorn;e deuel [617] &para; Flaterers ben &thorn;e deueles chapeleyns &thorn;at singen ay. placebo. [618] I rekene flaterers in &thorn;e vices of Ire. For ofte tyme if oon man be wro&thorn; wi&thorn; ano&thorn;er. &thorn;anne wol he flatere som man to mayntene him in his querel</P>
<P>[619] Speke we now of such cursyng as come&thorn; of Irous hert malisoun generally may be said euery maner power of harm. such <MILESTONE N="270a" UNIT="folio">cursyng bireue&thorn; man fro &thorn;e regne of god as sai&thorn; seint poule [620] &para; And ofte tyme such cursyng wrongfully retourne&thorn; agayn to hym &thorn;at curseth as &thorn;at retourne&thorn; agayn to his owne nest. [621] and ouer alle &thorn;inges men oughten eschewe to cursen here oughne children and &yogh;iue to &thorn;e deuel here engendrure as ferforth as in hem is Certis it is gret peril and gret synne
<PB REF="00000658.tif" N="646"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="640"></P>
<P>[622] &para; let vs &thorn;anne speke of chydynge and reproche whiche &thorn;at ben ful grete woundes in mannes hert . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [623] &para; For certis vnne&thorn;e may a man plainly ben accordid with him &thorn;at him openly reuyled and reproued and disclaundrid. &thorn;is is a ful grisly synne as crist saith in &thorn;e gospel. [624] and takith keep now &thorn;at he &thorn;at reproue&thorn; his neighebor. ou&thorn;er he reproue&thorn; him by som harm of peyne. . . . .[625]. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> &thorn;anne tornith &thorn;e reproef to ih&umacr; crist. For peyne is sent by &thorn;e rightwis sonde of god and by his suffraunce be it meselrie or many o&thorn;er maladies. [626] and if he repreue him vncharitably as &thorn;ou holour &thorn;ou dronk|elewe harlot and so forth &thorn;anne aperteyneth &thorn;at to &thorn;e reioysing of &thorn;e deuel &thorn;at euer ha&thorn; ioye &thorn;at men doon synne. [627] And certis chidyng may nought come but out of a vileins herte &para; For after &thorn;e abundaunce of &thorn;e herte speke&thorn; &thorn;e mouth ful ofte. [628] and &yogh;e schal vnderstonde &thorn;at loke by any way whan any man schal chastise ano&thorn;er &thorn;at he be war fro chyding or repreuyng. For trewely but he be war; he may ful lightly quiken &thorn;e fuyr of anger and of wra&thorn;&thorn;e which &thorn;at he schulde quenchen: and par auenture sle&thorn; &thorn;at he mighte chaste with benig|nite. [629] for as sai&thorn; salamon &para; The amiable tonge is &thorn;e tree of lif &thorn;at is to sayn of lif espirituel. and so&thorn;ely dislaue tonge sle&thorn; &thorn;e spirit of him . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> &thorn;at is repreued [630] &para; lo what saith seint augustyn &para; Ther is no &thorn;ing so lik &thorn;e fendes child as he &thorn;at ofte chide&thorn; &para; Seint poule sei&thorn; eek I seruaunt of god bihoueth nou&yogh;t to chide. [631] and &thorn;ough &thorn;at chidyng be a vileins &thorn;ing bitwixe alle maner folk/; &yogh;it is it certes more vncouenable bitwix a man and his wif. For &thorn;er is neuer rest 
<PB REF="00000659.tif" N="647"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="641"> And &thorn;erfore saith Salamon &para; An hous &thorn;at is vncouered &amp; droppyng and a chidyng wyf ben like [632] a man &thorn;at is in dropping hous in many partes &thorn;ough he eschewe &thorn;e dropping in oon place; it droppe&thorn; on him in ano&thorn;er place &para; So farith it by a chydinge wyf; But sche chide him in oon place; sche wol chide him in ano&thorn;er [633] &para; And &thorn;erfore better is a morsel of bred with ioye &thorn;an an hous ful of delices with chyding sei&thorn; Salamon [634] <MILESTONE N="270b" UNIT="folio">&para; Seint poul saith &para; O &yogh;e wommen be &yogh;e sugettis to &yogh;oure housbondes as bihoue&thorn; in god. And &yogh;e men loueth &yogh;oure wyues ad Colocenses iij<SUP>o</SUP>.</P>
<P>[635] &para; Afterward speke we of scornyng which is a wikked &thorn;ing and sinful and namely whan he scornith a man for his goode workes [636] &para; For certes suche scornes faren lik &thorn;e foule toode &thorn;at may nought endure &thorn;e soote smel of &thorn;e vine roote whan it florischith. [637] &thorn;ese scorners ben partyng felawes wi&thorn; &thorn;e deuel. For &thorn;ay han ioye whan &thorn;e deuel wynneth and sorwe whan he leseth [638] &para; Thay ben aduersaries of Ih&umacr; crist. for &thorn;ay haten &thorn;at he loueth &thorn;at is to saye sauacioun of soule</P>
<P>[639] Speke we now of wikked counseil &para; For he &thorn;at wickid counseil &yogh;iueth. he is a traytour. for he deceyue&thorn; him &thorn;at truste&thorn; in him &para; vt achitofel ad absolonem &para; But na&thorn;eles &yogh;et is his wikkid counseil first a&yogh;ens him|self [640] &para; For as saith the wise man &para; Euery fals lyuyng ha&thorn; &thorn;is proprete in him self. &thorn;at he &thorn;at wil annoye ano&thorn;er man; he annoyeth first himself. [641] &para; and men schul vnderstonde &thorn;at men schulde nought take his counseil of fals folk ne of angry folk/ . . . . .] ne of folk &thorn;at louen specially to moche her oughne profyt ne in to moche worldly. folk. namely in coun|selyng of soules</P>
<P>[642] Now come&thorn; &thorn;e synne of hem &thorn;at sowen and maken discord amonges folk which is a synne &thorn;at/ 
<PB REF="00000660.tif" N="648"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="642"> crist hate&thorn; outrely . and no wonder is. for god died for to make concord. [643] and more schame do &thorn;ay to crist &thorn;an dede &thorn;ay &thorn;at him crucifiede &para; For god loueth bettre &thorn;at frendschipe be amonges folk &para; &thorn;anne he dide his owne body which &thorn;at/ he &yogh;af for vnite. &thorn;erfore ben &thorn;ay likned to &thorn;e deuel &thorn;at euer ben aboute to make discord</P>
<P>[644] &para; Now comith &thorn;e sinne of double tonge. suche as speken faire biforn folk and wikkedly bihynde or elles &thorn;ay make semblaunt as &thorn;ough &thorn;ay speke of good entencioun or ellis in game &amp; play and &yogh;it &thorn;ay speke in wikked entent</P>
<P>[645] &para; Now come&thorn; &thorn;e wreying of counseil &thorn;urgh which a man is famed &para; Certes vnnethe may he restore &thorn;at damage</P>
<P>[646] &para; Now come&thorn; manace &thorn;at is an open foly. For he &thorn;at ofte man[a]ceth he threttith more &thorn;an he may parfourme ful ofte tyme</P>
<P>[647] &para; Now come&thorn; Idel wordes &thorn;at is wi&thorn;oute profyt of him &thorn;at spekith &thorn;o wordes and eek of him &thorn;at herkene&thorn; &thorn;o wordes. or elles ydel wordes ben &thorn;o &thorn;at ben needeles or wi&thorn;outen entent of naturel profyt [648] and al be it &thorn;at ydil wordes ben som tyme venial synne; &yogh;it schulde men doute hem. For we schuln &yogh;iue rekenynge of hem bifore <MILESTONE N="271a" UNIT="folio">god</P>
<P>[649] &para; Now comith iangeling &thorn;at/ may nou&yogh;t be wi&thorn;|oute synne as saith Salamon &para; It is a signe of apert folie [650] and &thorn;erfore a philosophre whan men askid him how men schulde plese &thorn;e poeple and he answerde &para; Do many goode werkes. and spek/ fewe iangeles</P>
<P>[651] &para; After &thorn;is come&thorn; &thorn;e synne of iapers &thorn;at ben &thorn;e deueles apes For &thorn;ay maken folk to laughen at here iapes or iaperie as folk doon at/ &thorn;e gaudes of an ape / Suche iapes defendith seint poule [652] &para; Loke how &thorn;at vertuous and holy wordes conforten hem 
<PB REF="00000661.tif" N="649"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="643"> &thorn;at trauailen in &thorn;e seruice of crist; Right so conforten &thorn;e violent wordes and knakkis and iaperies hem &thorn;at trauayle in &thorn;e seruice of &thorn;e deuyl [653] &para; These ben &thorn;e synnes &thorn;at/ come&thorn; of . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> Ire and of o&thorn;er synnes<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; Remedium contra Iram</HEAD>
<P>[654]</P>
<P>REmedye agayns ire is a vertue &thorn;at men clepe mansuetude. &thorn;at is deboneirte. And eek ano&thorn;er vertue &thorn;at men clepe pacience or sufferaunce.</P>
<P>[655] debonairete wi&thorn;drawith and restreigne&thorn; &thorn;e stiringes and &thorn;e moeuynges of mannys corrage in his herte in such manere &thorn;at &thorn;ai ne skip not out by anger ne by Ire [656] &para; Suffraunce suffrith swetely al &thorn;e annoyaunce and &thorn;e wronges &thorn;at men doon to man outward [657] &para; Seint Ierom sai&thorn; &thorn;us of debonairte. &thorn;at it do&thorn; noon harm to no wight ne saith ne for noon harm &thorn;at men doon ne sayn. he ne eschaufith nought agayns his resoun [658] &para; This vertu comi&thorn; som tyme of nature &para; For as saith &thorn;e philosopher man is a quik &thorn;ing by nature and tretable to goodnesse &para; But whan debonairete is enformed of grace; &thorn;an is it &thorn;e more wor&thorn;</P>
<P>[659] &para; Pacience &thorn;at is ano&thorn;er remedie. agains Ire is a vertu &thorn;at suffreth swetely euery mannes goodnes as is not wro&thorn; for noon harm &thorn;at is doon to him. [660] &thorn;e philosopher saith &thorn;at pacience is &thorn;ilke vertue &thorn;at suffrith deboneirly alle &thorn;e outrages of aduersite and euery wickid word [661] &para; This vertue maki&thorn; a man lik to god and makith him goddes oughne dere child as sai&thorn; crist &para; &thorn;is vertu destroye&thorn; &thorn;in enemy and &thorn;erfore saith &thorn;e wise man &para; If &thorn;ou wolt venquisch &thorn;in enemy lerne to suffre [662] &para; And &thorn;ou schalt vnderstonde &thorn;at man suffrith foure maners 
<PB REF="00000662.tif" N="650"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="644"> of greuaunces in outward &thorn;inges. agains whiche he moot haue foure maners of pacience</P>
<P>[663] &para; The firste greuaunce is of wicked wordes. &thorn;ilke suffred Ih&umacr; crist wi&thorn;oute grucching ful paciently whan &thorn;e iewes despised him and reproued him ful ofte. [664] suffre &thorn;ou &thorn;erfore paciently &para; For &thorn;e wise man sai&thorn; &para; If <MILESTONE N="271b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;ou striue with a fool. &thorn;ough &thorn;e fool be wro&thorn; or &thorn;ough he laughhe algate &thorn;ou schalt haue no rest [665] &para; That o&thorn;er greuaunce outward is to haue damage of &thorn;i catel; &thorn;er agayn suffred crist ful paciently whan he was despoylid of al &thorn;at he had in his lif and &thorn;at nas but his clo&thorn;is [666] &para; The &thorn;ridde greuaunce is. a man to haue harm in his body. &thorn;at suffred crist/ ful paciently in al his passioun [667] &para; The fer&thorn;e greuaunce is in outrageous labour in werkis wherfore I say &thorn;at folk &thorn;at maken here seruaunt&yogh; to trauaile to greuously or out of tyme as on haly dayes. so&thorn;ely &thorn;ay doon greet synne [668] &para; Here against suffred crist ful paciently and taughte vs pacience whan he bar vpon his blisful schulder &thorn;e croys vpon which he schulde suffre despitous deth. [669] here may men lerne to be pacient. For certes nought oonly cristen ben pacient for &thorn;e loue of ih&umacr; crist and for guerdoun of &thorn;e blisful life &thorn;at is perdurable But &thorn;e olde paynymes &thorn;at neuer were cristen comaundedin and vseden &thorn;e vertu of pacience</P>
<P>[670] &para; A philosopher vpon a tyme &thorn;at wolde haue bete his disciple for his grete trespas. For which he was gretly amoeued and brought a &yogh;erde to scoure &thorn;e child. [671] &amp; whan &thorn;e child saugh &thorn;e &yogh;erde; he sayde to his maister &para; what &thorn;enke &yogh;e to do &para; I wolde bete &thorn;e quod &thorn;e maister for &thorn;i correccioun [672] Forso&thorn;e quod &thorn;e child. &yogh;e oughte first correcte &yogh;oure silf &thorn;at han left al &yogh;oure pacience for &thorn;e gilt of a child [673] &para; For so&thorn;e quod &thorn;e maister al wepyng. &thorn;ou 
<PB REF="00000663.tif" N="651"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="645"> saist soth. haue &thorn;ou &thorn;e &yogh;erde my deere sone and correcte me for myn impacience. [674] Of pacience come&thorn; obedience. &thorn;urgh which a man is obedient to crist/ and to alle hem to which him oughte to be obedient in crist. [675] and vnderstonde wel &thorn;at obedience is parfyt. whan a man do&thorn; gladly &amp; hastily with good herte outrely al &thorn;at he scholde do [676] &para; Obedience is generally to parforme &thorn;e doctrine of god and of his soueraignes to whiche him oughte to ben obeissant in alle rightwisnes.<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></P>
<P>[677]</P>
<P>AFter &thorn;e synne of enuye and Ire. now wol I speke of . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> accidie. For enuye blendith &thorn;e hert of a man and Ire troublith a man and accidie makith him heuy. &thorn;oughtful. and wrawe [678] &para; Enuye and Ire maken bitternes in herte. which bitternesse is mooder of accidie and bynimith &thorn;e loue of alle goodnes. &thorn;anne is accidie &thorn;e anguische of trouble hert and seint augustyn saith . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> [679] &para; Certes &thorn;is is a dampnable synne. For it do&thorn; wrong to Ih&umacr; <MILESTONE N="272a" UNIT="folio">crist in as moche as it bynyme&thorn; &thorn;e seruice &thorn;at we ought to do to crist wi&thorn; alle diligence as sai&thorn; Salomon [680] &para; But accidie do&thorn; noon such diligence. he do&thorn; alle &thorn;ing wi&thorn; anoy and with drawenes. slaknes and excusacioun. and with ydelnes &amp; vnlust for which &thorn;e book saith &para; Accursed be he &thorn;at do&thorn; &thorn;e seruice of god necligently [681] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> enemy to euery astaat of man &para; For certes &thorn;estat of . . . . .[682] . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> Innocence. as was &thorn;astate of adam biforn &thorn;at he fel in to synne in which estate he is holden to worche as in herying and honouryng of god [683] &para; Ano&thorn;er astat is &thorn;e state of sinful man. in which estate. men ben holden 
<PB REF="00000664.tif" N="652"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="646"> to labore in praying to god for amendement of her synnes. and &thorn;at he wolde graunte hem to rise of here synnes [684] &para; Ano&thorn;er estaat is &thorn;estate of which he is holde to werkis of penitence and certes to alle &thorn;ese &thorn;inges is accidie enuye con|trarie for it loue&thorn; no busynes at al [685] &para; Now certis &thorn;is foule synne accidie is eek a ful gret enemy to &thorn;e liflode of &thorn;e body For it hath no purueaunce a&yogh;ens temperel necessite. for it forslowthith and for|sluggith and destroyeth alle goodes temporels by rechelesnes</P>
<P>[686] &para; The fer&thorn;e &thorn;ing is &thorn;at accidie is like hem &thorn;at ben in &thorn;e peyne of helle by cause of her slou&thorn;e and of her heuynes For &thorn;ay &thorn;at ben dampned ben so bounde &thorn;at &thorn;ay may nought wel do ne wel &thorn;enke [687] &para; Of accidie cometh first &thorn;at a man is annoyed and encombrid for to do eny goodnes. and makith that god ha&thorn; abhominacioun of such accidie as saith seint Iohan.</P>
<P>[688] &para; Now come&thorn; slou&thorn;e &thorn;at wol suffre noon hardnes ne no penaunce For so&thorn;ely slou&thorn;e is so tendre and so delicat as saith Salomon &thorn;at he wol suffre noon hardnes ne penaunce. and &thorn;erfore he schendeth al &thorn;at he doth [689] &para; Agayns &thorn;is roten hertid synne of accidie and of slouthe schulden men exercise hemself to do goode werkes and manly and vertuously cacchin corrage wel to doo. &thorn;ink|ing &thorn;at oure lord ih&umacr; crist quite&thorn; euery good dede be it neuer so lyte. [690] &para; Vsage of labour is a ful greet &thorn;ing. for it makith as sai&thorn; seint Bernard &thorn;e laborer to haue stronge armes and harde synewes &para; And slouthe maketh hem feble and tendre [691] &para; Thanne come&thorn; drede to bygynne to werke eny goode deedes; For certes what &thorn;at is enclined to don synne him &thorn;inkith it is so gret emprise for to vndertake to doon werkes of goodnes [692] / as . . . . .
<PB REF="00000665.tif" N="653"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="647"> . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> sai&thorn; seynt gregory</P>
<P>[693] &para; Now come&thorn; wanhope &thorn;at is despair of &thorn;e mercy of god &thorn;at come&thorn; som tyme of to moche out|rageous sorwe <MILESTONE N="272b" UNIT="folio">and som tyme of to moche drede ymagyn|ynge &thorn;at he ha&thorn; do so moche synne &thorn;at it wil not auaile him &thorn;ough he wolde repent him and forsake synne. [694] &thorn;urgh which despeir or drede he abundith al his herte to alle maner synne as seith seint augustin. [695] whiche dampnable synne if &thorn;at it continue vnto his lyues ende it is cleped synnyng of &thorn;e holy gost. [696] This horrible synne is so perilous. &thorn;at he &thorn;at is despaired &thorn;er is no felonye ne no synne &thorn;at he doutith for to do. as schewed wel by Iudas. [697] Certes aboue alle synnes. &thorn;an is &thorn;is synne most displesant to crist and most aduersarie [698] sothely he &thorn;at despisith him is like &thorn;e coward campioun recreaunt &thorn;at seith recreaunt wi&thorn;oute neede. allas allas needeles is he recreaunt and needeles despaired [699] &para; Certes &thorn;e mercy of god is euer redy to &thorn;e penitent and is aboue alle his werkes. [700] allas can not a man by&thorn;enk him on &thorn;e gospel of seint luk/ wher as crist saith &thorn;at as wel schal &thorn;er be ioye in heuen vpon a synful man &thorn;at do&thorn; penitence as vpon nynety and nyne &thorn;at ben rightful men &thorn;at . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> needen no penitence [701] &para; loke for&thorn;er in &thorn;e same gospel &thorn;e ioye and &thorn;e fest of &thorn;e goode man &thorn;at had lost his sone. whan &thorn;e sone with repentaunce was torned to his fader [702] &para; Can not &thorn;ay remembre eek &thorn;at as sai&thorn; seint luk xxiij<SUP>o</SUP>. how &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;ef &thorn;at was hangid biside ih&umacr; crist sayde &para; lord remembre of me whan &thorn;ou comest in to &thorn;y regne [703] &para; Forso&thorn;e saith crist. to day &thorn;ou schalt be wi&thorn; me in paradis [704] &para; Certis &thorn;er is noon so horrible synne of 
<PB REF="00000666.tif" N="654"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="648"> man &thorn;at it may in his lif be destroyed with penitence &thorn;orugh vertu of passioun of &thorn;e deth of crist [705] &para; Allas what needith it man &thorn;anne to be despaired sith &thorn;at his mercy is so redy and large. aske and haue [706] &para; Thanne come&thorn; sompnolent &thorn;at is sluggy slumbring which maki&thorn; a man ben heuy and dul in body and in soule. and &thorn;is synne come&thorn; of slou&thorn;e [707] and certes &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at by way of resoun man schulde nou&yogh;t slepe &thorn;at is by &thorn;e morwe but if &thorn;er were cause resonable [708] For so&thorn;ely &thorn;e morwe tyde is most/ couenable to a man to say his prayers and for to &thorn;enk vpon his god and to honoure god and to &yogh;eue almes to &thorn;e pore &thorn;at first come&thorn; in &thorn;e name of crist [709] &para; lo what saith Salamon. &para; who-so wol by &thorn;e morwe arise and seeke me schal fynde [710] &para; &thorn;an come&thorn; negligence that/ rekkith of no &thorn;ing and how &thorn;at ignoraunce be moder of alle harm; Certis necgligence is &thorn;e norice [711] &para; Necligence do&thorn; no force whan he schal doon a &thorn;ing whethir he doo it wel or baddely</P>
<P>[712] &para; Of &thorn;e remedy of &thorn;ese tuo synnes as saith <MILESTONE N="273a" UNIT="folio">&thorn;e wise man &para; That he &thorn;at dredith god he sparith nou&yogh;t to do &thorn;at him ought to don. [713] and he &thorn;at loueth god wol do diligence to plese god by his werkis and abounde himself with alle his mightes wel for to doon [714] &para; Thanne comith ydelnes &thorn;at is &thorn;e &yogh;ate of alle<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Omnium ma|lorum mater est negligencia</NOTE> harmes. and ydil man is like an hous &thorn;at/ ha&thorn; noone walles. &thorn;e deueles may entre on euery syde or schete at him at discouert/ by temptaciouns on euery syde [715] &para; This ydelnes is &thorn;e thurrok/ of alle wickid vileyns &thorn;oughtes and of alle iangles tryfles and of alle ordure [716] &para; Certes &thorn;e heuen is &yogh;euen to hem &thorn;at wol laboure and nou&yogh;t to ydil folk &para; Eke dauid saith That / &thorn;ay ne ben not in &thorn;e labour of men ne &thorn;ay schul not be wiped with men &thorn;at is to sain in purgatorie 
<PB REF="00000667.tif" N="655"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="649"> [717] &para; Certes &thorn;anne semeth it &thorn;at &thorn;ay schal be tormentid wi&thorn; &thorn;e deuel in helle but if &thorn;ay don penitence</P>
<P>[718] &para; &thorn;anne comith &thorn;e synne &thorn;at men clepe tarditas. as whan a man is so latrede or tarying er he wil torne to god. and certis &thorn;at is a gret foly. he is like him &thorn;at fallith in to &thorn;e diche and wol not arise / [719] And &thorn;is vice cometh of a fals hope &thorn;at he &thorn;inkith he schal lyue longe. but &thorn;at hope fayle&thorn; ful ofte</P>
<P>[720] &para; &thorn;anne comith laches. &thorn;at is he when he bigynneth any good werk anoon he wol forlete it and stynte as doon &thorn;ay &thorn;at/ han eny wight to gouerne. and ne take of hem no more keep anoon as &thorn;ay fynde eny contrarie or eny anoy [721] &para; &thorn;ese ben &thorn;e newe schepherdes &thorn;at leten her schep wityngely go renne to &thorn;e wolf &thorn;at is in &thorn;e breres or don no force of her oughne gouernaunce. [722] Of &thorn;is come&thorn; pouert and destruccioun bo&thorn;e of spirituel and of temperel &thorn;inges &para; Thanne come&thorn; a maner of coldenesse &thorn;at frese&thorn; al &thorn;e hert of man [723] &thorn;anne cometh vndeuocioun &thorn;urgh which a man is so blunt &amp; as sai&thorn; seint Bernard he ha&thorn; such a langour in soule &thorn;at he may ney&thorn;eir rede ne synge in holy chirche ne heere ne &thorn;inke on deuocioun in holy chirche ne trauayle with his hondes in no good werk &thorn;at nys &thorn;o him vnsauory and al [724] &thorn;anne waxith he slow and slombry and soone wol he be wro&thorn; and soone is enclined to hate and to enuye [725] &para; &thorn;anne comith &thorn;e synne of worldly sorwe such as is clepid tristicia &thorn;at sleth man as saith seint poule [726] &para; For certis such sorwe werkith to &thorn;e deth of &thorn;e soule. &amp; of &thorn;e body also. For &thorn;er of cometh &thorn;at a man is anoyed of his oughne lif. [727] which sorwe schorte&thorn; ful ofte &thorn;e lif of a man or &thorn;at his tyme is come by way of kynde<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000668.tif" N="656"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="650"></P>
<P>[728] &para; Agains &thorn;is horrible <MILESTONE N="273b" UNIT="folio">synne of accidie and &thorn;e braunches of &thorn;e same &thorn;er is a vertu &thorn;at is cleped fortitudo or streng&thorn;e &thorn;at is affeccioun &thorn;urgh which a man despiseth alle noyous &thorn;inges [729] &para; This vertu is so mighty &amp; so vigurous &thorn;at it dar wi&thorn;stonde mighty and wisely kepe himself from perils &thorn;at ben wicked and wrastil agains &thorn;e assautes of &thorn;e deuel. [730] For it enhaunsith and enforce&thorn; &thorn;e soule. Right as accidie abateth it and makith it feble. For &thorn;is fortitudo may endure by long sufferaunce &thorn;e trauailes &thorn;at ben conuenables</P>
<P>[731] &para; This vertu ha&thorn; many spices. &thorn;e first is cleped magnanimite &thorn;at is to sayn gret corrage. For certis &thorn;er bihoue&thorn; gret corrage agains accidie lest &thorn;at it ne swolwe not &thorn;e soule by &thorn;e synne of sorwe or destroye it by wanhope [732] &para; This vertu makith folk vndertake harde &thorn;inges and greuous &thorn;inges by his owne wille willfuly and resonably. [733] and for als moche as &thorn;e deuel fighteth agaynst a man more by queyntise and by sleight &thorn;an by streng&thorn;e; &thorn;erfore many a man schal a&yogh;einstonde him by witte. and by resoun and by dis|crecioun. [734] Thanne is &thorn;er &thorn;e vertu of faith and hope in god and in his seintes to eschew. and to acomplice &thorn;e goode werkes in &thorn;e whiche he purposith fermely to continue. [735] thanne come&thorn; seurte or sikernes and &thorn;at is whan a man doutith no trauaile in tyme comyng of good werk &thorn;at a man ha&thorn; bygonne [736] &para; &thorn;anne come&thorn; magnificence &thorn;at is to say whan a man doth and parformith grete werkes of goodnesse &thorn;at he hath bygonne. and &thorn;at is &thorn;ende why &thorn;at men schulden do goode werkes. for in &thorn;e accomplising of grete goode werkes li&thorn; &thorn;e grete guerdoun. [737] &thorn;anne is &thorn;er constaunce &thorn;at is stablenes of corrage and &thorn;is schulde ben in herte by stedefast fai&thorn;. and in mouthe. and in 
<PB REF="00000669.tif" N="657"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="651"> beryng. and in cheer and in deede. [738] eek &thorn;er ben mo special remedies agayns accidie, in dyuers werkis and in consideracioun of &thorn;e peyne of helle and of &thorn;e ioye of heuen and in &thorn;e trust of &thorn;e hyhe grace of &thorn;e holy gost. &thorn;at wil &yogh;eue him might to parforme his good entent.<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De Auaricia[<I>from margin</I>]</HEAD>
<P>[739]</P>
<P>AFter accidie; I wil speke of auarice and of coueytise. Of whiche synnes For sothely whan saith sein poule &thorn;at &thorn;e roote of alle eueles &amp; harmes is coueytise/ [740] and &thorn;at &thorn;e hert of man is confoundid in it self and troublid and &thorn;at &thorn;e soule ha&thorn; lost &thorn;e comfort of god. &thorn;anne seekith he an ydel solas of worldly &thorn;inges.</P>
<P>[741] <MILESTONE N="274a" UNIT="folio">&para; Auarice after &thorn;e descripcioun of seint austyn. is a likerousnes in hert to haue er&thorn;ely &thorn;inges [742] &para; Some o&thorn;er folk sayn &thorn;at auarice is for to purchace many er&thorn;ely &thorn;inges and no &thorn;ing &yogh;eue to hem &thorn;at han neede [743] &para; And vnderstonde &thorn;at auarice ne stont not oonly in lond ne in catel; But som tyme in science and in glorie and eny maner outrageous &thorn;inges is auarice [744] &para; And &thorn;e difference bytwixe auarice and coueytise is &thorn;is. Coueitise is for to coueyte suche &thorn;inges as &thorn;ou hast not . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [745] &para; And auarice is a synne &thorn;at is ful dampnable. For al holy writ curseth it and spekith agayn &thorn;at vice. for it do&thorn; wrong to Ih&umacr; crist. [746] For it bireueth him &thorn;e loue &thorn;at men to him owen and turnith it bakward agains al resoun. [747] and makith &thorn;at &thorn;e auarous man hath more hope in his catel &thorn;an in ih&umacr; crist. and . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [748] &thorn;erfore saith 
<PB REF="00000670.tif" N="658"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="652"> seint poule ad Ephesios. &thorn;at an auerous man is &thorn;e &thorn;raldom of ydolatrie</P>
<P>[749] &para; what difference is &thorn;er bitwen an ydolaster and an auarous man. but &thorn;at an ydolaster per aduenture hadde but a mawmet/ . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> [750] &para; and certes &thorn;e synne of mawmetrie is &thorn;e firste &thorn;ing &thorn;at god defendith in &thorn;e ten comaunde|ment&yogh; as beri&thorn; witnes in exodo capitulo [751] &thorn;ou schalt/ haue noone false goddes biforn me. ne &thorn;ou schalt make to the no graue &thorn;ing. thus is he an auerous man &thorn;at loueth his tresor toforn god &para; And an ydolaster [752] &thorn;urgh his cursed synne of auarice and coueytise comen &thorn;ese harde lordschipes &thorn;urgh whiche thay ben distreyned by talliages custumes and cariages more &thorn;an here duete of resoun is. and elles take &thorn;ay of here bonde men amercimentes whiche mighte more resonably ben callid extorciouns &thorn;an mercymentis. [753] of whiche mersyments and raunsonyng of bonde men some lordes stywardes seyn &thorn;at it is rightful. For as moche as a cherl ha&thorn; no temperel &thorn;ing &thorn;at it nys his lordes as &thorn;ay sayn [754] &para; But certes &thorn;ise lordschipes doon wrong &thorn;at bireuen here bonde men &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;ay neuer &yogh;aue hem. Augustine . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">blank in MS.</NOTE> [755] soth is &thorn;e condicioun of &thorn;raldom and &thorn;e firste cause of &thorn;raldom is sinne Genesis</P>
<P>[756] &para; Thus may &yogh;e seen &thorn;at &thorn;e gilt deserued &thorn;raldom but not nature [757] &para; wherfore &thorn;ese lordschipes schulden nou&yogh;t moche glorifie in here lordschipes sith &thorn;at by naturel condicioun &thorn;ay ben nou&yogh;t lordes ouer &thorn;alles. but for &thorn;raldom com first by &thorn;e desert of synne [758] &para; And forther-ouer &thorn;er as &thorn;e lawe sayth &thorn;at temporel goodes of bonde folkes been &thorn;e goodes of her lordschipes; &yogh;e &thorn;at is to <MILESTONE N="274b" UNIT="folio">vnderstonde. &thorn;e goodes of &thorn;e emperour to defende in here right. but not to robbe hem ne to reue hem. [759] and &thorn;erfore 
<PB REF="00000671.tif" N="659"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="653"> sei&thorn; Seneca. &para; Thi prudence schulde liue benignely wi&thorn; &thorn;i &thorn;rallis [760] &thorn;ilke &thorn;at &thorn;ay clepe thralles ben goddes poeple. For humble folk ben cristes frendes &thorn;ay ben contubernially wi&thorn; &thorn;e lord</P>
<P>[761] &para; Thenk eek as of such seed as cherles springen. of such seed springe lordes. as wel may &thorn;e cherl be saued as &thorn;e lord. [762] The same deth &thorn;at takith &thorn;e cherl . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> as &thorn;ou woldist &thorn;i lord dide wi&thorn; &thorn;e if &thorn;ou were in his plyt. [763] Euery sinful man is a cherl as to synne &para; I rede &thorn;e certes &thorn;at &thorn;ou lord werke in such a wise wi&thorn; &thorn;y cherles &thorn;at &thorn;ay ra&thorn;er loue &thorn;e &thorn;an drede &thorn;e. [764] I wot wel &thorn;er is degre aboue degre as resoun is and skil &thorn;at men don her deuoir &thorn;er as it is dewe. &para; But certes extorciouns and despit of oure vndirlinges is dampnable</P>
<P>[765] &para; And for&thorn;ermore vnderstonde wel &thorn;at conquerours or tyrauntes maken ful ofte &thorn;ralles of hem &thorn;at born ben of als royal blood as ben &thorn;ay &thorn;at hem conqueren. [766] &thorn;is name of cherldom was neuer erst couth til noe sayde &thorn;at his sone chanaan schulde be &thorn;ral of his bre&thorn;eren for his synne [767] &para; what say we &thorn;anne of hem &thorn;at pylen and doon extorciouns to holy chirche &para; Certis the swerdes &thorn;at men &yogh;euen first to a knight whan he is newe dubbyd signifieth faith and &thorn;at he schulde defende holy chirche . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> [768] and as seith seint austin. Thay ben &thorn;e deueles wolues &thorn;at stranglen &thorn;e scheep of ih&umacr; crist. and doon wors &thorn;an wolues. [769] for so&thorn;ely whan &thorn;e wulf ha&thorn; ful his wombe; he stintith to strangle scheep. but so&thorn;ly &thorn;e pilours and &thorn;e destroy|ers of &thorn;e goodes of holy chirche ne doon nou&yogh;t so; For &thorn;ai stynte neuer to pile. [770] &para; Now as I haue sayd. sith so is. &thorn;at synne was first cause of &thorn;raldom; &thorn;anne is it 
<PB REF="00000672.tif" N="660"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="654"> &thorn;us. &thorn;at ilke tyme &thorn;at al &thorn;is world was in synne. &thorn;anne was al &thorn;is world in &thorn;raldom and in subieccioun [771] But certis sith &thorn;e tyme of grace com; God ordeyned &thorn;at somme folk schulde be more heigh in estaate and in degre and somme folkes more lowe and &thorn;at euerich schulde be serued in here estate and in degree [772] &para; And &thorn;erfore in somme contrees &thorn;ere &thorn;ay ben thralles whan &thorn;ay han turned hem to &thorn;e faith; &thorn;ay make here &thorn;ralles free out of thraldom &para; And &thorn;erfor certis &thorn;e lord oweth to his man &thorn;at &thorn;e man owith to &thorn;e lord. [773] &para; The pope callith himself seruaunt of seruaunts of god &para; But for as moche as &thorn;e staat/ of holy chirche . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> to &thorn;e commune profit might nought haue ben kepte ne pees <MILESTONE N="275a" UNIT="folio">ne reste in erthe. but if god had ordeyned som man of heiher degre and some men of lower; [774] &thorn;erfore was soueraignte ordeyned to kepe and to mayntene and de|fende her vnderlynges or her subiectis in resoun as fer|forth as it lith in her power and not to destroye ne confounde hem [775] &para; wherfore I say &thorn;at &thorn;ilke lordes &thorn;at be like wolues &thorn;at deuouren &thorn;e possessioun of &thorn;e catel of pore folk wrongfully wi&thorn;oute mercy or mesure; [776] &thorn;ay schul receyue by &thorn;e same mesure &thorn;at &thorn;ay han mesured to pouer folk &thorn;e mercy of ih&umacr; crist but if it be amendid [777] &para; Now come&thorn; deceipt bitwixe marchaunt and marchaunt. and &thorn;ou schalt vnder|stonde &thorn;at marchaundise is in many maneres. &thorn;at oon is bodily. and &thorn;at o&thorn;er is gostly. &thorn;at oon is honest and leful. and &thorn;at o&thorn;er is dishonest &amp; vnleful [778] &para; Of &thorn;ilke bodily marchaundise &thorn;at is honest and leful is &thorn;is. &thorn;at &thorn;er as god ha&thorn; ordeyned &thorn;at a regne or a cuntre is suffisaunt/ to himself. &thorn;anne is it honest/ and leful &thorn;at of &thorn;e abundaunce of &thorn;is contre &thorn;e men helpe ano&thorn;er cuntre &thorn;at is more needy [779] &para; And &thorn;erfore &thorn;er moote be marchaunt&yogh; to bringe fro &thorn;at oon cuntre to &thorn;at o&thorn;er her march|aundise 
<PB REF="00000673.tif" N="661"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="655"> [780] &para; That o&thorn;er marchaundise &thorn;at men hauntyn with fraude and treccherie and deceipt/ with lesynges and fals othis is cursed and dampnable [781] &para; Espirituel marchaundi&yogh;e is proprely symonie &thorn;at is ententyf desire to beye &thorn;ing/ espirituel &thorn;at is &thorn;ing &thorn;at apperteyneth to &thorn;e seintuarie of god and to &thorn;e cure of &thorn;e soule [782] &thorn;is desir is if so be &thorn;at a man do his diligence to parforme it. al be it &thorn;at his desir take noon effect. &yogh;it is it/ to him a dedly synne. and if he be ordrid he is irreguler [783] &para; Certis Symonye is cleped of Symon Magus &thorn;at wolde han bought for temporel catel &thorn;e &yogh;ifte &thorn;at god had &yogh;iuen by &thorn;e holy gost to seint petir and to &thorn;apostlis [784] &para; And &thorn;erfor vnderstonde &thorn;at bo&thorn;e he &thorn;at sellith and he &thorn;at bieth &thorn;inges espiritueles ben cleped Symonials be it by catel be it by procurement or by fleisshly prayere of his frendes ei&thorn;er flesshly frendes or spirituel frendes [785] &para; Fleisshly in tuo maneres as by kynrede or o&thorn;er frendes &para; Sothely if &thorn;ay pray for him. it is not worth . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> if he take &thorn;e benefice it is Symonie. and if he be worthy &amp; able. it is non [786] &para; That o&thorn;er is whan man or womman prayen for folk to avaunce hem oonly for wikkid fleisshly affeccioun &thorn;at &thorn;ay haue vnto &thorn;e persone and &thorn;at is ful Symonye. [787] but certis in seruice . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> moot he be honest and ellis not. and eek &thorn;at <MILESTONE N="275b" UNIT="folio">it be withoute bargaynynge and &thorn;at &thorn;e persone be able [788] &para; For as saith seint Damase &para; Alle &thorn;e synnes of &thorn;is world at &thorn;e reward of &thorn;is synne is a &thorn;ing of nought. For it is &thorn;e gretteste synne &thorn;at may be after &thorn;e synne of lucifer and antecrist [789] &para; For by &thorn;is synne god forlesith &thorn;e chirche and &thorn;e soule &thorn;at he bou&yogh;t wi&thorn; his precious blood by hem &thorn;at &yogh;euen chirches to hem &thorn;at ben not digne [790] &para; For &thorn;ay putten in &thorn;eues &thorn;at 
<PB REF="00000674.tif" N="662"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="656"> stelen &thorn;e soules of ih&umacr; crist and destroyen patri|moygne. [791] by suche vndigne prestis and curates. han lewed men &thorn;e lasse reuerence of &thorn;e sacrament/ of holy chirche and suche &yogh;eueres of chirches putten out &thorn;e children of crist. and putten in to &thorn;e chirche &thorn;e deueles oughne sone. [792] &thorn;ay sellen soules &thorn;at lambes schulde kepe to &thorn;e wolf &thorn;at stranglith hem. And &thorn;erfore schul &thorn;ay neuer haue part of &thorn;e pasture of lambes &thorn;at is &thorn;e blisse of heuen [793] &para; Now come&thorn; hasardrie wi&thorn; his appur|tenaunce. as tables. and rafles. of whiche come&thorn; deceipt. fals othis. chidynges and alle raueynes. blasphemyng. and reneying of god and hate of his neighebors. wast of goodes out of tyme. and som tyme man|slaughter. [794] &para; Certes hasardours ne mowe not be wi&thorn;oute gret synne whil &thorn;ay haunte &thorn;at craft [795] &para; Of auarice come&thorn; eek lesynges. &thorn;efte and fals witnesse and fals o&thorn;es &para; And &yogh;e schul vndirstonde &thorn;at &thorn;ese ben grete synnes and expresce agains &thorn;e comaundement&yogh; of god as I haue sayd [796] &para; Fals witnesse is in word and eek in dede. In word; as for to bireue &thorn;in neighebor his good name by &thorn;y witnessinge. or bireue him his catel or his heritage by &thorn;y fals witnesse. whan &thorn;ou for Ire or for meede. or for envie berest witnes or accusist him or excusist him by &thorn;y fals witnes. or ellis ex|cusist &thorn;iself falsly. [797] ware &yogh;ow questemongers and notaries &para; Certis for fals witnessynge was Susanna in ful gret sorwe and peyne and many ano&thorn;er mo [798] &para; The synne of thefte is eek expresse agayns goddes hestis &amp; &thorn;at in tuo maners corporel and spirituel. [799] Corporel; as for to take &thorn;y neighebours catel agayns his wille. be it by force or by sleight. be it by mette. or by mesure. [800] by stelynge eeke of fals enditements vpon him and in borwyng of &thorn;in neghebores catelle in entent neuer to paye/ and in semblable &thorn;inges. [801] Es|pirituel &thorn;efte. is sacrilege &thorn;at is to sayn hurt|ynge 
<PB REF="00000675.tif" N="663"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="657"> of holy &thorn;inges. or of &thorn;ing sacred of crist &para; Sacrilege is in tuo<MILESTONE N="276a" UNIT="folio"> maneres &thorn;at oon is by resoun of holy place as chirches or chirchehawes. [802] For whiche euery vileins synne &thorn;at men doon in suche places may be clepid sacrilege or euery violence in semblable place &para; &thorn;at o&thorn;er maner is. as &thorn;o &thorn;at wi&thorn;drawen falsly &thorn;e rightes &thorn;at longen to holy chirche [803] &para; . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> and generally sacrilege is to reue holy &thorn;ing fro holy place. and vnholy &thorn;ing out of holy place. or holy thing out of holy place<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; Remedium contra Auariciam[<I>from margin</I>]</HEAD>
<P>[804]</P>
<P>NOw schul &yogh;e vnderstonde &thorn;at &thorn;e releuynge of auarice is misericorde and pite largely taken. And men might axen why &thorn;at misericord and pite is relieuyng of auarice. [805] &para; Certes &thorn;e auaricious man schewith no pite ne misericorde to &thorn;e needeful man. For he delitith him in kepyng of his tresor and nou&yogh;t in &thorn;e rescowyng ne relieuyng of his euen|cristen. &amp; &thorn;erfore speke I first of misericord [806] &para; Thanne is misericord as saith &thorn;e philosopher a vertu. by which &thorn;e corrage of a man is stired by &thorn;e myseise of him &thorn;at is myseysed. [807] vpon which misericorde folwith in parformynge of chariteable werkis of misericord. [808] &para; And certes &thorn;ese moeuen men to &thorn;e misericord of ih&umacr; crist &thorn;at &yogh;af himself for oure gult. and suffred de&thorn; for misericord and for&yogh;af vs oure original synne [809] and &thorn;er by relessid vs fro peyne of helle and amenusid &thorn;e peynes of purgatorie by penitence and &yogh;eueth grace wel to do and at &thorn;e laste &thorn;e ioye of heuen [810] &para; The spices of misericorde ben for to loue and for to &yogh;iue. and eek for to for&yogh;iue and for to relesse and for to haue pite in herte and compassioun of &thorn;e meschief of his 
<PB REF="00000676.tif" N="664"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="658"> euencristen and eek chasti&yogh;e &thorn;e as neede is [811] &para; Ano&thorn;er maner of remedye agayns auarice is resonable largesse but sothely here bihouith &thorn;e con|sideracioun of &thorn;e grace of ih&umacr; crist and of his temporel goodes and eek of his goodes perdurable &thorn;at crist &yogh;af vs. [812] and eek to haue remembrance of &thorn;e de&thorn; &thorn;at/ he schal resceyue he noot not whanne . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> and eke he schal forgon al &thorn;at he hath saue oonly &thorn;at he ha&thorn; dispendid in goode werkes</P>
<P>[813] &para; But for als moche as some folk ben vnreson|able men oughte to eschiewe foly largesse &thorn;am clepen wast/ [814] Certes he &thorn;at is fool-large ne &yogh;iue&thorn; nou&yogh;t his catel. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> Sothely what &thorn;ing &thorn;at he &yogh;iueth for vayn glorie as to mynstrals and to folk for to bere his renoun in &thorn;e world; he ha&thorn; synne and noon almes [815] &para; Certes he lesith foule his goodes &thorn;at sekith wi&thorn; &thorn;e &yogh;ift <MILESTONE N="276b" UNIT="folio">of his good no &thorn;ing but synne. [816] he is like to an hors &thorn;at sekith ra&thorn;er to drynke drouy watir and trouble &thorn;an for to drinke watir of &thorn;e welle &thorn;at is cleer. [817] And for as moche as &thorn;ay &yogh;iue &thorn;er as &thorn;ay schuld not &yogh;iue; to hem appendith &thorn;ilke malisoun &thorn;at crist schal &yogh;iue at &thorn;e day of doom to hem &thorn;at schal be dampned.<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; <B>De Gula</B>[<I>from margin</I>]</HEAD>
<P>[818]</P>
<P>AFter auarice come&thorn; Glotenye which is expresse eke agayns &thorn;e comaundement of god. Glotenye is vnresonable and desordeyned coueytise to ete and to drynke. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> [819] &thorn;is synne cor|ruptid al &thorn;is world as is wel schewed in &thorn;e synne of adam. and of Eua &para; loke eek what saith seint poul of glotouns [820] &para; Many saith seint/ poul gon of whiche 
<PB REF="00000677.tif" N="665"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="659"> I haue ofte said to &yogh;ow and now I say it wepyng &para; That thenemyes of &thorn;e cros of crist of whiche &thorn;ende is deth and of whiche here wombe is here god and here glorie in confusioun &thorn;at so saueren er&thorn;ely &thorn;inges [821] &para; he &thorn;at is vsant . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [822] to &thorn;is synne hath many spices &para; The firste is dronkenes &thorn;at is thorrible sepulture of mannes resoun. And whan man is dronken he hath lost/ his resoun and &thorn;is is dedly synne [823] &para; But schortly whan &thorn;at a man is not wont to strong drinke and par auenture ne knowi&thorn; not &thorn;e streng&thorn;e of &thorn;e drynk or hath feblesse in his heed or ha&thorn; trauayled &thorn;urgh whiche he drynkith &thorn;e more and be sodeynly caught wi&thorn; drynke it is no dedly synne but venial [824] &para; The secounde spice of dedly synne is. whan &thorn;e spirit of a man wexith al trouble for drunkenesse. and bireue&thorn; him his witte and his discres|sioun [825] &para; The &thorn;ridde spice of glotouns is whan a man deuoureth his mete and ha&thorn; no rightful maner of etyng [826] &para; &thorn;e fer&thorn;e is whan &thorn;urgh &thorn;e grete abund|aunce of his mete &thorn;e humours of his body been dis|temprid [827] &para; &thorn;e fifte is &thorn;e Idilnes by to moche drinking. For which a man som tyme forgetith by &thorn;e morwe what he dide at eue or on &thorn;e night bifore</P>
<P>[828] In o&thorn;er maner ben distinct &thorn;e spices of glotonye after seint Gregory &para; The firste is for to ete or drynke byfore tyme to ete &para; The secound is. whan man &yogh;iueth him to delicate mete or drinke [829] &para; The &thorn;ridde is. whanne man takith to moche &thorn;erof ouer mesure &para; The ferthe is curiosite with gret entent to make and apparayle his mete &para; The fifte is. For to ete to gredely [830] &para; These ben &thorn;e fyue fyngres of &thorn;e deueles hand. by whiche he drawith folk to synne. /
<PB REF="00000678.tif" N="666"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="660"></P>
<P>[831]</P>
<P><MILESTONE N="277a" UNIT="folio">AGayns Glotonye is &thorn;e remedie abstinence as sai&thorn; Galien. But &thorn;at holde I nou&yogh;t meritorie. If he do it oonly for &thorn;e hele of his body &para; Seint austyn wol &thorn;at abstinence be don for vertu and wi&thorn; pacience. [832] Abstinence he saith is litil worth but if a man haue good wille &thorn;erto and but it be enforced by pacience. and by charite. and &thorn;at men doon it for goddes sake and in hope to haue &thorn;e blisse of heuen</P>
<P>[833] &para; The felawes of abstinence ben attemper|aunce &thorn;at holdith &thorn;e mene in alle &thorn;inges. eek schame &thorn;at eschiewith al dishoneste. Suffisaunce &thorn;at seeketh noone riche metes ne drynkes ne do&thorn; no force of to outrageous apparaillyng of mete [834] &para; Mesure also &thorn;at restreyne&thorn; by resoun the dislaue appetit of etyng. Sobernes also restreyne&thorn; . . . . .[835] . . . .] &thorn;e delicat wille to ete and &thorn;e lasse leysir . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; <B>De luxuria</B></HEAD>
<P>[836]</P>
<P>AFter Glotonye &thorn;anne cometh leccherie. For &thorn;ese two synnes ben so neih cosyns &thorn;at ofte tyme &thorn;ay wol not departe. [837] Vnde paulus ad Ephesios &para; Nolite inebriari vino &amp;c. God wot &thorn;is synne is ful displesaunt &thorn;ing to god. vino in quo est luxuria. For he sayde him|self. Do no leccherie. and &thorn;erfore he putte gret peyne agayn &thorn;is synne / in &thorn;e olde lawe. [838] If a wom|man &thorn;ral were take in &thorn;is synne. sche scholde be beten with stoones to &thorn;e deth. and if sche were a gentil womman; sche schulde be slayn wi&thorn; stoones./ and if sche were a bisschoppis dou&yogh;ter; sche schulde be brent by goddis comaundement. [839] &para; Forther ouer by &thorn;e synne of leccherie; god dreinte al &thorn;e world at &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000679.tif" N="667"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="661"> diluue &para; And after &thorn;at he dreynte fyue citees with thonder layt and sonk hem in to helle</P>
<P>[840] &para; Now let vs thanne speke of &thorn;ilke stynkyng synne of leccherie &thorn;at men clepen aduoutry of weddid folk &thorn;at is to sayn if &thorn;at oon of hem be weddid or elles bo&thorn;e [841] &para; Seint Iohan saith &thorn;at aduoutris schuln be in helle in watir brennyng of fuyr and of brimston. In fuyr for &thorn;e leccherie. In brimston For &thorn;e stynk or her ordure. [842] &para; Certis &thorn;e brekyng of &thorn;is sacrament is an horrible &thorn;ing. hit was makid of god himself in paradis Confermed of ih&umacr; crist as witnesseth seint Mathew &para; A man schal lete fader and mooder and take him to his wif and &thorn;ay schul ben two in oon fleisch [843] &para; This sacrament bitok|ene&thorn; &thorn;e knyttyng togider of crist and of holy chirche [844] nat oonly &thorn;at god forbad aduotrie in dede; but eek he comaunded &thorn;at &thorn;ou scholdest <MILESTONE N="277b" UNIT="folio">not coueyte &thorn;y neyhebors wif [845] &para; In &thorn;is heste sei&thorn; seint austyn is forboden al maner coueytise to do leccherie &para; lo what sei&thorn; seint mathew in &thorn;e gospel. that who-so seth a womman to coueytise of his lust; he ha&thorn; doon lecchery wi&thorn; hir in his herte. [846] &para; here may &yogh;e se &thorn;at nou&yogh;t oonly &thorn;e dede of &thorn;is synne is forboden; but eek &thorn;e desir to do &thorn;at synne [847] &para; This cursed synne annoyeth greuosly hem &thorn;at it haunten and first to here soule. for he obligith it to synne and to pyne of &thorn;e de&thorn; &thorn;at is pardurable [848] &para; vnto &thorn;e body annoye&thorn; it greuously. also for it dreye&thorn; him and wastith him &amp; schent him. and of his blood he makith sacrifice to &thorn;e deuel of helle &para; It wastith eek his catel and his substaunce. [849] and certes if &thorn;at it be a foul &thorn;ing a man to waste his catel on wommen; &yogh;it is it a fouler &thorn;ing whan &thorn;at for such ordure wommen dispende vpon men here catel and here substaunce [850] &para; This synne as saith &thorn;e prophete byreueth man and womman her good fame and al here honour. and it is ful pleasaunt to &thorn;e deuel. For &thorn;er by 
<PB REF="00000680.tif" N="668"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="662"> wynneth he &thorn;e moste pray of &thorn;is world [851] &para; And right as a marchaunt delite&thorn; him most in chaffare &thorn;at he ha&thorn; most auauntage of; Right so delitith &thorn;e feend in &thorn;is ordure</P>
<P>[852] &para; This is &thorn;e o&thorn;er hond of &thorn;e deuel with fyue fyngres to cacche &thorn;e poeple to his vilonye [853] &para; &THORN;e firste fynger is &thorn;e foule lokyng of &thorn;e foule womman and of &thorn;e foule man &thorn;at sleth right as a basiliskoc sle&thorn; folk by &thorn;e venym of his sight. For &thorn;e coueytise of eyen folwi&thorn; &thorn;e coueytise of &thorn;e herte [854] &para; The secounde fynger is the vileynes touchinge in wikkid manere. and &thorn;erfore saith salamon &thorn;at who-so touchith and handelith a womman; he farith lik him &thorn;at handelith &thorn;e scorpioun &thorn;at styngith and sodeinly sleeth &thorn;urgh his enuenemynge as who so touchith warm picche. it schent his fyngres [855] &para; The &thorn;ridde is foule wordes &thorn;at farith lik fuyr &thorn;at right anoon brenne&thorn; &thorn;e herte [856] &para; The fer&thorn;e is &thorn;e kissyng. and trewely he were a greet fool &thorn;at wolde kisse &thorn;e mouth of a brennyng ouen or of a forneys: [857] and more fooles ben &thorn;ay &thorn;at kyssen in vilonye. For &thorn;at mouth is &thorn;e mou&thorn; of helle. and namely &thorn;ise olde dotard fooles holours. &yogh;it wol &thorn;ay kisse &thorn;ough &thorn;ay may nought do &amp; smater hem. [858] &para; Certis &thorn;ay ben like to houndes. For an hound whan he come&thorn; to a roser or by o&thorn;er beautes. &thorn;ough he may nou&yogh;t <MILESTONE N="278a" UNIT="folio">pisse; &yogh;et wil he heue vp his leg and make a coun|tenaunce to pisse. [859] and for &thorn;at many man weneth he may not synne for licorousnes &thorn;at he doth with his wif; Certis &thorn;at oppinioun is fals. God wot a man may sle himself wi&thorn; his owne knyf and mak himself dronke of his oughne tonne [860] &para; Certis be it/ wif or child or eny worldly &thorn;ing &thorn;at he louyth biforn god it is his maumet and he is an ydolastre /. [861] man schulde loue his wyf by discrescioun paciently and attemperelly. and &thorn;anne is sche as it 
<PB REF="00000681.tif" N="669"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="663"> were his suster [862] &para; The fyfte fynger of the deueles hond is &thorn;e stynkynge dede of leccherie [863] &para; Certes &thorn;e fyue fyngres of glotonye &thorn;e deuel put in &thorn;e wombe of a man. &amp; his fyue fyngres of lecchery bygripeth hym by &thorn;e reynes for to &thorn;rowe him in to &thorn;e fourneys of helle. [864] &thorn;ere as &thorn;ey schuln haue &thorn;e fuyr. and &thorn;e wormes &thorn;at euer schal lasten. and wepyng and wayling scharp hunger and &thorn;urst. and grislines of deueles &thorn;at schul alto-tere hem wi&thorn;oute respit/ and wi&thorn;|outen ende [865] &para; Of leccherie as I sayde sourdren diuers spices of fornicacion &thorn;at is bitwen man and womman &thorn;at ben nou&yogh;t maried and &thorn;is is dedly synne and against nature [866] al &thorn;at is enemy and destruccioun to nature. [867] par fay &thorn;e resoun of a man telli&thorn; him wel &thorn;at it is dedly synne For als moche as god forbad leccherie and seint poule &yogh;euith hem &thorn;at regne &thorn;at is due to no wight but hem &thorn;at doon synne dedly [868] Ano&thorn;er synne of lecchery is for to bireue a mayden of hir maydenhede / for he &thorn;at so do&thorn;; Certes he casteth maydenhede out of the heighest degre &thorn;at is in &thorn;e present lif [869] and bireuith hir &thorn;ilke precious fruyt &thorn;at &thorn;e book clepith &thorn;e hundrid fruyt. I can &yogh;eue it noon o&thorn;er name in englisch. but in latyn it is I-cleped Centesimus fructus secundum Ieronimum contra Iouinianum [870] &para; Certes he &thorn;at so doth is cause of many harmes and vilenyes mo &thorn;an eny man can rekene. Right as he som tyme is cause of alle &thorn;e damages &thorn;at bestis doon in &thorn;e feeld &thorn;at brekith &thorn;e hegge or &thorn;e closure &thorn;urgh which he destroye&thorn; &thorn;at may not be restored; [871] for certes no more may maydenhode be re|stored &thorn;an an arm &thorn;at is smyten fro &thorn;e body retourne agayn to waxe. [872] sche may haue mercy &thorn;is wot I wel if sche do penitence but neuer schal it be &thorn;at sche nas corrupt [873] &para; And al be it so &thorn;at I haue spoke som what of aduoutre; &yogh;it is it good to speke of mo <MILESTONE N="278b" UNIT="folio">perils &thorn;at longen to aduoutre for to eschiewe &thorn;at foule 
<PB REF="00000682.tif" N="670"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="664"> synne [874] &para; Aduoutrie in latyn is for to sayn approching of o&thorn;er mannes bed &thorn;orugh &thorn;e which &thorn;at whilom were oon fleisch abounden here bodyes to o&thorn;er persones [875] &para; Of &thorn;is synne as sai&thorn; &thorn;e wise man many harmes cometh &thorn;er-of &para; First brekyng of faith &para; And certes faith is &thorn;e keye of cristendom. [876] and whan &thorn;at faith is broke &amp; lorn; so&thorn;ely cristendom stont veyn and wi&thorn;outen fruyt [877] &para; This synne is eek a &thorn;eef. For &thorn;efte is generally to speke to reue a wight his &thorn;ing agayns his wille [878] &para; Certis &thorn;is is &thorn;e foulest thefte &thorn;at may be whan a womman stelith hir body from hire housbounde and &yogh;iueth it to hire holour to defoule hire &amp; stelith hir soule fro crist/ and &yogh;euith it to &thorn;e deuel [879] &para; This is a fouler &thorn;efte &thorn;an for to breke a chirche and stele chalises. For &thorn;ese aduouteres breke &thorn;e temple of god spirituelly and stelen &thorn;e vessel of grace &thorn;at is &thorn;e body and &thorn;e soule &para; For Ih&umacr; crist schal destroyen hem as saith seint poule [880] &para; Sothely &thorn;is &thorn;efte doutyd gretly Ioseph whan &thorn;at his lordes wyf prayde him of vilonye whan he saide. lo my lady how my lord ha&thorn; take to me vnder my warde al &thorn;at he ha&thorn; in &thorn;is world. ne no &thorn;ing of his power is oute of my power but oonly &yogh;e &thorn;at ben his wyf. [881] and how schuld I do &thorn;anne &thorn;is wikkidnes and synne so horribly agayns god and my lord. God it forbede &para; Alas al to litel is suche trou&thorn;e now I-founde [882] &para; The &thorn;ridde harm is &thorn;e filthe &thorn;urgh which &thorn;ay breken &thorn;e comaundement of god and defoule &thorn;e auctour of here matrimonye &thorn;at is crist. [883] For certis in so moche as &thorn;e sacrament of mariage is so noble and so digne; So moche is it &thorn;e gretter synne for to breke it. for god makid mariage in paradis in &thorn;estat of Innocence to multiplie man kynde to &thorn;e seruice of god [884] and &thorn;erfore is &thorn;e brekyng &thorn;e more greuous. Of which breking come&thorn; fals heires ofte tymes &thorn;at wrongfully occupien mennes heritage. and &thorn;erfore wolde crist putte 
<PB REF="00000683.tif" N="671"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="665"> hem out of &thorn;e regne of heuen &thorn;at is heritage to goode folk. [885] Of &thorn;is breking come&thorn; ek ofte tyme &thorn;at folk vnwar wedden or synnen wi&thorn; her kynrede and namely &thorn;ese harlottis &thorn;at haunten bordels of &thorn;ese foule wommen &thorn;at mowe be likened to a comune gonge where as men purgen here entrayles of her ordure [886] &para; what say we ek of putours &thorn;at lyuen by &thorn;e orrible synne of putrie &amp; constreyne wymmen &yogh;e som tyme his oughne wyf or his child as don <MILESTONE N="279a" UNIT="folio">&thorn;ese baudes to &yogh;elde hem a certeyn rente of here bodily putrie &para; Certes &thorn;ese ben cursede synnes [887] &para; Vnderstonde eek that avoutrie is set gladly in &thorn;e ten comaundements bituixe man|slau&yogh;ter and thefte. For it is grettest thefte &thorn;at may be. for it is thefte of body and soule / [888] and it is lik homicidie For it kerueth a-tuo hem &thorn;at first were makid oon fleisch. and &thorn;erfore by &thorn;e olde lawe of god &thorn;ay scholde be slayn [889] &para; But na&thorn;eles by &thorn;e lawe of Ih&umacr; crist &thorn;at is lawe of pite whan he sayde to &thorn;e womman &thorn;at was founde in aduoutri and schulde haue ben slayn with stoones aftir &thorn;e wille of &thorn;e Iewes as was her lawe. Go quod ih&umacr; crist and haue no more wille to synne. or wilne no more to do synne. [890] &para; Sothely &thorn;e vengeance of avouterye is awardid to . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> helle / but it be destourbed by penitence [891] &para; &YOGH;it ben &thorn;er mo spices of &thorn;is cursed synne. as whan &thorn;at oon of hem is religious or ellis bothe or for folk &thorn;at ben entred in to ordre as subdekin or dekin or prest or hospitalers and euer &thorn;e higher &thorn;at he be. &thorn;e gretter is &thorn;e synne. [892] &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at gretly aggreggith her synne is &thorn;e brekyng of here avow of chastite whan &thorn;ay resceyued ordre. [893] and for&thorn;er ouer is so&thorn; &thorn;at holy ordre is chef of alle &thorn;e tresor of god and his especial signe and mark of chastite to schewe &thorn;at &thorn;ay ben ioyned to chastite which &thorn;at is &thorn;e moste precious lif &thorn;at is [894] &para; And eek &thorn;ese ordred folk ben specially tytled to god and of &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000684.tif" N="672"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="666"> special meyne of god of whiche whan &thorn;ay don dedly synne &thorn;ay ben &thorn;e special traytours of god and of his poeple. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> and whil &thorn;ay ben suche traytours; here prayer auayle&thorn; not to &thorn;e poeple [895] &para; Prestis ben aungels as by &thorn;e dignite of here misterie &para; But forso&thorn;e seint poul saith &thorn;at Sathanas transformeth him in aungel of light. [896] So&thorn;ely &thorn;e prest &thorn;at hauntith dedly synne; he may be likened to &thorn;e aungel of light. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> &amp; he semeth aungel of light: but for so&thorn;e he is aungil of derknes [897] whiche ben &thorn;e sones of belie as schewith in &thorn;e book of kinges &thorn;at &thorn;ay were &thorn;e sones of belial &thorn;at is &thorn;e deuel. [898] belial is to say wi&thorn;oute Iuge and so faren &thorn;ay &thorn;ay &thorn;ynke hem fre and han no Iuge no more &thorn;an hath a fre bole &thorn;at takith which cow &thorn;at him like&thorn; in &thorn;e toun [899] so faren &thorn;ay by wommen For right as a fre bole is y-nough for al a toun; / Right so is a wikked prest corrupcioun ynough for al a parisch or for al a contray [900] &para; These prestes as sai&thorn; &thorn;e book ne conne not &thorn;e mistery of presthode. &thorn;e poeple ne <MILESTONE N="279b" UNIT="folio">god ne knowe &thorn;ay not. &thorn;ay holde hem nought apayed as saith &thorn;e book of soden fleissh &thorn;at was to hem offred; but &thorn;ay tooke by force &thorn;e fleissch &thorn;at is raw; [901] Certes so &thorn;ese schrewes holde hem not appayed with rosted fleissh and sode fleissh wi&thorn; whiche &thorn;e poeple feeden hem in gret reuerence. But &thorn;ay wil haue raw fleisch of folkes wyues and here dou&yogh;tres [902] &para; And certes &thorn;ese wommen &thorn;at consenten to here harlotrie don gret wrong to crist and to holy chirche and alle halwes / and to alle soules for &thorn;ay bireuen alle &thorn;ese hem &thorn;at schulde worschipe crist and holy chirche and praye for cristen soules [903] &para; And &thorn;erfore han suche prestis &amp; here lemmans eeke &thorn;at consenten to here leccherie &thorn;e malisoun of al &thorn;e court cristian til &thorn;ay come to amendement 
<PB REF="00000685.tif" N="673"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="667"> [904] &para; The &thorn;ridde spice of aduoutry is som tyme bitwix a man and his wif and &thorn;at is whan &thorn;ay take noon reward in her assembling but only to &thorn;e fleischly delit as saith seint Ierom. [905] and ne rekke of no &thorn;ing but &thorn;at &thorn;ay be assemblid by cause &thorn;at &thorn;ay ben maried. al is good ynough as &thorn;inkith hem. [906] But in suche folk ha&thorn; &thorn;e deuel power as saith &thorn;e aungel Raphael to Thoby in here assemblyng &thorn;ay putten ih&umacr; crist out of her herte. and &yogh;iuen hemself to alle ordure [907] &para; The ferthe spice is &thorn;e assemble of hem &thorn;at ben of here kynrede or of hem &thorn;at ben of oon affinite or elles wi&thorn; hem wi&thorn; whiche here fadres or here kynrede han delitid in &thorn;e synne of leccherie. &thorn;is synne makith hem like houndes &thorn;at taken noon heede of kynrede [908] and certes parenteal is in tuo maneres ey&thorn;er gostly or fleisshly. gostly as for to dele wi&thorn; her gossib. [909] For ri&yogh;t / so as he &thorn;at engendrith a child is his fleisshly fader; Ri&yogh;t so is his godfader his fader espirituel. for which a womman may in no lasse synne assemble wi&thorn; hir gossib &thorn;an wi&thorn; hire oughne fleischly fader or bro&thorn;er [910] &para; The fifte spice of &thorn;ilke abhominable synne of which &thorn;at no man unne&thorn;e oughte to speke ne write. na&thorn;eles it is openly rehersed in holy wryt/. [911] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> but &thorn;ough &thorn;at holy writ speke of horrible synne; Certes holy writ may not be defouled no more &thorn;an &thorn;e sonne &thorn;at schyneth on a dongehul [912] &para; Ano&thorn;er synne appertenith to lecchery &thorn;at come&thorn; in sleping. &amp; &thorn;is synne come&thorn; ofte to hem &thorn;at ben maydenes and eek to hem &thorn;at ben corrupte and &thorn;is synne men clepen pollucioun &thorn;at cometh in .iiij. maners [913] &para; Som tyme of languisschynge of body for &thorn;e humours ben to ranke and to abundaunt in &thorn;e body <MILESTONE N="280a" UNIT="folio">of man. somtyme of infirmite for &thorn;e feblenesse of &thorn;e vertu retentyf as phisik make&thorn; mencioun. And som tyme for surfete of mete and drynke. [914] som tyme of 
<PB REF="00000686.tif" N="674"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="668"> vileins &thorn;oughtes &thorn;at ben enclosed in mannes mynde whan he . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> kepe him wisely or elles may men synne greuously<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></P>
<P>[915] &para; Now cometh &thorn;e remedye a&yogh;ens lecchery and &thorn;at is generally chastite of wikkedhede and continence &thorn;at re|streyne&thorn; alle &thorn;e desordeigne moeuynges &thorn;at comen of fleischly talentes. [916] and euer &thorn;e gretter meryt schal he han &thorn;at most restreyneth eschau|fynges of ordure of &thorn;is synne. and &thorn;is is in &thorn;re maneres. &thorn;at is to sayn chastite of mariage / chastite of/ wickedhede [917] &para; Now schalt &thorn;ou vnderstonde &thorn;at matrimoigne is leful assemblynge of man and womman &thorn;at resceyuen by vertu of &thorn;e sacrement &thorn;e bond &thorn;urgh which &thorn;ay may not be departid in al here lif &thorn;at is to say whil &thorn;ay lyuen bo&thorn;e. [918] &thorn;is as saith &thorn;e boke is a ful gret sacrement God makid it / as I haue said in paradis and wolde him|self be born in mariage [919] and for to holden mariage. he was at &thorn;e weddyng wher as he turnede watir in to wyn which was &thorn;e firste miracle &thorn;at he wrought in er&thorn;e biforn his disciples [920] trewe effect of mariage clensith fornicacioun and replenischith holy chirche of good lynage. for &thorn;at is &thorn;e ende of mariage and it chaungith dedly synne in to venyal bituixe hem &thorn;at ben weddid . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> as wel as &thorn;e bodyes [921] &para; &thorn;is is verray mariage &thorn;at was first blessed by god er &thorn;at &thorn;e synne bigan whan naturel lawe was in his first poynt in paradis. and it was ordeyned &thorn;at/ oo man schulde haue but oon womman. and oon womman but oon man as saith seint augustyn by many resouns</P>
<P>[922] &para; First for mariage is figured bitwixe crist and 
<PB REF="00000687.tif" N="675"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="669"> holy chirche &para; Ano&thorn;er is for a man is heed of a womman algate by ordinaunce it/ schulde be so [923] &para; For if a womman had mo men &thorn;an oon; &thorn;anne schulde sche haue mo hedes &thorn;an oon &amp; &thorn;at were an horrible &thorn;ing biforn god. And eek a womman. my&yogh;te nou&yogh;t please to many folk al at oones. and also &thorn;er ne schulde neuer be pees &amp; rest among hem. For euerich wolde aske his oughne &thorn;ing. [924] and for&thorn;er-ouer no man schulde knowe his oughne en|gendrure ne who schulde haue his heritage and &thorn;e womman scholde be &thorn;e lasse loued fro &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at sche were ioyned to many men</P>
<P>[925] &para; Now come&thorn; how &thorn;at a man schulde bere him wi&thorn; his wif and namely in tuo &thorn;inges &thorn;at is <MILESTONE N="280b" UNIT="folio">to sayn in sufferaunce and in reuerence and &thorn;at schewed crist whan he made first womman. [926] For he ne made hire not of &thorn;e heed of adam. for sche schulde not to gret lordschipe haue / [927] &thorn;er as &thorn;e womman ha&thorn; &thorn;e maistry sche makith to moche disaray. &thorn;er nedith noon ensample of &thorn;is. &thorn;e experience of &thorn;is of day by day oughte suffice [928] &para; Also certes god ne made nou&yogh;t womman of &thorn;e foot of adam. For sche ne scholde nou&yogh;t be holden to lowe for sche can not/ paciently suffre &para; But god made womman of &thorn;e ribbe of adam For womman schulde be felawe vnto man [929] Man schulde bere him to his wif. in faith in trou&thorn;e and in loue as sai&thorn; seint poule. aman schulde loue his wif as crist loued holy chirche . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> &thorn;at deyed for it. so schulde a man for his wyf if/ it were neede</P>
<P>[930] &para; Now how &thorn;at a womman schulde be subiect to hir housbonde &thorn;at tellith seint peter. iij<SUP>o</SUP>. c<SUP>o</SUP>. first in obedi|ence [931] and eek/ as sai&thorn; &thorn;e decre. A womman &thorn;at is a wif as longe as sche is a wif sche ha&thorn; noon auctorite to swere ne to bere witnesse wi&thorn;oute leue of hir housbonde &thorn;at is hir lord. algate he schulde be so by resoun. [932] sche schulde eek serue him in al 
<PB REF="00000688.tif" N="676"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="670"> honeste and ben attempre of hir array / I wot wel &thorn;at &thorn;ay schulde sette here entent to please her house|bondes but nought by here queyntise of array [933] &para; Seint Ierom saith &thorn;at wyues &thorn;at ben arrayed in silk and in purpre ne mowe nou&yogh;t clo&thorn;e hem in ih&umacr; crist &para; loke what saith saint Iohn eek in &thorn;e same matier [934] &para; Seint gregori saith eek &thorn;at no wight sekith precious clo&thorn;ing ne array but oonly for veyn glorie to ben honoured &thorn;e more biforn &thorn;e poeple [935] &para; It is a gret foly a womman to haue fair array outward and hirsilf to ben foul inward [936] &para; A wyf schulde eek be mesurable in lokyng and in beryng and in laugheing and discrete in alle hir wordes. [937] and aboue alle worldly &thorn;inges sche schulde loue hir housebonde/ with al hire herte and to him to be trewe of hir body. [938] so scholde an housebonde eeke ben to his wif. For sith &thorn;at al &thorn;e body is &thorn;e housebondes. so schulde here herte ben. or ellis &thorn;er is bitwixe hem tuo as in &thorn;at no parfyt mariage [939] &para; Thanne schal men vnder|stonde; &thorn;at for &thorn;re &thorn;inges a man and his wyf mowe fleischly assemble &para; The firste is in entent/ of engen|drure of children to the seruice of god. for certis &thorn;at is &thorn;e cause fynal of matrimoyne [940] &para; The secounde cause is to &yogh;elden euerych of hem his dette vn<MILESTONE N="281a" UNIT="folio"> to o&thorn;er of his body &para; For euerych of hem ha&thorn; power of his oughne body &para; The &thorn;ridde is for to eschiewe leccherie and vilenye. &thorn;e fer&thorn;e forso&thorn;e is dedly synne. [941] as to &thorn;e firste it/ is meritory. The secounde also for as sai&thorn; &thorn;e decre &thorn;at sche ha&thorn; merit of chastite &thorn;at &yogh;eldith to hir housebonde &thorn;e dette of hir body. &yogh;e &thorn;ough it/ be agayn hir likyng and &thorn;e lust of hir hert [942] &para; The &thorn;ridde maner is venial synne. and trewly scarsly may eny of &thorn;ese be wi&thorn;oute venial synne for &thorn;e corrupcioun and for &thorn;e delit. [943] The fer&thorn;e maner is for to vnderstonde as if &thorn;ay assemble oonly for amorous loue and for noon of &thorn;e forsayde causes. but 
<PB REF="00000689.tif" N="677"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="671"> for to accomplise &thorn;ilke brennynge delyt &thorn;ay rekke neuer how ofte. so&thorn;ely it is dedly synne and &yogh;it wi&thorn; sorwe some folk wole more peyne hem for to doon &thorn;an to her appetit suffise&thorn;.</P>
<P>[944] the secounde maner of chastite is to ben a clene wydewe and to eschiew &thorn;e embrasynges of men and desiren &thorn;e enbrasynges of ih&umacr; crist [945] &thorn;ese ben &thorn;o &thorn;at han ben wyues and han forgon here hous|bondes and eek wommen &thorn;at han doon leccherie and be relieued by penitence / [946] and certis if &thorn;at a wyf cou&thorn;e kepe hir al chast by licence of hir housebonde so &thorn;at sche &yogh;eue non occasioun &thorn;at he agilt it were to hir a gret merit [947] &para; Thise maner wymmen &thorn;at obseruen chastite moste be clene in herte as wel as in body and in &thorn;ought and mesurable in clo&thorn;ing &amp; in countenaunce. abstinent in etyng and drynkyng in speche and in dede. and &thorn;anne is sche &thorn;e vessel or &thorn;e boyst of the blessed Magdaleyne &thorn;at fulfillith holy chirche ful of good odour. [948] &para; The &thorn;ridde maner of chastite is virginite. and it/ bihoue&thorn; &thorn;at sche be holy in herte and clene of body. and &thorn;anne is sche spouse of ih&umacr; crist and sche is &thorn;e lif of aungels. [949] sche is &thorn;e preysyng of &thorn;is world. and sche is as &thorn;ese martires in egalite. sche ha&thorn; in hir &thorn;at tonge &thorn;at tonge may nou&yogh;t telle. [950] virginite bar oure lord ih&umacr; crist and virgine was himselue</P>
<P>[951] &para; Ano&thorn;er remedy agayns leccherie is specially to wi&thorn;drawe suche &thorn;inges as &yogh;iuen occasioun to &thorn;ilke vilonye as is ease and etyng and drynkyng For certes whan &thorn;e pot boylith strongely. &thorn;e beste remedye is to wi&thorn;|drawe &thorn;e fuyr [952] sleping eek in gret quiete is eek a greet/ norice vnto leccherie</P>
<P>[953] &para; Ano&thorn;er remedy agayns leccherie <MILESTONE N="281b" UNIT="folio">is &thorn;at a man or a womman eschiewe &thorn;e companye of hem by whiche he doutith to be tempted. for al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;e dede be wi&thorn;stonde; &yogh;it is &thorn;er gret temptacioun 
<PB REF="00000690.tif" N="678"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="672"> [954] sothely a whit wal al &thorn;ough it brenne not fully by stikyng of a candel &yogh;et is &thorn;e wal blak of stiking of a candel ful ofte tyme. [955] I rede &thorn;at no man truste in his oughne perfeccioun but he be strenger &thorn;an Sampson or holiere &thorn;an Dauyd. and wiser &thorn;an salamon</P>
<P>[956] &para; Now after &thorn;at I haue declared &yogh;ow &thorn;e seuen dedly synnes as I can &amp; some of here braunches and here remedyes; so&thorn;ely if I cou&thorn;e I wolde telle &yogh;ow &thorn;e ten comaundementes. [957] but so heigh a doctrine I leue to diuines. but/ na&thorn;eles I hope to god &thorn;ay ben touchid in &thorn;is litil tretys eue&para;rich of hem alle</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De secunda parte penitencie[<I>in margin</I>]</HEAD>
<P>[958]</P>
<P>NOw for as moche as &thorn;e secounde part of penitence stant in confessioun of mouth as I bigan in &thorn;e chapitre I say seint austyn saith. [959] Synne is euery word and euery dede / and al &thorn;at men coueyten agayn &thorn;e lawe of ih&umacr; crist. and &thorn;is is for to synne in herte in mouthe and in dede by &thorn;y fyue wittis &thorn;at been. sight heeryng smellyng tastyng or sauoryng or felyng [960] &para; Now it is good to vnder|stonden &thorn;e circumstaunces &thorn;at aggreggen moche to euery synne. [961] &thorn;ou schalt considre what &thorn;ou art &thorn;at dost &thorn;e synne whe&thorn;ir &thorn;at &thorn;ou be mal or femal. old o&thorn;er &yogh;ong gentil or &thorn;ral. free or seruaunt hool or seek. weddid or sengle. ordrid. or vnordred wys or fool clerk or seculer [962] if sche of &thorn;y kyn bodily or gostly or noon. if eny of &thorn;y kynrede haue synned wi&thorn; hire or noon and many mo &thorn;inges</P>
<P>[963] &para; That o&thorn;er circumstaunce is whe&thorn;er it be don in fornicacioun or in aduoutry or incest or noon or mayden or noon in maner of homicide or non horrible grete synnes or smale and how longe &thorn;ou hast continued in synne [964] &para; The &thorn;ridde circumstaunce is &thorn;e place wher &thorn;ou hast don synne whe&thorn;er in o&thorn;er 
<PB REF="00000691.tif" N="679"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="673"> mennes houses or in &thorn;in owne in feld or in chirche or in chirchehawe. in chirche dedicate or noon. [965] For if . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> it be dedicate it is enterdited til it be reconsiled by &thorn;e bischop [966] and &thorn;e prest scholde be enterdyted &thorn;at dede such a vilonye to terme of al his lyf &amp; scholde no more synge no masse and if he dede he schulde do dedly synne at euery tyme &thorn;at he song masse [967] &para; The ferthe circumstaunce is by which media|tours as by which messagers <MILESTONE N="282a" UNIT="folio">or for entysement or for consentement to bere companye with felawes For many a wrecche for to bere companye wol go to &thorn;e deuel of helle. [968] for &thorn;ay &thorn;at eggyn or con|sentyn to &thorn;e synne ben parteneres of &thorn;e synne and of &thorn;e dampnacioun of &thorn;e synnere</P>
<P>[969] &para; The fyfte is how many tymes &thorn;at he ha&thorn; synned if it be in his mynde / and how ofte &thorn;at he ha&thorn; falle. [970] For he &thorn;at ofte fallith in synne. despise&thorn; &thorn;e mercy of god and encresceth his synne and is vnkynde to crist and he waxith &thorn;e more feble to wi&thorn;stonde synne and synne&thorn; &thorn;e more lightly [971] and &thorn;e latter arrisith and is &thorn;e more eschiewe to schriue him. and namely to him &thorn;at ha&thorn; ben his con|fessour. [972] For whiche &thorn;at folk whan &thorn;ay falle agayn in here olde folies eyther &thorn;ay forletin her confessours al vtterly or ellis &thorn;ay departen here schrifte in diuers places. but so&thorn;ely such departed schrifte ha&thorn; no mercy of god of his synnes [973] &para; The sixte circum|staunce is why &thorn;at a man synne&thorn; as by which temptacioun . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> or by ex|cityng of o&thorn;er folk or if he synne wi&thorn; a womman by force or by hir owne assent. [974] or if &thorn;e womman maugre hir heed ha&thorn; ben enforced or noon. &thorn;is schal sche telle. or for coueytise or for pouerte &amp; if it was hire procuryng or noon and alle such maner 
<PB REF="00000692.tif" N="680"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="674"> harneys [975] &para; The .vij. circumstaunce is in what maner he ha&thorn; don his synne or how &thorn;at sche ha&thorn; suffred &thorn;at folk han doon to hire. [976] &thorn;e same schal &thorn;e man telle pleynly alle &thorn;e circumstaunces. and whe&thorn;er he haue synned wi&thorn; commune bordeal womman or noon. [977] or doon his synne in holy tyme or noon. in fast|yng tyme or noon. or biforn his schrifte of after his latter schrifte [978] And ha&thorn; par aduenture broken his penaunce enioyned &thorn;erfore. by whos help or by whos counseil by sorcery or by o&thorn;er craft al moste be told [979] &para; Alle &thorn;ese &thorn;inges after &thorn;ay be grete or smale engreggen &thorn;e consciens of a man and eek &thorn;e prest &thorn;at is &thorn;e iugge may &thorn;e better ben auysed of his iugement in &yogh;iuyng of &thorn;y penaunce / and &thorn;at is after &thorn;y contricioun. [980] For vnderstonde wel &thorn;at after &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at a man ha&thorn; defouled his baptisme by synne if he wol come to sauacioun &thorn;er is noon o&thorn;er wey but penitence and schrifte of mouthe and by satisfaccioun [981] and namely by &thorn;o tuo. if &thorn;er be a confessour to which he may schryue him. and &thorn;e &thorn;ridde if &yogh;e haue lif to parforme it.</P>
<P>[982] &thorn;anne schal men loke it and considre &thorn;at if he <MILESTONE N="282b" UNIT="folio">wol make a trewe and a profitable confessioun &thorn;er moste be foure condiciouns [983] &para; First it moste ben in sorweful bitternesse of herte as sayde &thorn;e king E&yogh;echiel to god &para; I wol remembre me alle &thorn;e &yogh;eres of my lif in bitternes of myn hert. [984] &THORN;is condicioun of bitter|nes ha&thorn; fyue signes. The first is &thorn;at confessioun moste be schamefast not for to couere ne hyde his synne but for he ha&thorn; agultid his god and defoulid his soule [985] &para; And herof saith seint augustyn. The herte tremblith for schame of his synne. and for he hath gret schamefastnes. he is digne to haue gret mercy of god. [986] Such was &thorn;e confessioun of &thorn;e publican &thorn;at wolde nou&yogh;t heue vp his ey&yogh;en to heuen. For he had offendid god of heuen For which schamefastnes; he had anon &thorn;e mercy of god [987] &para; And &thorn;ere seith 
<PB REF="00000693.tif" N="681"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="675"> seint augustyn &thorn;at such schamefast folk ben next for&yogh;euenes of remissioun [988] &para; The secounde signe is humilite of confessioun &para; Of which sai&thorn; seint petre humblith &yogh;ow vnder &thorn;e might of god. &thorn;e hond of god is my&yogh;ty in confessioun For &thorn;er-by god for&yogh;iueth &thorn;e synnes he alone ha&thorn; &thorn;e power. [989] and &thorn;is humilite schal ben in herte and in signe outward. For right as he ha&thorn; humilite to god in his herte; right so schulde he humble his body outward to &thorn;e prest &thorn;at sittith in goddes place [990] For which in no manere sith &thorn;at crist is souerayn and &thorn;e prest is his mene and mediatour bi|twix crist and &thorn;e synnere and &thorn;e synner is &thorn;e lasse as by way of resoun; [991] &thorn;anne schulde nou&yogh;t &thorn;e confessour sitte as lowe as &thorn;e synnere but &thorn;e synnere schulde knele biforn him or at his feet but if maladye destourbid it for he schal take no keep who sittith &thorn;ere but in whos place &thorn;at he sitteth. [992] a man &thorn;at ha&thorn; trespassed to a lord and cometh for to axe him of mercy and to maken his accord / and settith him doun anoon by &thorn;e lord. men wolde holde him outrageous and not wor&thorn;y so soone for to haue mercy ne remissioun [993] &para; The &thorn;ridde signe is &thorn;at &thorn;y schrifte schulde be ful of teeris if men may wepe. and if he may not wepe wi&thorn; his bodily eyen let him wepe wi&thorn; his herte. [994] Such was &thorn;e confessioun of seint peter. For after he hadde forsake ih&umacr; crist. he wente out and wepte ful bitterly [995] &para; The ferthe signe is &thorn;at he lette nou&yogh;t for schame to schewen his confessioun. [996] Such was &thorn;e confessioun of &thorn;e magdaleyn &thorn;at spared for no schame of hem &thorn;at were at &thorn;e feste to go to oure lord <MILESTONE N="283a" UNIT="folio">ih&umacr; crist and byknowe to him hire synne [997] &para; The fifte signe is &thorn;at a man or a womman be obeisaunt/ to resceyue &thorn;e penaunce &thorn;at him is enioyned. For certis ih&umacr; crist for &thorn;e gultes of oon man was obedient to his deth</P>
<P>[998] &para; The o&thorn;er condicioun of verray confessioun is &thorn;at it hastily be doon. For certes if a man had a dedly wounde. euer &thorn;e lenger &thorn;at he taried to warisch 
<PB REF="00000694.tif" N="682"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="676"> himself; &thorn;e more wolde it corrupte and haste him to his de&thorn; and eek &thorn;e wounde wolde be &thorn;e worse to hele [999] &para; and right so fare&thorn; synne &thorn;at long time is in a man vnschewed [1000] Certes a man oughte soone schewe his synne for many causes as for drede of deth &thorn;at come&thorn; sodeinly and not certeyn what tyme it schal come or ben in what place. and eek &thorn;e drecchyng of oon synne drawe&thorn; ano&thorn;er [1001] and eek &thorn;e lenger he tarie&thorn; &thorn;e fer&thorn;er is he from crist and if he abyde vnto his laste day skarsly may he schriue him or re|membre him of his synnes or repente for &thorn;e greuous malady of his deth [1002] &para; And for as moche as he ha&thorn; not in his lif herkened Ih&umacr; crist whan he ha&thorn; spoken; he schal crien to ih&umacr; crist at his laste day. and scarsly wol he herken him. [1003] And vnderstonde &thorn;at &thorn;is condicioun moste haue foure &thorn;inges &thorn;y schrifte moste ben purueyed byforn and auysed. For wikked haste do&thorn; no profyt and &thorn;at a man can schryue him of his synnes. be it of pride or of enuye and so for&thorn; alle &thorn;e spices and &thorn;e circumstaunces [1004] and &thorn;at he haue comprehendid in his mynde the nombre and &thorn;e gretnes of his synne . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> [1005] and eek &thorn;at he be contrit of his sinnes and in stedefast purpos by &thorn;e grace of god neuer eft to falle in synne and eek &thorn;at he drede and countrewayte himself and &thorn;at he flee &thorn;e occasiouns of synne to whiche he is enclyned [1006] &para; Also &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt schriue &thorn;e of alle &thorn;in synnes to oon man. and nat a parcel to oon man and a parcel to ano&thorn;er man &thorn;at is vnderstonde in entent to parte &thorn;y confessioun as for schame or drede. for it nys but strangelyng of &thorn;y soule [1007] For certes ih&umacr; crist is enterely al good. in him is noon imperfeccioun. and &thorn;erfore ou&thorn;er he for&yogh;iueth al parfitely or elles neuer a del. [1008] I say nought if &thorn;er be assigned to &thorn;y penitencere for certein synne &thorn;at &thorn;ou art bounde to schewe him al &thorn;e remenaunt of &thorn;y synnes of whiche 
<PB REF="00000695.tif" N="683"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="677"> &thorn;ou hast ben schryuen of &thorn;y curate but if it like &thorn;e of &thorn;in humilite. &thorn;is is no departyng of schrifte [1009] ne I ne say not &thorn;ere as I speke of diuisioun of confes|sioun <MILESTONE N="283b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;at if &thorn;ou haue licence to schryue &thorn;e to a discret and to an honest prest wher &thorn;e likith and eek by &thorn;e licence of &thorn;y curate &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne maist wel schriue &thorn;e to him of alle &thorn;yn synnes. [1010] but let no synne be byhinde vntold as fer as &thorn;ou hast remem|braunce. [1011] and whan &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;e schriue to &thorn;i curate; telle him eeke al &thorn;y synne &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast doo sith &thorn;ou were last I-schryue. &THORN;is is no wikkid entent of diuisioun of schrifte</P>
<P>[1012] &para; Also &thorn;y verrey schrifte askith certeyn con|diciouns. First &thorn;at &thorn;ou schriue &thorn;e by &thorn;y fre wille nou&yogh;t constreyned ne for schame of folk ne for maladye or such &thorn;ing. for is resoun &thorn;at he &thorn;at trespassith wi&thorn; his fre wille . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> confesse his trespas. [1013] noon o&thorn;er man schal telle his synne but himself. ne he schal not nayte or denye his synne ne wra&thorn;&thorn;e him with &thorn;e prest for his amonestynge to lete synne [1014] &para; The secounde condicioun is &thorn;at &thorn;y schrifte be laweful &thorn;at is to sayn &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;at schriuest &thorn;e and eek &thorn;e prest &thorn;at herith &thorn;y confessioun ben verrayly in &thorn;e feith of holy chirche [1015] and &thorn;at a man be nought despaired of &thorn;e mercy of Ih&umacr; crist/ as caym or Iudas. [1016] and eek a man moot accuse himself of his owne trespas and not another; but he schal blame and wite himself and his oughne malice of his synne / and noon other [1017] &para; But na&thorn;eless if &thorn;at ano&thorn;er man by occasioun or ellis enticer of his synne or &thorn;at &thorn;e estate of a persone be such &thorn;urgh which his synne aggreggith or elles &thorn;at he may not playnly schryue hym but he telle &thorn;e persone wi&thorn; which he ha&thorn; synned &thorn;anne may he telle it [1018] so &thorn;at his entent be nou&yogh;t to bakbyte &thorn;e persone; but oonly to declare his con|fessioun
<PB REF="00000696.tif" N="684"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="678"></P>
<P>[1019] Thow schalt nou&yogh;t eke make no lesyng in &thorn;y confessioun for humilite . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> to sayn &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast don synnes of whiche &thorn;ou were neuer gulty [1020] as seint augustyn sai&thorn; &para; If &thorn;ou by cause of humilite makest lesynges on &thorn;iself. &thorn;ough &thorn;ou were not in synne biforn &yogh;it art &thorn;ou &thorn;anne in synne &thorn;urgh &thorn;y lesynges [1021] &para; Thou most schewe &thorn;y synne by &thorn;yn oughne propre mouth but &thorn;ou woxe dombe. and not by no lettre. for &thorn;ou &thorn;at hast don &thorn;e synne &thorn;ou schalt haue &thorn;e schame. [1022] &thorn;ou schalt nou&yogh;t peynte &thorn;y confessioun by faire subtil wordes to couer &thorn;e more &thorn;y synne for &thorn;anne bigilist &thorn;ou &thorn;iself and not &thorn;e prest. &thorn;ou most telle it platly be it neuer so foul ne so horrible. [1023] &thorn;ou schalt eek/ schriue &thorn;e to a prest &thorn;at is discrete to counsaile &thorn;e &para; And &thorn;ou schalt nou&yogh;t schryue &thorn;e for <MILESTONE N="284a" UNIT="folio">veinneglorie ne for ypocrisie. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [1024] &para; &thorn;ou schalt not eek renne to &thorn;e prest sodeinly to telle him lightly &thorn;y synne as who-so tellith a tale or a iape. but auysily and wi&thorn; gret deuocioun; [1025] and generally schriue &thorn;e ofte. if &thorn;ou ofte falle; ofte &thorn;ou aryse by confessioun [1026] &para; And &thorn;ough &thorn;ou schryue &thorn;e ofter &thorn;an oones of synne of which &thorn;ou hast ben schriuen; it is &thorn;e more merite and as saith seint augustyn &para; Thou schalt haue &thorn;e more lightly relessyng and grace of god bothe of synne and of payne. [1027] and certes oones a &yogh;er atte atte lest/ way it is laweful to be houselyd. For sothely oones a &yogh;er alle &thorn;inges renouelen<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></P>
<P>[1028] &para; Now haue I told of verray confessioun &thorn;at is the secounde partye of penitence
</P>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000697.tif" N="685"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="679">
<HEAD>&para; De tercia parte penitencie</HEAD>
<P>[1029]</P>
<P>The &thorn;ridde partye of penitence is Satisfaccioun and &thorn;at stondith generally in almes dede and bodily peyne [1030] &para; Now ben &thorn;er [. . . .] of almes dede &para; Contricioun of herte where a man offere&thorn; himself to god &para; The secounde is. to haue pite of &thorn;e defaute of his neighebor &para; The &thorn;ridde is. in good counseil and comfort gostly and bodily where men han neede and namely in sustenaunce of mennes foode. [1031] and take keep &thorn;at a man ha&thorn; neede of . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> clo&thorn;ing and herberwe. he ha&thorn; [. . . . .] charitable counseil and visityng in prisoun and malady. and sepulture of his dede body [1032] &para; And if &thorn;ou may not visite &thorn;e needeful wi&thorn; &thorn;y persone; visite by &thorn;y message and by &thorn;y &yogh;iftes. [1033] &thorn;ese ben general almesses or werkes of charite of hem &thorn;at han temporal riches or discrecioun in counselynge. Of &thorn;ese werkes schalt &thorn;ou hieren at &thorn;e day of doom</P>
<P>[1034] &thorn;is almes schalt &thorn;ou doon of &thorn;in oughne propur &thorn;inges and hastily and priuely if &thorn;ou maist. [1035] But na&thorn;eles if &thorn;ou maist not do priuely; &thorn;ou schalt nou&yogh;t forbere to do almes &thorn;ough men se it / so &thorn;at it be nou&yogh;t don for &thorn;ank of &thorn;e world but oonly for &thorn;onk of ih&umacr; crist [1036] &para; For as witnessith seint Mathewe .v<SUP>to</SUP>. &para; A cite may not ben hid &thorn;at is set on a mountayn ne non light not a lanterne and put it vnder a buisschel but men sette it on a candel stikke to lighte &thorn;e men in &thorn;e hous. [1037] Right so schal &yogh;oure light lighten biforn men &thorn;at men may se &yogh;oure goode werkes and glorifien &yogh;oure fader &thorn;at is in heuen</P>
<P>[1038] &para; Now as to speke of bodily peyne. it is in prayere in wakinges in fastynges. in vertuous 
<PB REF="00000698.tif" N="686"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="680"> techinges of orisouns. [1039] &yogh;e schul vnderstonde &thorn;at orisouns or prayeres is for to seyn a pitous wil of herte &thorn;at redresse&thorn; in god and expressith it by word outward to remembre harmes and to haue &thorn;inges espirituel &amp; <MILESTONE N="284b" UNIT="folio">durable and som tyme temporel &thorn;inges of whiche orisouns of &thorn;e orisoun of &thorn;e pater noster ha&thorn; oure lord ih&umacr; crist enclosed most &thorn;inges [1040] &para; Certis it is priuileged of &thorn;re &thorn;inges in his dignite . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> &thorn;an any o&thorn;er prayer. For ih&umacr; crist himself maked it. [1041] and it is schort for it schulde be coud &thorn;e more lightly. and forto wi&thorn;holde it &thorn;e more esily in herte and helpe himselfe &thorn;e oftere with &thorn;e orisoun [1042] and for a man schulde be &thorn;e lasse wery to say it. and for a man may not excuse him to lerne it. it is so schort and so easy and for it comprehendith in it self alle goode prayeres [1043] &para; The exposicioun of &thorn;is holy praier &thorn;at is so excellent and so digne. I bitake to &thorn;ese maystres of theology. saue &thorn;us moche wol I sayn whan &thorn;ou prayest/ &thorn;at god schulde for&yogh;iue &thorn;e &thorn;y gultes as &thorn;ou for&yogh;iuest hem &thorn;at &thorn;ey gulten to &thorn;e; be ful wel war. &thorn;at &thorn;ou be not out of charite. [1044] &thorn;is holy orisoun amenisith eek venial synne. and &thorn;erfore it appendith specially to penitence.</P>
<P>[1045] &thorn;is praier moste be trewely sayd and in verray faith. and &thorn;at men pray to god ordinatly and dis|cretly &amp; deuoutly and alway a man schulde putte his wille to be subiect/ to &thorn;e wille of god [1046] &para; &thorn;is orisoun moste eek be sayd wi&thorn; greet humblesse and ful pure honestly and nou&yogh;t to &thorn;e annoyaunce of eny man or womman &para; It most eek be continued with &thorn;e werkis of charite. [1047] hit auaylith agayns &thorn;e vices of &thorn;e soule / as sei&thorn; seint Ierom &para; By fastyng ben saued &thorn;e vices of &thorn;e soule.</P>
<P>[1048] &para; After &thorn;is &thorn;ou schalt vnderstonde &thorn;at bodily peyne stant in wakyng. for ih&umacr; crist saith &para; wakith and prayeth &thorn;at &yogh;e ne entre not/ in to 
<PB REF="00000699.tif" N="687"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="681"> temptacioun. [1049] &yogh;e schul vnderstonde &thorn;at fast|ynge stont in &thorn;re &thorn;inges &para; In forbering of bodily mete and drink. and in forberyng of worldly iolite. and in for|bering of worldly synne. &thorn;is is to sayn &thorn;at a man schal kepe him fro dedly synne in al &thorn;at he may</P>
<P>[1050] &para; And &thorn;ou schalt vnderstonde eek &thorn;at god ordeyned fastyng. and to fastyng appurteynen foure &thorn;inges [1051] &para; largesce to pouer folk. gladnes of hert espirituel. not to ben angry ne annoyed ne grucche for he fastith. and also resonable hour for to ete. ete by mesure &thorn;at is to sayn a man schulde not ete in vntyme ne sitte &thorn;e lenger at his mete for he fastith</P>
<P>[1052] &para; Thanne schal &thorn;ou vnderstonde &thorn;at bodily peyne stant in discipline or teching by word or by writyng or by ensample. Also in heires weryng or of stamyn or of habeiouns on her naked fleisch for cristes sake and suche maner penaunce [1053] &para; But ware &thorn;e wel &thorn;at such maner penaunce <MILESTONE N="285a" UNIT="folio">of &thorn;yn fleissh make nou&yogh;t &thorn;in herte bitter or angry or anoyed of &thorn;iself. for better is to cast away &thorn;in hayre &thorn;an for to caste away &thorn;e swet|nes of ih&umacr; crist. [1054] and &thorn;erfor sei&thorn; seint poule &para; Clothe &yogh;ow as &thorn;ay &thorn;at ben chosen of god in herte of misericorde debonairete. sufferaunce and such maner of clo&thorn;ing. of &thorn;e which ih&umacr; crist is more appayed &thorn;an of haires or of hauberkis</P>
<P>[1055] &para; &thorn;an is eek in knokkyng on &thorn;e brest. in scourgyng wi&thorn; &yogh;erdes. in knelynges. in tribulaciouns [1056] in suffring paciently wronges &thorn;at ben doon to him/ and eek in pacient sufferaunce of maledies or lesyng of worldly catel or of wif. or of child or of o&thorn;ir frendes</P>
<P>[1057] &para; Thanne schalt &thorn;ou vnderstonde whiche &thorn;inges destourben penaunce / and &thorn;is is in foure &thorn;inges. &thorn;at is. drede. schame. hope. and wanhope. &thorn;at is desperacioun [1058] &para; And for to speke first/ of drede for which he 
<PB REF="00000700.tif" N="688"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="682"> weneth &thorn;at he may suffre no penaunce. [1059] &thorn;er agayns is remedye for to &thorn;inke &thorn;at bodily penaunce is but schort and litel at &thorn;e regard of &thorn;e peyne of helle &thorn;at is cruel and so long &thorn;at it/ lastith wi&thorn;outen ende</P>
<P>[1060] &para; Now agains &thorn;e schame &thorn;at a man ha&thorn; to schryue him and namely &thorn;ese ypocrites &thorn;at wolde be holde so parfyt &thorn;at &thorn;ay haue no meede to schriue hem. [1061] agayns &thorn;at schame schulde a man &thorn;inke &thorn;at by way of resoun &thorn;at he hath not ben aschamed to do foule &thorn;inges. Certis him oughte not ben aschamed to doon faire &thorn;inges &amp; goode &thorn;inges and &thorn;at is confessioun [1062] &para; And man scholde eek &thorn;inke &thorn;at god seeth alle &thorn;y &thorn;oughtes and &thorn;y werkes to him may no &thorn;ing be hyd ne couered [1063] men schulde eek remembre hem of &thorn;e schame &thorn;at is to come at/ &thorn;e day of doom to hem &thorn;at ben nought penitent and schriuen in &thorn;is present lif. [1064] For alle &thorn;e creatures in heuen ne in erthe and in helle schuln seen apertly al &thorn;at he hydith in &thorn;is world</P>
<P>[1065] &para; Now for to speke of hem &thorn;at ben so negligent and slowe to schryue hem stant in tuo maneres [1066] &para; &thorn;at oon is. &thorn;at he hopith for to lyue longe and for to purchace moche riches for his delyt. and &thorn;anne he wol schriue him. and as he saith he may as him semith tymely ynough come to schrifte [1067] &para; Another is of &thorn;e Surquidie &thorn;at he ha&thorn; in cristes mercy [1068] &para; Agains &thorn;e firste vice he schal &thorn;inke &thorn;at oure lif is in no sikernesse. and eek &thorn;at al &thorn;e riches in &thorn;is world ben in aduenture and passen as a schadowe on &thorn;e wal [1069] and as saith seint Gregory &thorn;at it apperteyneth to &thorn;e grete rightwisnes of god &thorn;at neuer schal &thorn;e <MILESTONE N="285b" UNIT="folio">peyne stynte of hem &thorn;at neuer wolde wi&thorn;drawe hem fro synne her &thorn;ankes. but ay continue in synne for &thorn;ilke perpetuel wille to doon synne. schul &thorn;ay haue perpetuel peyne</P>
<P>[1070] &para; wanhope in tuo maneres is. &thorn;e firste wan|hope is in &thorn;e mercy of crist &para; That o&thorn;er is &thorn;at &thorn;ay 
<PB REF="00000701.tif" N="689"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="683"> &thorn;inke &thorn;ay mighte nought longe perseuer in good|nesse [1071] &para; The firste wanhope come&thorn; of &thorn;at he demyth &thorn;at he synned so highly and so ofte and so longe layn in synne &thorn;at he schal not be saued [1072] &para; Certis a&yogh;ens &thorn;at cursed wanhope schulde he &thorn;enke &thorn;at &thorn;e passioun of Ih&umacr; crist is more strong for to vnbynde &thorn;an synne is strong for to bynde [1073] &para; Agains &thorn;e secounde wanhope he schal &thorn;inke &thorn;at als ofte as he fallith; he may arise agayn by penitence / And &thorn;ough he neuer so longe haue leyn in synne; &thorn;e mercy of crist is alway redy to resceyue him to mercy [1074] &para; Agains &thorn;e wanhope &thorn;at he demeth &thorn;at he &thorn;inkith he schulde not longe perseuere in goodnesse. he schal &thorn;inke &thorn;at &thorn;e febles of &thorn;e deuel may no &thorn;ing doon but men wol suffre him. [1075] And eek he schal haue streng&thorn;e of &thorn;e help of god and of al holy chirche and of &thorn;e proteccioun of aungels if him list</P>
<P>[1076] &para; Thanne schal men vnderstonde what is &thorn;e fruyt of penaunce And after &thorn;e word of ih&umacr; crist &para; hit is &thorn;e endeles blisse of heuen [1077] &thorn;er ioye ha&thorn; no contrariete of wo ne of penaunce ne greuaunce. &thorn;er alle harmes ben passed of &thorn;is present lif. ther as is &thorn;e sikernesse fro &thorn;e peyne of helle. . . . .[1078] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> &thorn;ere as is &thorn;e body of man &thorn;at whilom was seek. frel and feble and is immortal. and so strong and so hool &thorn;at &thorn;er may no &thorn;ing empeire it. [1079] &thorn;er nys ney&thorn;er honger &thorn;urst ne colde. but euery soule replenisched wi&thorn; &thorn;e sight and &thorn;e parfyt knowyng of god [1080] &para; This blisful regne may men purchace by pouerte espirituel and &thorn;e glorie by lowe|nes. &thorn;e plente of ioye by hunger and &thorn;urst and reste by trauaile and &thorn;e lif by deth and mortificacioun of synne.<NOTE PLACE="end">[Small break in the MS.]</NOTE></P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">

<PB REF="00000702.tif" N="690">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="684">
<HEAD>&para; Preces de Chauceres./</HEAD>
<P>[1081]</P>
<P>NOw pray I to &yogh;ow alle &thorn;at heren &thorn;is litel tretis or reden &thorn;at if &thorn;er be any &thorn;ing &thorn;at likes hem &thorn;at &thorn;er-of &thorn;ay &thorn;anke oure lord ih&umacr; crist of whom procedith alle witte and al goodnes [1082] &para; And if &thorn;er be eny &thorn;ing &thorn;at displesith hem I pray hem &thorn;at &thorn;ay arette it to &thorn;e defaute of myn vnconnyng <MILESTONE N="286a" UNIT="folio">and not to my wille &thorn;at wolde fayn haue sayd better if I hadde connyng [1083] &para; For &thorn;e book sai&thorn;. al &thorn;at is writen. for oure doctrine is writen . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> [1084] For I biseke &yogh;ow mekely for &thorn;e mercy of god &thorn;at &yogh;e pray for me &thorn;at god haue mercy on me and for&yogh;eue me my giltes [1085] and nameliche my translaciouns and of endit|yng/ in worldly vanitees. whiche I reuoke in my re|tracciouns [1086] as is &thorn;e book of troyles. &thorn;e book also of fame. &thorn;e book of .29. ladies &thorn;e book of &thorn;e duchesses. &thorn;e book of seint valentines day and of &thorn;e parliment of briddes. &thorn;e Tales of Cauntur|bury alle &thorn;ilke &thorn;at sounen in to synne [1087] &thorn;e book Many of &thorn;e leo. and o&thorn;er bokes if &thorn;ay were in my mynde / or remembraunce and many a song and many a leccherous lay. Of &thorn;e whiche crist for his grete mercy for&yogh;iue me &thorn;e synnes [1088] &para; But of &thorn;e translacioun of boce de consolacione and o&thorn;er bokes of consolacioun and of legend of lyues of seintes and omelies and moralitees and of deuocioun. [1089] that &thorn;anke I oure lord ih&umacr; crist and his moder and alle &thorn;e seintes in heuen [1090] bisekyng hem &thorn;at &thorn;ay fro hennysforth vn-to my lyues ende sende me grace to biwayle my gultes and to studien to &thorn;e sauacioun of my soule and graunte me grace and space of verray repentaunce. 
<PB REF="00000703.tif" N="691"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="685"> penitence. confessioun. and satisfaccioun. to don in &thorn;is present lif [1091] &thorn;urgh &thorn;e benigne grace of him &thorn;at is king of kynges and prest of alle prestis &thorn;at bought vs wi&thorn; his precious blood of his hert; [1092] So &thorn;at I moote be oon of hem at &thorn;e day of doom that schal be sauyd Qui cum patre</P>
